<SLUG> BC-BBA-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS PAY TRIBUTE TO LEMON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Bob Lemon was a sacred part of baseball
lore, but he was a man without pretenses who never left Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He was with the Cleveland Indians that memorable post-World War
II summer of 1948 when they became the first major league franchise
to draw more than 2 million fans and when he and Lou Boudreau and
Bob Feller and Gene Bearden led the Indians to a World Series
title.
</P>
<P>
   He was the losing pitcher for the Indians against the New York
Giants at the Polo Grounds that early October afternoon in 1954
when Willie Mays made his legendary over- the-shoulder catch of Vic
Wertz's 440- foot drive to center field and when Dusty Rhodes
touched him for a 254-foot game-winning home run.
</P>
<P>
   He was the winning manager for the New York Yankees on Oct. 2,
1978 at Fenway Park when an unlikely hero, Bucky Dent, would launch
a seventh- inning, three-run homer that would slay the Boston Red
Sox in a division playoff game and ultimately would give the
Yankees the opportunity to beat the Los Angeles Dodgers in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   He was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1976 after a 13-year
career in which he had eight 20-win seasons on the way to a 207-128
record, routinely facing such renowned batsmen as Joe DiMaggio and
Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite his immense achievements and his widespread fame,
Robert Granville Lemon, who passed away Tuesday evening at 79,
remained the same unassuming, low-key person he was as a teenager
when he graduated from Wilson High in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   He never changed, and he inspired such great fondness from those
people he befriended that one of them, George Steinbrenner, the
notoriously fickle Yankee owner, never stopped sending him
paychecks even though Lemon retired from the organization several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob was the most regular guy I've ever known in my life,''
says Bob Harrison, the longtime major league baseball scout and
contemporary of Lemon who graduated from Jordan High in 1938. ``He
never once talked about being a Hall of Famer, or about anything he
did in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard Bob Lemon say an unkind word about another human
being,'' says Chuck Stevens, the one-time St. Louis Browns and
Hollywood Stars first baseman who graduated from Poly High in 1937.
``He might have been the nicest, kindest and most gentle man I ever
met in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Stevens pauses a moment, and then says, ``I also never saw
a man enjoy a cigarette and a pop as much as Bob. He was his
happiest when he was smoking a cigarette, having a toddy, and
sitting around with his pals shooting the breeze about baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Bob Lemon became a fixture at monthly Thursday
afternoon gatherings among former professional ball players at
various local restaurants. He usually would attend with one of his
closest friends, Bob Sturgeon, a one-time Chicago Cubs shortstop
and Pacific Coast League performer who graduated from Poly High in
1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lem and I had a lot of laughs and fun times together,'' says
Sturgeon, who now resides in Chino Hills. ``We were very close. I'm
the one who introduced him to his wife Jane. She was working at the
same place my dad was working, Strickland's, which was a radio and
electronics store at Fifth and Pine. I stood up for Lem when he
married Jane in around 1941 and he stood up for me when I got
married a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nicest thing about Lem is that I never heard him downgrade
anyone. He was just a person who liked everyone, and everyone liked
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lemon was a third baseman at Wilson High, and played that
position for a time with the Indians until the Cleveland manager,
Lou Boudreau, decided Lemon had a brighter future as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing for the St. Louis Browns in 1946, and Lou
Boudreau asked me before a game with the Indians if I had ever seen
Lemon pitch,'' relates Chuck Stevens. ``I told him I saw Lemon
pitch during the War years for the Los Alamitos Navy Base team, and
that he could really throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, darned if Boudreau doesn't pitch Lemon that day, and the
first hitter he faces is me. I hit a double off him, sliding into
second base. Lemon came over and said, `What the hell you doing to
me?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't long before Lemon got the grasp of pitching, and
became terrific at it. He had a great sinker. He had one of those
fastballs that just sank naturally. And what made him even more
effective as a pitcher is that he was like an infielder out there
at the mound. No one could bunt on him. And he also helped himself
often with the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another close friend of Bob Lemon, Red Meairs, the old Long
Beach Nitehawk manager, recalls the time in the late 1940s when his
team was in a softball tournament in Davenport, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a day off, and took the train over to Chicago to watch
Lem pitch against the White Sox,'' recalls Meairs, a 1941 Wilson
High graduate. ``We all visited him at the hotel before the game,
and he wouldn't let us go. And then he paid for all of our tickets
to the game. That was Lem. A very kind, generous person.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like an end of an era for me. I've known Lem every
since I was a kid. Heck, I grew up at 10th and Belmont and he grew
up at 10th and Ximeno. We used to play touch football all the time
around Wilson High, and years later after baseball games we used to
go over to Pop Lemon's gas station at Fourth and Termino and have
some sandwiches and beers together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the Navy with Lem, and we were stationed together for
a time at the Los Alamitos Navy Base. We had a heck of a baseball
team. Lem and I had so much fun together. He took me to the Hall of
Fame in Cooperstown about five years ago, and we had a blast. Great
memories with Lem. Nothing but great memories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Lemon might have been the most down to earth guy ever,''
says Jerry Gardner, the venerable scout for the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays who graduated from Jordan High in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview I had with Bob Lemon last year at Phil
Trani's, the old baseball player said he knew the hours were
drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't betray a hint of depression.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ol' Lem seemed quite content that glad afternoon, as he
puffed happily on a cigarette and sipped an alcoholic beverage with
practiced deliberation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
