<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CAMAPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SOFT-MONEY NEGOTIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, Jan. 13: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The campaign managers for Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudolph
Giuliani have begun a tentative discussion about eliminating soft
money from the Senate contest in New York. It is in the interest of
both sides to ban these unregulated expenditures. The talks between
Bruce Teitelbaum of the Giuliani campaign and Bill de Blasio of the
Clinton campaign got off to a positive start and should not end
with the testy letters the two exchanged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, absent an agreement, is that the need to raise a lot
of money will be taken as a license by both campaigns to engage in
financing schemes that circumvent federal limits on large donations
to individual candidates. Enforcement of the fund-raising limits by
the Justice Department and the Federal Election Commission now
verges on nonexistent, heightening the temptation to cheat. New
Yorkers, however, like voters elsewhere, have a right to expect
contests for powerful positions to be waged on higher ethical
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The early signs in this campaign were not encouraging. Giuliani
used New York City's tourist agency, NYC &AMP; Co., to run radio ads in
the city and upstate using the mayor's voice. Moreover, for much of
the past two years, Giuliani collected money through two political
committees that are subject to more lenient fund-raising
restrictions than his official Senate campaign committee. Using a
federal ``leadership account,'' Solutions America, and another
fund-raising committee established under lax New York rules to aid
elections to state offices like governor, Giuliani was able to
raise more than $800,000 from donors who would otherwise have
reached the $2,000 limit for his Senate campaign committee. The
committees shared at least one major fund-raising event, as well as
rent, administrative costs and salaries, including that of the
mayor's chief political aide, Teitelbaum. Apparently, the mayor
largely stopped raising and spending money through the two
committees after April 1999, when he formally notified the Federal
Election Commission that he might run for the United States Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, meanwhile, has exacerbated fears of a fall
campaign run in large part outside the normal federal limits by
aggressively channeling big, unregulated soft-money donations to a
special party ``victory fund'' to help pay for television spots
promoting her Senate candidacy. Giuliani, to his credit, has not
begun raising or spending soft money. But without a soft-money
truce, evasive fund-raising by both sides would inevitably spiral
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Now both candidates seem to agree in principle to a ban on soft
money. De Blasio broke the ice Wednesday by phoning Teitelbaum. In
a follow-up letter, Teitelbaum said that Mrs. Clinton should repay
the Democratic Party for the nearly $400,000 in ads it ran for her
this summer. De Blasio fired back by citing Giuliani's suspect
committees and the NYC &AMP; Co. ads, and accused the Giuliani campaign
of rejecting further talks. Such posturing is understandable in any
political negotiation, but the matter should not end there.
Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton should instruct their managers to meet
and agree that neither of the national parties will be allowed to
flood New York with advertising financed by soft money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
