<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION PLANS ON SCHEDULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With hopes the whole world will be watching in
seven months, officials planning the Democratic National Convention
in Los Angeles said Wednesday they are on schedule for the August
event nominating their next presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, can the trains run on time?'' said Lydia
Camarillo, chief executive officer of the event. ``We are confident
they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working closely with the mayor, the Department of
Transportation, Caltrans, the Police Department and the Secret
Service and everything is on track.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-day event will involve some 4,600 delegates and more
than 17,000 media staying in 84 hotels in six cities in and around
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At ground zero for all the attention will be the Staples Center,
which Joe Andrew, national chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, said has exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is such a new building wired for modern technology,
Andrew said the arena will allow Democrats to reach out beyond the
traditional media to include broad Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone in Florida wants to see what their delegation is
doing, they will be able to hook in immediately,'' Andrew said.
``If they are concerned about an issue, they will be able to track
where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said he is particularly pleased at the selection of Los
Angeles with its diverse population and emphasis on new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a convention that looks like and reflects
America,'' Andrew said. The party's nominee probably will be known
long before the convention, but Andrew said the party will not
attempt to make it simply an entertainment spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be about content and what the Democratic agenda is
for the next four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew also disputed accounts of any problems with the Los
Angeles Host Committee, which has promised to provide some
$33.5million in cash and services to offset the cost of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The host committee has done everything we have asked of it and
has been there when we needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
