u s BC-GOLF-MARTIN-NYT     01-13 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-MARTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN RIDING INTO THE PGA TOUR AND UNDER A WORLDWIDE MICROSCOPE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To reach the PGA Tour, Casey Martin has persevered through legal
battles, a painful disease, and intense media attention that has
made him a household name.
</P>
<P>
   So when Martin begins his rookie season at next week's Bob Hope
Chrysler Classic, excuse him for being nervous, as well as excited.
After successfully suing the tour in 1998 for the right to use a
golf cart during competition, Martin is about to realize a dream.
But once again, he will be playing under a worldwide microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most stressful thing I deal with is the fear of failure,''
said Martin, who suffers from Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber syndrome, a
disease that affects circulation in his right leg. ``I don't want
to let people down. I've played well enough to make the PGA Tour,
and I hope and pray I will be able to continue playing as well as
I'm capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who spoke on a conference call from his hometown of
Eugene, Ore., earned his PGA Tour card by finishing among the top
15 winners on last year's Nike Tour, a satellite tour a level below
the PGA Tour. But Martin's long-term future remains uncertain. He
still deals with intense pain in his fragile right leg, and one
wrong step could lead to the end of his career. ``I'm at a high
risk for a fracture,'' Martin said. ``If I were to twist my leg, it
could break. My leg in the tibia region is very weak, which is why
I'm very grateful to have the buggy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin won the right to play on the PGA Tour when a federal
judge in Eugene granted an injunction that required the Tour to
furnish him with a cart at all of its events, as well as those on
its satellite tour. At the time, he was the first professional
athlete to successfully sue under the Americans With Disabilities
Act for a change in a sports organization's playing rules.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour has filed an appeal, and a decision on the appeal
is expected some time this year. If the Tour wins the appeal,
Martin will consider further legal action, because the cart has
become a necessity for him to compete consistently with the world's
best players.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not walked a round of golf since late in 1997.
``It has been a long time,'' he said. ``I hope and pray I don't
have to find out, but I don't know if I could go 72 holes or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a decline in my leg the last five or six years,
however we've noticed that since I've been riding, the
deterioration has kind of leveled. It hasn't gotten any better, but
it hasn't gotten any worse either. I think that's due to the fact
that there's less wear and tear.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has also entered the Phoenix Open the week following the
Bob Hope, and he said he tentatively plans to play around 25
events. Tour players are divided on the Martin issue, with some who
feel he should be given a cart, while others believe that the Tour,
not the courts, should govern the rules of the game.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Martin is not worried about how he will be received on
tour, and he scoffs at the notion that a cart gives him an unfair
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had any problems with the guys on the Nike Tour,''
said Martin, who will be reunited on the PGA Tour with two former
Stanford teammates, Tiger Woods and Notah Begay. ``Not everyone
agreed with it, but I never had one problem,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played with the PGA Tour guys enough to know, but I
don't anticipate any problems. There might be some, you never know.
I'll be able to answer that question better in a month,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk more than you might think during a round. A lot of
times you can't really get close to a green. I read one paper that
said I would walk zero, but that's ridiculous. I walk a
considerable amount, and there's no top to the cart, so if it's
raining or hot, I'm totally exposed, which is good.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Martin has shown an ability to play his best under
pressure, both on the Nike Tour, and during the 1998 U.S. Open,
when he tied for 23rd, finishing higher than Vijay Singh, Mark
O'Meara, Justin Leonard and Ernie Els.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Martin will begin testing his game at the highest
level. And while he is uncertain how he will fare, he is grateful
for the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill, but it's a challenge,'' said Martin. ``Most
people don't deal with the kind of attention I deal with until
they've won majors or shot 59 to win tournaments. But I've grown
accustomed to it. When I tee it up next week, it will be like a
dream come true.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
