<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SNOWSHOEING-ART-NYT &LR;      01-13 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOWSHOEING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOWSHOEING: DISCOVERING FLAT-FOOTED FUN AT ALTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Utah, N.Y., N.J., Calif., Wis.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wendy Miller, an activities coordinator at Snowbird, Utah, was
leading a small group of people on snowshoes last month along a
mountain trail. The pace was easy because of the resort's
8,000-foot altitude. Most of the guests had just come from
sea-level destinations and were still adapting to the thin air.
</P>
<P>
   But one man kept disappearing into the woods, and Miller was
concerned. ``Snowshoeing is a great activity for people who don't
ski to get on the mountain,'' Miller said. ``Some people are afraid
of skiing, and some are even afraid of being in the mountains. But
I found out that the man who kept going off the trail had once
hiked the Himalayas. He was just trying out the snowshoes to see
how they felt. So I let him go ahead on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The story reflects the widespread allure of snowshoeing, which
is drawing converts at every level. Ski areas, many for the first
time, are including snowshoes in their rental inventory. And at
least two national programs are touting what they see as the
fitness benefits of the shoe that walks _ or runs _ on snow.
</P>
<P>
   The national programs, a 12-week Venture-Reebok/WinterFit
instructional series and Winter Trails 2000, a free introductory
snowshoe fest this Saturday at 14 sites around the country, bespeak
the major marketing and sponsorship clout behind snowshoeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snowshoes offer the best transition from a workout club
environment to something more interesting than being inside all
winter,'' said Gary Johnson, a fitness expert for Reebok, the
athletic equipment company. ``They're comfortable and easy to learn
how to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok has joined forces this year with Tubbs, the snowshoe
company based in Stowe, Vt., to offer its program in various gyms
and ski resorts. Besides Snowbird, snowshoe fitness classes are on
the schedule at Mountain Creek Resort, N.J.; Stratton Mountain,
Vt., and Catamount, N.Y. In addition, health clubs, such as the
Sports Mall Gym in Salt Lake City, begin aerobic preparations
indoors before urging people outside.
</P>
<P>
   The fitness component of snowshoeing is still being discovered.
A recent study by the University of Vermont reveals that
snowshoeing's movement is similar to running but without the same
physiological impact.
</P>
<P>
   The results indicated that, over a six-week period, snowshoeing
turned out to be better training for runners than running.
Researchers found that snowshoeing can burn up to 45 percent more
calories than walking or running at the same pace.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's surge in popularity began in the 1990s. The Sporting
Goods Manufacturers Association, a national trade group, estimates
that 1.7 million people tried snowshoeing at least once in 1998.
That compares to 7 million skateboarders and 5.4 million
snowboarders that same year.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the snowshoe craze comes from new technology that has
made snowshoes smaller and lighter than the five-foot-long bear paw
designs used by Alaskan fur trappers 50 years ago. Tubbs, for
example, now makes 27 different models, including snowshoes for
running. They range in price from $100 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting solid material where the old snowshoes were made
with hide lacing,'' said Kathy Murphy, marketing director for
Tubbs. ``The new materials are lightweight and practically
bulletproof.''
</P>
<P>
   Other manufacturers have come up with innovative designs created
for children. They include the T-Rex Snowshoe by Yuba, crafted in
the shape of a dinosaur foot, and the Snowpaw Snowshoe by
Redfeather, which is made to look like the print of an abominable
snowman.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Trails 2000 event Saturday includes free snowshoe
lessons and equipment demonstrations at resorts such as Gore
Mountain, North Creek, N.Y.; Eagle Mountain at Lake Tahoe, Calif.;
the High Point X-C Center at Sussex, N.J., and the Tyrol Ski Basin,
Mt. Horeb, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Snowshoeing takes about a six-inch snow base compared to about
two feet for skiing. But with a dearth of snow at many resort areas
this winter, organizers of Winter Trails suggest checking in with
the event's Web site at www.snowlink.com, or by telephoning the
American Hiking Society at (888) sno-hike. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 0013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
