<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HAMILTON-     01-13 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HAMILTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN FRANCISCO _ Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich returned to the
visitors' locker room in Sacramento in a rush Tuesday and, with a
quick order, cleared out everyone but his players. By the time one
of the strangest moments of this odd season had echoed through the
halls, he had one less player.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Rockets left Sacramento with their seventh consecutive
road loss, center Thomas Hamilton remained behind. He will be cut
today, having all but dared Tomjanovich to set him free from what
sources said he called his unfair persecution by the Rockets coach
in a long, loud and often incoherent soliloquy.
</P>
<P>
   In front of stunned teammates, sources said, Hamilton told
Tomjanovich, ``Do what you have to do.'' Now the ranks of healthy
centers on the Rockets' roster will be reduced solely to a player
signed to a 10-day contract last week,
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Rockets began searching for Hamilton's
replacement, and the team could add a player as soon as today.
Former Celtics and Clippers forward Marty Conlon, former Celtics
and Rockets center Eric Riley, and former Timberwolves center Bill
Curley are among players available.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's official release will end the Rockets' experiment
with a 7-2, 330-pound enigma whose potential had intrigued them but
gone untapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was best for the team,'' said Tomjanovich, who would
offer little else about Hamilton's brief tenure with the Rockets or
Tuesday's last straw.
</P>
<P>
   But because he was determined to cut ties quickly, Tomjanovich
said he had to make the move despite the Rockets' injury woes at
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around the league a long time and have seen some
crazy things,'' forward Matt Bullard said, declining to discuss any
of the conversations in the postgame meeting. ``It's too bad he
(Hamilton) chose to do that. He's got some skills we can use. But
if you're not with the team mentally, you can't have that kind of
player. He had a great situation if he worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just weird, one of the strangest situations I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's departure leaves a void in the middle nearly as large
as he is.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rogers, forced to play center since Kelvin Cato sprained
his right wrist Dec. 30, sprained his right thumb Tuesday night. He
would have been unavailable tonight anyway because of the funeral
of a brother who died Saturday. He is questionable for Saturday's
game in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon isn't due back from hernia surgery until
Saturday at the earliest. Cato is not expected back until next
week. Tony Massenburg, out since Nov. 25 with a strained groin,
might not come back this season at all.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Anthony ``Pig'' Miller, signed to a 10-day contract
Jan. 6, as the only healthy center on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets were only too happy to exchange a ``Pig'' for
``Big Ham'' after Tuesday's bizarre scene.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 24, had shown previous dissatisfaction with his
often-limited role. But when Tomjanovich called Hamilton and four
other players into the game with four minutes left Tuesday,
Hamilton remained seated until Tomjanovich insisted he play. Once
in the game with Kings fans mocking him heartily, Hamilton seemed
angry and disinterested.
</P>
<P>
   First he failed to notice a pass from Shandon Anderson. Then,
when Hamilton failed to get a pass from Cuttino Mobley, he rolled
his eyes, looked at the ceiling and trudged out of the low post to
the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich called time out and asked Hamilton, ``Do you want to
play?'' Failing to get an answer, Tomjanovich said, ``I asked you a
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton remained in the game. But though usually among the last
to dress and leave the locker room, he was dressed and meeting with
Tomjanovich minutes after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Hamilton screamed that Tomjanovich had singled him
out for criticism and not given him a fair chance. He was also said
to have complained about his recent lack of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who had started seven of his 22 games, played 21
minutes last week against Miami, scoring seven points with seven
rebounds. But he was scoreless in three minutes against the Jazz on
Saturday and had two points and no rebounds in his four minutes
Tuesday. He averaged 3.7 points and 4.1 rebounds with the Rockets
this season.
</P>
<P>
   When he trained, Hamilton was said to be an extremely hard
worker and was considered among the Rockets' strongest players. But
he often fell off his conditioning program entirely.
</P>
<P>
   He had begun to develop a jump hook that Rockets vice president
Carroll Dawson had shown him and had said it would become a staple
of his game. But because of his weight, he was unable to match up
with quicker centers and struggled to get the elevation needed on
many shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets signed Hamilton to a two-year, $1.1 million
contract. But the second season was at the team's option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing to see, because he really doesn't know how
much talent he has,'' Miller said. ``There's a lot he could bring
to the game. I've been in situations like him, going into games
with four minutes left. That's what the coaches look at, trying to
see how hard you're going to play those last four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he was upset. He felt like he should have been in
there earlier. It's a messed-up situation, because he could have
helped us. He's a big fella. He's young. He lost a lot of weight
over the summer. It was starting to pay off for him. He just needed
to keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's departure from the Rockets was the latest in a series
of brushes with opportunity that have not panned out. A 1993
graduate of Martin Luther King High School in Chicago, he went to
the University of Pittsburgh but left before he ever played college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He played 11 games for the Celtics late in the 1995-96 season,
averaging 2.3 points and two rebounds. He has also gone through
training camps with the Bulls, Heat and Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   He is six months into a 36-month probation after agreeing to a
plea bargain for possession of 40 grams of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's departure left the Rockets with only nine healthy
players, including two, Miller and Devin Gray, on 10-day contracts.
Miller, Bullard and Kenny Thomas are the only centers or power
forwards available tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, man,'' Bullard said. ``You get tested in different
ways. This is sort of our test _ if we can stay together and stay
positive through everything. We've had unbelievable bad luck,
injuries, guys going down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're holding together great. Any other team would
have fallen apart. We're still upbeat, having fun. We're passing
the test so far.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a test that grows more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to win,'' guard Steve Francis said. ``You can
see it in everybody's eyes. Everybody wants to win, and it's hard.
We're starting over again.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
