<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4753 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-VIKINGS-HNS &LR;      01-13 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Minnesota Vikings know what it's like to be the St. Louis Rams
right now.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, the Vikings were coming off a first-round playoff
bye after whipping up on opponents all season. They had the most
prolific offense the league had seen in years. Defenses weren't
even coming close as they surged to a 15-1 regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Randall Cunningham, while certainly not new to the
league, was having a career season, and with Randy Moss and Cris
Carter as targets, it seemed the Vikings couldn't be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Until they ran into Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Vikings hope to pull an Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be a motivational factor for them,'' said St. Louis
coach Dick Vermeil, whose team will host Minnesota in a divisional
playoff game Sunday. ``They got so close and were so dominating,
and then they didn't get it done. I think our team would feel the
same way. That sticks with you for a long time. You never lose that
or erase that thought. It's got to be a motivator for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Vikings scored an NFL-record 556 points. The
rate of production slowed this year, but the Vikings still finished
third in the NFL in yards and fifth in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vikings have a lot of firepower on offense, and so do
we,'' Rams vice president of personnel Charley Armey said. ``The
Vikings have a lot of weapons, just like we do. You're going to
have two teams with great speed on that field. It really should be
something to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings think they're better equipped to pull an upset than
even the Falcons were last year. The Vikings are a more
well-balanced team than they were last season, with running back
Robert Smith running as well as ever. Smith, who played much of the
early season with a double hernia before missing three games after
surgery, was named the NFL's Offensive Player of the Week after
rushing for 140 yards and catching three passes for 58 yards and a
touchdown in Minnesota's wild-card victory over Dallas on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When teams double-team Moss or Carter, the Vikings have found a
way to get the ball into Smith's hands, be it via a screen pass or
a running play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have receivers like this, it's hard not to try to get
them the ball,'' Smith conceded. ``I don't remember any stretch in
my career where I've gotten the ball 20, 25 times so many games in
a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Four times in the last five weeks, the Vikings have run more
than they've passed. During that span, Smith has averaged 111 yards
on 21 rushes, a 5.3-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our style of play has moved more toward two tight ends and
more toward the run formation over the last four games,'' Minnesota
coach Dennis Green said. ``We think that's really our biggest
weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hard to believe with a team that features one of the most
prolific receiving tandems in NFL history in Moss and Carter, but
perhaps Minnesota is taking a cue from the Falcons. Atlanta's
strategy last year was to run the ball, and the clock, keeping
Minnesota's explosive offense on the sideline as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Rams) could be the Vikings of '98,'' Moss said.
``But some bad things happened to the Vikings of '98.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are hoping the more balanced attack they used to
beat the Cowboys will add a dimension they didn't show when they
faced Atlanta last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sent out an alert,'' Vermeil said. ``We saw how well
Minnesota can run the ball against a good defensive front.
Obviously, Dallas was playing a seven-man front and
(double-covered) those receivers, so they weren't including the
safeties in run defense. But Smith did a heck of a job. They really
beat them running the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   This St. Louis team has no playoff experience, and the Vikings
are hoping that will give them an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's far more pressure than you've been under, and you do
get nervous, and you do have anxiety, and you do have concerns,''
Carter said. ``The only teams that say experience is not vital are
the teams that don't have any.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process that Dallas went through with San Francisco.
It's a process that Green Bay went through with Dallas. It's a
process that we went through with Green Bay and also that Denver
went through. And all those teams, they had experience. And if you
look at last year's Super Bowl, I think that Denver's experience
outweighed Atlanta's.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons also proved last year that an underdog can come
in and steal a game in a hostile arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of people are going to use that against St.
Louis, and I'm sure they're tired of hearing about it,'' Smith
said. ``They're tired of hearing about how they don't have
experience, how they didn't play anybody in the regular season, all
those things. To me, they don't mean a whole lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new season. They've got talented players. We've
got talented players. It's time to suit up and play and let
everybody else on the outside worry about what's going to happen in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
