<HEADLINE>
FOR YORK, MAGIC NUMBER IS SEVEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Today, jockey Ray York makes history. If all
goes right, the 66-year-old resident of Taft will hop aboard
Culebra in the eighth race at Santa Anita and become the first
jockey to ride in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait,'' York said. ``It's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   York, who rode his first race in June, 1949, as a 15-year-old
fresh off the farm, entered the Southern California racing scene at
the same time as the legendary Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually rode my first race when I was still 15,'' York said
in a recent interview. ``I never thought I'd be riding
thoroughbreds, I wanted to be a cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rounding up cattle, York rounded up wins on the race
circuit. In his career, he won 3,082 races, including the 1954
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Derby was one of the greatest thrills of my life,'' York
said. ``I probably could have done better (in my career), but I
didn't have any brains at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Saturday's $300,000 Grade II San Fernando
Breeder's Cup Handicap could attract seven or more horses.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to run in the 1 1/16-mile event is Cat
Thief, winner of the Breeders' Cup Classic. Not to be overlooked,
though, are the Bob Baffert-trained General Challenge and Straight
Man or John Shirreffs' Cliquot among others.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, for one, is confident about his chances Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe (General Challenge's) win in the Native Diver is a sign
of things to come,'' Baffert said. ``This horse is just so
talented. He's earned $1.6 million just fooling around. ''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Baffert, who turns 47 today, said Wednesday he plans
to run Kentucky Derby prospect Captain Steve in the Jan. 30 Santa
Catalina Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   __ The one to catch: Entering Wednesday's races, jockey Kent
Desormeaux remained in the top spot among Santa Anita riders.
Desormeaux had 14 winners, followed by Patrick Valenzuela and David
Flores with 10 each.
</P>
<P>
   Among trainers, Baffert led the pack with seven wins. Ron
McAnally was in second place with six.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
