<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     01-13 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DRAFT OF ISRAEL-SYRIA TREATY REPORTED IN ISRAELI NEWSPAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to change time element throughout story; subs lead graf to
change wording, other small editing changes throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Israeli newspaper on Thursday published what it
said was a draft peace treaty framed by the Clinton administration
for Israel and Syria, laying out marked differences between the two
sides on the most difficult issues of borders and security.
</P>
<P>
   There were few surprises in the document, which appeared in
Haaretz. It was described on Thursday night by diplomats familiar
with the negotiations as a working tool that was not intended to be
definitive.
</P>
<P>
   On the most vexing issue, the border between Syria and Israel,
the document contains in brackets each side's well-known views of
how and where the border should be.
</P>
<P>
   The document describes Syria's position as ``based on the June
4, 1967, line.'' This is a reference to the border at the time of
the 1967 war, when Israel seized the Golan Heights from Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's position is described as ``taking into account security
and other vital interests of the parties as well as legal
considerations of both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Another stark difference in the document, which has also been
well-known, is how an early-warning station on Mount Hermon in the
Golan Heights would be operated. The core of the negotiations have
centered on whether Israel would be prepared to give up the Golan
Heights to Syria and, if Israel were to do that, how it could
ensure that its security would not be threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The draft treaty published on Thursday says that the Israelis
want an early-warning ground station on Mount Hermon to be manned
``with an effective Israeli presence.'' On the other hand, the
document says, the Syrians want it ``operated by the United States
and France under their total auspices and responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Successive Israeli governments have insisted that an
early-warning system on Mount Hermon was a key ingredient of a
peace settlement and that it must be manned by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   If the security conflicts can be resolved, the document points
to diplomatic actions that would be included in a treaty. It says
the countries would agree to end their state of war and enter into
``honorable, friendly and good neighborly relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, both would ``establish full diplomatic and consular
relations, including exchanges of resident ambassadors,'' the
document says.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats stressed on Wednesday night that the document
represented the American negotiators' best understanding of each
side's position. It was intended for both sides to consider before
returning to the talks that are set to resume in Washington next
week.
</P>
<P>
   But the document as published in Haaretz was missing several
elements from a document that President Clinton gave to the Israeli
prime minister, Ehud Barak, and the Syrian foreign minister, Farouk
al-Shara, last Sunday night, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   A rough timeline that had been included in that document was not
published, and the Israeli newspaper did not publish a disclaimer
that appeared on every page of the original, the diplomats said.
The disclaimer said that the document was intended as a working
tool and was not final.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of disagreement in the document concerned the
demilitarized zone to be established on either side of the new
border.
</P>
<P>
   For the Israelis, the zone encompassed ``both the area from
which Israeli forces will be relocated and the existing area of
separation established under the Agreement on Disengagement between
Israel and Syrian Forces of May 31, 1974.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Syrians, the document said that the demilitarized zone
would be ``of equal scope on both sides of the border.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the talks, which were held in Shepherdstown,
W.Va., the Clinton administration said that the two sides had been
given a document devised by the American negotiators as a way of
identifying the gaps between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Shara were encouraged by Clinton to come back
with responses for the resumption of the talks next Wednesday. Both
the Israeli leader and the Syrian foreign minister had to return
home to test the temperature of their domestic constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, more than 100,000 people rallied against giving up
the Golan Heights on Monday night, and new public opinion polls
show more resistance to a peace plan with Syria than had been
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Shara, who is representing the Syrian president, Hafez Assad,
returned home to consult with Assad, who is the decision maker on
the Syrian side.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has sought to hold the draft treaty
as tightly as possible, though there were qualms that it would
finally leak out in the Israeli press. The American negotiators had
stressed that they were concerned that making the document public
would make already stressful negotiations much more difficult
because any change in position from the published text would sound
like a concession.
</P>
<P>
   At the time that American officials offered their ``working
paper,'' they said they were not laying out new proposals for
resolving the toughest issues. They said such proposals would be
counterproductive so early.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
