<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4759 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-GOLF-PREVIEW-TEX     01-13 1923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 GOLF SEASON ROARS IN WITH FULL COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new season in professional golf is in full swing with some
familiar faces in new places, as well as some old reliables trying
to top past achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who concluded last season with four consecutive
victories, built on his record-setting success from 1999 in
Sunday's final round of the Mercedes Championships. With his
victory, Woods, 24, became the first golfer in 52 years to win five
consecutive PGA Tour events. The only golfers to post longer
winning streaks are two Fort Worth legends, Byron Nelson (11 in
1945) and Ben Hogan (six in 1948).
</P>
<P>
   While Woods tries to approach his tour-best totals of eight
victories and $6.6 million in earnings from last season, two Texans
who combined for 40 career victories as PGA Tour participants will
move on to the next level. Lanny Wadkins and Tom Kite will be
rookies this season on the Senior PGA Tour. Both turned 50 in
December and are eligible to begin competition in the first
full-field event of the season, the Royal Caribbean Classic (Feb.
4-6).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the home courses of the MasterCard Colonial and GTE
Byron Nelson Classic have undergone some off-season tweaks to make
them more challenging for PGA Tour participants in May.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the faces and places worth tracking in the
professional golf world in 2000:
</P>
<P>
   Inside the numbers
0 _ Tournaments in Fort Worth-Dallas on the 2000 LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   3 _ Tournaments in Fort Worth-Dallas on the 2000 PGA or Senior
PGA tours.
</P>
<P>
   7 _ Tournaments in Texas on the 2000 PGA, Senior PGA or LPGA
tours.
</P>
<P>
   8 _ Victories by Tiger Woods in 1999, most on the PGA Tour in 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   9 _ Texans ranked among the top 75 players in the world golf
rankings, including Southlake resident Brandt Jobe (No. 62).
</P>
<P>
   13 _ Players from Tarrant County competing on the PGA, Senior
PGA, LPGA or Buy.com tours.
</P>
<P>
   15 _ Texans with LPGA Tour cards.
</P>
<P>
   34 _ Texans with Buy.com Tour cards.
</P>
<P>
   35 _ Texans with PGA Tour cards.
</P>
<P>
   35 _ Texans with Senior PGA Tour cards.
</P>
<P>
   50 _ Events on the 2000 PGA Tour schedule.
</P>
<P>
   $1.4 million _ Prize money at the Bank One Championship (Sept.
22-24, Dallas).
</P>
<P>
   $3.3 million _ Prize money at the MasterCard Colonial (May
18-21, Fort Worth).
</P>
<P>
   $3.5 million _ Prize money at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic (May
11-14, Irving).
</P>
<P>
   $8.2 million _ Combined prize money at tours in Fort
Worth-Dallas.
National story lines
1. Topping the latest Tiger tale. Tiger Woods won eight PGA Tour
events last season, the most in 25 years. He earned $6,616,585, a
single-season record that almost doubled runner-up David Duval's
total ($3.64 million). In 1999, Woods also won his second major
championship (PGA), contributed to the greatest comeback victory in
Ryder Cup history and celebrated his 24th birthday. He began this
season with his fifth consecutive victory, behind only Ben Hogan
(6) and Byron Nelson (11) on the consecutive victories list. What
does Woods do for an encore? Is an encore possible?
</P>
<P>
   2. LPGA Tour celebrates its 50th anniversary. It stands as the
longest-running women's professional sports organization in the
world. A yearlong celebration begins with tomorrow's ``LPGA Night
of Champions'' dinner honoring the organization's 13 founders in
conjunction with the season-opening event, The Office Depot
Championship (today through Sunday), in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   3. Great venues make for great championships (hopefully). Three
of the four major championships will be contested on some of the
world's most hallowed courses. In addition to the Masters
Tournament at Augusta National Golf Club in Augusta, Ga., the U.S.
Open returns to Pebble Beach Golf Links in California, and the
British Open will be played at St. Andrews, the birthplace of golf.
</P>
<P>
   4. Rookies ready to rock Senior PGA Tour. Tom Kite and Lanny
Wadkins, who combined for 40 victories and two major championships
as PGA Tour competitors, join the 50-and-over circuit this season.
Tom Watson, a 34-event winner and eight-time major champion on the
PGA Tour, will spend his first full season on the Senior Tour after
becoming eligible in September.
</P>
<P>
   5. Casey Martin rolls on. By finishing in the top 15 on last
year's Nike Tour (now Buy.com Tour), the golfer, who has a physical
disability, earned full-time playing privileges on the PGA Tour in
2000. That means his golf cart could be headed to Colonial ...
unless an appeals court overturns the ruling that allowed him to
use the cart in competition, beginning in 1998. A ruling from the
appeals court is expected within the next two months. Martin has
said his physical condition (a circulatory disorder in his right
leg) has worsened to the point that walking 72 holes over four days
no longer is an option.
Tarrant County story lines
1. Mark Brooks returns to the scene of his greatest triumph.
Brooks, a Fort Worth resident, won the 1996 PGA Championship at
Valhalla Golf Club in Louisville, Ky., by beating Kenny Perry in a
sudden-death playoff. It stands as the only major championship won
by a Tarrant Country resident since Ben Hogan prevailed at the 1953
British Open. The PGA Championship returns to Valhalla (Aug. 17-20)
for the first time since Brooks' victory, and Brooks is exempt into
the field.
</P>
<P>
   2. John Grace's world tour. Grace, a Fort Worth resident, is a
nonexempt member of the Senior PGA Tour. But he has an exemption on
the European Senior Tour, largely because of strong finishes at the
1999 British Senior Open (12th) and 1999 Energis Senior Masters
(seventh). Grace plans to hone his game overseas, as much as time
and finances will allow, in hopes of landing a full-time berth on
the U.S. circuit in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   3. Greg Gregory's big chance. Gregory, a Burleson resident and
former UT-Arlington player who has been a regular on Texas-based
minitours in recent years, earned playing privileges on the Buy.com
Tour. It marks the first time that Gregory, 26, has had the
opportunity to compete regularly on one of the country's two
largest professional golf tours. Gregory caught the eye of local
golf fans by qualifying to compete in the 1999 U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   4. Hunter Haas gets his Masters moment. Haas, a Fort Worth
resident, earned a spot in the 2000 Masters by winning the 1999
U.S. Amateur Public Links Championship. Haas, the 1998 Big 12
individual champ while playing at Oklahoma, also reached the
semifinals of the 1999 U.S. Amateur. As part of his Masters
experience, Haas has lined up a practice round with Arnold Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   5. Colonial toughens its course. As part of a $4.5 million
renovation project announced in 1998, Colonial Country Club
officials have rebuilt all 18 greens and more than 80 bunkers since
the final putt dropped at the 1999 MasterCard Colonial. In
addition, the championship tees were pushed back at hole Nos. 9 and
14, six new fairway bunkers were added and 70 new trees were
planted. Officials at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic have tweaked the
TPC Las Colinas course as well, with tees lengthened at the sixth,
10th and 15th holes for the 2000 event. In addition, 1,500 new
trees have been planted and spectator mounts have been built to the
right of the 17th hole.
International story lines
1. Sergio Garcia's globetrotting. The Spanish teen-ager, who
finished second to Tiger Woods at the 1999 PGA Championship, earned
playing privileges on both the PGA Tour and European Tour for the
2000 season. Garcia, 19, said he plans to compete on both tours in
his first full season as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   2. Grace Park's expectations. A native of South Korea who won
the 1999 NCAA individual championship at Arizona State, Park will
be a 20-year-old rookie on the LPGA Tour. The last 20-year-old
rookie from South Korea was Se Ri Pak, who won two majors in her
inaugural season (1998). In the estimation of peers, Park may be a
more complete player at 20 than Pak.
</P>
<P>
   3. Karrie Webb's defense of her Triple Crown. Webb, a native of
Australia, set LPGA records for season earnings ($1,591,959) and
lowest season scoring average (69.43) in 1999. By winning six times
and posting 22 top-10 finishes, she also accumulated more points
(337.29) while winning the Rolex Player of the Year Award than any
predecessor. Webb, 25, also won her first major championship (du
Maurier Classic). What does she do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   4. Memories beckon at British Open. Because of the calendar and
the location, officials at the 2000 British Open at St. Andrews
have encouraged as many past champions as possible to return for
one final farewell at the turn of the century. Jack Nicklaus and
Lee Trevino, among others, are expected to take part. Arnold Palmer
said he is considering a trip to St. Andrews, but has no plans to
attend at present.
</P>
<P>
   5. In pursuit of 58. Until May 1998, only two rounds of 59 had
been recorded in the history of professional golf. Since then,
we've had three. The most recent was David Duval's 59 during the
final round of the 1999 Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, which sealed a
comeback victory. Can 58 be far behind? If so, who will be the
first to do it?
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County touring pros These touring professionals list
Tarrant County addresses for the 2000 season and have playing
privileges on the PGA, Senior PGA, LPGA or Buy.com tours. Some
players might compete on more than one tour, depending on their
exemption status: Player City Tour Alan Bratton Fort Worth PGA Mark
Brooks Fort Worth PGA Clark Dennis Fort Worth PGA Brandt Jobe
Southlake PGA Bob Eastwood Fort Worth PGA Senior John Grace Fort
Worth PGA Senior Chuck Lindley Euless PGA Senior Keoke Cotner
Colleyville Buy.com Greg Gregory Burleson Buy.com Kelly Grunewald
Arlington Buy.com J.J. Henry Fort Worth Buy.com Brian Wilson Fort
Worth Buy.com Missie McGeorge Southlake LPGA
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to watch
1. Tom Kite: Turned 50 in December, should be major force on Senior
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lanny Wadkins: Turned 50 in December, should be major force
on Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   3. Grace Park: Most heralded LPGA rookie in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   4. Casey Martin: Earned his first PGA Tour card, but the courts
will decide how long he keeps his cart.
</P>
<P>
   5. Gary Nicklaus: Jack's son, 30, earned his first PGA Tour
card.
</P>
<P>
   6. Hank Kuehne: Former SMU standout will play most of rookie
season on Buy.com Tour.
</P>
<P>
   7. Andy North: Two-time U.S. Open champ joins Senior Tour on
March 9.
</P>
<P>
   8. Rex Caldwell: San Antonio resident joins Senior Tour on May
5.
</P>
<P>
   9. Jean Van de Velde: British Open runner-up plans to play more
in U.S. in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   10. Jim Simons: Former phenom on PGA Tour joins Senior Tour on
May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces to monitor
1. David Duval: Leaner, hungrier after extensive off-season work
with weights.
</P>
<P>
   2. Hale Irwin: Will rookie talent influx on Senior Tour cut into
his gravy train?
</P>
<P>
   3. Gil Morgan: Will rookie talent influx on Senior Tour cause us
to forget him entirely?
</P>
<P>
   4. Juli Inkster: LPGA's newest Hall of Famer hopes to build on
career year.
</P>
<P>
   5. Carlos Franco: Can Paraguay's favorite son repeat his
breakthrough '99 season?
</P>
<P>
   6. Ben Crenshaw: Can ``Captain Comeback'' resurrect his own
game?
</P>
<P>
   7. Hal Sutton: Life clearly began at 40 for Ryder Cup hero.
</P>
<P>
   8. Justin Leonard: His ``putt heard 'round the world'' sealed
1999 Ryder Cup comeback.
</P>
<P>
   9. Greg Norman: Is 45 too old to be considered a Masters
contender?
</P>
<P>
   10. Phil Mickelson: Will he reach 30 (June 16) without a major
title on his resume?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
