 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Jan. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokyo) _ More than any previous event in a history
full of serious mishaps, the nuclear accident in Japan last fall
rattled the coalition between industry and government that has long
made Japan the world's most ambitious user of nuclear energy.
Strikingly, in a country known for its political quiescence, the
sharp movement of public opinion against nuclear power has taken
the form of a genuine groundswell. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FOOD (Paris) _ The European Union is creating its own
version of the U.S. FDA to try to improve food safety. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLU-DRUG-DEATHS (Washington) _ The FDA is investigating to see
if doctors prescriptions of new antiflu drugs have played any role
in several deaths this season. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-INCINERATOR (East Liverpool, Ohio) _ Opponents of a
hazardous-waste incinerator that Al Gore first opposed as a vice
presidential candidate in 1992 are on his case again as the Ohio
primary approaches in March. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-PAY (Undated) _ A new study by Education Week documents
the yawning gap between the salaries of teachers and other
professionals, particularly those with advanced degrees. By Jacques
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NH-VOICES (Madbury, N.J.) _ In more than 50 interviews, voters
here were hard pressed to come up with a nagging issue upon which
they would select their candidate. Instead, in a contrast to four
or eight years ago, when voters were bursting with worries about
the economy, this year they seem relatively content. That leaves
them the luxury of tuning their political antenna on the personal
attributes of the candidates, their spouses, their parents and, in
case of Al Gore, their bosses. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
