<HEADLINE>
RICE STUNNED BY DEATH OF EX-TEAMMATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Glen Rice, his eyes red and his voice low, said he
was stunned Wednesday morning by the news that former Charlotte
Hornets teammate Bobby Phills had been killed in an auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson delivered the news to the Los Angeles Lakers
at their morning shootaround, and no one was more deeply affected
than Rice, who played alongside Phills for the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically still in shock, pretty much,'' Rice said before
tipoffagainst the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close. Bobby was the type of individual that was hard
not beclose to. He was a very friendly, very outgoing, very caring
individual. It's just, it's just sad when things like that happen
to good people, you know. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``(Phills) was one of the players that you could really say that
he thought of other people before he thought of himself, always put
other people in front of himself, a guy that was dedicated not only
on the basketball floor, but inside the community. He was
definitely one of the guys in the NBA that was a first-class
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Phills died Wednesday morning, the result of a
three-car collision that occurred on his way home from a
shootaround in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems really freakish,'' Rice said. ``That's a road that
former (Hornets) players like myself, we've all driven down time
after time, again and again. It's... It's very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice spoke with former teammate Matt Geiger, now playing for the
Philadelphia 76ers, but he had not yet phoned Phills' family.
</P>
<P>
   It was just last Friday that Rice and Phills chatted in L.A.,
before their teams played, and made plans to have their families
get together next month, when the Lakers play in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and his wife, they talked about the babies, we both
just hadbabies eight to 10 months ago. We talked about when we go
down to play Charlotte getting together and getting the babies
together. It's going to be sad that he's not going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Robert Horry is day-to-day after suffering a
broken nose in the fourth quarter Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Horry caught a Tim Thomas elbow with 6:40 remaining and went to
the locker room with a bloody nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I get out of the way. He (moved) so quick that I
couldn't get out of the way,'' Horry said. ``It wasn't on purpose.
He just turned around and I got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry said he expects to play Friday at Indiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
