<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCSIDE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ARE LATE, LETHARGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins misjudged traffic and arrived at
the Sports Arena a scant 30 minutes before tipoff _ approximately
45 minutes later than usual.
</P>
<P>
   They shouldn't have come at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were outted Wednesday in a 91-79 loss to USC _
outplayed, outhustled, and outcoached.
</P>
<P>
   It was their first city series loss since 1994 and their worst
since 1986, and they have just two days to recover before playing
North Carolina in the Dean Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently unaware the Mexican Olympic soccer team was playing
at the Coliseum at 7 p.m., the Bruins left Westwood at their
regular time and got stuck in brutal traffic as they approached
USC's campus.
</P>
<P>
   They usually arrive about 75 minutes before tipoff for road
games. Wednesday, they reached the Sports Arena 30 minutes before
tip _ just enough time to stretch and take a few shots.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the cause was traffic, lethargy or poor preparation, the
Bruins were not ready to play. They were confused by USC's changing
defenses and repeatedly failed to box out the high-flying Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA's biggest problem was an ill-prepared defense that
allowed USC to score at will. The Bruins played like they'd never
seen Brian Scalabrine pass to Sam Clancy in the post, yet it was
USC's regular offense.
</P>
<P>
   From first whistle to last, UCLA seemed surprised by USC's
aggressiveness, but it shouldn't have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half their guys wanted to come (to UCLA),'' Bruins freshman
Jason Kapono said before the game. ``They'll be fired up. They'll
be ready to ball, and we have to match that. They'll be thinking,
`Since the Bruins lost to Washington by two and we beat Washington,
that must mean we're better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be jacked up, sitting in first place. They'll be
pumped up. Their fan support will grow from 20 to 6,000.''
</P>
<P>
   USC was a slight favorite before tipoff, with just cause. The
Trojans had won six of their previous seven and swept the
Washington schools, while UCLA has struggled for weeks and lost in
Seattle in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite, underdog, success or failure in Seattle _ it mattered
not to UCLA. Its gaze, supposedly, was on first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to UCLA and you're not excited to play USC,
something's wrong,'' Bruins forward Sean Farnham said before the
game. ``The fact that they're 2-0 brings something (extra) to it,
not the fact they beat Washington and Washington State.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (9-4, 1-2) couldn't afford to lose Wednesday, fall
two games behind Arizona and retain a reasonable chance to win the
Pac-10 title. They lost a game they shouldn't have (Washington) and
now must get it back by beating a top team on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the conference, anywhere you can win on the road, that
gives you a distinct advantage,'' coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA has a more immediate problem: qualifying for the NCAA
Tournament. It needs 18 victories to secure an at-large berth, but
that's tougher than it seems: six of its 17 games remaining are
against Arizona (twice), Stanford (twice), North Carolina and
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins were to lose all six _ not unreasonable, given the
way they're playing _ they must win nine of the remaining 11. That
won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a long way to go in terms of playing to our
ability,'' Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
