<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      01-13 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON LEADS SONICS PAST NUGGETS FOR THIRD WIN IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sonics guard Gary Payton is on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   And his motives have nothing to do with whether he starts at the
All-Star Game next month in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   That, says Payton, is for others to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the 6-foot-4 guard is too busy planting something in
the minds of his team's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about getting this team right. We haven't been
playing too well. But now we're starting to do the things we're
supposed to do,'' Payton said after the Sonics beat the Denver
Nuggets, 103-93, Wednesday night at Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   A part of Payton still lingers in 1999, when the Sonics ended
the 20th century with a five-game losing streak. But they have won
five of their past six games since the new millennium began.
</P>
<P>
   In beating Denver, the Sonics won their third straight, and
fourth in a row on the road. Their only blemish was a Jan. 8
twilight zone loss to the Los Angeles Lakers when the offense broke
down.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Sonics have played sound basketball with
impressive moxie down the stretch. Payton has served as the
catalyst _ particularly in the past two games _ a back-to-back
situation _ where Payton's taken over.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 23 of his game-high 35 points in the second half
Wednesday, when the Sonics literally snatched the game away from
the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary hasa nice game every night,'' said shooting guard Brent
Barry, who added 21 points. ``Not only does he do what you expect,
but he does things you don't expect to help win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed by five points at halftime before Payton
tossed in 16 points in the third quarter. His layup that ended the
period put the Sonics in front, 78-76, heading into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Sonics slowed the Nuggets' transition game long
enough for Payton to eventually put the Sonics ahead 96-89 with a
short running jumper. Barry's 3-pointer with 1:56 left in the game
was the final blow.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics went ahead 99-93, and Payton's free throws with 53
seconds left provided the final margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night he amazes me,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said of
Payton. ``I hope people appreciate what they're watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton made eight of his 11 baskets in the second half, and also
finished with 10 rebounds and five assists. His effort epitomized
the Sonics' efficiency. They turned the ball over just six times in
the second half after committing 12 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Better offensive execution swung the tempo into the Sonics'
favor. Denver had made a living off converting Sonic turnovers into
easy fast-break baskets in the first half. But the Nuggets had just
two fast-break points in the third and fourth quarters combined.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Sonics contained Ron Mercer, who finished
with 25 points after picking the Sonics apart for 18 points in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent production off the bench has been a plus, too. This
time, Emanual Davis scored clutch baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Davis amassed all of his 10 points in the fourth quarter and
made two 3-pointers that prevented the Nuggets from seriously
threatening. Barry had one of his best games this season, adding
eight assists and seven rebounds to his point total.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we pass the ball and rotate and get good looks, we're a
good team,'' Payton said. ``We started moving the ball in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense, though, was the key.
</P>
<P>
   There was 11:11 left in the fourth when Denver point guard Nick
Van Exel scored his first field goal of the game. Van Exel had
missed his first five shots, and finished 2-for-11 with Payton
mostly guarding him.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night against Phoenix, Payton held Jason Kidd in
check while collecting 23 points and 13 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Payton's) phenomenal,'' Denver coach Dan Issel said. ``There
may be only two guards in the league of his caliber with Jason Kidd
being one of them. He's one of the few players that can take over a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Payton still trails Kidd and the Lakers' Kobe Bryant
in all-star balloting. Payton is third in the voting. He likely
will not start for the Western Conference for the first time in
three seasons, even though the mid-season classic will take place
at Payton's birthplace, Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has spent most of this week discussing the All-Star Game,
although he maintains the topic should be moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about starting and all of that stuff. I've
done all of that. I've started before and done a lot of things,''
Payton said. ``I've been to Olympic teams. I've been in the (NBA
Finals). All I need to do is win a championship. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
