r s BC-BKC-SCUCLA-LADN-(SLAN     01-13 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCUCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW DAY IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There were no USC basketball players proposing to
girlfriends at midcourt, but that was about the only difference as
the Trojans broke another streak of futility against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   USC snapped its second losing streak to its cross-town rivals in
two months, dominating the Bruins in a 91-79 victory before 10,001
at the Sports Arena on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was USC's first victory over UCLA since March 3, 1994. The
Trojans had lost 10 straight games to the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   That's similar to USC snapping its losing streak in football to
UCLA at eight games last November at the Coliseum, which included
quarterback John Fox successfully proposing to his girlfriend at
midfield after the game.
</P>
<P>
   No such dramatics this time, but USC celebrated this victory
nearly as much.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans enjoyed one of their most lopsided recent victories
over UCLA, leading by 19 points (63-44) when guard Brandon
Granville hit a 3-pointer with 14:17 remaining. It was USC's
biggest margin of victory against UCLA since a 15-point win in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   USC (10-5, 3-0) was on top of its game from the outset, as the
Trojans played one of their best halves of the season. The Trojans
had a lopsided 28-10 rebounding advantage in the opening 20
minutes, and had more offensive rebounds (12) than UCLA had total
rebounds. Guard Jeff Trepagnier had seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy belied USC coach Henry Bibby's fears before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very physical,'' Bibby said. ``They remind me of
Arizona a couple years ago that really pounded the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans took an early 12-5 advantage, and although the
Bruins cut the lead to one point (14-13), USC boosted the advantage
to eight points (27-19) after Granville hit a 3-pointer and layup.
</P>
<P>
   USC increased its lead to 35-23 after David Bluthenthal's layup,
and took its biggest advantage of the half (47-34) on Trepagnier's
dunk with 0.01 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier was the star for USC with a career-high 26 points on
11-of-16 shooting before fouling out. UCLA was led by freshman
Jason Kapono, who had 21.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for USC's early success was because the Trojans
shot 51.3 percent from the field in the first half while the Bruins
(9-4, 1-2) shot 43.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Granville (12 points) and Trepagnier (11) were USC's leading
scorers in the first half. Kapono led the Bruins with 11 points,
hitting 5 of 7 shots.
</P>
<P>
   USC's fast start was not surprising, considering how serious the
players were heading into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about as big as it's been here,'' sophomore forward Sam
Clancy said. ``We've won two on the road people didn't expect. The
time is right, right now for us to play them.''
</P>
<P>
   USC is currently alone in first place in the Pacific-10
Conference, a half-game ahead of Arizona (13-2, 2-0).
</P>
<P>
   Before the contest, Bibby tried to emphasize how much respect he
had for his alma mater, even as criticism has mounted in recent
weeks over the Bruins' play.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about how bad UCLA's been, but UCLA's very good,''
Bibby said.``It's probably the best execution since I've been here.
They probably have more patience. I'm not trying to play UCLA up.
I'm saying what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   After that glowing assessment, Bibby finally conceded that USC
might be the superior team in one area. ``I think maybe we shoot
the ball a little better,'' he said, then quickly added, ``But they
fastbreak the ball better than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Traffic outside the Sports Arena was a mess before the
game, because the Coliseum scheduled a soccer doubleheader at the
same time, clogging surface streets like it was a USC football
game. . . . Among those at the game were former Lakers coach and
USC basketball player Bill Sharman and New York Jets and former USC
wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
