r f BC-ENCRYPT-RULES-SFCHRON     01-13 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCRYPT-RULES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENCRYPTION EXPORT RULES RELAXED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HENRY NORR and TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bowing to intense pressure from Silicon Valley, the Clinton
administration has eliminated most restrictions on the export of
data-encryption technology _ software that scrambles electronic
messages to keep them private.
</P>
<P>
   The move Wednesday fulfilled a commitment the White House made
September when it abandoned its long-standing opposition to
liberalized encryption-export rules. Since then, high-tech
executives and lobbyists have been battling behind the scenes to
shape the new regulations their way, over the opposition of
law-enforcement and national-security officials who fear that
easier access to encryption would help terrorists and other
criminals keep their communications secret.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, industry spokespeople expressed satisfaction
with the new rules, saying they should help U.S. firms compete more
effectively in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over encryption had put the administration in a
difficult position. Republicans attempted to use the issue to drive
a wedge between the Clinton administration and Silicon Valley, an
increasingly potent political force.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules permit U.S. companies to export any encryption
product available on the retail market to businesses and
individuals in almost every country in the world. In most cases,
software publishers will have to submit their products to the
Commerce Department for a one-time review, but they'll no longer
have to apply for a license on each sale.
</P>
<P>
   Exports of advanced encryption technology to foreign governments
will still require licenses, and they will remain prohibited to
seven countries that the U.S. considers ``terrorist-supporting
states'' _ Cuba, Iran, Iraq, Libya, North Korea, Sudan and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The revised rules should mean reduced costs and new business
opportunities for many U.S. companies. Rick Miller, a Microsoft
spokesman, noted that the government's previous restrictions on
encryption exports increased the software giant's development costs
by forcing it to produce separate U.S. and international versions
of its Windows 95 and Windows 98 operating systems, as well as its
Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't calculate lost product sales,'' Miller said. ``But we
do know that customers overseas were saying they really wanted
encryption and that they couldn't buy our products because we
didn't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech officials had also complained that the old rules put
them at a disadvantage because they were unable to compete with
software developers in countries without stringent export controls.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Larson, chairman and chief executive of Network Associates,
a Santa Clara developer of security and antivirus software, said
his company lost hundreds of thousands of dollars in the fourth
quarter of 1999 alone because the old rules prohibited it from
selling some data-scrambling technology to banks in Mexico. They
also prevented the company from providing its encryption software
to multinational companies based overseas, such as Sony or
DaimlerChrysler, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the software market's changing landscape, the
industry had lobbied hard for a definition of ``retail software''
that would encompass not only packaged products, but programs sold
over the Internet and even software on network servers that
customers pay for on a per-use basis _ both increasingly common
phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Clinton administration accepted the broad
definition. Dan Cooperman, senior vice president and general
counsel of database-maker Oracle in Redwood Shores called that a
``breakthrough.'' ``The new policy recognizes online channels of
distribution for the first time,'' he said. ``Online sales and
online distribution will be driving our business in the future.
This will allow us to implement a single global model for all our
products.'`
</P>
<P>
   The new rules also eliminate all restrictions on exports of
encryption products to foreign subsidiaries of U.S. companies, as
well as regulations that required licenses before foreign nationals
working in the United States for U.S. firms could work on
encryption.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry representatives are still concerned about the
complexity of the export regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big step, but I wouldn't consider it total victory,''
said Piper Cole, vice president for global public policy at Sun
Microsystems. ``The regulations are still a little complex, with
different procedures and review periods for government and
nongovernment customers and retail and nonretail products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need any further major changes,'' she added,
``but there's plenty of room for streamlining and simplification.''
She said the Clinton administration has committed to review the
rules within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians have raised the same issue. ``I don't want to
underestimate the advance this represents,'' said David Sobel,
general counsel of the Electronic Privacy Information Center in
Washington, ``but the bottom line for us is that this is not
decontrol _ a very complicated licensing process remains in place.
To our mind, encryption software shouldn't be treated any
differently from word processing or spreadsheet software.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes announced Wednesday, Sobel noted, are ``all cast in
terms of exceptions. If you don't fall under any of the exceptions
they've spelled out, you're still under the old regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Cohn, an attorney working with the Electronic Frontier
Foundation, an online civil liberties lobby, said the new
regulations still prevent people from freely sharing new encryption
software over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn represents former University of California at Berkeley
mathematician Dan Bernstein, who sued the government six years ago,
charging that his First Amendment rights were violated by rules
requiring him to seek government permission before posting new
encryption software on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's Cole, however, said she believes that the new rules will
protect researchers and others who choose post new algorithms on
the Internet. She cited a passage that expressly removes controls
on ``open-source'' software posted on the Internet, as long as the
poster sends the Internet address to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, when the first Republican-sponsored bills to
liberalize encryption exports were introduced, the measures have
gradually built up strong support. One bill, authored by Rep. Bob
Goodlatte, R-Va., was poised to go to a floor vote, with 285
co-sponsors, including prominent Bay Area Democrats such as Zoe
Lofgren. Goodlatte praised the administration ``for making a
180-degree about-face'' on the encryption issue, but he couldn't
pass up a parting jab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only sorry they may have been about two or three years too
late on this issue because they've allowed other countries like
Israel to create some strong competitors to our U.S. firms,''
Goodlatte said.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers David Lazarus and Kelly Zito
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
