<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RNC-HISPANICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REPUBLICAN FORUM TO CONCENTRATE ON GETTING LATINO VOTE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ Declaring the Latino vote to be the hottest political
battleground in the war for the White House, Republicans are
meeting in San Jose this week to appeal to them on issues, at the
ballot box _ and even on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The 165-member Republican National Committee is gathered for its
winter meeting this week at the Fairmont Hotel to hash out a game
plan for the coming elections and address a range of issues,
including congressional races, outreach to women, and technology.
But GOP leaders made it clear that from now until November, their
chief spotlight will be aimed at Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Leadership Council opened the week with a special
focus group for 14 working-class Latinos to hear their views on a
range of issues, particularly health care. Republican leaders are
trying to talk up medical programs such as Fair Care, a limited
tax-credit proposal by Republican House Majority Leader Dick Armey
of Texas that serves as an alternative to those already floated by
Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get the party talking about ideas, we're going to
lose,'' said Scott Reed, who managed Bob Dole's 1996 campaign and
now heads the Republican Leadership Council. ``We're going to
devise a strategy in a very targeted manner ... and the way to do
that is to talk about issues that matter in people's lives, like
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   The RNC plans to unveil what it calls ``a sweeping political and
cultural poll'' of Latino voters and a panel targeting Latino
voters Thursday, and to debut a multimillion-dollar ad campaign to
run in California and other key states. The campaign was described
as ``the first in a series ... intended to broaden the party's
efforts to earn the trust'' of Latinos. But party leaders,
acknowledging that more than 70 percent of the Latino vote in
California went to Democrats in 1998, said aggressive moves will be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson, in a press conference to unveil the
new GOPnet.com Web site _ which effectively makes the GOP an
Internet service provider _ argued that technology will be one
critical way to reach out to women and minority voters in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear that there still is some work needed in the
party's new efforts to reach out to new communities. At one seminar
yesterday, for example, GOP women were instructed in how to speak
on behalf of the party before community groups and to media.
</P>
<P>
   The lecturer, telling the crowd that many Americans don't think
Republicans are in touch with the culture, urged them to use
keywords that would show them to be knowledgeable and sensitive.
For Latinos, he said, a mention of Ricky Martin and ``La Vida
Loca'' might be appropriate, according to one who watched the
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Republicans attempted to discuss the issues, it was
also clear that Democrats didn't intend to concede the Latino vote.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Loretta Sanchez of Orange County, who co-chairs
the Democratic National Committee, came to the Fairmont to
challenge GOP leadership directly, while issuing a letter to
Nicholson charging that what Republicans have done for Latinos is
too little and too late.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that under President Clinton, Latino
unemployment has been halved, business loans to Latinos have more
than doubled and that Latinos now represent more Cabinet members _
12 percent _ than ever before in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not allow you to run away from your party record,''
Sanchez wrote, citing what she called ``divisive'' measures from
the GOP, including English-only legislation and Prop. 209, which
called for an end to affirmative-action programs.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear jab at Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has touted his
outreach to Latinos in state campaign stops, Sanchez said, ``We
will not allow Latinos to be used as props at events or as photo
opportunities by your presidential candidates during this election
cycle.'' Bush, she later told The Chronicle, has been
``particularly offensive'' in that area, making a point to speak
Spanish at events and surrounding himself with Latinos on stage.
She said she will remind him and other Republicans that he will not
be able to ``rewrite history'' in the coming election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are content leaving Latinos in their own poverty,''
countered RNC deputy press secretary Leslie Sanchez, who is no
relation. ``We are fighting for opportunity and prosperity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
