<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 03:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-NET-SFCHRON &LR;      01-13 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN PARTY FAITHFUL GET WIRED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that the best way to gauge a national
organization's political clout was by the length of its mailing
list and the depth of its pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's another way: Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight national organizations, from labor unions to
political parties, are rapidly embracing the Net as a way of
forging tighter bonds with members.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee announced the latest example
Wednesday at its winter meeting in San Jose _ a GOPnet.com portal
that party leaders say is the most extensive and sophisticated
Internet outreach effort by any political party to date.
</P>
<P>
   The move underscores how the Internet is not only reshaping
internal operations for large organizations, but also transforming
the entire political landscape as more information becomes
available online and as voters in turn become more engaged in the
electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web organizing is a tool that's absolutely essential,'' said
Elizabeth Toledo, vice president of the National Organization for
Women. ``It's not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of efforts to bring more women onto the Net, she said
NOW is in talks with potential partners about creating its own
online service, which may provide cut-rate access for the
organization's roughly 500,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the Internet as the best mechanism we've ever had to
reach members,'' said Mark Carpenter, manager of interactive
services for the 32 million-strong American Association of Retired
Persons.
</P>
<P>
   The politically influential AARP already offers members a 10
percent discount for leading online services. Carpenter said free
Net access is now being explored.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the powerful AFL-CIO plans to present a new
initiative later this week to bring its 13 million members into the
Information Age. Under the Workingfamilies.com program, the labor
confederation will provide members with low-cost computers and Net
access, as well as portals for individual unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that we don't leave any union members
behind in closing the digital divide,'' said Leslie Tolf, assistant
to AFL-CIO President John Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   For an organization, the benefits of being wired are readily
apparent. The Net facilitates fund-raising, lobbying and
communication with the rank and file. All this, in turn, translates
into increased political muscle.
</P>
<P>
   For members, there is greater access to information and services
and a heightened sense of inclusion in the form of online
discussions, chats and communities.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are hoping their party faithful will feel
suitably empowered by GOPnet.com. The site offers such proven lures
as free e-mail, chat rooms and even stock quotes, as well as
political news bulletins and online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
said his party has undergone ``a digital revolution'' that will
allow it to reach 100,000 GOP activists daily by the start of the
Republican National Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at phase one right now in terms of building our
community,'' said Larry Purpuro, the committee's deputy chief of
staff. ``Phase two is to deliver all our activities online in a
seamless, paperless format.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he pointed out, surveys show that more than half of the
approximately 40 million registered Republicans use the Internet
every day and that about a third are online at least five hours a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the Net an improved information channel?'' Purpuro asked.
``That's a no-brainer. It's the telephone, TV and radio all rolled
into one.''
</P>
<P>
   Although few might immediately associate the buttoned-down GOP
with cutting-edge technology, Purpuro insists that the party's
commitment to unregulated business makes it the true champion of
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He characterizes the Democrats as being all too eager to impose
restrictions on the tech industry's vitality and entrepreneurism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Al Gore has invented the Internet, he should just
stay away from it,'' Purpuro said. ``Silicon Valley is an example
of Republican free-market ideals in action.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, needless to say, beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Republicans are doing is just an image,'' said Joe
Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``It's just
public relations. The Republicans are focused on using the Internet
only for fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal,'' he continued, ``is to make as many people vote as
possible. We're focused very much on the Internet as an
organization tool.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, the Democrats' Web site at  &UR; www.democrats.org  &LR; is a bit
more static than what the Republicans will be cooking up this week.
It is designed to inform users rather than to invite them in to
join the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   This will change, though. Democratic sources say a number of
upgrades are in the works, including online chats with top party
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew shrugged off the suggestion that the Republicans are
making headway in being perceived as the truly wired political
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is part of everything we do,'' he said. ``But all
that really matters is whether you win elections. Winning elections
is all about using the Internet as an organizing tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping out in this regard are a number of private companies
that specialize in Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading such firms in the political arena is an Idaho
outfit called Netivation.com. Its Votenet.com site provides a Web
presence for a variety of state party chapters and candidates in
local races.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the coolest feature at Votenet is a ``Follow the
Money'' box that allows users to simply type in a zip code to see
who in any particular neighborhood is making political donations
and how much is being given.
</P>
<P>
   A check of Beverly Hills (90210), for instance, reveals that
actress Candice Bergen has donated $1,000 to both the Gore and
Bradley campaigns, while ``Batman'' co-producer Jon Peters has
handed $1,000 to the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to have to fly to Washington and stand in line and
ask for those records,'' said Tony Paquin, Netivation's chief
executive. ``This is a clear example of how the Internet is
changing the rules of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another such example is how adept candidates are becoming at
raising money online. It's no coincidence that when Bill Bradley
appears at campaign events, a sign is displayed promoting his Web
site,  &UR; www.billbradley.com,  &LR; where the ``Get Involved'' button
leads visitors to a link for making donations.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley claims to have raised about $1.3 million via the Net so
far, while Gore has raked in just $900,000 online.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush remains the clear leader in overall fund-raising
_ pocketing a record $67 million as of the end of December _ but
only about $200,000 has arrived via the Net. His main challenger
for the Republican nod, John McCain, has raised about five times
that amount online.
</P>
<P>
   On a party basis, the Republicans have historically proved
themselves to be more effective at fund-raising than the Democrats.
A growing awareness of the power of the Internet likely will
increase that advantage _ and the party doesn't mind if there's
snickering in Silicon Valley about the GOP's newly minted
cyber-credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if we win the industry-insider campaign for
who's more Net-savvy,'' said Purpuro at the Republican National
Committee. ``The proof will be in the pudding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 0313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4797 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     01-13 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR IS ALWAYS THE LAST TO KNOW
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
I found myself in Chicago on Tuesday, though I don't mean that in
the spiritual sense, because I wasn't on a journey of
self-discovery. (``Self, please pick up the white courtesy
phone.'')
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune had a front-page story about a scandal
involving Mayor Richard Daley, who was simultaneously apologizing
for the bad stuff and lashing out at the media for exposing it,
which is harder to do than patting your head while rubbing your
tummy.
</P>
<P>
   The story sounded eerily familiar.
</P>
<P>
   A company with a contract with the city was getting waaay more
city money than it should have been getting. And hey, the company's
owner buys much insurance from the mayor's brother and is best pals
with the city's purchasing agent, and is a major contributor to
Mayor Daley's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier Tribune expose told of a female-owned company that
won millions of bucks in minority city contracts but is actually
run by men, who happen to be Daley campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset with myself,'' Daley said. ``I'm mad at myself. I'm
embarrassed. These things should have been caught, to be very
frank.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Daley denied that he knew any of this stuff was going on, or
that he used his influence to help these close pals get city money.
In fact, how could anybody think he could stoop so low? He's the
mayor, gosh-darnit!
</P>
<P>
   Wow, that kind of stuff could never happen here in the Cool,
Gray City of Kooky Kontracts. But it makes you wonder:
</P>
<P>
   -- Why do so many of these shaky contracts that mayors know
absolutely nothing about involve close friends of, big contributors
to, and/ or people with business links to the mayor? So many zany
coincidences!
</P>
<P>
   -- How come the mayors never know anything until the spit hits
the fan? Aren't mayors supposed to know stuff?
</P>
<P>
   -- Since mayors usually hear about the trouble first in the
newspaper, why don't mayors hire their own investigative people to
dig up stuff to tell the mayor, thus scooping the nasty newspapers?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Daley used a word to describe what it is he denies
doing. If a contract is awarded because of some cozy relationship
with the mayor, the contract was ``clouted.''
</P>
<P>
   A good Chicago-type word, but it could also be used here, if
anything like that were to ever happen.
</P>
<P>
   STEVE YOUNG OUT of the 49ers' picture? Yes, say inside sources.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't really gossip. More like hearsay.
</P>
<P>
   Steve is engaged, you know. He and she (Barbara Graham, if you
must be nosy) were in a Peninsula deli and the counter people asked
her if Steve would be back next season at QB, and she supposedly
said, ``It doesn't matter what the doctors say. I'm not going to
start spoon-feeding him while he sits in a wheelchair the day after
the wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Barbara: Can Steve come out and play quarterback?
Please? I happen to know that he has saved some money, despite
splurging on a new wardrobe every few years at the Gap. So you can
hire someone to spoon-feed him.
</P>
<P>
   YOU GO, GUY! Arthur Jackson, a dynamo in local government and
business, got a phone call Tuesday afternoon: ``Mr. Jackson, have
we got a kidney for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been on dialysis for six years, waiting, a dynamo
cut to half power by a funky organ. Yesterday, he got his kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur runs Jackson Personnel Agency and has been commissioner
of the Public Health Dept. and the Commission on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   This is your man if you're looking for someone who gives his
heart to the city. So Arthur getting a kidney seems like a fair
trade.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD MAN BALKING: A letter to Datebook, published Tuesday,
regretted an omission from a list of significant deaths of '99 in
the local arts world.
</P>
<P>
   Letter-writer Ken Sundowner praised Chet Helms, one of the
giants of the '60s S.F. hippie music scene, and a large presence in
the arts community until his death last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was a shock to Chet. His semi-grieving friends have
scheduled a wake Monday at the Gold Coast, at happy hour. Chet will
be brought in by hearse, in a casket, and will be given his
second-to-last rites.
</P>
<P>
   Sundowner will be invited to ride in the hearse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
