<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-CO     01-13 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fisk did it the right way
 &HT;    (For release Jan. 16, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk was a major-league baseball player with a .269
lifetime batting average. He hit a renowned home run in the sixth
game of the 1975 World Series. He lasted 24 seasons in the major
leagues and caught more games than any other catcher in history;
2,226.
</P>
<P>
   Just his durability was enough to elect him to baseball's Hall
of Fame last week at the age of 52. But there is far more to the
man.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers often have to endure constant taunting about their
equipment. It's called ``the tools of ignorance.'' What intelligent
person would want to take such a beating behind home plate?
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Berra played the ``ignorant'' catcher into a commodity,
even though he was a lot smarter than anyone ever gave him credit
for and didn't say half the things for which he's been quoted.
Carlton Fisk was just the opposite. From his beginning days with
the Boston Red Sox, Fisk had an erudite manner about him. He
functioned as an elder statesman before he ever became an elder.
</P>
<P>
   There is one moment in Fisk's major-league career that stands
out to me as the hallmark difference between the players of a
generation ago and those who play today for big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   I would hope that when the baseball writers voted Fisk into the
Hall of Fame, this incident was part of the equation, just as equal
to or surpassing the consideration given his durability.
</P>
<P>
   On May 22, 1990, Fisk was the catcher for the Chicago White Sox,
having left Boston _ and his native New England _ over a contract
squabble. The White Sox were playing the Yankees in New York. On
that Yankees team was a brash rookie celebrated alternately as Neon
Deion Sanders or Prime Time Deion; the same fellow who now plays
defensive football quite well for the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   He was awash in gold chains and he swaggered. As a major-league
baseball player, he never amounted to much. But he did talk a good
game.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, Sanders was at bat and popped a pitch up to the second
baseman. Part way down the path to first base, Sanders quit
running. He was an easy out, he figured, so why bother to run?
</P>
<P>
   From behind the plate, emotion overcame Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   As Sanders walked from the first base line back to the Yankees
dugout, Fisk pursued him, demanding that he run it out. ``There is
a right way and a wrong way to play this game,'' he called out.
``You're playing it the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was not a Yankee, Fisk knew the tradition and
glory of the Yankees franchise. He later said that Lou Gehrig had
to be spinning in his grave at Prime Time's lack of industry.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Sanders has not really talked that much about
the incident. Nevertheless, he has changed his lifestyle; while
still a flashy dresser, he is very much a born-again Christian.
He's a bit more humble and I would speculate that if ever he popped
up again, he'd run like the wind to first base _ the Fisk message
not being lost.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment on, I felt Fisk was destined for the Hall of
Fame. He has been described as anachronistic and maybe that is
true. But what baseball needs, what all of professional sports
needs, is players with a little more devotion to their game and
less to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Football has been infected with taunting athletes who have
degraded the game with their egotistical displays on the field. All
but gone are the athletes who, after scoring a touchdown, simply
hand the ball to the game official. They've been replaced by
gyrating exhibitionists who are joined by chorus lines of teammates
in displays of leg and pelvic dexterity and coordination.
</P>
<P>
   We need more Carlton Fisks in professional sports, not so much
for their batting averages or off-tackle slants, but for what their
sports meant to them and should mean to all professional athletes:
a little humility, please.
</P>
<P>
   That's the legacy that brought Carlton Fisk to the summit of
baseball excellence.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
