<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX     01-13 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Deportation law is plain un-American
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks as though Mary Anne Gehris will slip the hangman's
noose that the Immigration and Naturalization Service had around
her neck, but if her near-death experience doesn't convince
Congress to scrap its over-the-top deportation law, then is it hard
to imagine any abuse will ever move the legislators.
</P>
<P>
   One of Congress's anti-crime spasms coincided in 1996 with one
of its anti-immigrant spasms. The resulting convulsion cast up a
law requiring the deportation of immigrants convicted of crimes
carrying a one-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The law has been piling up an appalling record of heartless
deportations, as longtime residents are torn from friends and
relatives and thrown out of the country for minor brushes with the
law, incidents sometimes decades old and often the only blemish on
sound lives. Some are sent ``back'' to countries they left as
infants and can't remember and whose language they don't speak.
</P>
<P>
   Gehris's case is especially absurd and cruel, but at its core it
is not atypical.
</P>
<P>
   Born German, she was adopted by a Georgia family when she was 2
years old. She was reared in Georgia, lives there and is married
and has two children, including a 14-year-old with cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago Gehris decided finally to apply for
citizenship, formalizing her as the American that in every other
way she manifestly is. She answered honestly when she was routinely
asked whether she had ever been convicted of a crime _ and the next
thing she knew, INS was giving her the bum's rush to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   And just what danger were the American people to be protected
from? Eleven years ago, Gehris pulled another woman's hair in a
spat over a guy and was put on probation for a year as a
misdemeanant. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Gehris's story hit The New York Times and the ``Today'' show.
Staffers at the Georgia Board of Pardons and Paroles read it in The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution and invited Gehris's lawyer to submit
a pardon application. A pardon would moot the deportation.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a rare break. INS deports about 62,000 a year and
says 90 percent are here illegally in the first place or have been
convicted of felonies. Only some few hundred are deported for petty
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but hundreds, year after year, add up to a lot of injustice
and needless heartache. Few cases manage to get the attention
Gehris lucked into, and fewer still find a magical out if they do.
Gehris's attorney has clients who are being deported for
shoplifting $15 in baby clothes and for stealing a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way America is supposed to work. Congress needs
to repeal this mindless and brutish law, return to the old tripwire
of a five-year sentence, give discretion back to immigration judges
in cases involving minor crime and let deportation rulings be
appealed to federal courts under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Two bills have been introduced to fix the 1996 excesses. Our
honor rides on them. Justice shouldn't have to depend upon winning
the publicity lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 0926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
