<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If Bush is choice, cartoonists will have some studying to do
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Not long ago, a straw poll found that if given the
choice between Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, editorial cartoonists would choose the latter. This was a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, an endorsement from political cartoonists is no
badge of honor. One cartoonist said that his choice for president
likely would be the one ``with the biggest nose.''
</P>
<P>
   If cartoonists were in charge, Ross Perot would be president for
life.
</P>
<P>
   I understand the cartoonists' case against Gore. They're saying
that there's only so many ways to draw a Popsicle stick.
</P>
<P>
   However, judging from the inability thus far of the nation's
cartoonists to get a bead on Bush, I wonder from where any
enthusiasm comes.
</P>
<P>
   Few figures of such note have been missed by such a wide mark by
their caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem seems to that by and large when the
cartoonists draw George W. they can't distance their imagery from
that of President George H.W. They want to draw W. angular, like
they did his father, whereas W. is more compact, like his mother.
They want to give him his father's chin, which did not get passed
to him.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that certain other traits of the father didn't get
passed down to the son. Passion for foreign affairs, for one.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas George H.W. had an arm-long Washington resume with
international connections _ CIA director, United Nations
representative, envoy to China, a stint in Congress _ his son comes
before the nation almost blessedly bereft. Is this a point of
pride? Whatever Bush's features, I'm waiting for someone to draw
them with acuity.
</P>
<P>
   Texans have trouble themselves expressing what gives their
favorite son his distinction. He's immensely popular _ 78 percent
approval as governor _ but when asked by the Texas Poll what they
considered his chief accomplishment in office last year, 45 percent
of respondents couldn't come up with anything specific.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has done some important things, like oversee a needed
reform of the juvenile justice system that gave more gravity to
entry-level offenses. Some of his achievements, such as in
education reform, have been tokenistic, built on the backs of those
who set up wholesale education reforms in the 1980s at considerable
political cost.
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed a bill that will put Texas at the forefront of
blunting social promotion through standardized testing. Though
groundbreaking, it came with almost no controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Implementation of charter schools, a professed point of pride
for Bush, has been marked by shoddy oversight, causing many Texans
to gain new appreciation for the role demon bureaucracy plays in
bringing accountability to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the bottom line in support for Bush may come down
to good times, a personal amiability quotient, and an ability to
get along with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, that amiability would take on marked difference
depending on which party controls Congress. Good-guy Bush in the
White House would be like jail break for GOP House crazies like
Reps. Tom DeLay and Dan Burton.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats were to lay claim to Congress, Bush as
president wouldn't declare ``culture war.'' He'd be awaiting them
with a hand to shake.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, unless voters and cartoonists come to see
Bush as mostly hat without cattle, and send him back to Texas to
find substance.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
