<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conceding defeat: It's the 21st century
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I surrender.
</P>
<P>
   For just over a year, I have fought a losing battle against
referring to 2000, the much ballyhooed Y2K, as the beginning of the
21st century or the beginning of the new millennium. I'm waving the
white flag and joining the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As Dec. 31 approached, I began to feel like a spinster English
teacher trying to force students not to say ``He graduated from
high school,'' and to say what used to be considered the proper
form: ``He was graduated from high school.'' Just as I ignored my
teachers, my reporters routinely ignored me, referring at every
opportunity to 1999 as the last year of the century, the end of the
millennium, etc., etc., ad nauseum. I caught and corrected it when
I could, sent out memos, did everything short of threatening
banishment to covering sixth-grade volleyball games to anyone who
broke the rule. The rule was broken regularly.
</P>
<P>
   I blame President Clinton. He should have come out right at the
get-go and proclaimed 1999 to be the next-to-last year of the 20th
century and the millennium, ideally in his state-of-the-union
address last January. Instead of worrying about whether he was
going to be convicted in his impeachment trial (which now seems
like it happened 10 years ago instead of just 10 months), Wild Bill
should have set everyone straight.
</P>
<P>
   We could have still had the parties, the fireworks, the glitz
and glamour that many of us poor saps were reduced to watching on
television while sitting around the office waiting for midnight to
strike Dec. 31 to see if anything bad would happen to the
computers, the power or the water. Talk about a nonevent. I figure
there were more than a few folks sitting around bored at power
plants and other places who considered flipping a switch and
knocking off the power for a few minutes just to liven things up.
Lucky they didn't, because the rest of us waiting with bated _ and
unusually sober breath for that time of night and date _ would have
probably had a heart attack wondering what was happening. Odds are
good you can pick up a barely used generator pretty cheap this
week, and bottled-water sales have probably gone down the tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this wasn't the dawn of the new millennium, the fact we
were leaving the 1900s was reason enough to have a throw-down, and
then everyone could have geared up for a real millennium bash this
New Year's Eve. And those of us who had to work last New Year's Eve
could have participated, since far as I know there is no Y2K+1 bug
lurking out there.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it was utterly hopeless when my Time magazine arrived
last week. COMMEMORATIVE ISSUE, it proclaimed in fat type.
``January 1, 2000. Welcome to a new century.'' When Time says it's
true, you best give in and go along with the crowd, even if they
are math-challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The argument of the few Luddites holding to their principles (my
former colleagues) is that the calendar starts with ``1.'' There
was no 0 A.D. If you start with ``1,'' then you end a century with
100. Thus, if you start with 1901, you end with 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact that the Gregorian calendar had a few minor
adjustments along the way and most biblical scholars believe Jesus
was born in what was actually 4 B.C. skews the whole concept
anyway. Which is one reason I wasn't terribly worried the world
would end at the stroke of midnight. At least not that midnight
anymore than next week, next month or next year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Chinese. This is year 5740 on their calendar
_ and the Year of the Dragon, number 5741, doesn't begin until Feb.
5. Did that stop them from partying down? Of course not. Everyone
knows what party animals the Chinese are.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are. At least many of us have learned how to spell
``millennium,'' and a few of us have an awesome supply of canned
goods and bottled water on hand. The world held one heckuva party,
the terrorists didn't raise their slimy heads, and at least for one
day, a meaningless passage of numbers on a calendar seemed to bring
a lot of people together, if just for a little while.
</P>
<P>
   That's not so bad. Let's try it again this New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Happy 21st century, everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
