<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Democrats hope to reverse slim GOP advantage in Senate
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Democrats who controlled redistricting of
the Texas Senate last decade did such a good job of packing
Republican-leaning districts with Republican voters that none of
the six Republicans seeking re-election this year drew Democratic
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only incumbent Republican opposed is Jeff Wentworth
of San Antonio. Wentworth, whose 25th district wanders through the
Hill Country across the western end of Travis County into
Williamson County, is opposed by Libertarian Party candidate George
Meeks, of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth said Democrats stayed out not only because the
districts are Republican, big and expensive to run in, but also
because the 15 senators elected this year will serve two-year
terms. All 31 senate districts are up in 2002 after redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   With popular Texas Gov. George W. Bush likely to head the GOP
ticket for president this year, Democratic hopefuls will wait for
the redrawn districts and no Bush, Wentworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Democrats think they can reverse the current 16-15
Republican advantage in the Senate by holding Senate District 2,
represented by Democrat David Cain of Dallas, and picking up Senate
District 3 in deep East Texas, originally drawn for a Democrat.
Republicans, as might be expected, think they have a chance not
only to hold onto their edge, but add the seat Cain now holds.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Drew Nixon of Carthage, the incumbent in
District 3, was embarrassed during the 1997 legislative session
after offering to pay for sex with a woman on South Congress Avenue
who turned out to be a cop. Nixon had hinted he'd seek re-election,
despite urging by state GOP Chairwoman Susan Weddington to quit. He
finally decided not to run.
</P>
<P>
   Three Republicans had already filed for the nomination, which
probably helped Nixon decide. They are state Rep. Todd Staples of
Palestine, homebuilder Les Tarrance of Conroe and building
contractor Van Brookshire of Coldspring.
</P>
<P>
   The lone Democrat is lawyer David Fisher of Silsbee. Fisher is
the grandson of longtime U.S. District Judge Joe Fisher, and he has
been campaigning for months, which helped keep other Democrats out
of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic operatives agree that of the eight
districts in which Democrats are seeking re-election, the only one
truly in play is District 2, which stretches from Dallas to Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Cain of Dallas has represented the district since
winning it by just one percentage point in 1994. Three Republicans
want to oppose him:
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Harvey of Tyler, who has run unsuccessfully five times
for the seat. He was the GOP nominee narrowly beaten by Cain in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keith Wheeler of Rockwall, a lawyer who lost a race for
district judge in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Deuell of Greenville, a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   In the other eight districts represented by Democrats, three
senators _ Eddie Lucio Jr. of Brownsville, Eliot Shapleigh of El
Paso and Gonzalo Barrientos of Austin _ escaped Republican
opposition. Barrientos is opposed by Libertarian Party candidate
Tom Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Leticia Van de Putte, who won a special election
to replace the late Gregory Luna in San Antonio's 26th District,
will face lawyer David Leibowitz in the Democratic primary.
Republican Mark Weber's filing was undone because he mistakenly
filed with state GOP headquarters rather than in Bexar County, as
required for a district wholly within a county.
</P>
<P>
   These Democratic incumbents are expected to withstand Republican
challenges:
</P>
<P>
   _ District 12 (Fort Worth): Mike Moncrief, opposed by
businessman George Host.
</P>
<P>
   _ District 15 (Houston): John Whitmire, opposed by Warren A.
Lawless of Humble, who listed himself as a ``customer engineer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ District 21 (San Antonio to Laredo): Judith Zaffirini of
Laredo, opposed by insurance agent David Swift of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
