r f BC-TECH-JOBS14-COX     01-13 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-JOBS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computers creating new class of hot jobs for 21st century
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology is adding a new twist to some old jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Take concierges, for instance. At the Atlanta-based Ritz-Carlton
hotel chain, guests with computer problems have 24-hour-a-day
access to ``computer butlers,'' or compcierges as they're called by
Los Angeles-based career management Web site Careerpath
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   The job is one of the 17 hottest for the 21st century, according
to Careerpath.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer good enough to greet people with a warm smile
and deliver hot towels to their rooms,'' says Anne Gregor,
editorial director at Careerpath.com. ``A concierge will now need
to know how to plug in computers, help people with their cell
phones and other technical appliances with which they travel.''
</P>
<P>
   The same technological savvy applies to television show set
designers _ now known as virtual set designers _ and disaster
relief workers, Gregor says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A television set designer is becoming a digital maven, someone
who can create a set within a computer on the screen as opposed to
real life,'' Gregor said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, rescue teams, or pararescuers, at last fall's
devastating earthquake in Turkey showed how their role has grown
exponentially with technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer is it sheer brute manpower with bulldozers,'' Gregor
said. ``These teams arrive with highly sophisticated computers to
monitor the slightest sound in hopes of being able to find people
who might not have been rescued in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the hottest jobs, what they could pay and what
you'll need to get them:
</P>
<P>
   COMPCIERGE
</P>
<P>
   Essentially on call for 55 percent of hotel guests who travel
with laptop computers. These jobs are expected to skyrocket from a
handful today to one in nearly every major hotel by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Prep work: The Ritz-Carlton requires at least one year of
help-desk management and a bachelor's degree in computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Pay: $40,000-plus
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE ACCOUNTANT
</P>
<P>
   Determines when it makes financial sense to go online to sell
goods. Offers advice on finding Web developers and managing credit
card and sales records and makes sure your site is hacker-free.
</P>
<P>
   Prep work: Bachelor of science degree in accounting plus state
certification as a public accountant. Understanding of software and
Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   Pay: $28,500 to $54,250
</P>
<P>
   BIOINFORMATICIST
</P>
<P>
   Studies gene maps and deciphers which gene can help an orange,
for example, withstand colder weather. As the importance of
manipulating plant genes increases, so will demand for this job.
</P>
<P>
   Prep work: Biology and computer science. You should have a
bachelor's in computational biology or a bachelor's in computer
science with a doctorate in genetics.
</P>
<P>
   Pay: $75,000 to $100,000-plus
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL SET DESIGNER
</P>
<P>
   Combine a decor built on a computer with a physical space. With
future production budgets spread thin, virtual sets will allow TV
companies to tape many shows in the same studio.
</P>
<P>
   Prep work: Architecture, 3-D computer modeling and experience
working in traditional set design.
</P>
<P>
   Pay: $60,000- $150,000
</P>
<P>
   PARARESCUER
</P>
<P>
   Sent on humanitarian missions to provide aid during natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Prep work: Fitness test and training. Swim class weeds out most:
When the examiner ties up hands and feet to teach drown-proofing, a
lot of people realize the job is not for them.
</P>
<P>
   Pay: $29,000 to $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   DATA MAPPER
</P>
<P>
   Translates information such as crime and traffic on maps and
points out patterns and problems.
</P>
<P>
   Prep work: Geographic information system specialists need
expertise in information systems, computer science or public
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Pay: $30,000 to $40,000
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
