<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FINANCIER14-COX     01-13 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Son follows in father's footsteps, setting up success with
bio-tech companies
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Marc Gorlin graduated from the University of
Georgia in the summer of 1995, his father offered some interesting
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him the worst thing you can do is find a job. I told
him to find a deal,'' said Steve Gorlin. But first, the elder
Gorlin offered his son the chance to take his time and learn the
family business.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gorlin is a financier responsible for seeding several
well-established Atlanta biotechnology companies, including CytRx,
Theragenics and SurgiVision.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Gorlin, 27, has since helped start three technology-related
companies, two of which were sold within two years. The third,
Lanta Technology Group of Atlanta, finds people to flesh out other
technology start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   By taking his father's advice, finding deals instead of jobs,
the Atlanta native has amassed a career's worth of experience in
little more than four years. Part of that breadth and depth is made
possible by the fast pace at which modern technology companies are
evolving in Atlanta. But part comes from taking a father's advice
and applying it to a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   And it started on a bus outside Newark, N.J.:
</P>
<P>
   It is January 1996. Father and son are on their way to Manhattan
to look at a deal. Marc is reading the newspaper. He learns that
the Department of Justice has dropped its case against a man who
developed a way to encrypt e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Zimmerman's software tool, Pretty Good Privacy, allowed
someone to send information that could be read only by the intended
recipient, the Internet version of ``eyes only.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, however, considered encryption
technology a munition. Posting the program on the Internet _ where
it could be downloaded by anyone, anywhere _ violated export laws.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Justice Department dropped the case, Zimmerman hoped to
build a company around it. He was looking for money, either formal
venture capital or private investment.
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin, reading the story, thought, ``This guy is smart enough
to write a code that (ticked) off the government this much. It
seemed logical that companies would want encryption software to
protect their information.''
</P>
<P>
   His father's advice: Call the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin was 23 and five months out of college. He knew little
about encryption technology and less about writing code. His
business experience was limited to a college venture offering tours
from a rented airplane of downtown Athens, Ga., and Kenny Rogers'
farm.
</P>
<P>
   So what did the young Gorlin say to convince a then 41-year-old
man who had almost gone broke fighting the government to take him
seriously?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `My Dad and I do these kinds of deals. I really admire
what you've done, and we think you've got an awesome brand. It
would make a lot of sense to turn it into a company, and we'd like
to be a part of helping you do it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think he trusted me,'' Gorlin said. ``Trust is so
important in things, and so often it gets overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, Gorlin and his father were on a plane to Boulder,
Colo. The Gorlins helped gather investors willing to put just under
$10 million in Pretty Good Privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gorlin said he helped by showing his son how to write a
presentation to pitch potential investors. Then he gave him a list
of names of people who had invested in his deals before.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad gave me the credibility initially,'' Gorlin said. ``But
then he backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty Good Privacy was launched in San Mateo, Calif., in 1996.
Marc Gorlin took a seat on the board of directors but kept a home
in Atlanta. He worked on business development, talking to e-mail
software firms about integrating PGP into their programs. He helped
recruit and hire the eventual 60 employees. And he sat in on talks
for strategic agreements and participated in the negotiations that
led to PGP's buyout.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1997, PGP was bought by Network Associates, for
about $36 million plus warrants.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman is now Network Associates' resident visionary. He and
Marc Gorlin still talk regularly. He said he remembers being
surprised at the confidence Gorlin showed at such a young age. He
said Steve Gorlin played a stronger role at first, but eased off as
his son learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of surprising, a guy this young,'' Zimmerman said.
``But over time, I saw how he could raise money and help run a
company. Over the course of a year or so, I saw him become more
sophisticated and saw how he grew into the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin knows age can bring experience, ``but when it comes to
making basic decisions, common sense is a pretty good guide.''
</P>
<P>
   After PGP was sold, Gorlin focused on his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, Gorlin met Greg Malever, who had an idea for a
staffing company.
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin said he learned from his experience with PGP that finding
the right people is one of the keys to starting a successful
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these companies are getting put together, but the biggest
resource no one has is people,'' Gorlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch they sketched a business plan on a
chicken-wing-stained napkin.
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin and Malever started Lanta Technology Group early that
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Within three months, it was profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malever had a different idea,'' Gorlin said. ``I know it
sounds cheesy, but it's not. We not only interview people for their
skill sets, we sit down with them, understand their interests,
pinpoint their skills and learn about their personalities. Common
interests make a difference when you're working.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanta also occasionally will take an equity stake in a young
company instead of a placement fee.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has placed people at more than 35 Internet or
technology companies including BellSouth.net, eTour, HSupply.com
and Internet Security Systems, an adaptive network security firm.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Klaus, the 26-year-old founder of ISS and a colleague of
Gorlin's, said technology firms will pay to find good employees
because speed is so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to market is essential,'' Klaus said. ``If you can save
time and get a list of candidates with the qualifications you're
looking for, it reduces that time. Lanta has done a good job of
finding good people.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, in the fall of 1998, Malever was talking to
Gregg Freishtat, then at Premiere Technologies, about placing some
Lanta candidates. Freishtat had an idea that he said would do for
personal information on the Internet what sites like Yahoo did for
general information: organize it. Vertical One would be a company
with a technology that would let people reach all their Internet
accounts from one site with one password.
</P>
<P>
   But Freishtat didn't have the technology. Malever suggested he
call Gorlin. Within a few weeks, Gorlin was helping Freishtat raise
money, find office space and round out his management team.
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin helped raise $16 million over two rounds of venture
capital. He created a security council, which included PGP creator
Zimmerman. He helped attract Klaus to the Vertical One board. He
interviewed prospects and conducted background checks. He also
helped convince the people who run Web sites that Vertical One's
prototype actually could work.
</P>
<P>
   In September, S1, an Atlanta company that helps banks offer
their services online, said it was buying Vertical One for what was
then more than $166 million worth of stock. The price has since
almost doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Gorlin participated in the negotiations over the course of
several weeks in August and September.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, he stepped down as Vertical One's executive
vice president and is back to focusing on Lanta. For now.
</P>
<P>
   Which follows more of his father's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really make any money unless you multiply
yourself,'' Steve Gorlin said. ``A doctor can only see so many
patients. A lawyer can only have so many clients. If you really
want to grow, have a company and have other people work for you. I
`D and D' _ delegate and disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
