<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, January
14, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-COURSE _ For $9,600, New York shrink Marilyn Graman will
prep you for marriage. She won't introduce you to any guys, she'll
just put you in a more receptive mind-set. Her six-month course
even covers how to arrange your furniture so it's more ``male
friendly.'' (Grantham, Palm Beach Post). 17.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-TIPSBOX _ Tips for altar-bound folks of both sexes.
(Grantham, Palm Beach Post). 10.
</P>
<P>
   GRANDPARENTS _ Grandparents _ once considered the silver-haired
sages of the rocking chair _ are no longer content to spoil, pamper
and regale their grandchilren with tales of times gone by. Now they
want to teach them a thing or two while they're at it. (Lambert,
Palm Beach Post). 33. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   ASTRONOMY-BLACKHOLES _ ATLANTA _ Thursday is ``black hole day''
at the American Astronomical Society meeting. Astronomers describe
observations from the Hubble Space Telescope and its newer sister,
the Chandra Observatory, of enormous black holes at the center of
galaxies and evidence suggesting the existence so-called ``naked''
or isolated black holes in empty regions of space. (Nesmith, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-THERAPY _ Specialists are more cautious than the lay
psychologists of the sports pages, letters-to-the-editor columns
and talk radio, whose armchair diagnoses of Braves pitcher John
Rocker range from the pathological to the political: He needs to
get himself into therapy. ``You can't go around insulting people or
sooner or later you're going to get punched out,'' says Jack
Feldman, a professor psychology at Georgia Tech. ``And any society
wants to reduce the amount of violence. But is therapy the way to
do that?'' His question implies something the sociologist Philip
Rieff once called ``the triumph of the therapeutic'' in American
life. He meant, among other things, the faith in perfecting the
personality and achieving fulfillment through psychological
techniques. More than any other people, Americans expect happiness
as a birth right (it's in the Declaration of Independence, after
all), and they were among the first to exalt the role of the
``expert.'' All of it was made to order for a brave new world of
psychological testing and psychotherapy. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 31.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   CAPECOD-KAYAK _ ORLEANS, Mass. _ Cruising with this Cape Cod
kayak corps is a clarion call to courage. Four family members
paddle on a 10-mile kayaking adventure in Cape Cod. (Flannery, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DENMARK _ COPENHAGEN, Denmark _ Copenhaven, a great Dane
delight. Looking for a travel destination the kids can enjoy, too?
Denmark's capital is fun and safe, even when you have to improvise.
(Emling, Palm Beach Post). 40.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0111 -- A `goofy' novice learns some new moves and
new lingo in a fast-growing extreme sport (Hamilton, Cox News
Service) Art includes 3-column color photo of a snowboarder on a
hill, a 2-column color photo of an instructor giving lessons and a
1-column color photo of the writer posing with his snowboard.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TELLURIDE BEAUTY -- A rich vein of natural beauty
surrounds Telluride, Colo., which makes it a fine alternative to
Apen and Vail. Art includes an 18-pica color photo of downtown
Telluride.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- For sheer magnitude and ecological
audacity, few millennium events can match La Meridienne Verte, the
showcase of the Mission 2000 project planned by the French
government. (N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Art lovers in Rutledge don't have to visit Atlanta's
High Museum to experience Norman Rockwell's Americana. Their Morgan
County hometown (population 700), 50 miles east of Atlanta, is a
montage of the kind of nostalgic apple pie-and-salute the flag
images Rockwell illustrated for Saturday Evening Post. (Schemmel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by NYTNS
clients). MOVED. 40.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-ART _ A Tequesta woman has written the first history of
Florida art and it's the basis for a new exhibit opening this
weekend at Jupiter's Florida History museum. Lots of beautiful art,
plus mug of author. (Schwan, Palm Beach Post). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWSMOVIES-BANDITS _ Movie review: German film
``Bandits'' at Cinefest. Grade: B-. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BANDITS _ Review of ``Next Friday,'' which opened
Wednesday. Grade: D+. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-GIRL _ Movie review: ``Girl, Interrupted'' with Winona
Ryder as a young woman placed in a mental institution. Supporting
star Angelina Jolie's got the juicy part and steals the show.
Grade: B+. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MRSMITH _ Reel alternatives: ``Mr. Smith Goes To
Washington'' and other special films showings. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GIRL _ Review of ``Girl, Interrupted.'' 3 stars. The true
story of a teen-age girl's yearlong stay in a mental institution.
Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie are the inmates; Whoopi Goldberg
and Vanessa Redgrave their keepers. (Macor, Austin
American-Statesman). 12.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-HURRICANE _ Review ``The Hurricane.'' 3 stars. Denzel
Washington delivers a knockout performance as wrongly imprisoned
boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter. (Macor, Austin
American-Statesman). 18.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MOTHER _ Review of ``All About My Mother.'' 3 stars. A
grieving mom, a peculiar prostitute and a pregnant nun discover
their sisterhood in Spanish wild boy Pedro Almodovar's latest.
(Garcia, Austin American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
