<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Jan. 13, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DNA-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ The ``secret of life'' might lead to
new computers that can solve unusually frustrating types of
mathematical problems, scientists hope. They're creating
microscopic chemical ``computers'' from DNA, the coiled molecules
that decide whether a living organism becomes a person or a
petunia, a possum or a peanut. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSPAPER-SUIT (San Francisco) _ The proposed merger of San
Francisco's two daily newspapers would benefit consumers by
boosting newspaper
</P>
<P>
   competition in Bay Area suburbs, the Hearst Corp. says. In
pleadings filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court, Hearst Corp.,
owner of The San Francisco Examiner asked a judge to dismiss an
anti-merger lawsuit filed by former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly.
By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-QUAIL (San Francisco) _ California quail, the Golden
State's official bird, are on the verge of disappearing from Golden
Gate Park, where they were once so numerous they were regarded as a
nuisance. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Plunging into the working world can
baffle a lot of college students. They may have tons of technical
skills, but street smarts are much harder to acquire. If you don't
think so, look at some foundering 40-year-olds; they still don't
have the street smarts they need to make it. We look at what every
worker should learn, quickly. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (`t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DAYTONA-BEACH (Daytona Beach, Fla.) _ Long known as a
spring break and its Bike Week motorcycle festival, Daytona Beach
welcomes more than eight million visitors each year and entices
Florida-bound families
</P>
<P>
   with nature cruises, historical sites, watersports and diverse
attractions, including one of the world's largest flea markets. By
SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   W/ TRAVEL-DAYTONA-GO-BOX
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ The words on the hotel chain's
promotion elicited a double take: ``Buy your hotel room pillow for
$30; buy the entire bed for $1,300.'' Seems like only yesterday a
guest needed three ``hotel pillows'' just to get sufficient support
for one person. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEVON-HELM (Albany, N.Y.) _ Levon Helm, best known for his music
with the seminal '60s and '70s Woodstock-based rock group called
simply The Band, was diagnosed with cancer of his vocal cords.
Eighteen months later the soulful voice that belted out ``The Night
They Drove Old Dixie Down'' and other classics for The Band (which
was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1994) is a
raspy, faint version of what it once was. But Helm, 57, is
reinvigorated as a musician. By DOUG BLACKBURN,
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BAMBOLEO (Undated) _ The spoils of two years that saw
Cuba's Buena Vista Social Club gain international recognition and
Mexican-born Carlos Santana sweep Grammy nominations are now being
felt. Interest in Latino music is moving past the pop of Ricky
Martin and Enrique Iglesias and toward a more cultural
representation of its roots. By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ROTH (Undated) _ Actor Tim Roth's concerns over incest and
child abuse guided him to direct the grueling family drama ``The
War Zone,'' which opens this weekend. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ A review of films ``Lake Placid,''
``Mystery Men'' and ``Detroit Rock City,'' which are being released
on video. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOX (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Sandy Grushow, the new chairman of
the Fox Television Entertainment Group, doesn't mince words about
how cruddy the network's last season was. The new boss plans to
rebuild the brand using such successes as ``Malcolm in the Middle''
as a starting point. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAMS (Undated) _ If you're the St. Louis Rams right now, you
</P>
<P>
   should be a little worried. Life has been too easy lately. The
wins have come too smoothly. Their world is similar to that gentle
breeze
</P>
<P>
   that swirls in the air just moments before Mother Nature
</P>
<P>
   starts unleashing her haymakers. Something ugly is about to
</P>
<P>
   hit St. Louis, something more commonly known as the Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Vikings. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SHRINE-BOWL (Stanford, Calif.) _ Steve Spurrier is still
playing in John Brodie's shadow, at least when the former
quarterbacks hit the
</P>
<P>
   golf course in various celebrity tournaments. When it comes to
coaching college football, however, Spurrier is in a class of his
own. This week, Spurrier is coaching the East squad in Saturday's
Shrine Bowl
</P>
<P>
   at Stanford Stadium. By JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COACHES (San Francisco) _ This looks horrible. The Green Bay
Packers fired their head coach after one year, when the team
finished at .500, and also dropped their offensive and defensive
coordinators. All three coaches are black, the first such trio in
NFL history. This looks horrible, too. The Bay Area had two
defensive coordinators, each of whom had been in his position for
two years. One took the Raiders' last-place defense and moved it
into the top 10. The other took the 49ers' top-ranked defense and
dropped it into the NFL cellar. The Raiders' coordinator is a
56-year-old black man with decades of
</P>
<P>
   experience. The 49ers' is 38 and white, a relative newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was fired this week, and it wasn't the young white
</P>
<P>
   man with the bad statistics. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-PEREZ (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _Good for Carlton Fisk. Better for
Tony Perez. Best of all for those of us who don't have the stomach
for yet another year of complaints about the indignities and
injustices done to Perez. This time, the Baseball Writers
Association of America voted Fisk and Perez into the Hall of Fame.
By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The following is from a news
story of the future:
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the latest of a long series of maneuvers that began
in December 1999, the family of 28-year-old Elian Gonzales
announced that he has been chosen as the vice presidential running
mate of Republican presidential candidate Tucker Quayle. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
