<SLUG> BC-BKO-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEAUTIFUL PERSON IS GONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My refrain for him was always the same. (itals)Not
Bobby.(unitals) That's because Bobby Phills was the exception to
every cliche you've heard about pro athletes. He was so exceptional
that his college basketball coach, Ben Jobe, even begged him not to
play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Self-important and rude? Not Bobby. Consumed with cash and
repulsed by the classroom? Not Bobby. No sense of perspective? Not
Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   And so Wednesday, just after 1 p.m., I wanted to say the same
thing when I heard the news of a Charlotte Hornets guard, killed
instantly around 11:30 a.m. after his black Porsche was involved in
a three-car accident outside Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Not Bobby. Please. Not Bobby.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ray Phills II, who was leaving a Hornets shootaround, was
the driver of the Porsche. He was 30.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between pro athletes and sportswriters is
supposed to be purely professional, but Phills made objectivity
impossible for me. I first met him in 1992 when we both worked in
Ohio. Believe me, all the things that will be said about him in his
eulogy will be true; he was a beautiful person.
</P>
<P>
   Some days I sit before a keyboard and write, trying to better
understand myself and the place I live. But, at this moment, it's
difficult. I guess I will never comprehend why so many gentle souls
pass away at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   Phills was not much older than I, but it always seemed that way
to me. Once again, I think it had to do with defying cliches. He
was not a typical Generation Xer at 23. Even then, he talked about
having a family and treating people with respect. I'll never forget
walking into the Cleveland Cavaliers' locker room and seeing
Phills, John Battle, and John ``Hot Rod'' Williams having an
``argument.'' The dispute was over dominoes. The three of them
loved playing Bones, as Phills called them, and would spend hours
on the road challenging each other to yet another game.
</P>
<P>
   I remember that I used to ask Phills silly questions, just so I
could hear him speak. He was extremely bright and he spoke in an
exquisite Southern accent (he was raised in Baton Rouge, La.). He
had a lot of time to talk in '92 because he was locked on Lenny
Wilkens's bench in Cleveland. Wilkens always said that Phills was
the team's best dunker and that he had a future in the league, but
he didn't give him much playing time.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't go over well with Jobe, who coached Phills at
Southern University. There, the 6-foot-5-inch guard was nicknamed
``The Natural.'' He had 5 percent body fat and, although his jump
shot was an awkward line drive, he could jump over anybody. That's
the way sports fans described him. Non-sports fans who happened to
be females put it a different way: Bobby Phills looked good in a
suit. Jobe, though, was more concerned about his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart will feel better,'' the coach once said, ``when he's
Dr. Bobby Phills.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is another way of saying he wanted Phills to be like his
father. The elder Phills was a dean at Southern. His wife, Mary,
was a postal worker. Their rules were simple. Bobby could play
basketball and tennis, shoot pool and bowl as much as he wanted.
But he would have to maintain a B average at all times. He missed
the cut once. In college, he graduated with a 3.2 grade-point
average in animal science. If he hadn't made it to the NBA, he
would have most likely studied at Cornell in an attempt to become a
veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   As smart, handsome, and rich as he was, there was no pretense to
him. He liked to talk about his family and his sweetheart, Kendall,
who in 1994 became his wife. During the 1993-94 season _ his first
good season with the Cavs _ he talked about Kendall constantly and
told me how much he wanted me to meet her. By chance, I saw him at
a movie theater in the offseason and Kendall was with him. He
stopped everything he was doing and excitedly introduced her. Bobby
Phills had a way of making you feel important.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, I thought of Kendall, her 3-year-old son Bobby Ray
Phills III, and her 1-year-old daughter Kerstie. I thought of Dr.
Phills and his wife and the conversation they had in 1969 before
Bobby was born. At the time, Dr. Phills was a young soldier on his
way to Vietnam. Mary was pregnant. The soldier was not sure if he
would see his wife again, so the decision was made then that if a
male child were born he would be named after his father. And that
he would be a special baby.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot imagine what the Phills's grieving must be like now,
but they should know that they raised a practical and pleasant son.
I knew how to get a laugh out of him. All I had to do was tell him
what Phil Jackson called him. Jackson, who was coaching the Bulls,
often referred to him as ``Bobby Phelps.'' This made Phills laugh.
``Sometimes I go in the game,'' he said in '94, ``and I know guys
are wondering, `Who is Bobby Phills?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The last time I talked with him was on Nov. 5, before the
Celtics played the Hornets at the FleetCenter. I was having a
conversation with someone else when he walked by. I tried to stop
him and have him join the discussion, but Bobby wasn't like that.
He would have felt that he was interrupting. So he kept walking and
spoke the last words I ever heard from him. I thought of those
words over and over Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep talking,'' Phills said that day, ``I'll catch up with you
later.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
