<SLUG> BC-BOX-TELESCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELESCO ISN'T INTIMIDATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Telesco had a word for what he was trying to
describe Wednesday. He just couldn't come up with it.
</P>
<P>
   That awkward moment was how most of Roy Jones Jr.'s opponents
have responded when they had to come up with the punches to defeat
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people get . . . ah . . . animated . . . ah . . . ah
. . . scared,'' Telesco said when asked to describe the key to the
light heavyweight champion's long string of successes in the ring.
``Scared. Overwhelmed. Because people say this and people say that
about Roy Jones being the greatest pound for pound in the world and
they listen and believe. They get . . . intimidated! There you
go.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what most boxing experts expect will be Telesco's fate
Saturday night when he tries to take the undisputed 175-pound title
from Jones at Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Never has that venerable old building hosted a boxing match and
never in the world does anyone expect Telesco to leave it as light
heavyweight champion. No one but Telesco and perhaps his promoter,
the legendary Don Elbaum, who said Wednesday he bet $2,000 on his
fighter at 12-1 before he arrived in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The hard punching No. 2-rated Telesco understands this general
lack of faith in him. He understands it every time he looks at the
fight poster HBO has produced for the bout, a poster which features
only one man's picture on it.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is not of David Telesco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I've been given no respect,'' a tight-lipped
Telesco said at a press conference that Jones was nearly two hours
late for. ``The writers have. Some writers have. But HBO? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish not to talk abt but they got one guy on the
poster. I know he's the champion but he's fighting somebody. But
it's not only that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else it is, Telesco chose to keep it to himself.
Although he was talking, he wasn't saying much about himself or his
life. He only briefly touched upon the long prison term he served
at the Mid-State Correctional Facility in Utica, N.Y., a few years
back for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't even talk much about Jones, except to promise that
unlike so many of Jones's previous victims he will not share their
. . . what was that word again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimidation . . . there you go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Each opponent is different,'' said Telesco (23-2, 19 KOs). ``I
watched all of his on tape and took from each what they lacked to
make sure I won't lack anything. What I got (that they didn't) is
courage and determination.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is 40-1 with 33 knockouts and the only loss was a
disqualification that came after he'd knocked Montell Griffin off
his feet and chose to add some extra curricular punctuation after
he landed on his shorts. In the rematch that followed only months
later, Griffin lasted less than one round.
</P>
<P>
   Telesco talked briefly of a high school football career in which
he was an All-State halfback out of Port Chester, N.Y., whose
problems with his high school coach led him to the ring. What led
him to a 1,600-man prison facility was easier to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs and poverty. Or rather the other way around. It was, in a
sense, a business decision that went bad, and it took away a part
of his life. But now Telesco is working under the illusion the same
can be true for Jones.
</P>
<P>
   He could, in theory, find he made a bad business decision
himself in agreeing to fight Telesco after more than a year of
being pursued by him. He could pay for that with a long night and
maybe even the loss of a title fight.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones gave no indication he feared that possibility. As the
champion talked and joked in a ballroom at the New York Hilton,
Telesco sat glaring out from behind a pair of dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel deep down in my heart this is where I was supposed to
be since Day 1,'' Telesco growled. ``I had a dream about how this
fight is going to end, but I won't say what it was until the end
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Telesco said those words with Jones in another room. The
question he must face is what he will say when Jones is in the same
room with him Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of guys before him have found Jones can make that a very
small room with dim lighting. Which, of course, quickly leads to
one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimidation. There you go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
