<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN HAVE HEART ATTACKS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was one thing my friend Sarah didn't have to worry about.
A doctor had once looked her right in the eye and said, ``Well, I
can tell you this much. You're never going to die of a heart
attack!''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah and I are in the same aerobics class and she never even
gets winded. She's 58, and her slim, well-muscled body is a result
of running 5 miles, rollerblading 7 miles, or riding her bike for
20 miles on alternate days. She has outstanding figures for
triglycerides and homocysteine as well as perfect numbers for
cholesterol. Remarkably, her good cholesterol is higher than the
bad, a blood-lipid profile a professional athlete would envy. This
coming summer she had planned to bicycle coast to coast with a
group, and in her mind she hasn't yet started training.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, however, as Sarah was running up a hill, she felt
as if someone were pressing
</P>
<P>
   a brick against her chest right where a pendant on a chain might
fall. ``I felt pressure at the base of my throat,'' she explains,
``and I said to the person I was with, `I can't run anymore. I have
to walk.' It wasn't hugely painful, and when I stopped, it stopped.
But it kept happening whenever I exercised.'' That was at the
beginning of August.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Sarah saw her physician's assistant. Since Sarah's
ex-husband had died of lung cancer, she requested a chest X-ray,
which showed nothing. The assistant treated her for bronchitis.
When the pressure persisted, the assistant prescribed an inhaler
for asthma. Still no relief. Sarah, who'd started having stomach
pains, thought it might be esophagitis and was referred to a
gastroenterologist. The first thing he said to her in tones of
disbelief was, ``Are you telling me you're a 58-year-old woman with
chest pains and you haven't had a stress test?''
</P>
<P>
   You may think I'm about to blame someone for this oversight, but
the denial about heart disease in women is so profound that it
extends far beyond issues of individual responsibility. Most women
do not know that heart attacks kill more females than stroke, lung
cancer, and breast cancer combined. Doctors, too, underestimate the
danger. According to the article ``Women and Heart Attacks'' in
November's Fortune magazine, 88 percent of primary care doctors did
not know that the symptoms of heart attack in females are
substantially different from males, and one-third were unaware that
heart attacks are the number-one cause of death in women. It's no
wonder Sarah wasn't given a stress test until her fourth visit to a
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   After various tests, including a stress test, Sarah was finally
told she'd had a mild heart attack. She was put on beta blockers,
given nitroglycerin pills, and encourged to continue to exercise.
Sarah's grown childen were the ones who insisted she get a second
opionion.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Sarah asked her primary physician face-to-face
what he would do in her place that he answered: ``I'd have a heart
catheterization to determine the extent of the damage to your
heart.'' In late December, five months after her first symptom,
doctors finally discovered that Sarah had significant blockage on
the left side of her heart, as well as lesser blockage on the right
and in her carotid artery. ``The first words out of my doctor's
mouth,'' Sarah says, ``were `I'm flabbergasted!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike men, who often experience chest-crushing pain, women with
heart attacks are more likely to suffer nausea, exhaustion, or
breathlessness, have mild chest discomfort or abdominal pain like
Sarah, or experience pain in their jaws or backs. Studies show that
up to 45 percent of heart attacks are dismissed by women as
inconsequential and never reported. Odder still, the vast majority
of women who have heart attacks keep that fact a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah herself confided only in her family members. She was proud
of her strength and endurance and hated feeling old and weak. As a
management consultant, she was also worried that her colleagues
might think she could no longer handle the demands of her job, so
she kept the fact that she would soon be having an angioplasty
under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah didn't decide to share her story with my readers until she
read in Fortune that not a single prominent woman in America has
ever admitted to having a heart attack, as Betty Ford did with
breast cancer. As a result of this information blackout, studies
show that women tend to take fewer preventive actions, minimize
their symptoms, call their doctors later, demand and receive less
aggressive treatment, lack female support groups, and are more
likely to die of a heart attack than men.
</P>
<P>
   This can only be remedied by education, by openness, by
courageous women willing to share what a heart attack can teach you
about surviving.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't find a better role model than Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
