<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-FOX-HNS &LR;      01-13 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MANAGEMENT IS GETTING SLY WITH FOX 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Rarely has there been a mea culpa as loud and
as large as the one the Fox network unleashed this week.
</P>
<P>
   In front of television critics gathered here, Sandy Grushow, the
new chairman of the Fox Television Entertainment Group, dispensed
with about two seconds of chitchat before falling on the grenade
that was Fox's fall season and, ultimately, its last several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, this has been a pretty challenging and
dissatisfying year,'' said Grushow, known in the industry as a man
not given to mixing his message. He said programming, scheduling
and marketing were good places to start placing blame, but not the
real focus of the network's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that what Fox experienced since the start of this
broadcast season has been several years in the making. The recipe
is pretty clear. First, we've experienced a natural aging of our
most successful and defining series franchises. Second, we failed
to create enough new franchises to replace those in decline or
retired completely. Finally, for several years, we've over-relied
on the short-term fix of shock reality specials and series.''
</P>
<P>
   What that has led to, Grushow said Tuesday, was a loss of brand
identity. Or, in layman's terms: Viewers don't know what to expect
from Fox these days, outside of animals attacking and bad workers
caught on tape. This particularly annoys Grushow because he was one
of the original founders of Fox, when the network was considered
scrappy, original and daring.
</P>
<P>
   A complete rebuild is needed, Grushow said, and it's going to
take a long time to do it. He credited such shows as ``Malcolm in
the Middle,'' which had the highest debut ratings since ``The
Simpsons'' in 1990, as being one of a few the network hopes will
turn around its fortunes. In addition to turning away from good
pets that have gone bad, Fox seems to be putting new animation on
the back burner and returning to live-action shows such as
``Malcolm.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the recipe Grushow says will redefine Fox. ``That means
resisting that temptation to try and improve our ratings overnight
by saturating our schedule with blood-and-guts reality specials,''
Grushow said. ``Let me be a little more specific on this last
point. While I have no problem with bloopers or magic or even the
occasional wild police videos, I can assure you that the American
public will never see a 747 crash-land in the Mojave Desert on the
Fox network.''
</P>
<P>
   That last stunt was considered at Fox, then rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow left a little breathing room for reality series partly
because Fox has paid for a bunch it has yet to air, so it's a good
bet the network will air them selectively and call it a business
decision despite trying to distance itself from the genre.
</P>
<P>
   If Fox is going to turn around _ and ``Malcolm'' is the
network's best hope so far this season _ Grushow probably is the
guy to do it. He is considered a powerful figure in this town after
a three-year stint at the helm of Twentieth Century Fox Television.
He was brought in over Entertainment President Doug Herzog in
November, and although he had a chance to give Herzog a ringing
endorsement, Grushow took a pass.
</P>
<P>
   At least he is honest. Herzog may yet survive (most Fox
entertainment presidents never last past two years, and Tuesday was
Herzog's one-year anniversary). Why? Because Herzog didn't create
the fall shows but had his hand in ``Malcolm'' and had a glorious
history at MTV and Comedy Central _ networks that have pretty much
stolen Fox's mojo in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Herzog took the hit as well. ``All right. So we
had a bad fall. Not like Sofia Coppola in `The Godfather III' bad,
but like really bad. Bad like one of those movies, you know, where
the train's barreling toward the crossroads and they're cutting
back and forth to the kids in the car, and they're listening to
music and drinking beer and having a great time. You know what?
Frankly, we should have seen it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Herzog, in addition to taking the disastrous Fox fall and
Grushow's less-than-sterling support with a dose of humor,
announced that the network will try to program year-round in an
effort to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of networks talk like that, then proceed normally _
fall-season premieres, big movies in November sweeps, a holiday
shutdown, midseason in late January, one more big sweeps stunt in
February and May, and then closing shop for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog said ``The PJ's'' and ``Family Guy'' will return in late
spring and extend into June, July and August; there will be other
summer programming (including the possibility of new ``Beverly
Hills, 90210'' episodes); and then fresh episodes of returning
series earlier than September. It's certainly a great idea _ making
it happen may be the difference of him being employed or not.
</P>
<P>
   To further distance themselves from schlock, Herzog and Grushow
announced they have signed a far-ranging development deal with
David E. Kelley; produced a 13-episode non-fiction series from R.J.
Cutler, who made ``The War Room'' documentary; and will get two new
comedies from Carsey-Werner productions (``That '70s Show,'' ``3rd
Rock From the Sun,'' etc.), a much-anticipated pilot from James
``Titanic'' Cameron and a new drama series from Michael Crichton
(``Jurassic Park,'' ``ER'').
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Herzog announced that the actor Tom Hanks will
produce an ensemble drama set at West Point, and Fox will get a new
drama series from Marshall Herskovitz and Ed Zwick (``Once and
Again,'' ``thirtysomething,'' etc.). Plus, Darren Star (``Sex and
the City'') will come back to the network that kicked off his
career and do a drama about ``young people in and around Wall
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Other shows Fox touted included a new series called ``Fearsum,''
from the people behind ``The Blair Witch Project,'' as well as a
live-action version of the cartoon series ``The Tick,'' from Barry
Sonnenfeld (``Men in Black'').
</P>
<P>
   All very impressive. And all very necessary. Those are the kinds
of shows, Grushow said, ``the two of us would like to be up here
talking about instead of all this crap.''
</P>
<P>
   Change clearly is in order. Fox needs a turnaround in the worst
way but has vowed not to get there with the worst programming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
