<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER WAY TO INSULATE THOSE FOLDING ATTIC STAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it ever gets cold enough this winter, you might notice one
heck of a draft in the hole in the ceiling where the folding attic
stairs are.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the cover of that hole in the ceiling is not
insulated. It forms a sort of trapdoor when the stairs are raised,
and being uninsulated, the result is that draft, and a huge loss of
heat into the cold attic.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of ways to fix this. You can get ready-made
insulation kits that fit right over the opening, or you can make
your own box of insulation to fit.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman has described a do-it-yourself insulation cover a
number of times, but it bears repeating here because many
homeowners have a similar problem.
</P>
<P>
   To make the box, measure the opening and build a slightly larger
box to fit over the opening. Use 1 x 6s for the sides, and nail
1/4-inch hardboard on the bottom. Fill the box with 6 inches of
fiberglass insulation. Cover the top with 1/8-inch hardboard. The
insulation has an R value of 19, good for this purpose. An R value
is the resistance of a material against the passage of heat. The
higher the number, the more the resistance, the better the
insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when you climb the stairs to get to the attic, lift this
box out of the way. Better yet, hinge it to the floor and you can
push it up and away just like a door.
</P>
<P>
   Another way: Use a modified urethane foam board instead of
fiberglass in the box. One inch of this High R Sheathing or Thermax
(two brand names) has an R value of 7; 2 inches is 14, and 3 is 21.
So, make a box of 1 x 4s instead of 1 x 6s; it will be lighter and
easier to manage.
</P>
<P>
   One little thing, however, may interfere with this brilliant
idea. Sometimes the folding stairs in the raised position will
extend above the attic floor.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, there is an answer. You can build a berm
around the opening; depending on how far the stairs extend, make it
of 2 x 4s or 2 x 6s, or any other board to allow clearance. Boards
1 1/2 inches thick do best because they are sturdy and provide a
pretty fair insulative value. Then put the insulated box on top of
the berm; it can be hinged, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Two more little things to think about before you rest. It would
be a good idea to put weatherstripping between the box and the
opening, to keep everything nice and right. Use a strip of felt
along the bottom side of the box, or install foam-type,
self-adhesive insulation tape.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above will also work on a small trapdoor in the attic
floor, in case you don't have folding stairs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGGING TO DIFFER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl McLatchy read about this idea, and thought it was great,
except she figured such a box was pretty heavy, maybe too heavy.
</P>
<P>
   And, she called to tell the handyman what she did, after a few
minutes of thought about wrestling with a heavy door at the top of
the folding stairs.
</P>
<P>
   And this is what she said: ``I made a frame out of PVC tubing. I
don't remember whether it was 1/2 or 3/4 inch, but size doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used the usual L-shaped corner units and some T units as
well because I wanted an extra piece in the middle of my frame for
rigidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also made some borders on the frame so it would sit over the
opening and clear the folding stairs in their `up' position. I used
the standard technique to put all these pieces together, using the
solvent to hold them together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, I was aware of how this solvent system holds so well
that it cannot be taken apart, so I put everything together dry
first, then did the solvent bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrapped flexible insulation (foil backed by what looks like
bubble wrap) around the frame and the sides, securing it with duct
tape. All I had to do was unroll the insulation and secure it.''
</P>
<P>
   That insulation is a form of reflective insulation, used in a
number of ways. Cheryl's use is a brand new one: light in weight,
fair in insulation value, and well weatherstripped.
</P>
<P>
   Well done, Cheryl McLatchy. We can use more people like you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
