<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5010 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART     01-13 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 A BIG HITTER BOWS OUT, A FEW SEASONS TOO LATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Vanderheiden is like a great ballplayer who hung around a
few seasons too long. He lost a step in the field, his bat got a
little slower, and in his final season he hit .206.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, many fans didn't even realize what a superstar he
once had been.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden hung up his spikes Wednesday after 29 years with
Fidelity Investments. Between 1980 and 1995, Vanderheiden was one
of America's premier money managers. In those years, his Destiny I
fund returned an average of 19 percent a year. Among his peers,
only two managers in the country, Peter Lynch and Kenneth Heebner,
both Bostonians, had better numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning in 1995, Vanderheiden's performance began to slip.
He trailed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index slightly that year. He
did the same in 1996, 1997, and 1998. In 1999, his fund returned
3.9 percent, compared with 21 percent for the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vanderheiden was a victim of the new economy,'' said Jim
Lowell, the editor of Fidelity Investor, a newsletter that tracks
Fidelity funds.
</P>
<P>
   If Lowell is right, then Vanderheiden had plenty of company.
Along with Alan Greenspan, Warren Buffett, and most economists and
money managers, he didn't quite know what to make of an economy
that grew rapidly year after year and a stock market that rose to
levels that didn't seem to make any sense.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, he put 15 percent of his fund's money into bonds,
on the expectation that the economy would tank. It didn't, and it
still hasn't. Vanderheiden has whittled down his bond holdings over
the years, but they remain a major drag on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Vanderheiden was light on technology and heavy on
financial stocks, the exact opposite of where he should have been.
He remained loyal to Philip Morris, the troubled cigarette company,
long after most of his colleagues at Fidelity had given up on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was too defensive during a period when the Nasdaq went up
threefold,'' said David O'Leary, president of Alpha Equity
Research, another Fidelity-watcher.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden's approach should not have come as a surprise. In a
1995 interview with Boston Capital, he described his investment
philosophy this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people buy stock and are kind of blinded by the
upside potential. The first question I ask when I buy stock is: How
much can I get hurt by this stock if something goes wrong? And I
figure that in most cases, if you take care of the downside first
and address yourself to that, then the upside takes care of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knew there would be no downside and the upside would turn
out to be almost unlimited?
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone press conference Wednesday, Vanderheiden
stuck to his guns. ``I've had rough spots off and on over 20
years,'' he said. ``This is just another one. If I stayed around
I'm sure I would sail through it.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the valuation of technology stocks as ``inflated''
and predicted that many of today's Internet companies will not be
around five years from now. Asked about the stock market in
general, he said, ``This has been a momentum-driven market, and we
all know momentum-driven markets don't end that well.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid outdoorsman, Vanderheiden, 54, plans to climb mountains
and travel the world with his new free time. He will, however,
retain a role at Fidelity as a board member and as a mentor to
young money managers.
</P>
<P>
   Think Ted Williams coming to spring training to help young
ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Williams hit a home run in his final at-bat. Vanderheiden hit
into a double play. But that should not obscure the fact that he
had a terrific career. Over 19 years, Destiny I returned 2,689
percent, compared with 1,777 percent for the S&AMP;P 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, if you had invested $10,000 with Vanderheiden
in 1980, it would be worth roughly $270,000 today. Even in the age
of Internet valuations, those are pretty good numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, a reporter approached Russel Kinnel of
Morningstar, the mutual fund rating company, and asked for names of
great money managers who were having a bad year. Kinnel recommended
Vanderheiden. The reporter's response was: Who's that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' said Kinnel, ``because Vanderheiden is leaving
at a point when no one appreciates what he did. But if you were
starting a hall of fame for mutual funds, Vanderheiden would be one
of your great fund managers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden's Feb. 1 departure will trigger a major game of
musical chairs at Fidelity.:
</P>
<P>
   --Bettina Doulton will succeed Vanderheiden as the manager of
Fidelity Advisor Growth Opportunities Fund and Fidelity VIP III:
Growth Opportunities Portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   --Karen Firestone will succeed Vanderheiden as manager of
Fidelity Destiny I. She will continue to manage Fidelity Large Cap
Stock Fund and Fidelity Advisor Large Cap Stock Fund.
</P>
<P>
   --Stephen Peterson will run Fidelity Puritan Fund, succeeding
Doulton. Petersen will continue to manage Fidelity Equity-Income
Fund and VIP: Equity-Income Portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   --Stephen Dufour will run Fidelity Equity-Income II Fund,
succeeding Doulton.
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Ewing will run Fidelity Balanced Fund, succeeding
Dufour.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity also named new managers for some of its select funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
