<HEADLINE>
PARENTING VIA THE WEB, CREDIBILITY IS THE CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
 -BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With dozens of press releases, electronic or otherwise, crossing
my desk to trumpet the wonders of yet another Web site for parents,
one thing is clear: No matter what parenting issue we face,
information is only a fingertip away. As comforting as that thought
may be, however, actually wending one's way through what's
available for parents on the World Wide Web takes more patience
than parenting a 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   As a novice user, I began my efforts to make sense of it all
intelligently enough, I thought, with a search engine (Yahoo!) and
a subject a reader had recently e-mailed me about: thumb-sucking.
</P>
<P>
   Aha! Four possibilities. Good start.
</P>
<P>
   The first was for adults who still suck their thumbs. Uh-uh. The
second, ``My thumb and I,'' looked hopeful but offered only a link
to purchase a book. The third and fourth options were eye-openers:
Triggered by the second two syllables of my query, the search
engine was suggesting porn sites. (Did I say I was a novice?!) As
much as that took me by surprise, it was a stark reminder that
searchengines are not a safe tool for our children.
</P>
<P>
   OK, try again. New search engine (Alta Vista), new subject:
bed-wetting.
</P>
<P>
   This gave me 10 choices: three direct links to products; one
server that could not be found; three parent chat rooms; one
definition of enuresis; one page on enuresis in children with spina
bifida; and one ``free'' consultation with a doctor that turned out
to cost $475.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Forget the search engine.
</P>
<P>
   With many hundreds of Web sites for parents and new ones
appearing on the screen almost daily, the biggest issue clearly is
not information _ it's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about parents out there on the Web,'' says Dianne
Rothenberg, associate director of ERIC Clearinghouse on Elementary
and Early Childhood Education at the University of Illinois. She
has reviewed more than 200 sites for parents and says there are
typically two problems with using search engines: They often lead
to commercial sites, and there is no evaluation of the links, which
is why searching for something like thumb-sucking can lead to
pornography. (A third problem, which she didn't mention but which
surfaced when I tried to retrace my steps, is that search engines
do not necessarily turn up the same links the second time through.)
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg's concern about commercial sites is that they tend to
have a bias that may or may not be obvious or stated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A parent's first question needs to be: What is (a site's)
purpose in giving advice?'' she says. ``If they are selling a book
or product . . . typically, a commercial site presents only one
side of an issue and doesn't provide you with a range of opinion or
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Blagojevic, an early-childhood Internet guru and
curriculum coordinator at the Sharing Place Child Care Center in
Orono, Maine, says a good rule of thumb for any parenting site is
``Look at the reputation of the group offering the information.''
</P>
<P>
   A reputable site, she says, immediately spells out its goal or
purpose and identifies the author or sponsoring organization. That
goes a long way toward helping you judge the content, Rothenberg
points out: ``If there's a bias, a reputable site will tell you so
right away.'' For instance, www.pampers.com is decidedly a
commercial site, but its Pampers Parenting Institute offers advice
from clearly identified, reputable authorities, including
pediatrician and author T. Berry Brazelton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Web site pitfalls:
</P>
<P>
   --Question-and-answer format. This is a popular device on Web
sites for parents, but Rothenberg urges caution. ``View it as input
into understanding a problem, not as an answer,'' she says. ``I'd
be leery of any place on the Web that tells you, `This is what you
should do.' '' She says the best parenting sites offer information
and research, not advice.
</P>
<P>
   --Experts. Many Web sites offer ``expert'' resources but don't
identify the expert, identify him or her without affiliation, or
spread the person too thin, so that he or she is answering
questions without the proper background. ``Don't assume credibility
just because someone is identified as an `expert,' '' says
Blagojevic.
</P>
<P>
   --Chat rooms. Similarly, many parents fall into the trap of
accepting information as gospel just because it's on line, says
Rothenberg. Not everyone in a parent chat room is necessarily a
parent, however, and the person's perspective may have no relevance
to your situation: Perhaps the writer has a 3-year-old and is
giving advice about your 7-year-old. ``I always tell parents to
ask, `How old are your children?' '' says Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of chat rooms, Blagojevic recommends ListServ discussion
groups, which are like chat rooms except that they are not
instantaneous. She is co-ListServ owner of Early Childhood
Education On Line, which you can subscribe to at no charge by
sending e-mail to LISTSERV(at)Maine.Edu and typing subscribe
ECEOL-L and your name in the message field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With these cautions in mind, there are some excellent Web sites
for parents. Here are some worth bookmarking:
</P>
<P>
   --NPIN.org This site of the National Parent Information Network,
sponsored by ERIC and funded by the US Department of Education, is
the world's largest database on education and offers links to an
exhaustive list of Web sites. It is probably the best single site
out there, and a good choice for your search engine (click on
Searching NPIN) for any education and/or parenting topic.
Highlights: ``Parent ListServe'' and ``AskEric.'' The former is an
on-line discussion group (click on questions) where you submit
questions and comments and receive responses. You need to subscribe
to get on the list, but there is no fee. You can also submit
questions to AskERIC by e-mailing askERIC(at)ericir.syr.edu or you
can go directly to the AskERIC Web site at www.askERIC.org/.
Questions are forwarded to an appropriate professional within the
ERIC network. Signed answers, which typically include relevant Web
sites, resources, and related reading, are returned within two
days. AskERIC receives 50,000 questions a year.
</P>
<P>
   --zerotothree.org A national nonprofit for parents of children
ranging from infancy to age 3, this site provides a wealth of
material on infant and toddler development. Highlights: A
``Parent's Guide to Developmental Assessment'' and ``Choosing
Quality Child Care,'' especially ``Questions to Ask.''
</P>
<P>
   --http://www.ume.maine.edu/cofed Early Childhood Education on
Line at the University of Maine offers quality links on a range of
educational and developmental issues for parents of young children.
Highlight: At the bottom of the Welcome page, click on ``Research
and Resources,'' then on ``Early Childhood Education On-Line''; go
to the blue boxes and click on ``ECE and the Net,'' ``Children and
Developmental Guidelines,'' or ``Professional Development.'' Don't
be put off by the titles; although some of this is in academese,
there's plenty here for parents. This is also where Bic's
ListServ lives.
</P>
<P>
   --http://ldonline.org LDOnline is sponsored by the Learning
Project of WETA-TV and radio of Washington, D.C., and the
Coordinated Campaign for Learning Disabilities. It offers a
positive perspective for parents on living and coping with
children's learning disabilities. Highlights: Periodic on-line
chats with respected LD experts; comprehensive state-by-state
listing of conferences on learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   --www.parentsoup.com This is a commercial site with lots of ads
(part of IVillage.com), but it also has many helpful aspects.
Highlights: Chats available daily according to the age of your
child. Also, click on ``Resources,'' then on ``Parenting
Organizations'' and you'll find a definitive listing of every
conceivable organization you ever wanted to know about.
</P>
<P>
   --www.nncc.org National Network for Child Care, funded by the US
Department of Agriculture, offers more than 1,000 professionally
reviewed, research-based publications on child-care issues.
Highlights: KIDCARE, an e-mail ListServ, and Person-to-Person, both
specializing in child-care issues.
</P>
<P>
   --naeyc.org The National Association for the Education of Young
Children, the nation's most respected accrediting organization for
day care and preschool. Highlight: The ``For Parents'' section is
under development so there's not much here yet, but you get a list
of accredited centers in your area.
</P>
<P>
   --www.nmsa.org The National Middle School Association offers a
wide range of research material for parents of 10- to 14-year-olds,
from developmental issues like dating to controversial subjects
such as whether Grade 5 should be included in the middle school.
Click on ``Resource Center'' to see the range of topics. (Material
in this site is high quality but sometimes not very readable.)
</P>
<P>
   --http://education.indiana.edu/cas Center for Adolescent Studies
at Indiania University. Highlight: Click on ``Sites for Parents,''
then on ``Parenting Adolescents'' and ``Archives,'' and you'll find
any teen topic from appearance to unacceptable peer behavior. Also
worth looking at: Click on ``Normal Adolescence,'' then on
``Developmental Tasks of Adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   --www.familyeducation.com Family Education Network, an
interactive educational site for parents and teachers, K through
12. It has lots of ads and is a complicated site to wend through,
but it offers lots of educational materials.
</P>
<P>
   --www.kidsource.com KidSource, also a commercial site, but less
overwhelming than some. It collects and repackages materials from
other reliable sources. Highlight: New product news and recalls.
</P>
<P>
   --www.aap.org The American Academy of Pediatrics, the definitive
site for everything health-related, from diaper rash to car seats.
Highlight: Use the search at left to find topics of interest.
</P>
<P>
   So what about thumb-sucking? The good news is that at all these
sites, ``sucking'' is not a dirty word. Unfortunately, none of the
sites I researched had as much information as I wished for. At
www.aap.org, there's a reprint from a book about the developmental
need for sucking but not much about how to cope; parentsoup.com
turned up nine related thumb-sucking questions from other parents,
which is helpful. But the answers were from a variety of experts
whose credentials were not always clearly identified.
</P>
<P>
   So here was another lesson learned: You can spend a lot of time
trying to get information on the Web, when one good book from the
library (or a search of Boston.com for past Child Caring columns;
may I recommend the one on thumbsucking?) would do the trick very
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments. She can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
