<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEDROOMS HAVE DUCTS, BUT NO HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have two-zone hot-air heat by gas. Upstairs there are two
identical duct runs of 20 feet leading to bedrooms, and a third to
a bathroom. I can feel heat coming out of the register in the
bathroom, but not in the bedrooms, and they are cold. What's wrong,
and how can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   MARK CHAPMAN, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. A two-zone system with hot air heat is tricky, and I just
wonder if the installers neglected to include those two 20-foot
ducts in either zone. If the house is new, and you have been in it
less than a year, the onus is on the installers and they should
make the correction. Those 20-foot runs seem rather long, but a
forced hot-air system of adequate size shoud handle it without
breathing hard.
</P>
<P>
   Also, check to make sure there are cold-air returns in one or
both rooms; a hot-air system must have a cold-air return to allow
the warm air that heats the rooms to return to the furnace after it
has cooled. If there are no cold-air returns, the furnace can pump
all the hot air in the world, but not much of it would get into
those rooms, because it would be pumping into a dead end, an
enclosed area.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it might be a simple matter of a damper in the wrong
position. Small, round, hot air ducts leading from the furnace or
trunk-line plenum (a large square or rectangular duct, most often
in the basement) usually have a damper where they leave the plenum.
The damper looks like a little metal handle that is either parallel
to the duct (open) or at right angles to it (closed). The dampers
are used to balance the heating system, providing more hot air to
go to rooms that need it and less to rooms that do not. Check the
ducts leading to the two rooms involved; if the dampers are closed,
open them and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Carp asked why her one-handle shower valve rumbles and
rattles when she turns it on. The handyman suggested it might be
due to a faulty or dirty valve, adding that cleaning it might work,
or that it might have to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, said William Tragakis, who heads Watertown Plumbing &AMP;
Heating Supply. Tragakis said the rumbling, which can get pretty
scary, is caused by a loose washer, or two loose washers, and that
replacing them, or having a plumber do so, will fix the problem.
So, thanks Bill; the handyman appreciates the tip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I turn up the heat and my gas boiler goes on, water
comes out from the drainpipe that I think is the safety relief
valve. I get about a gallon overnight. How can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   LOAN VO, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Pressure relief valves (they are on top of the boiler with a
pipe leading down the side to the floor) are designed to keep the
water pressure in the boiler from getting so high that it blows the
boiler apart. They are very sensitive to pressure, and sometimes
leak water for no good reason. Sometimes they get out of adjustment
when they are tested. The cure is to replace the pressure relief
valve. A plumber could do this, or have ServicEdge do it, by
calling 888-942-3343. ServicEdge, a company separate from the gas
company, services boilers, furnaces, burners, and other gas-fired
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Since I moved to a new town, I've found that my laundry
doesn't smell of detergent anymore. I liked the fresh scent of
detergent. What happened? How can I get that fresh smell back?
</P>
<P>
   M.G., Dracut, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's only a guess, but I think it's because of the water. If
the water in Arlington is softer than in Dracut, your washing
machine did not take all the detergent out during its rinse cycle,
and you were smelling the residue. But, the harder water in Dracut
holds less detergent, and detergent is more easily removed from
hard water. It's only a guess. Perhaps you could use a
stronger-smelling detergent to get back that fresh aroma.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have single-glazed double-hung windows with aluminum storms
and screens. The main windows have true divided lights, with no
grids. One window does not go all the way down. I push it down and
it pops right up again. How can I get it to go down and stay down?
</P>
<P>
   GREG BOCKWEG, Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If your windows are weight balanced (with ropes, pulleys, and
weights), it may be that the cord holding the weight is too short,
and when the window is lowered, the weight rises and hits the
pulley before the window hits the sill. It could happen with the
weights on both sides of the window. To check this, lower the
window and lock it, if possible. Then pull the cord; if there is no
slack in the cord, it is, indeed, too short, and needs to be
replaced with a longer one.
</P>
<P>
   If your windows are not weighted, something might be in the jamb
where the window goes up and down, thus blocking its movement. It
could be a bent piece of metal weatherstripping or a nail sticking
out. It does not seem like a broken spring; when springs fail, the
windows usually go down and stay down. Finally, there might be
something on the sill that is preventing complete closure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house has some nice hardwood floors, but they are 12 years
old and in need of some refurbishing, although not necessarily
resanding and refinishing. I'd like to put on one new coat of
varnish. How can I tell whether the old varnish is water- or
oil-based?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BALUNAS, Northborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ordinarily, you would have to have a paint chip analyzed by a
lab, but that is not necessary here. Being 12 years old, the
varnish is probably oil. And, to refurbish, sand the floors with
medium-fine sandpaper by hand or machine (but not necessarily a
floor machine) to roughen the finish and reduce gloss. Then wash
with paint thinner or a strong solution of Spic and Span and water.
No need to rinse. Then apply one coat of an oil-based polyurethane
varnish. Two will be better. Be sure to apply thin coats, with a
brush. The sanding is essential for proper adhesion of the new
coats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Raccoons are raiding my in-ground garbage can and having a
wonderful time at my expense. They seem to share the work in
opening the can. How can I deter them?
</P>
<P>
   M.G., Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are various animal repellents you can spray on and
around the can, but they are effective only temporarily, if at all.
First, try sprinkling cayenne pepper flakes on the garbage and on
the can. Or, better yet, cayenne powder, but be careful with that
powder because it can cause allergic reactions if inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you may have to build a heavy-duty steel cage around
the can to keep the varmints out. But you know they can open almost
anything, so the cage must be super-strong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
