<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-13 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE WORLD IS ALWAYS IN BLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the year you won't find many busy gardeners sitting
glued to computer screens. After all, gardening is sensual and
tactile. It's about escaping confinement, wrestling with weeds, and
enjoying sunlight and fresh air alongside the plants in your veggie
patch and flower bower.
</P>
<P>
   But winter's different. It's the time when the gardener's world
is defined by anticipation, frustration, and four walls. It's the
season of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   For housebound people with time, rather than dirt, on their
hands, Web sites can offer answers to gardening questions, notice
of upcoming lectures, invitations to garden-oriented vacations, the
opportunity to trade opinions with other gardeners who share a
passion for a specific kind of plant, or a chance to electronically
visit gardens far from home. Though the world outside may be
barren, the virtual world is always in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Web also offers unlimited shopping opportunities
and may eventually replace catalogs as the main way to place
midwinter orders for seeds, plants, garden art, and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But at this still-early stage, part of the charm of gardening
Web sites is that so many are predominantly noncommercial. After
all, the Web was established by university researchers to help them
trade knowledge for its own sake, and that's exactly what gardeners
like to do. Many of the most informative sites remain those posted
by land-grant colleges with strong agricultural programs.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing the gardening Web is easy using so-called search engines
like Alta Vista and Yahoo! Just type in a few descriptive words,
and these programs will whisk you to related Web sites, even if you
don't have their names or addresses. Be as specific as possible.
For instance, type ``Ohio State horticulture,'' and you'll get onto
the great Web site at www.hcs.ohio-state.edu/hcs/hcs.html. Type
``gardening'' and you'll be swamped by options, many of them not
worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   Finding just one good Web site can open the door to many more. A
lot of Web sites offer links to other good sites devoted to the
same topic that you can jump to with a double click. After a few
hours of this, you'll stop thinking in terms of individual Web
sites and start picturing gardening on line as a huge,
interconnected subculture.
</P>
<P>
   If surfing this network is almost effortless, locating specific
information can be difficult and time-consuming. Most gardeners
find it much quicker to turn to their well-worn reference books for
answers to questions. But the more you use the Web, the faster and
more efficient you'll get at zeroing in on what you really want to
know instead of just wandering dazed through the giant shopping
mall of virtual gardening. One timesaver is ``bookmarking,'' making
your own permanent links between your ``home page,'' the place you
start out, and gardening Web sites you find repeatedly helpful.
Just click on ``bookmark'' while the Web site you want is on your
screen, and soon you'll build a directory of these favorites
without having to type a single address.
</P>
<P>
   Constant updating is one big advantage the Web has over books
and catalogs. You have a better chance on the Web of finding
information on pests that reflects the latest research. For
instance, you can learn the latest about Integrated Pest
Management, including University of Rhode Island entomologist Dick
Casagrande's project to release parasitic wasps that kill the lily
leaf beetle, by going to www.nysaes.cornell.edu/ipmnet/ri. And this
address will link you to IPM Web sites in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Local Web sites offer information on upcoming garden events, and
are geared to gardening in our climate.
</P>
<P>
   Hilda Morrill, former public relations chairwoman of the Garden
Club Federation of Massachusetts and past president of the Amateur
Gardeners of Milton, has developed www.bostongardens.com, which
invites free postings of garden club events open to the public.
Visitors to the site will also find gardening tips, articles, book
reviews, and links to other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Other local sites include the Arnold Arboretum at
www.arboretum.harvard.edu and its Institute for Cultural Landscape
Studies at www.icls.harvard.edu. Then there's the Massachusetts
Horticultural Society at www.masshort.org and the New England
Garden History Society at www.masshort.org/neghs.htm, the New
England Wild Flower Society at www.newfs.org/ and the Worcester
County Horticulture Society at towerhillbg.org/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   You can visit the beautiful gardens and greenhouses of Smith
College at www.smith.edu/garden/, which has won design awards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the best horticultural Web sites are:
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Botanical Garden at www.bbg.org, which contains a
clever virtual garden tour of its premises with a directory called
the ``Stroll Control.'' Botanical gardens and colleges are good
places to sign up for botanical tours, either to local gardens or
far-flung destinations like Japan or New Zealand. This site offers
some of the best travel programs for the well-heeled enthusiast.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State University's ``Plants of Horticulture'' database at
www.hcs.ohio-state.edu/hort/plants.html has nearly 4,000
descriptions and images.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Horticultural Society Web site at
www.libertynet.org/phs contains profiles of recommended Gold Medal
Plants and sources for buying them. Each plant has been selected
for ease of growth, disease resistance, and beauty by panels
including gardeners and landscapers.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution Research Information System at
www.siris.si.edu has a great collection of photographs of private
and public gardens throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Strybing Botanical Garden in San Francisco at
www.strybing.org is a beautiful site for sore eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Botanical Garden in England has a site at
www.rbgkew.org.uk that allows you to visit abroad without leaving
your chair.
</P>
<P>
   The Rutgers Cooperative Extension at
rce.rutgers.edu/weeddocuments will help you identify weeds, and
much else.
</P>
<P>
   You can also get gardening articles that appeared in print from
some Web sites. Present and past garden columns from the At Home
section are available through www.boston.com.
</P>
<P>
   You can find articles from Boston-based Horticulture magazine at
www.horticulturemagazine.com. Or you can read stories from Organic
Gardening at organicgardening.com or Fine Gardening at
finegardening.com without paying for a subscription.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of these sites will try to sell you something. But if you're
interested in shopping over the Net, garden.com is by far the
largest commercial gardening site, though those who have ordered
through it give it mixed reviews on plant quality. Even if you're
not buying anything, this site is a good source for information and
links to other sites. It, too, has an on-line magazine, called
Garden Escape.
</P>
<P>
   Another large commercial site is the Virtual Garden at
www.vg.com, which features the on-line version of the ``Time Life
Complete Gardener Encyclopedia,'' as well as regional gardening
advice, chat rooms, a column by noted writer Alan Lacy, and someone
to answer gardening questions.
</P>
<P>
   Many nurseries and seed companies also have Web sites, which are
updated according to plant availability. Checking them out is a
great way of eliminating the disappointment all gardeners have felt
when a box of long-awaited plants arrives full of substitutions for
the sold-out plants they really wanted. Even if you order by mail
or fax, nursery Web sites can be great for researching the
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The W. Atlee Burpee Co. at www.burpee.com has a particularly
lively Web site, including a virtual tour of its test gardens and a
link to a horticulturalist at the National Gardening Association in
Burlington, Vt., who answers questions.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can got straight to the NGA Web site at
www2.garden.org/nga, which is one of the best. Can you expect less
from a nonprofit organization based in a city were IBM is a major
employer? In addition to answering questions, NGA has a great
system for linking you to other Web sites. It also offers on-line
courses (these cost money) and the contents of its National
Gardening Association magazine (free).
</P>
<P>
   The search engines and links can help you find specialty
nurseries if you want a larger selection of, for instance, lilacs
or hydrangeas to choose from than a general nursery can offer. And
the Web gives them more space to describe (and hopefully picture)
each plant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can also use the Web to get in touch with other gardeners or
to receive specialized e-mail. One way to do this is to subscribe
to an e-mail ``list'' shared by gardeners who have similar
interests, be it aroids or trilliums. One Web site for finding such
lists is www.liszt.com/select/Nature/Plants. When you subscribe,
the list owner will provide you with all the necessary information.
</P>
<P>
   You can also post questions at Web site forums, where readers
will leave you answers. One of the biggests links for this is
www.gardenweb.com.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of sites ask you to register your address, which means
you'll receive unsolicited e-mail, or ``spam,'' from them. But you
don't have to sign in unless you choose to.
</P>
<P>
   The Web isn't for everybody all the time, but it can be a great
way to get through winter. And by the time you've mastered the
virtual garden world, it may be warm enough to go outside and do
some real 3-D gardening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-E-FURNITURE-BOS &LR;      01-13 1979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-E-FURNITURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOST OF HOUSEWARES A CLICK AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Choosing furniture is such a touchy-feely process. Who would buy
a sofa without sitting on it? A mattress without stretching out on
it? A comfy chair without curling up in it?
</P>
<P>
   Well, if the predictions of industry analysts materialize, the
answer is _ a lot of folks. At the moment, buying furniture off the
Net is still in its infancy. But 1999 will go down as the year of
the start-up e-furnishing store. Just a few of the recently born
sites hoping for a piece of the cyberspace pie are living.com,
retromodern.com, furnitureonline.com, behome.com,
decoratewithstyle.com, and two locally based sites, furniture.com
and homeportfolio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these sites are backed by millions in venture capital.
But all have dreams of rising above the herd and becoming the next
amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly no guarantees out there in cyberspace, but
that doesn't seem to matter. A lot of people with a few extra bucks
just don't want to be left behind. They're gambling that the
brick-and-mortar stores of today will go the way of the dinosaur
and that on-line furniture and home-furnishings shopping will be
the future.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be worth the gamble. After all, home furnishings is a
$178 billion-a-year industry; on-line projected sales for 1999
topped $319 million and could hit $3.5 billion by 2003, according
to Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the greatest hurdle for e-commerce furniture
hopefuls is that it's a very test-the-sofa and fluff-the-pillows
market. Therefore, the majority of people using the sites today are
logging on for information and comparison pricing. Pressed for time
and unwilling to spend weekends shlepping from showroom to
showroom, they surf the Net and then head to local stores, armed
with price and product information.
</P>
<P>
   Size is another problem. According to Forrester analyst Seema
Williams, 75 percent of home products sold through catalogs are
UPS-shippable _ in other words, relatively small items such as
lamps, tables, miniblinds. This will most likely be mirrored on the
Internet. People will buy small products before they'll purchase a
sofa or armoire. But in the future? Sure, we'll be buying large
purchases on line, says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Internet is so new and so vast and the
possibilities so limitless, it's merely a matter of time before
further technological innovations and advancements make on-line
shopping increasingly consumer-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston area, there are two sites that demand attention.
One is furniture.com, based in Framingham; the other is
homeportfolio.com, with offices in a renovated church in Newton.
Both were begun by novice entrepreneurs but are now backed by
deep-pocket financing and run by seasoned CEOs from the corporate
world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com was the brainchild of Steve Rothschild, whose
family owned the Empire furniture store in Worcester, Mass., and
Misha Katz, a technological guru who built the outfit's original
Web site and is now vice president of new technology. The duo
created their site, originally called furnituresite.com, in July
1997. In January 1999, the name was changed to furniture.com, and
financing to date tops $48 million. The site offers more than
50,000 items. Most analysts agree that furniture.com is a strong
leader in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September, we had 772,000 unique visitors come to the
site,'' meaning new visitors, not repeat customers, says Andrew
Brooks, CEO of furniture.com. ``And they spent an average of nine
minutes on site, which indicates to us that they're finding the
experience evolving and user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And no, shoppers are not just buying small items,'' Brooks
adds, ``but will very often buy a multithousand-dollar item as
their first purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   He credits some of their success to three consumer services.
</P>
<P>
   --``Furniture Finder.'' This search tool is for consumers who
want to redo a room but don't know exactly what they want. If the
room to be decorated is a bedroom, they can click ``bedroom'' and
find a vast array of beds, bureaus, and so forth, in various
styles, finishes, and prices, with other helpful information such
as dimensions, care, warranties, and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   --``Style Guide.'' This further helps the consumer by
identifying and dividing all available items into four main
categories: casual contemporary, country, modern, and traditional.
</P>
<P>
   --``Room Planner.'' This allows users to create a plan of their
home bedroom on the screen with the proper dimensions and placement
of doors and windows _ like an architectural drawing. They can then
place the furniture they already own in the room with the proper
dimensions, then introduce new pieces into the space. This helps
consumers to visualize how the room will look with both old and new
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com represents more than 150 manufacturers of medium-
to higher-price contemporary furniturs are shipped directly
from manufacturer to consumer, thereby cutting out the middleman,
or retailer. Also, 50 percent of this site's offerings are private
labels _ items made especially for furniture.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another asset is the live-human-being element: design
consultants or personal shoppers who will answer consumer questions
on a pop-up window on the computer screen or by telephone. In
addition, fabric swatches are available _ not many; one to eight
per item _ and are delivered within four days. Delivery of ordered
furniture is free, along with setup. There is no charge for
returns, but you won't get your money back, only credit toward your
next purchase. There's also an on-line magazine with ``unbiased''
product information, a ``QuickShip Boutique'' with 13 items
available for delivery within three weeks, and instant on-line
financing with credit approval, according to CEO Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furniture is not a commodity,'' says Kirsten von Hassel, vice
president of marketing. ``It is style-driven and ego- driven.
People are nest-building and want to make a public statement in
their homes of their individual style and tastes. We want to help
consumers realize what they are trying to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Crain recently bought a bedroom set from furniture.com.
After looking in various local stores and not finding what she
wanted, she began searching the Net. She found furniture.com the
easiest and most informative site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd bought books and CDs before off the Net, but never a large
purchase,'' says Crain, a national category manager for Gillette.
``But I really didn't have a problem with such a large order. I
figured if the merchandise was terrible, they'd have to take it
back or they'd have a serious lawsuit on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the set was delivered on time and was exactly what she
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks great,'' says Crain, ``and I'd buy something again
from them, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Homeportfolio.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homeportfolio.com has recently evolved from an Internet guide to
top-of-the-line and hard-to-find home design products to an
emerging e-commerce site. In other words, the site was originally
more educator than retailer, offering the consumer and design
professional products chosen by the site's editorial team for their
workmanship, design, and materials. Unlike furniture.com, this is
not just a furniture site but features bath fixtures, appliances,
windows and doors, and flooring, along with the products of 500
furniture manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Homeportfolio entered the e-commerce fray the week after
Thanksgiving. Merchandise is limited to 22 brands and 2,000
products. Some analysts feel this site may have an uphill battle
competing with the more seasoned, everything-already-in-place
e-commerce players.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the site was born in 1994 when two former Yale
classmates met for lunch. Rolly Rouse, an architect and engineer,
wanted to help people create the house of their dreams by providing
them with on-line information to achieve their goals. He shared his
thoughts with his friend Tom Ashbrook, a journalist who was then
working for The Boston Globe. They got their first seed money in
1996 and hired Shawn Becker from the MIT Media Lab to help design a
site.
</P>
<P>
   Homeportfolio was launched under the umbrella of BuildingBlocks
Interactive in January 1998. It recently completed a second round
of financing totaling $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to reorganize the entire home-design industry around
the consumer,'' says Rouse. ``We wanted a site that would link the
consumer with manufacturers, retailers, and design professionals.
We wanted to help people get homes that matched their
aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, they are showing 750 top brands from around the
world. Consumers can build on-line portfolios of wish-list products
and also keep a tally of where these products are sold in their
local area _ ``Dealer Locator'' lists top 25,000 retailers. Another
addition is the ``Interior Designer Portfolio,'' which includes
short biographies of designers, a statement of their vision and
approach, and several images of their work.
</P>
<P>
   A warning posted for visitors to the site during the holidays
stating that they might ``experience periodic slow performance''
has been removed since Homeportfolio switched to a more robust
server, according to company spokesperson Jennifer Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site is running a lot faster now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Maguire of Louisville, Ky., who is in the process of
putting an addition on his house and renovating a kitchen, has used
Homeportfolio as a launching point for ideas on different products
and on cabinetry and lighting. When it became an e-commerce site,
he purchased two dozen pulls for his kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kitchen is a very organic space and I wanted complementary
cabinet pulls,'' say Maguire, an architect, who does a lot of
purchasing off the Internet. ``I found a collection of pulls, the
Arizona Knob collection, made by a company named Providence, that
are made from rocks, and ordered two dozen on Dec. 10. I didn't
expect to receive them until after the holidays. Well, I got them
in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal says the best feature of this site is
its ``personal portfolio.'' A negative is ``the site isn't easy to
navigate and it is hard to comparison-shop; too often, . . . prices
are `withheld at the manufacturer's request.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Other sites
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another site is hometownstores.com, which grew out of the
family-owned Curry Ace Hardware stores in Quincy and Braintree,
Mass. Sean Curry and Mark Vassalli came up with and designed the
site, supported by Curry's father, Bob. Launched in July, this site
offers more than 50,000 brand-name hardware and home-goods
products. In the future, the site hopes to include other stores,
making it similar to shopping in a small New England mall.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites worth visiting:
</P>
<P>
   --behome.com: Limited furniture selection _ eight manufacturers
_ but detailed descriptions of finish, construction, style,
dimensions, price, and warranty of mid-to-high-price pieces on a
very usable site.
</P>
<P>
   --decoratewithstyle.com: Easy-to-use site with large selection
of wallpaper and blinds, as well as some inexpensive, framed
poster-type artwork, with helpful hints on selecting paper and
measuring a room, and decorating ideas.
</P>
<P>
   --ezshop.com: Visually attractive site includes gifts, toys, and
decorations along with inexpensive furniture.
</P>
<P>
   --furniturefind.com: Furniture by more than 50 well-known
manufacturers on an accessible site.
</P>
<P>
   --furnitureonline.com: Inexpensive furniture, good for home
office furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   --living.com: Limited selection but a quick site, with some
items aimed at the more adventurous, young decorator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
