<HEADER>
A5020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-INJURIES-BOS &LR;      01-13 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-INJURIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOOLS, WORK LOAD KEY IN COPING WITH RSI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the RSI that's the worst of it. Gardening brings aches and
pains, especially to the suburban gardener after a long winter's
layoff. But, oh, that RSI.
</P>
<P>
   Every spring I hurt. A not-so-cold weekend is spent spraying
dormant oil and maybe fungicides and pruning the apple tree, which
is getting closer to the open, low shape I want for it.
</P>
<P>
   I turn over beds in the vegetable garden, lop the buddleias low,
trim dead foliage all over the place (taking care not to disturb
the swelling buds of the peonies).
</P>
<P>
   And I hurt. My back aches, my shoulders throb, my legs turn to
iron. For all of that, there's ibuprofen and hot showers or baths.
Take a day or two off, and it's all back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with repetitive strain injuries. My wrists and hands and
forearms ache, and they don't seek warmth, because they are
inflamed. They want cold. And while the pain subsides after a few
days off, the injuries don't completely heal. They are easily
aggravated.
</P>
<P>
   Repetitive strain injuries pretty much involve awkwardness,
force, vibration, and, above all, repetition, according to Dr.
David Diamond of the medical department at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Computer operators, office workers, and researchers endure such
work conditions. Diamond, an RSI expert, treats them all at MIT.
Gardeners experience those conditions, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mixed in with all the computer users here . . . I have seen a
handful of RSI sufferers whose symptoms were aggravated by
gardening tasks,'' Diamond told me in a recent phone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I've seen it is people planting 300 bulbs with a trowel
that doesn't quite fit their hand comfortably and doing a lot of
pruning with pruning shears,'' Diamond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it with a woman who was cutting twigs to make floral
arrangements and repetitively using dull shears, and so applying a
lot of force.''
</P>
<P>
   In the office environment, Diamond said, RSI sufferers need to
look at how they do the job, how they position themselves. It's the
same in the garden. Get a kneeling pad instead of leaning over or
climb a ladder instead of reaching too high.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to look at is the tools. They need to be sharp to
reduce the force needed to make them work, Diamond said. If they
have a spring component, it should be at the proper tension so you
don't have to grip excessively hard.
</P>
<P>
   Use tools with softer, fatter, more curved handles, which allow
more neutral hand positions, Diamond said. Garden hoses with a
pistol grip are better than the old-fashioned turn-nozzles.
</P>
<P>
   And beware of so-called ergonomic tools. Not all are truly
ergonomic, so you have to do some shopping. You get what you pay
for.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners can address the issue of repetition by how they
structure their work, Diamond said. Mix up the tasks. If you have
five hours of pruning, do some, then something else; then do some
more, then something else.
</P>
<P>
   My first encounter with gardening RSI was in a class at the
Arnold Arboretum in Boston about 10 years ago. A nice woman who did
almost nothing but garden showed up one day with her hand in a
splint. Pruning, squeezing those handles over and over, did her in.
She was worried.
</P>
<P>
   I became worried when my RSI at the newspaper started coming
home with me at night. Cold compresses helped, but I found it took
all weekend to be rid of the pain. All weekend without gardening.
</P>
<P>
   So I did something. I saw a doctor, I attended classes, I got
involved with my union's RSI effort.
</P>
<P>
   I have used a splint to keep my left wrist from flexing in my
sleep, I have learned to hold my hands and arms naturally and how
to type to minimize injury, and I have set up my work station
ergonomically. I have good tools, I use them right.
</P>
<P>
   It has helped a lot, but it cannot eliminate the RSI. The
gardening makes it worse, but I am not going to give that up. You
shouldn't either. Get help, educate yourself, don't ignore RSI.
</P>
<P>
   If all I did was a little gardening, I'd be fine, so I look
forward to retirement. Of course, then I'll be doing just that much
more gardening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
