<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERTIBLES AND THEIR SIREN CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a day when winter blinked.
</P>
<P>
   Three days into the New Year, air warm and sun glistening, she
passed me on the interstate. The top on her Saab convertible was
down and she had a scarf on her head, sunglasses wrapped across her
eyes, as she bopped to music I could not hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thelma or Louise?,'' I asked myself.
</P>
<P>
   And that got me to thinking about convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering how they had symbolized different things down the
years: panache, elegance, escape, the freedom of the open road.
</P>
<P>
   They'd evolved from the elegant days of Delahayes, Duesenbergs,
and Packards to the hot droptops of the 1950s, the T-Bird and the
'Vette, the big Lincoln and Cadillac ragtops. In the 1970s, they
virtually disappeared from showrooms.  &UR; Today &LR; , they are making a
big comeback, particularly as Miata-inspired roadsters.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home, I picked up a book, ``The Convertible,'' by Ken
Vose (Chronicle Books, San Francisco; www.chronbooks.com) and
through words and pictures followed his ode to the convertible as
it captured romance, rumble, and revival.
</P>
<P>
   Vose subtitled his book ``An Illustrated History of a Dream
Machine'' and one of the first images you see when you open it is a
shot of Cary Grant and Grace Kelly sitting in a Sunbeam Alpine,
heads in the Mediterranean sun, looking down on Monte Carlo. It's a
shot from the Hitchcock flick, ``To Catch a Thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere you find shots of other actresses and actors who added
to the romance of the ragtop: George Maharis and Martin Milner
beside the Corvette in which they roamed ``Route 66''; Susan
Sarandon and Geena Davis _ ``Thelma and Louise'' _ in front of
their '66 T-Bird; and Jack Nicholson and Shirley MacLean in the
'Vette that symbolized his fight against middle-age angst in
``Terms of Endearment.''
</P>
<P>
   The images all speak to one essential of the convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Vose writes: ``Driving a convertible means more than just
freedom of movement. It's also the freedom to enjoy the great
outdoors on an equal footing with the richest of the rich. Put the
top down on your beat-up-mobile, and the sun on your face is
identical to that shining on the guy over there in the Lamborghini
Diablo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't that America?,'' in the words of singer John Mellencamp.
</P>
<P>
   Think early convertible and you think 1936 Cord Supercharged
Convertible Coupe. Or, as Vose points out, the elegance of Clark
Gable as manifested in his fine fleet: a 1932 Packard Twin Six, a
1934 Packard Twelve LeBaron, a Rollston-bodied 1934 Duesenberg J, a
1938 Packard Darrin Convertible Victoria, a 1946 Lincoln
Continental, a 1940 Jaguar XK120, and a 1957 Mercedes 300 Sc
cabriolet.
</P>
<P>
   Vose gives us hot rods like the classic 1932 Ford Roadster, and
he gives us James Dean, alive and dead, in his Porsche 356 with the
words ``Little Bastard'' painted on its rear engine cover.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s were a heady time for the convertible and its
popularity rolled into the 1960s when pony cars got droptops, the
Volkswagen Bug took off, and convertible sales hit half a million
by 1965. By 1969, Vose reports, they had dropped to 200,000, and in
1976 the last Cadillac Eldorado convertible _ the only domestic
droptop being built at the time _ rolled off the line.
</P>
<P>
   Were we bored with ourselves, had we lost our sense of
adventure, were we too self-conscious? Did air conditioning and the
fuel crisis help kill the convertible? It seems the '70s, with an
essence of counterculture, should have been a good decade for the
convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Vose quotes Peter Marsh and Peter Collett from their book
``Driving Passion'': ``Convertibles communicate their own
distinctive messages. For many people they evoke not only the true
spirit of motoring, but also a sense of youthful freedom and
nonconformity.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the '70s, nonconformists drove Volkswagen vans and
slant-six Valiants, not convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the heady '80s, which showed, as Vose writes, ``the
convertible was not dead, it had just gone into hiding, waiting for
a more favorable economic and political environment.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lee Iaccoca, who gave us the minivan, also brought back the
convertible with the Chrysler LeBaron. By the end of the decade,
the Mazda Miata had come ashore and its advent meant the return of
the real two-seat sports roadster. Were it not for the Miata, we
might not  &UR; today &LR;  have the BMW Z3, Porsche Boxster, Mercedes SLK,
Dodge Viper, Plymouth Prowler, or upcoming Audi TT roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Saab's got a droptop and so does Volvo. They seem to be
everywhere again.
</P>
<P>
   You see them driven by young and old, men and women, all out
there in the sun and the wind in a way you cannot be in an enclosed
box. Possibility seems boundless, adventure endless.
</P>
<P>
   It's what convertibles are all about, even on a warm faux fall
day that comes upon us in early January.
</P>
<P>
   Vose captures this essence very well when he quotes an old
British Leyland ad extolling the essence of the Triumph TR-7.
</P>
<P>
   It reads: ``Headroom: 93 million miles.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's to convertibles, to unexpected warm days, and to the
woman in the Saab _ Thelma or Louise _ and many miles in open cars
on open roads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-13 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EVEN OLDER WORKERS NEED TO SHARPEN THEIR STREET SMARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plunging into the working world can baffle a lot of college
students. They may have tons of technical skills, but street smarts
are much harder to acquire. If you don't think so, look at some
foundering 40-year-olds; they still don't have the street smarts
they need to make it.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 things every worker should learn, quickly:
</P>
<P>
   _ Get your financial act together.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows which group of people will strike it rich over the
next 30 years, but I can tell you who won't: those who live from
paycheck to paycheck, running up credit card bills instead of
investing.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy when you are young to discount the importance of
money, but understanding how to save and invest is one of the most
crucial career skills. Find a job that can support your lifestyle.
Learn to budget. Understand personal finance, including how to
invest in individual stocks. Then put your money where your future
is.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this survey from the December issue of Money magazine,
when people were asked what they would do in their job if money
were not an issue. Only 25 percent said they would continue to work
full time. Thirty-nine percent said they would work part time, 21
percent would retire completely and 15 percent would become active
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   People who live from paycheck to paycheck won't have those
options. They can't start their own businesses or retire early or
cut back or risk changing careers. When rumors of layoffs surface,
they'll be the ones having the sleepless nights.
</P>
<P>
   Money can't buy happiness, but it can buy peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Technology won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Warren Buffett, possibly the greatest individual
investor of all time. He has said that he won't buy a business he
doesn't understand, so he avoids technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers can appreciate that sentiment. They don't
understand technology, so they avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett is a billionaire, meaning he can afford to do what he
damn well pleases. You probably can't. Technology is changing not
just jobs and companies, but entire industries. If you don't
understand it, take the time to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are no techie, spend an hour or two each year
learning what tech jobs are being invented. As the Web continues to
grow, more high-tech jobs are being created that don't require such
a technical background.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, while the Dow Jones industrial average rose 25 percent
and the technology-heavy Nasdaq Composite index soared 85 percent,
the stock in Buffett's company, Berkshire Hathaway, fell almost 20
percent. That's pretty much how the job market is going, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand what kind of company you work for.
</P>
<P>
   The first post-college job I had was an exercise in mutual
exploitation. The newspaper hired people straight out of college,
worked them hard and paid them poorly. On the other hand, it also
gave them good experience that allowed them to move on to better
jobs (at other newspapers, of course).
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with any of that. They used me and I used
them.
</P>
<P>
   But some employees do a good job for a couple of years, then
expect big raises and get frustrated when they don't materialize.
They've forgotten that they would never have been hired in the
first place if the employer weren't an exploiter.
</P>
<P>
   Pick five words to describe your company. If ``cutthroat'' is
one of them, don't expect loyalty. If ``demanding'' is there, don't
expect long vacations. If ``understaffed'' is there, don't complain
about the workload. And if ``quality'' is not there, don't hold
your breath about merit raises.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find co-workers you respect, and learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   If you are at a medium-sized company and you can't find at least
three people worthy of your respect, it means one of two things:
You have outgrown the company and should move on, or you are
incredibly arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   Resist the temptation to get advice only from people who are
just like you: same age, same job, same background, same sex, same
skin color. You'll learn a lot more with a diverse network.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn what makes other people tick.
</P>
<P>
   Take the time to see things from other people's perspectives.
Without turning yourself into a wreck, what can you do to make
other people's jobs easier? What are you doing to make their jobs
more difficult?
</P>
<P>
   Before you ask for a raise, for example, look at it from your
boss's perspective. It doesn't matter to the company that your
kid's about to go into college, but it does matter that your sales
have increased 15 percent or that you now have more
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be a constant grumbler, but certainly make constructive
suggestions about how the company can improve.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes this can be a great way to move up if you are feeling
stifled. Identify tasks that no one is now doing but that would
help the company, then offer to do them.
</P>
<P>
   If your boss is rejecting your ideas without adequate
explanation, ask the people you respect for their honest opinions.
If they think the ideas are strong, it may be a sign to change
companies, or at least bosses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add something to your repertoire each year.
</P>
<P>
   What skill did you add in 1999 that made you a better worker
than you were a year earlier? Did you learn a computer program or
study some management techniques _ or simply learn how to sleep
with your eyes open?
</P>
<P>
   Every skill you have makes you a little more attractive, not
just to your current employer, but to potential ones. It carries an
extra bonus for older workers, helping them overcome the stereotype
of being complacent.
</P>
<P>
   _ The difference between a 30-minute commute and a 10-minute
commute is more than 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Commuting half an hour can sap your energy more than two hours
at the office.
</P>
<P>
   But having a short commute _ or, even better, telecommuting _
can offer you the great workplace luxury of having a relaxing lunch
at home. Don't underestimate how valuable that can be.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't give in to self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   There will be times when you feel stuck in a dead-end job or sad
about getting laid off or angry about discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Experience the emotion, but then move on.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest obstacles to a successful career and a happy
life is when you dwell on mistakes or mistreatment, saying that you
can't accomplish something because of this or because of that.
Don't use that as an excuse for inertia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   We live in an age of hyperbole, when people will say and do
extreme things to get attention. E-mail makes it easy to say some
thoughtless and cruel things _ without seeing and hearing the pain
that they cause.
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't like Nordstrom: There are a lot of things you just
can't take back. People may forgive, but they will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
