<HEADLINE>
VW EUROVAN SHORT ON FEATURES, BIG ON PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when Arlo Guthrie took a ``half-ton of garbage, put it
in the back of a red VW microbus, took shovels and rakes and
implements of destruction'' and headed out for his Thanksgiving
encounter over littering with the fearsome Officer Obie?
</P>
<P>
   You could do the same with the new 2000 Volkswagen EuroVan GLS,
but there's a hitch: Arlo didn't pay $33,750 for the VW van he
drove in ``Alice's Restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   And that price is my problem with the new EuroVan, descendant of
the old microbus, but more closely descended from the EuroVans of
1980-91, rectangular boxes with 90 horsepower engines.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at VW call the EuroVans ``highly versatile vans for
the adventuresome,'' and say the GLS is ``well equipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, do I feel as if I'm driving a delivery van as I sit
high in the seat and listen to the roar of the motor seep into the
cab?
</P>
<P>
   At almost $34,000 I'd expect firm leather seats (heated, at
that), double sliding doors (a trend in vans these days), and, hey,
even a glove compartment or a big storage console between the front
seats.
</P>
<P>
   What you get is soft fabric seats that dip at the thigh, no
glove compartment, no console. Storage is limited to slots in the
front doors and sidewalls in the rear. Vans are meant for journeys,
and spartan doesn't work here.
</P>
<P>
   I think that what Volkswagen is offering in the EuroVan is a
base on which to build a camper _ you can add a pop-up roof with a
two-person bed, window screens, a refrigerator, a second battery,
and a two-burner LP gas stove.
</P>
<P>
   But $33,750 is too high a price to pay for a base on which you
build your camper. And as a van in competition with far more
luxurious offerings _ say the Honda Odyssey 5-door with a
navigation system at $28,000, or offerings from Toyota, Mazda,
Ford, and Chevrolet _ the EuroVan is just not plush enough.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad, because there are things about the van that
are admirable.
</P>
<P>
   Its 2.8-liter, VR6 engine _ two overhead cams, two-valves per
cylinder, 140 horsepower, 18.4 miles per gallon in a week of
driving _ makes it a virtual rocket in its class. Straight ahead on
hilly country roads or on highways, it's got all the power you
need.
</P>
<P>
   But you can hear that power coming back at you through the
firewall _ and if you happen to have your wipers set on
intermittent, the loud clicks they make with each movement are like
an annoying metronome set to a background rumble.
</P>
<P>
   It's got great heat _ remember the old VW buses with that tiny
metal chimney that rose from floor to dash and heated nothing? _
but the defroster doesn't cover the windshield to its edges.
</P>
<P>
   The EuroVan is front-wheel drive, and a standard low-speed
traction control system should help make it a good winter vehicle.
The ride is fairly smooth on its four-wheel independent suspension,
rack-and-pinion steering is crisp, and ABS-assisted four-wheel disc
brakes bring it to quick stops.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a very tall box and the suspension that gives it a
comfortable straight-ahead ride can't compensate for that high
center of gravity. Occupants are at the mercy of strong lateral
forces in turns.
</P>
<P>
   If you suddenly come upon a sharp turn at a good speed, the feel
of the steering wheel does not instill confidence as you roll into
the turn, and I had the sensations of both oversteer and understeer
at various times.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, it's got a rigid, rugged body, and safety
features include dual front airbags and side impact beams in the
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment includes power door locks, cruise control, a
6-speaker AM-FM radio with cassette player, heated windshield
washer nozzles, power outside mirrors, and a four-speed automatic
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Zoned climate control for the rear is a nice touch, as are
focused reading lights that let passengers read without interfering
with the driver's vision.
</P>
<P>
   The rear cargo area, with roll-up cover, seems cavernous, though
a brighter light for finding gear at night would be nice. But,
because the van is so tall, I'm not sure how a short person _ say
under 5-foot-4 _ would close the heavy rear hatch once it has been
opened; it swings well up and out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a Volkswagen fan. The Golf, New Beetle, Jetta, and Passat
are all wonderful cars sold at good prices.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen is a company broadening its offerings, from
high-powered Beetles to a 12-cylinder luxury sedan, and it is
cutting edge in much of what it already offers.
</P>
<P>
   But with the EuroVan, it's a company behind the times in terms
of passenger comfort and convenience. If they want to sell campers,
they should just build them fully loaded and sell them as such.
</P>
<P>
   If they want to sell a minivan, they should design and build one
_ and not try to pass off a stripped-down camper as a comfortable
family van.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, at a base price of $31,300, I don't feel I
should have paid for the power sunroof ($1,000 option), heated
front seats ($400 option), and metallic paint ($275 extra).
</P>
<P>
   But at least you get a full-size spare tire.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The $275 extra is annoying, but the Black Magic Metallic paint
is liquidly beautiful. Looks as if you could dip a finger in it.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The radio, center dash, is too low. You must take your eyes
off the road to see what you are doing down there.
</P>
<P>
   --Even worse, the cup holders sit on the floor. You're high in
the driver's seat, and if you reach for bottle or cup, you have to
bend so far your head may be below the dash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $31,300 &QL; 
Price as tested: $33,750 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 144/172 lb-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 114.9 inches/188.4 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 72.4 inches/76.4 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 4220 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 7 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
