<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMIZED WEB BEGINS WITH A JOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Goldberg isn't a card-carrying comedian. He's never sweated
through open mike night at some seedy, basement bar. He's never
bombed before a convention of drunk dentists nor has he ever felt
the cool breeze of a tomato cruising past his ear. All the same, he
and his colleagues think they can predict what jokes make you
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   How? It's all in the math.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, an associate professor of industrial engineering at
the University of California at Berkeley, has created a program
called Jester 2.0 that serves as a kind of Joke-o-Meter. At the
Jester Web site (eigentaste.berkeley.edu), you are asked to rate a
series of jokes on a scale of Not Funny to Very Funny. Based on
those responses, the system lumps you with people who share similar
opinions and sends you jokes that they enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not magic,'' says Goldberg. ``It's statistical pattern
recognition. You don't need to know anything about humor.''
</P>
<P>
   But does it actually work? Well, yes and no. Goldberg and his
team of graduate students chose jokes designed to elicit a strong
response. We're talking light bulb jokes, Clinton jokes, pope
jokes, gender jokes, everything but knock-knock jokes. After I
rated dozens of them, the system gave up and announced, ``Sorry,
Jester could not find any personalized joke recommendations for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   That happens, Goldberg explains, in rare circumstances when
users have particularly strong (and well-defined) tastes. ``There
are certainly improvements that can be made, but this technique has
enormous potential,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Enormous potential, indeed. The good professor has signed on as
an adviser at a company called NetCustomize Corp., which is
striving to perfect the technology in the commercial arena. It is
currently offering a joke delivery service called eLOL (as in
``electronic laugh out loud''). You sign up for the free service at
elol.com, and then you receive jokes on your desktop every day at
the time of your choice. You can also specify how many jokes you
want to receive as well as what kind _ ranging from one-liners and
stories to videos and cartoons. You rate the jokes, and after a
time, the system tailors the yuks to your particular taste.
</P>
<P>
   So why does it keep sending me the kind of jokes that could get
me accused of sexual harassment? For some reason, the comedians in
my computer seem to think I enjoy only off-color humor, the bawdier
the better (as in full-screen, full frontal). No matter how many
times I rate a joke with a groan, I still receive similar fare.
(You can request that the service deliver only clean, politically
correct jokes, but we have nothing against the occasional adult
joke as long as it's funny.)
</P>
<P>
   Shuki Nir, CEO and cofounder of NetCustomize, insists that I'm
an anomaly. ``It's not about dirty vs. nondirty,'' he says. ``There
is no relevancy to the category itself. It's a matter of taste _
meaning the quality of the joke and how funny you find it compared
with other people,'' he adds, noting that, so far, 70 percent of
eLOL users have given the system high grades. ``I guess you fall in
the 30.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, is it really possible to quantify something as
elusive as taste? ``That's the million-dollar question,'' says
Goldberg. Indeed. The folks at Amazon.com have been trying to
figure it out for years by offering personal recommendations to
users based on past purchases. As any Amazon user knows, though,
the suggestions aren't always perfect. If you ordered a book on
thermodynamics for your dear Uncle Charlie a few months ago, you
might still be receiving recommendations for books with titles like
``Absolute Zero and the Conquest of Cold.''
</P>
<P>
   But think of the time you could save if there really is a
mathematical formula for taste. The infinite expanse of the
Internet has created a need for personalized filters. ``I started
this business from my personal frustration with having too much
entertainment content delivered at the wrong time with low
quality,'' says Nir, who plans to launch a service offering
customized music and video content starting in April.
</P>
<P>
   And there are many other dot coms trying to perfect the
technology; one Connecticut-based outfit called MeTV.com aims to
offer a customized movie rental service over the Internet in June.
The goal? When it comes to entertainment, everyone ought to be able
to say, ``It's all about me.''
</P>
<P>
   So for now, it's up to the engineers and scientists to figure
out the appropriate algorithm for taste. Isn't there something a
tad bit bizarre about that concept? ``Nothing around here is
strange these days,'' says Goldberg. ``I mean, I'm at Berkeley,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last of the Y2K Bugs: The Y2K watchers turned out to have a
rather slow evening, when the New Year turned into a nonevent. Now,
one final attempt to cash in on the ``crisis'' has gone bust. The
folks at www.year2000.com, a profitable Y2K watch venture,
auctioned off the domain name on eBay, reporting a winning bid of
$10 million. But the bid turned out to be a fraud, and the name was
still up for sale. After all that hype, something had to go wrong,
didn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send e-mail to p_hartigan(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
