<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A GRIP ON OPTIMISM IS A REAL DRAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A story in Monday's paper reported that researchers are
``finally getting a grip on optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   A curious picture came to mind, a half dozen or so
serious-looking scientists struggling to subdue a large, bright,
slippery mass. As any pessimist knows, nothing is harder to get a
grip on than optimism. In fact, the whole notion of being able to
grip it at all seems absurd, given its elusive nature.
</P>
<P>
   The story reported that the researchers found optimists do
better than pessimists in every area of life, work, school, and
sports. They achieve more goals, suffer less depression, battle
illness more effectively. They live longer.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't we heard this before? It seems researchers are
constantly discovering that optimists do better than pessimists and
announcing their findings to the media. How many times do they have
to rediscover it?
</P>
<P>
   I come at this subject as a bred-in-the-bone pessimist, born of
people who would no more think of looking on the bright side of
life than they would of telling you to have a nice day. I suspect
optimists don't really live longer. The truth is pessimists live
shorter, for any number of reasons, not the least of which is that
optimists are so damned irritating, wearing us down, telling us to
cheer up, be happy, smile.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Seligman, a University of Pennsylvania psychologist, is
quoted in the story as saying that in the past three decades there
were 46,000 papers on depression in psychology literature and
``just 400'' on joy. Things will be different in the 21st century,
Seligman predicts, when psychology ``will become a science of human
strength and personal fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   Seligman is a respected expert on the subject. As it happens,
I've read his book, ``Learned Optimism: How to Change Your Mind and
Your Life.'' It was published in 1990 to enthusiastic reviews
(``Vaulted me out of my funk. . .'' _ The New York Times) and has
been selling briskly ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Seligman believes that optimism and pessimism are learned
behaviors. He's undoubtedly right, although, looking at my
relations I can't help thinking that at least some of it must be
genetic. In his book, he provides cognitive therapy techniques
designed to turn the pessimist into an optimist. The key lies in
changing what Seligman calls your ``explanatory style,'' how you
view and explain your life experience. He provides a test of 48
scenarios designed to test the reader's level of optimism. Here's
one example:
</P>
<P>
   You win the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   A. It was pure chance.
</P>
<P>
   B. I picked the right numbers.
</P>
<P>
   I chose A, the pessimistic answer. When something good happens
to pessimists they assume it was due to circumstances outside
themselves. Conversely, when something bad happens, it's always
their fault.
</P>
<P>
   Optimists do exactly the opposite. They breeze happily through
life taking credit for everything that goes right and blaming
outside circumstances for anything that goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There's something to be said for optimism, in moderation, but to
choose answer B, ``I picked the right numbers,'' and ignore the
element of chance seems unrealistic, if not insane. But what do I
know? I'm a die-hard pessimist, too far gone to be vaulted out of
my funk by ``learned optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book Seligman concedes that pessimism has one good use:
It helps people perceive reality accurately. He writes that
depressed people, who tend to be pessimists, ``see reality
correctly while non-depressed people distort reality in a
self-serving way. . . . There is considerable evidence that
depressed people, though sadder, are wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   We're wise enough, at least, to know we'll never get a grip on
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist; her e-mail address is
dwhite(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
