<HEADER>
A5044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SKIING-ACCORD-BOS &LR;      01-13 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIING-ACCORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON ISRAELI SLOPES, DIPLOMACY TAKES A BACK SEAT TO THE SCHUSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT HERMON, Golan Heights _ At the peak of this volcanic
mountain blanketed in snow, a blue-white Israeli flag whipped in
the icy wind as a chairlift deposited Israeli skiers onto the
slopes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Hermon Ski Area was overrun this week with skiers and
tobogganers set loose on roughly 3 feet of soft white powder that
had fallen since Sunday in the Golan's first real snowstorm in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The glee of children taking runs on plastic sleds or skiers
cascading down the hills seemed far removed from the bloody battles
for control that took place on this strategic highground in the
Arab-Israeli wars of 1967 and 1973.
</P>
<P>
   It was equally worlds away from the difficult high-level
diplomacy in Shepherdstown, W. Va., where control of Mount Hermon
was a central issue as Syria sought the return of the Golan in
exchange for security guarantees for Israel and an end to the
half-century state of war between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   Every voice on the question _ Israeli hardliners, Peace Now
activists, the ultra-Orthodox and the completely secular, along
with Israeli Arabs and ethnic Druze who claim loyalty to Syria _
could be heard on Mount Hermon this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you see that? That is Syria, and that is Damascus,'' said
an Israeli soldier stationed on the hill, who because of military
regulations could only give his first name, Sefi.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of Mount Hermon the view is of red-tiled roofs of
Israeli ski lodges and settlements; on the other is the gray
skyline of Syria's capital, Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you see how close that is? You can visualize how insane it
would be for us to give this up? The settlements will be sitting
ducks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot, Kamal Hussein, was furiously trying to
direct the traffic jam caused by some 25,000 who descended on the
slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mountain belongs to Syria,'' said Hussein, a member of
the Druze community on the Israeli-held Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is to be peace, it will have to be returned,'' said
Hussein. ``Besides, if this is real peace, the Israelis can still
come skiing here even if the mountain is under Syrian control. Why
not?''
</P>
<P>
   The scene was winter wonderland-Middle East style, full of
bizarre vignettes. Israel soldiers wearing military green winter
suits and carrying machine guns mixed with skiers in silky spandex
snowpants and backpacks with picnic lunches. Atop the hill, a
military early warning station monitored Syrian troop movements
while just below it young children on sleds whipped past an Israeli
troop transport parked nearby. Ultra-Orthodox tourists looked a bit
lost amid the crowds of Israeli Arabs smoking water pipes and
playing traditional drums in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I look like a skier?'' asked Joseph Ausch, 40, a member of
the Satmar stream of ultra-Orthodox Judaism, in the traditional
long beard, side curls, black wool suit, and fedora.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just rented a car to see what the place looked like. We had
no idea all these Arabs would be here,'' said Ausch, who lives in
Munson, N.Y. and was in Israel on business. ``Well, looks like
they're amusing themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Six-Day War in June of 1967, an intense 20-hour
battle resulted in Israel taking the Golan Heights. When the
fighting ended in a ceasefire on June 10, Israel had left
neighboring Egypt, Jordan, and Syria _ which combined had
significantly superior military power _ stunned and defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The victory left Israel in control of the Golan, the West Bank,
and the Sinai Peninsula _ an area three times its pre-1967 borders.
In the 1973 war, Israel repelled a furious assault in the Golan and
ended by recapturing one peak of Mount Hermon and taking another.
</P>
<P>
   The Six-Day War's toll was 700 Israeli lives and 2,500 wounded.
Syria suffered about 1,000 casualties; Egypt 1,500; and Jordan
claims to have lost about 6,000. In 1973, nearly 3,000 Israelis
were killed, several hundred on the Golan alone, while more than
3,000 Syrians were killed in fierce armor and commando battles for
the strategic heights.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to Ausch was his Israeli friend, Steve Weiss, who
added, ``We gave too many lives to get this mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is always giving'' in the peace process, said Weiss. Of
the Syrians and Palestinians, he asked, ``What have they ever
given?''
</P>
<P>
   There is much at stake in the Golan, not only the sacrifice of
lives on both sides, but economic interest as well.
</P>
<P>
   Today 17,000 Israeli settlers live in the Golan, which contains
roughly one-third of Israel's water resources and bountiful
orchards and vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   The ski area itself is an example of the kind of lost business
that would have to be compensated if the Golan goes back to Syria.
Menachem Baruch, the manager, said the 9 lifts and 45 trails were
built in 1969 by a consortium of 32 families from the nearby town
of Newe Ativ. He estimates the business is worth $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything we can to oppose it,'' he said,
referring to Prime Minister Ehud Barak's peace plan. ``In the
meantime, we have to continue to work and invest. You can't do
that, if you think next year you won't be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
