<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MLK16-COX     01-13 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MLK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In search of the true King
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 16.
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, in an interview about her efforts to carry
on her late husband's work, Coretta Scott King told me that it
wouldn't surprise her to one day see a new religion based on the
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s philosophy of nonviolence. In some
ways, the widow's prophecy has come true. A broad spectrum of
people treat King's most famous words as holy Scripture: Few
dispute their truth, but many argue over what they mean. The image
of King preserved in the public mind is more messianic than mortal.
The ``I Have a Dream'' speech is his Sermon on the Mount; the
balcony of Memphis' Lorraine Motel is his Calvary.
</P>
<P>
   And now, just as there have been books promising to portray the
real Jesus, Michael Eric Dyson has written ``I May Not Get There
With You: The True Martin Luther King Jr.'' Dyson, an ordained
Baptist minister, Columbia University professor of African-American
studies and the author of four previous books whose subjects
include Malcolm X and gangsta rap, says his aim is to ``keep Dr.
King alive, the way he really was.''
</P>
<P>
   It's audacious even to state the need for that task, much less
take it on, given that King's life has been written about so
thoroughly, including in two Pulitzer Prize-winning books. What's
more, the opening of Dyson's account may convince some readers that
he's not up to the job. He starts with narrative writing that is,
at best, awkward: ``King's mellifluous baritone had been silenced
by a piece of metal that traveled with ungodly speed and accuracy
to explode its message of death inside his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers who persevere, however, will be rewarded. Dyson moves
from telling a story to arguing his case, and that is where he hits
his stride. He takes on individuals and groups ranging from
affirmative action opponents to right-to-life zealots, indicting
them for appropriating King's words for uses that run counter to
the man's mission in life. The case has been made many places
before. But few, if any, have made it in the cogent, comprehensive
and passionate way Dyson does.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson's criticism isn't limited to conservative usurpers of
King's lectures and likeness, such as anti-affirmative action
activist Ward Connerly of California or Republican Sen. Jesse Helms
of North Carolina. Though he shows compassion for King's widow and
grown children, Dyson rightly questions their stewardship of King's
legacy for its emphasis on protecting the commercial value of his
words and image at the risk of lessening their ability to continue
changing the world.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Dyson can't deliver the ``true'' Martin Luther King
Jr. simply by skewering those who misappropriate King's message. He
fulfills his promise by going much further. The book reminds us of
the King we've forgotten, a man whose career in the public eye
lasted just 13 years but who went through many changes in that
time, including struggles with disillusionment and depression near
the end of a short life filled with incredible accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, Dyson looks critically at King's flaws. He
does not sugarcoat.3 King's plagiarism of college papers and
sermons, nor his treatment of women, from his well-documented
(thanks to the FBI and other sources) philandering to his less
known anti-feminist attitudes toward women in leadership roles.
Dyson's frankness about King's faults enhances his credibility when
he argues that the ledger sheet for the civil rights leader's life
shows an enormous balance in favor of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Like its subject, this book is not perfect. In addition to the
weakness in narrative writing, Dyson takes unnecessarily long side
trips into issues such as the origins of communism and the socially
redeeming value of rap music. Though relevant to his discussion,
those subjects should have been covered in a few paragraphs, not
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The book's virtues outweigh its flaws, much as King's
accomplishments are greater than his personal shortcomings. The
scale here isn't tipped toward greatness, but, on balance, Dyson
has produced a work that will be valuable to those who want to
remember the true Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   I May Not Get There With You: The True Martin Luther King Jr. By
Michael Eric Dyson. Free Press. $24. 240 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Like its subject, flawed but important.
</P>
<P>
   John Head, a staff writer for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
is the author of ``We Were the Land's: The Biography of a
Homeplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
