<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN THE YEAR 2024, THE ELIAN CASE IS STILL ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The following is from a news story of the
future:
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the latest of a long series of maneuvers that began
in December 1999, the family of 28-year-old Elian Gonzales
announced that he has been chosen as the vice presidential running
mate of Republican presidential candidate Tucker Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident that this move will keep Elian in the United
States for at least another two years because the election isn't
even until 2024,'' said Josefina Morales Smith, Elian's great-great
aunt twice-removed. ``And if Elian and Mr. Quayle should win, our
dear, sweet boy can remain here in the land of the free and home of
the brave for at least six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is the son of former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, who is never referred to by his surname because everyone
still thinks of him as ``the little boy who escaped from Cuba,'' is
in his second term as a congressman from his adopted Miami
district.
</P>
<P>
   Once an aide to retired Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., Elian was
encouraged by Burton to join Quayle on the GOP ticket, just as
Burton had encouraged the young Cuban refugee to run for the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since Elian was 6, I have been committed to finding ways
to keep him in the United States,'' said the octogenarian Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time was January 2000 when I subpoenaed the little tyke
to testify before Congress. I bought almost two months with that
ploy _ and that was long enough to get a Miami family court judge
to throw a major wrench into the INS' plan to send the kid back to
his dad in that godforsaken communist hellhole.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, over the years Burton has come up with a variety of
successful schemes to prevent Elian from being sent back to his
native Cuba and reunited with his father, who died in 2014.
</P>
<P>
   With economic and political support from anti-Castro
Cuban-Americans in Miami, the Hoosier congressman managed, among
other things, to spearhead two constitutional amendments, enroll
Elian in Indiana University and, in the boy's senior year, enlist
him in an ROTC program that mandated he serve 18 months in the U.S.
Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a close one, I'll tell you,'' Burton recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down to the wire with Elian needing only three units
to graduate. I was this close to asking the homecoming queen at
I.U. to accuse him of date rape, just so we could buy some more
time with a trial and _ if necessary _ a conviction. Even a U.S.
prison is better than Castro's Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Elian, Tucker Quayle's mother, Marilyn, came up
with the idea of enrolling the refugee in a mandatory-service ROTC
program. University administrators and Air Force brass were only
too happy to waive the customary two-year ROTC college minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in Burton's final congressional term, he had little
trouble persuading both the House and Senate to pass constitutional
amendments that lifted the citizenship requirement for
congressional candidates and the age requirement for presidential
and vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, non-citizen Elian breezed to victory at age 25 in his
maiden run for office and, at age 28, is Quayle's first choice for
veep.
</P>
<P>
   It is also widely believed that Burton was instrumental in
employing a significant non-political maneuver that helped ensure
Elian would not return to Cuba: He introduced the young man to his
soon-to-be wife, Lourdes Maria Ciccone Leon, the only daughter of
former rock singer Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the alleged matchmaking, Burton chuckled and
said only: ``Let's just say there came a time when Disney World and
Big Macs were not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   News of Elian's vice presidential candidacy did not go down well
in Havana, where hundreds of mostly gray-haired students took to
the streets in protest. The 95-year-old Fidel Castro, in
characteristically robust health, decried the ``imperialistic
encroachment'' of the United States in Cuban affairs and vowed that
he ``will not rest'' until Elian is returned to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
