<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS16-COX     01-13 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Searching out the true story of Jesus Christ
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 16.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For two millennia, a single man has been at the center of all
that has become Western civilization _ its expansion across Europe
and into the Americas, its conflicts as much as its conquests, its
moral code and its most deeply held beliefs. The pre-eminence of
Jesus Christ is taken for granted, even apart from the reverence of
the faithful. In writing of Abraham Lincoln, for example, it is
customary to note that only Christ has been the subject of more
books, more scholarship, more study.
</P>
<P>
   None of those books is so widely read or so frequently quoted as
the Bible, the latter part of which deals with the life and work of
Jesus. The irony is that so little should be known about either the
life or the man. As the biblical scholar Paula Fredriksen writes in
``Jesus of Nazareth, King of the Jews: A Jewish Life and the
Emergence of Christianity,'' ``The single most solid fact about
Jesus' life is his death: he was executed by the Roman prefect
Pilate, on or around Passover, in the manner Rome reserved
particularly for political insurrectionists, namely, crucifixion.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that we have ... what? The easy certitude of Sunday
pulpiteers, the ready reference to Scripture and its inerrant
authority, the vague heritage of tradition. And so we speak with
assurance of ``what Jesus meant,'' when there is precious little we
know about the man _ when, in fact, his own followers seem not to
have been sure what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   A part of Fredriksen's thesis is that the Gospels cannot easily
be gospel when they tell conflicting stories, both in chronological
detail and narrative emphasis. Most Christians would settle on
Jesus as Redeemer, Lord, Messiah and Son of God _ a transcendent
figure, in other words. But any or all of these come at no cost;
faith may be hard-won, but it is free for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing the historical Jesus imposes greater demands.
Pressed to be more specific (and lacking evidence), lay Christians
are apt to see the Jesus they want to see: prophet and teacher,
healer and exorcist, herald of apocalypse, religious martyr, even
political insurrectionist. There is a Jesus for every Christian,
and fragments of proof (chapter and verse, as we say) are drawn
from a Bible whose most obvious feature is not consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Delving into a detective story
</P>
<P>
   Fredriksen is painstakingly clear in all of this. Professor of
Scripture at Boston University and the author of ``From Jesus to
Christ: The Origins of New Testament Images of Jesus,'' she wants
to answer a question she thinks central to the genesis of
Christianity: Why was Jesus killed? And why, if Jesus was a threat
to the priests of the temple or even the Roman authorities, were
his followers not also executed?
</P>
<P>
   Fredriksen's search for an answer is almost a detective story,
as labyrinthine as the catacombs themselves but refreshingly
independent of dogma and cant. ``Though the word is unfashionable
in academic history right now,'' she says, ``I shall breathe it
anyway, here: We have facts. Facts about Jesus, and facts about the
movement that formed after his crucifixion. Facts are always
subject to interpretation _ that's part of the fun _ but they also
exist as fixed points in our investigation. Any explanation, any
reconstruction of Jesus' mission and message must speak adequately
to what we know to have been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   It would rob the reader of some of that fun (and do Fredriksen
an injustice) by blurting out an answer, especially one that is
neither simple nor easily arrived at. But a hint will do: Read the
Gospel of John again. Read it carefully. Note how it conflicts with
the Gospel of Mark, which, as Fredriksen shows, was almost
certainly the basis for the Gospels of Matthew and Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Connection between religion, politics
</P>
<P>
   In the life and death of Jesus, religion and politics were
inevitably intertwined. ``Pilate,'' Fredriksen writes, ``would have
known little and cared less about Jewish religious beliefs and
intra-Jewish religious controversy.'' But he understood crowd
control, and the necessity of dispersing dissent. The last time
Jesus came to Jerusalem, crowds were hostile. Pilate's concern was
not that of the priests of the temple. Theirs was religious, his
civil. The two could find common ground in a common nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Pilate knew who Jesus was, but had no reason to care about his
disciples. ``This datum alone, from all other traditions the
Gospels offer,'' Fredriksen writes, ``can explain the core
historical anomaly of the Passion stories: Jesus was crucified, but
his followers were not.''
</P>
<P>
   What is lost to time and forgetfulness is that Jesus never
called himself a Christian, for the simple reason that his mission
and message did not extend beyond his own subjugated people. He
preached in the prophetic tradition, and might have been included
among the true prophets of Israel had not St. Paul and others taken
liberties with his word. It is a delicate point, but only in
retrospect. ``As it was,'' the historian Herbert J. Muller wrote in
the '50s, ``Jesus was crucified as the King of the Jews; on the
cross he appealed to the God of the Jews. He died, as he had lived,
a devout Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus of Nazareth, King of the Jews: A Jewish Life and the
Emergence of Christianity. By Paula Fredriksen. Knopf. $26.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
