<HEADER>
A5049 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BANDITS14-COX     01-13 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BANDITS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    German `Bandits' take to the road on the run in jailbreak tour
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it pushes too often into fantasy and works itself into a
corner that can be solved only by a not-great ending, ``Bandits''
is a peppery, amusing variant of ``Thelma &AMP; Louise,'' retooled as
an MTV video.
</P>
<P>
   German director Katja von Garnier, working from an idea she
hatched with Atlanta writer-director Ben Taylor (``In the Flesh''),
gives us a tale of four tough women prisoners who form a band
behind bars. Making an unexpected jailbreak, they drive across
Germany hoping to make it to a ship that will carry them to South
America. Staging impromptu concerts at nightclubs, signing
autographs for star-struck fans and taking the cutest boy in the
bar (Werner Schreyer) hostage when police close in, the gals become
folk heroes, with a hit record and money in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The fun times start to slip away, though, when both the sullen
Luna (Jasmin Tabatabai) and delicate Angel (Nicolette Krebitz) fall
for the same guy. Meanwhile, a determined detective (Hannes
Jaenicke) is hot on their trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bandits'' is a cheerfully implausible adventure that you don't
believe for a minute. But, like some of the fair-to-decent songs
the stars sing, it has a good beat. It's jokey and lightweight, and
everything that German cinema is stereotypically not supposed to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bandits''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Katja Riemann, Jasmin Tabatabai and Nicolette Krebitz.
Rated R for profanity, sexuality and drug use. In German, with
subtitles. Through Thursday at Cinefest (Georgia State University).
$3, $5 after 6 p.m. 404-651-2463. 1 hour, 49 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A gender-bent prison-break rock 'n' roll fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
