   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science &LR; 
stories for papers of Friday, Jan. 14:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-MINORITIES (Undated) _ For the first time, the
proportion of AIDS cases among black and Hispanic gay men exceeds
those among white gay men, federal health officials reported
Thursday. One quarter of the black men who said they got infected
from sex with other men do not identify themselves as homosexual or
bisexual, which often means they do not consider themselves, other
sexual partners or their children at risk, the CDC research found.
By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLD-BLACKHOLES (Undated) _ New x-ray observations of deep
space have found what appear to be black holes that predate the
formation of galaxies. By John Noble Wilford. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRIMATE-EMBRYOS (Undated) _ Scientists in Oregon have
divided an eight cell monkey embryo into quarters, creating
identical quadruplet embryos. One of them survived and resulted in
the birth of a baby monkey. But the results do did not achieve
nearly the success that was accomplished with other animals. By
Gina Kolata.
</P>
