<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond _ The fourth annual Winter Wine Festival Friday and
Saturday is the only indoor wine fest in the state. Featuring wines
from 17 Virginia wineries, wine tastings, cooking demonstrations,
dinners and auctions. 804-746-1007.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ The 10th annual Wilderness Wildlife Week
in Pigeon Forge, Tenn., continues through Sunday with nearly 100
nature experts conducting hikes, walks, multimedia presentations,
exhibits and seminars in and around the Great Smoky Mountains. All
activities are free and open to all. 1-800-946-8373.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biloxi, Miss. _ The Professional Cowboy Association's
Championship Finals are Thursday through Sunday at the Mississippi
Coast Coliseum. The family-oriented event includes special
appearances by ``Buffalo Bill,'' rodeo clown ``Punkin''-Town Smith,
a horse-driven stagecoach and chuck wagon racing. Two hours before
each performance, children 10 and under enjoy free pony rides and
searching through a haystack for money and prizes. 1-800-280-0785.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Silver Springs, Fla. _ The sixth annual Ford &AMP; Mustang Roundup
Saturday and Sunday is one of the largest gatherings of Fords in
the Southeast. Guests will view nearly 600 vehicles ranging from
Model Ts and Edsels to Shelby Cobras and every model of Mustang
dating to 1964 1/2. 1-800-234-7458.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tiptonville, Tenn. _ Reelfoot Lake State Park's Eagle Watch,
through March 12, includes guided tours of Reelfoot Lake State Park
to view the largest wintering population of bald eagles in the
eastern United States and migrating waterfowl. 901-253-7756; www.
eaglewatch.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Charles, La. _ Mardi Gras of Imperial Calcasieu, through
March 7, includes a parade, costumers, screams of ``Throw me
something, mister!''; also, gumbo cook-off, Cajun dancing.
1-800-456-7952.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guntersville, Ala. _ Eagle Awareness Weekends continue
Friday-Sunday and Jan. 21-23, 28-30. View wintering bald eagles at
Lake Guntersville and Joe Wheeler state parks; presentations on
birds of prey. 256-571-5444.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga. _ The exhibition ``Food and Ritual in the
Southern Experience'' continues through February at the Thomasville
Cultural Center. Macon artist Betty Bivins Edwards uses fabric,
crochet, beads, crystals and acetate to create highly detailed, 3-D
narrative quilts. Each quilt satirically describes a Southern
social event. 912-226-0588.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbia, S.C. _ South Carolina State Museum presents ``T. Rex
on Trial: Evidence of Meat-Eating Dinosaurs'' through May 7. The
exhibition presents evidence that the mighty ``King of the
Dinosaurs'' may have been less a fearsome predator than a cunning
scavenger. The star of the show is a 15-foot-tall robotic
Tyrannosaurus rex manufactured in Japan by Kokoro Co. Ltd.
803-898-4921.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Newport News, Va. _ The exhibition ``It's About Time,''
through March 12 at the Mariners' Museum, examines how our ability
to measure time, distance and our place on Earth has evolved over
the centuries. 1-800-581-7245.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ The Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts presents
``Sybil Gibson: Alabama Self-Taught Artist (1908-1995),'' an
exhibition of 16 watercolor paintings, Saturday through March 5.
The retired schoolteacher and native of Dora, Ala., began painting
at age 55. 334-244-5700.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
