<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-FRIDAY14-COX     01-13 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FRIDAY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Friday' enough to make you wish for Monday
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sorry, folks, but it looks like the end-of-the-year season of
prestige films is officially winding down. Now it's back to the
usual garbage. Example A: ``Next Friday,'' from producer,
co-scripter and star Ice Cube. It's not opening next Friday, but
today.
</P>
<P>
   The best that can be said for this sequel to the 1995 comedy
``Friday'' is that, unlike the first flick, the characters don't
spend most of the movie sitting on the front steps and yakking
while they get stoned. No, they go to other interesting locations
to get stoned. Like a record shop. And a suburban house. That's
where Craig (Cube) goes to stay with his lottery-winning uncle when
the thug he trashed in the first movie, Debo (Tommy ``Tiny'' Lister
Jr.) breaks out of jail and comes looking for him.
</P>
<P>
   This change of scenery doesn't do much to alter the movie's
tired vision of all its women characters as psychopaths or sluts.
Craig's uncle's wife (Kym E. Whitley) is always trying to stick her
tongue in his ear, while his cousin Day-Day (one-time Atlantan Mike
Epps) is on the run from two ex-girlfriends who stalk him with
pepper spray and vandalize his car.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception to cartoonish portrayal is Karla (Lisa
Rodriguez), but she fits another movie stereotype. She's the
standard-issue good girl with voluptuous curves who inexplicably
falls hard when she gets an eyeful of the single, sullen facial
expression Cube uses from first frame to last. In a fantasy scene,
Karla writhes seductively for him, standing on a coffee table. One
assumes that is an auteuristic reference to the star's directorial
work on the gritty and powerful expose of the world of exotic
dancers, ``The Players Club.'' Yeah, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Karla lives next door to Craig's uncle with her three
drug-dealing brothers, led by the tough little tattooed one named
Joker (Jacob Vargas). The guys give the movie an excuse to revel in
cliched jokes about Latino machismo. They also raise the T&AMP;A
quotient by holding a party and inviting three beauties, who each
wear about three square inches of clothing. Oh, the Joker Bros.
also have some high-powered firearms, so a lot of things get shot
up for fun at the film's climax. Did I mention their fierce little
pit bull, who turns out to enjoy getting stoned, too?
</P>
<P>
   Too lamely written to ever be really offensive, ``Next Friday''
is a reminder that, while more complex, mature but still funny
African-American comedies are getting made (``The Wood,'' say, and
``The Best Man''), there's always a market for flatulence and dog
poop jokes. Hey, nothing wrong with that. But the flick could use
Chris Tucker, co-star of the first ``Friday,'' AWOL in the sequel.
He probably took a look at the script and realized this sequel was
no reason to shout, ``T.G.I.F.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Friday''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ice Cube and Mike Epps. Rated R for strong language,
drug use and sexual content. 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's back to business as usual at the movies, with
the return of this typical dumb comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
