<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PERIOD-ROOMS (New York) _ Period rooms. Loosely defined, we all
live in them, don't we? Any one of our current abodes might be a
period room of tomorrow, a specimen of the as yet uncrystallized
turn-of-the-21st-century period style. But of course, loose is not
what's under discussion here. For an authentic period room you have
to leave your own fledgling interior and visit a major museum; in
New York this means going to the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the
Brooklyn Museum of Art. With roughly 80 period rooms between them,
they represent the greatest concentration to be found in any
American city. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORK-LIGHT (New York) _ Two years ago, Joe, the man I lived
with, suggested that we outfit our apartment with a light
especially created to combat the winter blues. Seasonal affective
disorder is its quaint moniker. I vetoed the proposal. What I
wanted was not to sit under 10,000 lux of white light to trick my
brain into believing it was spring. I wanted us to soak up the real
stuff, the unadorned light of the New York Harbor at sunset, say,
or the slow illumination of the city on a Sunday morning. Joe isn't
here anymore. He went hiking up a mountain one day last summer. It
is believed that he slipped and fell in the woods. Bloodhounds and
rescue teams were sent for him. But the forest is so dark and
dense, his body is yet to be found. This winter, with unusual
deliberation, I have taken to soaking up the light alone, or mostly
alone. I troll for outings that promise birds and sunsets on
Jamaica Bay in Queens. I bundle up for lunchtime sprints around
Bryant Park in Manhattan to watch how the windows of the library
spit out the sun's reflection. Unwittingly I have turned into a
student of light. The August light that envelopes the beaten-down
old streets of Red Hook, I have learned, is more melancholy than
the morning light during lilac season in the Brooklyn Botanic
Garden. The sun sparkling on the crown of the Chrysler building is
whimsical, like a woman dressed for a party at high noon. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-NEW-YORK (New York) _ The minimum requirement for Le
Weekend New Yorkais was about as basic as a crusty baguette. My
French husband and I yearned for a Manhattan with a Gallic accent _
a bistro perhaps where a petit caniche begs for sugar cubes below a
polished bar, or a brasserie where the mood is casual, the air is
more smoke than oxygen and the frites are served with mustard and
the songs of Serge Gainsbourg. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Wrong Mountain,'' at the
O'Neill Theater. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
