<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Jan. 14:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Argun, Russia) _ Russians struggle to reassert
control in a city they held, then lost to rebels and have now
recaptured. The Russian commander was killed by rebels. By Michael
R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA (Jerusalem) _ In a draft Israel-Syria peace plan
that stakes out initial positions, Israel wants to keep settlers on
Golan Heights. Also, visiting U.S. senators talks with Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-AFRICA (United Nations) _ The Security Council is to
discuss problems of refugees in Africa. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   HARRODS-PHILIP (London) _ Buckingham Palace announced that it
was withdrawing one of its Royal Warrants from Harrods, which held
it for 40 years. The store must remove Prince Philip's crest from
the front of the store, stationery and other products by the end of
the year. A palace spokesman sought to quash rumors that the move
was due to irritation at the claims of Harrods' owner, Mohammed
al-Fayed, that Prince Philip was behind the death of Diana, the
Princess of Wales and his son Dodi. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-BOY-SENTENCE (Pontiac, Mich.) _ A family court judge
Thursday sentenced 13-year-old convicted murderer Nathaniel Abraham
to a juvenile center until he is 21, a more lenient sentence than
prosecutors had wanted. Abraham was one of the youngest murder
defendants in the United States when he was convicted Nov. 16 of
shooting a stranger in the head with a rifle outside of a
convenience store. (Summary from wires) By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez situation
By Peter T. Kilbron.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-OUTLOOK (Perry, Iowa) _ Over the years, the Iowa caucuses
have made some presidential candidates (like Jimmy Carter) and
unmade others (like Edward M. Kennedy). But this time, they have
seemed like a sideshow, and a poorly attended one at that, to the
main event in New Hampshire. That may be changing. With only 10
days left until Feb. 24, when tens of thousands of Iowans will
assemble in living rooms, clubs and school halls to declare their
preferences, two well-funded, well-organized underdogs, Bill
Bradley and Steve Forbes, have accelerated their efforts. If not to
defeat their respective rivals, Al Gore and George W. Bush, they
hope to come very close _- close enough to give them a lift as they
move to New Hampshire, whose critical primary takes place only
eight days later on Feb. 1. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FATHER (Atlantic, Iowa) _ For the first time in the
campaign, former President Bush stumps for his son. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-NH (Manchester, N.H.) _ John McCain speaks before the New
Hampshire legislature. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-MERGER (Undated) _ Warner-Lambert calls off its merger
with American Home Products and enters into talks with Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB-USTRUST (New York) _ Charles Schwab agrees to acquire
U.S. Trust, a large money management company, for $2.7 billion. By
Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-WARNER (Undated) _ Daily developments in the
prospective merger.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   UAL-WARNING (Undated) _ United Airlines warns that earnings will
be below forecasts in 2000 because of rising fuel and labor costs.
Shares tumble 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-TELECOMS (Madrid, Spain) _ Telefonica of Spain plans to
spend about $21.7 billion in stock for full control of phone units
in South America, to create the world's sixth-biggest wireless
company. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Intel reports 4th quarter
earnings after the stock market closes. 63 cents is the consensus
forecast; 65 cents is the whisper. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-INVEST (Undated) _ For almost a year, Internet
companies have gotten a sweet ride from investors, public and
private, willing to accept enormous losses on the promise of great
future returns. But there were some signs last week that the
climate of unlimited forgiveness may be changing and that dot.coms
_ particularly those that cater to consumers _ are suddenly feeling
pressure to account much better for how they spend dollars. By
Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were higher at mid-afternoon; the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 60 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 14 points
and the Nasdaq composite index up 51 points. The long bond was
priced to yield 6.65 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Looking at the state of the Brazilian
economy and its currency as the year anniversary of the decision to
devalue the real approaches. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins'
``Public Interests.''
</P>
