A5118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MEDIA-FUTURE-$ADV16-C     01-13 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FUTURE-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: MEDIA CONVERGENCE: IS IT THE NEXT GREAT THING?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Jan. 16.
 &HT;    Eds: This article stands for the weekly GLASS-COLUMN.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You pick up the phone, and instead of a dial tone
you hear a friendly female voice purr: ``How may I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than punching the keypad, you say: ``Let me talk to my
wife.'' Or you might ask for some stock quotes or a ball score. At
your request, the service could even brief you on the top news
stories of the day, reporting first and at more length on topics it
knows interest you most.
</P>
<P>
   In such ways, VoiceTone, a technology now being tested by AT&AMP;T
Labs, could transform your familiar phone into a versatile
information appliance. In some parts of Europe and the Far East,
similar services are already available through wireless phones and
tiny screens linked at high transmission speeds to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming decade, AT&AMP;T executives foresee the integration of
wired and wireless telephones, television sets, personal computers
and the Internet into one seamless content-driven entity.
Facilitating such convergence is the fact that AT&AMP;T has recently
transformed itself into the nation's largest cable system.
</P>
<P>
   Similar ``unitary information pipe'' thinking prevails at AOL
Time Warner, the huge media combine pieced together last week. Time
Warner ranks as No. 2 in the cable business, while AOL leads the
U.S. market in providing Internet access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This overused word of convergence is, in fact, about to
happen,'' Gerald Levin, now Time Warner's chairman and chief
executive officer, said in a post-merger interview.
</P>
<P>
   When Levin's new partner, AOL's Steve Case, was asked whether
all that coming convergence was necessarily a good thing, he
replied: ``Oh, it's a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Case added: ``Consumers love the fact they (will) have new ways
to get information, new ways to communicate, new ways to buy
products, new ways to learn things, new ways to be entertained. ...
They're empowered to do what they want, when they want, the way
they want.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will happen when 21st century media takes over? Does the
advent of interactive AOL-TV, which would let viewers communicate
over the Internet even as they watch their favorite shows, signal
the fall of plain old television as we've known it for the last 50
years? And what about newspapers, magazines and books?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see some deaths,'' predicts Kurt Andersen, the
founder of Spy magazine and editor of New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Andersen observes, television didn't put an
end to radio, although it eclipsed it in many ways. While someday
we're likely to see ``peaceful coexistence,'' until that day
arrives, ``a lot of limbs (will) die on the media tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting the Internet on TV and TV on the Internet doesn't mean
that the traditional broadcast networks will soon vanish or that
most people will prefer to watch shows on their digital computer
monitors, even though it will easy to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But with Internet traffic doubling roughly every six to nine
months, such giant media concerns as AT&AMP;T and AOL Time Warner,
among others, will press to make faster advanced gear more readily
available. Widespread broadband access, in turn, promises to
radically alter the way many users now relate to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our kids will think about things like communications
very differently than we do,'' says Steve Perlman, the co-founder
of Web-TV, currently owned by Microsoft, the software giant that
both competes with and does lots of business with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Concludes Perlman: ``They're going to look at a telephone as a
strange thing where you had to remember a number to reach somebody.
What a dumb way to communicate. It's much better to communicate in
some IP (Internet protocol) way, whether it's voice or video.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as the AT&AMP;T lady might put: ``How may I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
