<HEADER>
A5124 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-ROTH-HNS &LR;      01-13 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIM ROTH TURNS TO DIRECTING IN `THE WAR ZONE' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LOUIS B. PARKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first call to Tim Roth about his movie ``The War Zone''
didn't work out. Bad timing.
</P>
<P>
   Roth was at a Pasadena, Calif., playground with two of his sons,
trying to hook the youngest into a child's swing. Juggling the cell
phone on his shoulder made it tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on one more second; we're having swing issues here,''
Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   In the background there was child-sized laughter. Daddy doing an
interview wasn't the kids' problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is sick, and so I ran from school down to have a
picnic, and (the interview) completely slipped my mind,'' Roth
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Should we try again later? ``That'd be great,'' he said. ``One
of them will be napping.''
</P>
<P>
   As an actor, Roth has a busy career playing offbeat supporting
roles, mostly gritty low-lifes with an attitude. He's a favorite of
filmmaker Quentin Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pulp Fiction,'' Roth was the petty thief Pumpkin. With his
girlfriend, Honey Bunny, he tried to rob a diner, only to run into
gun totting Samuel L. Jackson and John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rob Roy,'' Roth was a wicked, foppish villain who raped the
character played by Jessica Lange. He was so memorably evil he got
an Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He was more sympathetic in last year's ``The Legend of 1900,''
starring as a pianist who lived his whole life on an ocean liner.
</P>
<P>
   But Roth sometimes gets weary of acting, and he started looking
for a film to direct. That led to ``The War Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may lead to a new career, because ``The War Zone,''
opening Friday, is a devastating film experience, not soon to be
forgotten. It is a serious, sober and unflinching view of incest
and sexual child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It was not what Roth expected to be shooting, but when he read
the novel he quickly accepted the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that couldn't be denied,'' Roth said. ``I've
been around victims all my life. It's a subject I know. I was glad
that it came to me rather than somebody who didn't know the
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said he has been close to several victims of sexual abuse
and that he believes it is far more common than most people know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have the people we've caught, or the people who have
spoken about their abuse,'' Roth said. ``Mostly it's not going to
get reported.
</P>
<P>
   My opinion, and it's purely my opinion, is that it's highly
epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Alexander Stuart, who also did the
screenplay, ``The War Zone'' is about a seemingly normal English
family.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which is not rated, is especially troubling due to
the realistic, objective approach Roth takes to the material. He
keeps the camera still most of the time _ rather than cutting
frequently to different angles and faces _ drawing us into the
family life with its everyday chit-chat and, later, uncomfortable
silences.
</P>
<P>
   The film is anything but glamorous or titillating: the one
scene, late in the movie, in which the audience sees incestuous
sex, is shot from a distance and fairly dark. But it is still
brutal to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Because Roth takes a long time developing his characters into
real, seemingly likable people, it seems as if we are exposed to
much more.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers have walked out of screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been accused of being exploitive,'' Roth said. ``Merely
out for titillation, uh, what else? Pornographic, abusive ... I
really don't know (why). If someone sees it as an abusive film, I
kind of worry about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show this is what it feels like. This is what they
do, and this is how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth believes the movie can be informative to young people, but
he says parents should definitely see the movie before they decide
whether to allow children to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told my oldest son he can't see it. He's 15. This would
be one of his first sexual experiences. I don't want that to be the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the movie even more disturbing is how nice everyone is,
even the father _ the abuser of the film's family. It was a hard
role for actor Ray Winstone. He almost left the project midshoot
because he couldn't handle the sexual scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very scared,'' Roth said. ``But we created a tight
family around him, and he got through it. There were times I
thought we were going to lose him _ or I was going to lose some of
the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful. (The first part of the movie) created a tight
family, and they didn't want to see their family destroyed in this
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about Ray, he didn't understand what this
character was about _ how can we? _ he was just going on his
instincts that it was something that should be told.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day came when he had to be (this side of) this man, which
we had kind of separated from the man he was playing in the rest of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very tough day for him. But Lara (Belmont, who plays
his daughter) got him through it. And we all got him through it.
And they all got us through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth did a long search for the right young people to play the
children of the family, an 18-year-old girl and a 15-year-old boy.
He finally selected two nonactors, Belmont and Freddie Cunliffe,
because he didn't want viewers to think of them as stars of some TV
show. And he wanted their acting to be raw, not slick.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are young and have been trained in some kind of
manner are bringing with them a lot of (junk) that's been taught to
them,'' he said, adding, ``If I taught Lara and Freddie (junk),
it's the kind of (junk) I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said he cleared the script with the young actors' parents,
got them agents and kept counselors on the set.
</P>
<P>
   Roth has been pleased with most of the early response to ``The
War Zone,'' especially with people who talk to him afterward about
their own experiences with abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spoken to people who have never spoken about it before
who have started talking because of having seen the film,'' Roth
said. ``That's been a wonderful experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
