<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WNBA CHAMPION COMETS: TRIUMPH OVER TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE WESTBROOK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `HEARTS OF CHAMPIONS'
</P>
<P>
   For the Houston Comets, 1999 was a wrenching ordeal capped by an
incredible triumph. This video _ whose complete title is ``Hearts
of Champions: The Official WNBA Championship Video'' _ ably
captures how a dedicated team overcame adversity and responded with
heroism.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the setbacks, of course, was the illness of Kim
Perrot, the team's fiery emotional leader who succumbed to cancer
just days before the playoffs began.
</P>
<P>
   But her impact remained, as perhaps it always will.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is everywhere. Take the night that Comets star Cynthia
Cooper learned her close friend was nearing the end. Cooper took
the court and scored 42 points.
</P>
<P>
   As the narration puts it, ``Though their hearts were broken,
their spirits were not.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 47-minute video traces the story with overly
familiar clips and sound bites as the Comets march to their third
consecutive crown.
</P>
<P>
   But it also offers rare glimpses behind the scenes. Most
intriguing are moments when Sheryl Swoopes is heard intensely going
over strategy with her teammates during pauses in the action.
</P>
<P>
   Regular-season highlights are minimal; most of the focus is on
the playoffs _ in carefully edited form.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a product of NBA Entertainment, which wants
to project the best image possible.
</P>
<P>
   Due to that, the video ignores how heated the Comets'
first-round battle with the Los Angeles Sparks became, with
ejections and L.A.'s Lisa Leslie jabbing at the Comets' Tina
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the finals against the New York Liberty were marked
by opponents embracing each other in support and unity.
</P>
<P>
   With superb camera angles _ including a vantage directly above
the basket _ highlights include Teresa Weatherspoon's remarkable
half-court shot to steal a win at the end of Game 2. That's
followed by the Comets' determined title-clinching performance and
a moving celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The tape ends with a sassy music video by the Houston group
Destiny's Child for ``Jumpin' Jumpin','' followed by a memorial
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   A photo of Perrot is shown with her name and the years of her
life. She may not have played for the Comets in 1999, but she was
as much a part of that season as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, not rated, USA Home Entertainment, VHS $19.95, no DVD
</P>
<P>
   `LAKE PLACID'
</P>
<P>
   This spry horror comedy rises above convention with sharp
dialogue and lively, earnest performances.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from ``Jaws,'' the script is by TV wonder boy David E.
Kelley, who sets a massive crocodile to chomping on cattle and
humans in a lovely Maine lake.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Fonda plays the fish out of water _ a paleontologist
from New York _ with Bill Pullman as the nice-guy game warden who
catches her eye.
</P>
<P>
   But Oliver Platt owns the film as an obsessive inheritance-brat
who stalks crocs with near-spiritual zeal. Sparking much crisp
verbal sparring, he makes this monster mash sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake Placid'' ripples with other fun flourishes, from Betty
White as a grumpy granny who treats crocs as pets to a surprising
forest dance party to the tune of Tom Jones' ``It's Not Unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Grisly scenes are quick, brief and amusingly appalling, in the
vein of ``Mars Attacks.'' The 30-foot croc is a marvel of
computer-generated trickery, wisely hidden for most of the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, half of this film amounts to little more than
half an hour. ``Lake Placid'' runs 78 minutes without end credits.
</P>
<P>
   As they say, leave 'em laughing, and this fine little monster
movie does just that.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Fox, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   `MYSTERY MEN'
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to ``Lake Placid,'' ``Mystery Men'' doesn't leave us
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Its sweet but thin premise is stretched over a story that runs
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Macy, Ben Stiller, Hank Azaria and Janeane Garofalo
are among superhero wannabes in a fantasy city where Capt. Amazing
(Greg Kinnear) is top dog _ and dog is the word.
</P>
<P>
   As the vain, money-grabbing, image-obsessed hero, Kinnear is a
hoot. But his underdog rivals with no superpowers _ ``Blue Raja''
Azaria hurls forks, while ``Shoveler'' Macy wields shovels _ aren't
so much lovable losers as they are pathetic nerds given to empty
theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Rush plays Casanova Frankenstein, a villain whose
character and powers are as murky as his German accent.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, ``Mystery Men'' plays as a parody of the ``Batman''
films. One problem: The last two ``Batman'' films already were
parodies. Again, the Shoveler and company suffer from upstaging.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   `DETROIT ROCK CITY'
</P>
<P>
   Released three weeks ago on DVD, this '70s time trip now comes
to tape.
</P>
<P>
   Considering its quality, VHS consumers shouldn't mind the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Rifkin is a promising young director. (He helmed the ``The
Chase'' as well as the agreeably twisted ``Psycho Cop Returns.'')
But the adventures of four randy, rowdy teens as they go to a Kiss
concert in 1978 plays like a poor man's ``Dazed and Confused,''
saddled with preposterous plotting and incessant belligerence, with
severe beatings played as comedy. Avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 star.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, New Line, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO RATINGS 4 stars _ Excellent 3 stars _ Good 2 stars _ Fair
1 star _Poor
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
