<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DNA-COMPUTER-HNS &LR;      01-13 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-COMPUTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS SEE DNA AS PATH TO GREATER COMPUTING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists are creating microscoping chemical
``computers'' from DNA that they hope can solve unusually
frustrating types of mathematical problems.
</P>
<P>
   The research is difficult, partly because it involves a
radically new way of storing computer data in the four-letter
chemical code of DNA, rather than in the ``binary'' code of 0s and
1s used in present-day computers' magnetic memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gram of DNA might hold up to one quintillion bytes of data.
It's vastly more compact than our most compact conventional media
on computers,'' said John Reif, director of the Consortium of
Biomolecular Computing at Duke University in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   With funds from the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency
and National Science Foundation, Reif's center is backing research
on DNA computing at numerous institutions from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are trying to solve elementary mathematical problems
using millions of DNA molecules, which are either floating in test
tubes or scattered on a small gold chip like blades of grass on a
freshly cut lawn. The latest developments in the field are reported
in Thursday's issue of Nature, the British science journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A computer in which the (DNA) strands are attached to the
surface of a chip can now solve difficult problems quite quickly,''
researchers Mitsunori Ogihara and Animesh Ray write in an
editorial, ``DNA Computing on a Chip,'' which appears in the same
issue. They were not connected with the actual research finding.
</P>
<P>
   DNA stands for deoxyribonucleic acid, which is the chemical
basis of the genes that transmit hereditary traits. DNA are the
coiled molecules that decide whether a living organism becomes a
person or a petunia, a possum or a peanut.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, DNA computers would be what computer jockeys call
``massively parallel'' _ the equivalent of millions or billions of
micro-size computers working simultaneously on different aspects of
the same problem. Although much slower than ordinary
metal-and-silicon computers, such computers could prove ideal for
tackling the kinds of problems that are notorious for gobbling
large amounts of computer power.
</P>
<P>
   An example is what is known as a traveling salesman problem, in
which a company must pick a salesman's optimum route through
numerous cities _ that is, the cheapest, fastest route that
requires the least duplication of effort. There are more up-to-date
applications, such as an airline trying to select ideal routes for
stopover flights between airports.
</P>
<P>
   But even leading experts caution that the future of DNA
computing is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually don't think it would have any market unless it is
clearly superior to (alternative computer systems). ... This is a
field in its infancy,'' said Lloyd M. Smith, a chemistry professor
at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and the co-author of the
research paper in Nature. For now, at least, ``this is actually one
of the least practical projects I work on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The article by Qinghua Liu, Smith and four other scientists
points out that the field of DNA computing was invented in 1994 by
Leonard Adleman of the University of Southern California. Using DNA
in test tubes that encoded mathematical information on their
molecular structures, Adleman solved a so-called ``Hamiltonian
Path'' math problem ``determining an airline flight path between
several cities where each city would only be visited once,'' Liu
and his colleagues write.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Liu's team reports using DNA to solve what the
editorial commentators, Ogihara and Ray, describe as ``a
particularly difficult problem in mathematical logic.'' Their
solution ``represents a remarkable improvement over the best
conventional computer algorithm,'' Ogihara and Ray write.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is ``still unrealistic'' for the Liu team to hope to
use DNA computing to solve far grander problems, Ogihara and Ray
said. ``The authors claim that their ... approach is designed to
scale up to problems of practical significance, but solving a
problem that would embarrass a conventional computer is a long way
off.''
</P>
<P>
   History justifies such caution. DNA computing is a recent entry
in an old horse race: the effort to develop computer systems based
on fundamentally different physical principles from those of
today's computers. Some schemes have fallen flat: a plan for
``hydraulic'' computers, described in Scientific American three
decades ago, that would have worked by using fluids pumped through
pipes rather than electrons moving through wires and microchips.
</P>
<P>
   But others remain hot topics. These include efforts to develop
``quantum'' computers that deploy codes based on the eerie physical
phenomena of the subatomic world, and ``nanotechnological''
computers with electronic ``switches'' and ``gates'' as tiny as
atoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
