<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOTELIERS GET LITTLE REST ON SLEEP ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ I did a double-take upon reading the promotion from
Westin Hotels &AMP; Resorts: ``To purchase your hotel room pillow,
visit the front desk or call the Heavenly Hotline.''
</P>
<P>
   Was this a joke? I don't know about you, but last time I spent a
night on the road I had to summon housekeeping twice and stack four
flimsy pillows just to lift my head higher than my feet.
</P>
<P>
   Wait! There's more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purchase your hotel bed. Twin sets $1,300. Kings $1,900.''
</P>
<P>
   I've spent countless nights in hotels and long ago established
three criteria for an acceptable bed: (1) I only slide off the side
once or twice. (2) My toes barely wiggle beyond the foot of the bed
(I'm 5-foot-7; how does professional basketball player Hakeem
Olajuwon manage?). (3) I wake up with my back intact.
</P>
<P>
   I've certainly never felt an urge to take a hotel bed home. But
maybe I've been sleeping in the past.
</P>
<P>
   PREFERRED OVER SEX
</P>
<P>
   Hoteliers spent much of the '90s figuring out how to keep us
happy all day _ creating spas and health clubs; diversifying
restaurants and shops; incorporating state-of-the-art entertainment
systems into guest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a new century begins, the focus is on putting us to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because we've asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Westin-sponsored survey of 600 frequent travelers,
more than twice as many respondents said they would prefer a great
night's sleep over great sex.
</P>
<P>
   As if that message isn't strong enough: _ Respondents said they
get 51 percent less sleep on the road than at home and are 31
percent more likely to wake up in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   _ On average, 24 minutes is required to fall asleep compared
with 15 minutes at home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirty-one percent said their performance on the road has
suffered because of a bad night's sleep in a hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: 63 percent said that a good night's sleep is the
most important service a hotel can provide.
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN THE SHEETS
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the bed isn't the only factor involved. As early as
1994, Hilton Hotels, in cooperation with the National Sleep
Foundation, established a Sleep and the Traveler program through
which the main priorities for sound sleep were pinpointed as (1)
noise reduction; (2) improved bedding; and (3) improved temperature
control.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton addressed these and other concerns by installing
experimental ``Sleep-Tight Rooms'' _ with such features as ear
plugs, eye masks, ``natural sounds'' music and black-out (sealed)
curtains _ at several of its hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that people want a good night's sleep,''
said Alan T.
</P>
<P>
   Stutts, dean of the University of Houston's Conrad N. Hilton
College of Hotel and Restaurant Management. ``The mattress may be
part of that. The linens may be part. But air quality also is an
issue. Noise factors are an issue. The confidence for a business
traveler that you can accomplish what you want to do is an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, 49 percent of those surveyed by Westin cited the bed as
the most important item in a room (with no other item _ even a TV _
mentioned by as many as 10 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ``The Heavenly Bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Starwood Hotels &AMP; Resorts Worldwide, Westin's parent company, is
investing $30 million on placing 52,000 Heavenly Beds in 39,552
guest rooms throughout the United States and Canada. The company
expects to complete this task by early spring, then install the
beds at international properties. The new beds already are in place
at Houston's Westin Oaks and Westin Galleria hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Features include: _ A custom-designed pillowtop mattress set by
Simmons with 900 individual coils.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three sheets ranging in thread count from 180 to 250.
</P>
<P>
   _ A down blanket, with separate versions for three climates: a
Northern Star (29 ounces of down), Southern Star (18 ounces of
down) and Tropical Star (10 ounces of down).
</P>
<P>
   _ A comforter and duvet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Five pillows, including two king-size, 50/50
goose-down/goose-feather pillows.
</P>
<P>
   The future likely holds more advancements.
</P>
<P>
   According to UH's Stutts, technology now being studied includes
a comforter that regulates based on body temperature. ``If you are
hot-natured and tend to kick the covers, and your spouse is cold,
the comforter senses body temperature and releases heat or retains
heat,'' Stutts said. ``It works on a similar principle to the
thermal shields on the space shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Achieving total customer satisfaction may not be easy. As part
of Westin's sleep study, conducted for the chain by a New
York-based research firm, the main criticism by 27 percent of
respondents was that hotel mattresses are too soft. For another 21
percent, the No. 1 complaint was that mattresses are too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Stutts said two concepts _ one utilizing
springs and the other air _ are being studied that will allow hotel
guests to adjust the firmness of each side of a bed.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, here are some other findings in the Westin
survey: _ Women take longer to fall asleep in a hotel room than
men, and more women than men cite the poor quality of sleep in
hotels as compared to home.
</P>
<P>
   _ When asked what they miss most about sleeping at home when
they are in a hotel, 43 percent of men name their spouse or
significant other. Only 22 percent of women name their
spouse/significant other; 37 percent cite their own bed.
</P>
<P>
   _ To try to fall asleep in hotel rooms, 53 percent of travelers
read, 47 percent call their family, 43 percent draw the curtains or
shut the blinds and 42 percent leave the television on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventy-nine percent of those watching TV say they turn to
CNN, 59 percent access a national network's news, 51 percent watch
local news, 42 percent view the Weather Channel and 17 percent turn
to C-Span. Only 11 percent watch _ or admit to watching _ adult
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, about that Heavenly Hotline: It's 877-777-5418. Beds
and accessories are available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
