<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POLLUTION-FINE14-COX     01-13 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-FINE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS TO SPLIT $35 MILLION IN FINES FOR PIPELINE LEAKS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency said Thursday
that Koch Industries Inc. will pay $35 million in fines and
penalties to settle claims of contamination from oil spills in six
states. Texas will get half of the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will receive $15 million of the record $30 million civil
penalty and another $2.5 million from the settlement for state
environmental projects, EPA Administrator Carol Browner said at a
news conference. Koch also agreed to spend another $1 million for a
pipeline safety study in Texas, Kansas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement covers claims of more than 300 oil spills from
pipelines and other facilities between 1990 and 1997. Most took
place in Texas, Oklahoma and Kansas. In one instance, 90,300
gallons spilled into Corpus Christi Bay and Nueces Bay, causing a
12-mile oil slick and killing thousands of fish, Browner said.
</P>
<P>
   Over a seven-year period, Browner said, ``Koch illegally
discharged more than 3 million gallons of crude oil from its
pipelines and into the ponds, lakes, rivers and shorelines of
Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Louisiana, Missouri and Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in Wichita, Kan., Koch is the nation's largest pipeline
company with more than 35,000 miles of pipeline in the United
States and Canada. It also operates refineries in Texas and
Minnesota through its Koch Petroleum Group subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   At a Washington news conference, Browner said the case against
Koch had been ``one of our most difficult and contentious
environmental actions ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Koch issued a statement that the company had reduced
its crude oil pipeline leaks by more than 90 percent during the
1990s and spent nearly $1 billion on environmental improvements at
its facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the settlement is fair and reasonable and will
avoid even more years of litigation,'' said Pat McCann, senior vice
president of Koch Pipeline Co., a division of Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million fine is the largest civil penalty ever imposed
on a company under federal environmental law, said Browner.
However, Koch spokesperson Mary Beth Jarvis disputed that this was
the record, arguing that civil portion of penalties imposed for the
1989 Exxon Valdez tanker disaster in Alaska were larger. That case
also included criminal fines.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Texas had joined the Justice Department and EPA in
suing Koch and Browner thanked Texas Attorney General John Cornyn
for his legal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson that corporations must learn is that ``there is no
profit in pollution,'' said Browner. ``You pollute. You pay. It's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the spills were caused by corrosion of pipelines in
rural areas, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, Koch must assess the condition of 2,500
miles of specific pipelines and repair any defects. These include
Texas pipelines that run between Austin and Waco and between San
Antonio and Austin, as well as pipelines between Gonzales and Waco
and between Waco and Hillsboro.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also requires Koch to improve its program of
preventing and detecting pipeline leaks and to better inspect and
maintain its pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paying the $30 million fine, Koch agreed to spend
a total of $5 million on environmental programs hurt most by its
allegedly illegal discharges. These include:
</P>
<P>
   _ $2.5 million for Texas environmental projects to be carried
out under the direction of state officials. The projects will be
focused on the Corpus Christi Bay area, where one of the largest
spills occurred.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1 million for a pipeline safety study in Texas, Kansas and
Oklahoma aimed at educating the oil and gas industry about spill
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million to buy and preserve wetlands or wildlife
preserves in Kansas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
