<HEADER>
A5153 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-DAYTONA-BEACH-     01-13 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DAYTONA-BEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-GEAR ACTION STEERS FAMILIES TO DAYTONA BEACH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note that Daytona 500 is Feb. 20.) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Americans love their beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The sand, the sun, the smell of the surf _ it's no wonder that
more than 50 million towel-toting Americans are expected to descend
on U.S. beaches this summer. That number is courtesy of the Travel
Industry Association of America, which also points out that nearly
half of adult travelers don't plan their activities until after
they've arrived at a destination.
</P>
<P>
   That could be problematic at many beach destinations, where
options may be limited to eating, sleeping, sunbathing and the
occasional round of miniature golf.
</P>
<P>
   Families, in particular, require an array of recreational and
cultural diversions. No parent wants to hear ``I'm bored'' two days
into a weeklong vacation.
</P>
<P>
   One destination revving up the fun is sun-soaked Daytona Beach.
Long known for its spring break, its Bike Week motorcycle festival
and its speedway, Daytona Beach welcomes more than 8 million
visitors each year, enticing Florida-bound families with nature
cruises, historical sites, water sports and a diverse menu of
attractions, including one of the world's largest flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   Comprising seven communities (Port Orange, South Daytona,
Daytona Beach, Holly Hill, Ormond Beach, Daytona Beach Shores and
Ponce Inlet), the Daytona Beach area boasts 23 miles of coastline
on the Atlantic Ocean and three major rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Boat tours of the Halifax River, which flows between the
mainland and the peninsula and is also known as the Intracoastal
Waterway, offer a leisurely introduction to Central Florida's
natural wonders. A handful of companies offer boat tours ranging
from morning birding excursions to romantic sunset outings.
Pelicans, herons and bottle-nosed dolphins are among the wildlife
that can be seen on these casual expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   Other boat operators ply the waters of the quiet St. Johns
River. This is where, November-March, you're most likely to see the
lovable manatees. Like aquatic lawn mowers, manatees consume
massive amounts of sea grasses to maintain their 1,000-pound-plus
bulk. In addition to these playful but endangered marine mammals,
you may see alligators, otters, ospreys and bald eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor recreation is at the heart of a vacation at Daytona
Beach, where the average daytime temperature is 70 degrees. Golf
(more than a dozen courses dot this stretch of coast), horseback
riding, parasailing, windsurfing, snorkeling, scuba diving, hiking,
inline skating and canoeing are among the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Or enjoy a lazy afternoon of fishing. No license is required at
the Main Street Pier, which ranges a quarter mile into the
Atlantic. Families can rent poles and buy bait at the pier, then
drop their lines, sit back and watch the graceful pelicans fly by.
</P>
<P>
   The pier is at Daytona Beach's popular boardwalk, site of two
landmarks: the Clocktower and the Bandshell, built of coquina rock
by the Civilian Conservation Corps in 1937. Other boardwalk
diversions include gondola and Space Needle rides.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is Daytona Beach's newest attraction. Caribbean-themed
Adventure Landing is an architectural triumph, packing into just
five acres a quarter-mile go-cart track, a large video-game arcade,
three miniature-golf courses, three restaurants and a water park
with 12 slides, a wave pool and a drift river. Parents, watch your
wallets _ this place is a kids' wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   While the emphasis is fun in the sun, the Daytona Beach area has
several historic sites worth a stop.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular is the charming Ponce de Leon Inlet Lighthouse,
built in 1887 on the southern tip of the peninsula. Hardy visitors
can climb 203 steps to the top of the 175-foot-tall lighthouse for
spectacular views of the coast. Scattered on the grounds are
buildings that once were homes for lighthouse keepers. The
structures now house a lighthouse museum, the Museum of the Sea and
other marine exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The Casements, a mansion built in 1912 and purchased by
mega-millionaire John D. Rockefeller as a winter home in 1918,
today is a museum and cultural center. It exhibits period
furniture, some terrific examples of Hungarian folk art and a fine
collection of Boy Scout memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss the Retreat on the Bethune-Cookman College campus.
The Retreat was the name given to college founder Mary McLeon
Bethune's home. Built in 1915, it remains very much as it was when
she died in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Bethune, the 15th of 17 children born to freed slaves, became a
teacher and founded her school in 1904 with five students and
$1.50. In the mid-1920s, her all-women's school merged with the
all-male Cookman Institute. Today Bethune-Cookman thrives as a
private liberal-arts college.
</P>
<P>
   Bethune became one of the most influential women of her time. In
1935, she led the first meeting of President Franklin D.
Roosevelt's ``Negro Cabinet,'' an unofficial but influential group
of advisers on minority issues. Eleanore Roosevelt became a friend
and is known to have spent the night at the Retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Bethune is buried on the tidy, tree-shaded campus.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach's ballpark is another historic site. On March 17,
1946, Jackie Robinson broke the major-league color barrier by
playing in a baseball game here against the Brooklyn Dodgers.
Robinson was playing for the Montreal Royals, a Dodgers farm team,
and segregationist laws had kept him from playing at other Florida
ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, the park was renamed Jackie Robinson Ballpark; a
bronze statue of the Hall-of-Famer stands at the entrance to the
park, now home to the Florida State League's Daytona Beach Cubs, an
affiliate of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach gets about 54 inches of precipitation a year _
just enough to warrant mention of a few rainy-day pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Museum of Arts and Sciences, comprising a Cuban art
collection, an African wing, a planetarium and a prehistory
collection starring the 14-foot-tall skeleton of a 130,000-year-old
ground sloth.
</P>
<P>
   Or chill out at the new Daytona Iceplex, which hosts
recreational ice skating as well as the local minor-league hockey
club, the Riptides.
</P>
<P>
   And did we forget to mention the track?
</P>
<P>
   Daytona International Speedway, a 2.5-mile tri-oval track, is
billed as the World Center of Racing. It hosts nine racing weekends
each year, ranging from go-carts to sports cars. The track will
host the most famous race of the National Association for Stock Car
Auto Racing, the Daytona 500, on Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Even when engines aren't roaring, the speedway attracts
visitors. Daytona USA offers an interactive and often thrilling
look at motor sports. Fans can demonstrate their mechanic skills
during a fast-paced pit stop, test their NASCAR knowledge via
computer, play race announcer and take a walk through motor-sports
history. They also can explore the track on a behind-the-scenes
tour that includes stops on Pit Row and at one of the track's
31-degree banks.
</P>
<P>
   Race fans will appreciate the up-close view of the car that won
the last Daytona 500. Jeff Gordon's No. 24 car didn't even get a
bath before it was pulled into Daytona USA's Victory Lane, where it
will remain until next month's race.
</P>
<P>
   While the speedway is a hit with visitors, Daytona Beach's big
wheel is Bike Week.
</P>
<P>
   Held in early March, Bike Week is the country's largest
motorcycle event and the city's biggest tourism event, attracting
more than 500,000 motorcyclists from around the world. The 10-day
festival will celebrate its 59th birthday this year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the festivities are concerts, swap meets, races, a
Harley-Davidson parade and the Blessing of the Bikes. While the
leather-clad action is nonstop, most bikers come merely to relax
and to see and be seen. (A more family-oriented event,
Biketoberfest, is drawing as many as 60,000 motorcycle enthusiasts
each October.)
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach has been a magnet for motor-sports fans since
1902, when Ransom Olds, playboy maker of the Oldsmobile automobile,
began racing his sports car against those of his highfalutin pals.
His car, known as the Pirate, was clocked at 50 mph flying down
Ormond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, the beach was the site of automotive
history when Englishman Henry Segrave broke the 200 mph mark with
his Sunbeam Mystery S car. Between 1928 and 1935, the land speed
record was broken five times on Daytona's hard-packed sands.
</P>
<P>
   That brings up another reason why motor-sports fans love Daytona
Beach. While racing is no longer allowed, driving on the beach is
permitted in designated areas. For many visitors, cruising on the
sand is a novelty. For locals, it's a decades-old tradition
threatened by conservationists, who want to ban beach driving to
protect endangered sea-turtle hatchlings.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you walk or ride, exploring Daytona's beach can be a
gas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
