<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BAMBOLEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAMBOLEO: A MUSICAL JOURNEY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent marks needed over first i and third a in Ahi-Nama 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Bamboleo represents all that is right with the
progression of Afro-Cuban dance music in America.
</P>
<P>
   Right up until a young Cuban boy is found in the waters off
Miami. A survivor of an escape from Cuba that took his mother's
life, the child is at the center of a controversy that has set off
new rounds of anti-Castro protests in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Bamboleo _ a timba ensemble of young musicians visiting the
United States to promote its new album, ``Ya No Hace Falta'' (I
Don't Need You Anymore), _ is forced into the role of political
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief time the group experiences what it's like to be
``them'' to the United States' ``us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The band doesn't really like to take questions about
politics,'' says Angelica Sepulveda, a manager at Ahi-Nama Records,
the record label that promotes Bamboleo and other Cuban bands in
the States. ``They won't even discuss that little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Maslon, owner of Ahi-Nama, puts it more succinctly. ``They
resent that they have to be asked. My groups are not political.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode is a minor blip that might make Bamboleo's visa
process more difficult in the short term and require more security
for the band in cities with anti-Cuba factions. It is not enough,
however, to stop the infiltration of the island's music into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   After 40 years of embargo, contemporary timba, rumba and salsa
artists are anxious for a new audience. The spoils of two years of
a Latin-music renaissance in the United States are finally starting
to be felt.
</P>
<P>
   It started with the international acclaim for Buena Vista Social
Club's album of ``son,'' traditional Cuban folk music. Since then,
Mexican-born rocker Carlos Santana has put out ``Supernatural,'' an
album of Afro-Latin grooves recognized with 10 Grammy nominations.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there's been a glitzy pop bonanza of new stars such
as Jennifer Lopez, Ricky Martin and Enrique Iglesias. The next wave
should be a combination of old and new.
</P>
<P>
   Young Latin artists no longer have to ``Americanize'' their
sound to gain international recognition. Groups like Bamboleo and
Ahi-Nama label-mate Arte Mixto could be leading the way toward a
more cultural representation of Cuba's roots.
</P>
<P>
   If Bamboleo's 12-member assault of timba and Cuban ``clave''
draws well at Houston's Club Tropicana on Jan.18, expect it to be
the first in a line of Cuban bands to play in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep bringing these bands as long as it's
affordable,'' say Luis Ricardo, co-promoter of Houston's Bamboleo
show. ``I hope this is the start of a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   By day Ricardo is not a concert promoter. He's an insurance
broker. His partner, Juan R. Duran, owns a barber shop in Houston.
Both are Cuban natives. Ricardo is a percussionist who plays
several nights a week in a local salsa band, Batacha.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ricardo saw Bamboleo while visiting Cuba and
immediately had thoughts about bringing the group to Houston. After
meeting Maslon last year at an Arte Mixto concert in New Orleans,
he found his opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought there was a definite market for this in
Houston,'' Ricardo says. ``If this works, there'll be more Ahi-Nama
bands coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Timba music is an upbeat, fusion-enhanced, electrified version
of the traditional Cuban ``son'' that many now associate with Buena
Vista Social Club, which performs here Feb. 15 at Jones Hall.
Bomboleo is an even higher-energy departure. Translated, leader
Lazaro Valdes says, the band's name means ``movement,'' and the
band certainly doesn't lack that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's a fusion of different rhythms _ rumba,
hip-hop, Latin bop and jazz,'' Valdes says. ``All the groups that
do timba have a pattern that they follow. We take it further with
improvisations, mambos, percussion effect and style.''
</P>
<P>
   The members range in ages from 25 to 35 and are graduates from
the National School of Arts in Havana. Its base in Cuban music
can't be ignored, but songs like ``Circulame'' and ``Yo No Me
Parezco a Nadie'' also have roots in such '70s funk as Earth Wind &AMP;
Fire and the Commodores.
</P>
<P>
   The fashions of Valdes and the four vocalists _ Alejandro
Borrero, Jorge David Rodriguez, Yordamis Megret and Vannia Borges
Hernandez _ are that of a very elegant Latin soap opera. The men
wear Italian suits in black and burgundy; they accessorize with
gold chains and leather shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The women wear luxurious evening gowns and trademark hair so
short it looks painted on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Around Cuba, young women have taken to the hairdo the way
American teens took to the platform sneakers worn by the Spice
Girls a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   After touring Europe with Los Van Van and Celia Cruz, Bambeleo
has gathered a following in France, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In the States, though, it's often like starting from the
beginning, with politics constantly playing a role in the band's
success. Getting visas is easier with every visit, but the band has
experienced instances when shows were delayed or canceled because
of customs.
</P>
<P>
   One can't help but think that contemporary Cuban music will
continue to find its way onto U.S. soil _ first through Miami, New
York and Los Angeles. After that, who knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big honor to come to the United States and share Cuban
music as it is today,'' Valdes says. ``But it's only the beginning.
Our objective is to conquer the world with our sound.''
</P>
<P>
   This week Houston; tomorrow the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
