<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUBLISHER SAYS SAN FRANCISCO WOULD BENEFIT FROM NEWSPAPER
MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Filed in the ``f'' and ``a'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner SAN FRANCISCO _ The proposed merger of the city's two daily
<TEXT>
newspapers would benefit consumers by boosting competition in Bay
Area suburbs, the Hearst Corporation said in defense of its plan to
consolidate the San Francisco Examiner and San Francisco Chronicle.
<P>
   In pleadings filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court, Hearst,
owner of the Examiner, asked a judge to dismiss an anti-merger
lawsuit filed by Clint Reilly, an unsuccessful candidate for mayor
in last year's election.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based media company said its plan to buy the
competing Chronicle fully complied with federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly filed a lawsuit Tuesday against Hearst and the Chronicle
Publishing Co., contending that Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle
for a reported $660 million and merge it with the afternoon
Examiner would result in higher advertising and subscription rates
and thus harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, a former political consultant who finished fourth in the
mayor's race, asked the court to block the merger as a violation of
federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's proposed purchase of the Chronicle was announced in
August and has been under review by the antitrust division of the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Hearst Corporation told the court that Reilly
was wrong when he claimed the merger would mean higher prices for
readers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Examiner and the Chronicle have been jointly
setting their subscription and advertising prices under terms of
the Joint Operating Agreement through which the papers share
printing and business operations. Hearst argued that the merger
would actually boost competition among news outlets in the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   The merger ``will benefit consumers by increasing competition
between the Chronicle and other print and electronic media,
including such major firms as Knight-Ridder, which owns the San
Jose Mercury News and the Contra Costa Times,'' wrote Gary Halling,
a lawyer for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's attorney, Joseph M. Alioto, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a century, the Examiner and the Chronicle were
morning rivals. But in 1965, the two newspapers contended that it
was impossible for both of them to survive without relief from
head-to-head competition.
</P>
<P>
   They entered into a joint operating agreement under which the
Examiner switched to afternoon publication. The two newspapers
maintain separate news staffs and compete for stories, but share
business operations and profits. The agreement is set to expire in
2005.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area's newspaper market has undergone huge changes since
1965, in part because of the rise of strong suburban newspapers,
including those published by Knight-Ridder, the nation's second
biggest newspaper chain.
</P>
<P>
   Last year when the Thieriot family, which owns Chronicle
Publishing, decided to sell its media properties, Hearst said it
would buy the Chronicle and merge it with the Examiner unless a
buyer for the afternoon newspaper was found.
</P>
<P>
   In its legal response, Hearst said it had had no luck finding a
buyer for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Through a broker, the company contacted 81 prospective buyers,
but found no one interested in publishing an afternoon paper in the
city, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The morning Chronicle has an average daily circulation of about
484,000, while the Examiner's circulation is about 120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sale was announced, Mayor Willie Brown and other city
officials have said they oppose the merger. District Attorney
Terence Hallinan has threatened an antitrust lawsuit of the sort
Reilly filed.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has interests in publishing, broadcasting, syndication
and the Internet. It owns daily newspapers in Albany, N.Y.;
Edwardsville, Ill.; Bad Axe and Midland, Mich.; Seattle; and in the
Texas cities of Beaumont, Houston, Laredo, Midland, Plainview and
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing owns several television stations as well as
the Telegram &AMP; Gazette in Worcester, Mass., and the Bloomington
Pantagraph in Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
