<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GIRL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINONA RYDER'S BROODING LENDS CONTINUITY TO `GIRL, INTERRUPTED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Winona Ryder ever better than when she's brooding?
</P>
<P>
   She may have earned two Oscar nominations for her wistful
performances in ``Little Women'' and ``The Age of Innocence'' but
she didn't have nearly as much grave appeal as she did in Tim
Burton's ``Beetlejuice'' or, now, in ``Girl, Interrupted,'' which
is based on Susanna Kaysen's 1993 bestselling autobiographical book
about her descent into depression and illness.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe darkness suits Ryder, because she's certainly the glue
that keeps all the chaotic, manic co-characters from spiraling out
of control in ``Girl, Interrupted.'' As directed by James Mangold,
who made the gritty dramas ``Heavy'' and ``Copland,'' there are two
speeds to this film _ fast and furious or downbeat and slow.
</P>
<P>
   And while it's no ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' or even on
a par with Frank Perry's fragile porcelain puzzle, ``David and
Lisa,'' the film has its strengths. It looks as desaturated as a
newsreel and captures the tone and idealism of an era _ the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna washes a bottle of aspirin down with as much vodka,
cavalierly saying afterward that ``she had a headache.'' The move
lands her in Claymoore Hospital, an elite Boston mental
establishment where she is diagnosed with borderline personality
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, she meets the charismatic but sociopathic Lisa (Angelina
Jolie), who, on the surface is strong and wild, but beneath as
frightened and vulnerable as the rest of the patients on the floor.
Initially Susanna lingers beneath Lisa's seemingly magical aura,
breaking the rules and creating havoc, but after a tragedy occurs,
Susanna begins to repair her life by confronting her demons, apathy
and anger _ and writing it all down in a journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted'' tackles so much that it skims the surface
of mental illness ``chic,'' trivializing the plight of the young
women and conveniently presenting an array of patients diagnosed
with a smorgasboard of illnesses _ anorexia, pathological lying,
eating disorders, sociopathy and plain old human frailty. It comes
off as a schoolgirl's doomed romantic notion that feels more
old-fashioned than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   And the highs and lows nearly sink a film that's not quite sure
what it wants to convey and never finds its emotional pitch. For
all its sombre heaviness and reverential gravity, it never quite
pulls all the elements and themes together despite Ryder's
thankfully downplayed turn and an exceptional bit by Brittany
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   As Daisy, Murphy is heartbreakingly frail, tough and brittle as
a young patient who is discharged from Claymoore and ultimately
falls to pieces when she discovers a hard truth about the world:
life outside the four confining walls of the hospital is no
different and her supposed independence is little more than a thin
veil that keeps her self-delusion and illusion at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Girl, Interrupted. Directed by James Mangold. Written by
Mangold, Lisa Loomer, Anna Hamilton Phelan. Cast: Winona Ryder,
Angelina Jolie, Whoopi Goldberg, Vanessa Redgrave. Columbia
Pictures. 125 minutes. Rated R for language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1605EST &QL; 
