<SLUG> BC-FILM-42UP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`42 UP': REAL-LIFE TALE HAS SEASONED ANOTHER 7 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Apted is one of those rare directors who can jump back
and forth between the feature and documentary film worlds with
ease.
</P>
<P>
   He not only directed ``Coal Miner's Daughter,'' which scored a
best picture Oscar nomination, and the newest James Bond film,
``The World Is Not Enough,'' but also the politically impassioned
``Incident at Oglala,'' which focused on the plight of imprisoned
activist Leonard Peltier. In 1994, he ventured to China to make
``Moving the Mountain,'' which looked back at the Tiananmen Square
Massacre through the eyes of five students.
</P>
<P>
   ``42 Up'' is the sixth installment in a Granada TV series that
originated in 1962 with ``7 Up,'' which took 14 7-year-old English
children from various classes and temperaments and asked questions
about their families and aspirations. The series has followed them
at 7-year intervals (``7+7 Up,'' ``21 Up,'' ``28 Up,'' ``35 Up'')
through the course of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating premise that certainly appeals to the voyeur
in us all; so fascinating in fact, that Apted acted as executive
producer on ``14 Up in America'' and ``Age 14 in Russia'' and
Australian director Gillian Armstrong began her own series,
``Smokes and Lollies,'' following it up with ``14's Good, 18's
Better'' and ``Not 14 Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``42 Up'' proves that truth is far more interesting than
fiction. Eleven of the original kids agreed to participate in this
edition and Apted delves into their marriages, affairs, children,
ambitions, feelings about the series, and disappointments. He
intercuts footage from the previous age levels and ultimately
provides a concise history of each person so the viewer doesn't
have to see the other films to glean a consistent and well-rounded
sense of who each is and how, from the first glimpse in 1962, their
destinies were already forged and formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``42 Up'' is difficult to weigh and rate precisely because it
deals with real life and real people. As Symon, the ex-foster care
boy, shyly notes, ``We're not talking about a movie. We're talking
about life.'' And ``42 Up'' proves, as these once-optimistic
children now enter middle age, that life doesn't always turn out
the way we hoped when we were young and believed we had all the
time in the world to alter the course of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   42 Up. Documentary directed by Michael Apted. First Run
Features. 135 minutes. Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1607EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
