<HEADLINE>
CLOONEY SAYS NO TRUTH IN RUMOR THAT HE'S ON CALL FOR `ER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Contrary to rumor, George Clooney says no one
has asked him to return to ``ER,'' not even for the episode when
Julianna Margulies leaves the series later this season. Margulies
plays nurse Carol Hathaway, who now has twins fathered by Clooney's
character, Doug Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney says reports of his being offered $2 million per episode
are complete fabrications of wishful thinkers. ``I have never been
asked,'' he told TV critics this week, ``(but) I'd like to go on
the record as saying, `I'd go back for $2 million an episode.' I'm
not an idiot.'' But he also said he wouldn't return unless there
was a compelling reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it's necessarily smart for me to come back
for one scene and, you know, scoop Julianna up and walk out. ...
Julianna leaving will be a big enough story line, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor is more intent these days on a project for CBS that
recalls the early days of television. He is producing and will star
in a live black-and-white remake of the 1964 film ``Fail-Safe'' on
April 9 with his pal and ``ER'' co-star, Noah Wyle. Walter
Bernstein, who wrote the original novel and the 1964 screenplay of
the Cold War thriller, is writing the new script.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney hopes the ``Fail-Safe'' film will be more of an artistic
success than the live episode of ``ER'' he instigated a couple of
years ago, because the film's sets will be constructed from scratch
with a live broadcast in mind, rather than adapted to accommodate
something they weren't designed for.
</P>
<P>
   _Besides ``City of Angels'' CBS will make room in its midseason
schedule for two more series. One is ``Falcone,'' the long-awaited
hourlong drama based on the life of Joseph Pistone, the undercover
FBI agent who inspired the film ``Donnie Brasco.'' Jason Gedrick
plays Pistone, who poses as a brash young mobster named Joe
Falcone. The other series is ``Grapevine,'' a half-hour romantic
comedy that may ring a bell with some viewers. Six episodes of the
series aired in the summer of 1992, and creator David Frankel has
been waiting all these years to bring it back. Kristy Swanson,
Steven Eckholdt, George Eads and David Sutcliffe star.
</P>
<P>
   On the miniseries side, CBS's winter/spring slate includes a
little crime, a little sex and a little of that old-time religion.
``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town,'' a film about the JonBenet Ramsey
murder case starring Ronny Cox and Marg Helgenberger as John and
Patsy Ramsey, airs Feb. 27 and March 1; ``Sally Hemings: An
American Scandal'' has Sam Neill as Thomas Jefferson and Carmen
Ejogo as his slave and mistress, Sally Hemings, airing Feb. 13 and
16; and ``Jesus'' features Jeremy Sisto as Jesus Christ, Jacqueline
Bisset as the Virgin Mary and Debra Messing as Mary Magdalene,
airing in May.
</P>
<P>
   _Steven Bochco on the state of minority opportunities at the
major networks: ``I may get taken to task for this, but I don't see
an overt, rabid racism on the part of networks. I see a kind of
institutional laziness, a kind of ennui, if you will, that results
in a lack of diversity in hiring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
