<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-PINOCHET-BO     01-13 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PINOCHET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PINOCHET PRECEDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The majesty of the law was on display when Britain found Chile's
erstwhile dictator, General Augusto Pinochet, medically unfit to
stand trial in Spain for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Four highly qualified specialists conducted seven hours of
medical exams and concluded that the health of the 84-year-old
Pinochet had declined markedly last fall. The interior minister of
Britain's Labor government, Jack Straw, said the examining doctors
reached conclusions that were ``unequivocal and unanimous.'' Straw
is expected to refuse Spain's request for Pinochet's extradition
and to allow him to return home to Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the Chileans, Spaniards, and Americans who were
tortured and murdered after Pinochet's 1973 putsch will doubtless
feel that the tyrant has been permitted to elude the law. Human
rights organizations, too, may rue Britain's decision as a
desolating example of the impunity that criminals wielding state
power have enjoyed all too often in the past century.
</P>
<P>
   But two significant principles were affirmed in the dramatic
case of Pinochet. Britain's highest judicial authority, the Law
Lords of the House of Lords, ruled that Pinochet could not be
exempt from prosecution for crimes against humanity merely because
he had acted as a head of state. In this way the British legal
system established a Pinochet precedent: There is no such thing as
sovereign immunity for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more telling is the emblematic meaning of the due
process accorded Pinochet in Britain. The ailing tyrant was judged
by a truly independent judiciary. He was represented by counsel of
his choice, and when one of his judges was believed to have a
potential conflict of interest, Pinochet was granted a new hearing
before new judges. At the end of a meticulously fair process, he
received a mercy that is inherent in the law.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such mercy for the men and women who were tortured
and killed while Pinochet ruled Chile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     01-13 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN DESPERATION AND THE FIRING OF CHAN GAILEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old Henry David Thoreau certainly had it right about that
``quiet desperation'' that characterizes the lives of most men.
</P>
<P>
   I became more convinced of that than ever after seeing and
hearing the surreal goings-on at Valley Ranch late Tuesday
afternoon and the post-mortems of those proceedings later.
</P>
<P>
   The firing of Dallas Cowboys coach Chan Gailey was a byproduct
of that mass phenomenon. Make no mistake about it: Gailey deserved
it. Based upon some of the abominable calls he made in crucial
situations, one could make a good argument that he should not have
been allowed to finish the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But what, you ask, has Gailey's failure as a Cowboys coach got
to do with Thoreau?
</P>
<P>
   Simply this: He failed to provide a huge percentage of the
people who live in North Texas, or who regard the Dallas Cowboys
from afar as ``America's Team,'' with a steady jolt of release from
the grip of the desperation of their humdrum daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   Having a winning hometown sports franchise can do that for
people _ even those who are not real sports fans. The exhilaration
is contagious. It carries over into every phase of community life _
a tonic, an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   A win by the local football team on Sunday takes the blues out
of Monday, and the warm feeling lasts the whole week. Winning the
Super Bowl can have a monthslong time-release effect.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Fort Worth-Dallas have become greatly accustomed to
that kind of vicarious antidote to quiet desperation. Many of them
have suffered painful withdrawal pangs because of their team's
lackluster performance in 1998 and its 1999 disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, an 8-9 season would be acceptable; in Fort
Worth-Dallas, it's intolerable. Someone had to pay. If not Gailey,
who? And after all, he deserved it, although not by himself.
</P>
<P>
   There is real anger out there. Some of the sports talk-show
performers are capturing that mood, feeding upon it and spewing it
back with amplified vituperation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these mouthy vicarious coaches and sports franchise
owners have taken on the ferocity of Old Testament prophets,
condemning, ridiculing and offering inane advice.
</P>
<P>
   In their way, they provide some ventilation of frustration for
masses who have no way to voice their impotent rage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sports fanaticism is not the only means that people
use to escape vicariously from quiet desperation.
Non-sports-related television offers legions of avenues of escape.
Whatever strikes one's fancy, from soap opera sentimentality to
greed-teasing game shows to thrill-a-minute action programs to
gory, desensitizing violence to graphic sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   And one can travel almost anywhere on the tube, from the source
of the Nile to the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever television can do, the movies can do bigger, and
complement it with the added effect of sharing a vicarious event
with strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Movie stars have become the modern equivalent of the fickle and
exuberant gods, goddesses, nymphs and satyrs of Greek and Roman
mythology. Their lives and foibles provide a continuing stream of
grist for the print and broadcast scandal mills.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that mix the fingertip power of virtual living and
amusement on line, and the conformist behavior (like jogging) that
people do primarily because they see others doing it, and there
would appear to be no reason for anyone to be bored.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, millions are bored. Modern Americans are the most
overamused people in the history of the planet, and yet they derive
no lasting satisfaction from their amusements.
</P>
<P>
   That's not entirely because most of them do not work at jobs
that give them real satisfaction. After all, if one gets much
gratification from any activity, it can't be considered work.
</P>
<P>
   It goes deeper than that. The real reason is that Americans are
constantly being told that they need more stimulation to feel
really alive. They need that earth-shaking love affair portrayed in
the movies. They need wealth, fame. They need to score a touchdown!
</P>
<P>
   And if they can't score a touchdown themselves, then the next
best thing is to watch someone else do it and identify with him. So
if Chan Gailey can't provide the leadership to make the Cowboys
score the touchdowns that the fans need to see to get them through
the week ... well, ``Goodbye, Chan.''
</P>
<P>
   I, too, say ``good riddance'' as far as Gailey's firing is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   But I know that I, like many others, allow such vicarious
thrills to matter to me too much when there could be so much more
lasting satisfaction to be found by sitting before a pond of
slow-moving water and quietly drowning my sense of desperation in
its depths.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a Star-Telegram columnist and editorial
writer. You can reach him at cecil &LR; star-telegram.com or (817)
390-7663. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
