<HEADLINE>
REAL WORLD OF `CITY OF ANGELS' NEEDS A SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Bochco says if ``City of Angels'' fails, it will be a
serious setback for minority-produced, minority-acted programming
on the major networks, no matter what the nets are doing to assuage
the NAACP and other groups that want their color TV a little more
colorful, a little more reflective of the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Bochco is right, simply because there aren't a
half-dozen other shows out there with crews and casts composed
mainly of minorities. But his suggestion that we'll all be sorry if
this noble endeavor falters sort of makes him the biggest travel
agent for guilt trips this side of my mom. It's as if he's saying:
``Watch it or else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one way to make must-see TV, but we'd all be better
served if Bochco and his co-creators, Paris Barclay and Nicholas
Wootton, had delivered a better debut. Its relative weakness may be
precisely why Bochco is beating the social-significance drum so
steadily. Sunday's premiere episode of ``City of Angels'' is
polished, but it lacks the raw intensity of other Bochco shows like
``NYPD Blue,'' ``L.A. Law,'' ``Hill Street Blues,'' even ``Murder
One.'' Pacing is languorous _ closer to ``Chicago Hope'' than
``ER'' _ and anyone who remembers ``St. Elsewhere'' will quickly
realize that one of the show's key characters, the hospital itself,
seems underused in ``City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   This may all change as we get to know the staff and the quirks
of Angels of Mercy Hospital, but first impressions can be harder to
shake than the flu. And the first impression of ``City of Angels''
is that it's a better-than-average show that warrants another
visit, but which could also benefit from crisper direction and a
more passionate sense of what it's trying to be.
</P>
<P>
   The estimable Blair Underwood stands out as the acting chief of
surgery, Dr. Ben Turner, a gifted professional dedicated to quality
medical care for all. Turner's considerable zeal is matched by the
duplicity of hospital CEO Ron Harris (Michael Warren) and the
mysteriousness of Edwin O'Malley (Robert Morse), chairman of the
city's board of supervisors. But Vivica A. Fox, as the hospital's
new medical director who must deal regularly with all three men,
falls short of a convincing portrayal. Fox may grow in the role as
her character, Dr. Lillian Price, grows in the job, but for a woman
trying to impart lofty standards to an inner-city hospital
struggling to keep its accreditation, Dr. Price exhibits less
emotion than a patient under anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' may yet be the sort of program that becomes
the next water-cooler show for millions of Americans, but right now
it could use a shot of adrenaline. Stat.
</P>
<P>
   City of Angels. One-hour drama series about a county hospital
struggling to survive in inner-city Los Angeles. Starring Blair
Underwood, Vivica A. Fox, Michael Warren, Robert Morse, Hill
Harper, Phil Buckman, T.E. Russell, Viola Davis and Maya Rudolph.
Series premieres Sunday on CBS, moves to Wednesdays on Jan. 19.
Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
