<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TERRORIST-FILM-NYT &LR;      01-13 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TERRORIST': A GUERRILLA GROWS UP DURING A MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Malli (Ayesha Dharkar), the title character of Santosh Sivan's
remarkable new film, is a 19-year-old who lives in a guerrilla camp
in the South Indian jungle. Aside from her occasional execution of
a traitor and the constant threat of a government ambush, her life
seems in many respects perfectly ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   She could almost be the heroine of a sweet, wholesome Hollywood
coming-of-age story. She and her girlfriends engage in friendly
banter, brush each other's hair and do their best to ignore the
appraising looks of the local boys. When Malli is chosen for a
suicide mission, her peers respond with envy and admiration, as if
she had been elected prom queen.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of a rhinestone tiara, she is granted the rare
privilege of lunch with the Leader (Sonu Sisupal), the faceless
adult in command of this army of children, and then sent out to
assassinate a politician referred to only as the VIP.
</P>
<P>
   Malli's cause is never specified, but ``The Terrorist'' was
suggested by a very real event: the suicide bombing that killed
Rajiv Gandhi, the Indian prime minister, in 1991. In spite of the
political volatility of its subject matter, the film is less
interested in politics than in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to have been inspired by a basic, exquisitely difficult
question: what kind of a person would do something like that? And
by choosing to answer the question as literally and painstakingly
as possible, Sivan has accomplished something extraordinary: he has
given political extremism a human face.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean this metaphorically. Ms. Dharkar's unforgettable
face, with her wide, full mouth and enormous dark eyes, appears in
nearly every frame, often filling most of the screen, as if we
might be able to find our way into Malli's mind through her pores.
</P>
<P>
   At times Sivan's taste for extremely tight close-ups _ and his
tendency to decorate Malli's face with raindrops and tears _ feels
annoyingly arty, as does his habit of filling the soundtrack with
heavy breathing and portentous music.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part he tells Malli's story with subtlety and
simplicity, resisting the temptations of melodrama and ideological
point-scoring. He is helped by the astonishing Ms. Dharkar, who
manages to register, almost entirely through nuances of gesture and
facial expression, her character's complex inner transformation.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the movie Malli exists in a state of
perverse innocence. She inhabits a universe in which martyrdom
appears to be not only an exalted ambition but a reasonable career
choice. Her father, we learn, was a well-known nationalist poet,
and her older brother is described by a comrade in tones of
veneration as ``the first to consume cyanide and die for the
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leader, in his lunchtime pep talk, tells Malli he wants her
to become a ``thinking bomb,'' and she seems, from the start, to be
quite thoughtful, even as she matter-of-factly accepts her own
annihilation.
</P>
<P>
   But the most dangerous thing about a thinking bomb, at least
from the Leader's point of view, is that it has the potential to
defuse itself. And as she moves closer to her fate, Malli begins to
have second thoughts, not about the cause or her comrades but about
the logic of martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   In a less rigorous movie, Malli's passage from unwavering belief
to agonized doubt might have been hammered home through overwrought
speeches and tearful confrontations. But Sivan allows her zeal to
unravel slowly and quietly, through her gradual, accidental
immersion in a world unlike the jungle bases in which she has spent
her life: the decidedly unheroic world of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   When Malli arrives in the town where the assassination is
supposed to take place, she is lodged, under false pretenses, with
a farmer named Vasu (Parmeshwaran). At first Vasu seems like a
vain, lecherous old fool, dispensing demented parables (``Do you
know the story of the optimistic seed and the pessimistic seed?'')
and asking nosy questions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the course of Malli's sojourn _ four days that feel as
endless as the four days leading up to a foreordained death must
feel _ her perception of him, and ours, shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Vasu's life, a messy mixture of tragedy, absurdity and stoicism,
becomes the film's emblem of decency, and the relationship between
the farmer and the suicide bomber becomes its emotional core. And
the film, without stooping to political-thriller cliches, becomes
almost unbearably suspenseful, as we wonder whether Malli's new
self-knowledge _ her willingness to allow confusion into her life _
will prevent her from completing her mission. In presenting Malli's
dilemma, Sivan shows an ability to capture the texture of quotidian
reality _ to communicate both its exquisite beauty and terrible
fragility _ that recalls the work of Robert Bresson, or, closer to
home, Satyajit Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Terrorist'' is the first feature that Sivan, one of
India's most respected cinematographers, has directed, so it is
perhaps premature to enlist him in such exalted company.
</P>
<P>
   The film was shot in 17 days (on locations in Kerala and
Madras), with a cast made up entirely of nonprofessional actors, on
a tiny budget. But there is nothing modest about the ambitions or
talent that ``The Terrorist'' displays. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TERRORIST'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Santosh Sivan; written (in Tamil, with English
subtitles) by Sivan, Ravi Despanade and Vijay Deveshwar; director
of photography, Sivan; edited by Sreekar Prasad; music by Sonu
Sisupal and Rajamani; production designer, Shyam Sunder; produced
by Shree Prasad and Jit Joshi; released by Phaedra Cinema. Running
time: 95 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ayesha Dharkar (Malli), Parmeshwaran (Vasu), Vishnu
Vardhan (Thyagu), Bhanu Prakash (Perumal), K. Krishna (Lover), Sonu
Sisupal (Leader), Vishwas (Lotus) and Anuradha (Sumitra). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1626EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
