<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     01-13 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CHEESE THEORY IS A GOOD READ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A famous Jesuit once said that the only thing that stands
between humans and the truth is a story.
</P>
<P>
   That could easily be said of the book gracing the Top 10
bestsellers lists of The New York Times, Business Week and other
major publications, entitled ``Who Moved My Cheese? An A-Mazing Way
to Deal with Change in Your Work and in Your Life'' (G.P. Putman's
Sons, 96 pages, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Although far from complex theology, this book can trigger
profound thought through its use of a simple allegorical tale. It
seems to have moved entire corporations, as well as many people.
</P>
<P>
   It's written by Spencer Johnson, co-author of ``The One Minute
Manager'' and several other books, including a popular children's
series. Johnson has a medical degree, with internships at Harvard
Medical School and the Mayo Clinic, and worked for the company that
invented cardiac pacemakers.
</P>
<P>
   He is an international speaker and author whose books are
available in 26 languages.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in ``The One Minute Manager,'' Johnson has pared his
ideas to the bare bone in this book, making it easily read in an
hour or less. Nonetheless, readers may find themselves thinking
about it for days if not weeks after they have finished it.
</P>
<P>
   And then they will probably pass it on to coworkers, bosses and
clients. In a recent special edition, Johnson lists 100
corporations and organizations, from Anheuser Busch and AT&AMP;T to the
U.S. Army, Navy and Air Force, that have endorsed the book.
</P>
<P>
   I came to this book with skepticism, because every other
allegorical tale I've read that dealt with business fell flat. I
typically roll my eyes at the end of such books and wonder who
could ever get anything meaningful out of the story.
</P>
<P>
   But not this one. The story is so simple: two mice and two small
humans, or ``littlepeople,'' as Johnson calls them, in a maze
looking for cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The mice, not afflicted with emotion or overanalysis, fare well
in the maze, finding cheese and then moving on when a corridor
becomes empty.
</P>
<P>
   The littlepeople, despite their obvious superior intelligence,
have much more of a struggle. They initially find cheese but then
become far too complacent, so they not only cannot see their cheese
mound decline but, when it disappears, are completely terrified of
what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ranted and raved at the injustice of it all,'' Johnson
writes. ``The littlepeople couldn't believe it. How could this have
happened? No one had warned them. It wasn't right. It was not the
way things were supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The braver of the two littlepeople goes through quite an odyssey
searching for new cheese, having to break down his fears of the
journey and of new experiences while facing hunger and exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   This littleperson, Haw, comes up with several truths along the
way to finding more cheese, which he writes on the walls of the
maze. Among them are:
</P>
<P>
   If you do not change, you can become extinct.
</P>
<P>
   What would you do if you weren't afraid?
</P>
<P>
   Smell the cheese often so you know when it is getting old.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing small changes early helps you adapt to the bigger
changes that are to come.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to read the book to find out how the littlepeople
make out. (The mice, of course, find the new source of cheese
shortly after they exhausted the last one).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also includes a story outside the story to begin and end
his cheese tale. This second story involves four people meeting at
a college reunion, all in different stages of work and personal
life. This group is introduced to the cheese story by one
schoolmate, who thought it might help them.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the book, all four react to different aspects of
the story and go away carrying its message. Although this part of
the book comes off a little more clumsily, it serves to get readers
into the mind-set of hearing a story and then thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the message is a powerful one, and it doesn't take
much insight or analysis to get it. That's why it has stayed on all
those bestseller lists since it came out.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
