<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-QUIZSHOWFEVER-TEX     01-13 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUIZSHOWFEVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE GAME SHOWS SILLY OR INSIDIOUS? IS THAT YOUR FINAL ANSWER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Who has an itch,
</P>
<P>
   To be filthy rich?
</P>
<P>
   Who gives a hoot,
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of loot?,
</P>
<P>
   Who longs to live,
</P>
<P>
   A life of perfect ease?
</P>
<P>
   And be swamped by necessary luxuries?
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to be a millionaire?
</P>
<P>
   I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Songwriter Cole Porter might have traded riches for romance in
his 1956 tune, but in the waking hours of the 21st century,
millionaire-dom is hot.
</P>
<P>
   With the astounding success of the ABC game show ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire,'' prime-time television has morphed into a
virtual slot machine, promising ``ka-ching'' on every channel:
``Twenty One'' on NBC, ``Winning Lines'' on CBS, and the cutthroat
``Greed'' on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The high-dollar TV quiz show has again transfixed the nation as
it did during the 1950s, when ``The $64,000 Question'' and ``Twenty
One'' were among the most popular shows on the air. But the reasons
behind the national infatuation aren't quite as clear-cut as they
were 45 years ago. And not everybody is as gleeful about game-show
mania as is ``Millionaire'' host Regis ``Is that your final
answer?'' Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   The question critics are raising: Is the quiz-show boom innocent
family entertainment or a symptom of Americans' ignorant bliss?
</P>
<P>
   The new game shows put a few twists on their '50s brethren: The
jackpots are gobs bigger (in the six- and seven-figure realm), the
sets are a whole lot hokier (think pseudo-spaceship), and the
questions are embarrassingly easier (''an insult'' is how 1956
``Twenty One'' contestant Herbert Stempel put it recently to The
Washington Post).
</P>
<P>
   But the formula works. ``Millionaire'' averaged more than 24
million viewers during its November run, and ``Greed'' is doubling
Fox's ratings on the nights it airs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen thousand square miles of the polar ice cap melted
last year and all anyone can talk about is Regis Philbin,'' says
26-year-old Adam Werbach, an environmentalist and founder of Act
Now Productions, a San Francisco media company. Act Now's Web site,
www.smashregis.com, lets users literally bowl over the celeb by
dropping a money bag on his head. Why? ``We think Regis represents
everything wrong with television today,'' Werbach writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is drunk with its new wealth,'' he adds, but ``while
our cars may be shiny and our stocks may be booming ... there is a
void in the soul of America.'' A void we are hoping ``Millionaire''
can fill vicariously, Werbach contends.
</P>
<P>
   In November, New York Times columnist Frank Rich denounced the
new quiz shows as ``the giddiest manifestations yet of a culture
that offers a pornography of wealth almost everywhere you look.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rich's opinion, ``Millionaire's'' popularity springs from the
fact that so many people feel ``left out'' of the boom. ``Instead
of getting riled, have-not and have-not-so-much Americans are
looking for their own financial scores, especially quick scores,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But can a slew of silly quiz shows really be deleterious to the
social fiber?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty innocent if somewhat moronic entertainment,''
says Robert Thompson, founding director of the Center for the Study
of Popular Television at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson believes that the success of ``Millionaire'' and its
imitators owes more to the novelty than to an upsurge in greed or
ignorance. ``There's been this long detox period where we've had so
many cop shows and lawyer shows and sitcoms,'' he says. ``You've
got to be about 46 years old or older to remember when game shows
were a viable option on prime-time television.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Thompson notes, quiz shows fit into our hectic
schedules by requiring ``absolutely zero attention,'' unlike TV
shows with a narrative. The element of competition undoubtedly
generates excitement. And, with multiple-choice questions such as
``What two colors are an Oreo cookie?'' or, on the harder side,
``Which is the capital of Australia?'', the new game shows seem to
be crowing that anyone can be a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the appeal is in (viewers thinking) `I could do that,
I knew that, I could have won a million dollars,''' says Horace
Newcomb, a professor of radio, television and film at the
University of Texas in Austin. ``But I don't see any corrupting
influence with this ... (The games shows are) not any less vapid
than any local TV news.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s quiz-show boom was America's second, following the
format's original radio debut in the '30s. But, for the average
viewer, the experience of watching the most popular post-war game
shows, ``The $64,000 Question'' and ``Twenty One,'' was anything
but an ego-booster. Take this actual ``$64,000 question,'' from
Thomas DeLong's 1991 book ``Quiz Craze: America's Infatuation with
Game Shows'' (Praeger):
</P>
<P>
   ``Name the opera Puccini never completed and the man who
finished it.'' Contestant Gino Prato, Italian immigrant and
shoe-repair man, knew both answers: ``Turandot'' and Franco Alfano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those game shows (in the '50s) were really about showing
people who appeared to have an enormous body of information, which
we have to assume they gathered through a lifetime of paying
attention and studying and acquiring knowledge,'' Thompson says.
``And oftentimes you didn't win in a single night, so there was a
sense of earning'' over an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, the new breed of game show promotes its
immediate payoffs and its egalitarian, play-at-home appeal _ which
some people find entertaining and others a little insidious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game shows are popular in the same way that some
high-school kids are popular, when they're really not threatening
to anyone,'' says Matthew Felling, media director for the Center
for Media and Public Affairs in Washington, D.C. ``These shows,
arguably made with the `duh' factor in mind, are not going to make
anybody feel stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   In Felling's opinion, the new game shows represent a dire
cultural drift. ``The quality of television is imperative to the
quality of society,'' he says. ``It sets the standard. When people
watch a show like `Jeopardy!,' they know what is expected, that the
bar is set so high in terms of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Werbach is concerned, Regis and ABC have given him and
other critical viewers a greater excuse to get involved with
television content.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is basically to start questioning what we're being
fed,'' says Werbach, who, at 23, became the youngest-ever president
of the Sierra Club. ``There's a lot of skill being wielded to make
us feel that we're having a wonderful home-family experience
watching nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1642EST &QL; 
