<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRENCH-NEW-YORK-ART-3     01-13 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-NEW-YORK-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: tin pail.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So we tried a restaurant recommended by Pierre Buhler, the
cultural counselor for the French Embassy on Fifth Avenue. His pick
was La Bonne Soupe on West 55th Street in midtown Manhattan, a busy
restaurant that seems to peak in energy around noon on Sunday and
settles down for more leisurely eating by 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Paul Picot, the owner, presides over the red-checked tables
from a spot at a small curving wooden bar, his half-glasses
dangling from his neck. He has not deserted the French custom of
mingling to chat with diners or occasionally offer a free digestif.
</P>
<P>
   La Bonne Soupe is the kind of place that attracts French Embassy
employees and the occasional Parisian celebrity. On the Sunday we
were there, the French television personality and actress Sophie
Favier attracted little attention when she took a table next to us
with her mother, 4-year-old daughter and a photographer who was
trailing her for Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   But we found our true refuge _ sans poodle, helas _ when we
stumbled into Chez Bernard at West Broadway and Grand Street in
SoHo, a bistro with exposed brick walls, an old wine press
transformed into a lamp and wine bottles numbering in the
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   It passed the test when my husband and his visiting brother
ordered the charcuterie and settled into a kind of French reverie
that is difficult to spell: mmmm-mmmm-mmmm.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Paris on the Hudson? Mais Oui
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of French experiences in New York City:
</P>
<P>
   Events
</P>
<P>
   ``EDITH PIAF: HER STORY . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . HER SONGS,'' Carnegie Hall.
Raquel Bitton sings songs of Edith Piaf. Saturday at 8 p.m.
Tickets: $17 to $75. CarnegieCharge: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   CINE-CLUB, French Institute/Alliance Francaise, 22 E. 60th St.,
Manhattan, (212) 355-6100. Weekly screenings of French films (with
English subtitles) are on Tuesdays at 12:30, 3:30, 6:30 and 9 p.m.
Next week the film will be Claude Berri's ``Lucie Aubrac'' (1997)
with Carole Bouquet and Daniel Auteuil. Tickets: $7; $5.50,
students; free to members.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY MUSIC, Town Hall, 123 W. 43rd St., Manhattan, (212)
717-9246. Christophe Rousset will conduct the New York-based
ensemble New York Collegium in a program of French music, with
three French singers, Isabelle Poulenart, Karina Gauvin and Jerome
Correas. Jan. 24 at 8 p.m. Admission: $20 and $30; 15 percent
discount for students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE AND COGNAC, French Institute/Alliance Francaise, 22 E.
60th St., Manhattan, (212) 355-6100. On Feb. 3 at 6:30 p.m. Richart
Design et Chocolat shares its sweets and Marie Brizard Wine and
Spirits provides a tasting of four Gautier cognacs. Fee: $55; $45
for members.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN CONCERTS, Church of Saint Ignatius Loyola, Park Avenue at
84th Street, (212) 288-2520. Olivier Latry, organist for the
Cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris, offers the works of Messiaen in
six performances. At 8 p.m. on Feb. 11, 15, 17, 22, 24 and 29.
Admission: $20 ($15 for students and the elderly) or $70 for all
six concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Radio and TV
</P>
<P>
   RADIO FRANCE INTERNATIONALE, WNYE 91.5 FM. Weekdays from 6:30 to
7:10 a.m., 10 p.m. to 1 a.m., and weekends from 6:30 to 9 a.m., 11
p.m. to 1 a.m.
</P>
