 NEW YORK: Night Out.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWILO, 530 W. 27th St., Chelsea, (212) 268-1600. ``Respect Is
Burning,'' featuring French electronic music and DJs, take place
every other month. There is a performance Friday night at 11 p.m.,
with the DJs Shantel at 10 p.m., the headliner Richard Dorfmeister
at midnight), Kevin Yost at 3 a.m. and Adam Scott at 5 a.m.
Admission: $25.
</P>
<P>
   LA LUNCHEONETTE, 130 10th Ave., at 18th Street, Chelsea, (212)
675-0342. A bistro whose musical performers include the singer
Nicole Renaud, from 7 to 10 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Books
</P>
<P>
   ZERO HEURE, www.00h00.com. A new electronic publisher in Paris
that e-mails books electronically in seconds. The books include
classic literature, popular French books and original works
published by Zero Heure, which is headed by the former managing
director of the French publisher Flammarion. Books in traditional
form can also be ordered, at a higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   LIBRAIRIE DE FRANCE, Rockefeller Center, 610 Fifth Ave., near
50th Street, (212)581-8810.
</P>
<P>
   Museums
</P>
<P>
   P.S. I CONTEMPORARY ART CENTER, 22-25 Jackson Ave. at 46th
Avenue, Long Island City, Queens, (718) 784-2084. ``On Your Own
Time'' by Roman Opalka (though Jan. 30) and Claude Leveque's
longterm light installation ``Stigmata '99.'' Hours: Wednesdays
through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.. Admission: $5.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF MODERN ART, 11 W. 53rd St., Manhattan, (212) 708-9400.
Its ``Modern Starts: Places'' exhibition includes ``Changing
Visions: French Landscapes 1880-1920,'' with works by Cezanne, van
Gogh, Signac and Seurat, among others. Through March 14. Also on
view is Monet's epic ``Water Lilies.'' Hours: Saturdays through
Tuesdays and on Thursdays, 10:30 a.m. to 5:15 p.m.; Fridays, 10:30
a.m. to 8:15 p.m. Admission: $10; $6.50 for students and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH INSTITUTE/ALLIANCE FRANCAISE, 22 E. 60th St., Manhattan,
(212) 355-6100. ``American Writers in Paris,'' a selection of 50
black-and-white photographs by Sophie Bassouls. Opens Friday, Jan.
14, and runs through Feb. 18. Hours: Mondays through Thursdays, 9
a.m. to 8 p.m.; Fridays, 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.; Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 2
p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants
</P>
