<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-NEW-YORK-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS ON HUDSON: IT'S FUNKY FUNKY, WITH A FRENCH TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in category `e')  
(EDS: List of events and venues at end of text.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The minimum requirement for Le Weekend New Yorkais
was about as basic as a crusty baguette.
</P>
<P>
   My French husband and I yearned for a Manhattan with a Gallic
accent _ a bistro perhaps where a petit caniche begs for sugar
cubes below a polished bar, or a brasserie where the mood is
casual, the air is more smoke than oxygen and the frites are served
with mustard and the songs of Serge Gainsbourg.
</P>
<P>
   We never found the sugar-starved poodle beside the bar. But we
did learn how to satisfy the inexplicable urge to listen daily to
``La Marseillaise,'' the French national anthem, courtesy of the
French Embassy's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend search for La Vie a New York is rather like hurtling
through a dizzying blur of Metro stops. With such a richness of
traditional and unconventional French cultural offerings, a tourist
can visit a Museum of Modern Art exhibition of Monet and Cezanne
landscapes one day and head the next to Claude Leveque's ``Stigmata
'99'' installation, a disco-inspired staircase of flickering
crimson light and mirrors at the PS 1 Contemporary Art Center in
Long Island City, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Determined Francophiles can rise at dawn to the latest Radio
France Internationale news reports from Paris on 91.5 FM and drift
to sleep to the hypnotic drone of 24-hour TV5 satellite programming
featuring French shows like ``Bouillon de Culture'' or ``Paris Chic
Choc.''
</P>
<P>
   But the freshest serenade comes from a modern-day group of
French explorers who have come to New York to disseminate the
dernier cri in European music, a quirky minimalist electronic style
that is sometimes called Le French Touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here for two years and there are so many French
people it's getting scary,'' said Mary-Noelle Dana, an expatriate
Parisian and self-described ``settler'' who organizes periodic
showcases for French musicians and disc jockeys at the Knitting
Factory in lower Manhattan's Tribeca section.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the French Touch generation that's moving in,'' she said.
``We're between 20 and 30. I think that without getting spiritual
it's a question of energy. There's a huge unemployment problem in
France, and the young generation has a hard time in the
entertainment industry. And after a while you want to stop waiting
and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Renaud, 32, moved from Paris to New York about 10 years
ago and took up the accordion and microphone to perform a mix of
retro romance songs ranging from Edith Piaf to the medieval.
Wearing hooded form-fitting gowns, she presents what she considers
a modern take on cabaret inspired by futuristic films like ``Blade
Runner'' and ``The Fifth Element.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Renaud makes a weekly circuit of small clubs with names like
the Torch Club, on the Lower East Side, or La Luncheonette, in
Chelsea. On one slow Monday night, her ethereal soprano filled the
Torch Club, a warm, uncluttered space with textured walls, soaring
ceilings and glowing sconces that is so discreet there is nothing
to identify it from the street beyond its metal doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess being away from my country I have rediscovered my
culture,'' Ms. Renaud said. ``I started the accordion about three
years ago. Arriving in New York, the natural thing was to sing
French songs, and I felt free to do it: people expected me to sing
those songs. The other advantage in being in New York is that there
were not many people doing this kind of music, and so it was easier
for me to work here. I find that there's a different energy in New
York in the sense that people tend to take more risks.''
</P>
<P>
   `It's Really Burning'
</P>
<P>
   In late November the Knitting Factory organized its second
annual French Touch Festival, a regular series supported with seed
money from the Cultural Services of the French Embassy in New York
that seeks to promote French artists in the United States. PS 1
also was a host to French disc jockeys in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   There is a private circuit of clubs that regularly feature
Parisian-style dance music, notably Twilo, a cavernous club in
Chelsea. On Friday night, Jan. 14, it will present the latest event
in a series called ``Respect Is Burning.'' The gatherings, which
take place bimonthly (the next is March 17), are an outgrowth of
the ``Respect'' parties that used to be held regularly in Paris at
the Rex Club, a techno night spot next to the opulent Grand Rex
Theater on the Right Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it `Respect Is Burning' because the music would be so
crazy that we would say `it's really burning tonight,''' said Neil
Aline, a 23-year-old Parisian expatriate who has settled in the
East Village and makes his living as a disc jockey and concert
promoter.
</P>
<P>
   Like other fans of Le French Touch music, Aline stretches for
adjectives to characterize the sound, which exports the creme of
disc jockeys, programmers and producers working in France. ``It's
house music with a really funky touch,'' said Aline. ``It's
electronic-sounding but soulful at the same time. The bottom line
is that it's house music, but house music that never sounded like
this before.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowds that come to these events at the Knitting Factory,
Twilo or Izzy Bar are a mix of Americans and French expatriates.
Performers address the audience in English, but participants
respond with cries of ``Allez! Allez!''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very curious about electronic music because they
don't have as much as we do in Europe,'' said Adele Jacques, who
arrived from Paris a few months ago to sing at clubs like the
Knitting Factory or Fez. ``The reaction has actually been pretty
good. I was very astonished because they don't understand what
we're saying, but they like the music.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Balzac, par E-Mail
</P>
<P>
   Many of the French cultural events in New York are carefully
nurtured by the French government through subsidies and aid from
the Cultural Services of the French Embassy, which amounted to
about $500,000 last year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The French Embassy helped underwrite the Knitting Factory's Le
French Touch Festival in November. And it helped bring Leveque's
``Stigmata'' to PS 1, which is also the site of ``On Your Own
Time,'' an international show that includes the work of the painter
Roman Opalka. Since 1965 Opalka has been exploring the passage of
time on large canvases painted with numbers. In December the French
Ministry of Culture and Globecast France Telecom provided the
museum with live transmissions of Opalka, who apparently has
decided to keep counting to infinity.
</P>
<P>
   The French government also supports traditional offerings, like
a series of performances in February at the Church of Saint
Ignatius de Loyola on Park Avenue by Oliver Latry, the organist for
the Cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris. It is also trying in a
low-key way to promote French literature in New York by organizing
lectures and cocktail parties for visiting authors whose new works
have been translated and published in the United States, among them
Jean-Paul Kauffmann, author of ``Black Room at Longwood,'' a
bittersweet exploration of Napoleon's final years in exile as a
prisoner of the British on the island of St. Helena.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer their French literature in French, there
are stores to satisfy the urge. A traditional choice is the
Librairie de France at Rockefeller Center, where basic children's
titles can be $20 or more. But it's also possible to buy digital
books by e-mail in minutes from Paris, where a new Internet upstart
called Zero Heure is publishing classic titles, original works and
contemporary books from other French publishers. The Web site _
www.00h00.com _ gives shoppers an easy way to test the purchasing
system with invitations to order free books. The electronic books,
ranging from about a dollar to $30, are cheaper than conventional
books, which can also be ordered from Zero Heure by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Le News Flash
</P>
<P>
   The links to Paris do not end with the Internet. Radio France
Internationale is on every morning at 6:30 on 91.5 FM, and Le
Journal de France 2 _ the daily evening news from Paris _ is
broadcast at 7 by WNYE on Channel 25. (The English subtitles
occasionally don't match the stories, but it can add to the
entertainment when a news anchor announces a breaking story while
the subtitles have her warbling '60s song lyrics.) A satellite dish
and a $10 subscription fee to TV5 USA will bring you 24 hours of
programming from French-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television also offers an assortment of French movies.
CUNY-TV on Channel 75, the station operated by the City University
of New York, is broadcasting French films with English subtitles on
Friday nights at 10 and Sunday afternoons at 3. Among the
lesser-known offerings is ``La Voie Est Libre,'' Stephane Clavier's
1998 film about a railroad employee who is laid off from his job
after 20 years only to become the main suspect in a strange hostage
crisis on a suburban railway.
</P>
<P>
   A French movie is shown several times every Tuesday at the
French Institute/Alliance Francaise, which also plans to present a
festival of short films from Jan. 24-26 grouped around themes like
youth and the bizarre. There is ``John,'' a short tale about a
Tarzan who has taken up residence in France, for example, and
``Gisele Kerozene,'' a contemporary story of a group of
``proto-punk'' witches embarked on a wild search for a magic skull.
Vive la difference.
</P>
<P>
   The Bistro Look
</P>
<P>
   For newly arrived expatriates, a circuit of informal French
bistros offer a fleeting taste of Paris. Some of the French
settlers effusively praise little restaurants like Jules in the
East Village, which often has live music or accordion brunches, and
Casimir, a bar bistro on Avenue B named for a bunny in an old
French television series.
</P>
<P>
   Casimir had the appropriate understated bistro look: exposed
brick walls, wooden cafe chairs, Charles Aznavour posters, and
anise-flavored Ricard served at the bar. My husband and I were less
impressed by a gum-chewing waitress who blew bubbles while serving
us French fries stacked inelegantly in a tin pail.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So we tried a restaurant recommended by Pierre Buhler, the
cultural counselor for the French Embassy on Fifth Avenue. His pick
was La Bonne Soupe on West 55th Street in midtown Manhattan, a busy
restaurant that seems to peak in energy around noon on Sunday and
settles down for more leisurely eating by 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Paul Picot, the owner, presides over the red-checked tables
from a spot at a small curving wooden bar, his half-glasses
dangling from his neck. He has not deserted the French custom of
mingling to chat with diners or occasionally offer a free digestif.
</P>
<P>
   La Bonne Soupe is the kind of place that attracts French Embassy
employees and the occasional Parisian celebrity. On the Sunday we
were there, the French television personality and actress Sophie
Favier attracted little attention when she took a table next to us
with her mother, 4-year-old daughter and a photographer who was
trailing her for Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   But we found our true refuge _ sans poodle, helas _ when we
stumbled into Chez Bernard at West Broadway and Grand Street in
SoHo, a bistro with exposed brick walls, an old wine press
transformed into a lamp and wine bottles numbering in the
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   It passed the test when my husband and his visiting brother
ordered the charcuterie and settled into a kind of French reverie
that is difficult to spell: mmmm-mmmm-mmmm.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Paris on the Hudson? Mais Oui
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of French experiences in New York City:
</P>
