<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-QUAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIRD WATCHERS SAY QUAIL ON DECLINE IN GOLDEN GATE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California quail, the Golden State's official
bird, are on the verge of disappearing from Golden Gate Park, where
they were once so numerous they were regarded as a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Audubon Society's annual Christmas bird count
found just 12 quail in the park, all in Strybing Arboretum's
botanical gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The quail population ``won't resuscitate unless we do something,
that's for sure,'' said Alan Hopkins, past president of the Audubon
Society chapter. ``As a viable population, it's on the verge of
disappearing. There are only three females left.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins launched a Save the Quail campaign last summer to
restore habitat where quail coveys can flourish, but the population
count declined from 40 in 1998 nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades ago, hundreds of quail made their homes in the
park, and Strybing Arboretum horticulture manager Don Mahoney
recalls that ``there was an active program to get rid of them,
because they were scratching up the gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Mahoney said, cold weather and scrub jays,
which are fond of feeding on quail chicks, have reduced the
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be tons of quail in the park; now, you just
don't see them,'' said Arthur Feinstein, executive director of the
Golden Gate Audubon Society.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein blames feral cats for the perilous state of the quail
population, a charge hotly denied by animal-loving activists, who
feed the park's cats.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein has quit arguing the point. ``That issue is a dead end
in terms of resolution,'' he said. ``It's non-winnable.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also blames poor management of flora in the park,
which has deprived quail of the brushy habitat needed to maintain a
healthy population.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the quail population is in good shape, said
Department of Fish and Game biologist Sam Blankenship. The
population decline in Golden Gate Park may be hard to arrest
because ``it's difficult for an isolated area like that to
repopulate. Quail (populations) boom and bust, and there's no ebb
and flow from other population areas.''
</P>
<P>
   California hunters bagged 500,374 quail during the staggered
hunting seasons, which run from the last week in September until
Jan. 10. The bag limit is 10 quail per day.
</P>
<P>
   Two weekends ago, 40 Save the Quail volunteers from the Audubon
Society and two local high schools pitched in to plant atriplex
(quail bush) and ceanothus in the park's arboretum. They are
creating a quail-friendly thicket where the park's remnant coveys
live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quail like some space around the thicket, so we'll have to do
summer maintenance where the thick European grasses are,'' Mahoney
said. Quail need a clear field of vision beyond their thickets,
because ``cats hang out in those tall grasses,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
