<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-AIMEE-MANN-FEAT     01-13 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AIMEE-MANN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMEE MANN HELPS `MAGNOLIA' BLOOM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critically acclaimed singer-songwriter Aimee Mann doesn't
consider herself a muckraker, and she certainly doesn't see herself
as any kind of whistle blower. Yet this perennial music-biz
insider, whose songs play a pivotal role in Paul Thomas Anderson's
widely praised film ``Magnolia,'' is a fearless soul.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of burning bridges by exposing the inner-workings of
the world's largest record companies, Mann tells how label execs
have continually tried to change her music even to the point of
refusing to release her albums. Most recently, the Golden
Globe-nominated Mann shelled out a significant amount of cash to
buy back her latest album, ``Bachelor No. 2,'' from her previous
label, Interscope Records, rather than agree to their demands to
scrap parts of it so she could write and record more radio-friendly
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons it's so frustrating dealing with people at
record companies who are trying to push you in a direction you're
not comfortable with, is that they're trying to get you to do stuff
you're not good at,'' Mann said. ``Posing for pictures and videos
and schmoozing are the things I'm least competent at.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Magnolia'' soundtrack features nine songs from Mann,
including the opening theme, a cover of Harry Nilsson's ``One.''
The first single, ``Save Me,'' was nominated last month for a
Golden Globe for best original song. ``She is the great articulator
of the biggest things we think about,'' Anderson said. ``You can
look at the movie as the perfect memento to remember the songs that
Aimee has made. Aimee is a brilliant writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann, who rose to fame with '80s pop band 'Til Tuesday, appears
Saturday in an acoustic in-store show at Borders in Santa Monica.
In a perverse way, she enjoys the challenge of performing for free
at a busy bookstore. ``Part of me gets a kick playing for people
who aren't paying much attention,'' Mann said this week. ``I mean,
I don't think those kinds of things are my favorite gigs in the
world. It's a brightly lit situation where everyone's drinking
coffee and yawning. Lilith Fair was like that _ people wandering
around looking at booths. A lot of them don't know who you are. I'm
just the soundtrack to their good times.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann's third solo album and first independent release,
``Bachelor No. 2,'' released on her own Superego label, will be
available early next month just as she goes out on tour with her
husband of two years, fellow singer-songwriter Michael Penn. Mann
says Interscope's complaints about the new disc included her choice
of a writing partner (Elvis Costello) for a track titled ``Fall of
the World's Own Optimist.'' It marks her first collaboration with
Costello since ``The Other End of the Telescope,'' which Costello
also cut, after its initial appearance on a 'Til Tuesday album.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our record back, and I'm sure Interscope could've
given us a lot more trouble about getting it back, but they didn't,
and God bless 'em,'' Mann said. ``People who want to have giant
hits at any cost, that's the place for them. If they want to make
fabulous videos and have giant hits and have people asking them
what they're wearing at the Grammys, that's perfect for them. It's
the system they belong in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been a system for people like me in a long, long
time. I was crazy to think I could find some way to make it work
for me. As it happens, I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her marriage, many of Mann's songs on ``Bachelor'' deal
with being single. ``Some of them I had already written or started
working on before we were married,'' she explained. ``But my
relationship with Michael is so unique that there are ways in which
I don't really feel like I'm in a relationship, because I've
defined `relationship' as being this sort of unwieldy, nightmarish
thing. Having a happy marriage enables you to actually get work
done, rather than being so despondent you just sit in a room for
days on end. And he's also a great help in bouncing things off of
and getting a good second opinion. It's nice have another
professional musician in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   After 'Til Tuesday disbanded, Mann released her 1993 solo debut,
``Whatever,'' (Imago) to enthusiastic reviews. Her 1996 follow-up,
the Jon Brion-produced ``I'm With Stupid'' (Geffen), was hailed in
Time as one of the ``catchiest pop albums of the year, brimming
with poised three-minute mini-masterpieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter album's Squeeze-augmented ``That's Just What You
Are'' appeared on the popular ``Melrose Place'' soundtrack album.
Mann also placed songs in ``Jerry Maguire'' (filmmaker Cameron
Crowe being among of her most ardent fans), ``Cruel Intentions''
and ``Sliding Doors.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will probably be because of Anderson's inspired use of
Mann's material in his ``Magnolia'' that the Los Angeles-based
singer-songwriter will become even better-known. Typically, Mann
downplays her part in the creation of ``Magnolia,'' a strong
contender in this movie awards season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul gave me a sense early on of how the songs would be
used,'' she said. ``But when you see the finished product, it felt
like I fooled everyone. But I don't know who I felt like I was
fooling. Maybe myself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5221 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-DISCS-REVIEWS-L     01-13 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DISCS-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD REVIEWS BY DAILY NEWS STAFF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dot Allison/``Afterglow'' (Arista)
</P>
<P>
   Ex-chanteuse of the Scottish indie trio One Dove, Allison makes
her solo debut with this ambient and ultimately unsatisfying effort
that utilizes heavy-lidded dub rhythms and highly treated,
reverb-laden vocal effects. The over-produced album, which enjoys
strong word of mouth on the street, aims for the brooding, dark and
mysterious mood of Portishead, but rarely breathes the same chilly
night air. A diverse group including Death in Vegas' Richard
Fearless, ex-Stone Roses bassist Mani and even '60s lyricist Hal
David are on board, while Allison dabbles in so many half-baked
styles that the effect becomes blurred and boring.The best moments
here are the first two tracks _ ``Colour Me,'' a sensual slice of
trip-hop with a strong chorus that would sound terrific on KROQ,
and ``Tomorrow,'' an acoustic guitar-driven number that recalls
Beth Orton's electro-folk, but is plainly not as addictive. After a
few painful listenings to the rest, Allison's overly breathy
delivery _ which sounds like she's gasping for air through a
drinking straw _ begins to grate, and it quickly becomes clear that
time is too short to bask in this particular ``Afterglow.'' 2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack/``Girl, Interrupted'' (TVT)
</P>
<P>
   If you were listening to the radio 30 years ago, chances are
you'd run into at least a couple of these cuts. The makers of this
film about mental illness capture the mood of the times well, using
nuggets from the Band, Aretha Franklin, the Mamas &AMP; the Papas, the
Chambers Brothers and Jefferson Airplane to suggest the turbulence
both inside and outside the hospital walls. The compilation opens
strong with Wilco's ``How to Fight Loneliness,'' an example of a
current band clearly influenced by what's gone before. But the bulk
of the 10 tracks here are decades-old originals, like Merrilee
Rush's lovely reading of ``Angel of the Morning.'' Before the disc
veers off into Mychael Danna's original score, the Petula Clark hit
``Downtown'' strikes an optimistic, yet oddly disorienting note. 2
1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   F.S. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Savoy Recordings''/The Johnny Otis Rhythm &AMP; Blues
Caravan (Savoy Jazz)
</P>
<P>
   This three-disc, 77-song compilation of the fabulous r&AMP;b, blues
and jazz work by pioneer bandleader (and Watts club owner) Otis has
such collaborators as Little Esther, Big Jay McNeely, Jimmy Rushing
and the Robins. Among the nine previously unissued songs are a
couple of oddities, especially the ``Hunter Hancock Theme'' from a
long-lost L.A. radio show. The rest of the collection is wonderful,
ranging over a huge chunk of what used to be called ``race music,''
from burlesque-house fave ``Harlem Nocturne'' to big hits like
``Double Crossing Blues.'' As the excellent liner notes point out,
Otis is best-known for a rock 'n' roll song, ``Willie and the Hand
Jive,'' but he had 15 Top 10 hits in just two years on the then-new
r&AMP;b charts before that song (which isn't on this collection) came
along. Give a listen to some of the great early work of one of
modern pop's undersung pioneers. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   David Bloom &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sally Timms/``Cowboy Sally's Twilight Laments ... For Lost
Buckaroos'' (Bloodshot)
</P>
<P>
   The singer from the English art punk band the Mekons has
delivered a sweet and haunting little country-western collection,
with help from cow dudes as diverse as Chicago-based Robbie Fulks
and Wilco's Jeff Tweedy. The songs range from easygoing melancholy
swing (``Dreaming Cowboy'') to oddly upbeat apocalyptic shuffle
(``Dark Sun''), with big hat tips to traditions of all kinds
(Johnny Cash's ``Cry Cry Cry''to the nortena ``Cancion Para Mi
Padre'') in between. Through it all, Timms' ethereal, yet precise
vocals give every song a warm, mescal-and-honey resonance. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   Bob Strauss &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack/``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' (Sony Classical)
</P>
<P>
   As modern-day soundtracks go, this is both an honorable and an
interesting one, with music actually used in the film instead of
conjured up as a marketing add-on. It's wonderfully diverse and
atmospheric, with classic '50s jazz tracks from Charlie Parker,
Miles Davis and Dizzy Gillespie; more recent work of the same
period sensibility by the Guy Barker International Quintet;
luscious orchestral scoring from Gabriel Yared; and wonderful slow
ballads by Sinead O'Connor and John Martyn, whose ``You Don't Know
What Love Is'' is his second amazing cover release in four months
(see KCRW-FM's ``Morning Becomes Eclectic'' album). The one
moderately regrettable inclusion, done purely for marketing
purposes: actor Matt Damon's flat-toned ``My Funny Valentine.'' He
may be as gorgeous and cool as a would-be Chet Baker, but that
doesn't mean Damon can sing like that lost great one. Couldn't they
have lip-synched in the original? Or !ital!something!off!?
Otherwise, a stellar collection. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   D.B. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack/``Sweet and Lowdown'' (Sony Classical)
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's latest, a much-lauded paean to a boorish boho of
Django Reinhardt-ian talent, results in an equally fine collection
of Depression-era jazz sounds (``Sweet Georgia Brown,'' ``All of
Me'') performed by the Dick Hyman Group, with fine guitar work by
Howard Alden (and rhythm guitar by Bucky Pizzarelli). Tracks by
Sidney Bechet and Noble Sissle's Swingsters and Bunny Berigan's
orchestra are also featured on this delightful, playful compilation
of toodle-oo jazz perfect for bemused Sunday afternoons filled with
light. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   D.B. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Jarrett/``The Melody at Night, With You'' (ECM)
</P>
<P>
   It's somehow appropriate to begin the new year with a word about
one of the finest albums produced in 1999. This is a change-up from
Jarrett, a pianist known best for breakneck improvisational skills
and freewheeling phrasing. Here, in a gorgeous program of
standards, Jarrett redefines himself with romantic, elegant and
spare playing, creating a timeless work of beauty that owes as much
to classical tradition as it does to jazz. It's as if Jarrett,
recently recovered from a bout with chronic fatigue syndrome,
decided to pause and reflect and, in doing so, finds as much
meaning in silences as he ever did in his rapturous roars. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Whipp &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur Harden and John Coltrane/``The Complete Savoy Sessions''
(Savoy Jazz) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Adderley Brothers/``The Summer of '55'' (Savoy Jazz)
</P>
<P>
   Savoy Jazz, courtesy of Atlantic Records, has one of the best
jazz reissue programs going right now, and these titles are but two
of several excellent albums finding their way into record stores.
The Harden/Coltrane sessions (3 stars), recorded over two dates in
1958, have been reissued in a number of different forms over the
years; here they find a definitive, two-disc compilation. Harden, a
talented trumpeter who more or less disappeared off the face of the
Earth after these sessions, wrote most of the material and finds
wonderful support from a blooming Coltrane, as well as pianist
Tommy Flanagan and trombonist Curtis Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   The Adderley Brothers dates (3 1/2 stars) likewise have been
available here and there over the years, having been originally
issued as an album from drummer Kenny Clarke. The two-disc set
marks the recording debut of famed alto great Cannonball Adderley
and brother Nat (who recently passed away), as well as trumpeter
Donald Byrd. The Adderleys arrived in New York, their talents
already fully formed, and these excellent, hard-blowing 1955
sessions show them swinging in high style with Byrd and Clarke,
pianist Horace Silver and bassist Paul Chambers. The music is every
bit as good as the stellar lineup.
</P>
<P>
   G.W. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
