</P>
<P>
   Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack/``Girl, Interrupted'' (TVT)
</P>
<P>
   If you were listening to the radio 30 years ago, chances are
you'd run into at least a couple of these cuts. The makers of this
film about mental illness capture the mood of the times well, using
nuggets from the Band, Aretha Franklin, the Mamas &AMP; the Papas, the
Chambers Brothers and Jefferson Airplane to suggest the turbulence
both inside and outside the hospital walls. The compilation opens
strong with Wilco's ``How to Fight Loneliness,'' an example of a
current band clearly influenced by what's gone before. But the bulk
of the 10 tracks here are decades-old originals, like Merrilee
Rush's lovely reading of ``Angel of the Morning.'' Before the disc
veers off into Mychael Danna's original score, the Petula Clark hit
``Downtown'' strikes an optimistic, yet oddly disorienting note. 2
1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   F.S. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Savoy Recordings''/The Johnny Otis Rhythm &AMP; Blues
Caravan (Savoy Jazz)
</P>
<P>
   This three-disc, 77-song compilation of the fabulous r&AMP;b, blues
and jazz work by pioneer bandleader (and Watts club owner) Otis has
such collaborators as Little Esther, Big Jay McNeely, Jimmy Rushing
and the Robins. Among the nine previously unissued songs are a
couple of oddities, especially the ``Hunter Hancock Theme'' from a
long-lost L.A. radio show. The rest of the collection is wonderful,
ranging over a huge chunk of what used to be called ``race music,''
from burlesque-house fave ``Harlem Nocturne'' to big hits like
``Double Crossing Blues.'' As the excellent liner notes point out,
Otis is best-known for a rock 'n' roll song, ``Willie and the Hand
Jive,'' but he had 15 Top 10 hits in just two years on the then-new
r&AMP;b charts before that song (which isn't on this collection) came
along. Give a listen to some of the great early work of one of
modern pop's undersung pioneers. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   David Bloom &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sally Timms/``Cowboy Sally's Twilight Laments ... For Lost
Buckaroos'' (Bloodshot)
</P>
<P>
   The singer from the English art punk band the Mekons has
delivered a sweet and haunting little country-western collection,
with help from cow dudes as diverse as Chicago-based Robbie Fulks
and Wilco's Jeff Tweedy. The songs range from easygoing melancholy
swing (``Dreaming Cowboy'') to oddly upbeat apocalyptic shuffle
(``Dark Sun''), with big hat tips to traditions of all kinds
(Johnny Cash's ``Cry Cry Cry''to the nortena ``Cancion Para Mi
Padre'') in between. Through it all, Timms' ethereal, yet precise
vocals give every song a warm, mescal-and-honey resonance. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   Bob Strauss &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack/``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' (Sony Classical)
</P>
<P>
   As modern-day soundtracks go, this is both an honorable and an
interesting one, with music actually used in the film instead of
conjured up as a marketing add-on. It's wonderfully diverse and
atmospheric, with classic '50s jazz tracks from Charlie Parker,
Miles Davis and Dizzy Gillespie; more recent work of the same
period sensibility by the Guy Barker International Quintet;
luscious orchestral scoring from Gabriel Yared; and wonderful slow
ballads by Sinead O'Connor and John Martyn, whose ``You Don't Know
What Love Is'' is his second amazing cover release in four months
(see KCRW-FM's ``Morning Becomes Eclectic'' album). The one
moderately regrettable inclusion, done purely for marketing
purposes: actor Matt Damon's flat-toned ``My Funny Valentine.'' He
may be as gorgeous and cool as a would-be Chet Baker, but that
doesn't mean Damon can sing like that lost great one. Couldn't they
have lip-synched in the original? Or !ital!something!off!?
Otherwise, a stellar collection. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   D.B. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack/``Sweet and Lowdown'' (Sony Classical)
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's latest, a much-lauded paean to a boorish boho of
Django Reinhardt-ian talent, results in an equally fine collection
of Depression-era jazz sounds (``Sweet Georgia Brown,'' ``All of
Me'') performed by the Dick Hyman Group, with fine guitar work by
Howard Alden (and rhythm guitar by Bucky Pizzarelli). Tracks by
Sidney Bechet and Noble Sissle's Swingsters and Bunny Berigan's
orchestra are also featured on this delightful, playful compilation
of toodle-oo jazz perfect for bemused Sunday afternoons filled with
light. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   D.B. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Jarrett/``The Melody at Night, With You'' (ECM)
</P>
<P>
   It's somehow appropriate to begin the new year with a word about
one of the finest albums produced in 1999. This is a change-up from
Jarrett, a pianist known best for breakneck improvisational skills
and freewheeling phrasing. Here, in a gorgeous program of
standards, Jarrett redefines himself with romantic, elegant and
spare playing, creating a timeless work of beauty that owes as much
to classical tradition as it does to jazz. It's as if Jarrett,
recently recovered from a bout with chronic fatigue syndrome,
decided to pause and reflect and, in doing so, finds as much
meaning in silences as he ever did in his rapturous roars. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Whipp &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur Harden and John Coltrane/``The Complete Savoy Sessions''
(Savoy Jazz) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Adderley Brothers/``The Summer of '55'' (Savoy Jazz)
</P>
<P>
   Savoy Jazz, courtesy of Atlantic Records, has one of the best
jazz reissue programs going right now, and these titles are but two
of several excellent albums finding their way into record stores.
The Harden/Coltrane sessions (3 stars), recorded over two dates in
1958, have been reissued in a number of different forms over the
years; here they find a definitive, two-disc compilation. Harden, a
talented trumpeter who more or less disappeared off the face of the
Earth after these sessions, wrote most of the material and finds
wonderful support from a blooming Coltrane, as well as pianist
Tommy Flanagan and trombonist Curtis Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   The Adderley Brothers dates (3 1/2 stars) likewise have been
available here and there over the years, having been originally
issued as an album from drummer Kenny Clarke. The two-disc set
marks the recording debut of famed alto great Cannonball Adderley
and brother Nat (who recently passed away), as well as trumpeter
Donald Byrd. The Adderleys arrived in New York, their talents
already fully formed, and these excellent, hard-blowing 1955
sessions show them swinging in high style with Byrd and Clarke,
pianist Horace Silver and bassist Paul Chambers. The music is every
bit as good as the stellar lineup.
</P>
<P>
   G.W. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1655EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
