<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT &LR;      01-13 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, Jan. 14. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Argun) _ The Russian military insists it has
taken back this Chechen town. But on Thursday Russian soldiers
nervously scanned the rooftops and windows of Argun's battered
buildings as they sought to keep order. ``There are snipers
around,'' a Russian officer called out. ``Take care.'' Set in the
Chechen lowlands, Argun was taken by the Russian military in early
December. Today, however, it has become a salient example of how
hard it may be for Russia to take Chechnya and keep it. All across
Chechnya, Russian troops tried to tighten their grip over the swath
of territory ``liberated'' by Russian forces. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   HARRODS-PHILIP (London) _ Buckingham Palace announced Thursday
that it was withdrawing the royal warrant awarded by Prince Philip,
the Duke of Edinburgh, to Harrods, the London department store that
is owned by Mohamed al-Fayed. A palace spokesman said the decision
was based on a falloff in business from the Duke, who originally
granted the honor in 1956. He made no reference to the fact that
six weeks ago Fayed called the prince a Nazi sympathizer and
accused him of masterminding a plot with the British security
services that resulted in the 1997 Paris car crash that killed
Diana, Princess of Wales, and her companion, his son, Emad Mohamed
al-Fayed, known as Dodi. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICH-BOY-SENTENCED (Pontiac, Mich.) _ In an unexpected verdict,
a state judge ruled here Thursday that the youngest American ever
charged and convicted as an adult of murder will serve a seven-year
sentence at a maximum-security juvenile detention center and then
be released. The judge, rejecting prosecutors' requests that the
boy be sentenced to additional time in an adult prison after
serving time in juvenile detention, rebuked a system that he said
had gone too far in punishing juveniles. His sentencing also bucked
a trend in which, increasingly, juveniles charged with violent
crimes have been sentenced as adults. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-KOCH-WATER (Washington) _ Koch Industries, an oil pipeline
company, found the weak points in its pipes the easy way, the
government said Wednesday. It simply waited for the pipelines to
break and spill oil, part of a pattern of negligence that resulted
Thursday in the biggest civil fine ever paid for a company for
environmental violations. The EPA said the company, based in
Wichita, Kan., had agreed to pay a $30 million penalty for more
than 300 separate spills of crude oil, gasoline and other oil
products between 1990 and 1997. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-OUTLOOK (Perry, Iowa) _ Over the years, the Iowa caucuses
have made some presidential candidates (like Jimmy Carter) and
unmade others (like Edward M. Kennedy). But this time, they have
seemed like a sideshow, and a poorly attended one at that, to the
main event in New Hampshire. That may be changing. With only 10
days left until Jan. 24, when tens of thousands of Iowans will
assemble in living rooms, clubs and school halls to declare their
preferences, two well-funded, well-organized underdogs, Bill
Bradley and Steve Forbes, have accelerated their efforts. If not to
defeat their respective rivals, Al Gore and George W. Bush, they
hope to come very close _ close enough to give them a lift as they
move to New Hampshire, whose critical primary takes place only
eight days later on Feb. 1. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-MERGER (New York) _ In an abrupt change of heart,
executives at the drug manufacturer Warner-Lambert Co. said
Thursday they are reconsidering a marriage proposal made by Pfizer
Inc., a suitor and rival they have been brawling with for two
months. The decision stands to leave Warner-Lambert's first choice
as a merger partner, American Home Products, alone again at the
altar for a third time in two years. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB-USTRUST (New York) _ Charles Schwab, a company built on
cheap stock trades for all, is acquiring the U.S. Trust Corp., a
private bank that caters to the wealthiest 1 percent of Americans,
for $2.7 billion in stock. The deal, if completed, would complete
Schwab's transformation from a discount brokerage into a
full-service firm that allows some investors to manage their money
on their own while offering personalized investment advice to those
willing to pay for it. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   BP-ARCO (Undated) _ BP Amoco breaks off talks with regulators,
setting up a likely showdown in court. The company says it will
give the Federal Trade Commission notice that it plans to close the
purchase of ARCO within 20 days. The FTC then can either allow the
buyout to be completed or go to court to block it. By Richard A.
Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-MINORITIES (Undated) _ For the first time, the
proportion of AIDS cases among black and Hispanic gay men exceeds
those among white gay men, federal health officials reported
Thursday. One quarter of the black men who said they got infected
from sex with other men do not identify themselves as homosexual or
bisexual, which often means they do not consider themselves, other
sexual partners or their children at risk, the CDC research found.
By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLD-BLACKHOLES (Undated) _ New x-ray observations of deep
space have found what appear to be black holes that predate the
formation of galaxies. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
