<SLUG> BC-ASTRONOMY-BLACKHOLES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK HOLES MAY LURK IN SPACE NEAR EARTH
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A newly discovered black hole floats alone and
invisible in a dark region of the Milky Way a few thousand light
years from the Earth, astronomers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Others probably await discovery much closer to this planet, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The newly found black hole, probably a relic of an exploding
star, is only about 12 miles in diameter and is several thousand
light years from the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is not chewing up nearby stars or interstellar dust,
it is truly unseeable, David Bennett of the University of Notre
Dame said at the annual meeting here of the American Astronomical
Society. Like all black holes, it is so dense that nothing, not
even light, X-rays or other radiation, can escape its gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Previously discovered black holes, while not visible themselves,
can be easily identified by the glow of radiation from dust and
stars that heat up as they fall into the holes' gravitational
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Some have companion stars, and others, known as ``supermassive''
black holes because they contain matter equivalent to hundreds of
millions or even a few billion suns, chew up stars and dust at the
centers of galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   But the isolated _ or ``naked'' black hole _ drifts through an
area of the galaxy where little or no matter is available to be
sucked in, Bennett said. Therefore, it is invisible.
</P>
<P>
   He and other astronomers said they located the Milky Way black
hole by observing the way its gravity distorted light from a star
passing behind it from the Earth, a technique known as
microlensing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results suggest that black holes are common and that
many massive but normal stars end their lives as black holes,''
Bennett said. He said similar objects may lurk in dark regions
closer to the Earth, within about 100 light years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The number of identified ``supermassive'' black holes in the
central bulges of elliptical galaxies like the Milky Way rose to 20
Thursday when astronomers reported finding three new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Richstone, leader of a team that has been conducting a
systematic search for central holes in the galaxies, said the three
new holes appear to have masses ranging from 50 million to 100
million suns.
</P>
<P>
   He said the mass was calculated by measuring the speed with
which nearby stars orbit the black holes and determining the
gravity necessary to hold the stars in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the more than 1,600 astronomers attending the
conference have been studying black holes, the first discoveries to
be reported from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's new Chandra X-ray Observatory included two new
kinds of objects billions of light years from the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra, which is 50 to 100 times more sensitive than any
previous X-ray telescope, discovered galaxies that ``shine''
brightly in X-rays but do not emit visible light, said NASA
astronomer Richard Mushotzky.
</P>
<P>
   These objects are being called ``veiled galactic nuclei,'' and
there may be tens of millions of them in the universe. The X-rays
they emit appear to come from black holes at their centers.
</P>
<P>
   Another class of hitherto undetected objects were described as
``ultra-faint galaxies'' because they also release little or no
optical light, either because it is absorbed by dust surrounding
them or because they are so far away, Mushotzky said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
