<HEADER>
A5233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MANATEE14-COX     01-13 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANATEE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS SUE TO ENFORCE MANATEE PROTECTIONS
 &HT;    530&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the manatee on the verge of extinction, a
coalition of environmental groups filed suits Thursday here and in
Florida demanding that laws be enforced to protect the endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
   The suits accused the Florida and federal governments of failing
to restrict and regulate the burgeoning pleasure boat traffic in
waters where manatees live, feed and breed.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 2,400 manatees, sometimes known as ``sea
cows,'' frequenting the coastal waters of the Gulf of Mexico and
the southeastern seaboard, although there have been reports of
manatees as far north as Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Last year 268 manatees were known to have died, of which 105
were killed as a result of human activity, said Patrick Rose,
director of government relations for the Save the Manatee Club.
That included 82 deaths caused by watercraft, the highest number
ever recorded in one year
</P>
<P>
   The suits seek to force federal and state agencies to put more
law enforcement officers on manatee waterways, establish more
manatee sanctuaries and no-boating areas, and suspend coastal
development in manatee areas until local governments adopt
comprehensive manatee protections.
</P>
<P>
   The Save the Manatee Club, the lead group of 18 organizations
and three individuals bringing the suits, was founded in 1981 by
singer Jimmy Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the 728 manatees killed by human activity in the 11
years since the Florida Cabinet unanimously adopted a tough manatee
protection program, Rose said, ``most of these deaths could have
been prevented if the agencies had had the will to fully implement
and adequately enforce the necessary protection measures. ``
</P>
<P>
   Manatees, which swim just below the surface of the water, are
difficult to spot by boaters, particularly at high speeds. The
impact from propeller blades leave most manatees with painful
gashes and kills many.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is that manatees and people like the same places
in Florida, and this mutual preference has led to ever-increasing
competition for space,'' said Naomi A. Rose, a marine mammal
scientist for the Humane Society of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who live and visit Florida have to make a decision.
Do they want ever-increasing numbers of boat slips and boats on the
water, at the expense of manatees and Florida's natural heritage?
Or do they want to protect the coastal habitats in Florida that
attract both manatees and people?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Cabbage, spokesman for the Florida Fish and Wildlife
Conservation Commission, said his agency was disappointed that
suits had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it would have been more productive to launch a
cooperative effort to protect and preserve manatees. We feel the
lawsuit will divert resources from conservation of manatees to ...
litigation,'' Cabbage said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the commission enacted new speed zones last month in
Lee County, which has the state's second highest manatee
population, Cabbage said the agency is committed to protecting the
species.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the federal Fish and Wildlife Service said her
agency had not seen the lawsuit and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Eric Glitzenstein, lead attorney for the environmental groups,
said agencies responsible for approving permits for boat docks,
marinas and other coast developments have violated the intent of
the federal Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies have evaluated each permit application individually
to determine whether that one project could lead to the extinction
of the manatee species, Glitzenstein said. The agencies should be
considering the cumulative affect of approving each project, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration, whatever its record may be on other
environmental issues, has had a tepid and timid approach to the
Endangered Species Act,'' he said. ``The manatee is literally dying
the death of a thousand cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
