<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEW-YORK-LIGHT-ART-2T     01-13 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORK-LIGHT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLOTTING YOUR WINTER DAYS TO GATHER THE LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, Joe, the man I lived with, suggested
that we outfit our apartment with a light especially created to
combat the winter blues. Seasonal affective disorder is its quaint
moniker. In fact, the condition is nothing more than a hunger for
daylight during the darkest days of winter.
</P>
<P>
   I vetoed the proposal. Call me a troglodyte. But what I wanted
was not to sit under 10,000 lux of white light to trick my brain
into believing it was spring. I wanted us to soak up the real
stuff, the unadorned light of the New York Harbor at sunset, say,
or the slow illumination of the city on a Sunday morning. We rarely
could make it. The light always faded too fast. There was always
too much work.
</P>
<P>
   Joe isn't here anymore. He went hiking up a mountain one day
last summer. It is believed that he slipped and fell in the woods.
Bloodhounds and rescue teams were sent for him. But the forest is
so dark and dense, his body has yet to be found.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, with unusual deliberation, I have taken to soaking
up the light alone, or mostly alone. I plot my days to squeeze in a
morning ride on the D subway train heading west across the
Manhattan Bridge. Early most Fridays, I walk through Prospect Park
in Brooklyn with a friend, sometimes after the rain has left a
carpet of leaves shiny black and treacherous. I troll for outings
that promise birds and sunsets on Jamaica Bay in Queens. I bundle
up for lunchtime sprints around Bryant Park in midtown Manhattan to
watch how the windows of the New York Public Library spit out the
sun's reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Unwittingly, I have turned into a student of light. The August
light that envelopes the beaten-down old streets of Red Hook, I
have learned, is more melancholy than the morning light during
lilac season in the Brooklyn Botanic Garden. The sun sparkling on
the crown of the Chrysler building is whimsical, like a woman
dressed for a party at high noon. The Chinese Scholars Garden on
Staten Island is perfect in late mornings in the fall; too bad it's
closed from January until spring, for the rock sculpture and
latticed windows would make a perfect canvas for the quick movement
of the sun in winter. The fluorescent light of the first snowfall
is, of course, best seen in a park _ in my mind, over the lake on
the southern edge of Prospect Park.
</P>
<P>
   Light regulates some of our most elemental functions. It enters
the retina and courses straight to the body clock, the ticking of
which controls everything from body temperature to cardiovascular
rates to the secretion of hormones. It isn't clear exactly why, but
disruption to those circadian rhythms _ pretending that it's July,
when in fact the nights last 14{ hours _ appears to provoke the
winter doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to intense light produces rapid changes to the body
clock, which is why scientists and entrepreneurs have developed
ingenious light contraptions for winter woes. You can bask under a
light box for a half-hour first thing each morning. Someone has
invented a cap with bulbs under the visor. There's even a dawn
simulator that sends low intensity light through closed eyelids;
you don't have to be awake to enjoy its benefits. Of course, the
more luxurious option is to make like a bear and hibernate.
</P>
<P>
   I keep a mental log of light spots. I ask friends for their
favorites. One suggests a corner on the west end of Tompkins Square
Park in the East Village, another a square in Chinatown where old
people go for tai chi at dawn. Someone else proposes lunch on a
bench in Battery Park. Another swears by a shore front park on the
Hudson, way up where Manhattan kisses the Bronx. The ferry to
Staten Island is a recurring favorite. The writer Joseph Mitchell
talks of the ``smoky river-bank dawn'' by the Fulton Fish Market in
Lower Manhattan as having the power to elate him.
</P>
<P>
   The excursions that follow were culled from those remembrances.
Consider it a guide in the hunt for light in the city.
</P>
<P>
   It should be said plainly that there is no substitute for the
light-seeking strategies of birds and butterflies: to spend the
winter in the warmer latitudes. Nothing here can approximate the
warmth of the sun on a December afternoon, hiking up a hill
overlooking Los Angeles. For those of us who must survive yet
another winter in New York, certain deliberate excursions must be
undertaken: getting up early, slipping out of the harsh glare of
office lights, even if only for a few minutes every day, devoting a
day off to seeking out the light.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, there's a simple reward: the chance to witness how
the 5 o'clock hour turns from black to purple and rejoice when it
becomes golden by May. The next two months can be brutal, but the
winter solstice has passed, and the days grow longer from now on.
</P>
<P>
   The D Train
</P>
<P>
   Mammals often sleep longer in winter. Still, on many winter
mornings many of us feel only half-awake and lethargic, as big and
slow as a bear. For these mornings, there's the D train from
Brooklyn to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it leaves the last stop in Brooklyn, Dekalb Avenue, the
D train climbs onto the elevated tracks on the Manhattan Bridge and
daylight washes in. I prefer facing north. Sunny mornings offer the
best panoramas. A shaft of light falls on one side of a tall
building in the industrial forest known as Down Under the Manhattan
Bridge Overpass, or Dumbo. Then gray-green water and a platinum eel
slide across the Williamsburg Bridge, probably the J, M or Z train
heading to Bushwick. As the D train approaches the Manhattan
anchorage, you spot an orange shopping cart next to a white Chinese
laundry van. From the train window you see a blur of fabric and
fast hands in the windows of a garment factory, then a rooftop
puckishly covered in graffiti. The train descends into the dark
after that. By the time it makes its next stop, at Grand Street, I
am a little more alert and back to reading the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Light
</P>
<P>
   A reminder from a friend who is a keen observer of such things:
in a city, the light on a narrow street is different from the light
on a wide boulevard; the light on one block can be completely
different from the light on the next, depending on the hue of the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Early on a Sunday morning, the brightly painted fire escapes on
the back of the Puck Building turn the tight alley of Mulberry
Street into a daring canvas of blue on terra cotta. To the east,
the narrow paths of the East Village are shaded by rows of upscale
tenements. At 10 a.m. the postage stamp of a park on the corner of
East Eighth Street and Avenue C is half lighted. Along one side, a
row of willow trees is the color of corn, not the wispy green of a
weeping willow in summer. Their yellow branches spill over the
sidewalk, turning the crisp early morning sunshine golden.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east still, at the East River Park, the light is
entirely different _ unobstructed, with the river as its mirror.
Standing here, near the Sixth Street footbridge over FDR Drive,
one's sense of scale can get completely tweaked. The Williamsburg
Bridge looms just to the south: you can see its every industrial
muscle and bone. The trees, when they are winter bare, are a row of
gnarled limbs, like dancers frozen in difficult poses.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica Bay
</P>
<P>
   Joe was a birder. When he disappeared, he was probably looking
for birds. He took his binoculars with him. I spent five years as
his reluctant birding partner. My job was to flip through bird
books, help identify whatever winged creature he thought he saw and
keep a record of it. Yellow warbler _ Cape May, N.J., 1996; scarlet
ibis _ Trinidad, 1997, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   So when a group of urban environmentalists announced a boat ride
at the end of the fall migration season through Jamaica Bay, that
marshy terrain oddly sandwiched between the towering housing
projects of the Rockaways and the runways of Kennedy Airport, it
caught my attention.
</P>
<P>
   Boat rides here are hard to come by, especially in winter, but
the shores of Jamaica Bay, whether from the trails near the
Wildlife Refuge Center or the sliver of the Rockaway Peninsula
called Bayswater Park, are perfect for midday walks. A colleague
once observed that the view of the Manhattan skyline from Queens is
like the inverse of the famous Manhattan-centric Saul Steinberg
cartoon. Nowhere is this more true than from the shores of Jamaica
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica Bay, with its cluster of tiny islands, is a rich
ecosystem. Some of the islands are covered with tall, marsh grasses
whose nutritious detritus is sustenance for the fish below; if you
squint into the sun, they look like wheat fields in water. On the
banks of Bayswater Park grow pines that resemble the gnarled
Monterey pine of the California coast. Hundreds of thousands of
birds, some 300 species, use these islands on their way south and
back again.
</P>
<P>
   A few birds stick around for the winter. The peregrine falcon,
when it chooses to stay, builds a nest on top of the southern tower
of the Gil Hodges Memorial Bridge, the westernmost bridge to the
Rockaways. We didn't see one on the afternoon of the boat ride. But
a flock of laughing gulls, shiny white in the buttery late
afternoon light, cruised by. A nearly extinct species of goose,
distinguished by its bright white rump, had arrived from the Arctic
tundra. A family of cormorants, their black bodies shiny and wet,
sat on a patch of sandy beach, flailing their wings for maximum
exposure to the sun. Just behind, a jumbo jet cruised down a
runway, part of another kind of migration.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hook
</P>
<P>
   Red Hook has a paucity of many modern conveniences _ banks,
restaurants, a subway stop closer than a mile away. Tall housing
projects dominate the skyline, and the Brooklyn neighborhood has
suffered from years of drugs, joblessness and official neglect.
What Red Hook has in abundant supply is light, some of the most
glorious light anywhere in the city. Painters and photographers
have long sung its praises.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon light is Red Hook's treasure, and its best vista is
the broken-down far end of the Beard Street Pier. There's something
strangely anachronistic about this place, which is probably why
sunset in Red Hook is among the most melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   If you stare west, you can watch the sun go down over the barges
that still troll New York Harbor. Turning to the north, you see the
modern skyscrapers of lower Manhattan. Behind you in this corner of
Red Hook are red-brick warehouses from centuries past glowing as if
on fire at 4 o'clock. Some date to the Civil War era, when they
were apparently used by the Union army to store munitions. There's
an old Brooklyn trolley car parked off to the side, scrubbed clean
by the purveyors of Brooklyn nostalgia. Its destination: Ebbets
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Spuyten Duyvil
</P>
<P>
   A friend, a child of the Bronx, suggested Spuyten Duyvil Shore
Front Park, an unadorned strip of green tucked under the Henry
Hudson Bridge in the northwest Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   In Dutch, the phrase means roughly, ``spouting devil,''
according to Webster's New World Dictionary. The Encyclopedia of
New York suggests that it may be a corruption of a Dutch phrase
meaning ``in spite of the devil.'' Spuyten Duyvil refers both to a
narrow tidal waterway connecting the Harlem and Hudson Rivers and
to the adjacent neighborhood of steep, undulating streets.
</P>
<P>
   On a gloomy Sunday afternoon, the light in Spuyten Duyvil seems
eerie, otherworldly. Just overhead is the blue underbelly of the
Henry Hudson Bridge, linking upper Manhattan and the Riverdale
section of the Bronx. Like a child's toy, another silver-colored
railroad bridge lies just to the west, its cheek so close to the
water that it must swing open every time a riverboat wants to pass.
Across the Hudson River rise the Palisades, now shorn of foliage.
And above that, the setting sun is a back light to a thick
gathering of clouds.
</P>
<P>
   My friend remembers going there before the park was fixed up in
1994, when it was more woody than it is now, and watching icebergs
course down the river. She suspects the presence of ghosts. She
says she imagines it as the setting of a Nordic fairy tale, a place
to be alone in the fjords.
</P>
<P>
   Like many places in the city, the Spuyten Duyvil park feels as
if it isn't of the city at all. For those of us who feel safer in
familiar urban climes, all you need do is climb back up the hill
and crane back your neck. The familiar red and gray towers of the
Bronx are right there.
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that the easiest way to get to the park is to ride
Metro North: a small, old-fashioned station sits at the edge of the
Hudson. It may be the best place from which to catch the end-of-day
light.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
