<SLUG> BC-FBC-SHRINE-BOWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE SHRINE BOWL LURES SPURRIER BACK TO BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN SHEA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Steve Spurrier is still playing in John
Brodie's shadow, at least when the former quarterbacks hit the golf
course in various celebrity tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely beat him, that's for sure,'' Spurrier said. ``Well,
I've been beating him lately, but that's because he gives me six
shots every time we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Brodie was the main man in the 49ers' huddle in the '60s
and '70s, he's the superior golfer now. Of course, it helps that
Brodie has made a second career of golf, competing on the PGA
Seniors Tour and spending every available minute working on his
putting game.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to coaching college football, however, Spurrier is
in a class of his own. He was the winningest coach in the '90s, and
his Florida Gators won the 1996 national championship. The school
had a so-so program before Spurrier arrived, and now it's a
perennial power.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Spurrier is in the Bay Area for the first time in six
years to coach the East squad in Saturday's Shrine Bowl at Stanford
Stadium. Last time he was here, 1994, was the last time he was a
Shrine coach.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after Tuesday's practice, Spurrier suggested
that all those years backing up Brodie weren't necessarily a
nuisance, as it seemed at the time. In fact, they had a lot to do
with the success he's achieved as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe because I watched the game from the sidelines a whole
bunch, it helped me as far as calling the plays,'' Spurrier said.
``Maybe I learned more about what was going on, hopefully a little
better than a lot of people who stand on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you're a player, you want to play. But I sort
of look back now and am thankful I didn't play a lot because of the
injury factor and all that. I'm in good health. No concussions, no
serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Todd, the old Jets quarterback, once told me, `If I
ever come back in a second life, I want to be a backup
quarterback.' He was right. The fans love you. You don't get hit.
You don't get hurt. You feel good when the game's over. And you
still get paid.''
</P>
<P>
   And you just may go on to boast the best winning percentage in
the history of the Southeastern Conference. Spurrier is the only
major college coach in the 20th century to win more than 90 games
in his first nine years at a school.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Spurrier is coming off his most disappointing
season, one that began 9-1 and ended with three straight losses,
including a 37-34 downer to Michigan State in the Citrus Bowl. His
team finished 12th in the final ranking, falling from the top 10
for the first time since 1990 and failing to win 10 games for the
first time since '92.
</P>
<P>
   Is it finally time for Spurrier to accept an NFL offer and move
to the next level? Not a chance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our last three games, so I don't know if anyone wants
me anyway,'' he said with a smile. ``The thing is, I think most NFL
people realize what a wonderful situation I have in Florida. It's
my alma mater, and I really enjoy living in Florida. I've got too
good a job to look for another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the football team is going way downhill. We were
competitive. Three of our four losses, we were ahead in the second
half, but we couldn't quite hold the lead or score when we had
to.''
</P>
<P>
   For Spurrier's East squad, he brought along two Gators,
quarterback Doug Johnson and tackle Cooper Carlisle. The other East
quarterback is Michigan's Tom Brady.
</P>
<P>
   The West's quarterbacks are Stanford's Todd Husak and Arizona's
Keith Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the QB who endured Florida's three straight losses,
said playing for Spurrier is ``challenging _ he's a perfectionist.
He's got a great offense, a fun offense. He really opens it up. We
lost our last three games, and playing in the Shrine Bowl is a
chance for us to go out a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier said he certainly wants to win on Saturday, but he
understands the motive for many seniors is to show their worth for
NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Spurrier is enjoying his rare visit to the Bay Area.
He has played golf with his son, Steve Jr. _ a receivers coach at
Oklahoma _ and introduced him to Fisherman's Wharf and the cable
cars.
</P>
<P>
   He dined with Steve Mariucci and the 49ers' brass and plans to
spend Thursday evening with several old 49er teammates, including
Frank Nunley, Larry Shreiber, Tommy Hart, Cas Banaszek and Len
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   Brodie is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun trip,'' said Spurrier, the 49ers' top draft pick in
1967 after he won the Heisman Trophy at Florida. ``I looked forward
to coming out here. I didn't play a whole bunch when I was here,
but I really enjoyed the area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
