<HEADLINE>
ON STAGE AND OFF: LONDON'S `ROSE' LIKELY FOR SPRING  
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lincoln Center Theater is in final negotiations with
the Royal National Theater in London to bring Martin Sherman's
one-woman show ``Rose'' and its star, Olympia Dukakis, to Broadway
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gersten, the executive producer of Lincoln Center
Theater, said that if an agreement can be reached, the production
will begin performances on March 28 at the Lyceum Theater on West
45th Street before an April 12 opening. As it did with last year's
productions of ``Ring Around the Moon'' and ``Via Dolorosa,''
Lincoln Center Theater is producing this show away from its 65th
Street home because its two on-site theaters are already booked.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which was a surprise hit at the National's Cottesloe
Theater, tells the story of a postwar Jewish emigre who travels
from a small Ukrainian village to Miami Beach. Ms. Dukakis, sitting
on a small bench with minimal set dressing, plays Rose, holding
forth for nearly two hours in a personal recollection of a Jewish
diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to that workload, the production will have only seven
performances a week, instead of the standard eight. Also limited is
the run, only eight and a half weeks. After that, there are
tentative plans to use the Lyceum for a revue of the American
theater, called ``The Broadway Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sherman, an American who lives in Britain, the play would
mark a return to Broadway after an absence of more than 20 years.
His last Broadway production, ``Bent,'' which opened in 1979 and
concerned a relationship between two gay men in Nazi Germany, was
nominated for a Tony Award for best play.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Bishop, the artistic director of Lincoln Center Theater,
has a long professional relationship with Sherman, dating back to
Bishop's tenure as the artistic director of Playwrights Horizon.
``Martin is an old friend,'' Bishop said. ``And a great writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gentrifying Off-Off
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is the Lower East Side getting too tony for
off-off-Broadway? That's the implication from the news this week
that the Present Co., which produces the New York International
Fringe Festival, was in danger of being evicted from its home, the
Theatorium.
</P>
<P>
   John Clancy, the Present Co.'s artistic director, said last
Friday that his company had received a notice from its landlord,
alleging that the company owed tens of thousands of dollars in
overdue rent, a charge Clancy denied. Legal help was sought, and a
call went out from the Theatorium for financial support. The
company started a campaign in hopes of raising $100,000, a figure
it says would settle affairs with its landlord as well as insure
next summer's Fringe festival.
</P>
<P>
   Similar money problems also beset another downtown theater
bastion, Todo Con Nada, on Ludlow Street, in December. That crisis
was again about rent, a shortfall of some $13,000. The threat of
eviction there passed after Aaron Beall, Nada's founder, asked for
$80 contributions from 167 ``friends of Nada,'' raising enough to
satisfy the landlord.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, Clancy said more than $20,000 had been pledged and
it looked as though a settlement would be reached. A call to the
property's management, Brookshire Equities, was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Clancy and Beall, who together founded the Fringe in
1997, say their rent problems underscore the increased
gentrification of their once-scrappy neighborhood _ a
gentrification, they say, that would not have been possible without
small theaters and performance spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no law in this country against making money,'' said
Clancy, speaking of his landlords. ``But we intend to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   A Romantic Streak
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It should come as no surprise that Kevin Chamberlin
was once a high school heavyweight wrestling champ. After all, he
looks the part: big, bald and burly.
</P>
<P>
   But audiences for ``Dirty Blonde,'' which opened on Monday at
New York Theater Workshop, are seeing another side of this talented
actor, one that he himself never expected to play: the romantic
leading man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The male ingenue,'' Chamberlin said with a giggle. ``I never
thought those words would come out of my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingenue might be a bit of a stretch _ or maybe just right _
considering Chamberlin's character, Charlie, has more than a
passing fancy for Mae West, and her clothes. What is certain,
though, is that Charlie is a departure for Chamberlin, who has
played more than his share of thugs, lugs and simpletons.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong actor _ he is a self-described ``theater freak'' _
Chamberlin struggled to find his niche. ``When you're 22 and
bald,'' he said, ``there's not a lot of roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, however, he is on a hot streak. He received great
reviews for ``Dirty Blonde,'' a production that is mulling a
commercial run. And after his stint in ``Dirty Blonde,'' he begins
work on ``Seussical,'' the much-anticipated Dr. Seuss musical, in
which Chamberlin will play another romantic lead, of sorts: Horton
the Elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wide-eyed innocent,'' he said. ``We have a few things
in common.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Briton in `Superstar'
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Glenn Carter, a little-known British actor, was
playing the role of a disciple in a 1998 West End version of
``Jesus Christ Superstar'' but when the musical went on tour in
Britain he ascended to the part of Jesus of Nazareth. Now he'll
reprise that role when a revival of the Andrew Lloyd Weber musical
opens on April 16 at the Ford Center for the Performing Arts.
Carter, the only foreigner in an otherwise American cast, said he
has never been to New York. ``I'm excited to visit like this,'' he
said. ``It's far too important a place to go as a tourist.''
</P>
<P>
   A Threesome Again
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The writer Larry Gelbart, the composer Cy Coleman and
the lyricist David Zippel, the team behind 1989's Tony-bedecked
Hollywood musical ``City of Angels,'' have rejoined forces on a
more austere topic: the lives of Napoleon and Josephine. The
unnamed project is aiming for a tryout in the fall and a Broadway
production to be announced.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
