r e BC-MOVIES-2000-STRAUSS-L     01-13 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-2000-STRAUSS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB STRAUSS' FIVE MOVIE PICKS FOR 2000
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: with MOVIES-2000-MAIN, MOVIES-2000-LIST and
MOVIES-2000-WHIPP) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, I see no reason to apologize for my
films-to-look-forward-to picks of January 1999. After all, this
time last year, everyone else thought ``Eyes Wide Shut'' would be a
masterpiece so, by comparison, my choices of ``Anywhere but Here''
(granted, that one sucked), ``Cradle Will Rock'' (interesting),
``Fight Club'' (weirdly interesting), ``Summer of Sam''
(underappreciated) and ``Magnolia'' (hey, my favorite film of the
year) seem pretty decent.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, however, you'll have another opportunity to make fun
of me for calling the following to your attention:
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm a Cheerleader'': If it lives up to the satirical
promise of its title, this story about a teen-age girl wrongly
committed to a lesbian deprogramming camp should be one hoot of a
social comedy. I mean, RuPaul without makeup? What could be
funnier?
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Myself and Irene'': I never thought I'd welcome the
prospect of Jim Carrey going back to over-the-top comedy. But after
that dreary Andy Kaufman thing, a rematch with the Farrelly
brothers (``Dumb and Dumber,'' ``There's Something About Mary'')
sounds like the most sublime of silliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm'': Wolfgang Petersen knows something about
directing seaborne suspense (witness ``Das Boot''), so this
adaptation of Sebastian Junger's non-fiction best seller about one
mama of a Nor'easter and the fishermen caught by it ought to be
pretty gripping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadow of the Vampire'': The ultimate film buff concept turned
into a real horror movie: A great German director hires a real
bloodsucker to star in his classic film. The fact that reborn king
of cinema cool John Malkovich headlines _ and Willem Dafoe seems
perfectly cast as the biter _ gives the project instant
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'': The most popular comic book of the last couple of
decades could actually mutate into an exciting movie under the
directing hand of Bryan Singer (``The Usual Suspects''). We know
there'll be studio pressure to dumb and dull it into a Batman-like
franchise, but with luck, the intelligence of Singer and the source
material will overcome such evil. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
