<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5250 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HIGH-SIERRA-FILM-2TAK     01-13 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-SIERRA-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ONE ROLE MADE BOGART INTO AN ICON  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Michael Sragow writes about film for Salon.Com and is working on a
biography of the director Victor Fleming.  
 By MICHAEL SRAGOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Humphrey Bogart was born on Christmas Day in
1899, and we're sure to be inundated this year with juicy
behind-the-scenes tales about the making of beloved hits like
``Casablanca'' and ``The Big Sleep.'' But the movie that marked him
as a towering star who would redefine crime movies, and action
films in general, was Raoul Walsh's stirring 1941 melodrama ``High
Sierra.''
</P>
<P>
   This film proved to be the end of the line for the old-time
gangster film and the beginning of genres like film noir and the
anti-western, which challenged knee-jerk public morality and
expressed ambivalence toward violent men.
</P>
<P>
   This combination of provocation and ambiguity has pervaded our
adult popular culture ever since: a circa-``High Sierra'' shot of
Bogart flashed on the screen in the first episode of ``The
Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of its influence derives from the 1940 novel by W.R.
Burnett, who is still best known for his 1929 novel, ``Little
Caesar,'' the basis of the first big gangster talkie. Burnett's
writing has an all-American, Jack London-like mix of veracity and
pulp intensity, urban smarts and atavistic yearning, sympathy for
the dispossessed and lionization of the superior individual.
</P>
<P>
   His emphasis on a manly code rooted in the gut, tested in action
and connected to trust and honor (even among thieves), is related
to Hemingway's. And in ``High Sierra'' Burnett locates the point
where American individualism meets existentialism. ``You always
hope you can get out,'' says the former dime-a-dance gal, Marie, to
the aging gangster, Roy Earle. ``That sort of keeps you going.''
</P>
<P>
   But much of the film's influence also comes from Bogart's
ability _ with the help of John Huston, who wrote the screenplay
with Burnett, and Walsh, who directed _ to turn an existential mood
into something irresistibly iconic. In Bogart's breakthrough
performance, it settles over Earle's dark suit like a battered
trench coat.
</P>
<P>
   Huston had already written one film Bogart had acted in _ the
clever, shallow ``Amazing Dr. Clitterhouse.'' But that script gave
Bogart a stock gangster role. ``High Sierra'' was a different
story. Roy (Mad Dog) Earle is the last great cornfed bandit _ an
Indiana desperado modeled on John Dillinger _ and this picture
chronicles his final job.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened 59 years ago this week, The New York Times called
it a ``Wagnerian'' valedictory, ``befitting a first-string god.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie established Huston and Bogart's friendship and
creative partnership. With Huston turning writer-director, he and
Bogart went on to make ``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``Across the
Pacific,'' ``The Treasure of the Sierra Madre,'' ``Key Largo,''
``The African Queen'' and ``Beat the Devil'' _ arguably the most
diverse and compelling credits ever compiled by an American
actor-director team.
</P>
<P>
   Although Huston was only the co-writer, ``High Sierra'' deserves
a place near the top of that list. (It returns to the small screen
in March as part of Warner Home Video's new Bogart Collection.)
From the start it snags the viewer in a vortex of existential doom.
A bedridden crime boss named Big Mac engineers Roy Earle's pardon
so he can lead a heist that Mac has planned at a ritzy California
resort, Tropico Springs.
</P>
<P>
   But when Earle drives to the High Sierra fishing spot where he's
supposed to wait for the go-ahead, he finds that his inside man,
Louis Mendoza (Cornel Wilde), has feet of clay and a big mouth,
while his safecrackers, Red (Arthur Kennedy) and Babe (Alan
Curtis), have done the unthinkable and brought along a dame, Marie
(Ida Lupino).
</P>
<P>
   Earle's nightmare memories of the Big House are matched by his
overripe nostalgia for the family farm. It leads him to form an
ill-advised friendship with a pair of displaced Ohio farmers (Henry
Travers and Elisabeth Risdon) and their wide-eyed, club-footed
granddaughter, Velma (Joan Leslie). He even grows attached to an
ownerless dog, which turns out to be a harbinger of death.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing Earle does is learn that Marie is better for him
than Velma _ and that life is better lived without illusions. But
he can't escape the defects that Big Mac has built into the caper,
and he can't outwit a modern radio-car dragnet when he takes to the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In a finale that's like Billy Wilder's ``Ace in the Hole'' done
in a matter of minutes, police pin Bogart down in sight of Mount
Whitney and reporters make him the center of a media circus.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Behlmer's book ``Inside Warner Bros. (1935-1951)''
documents how important this movie was to Huston and Bogart. ``It
would be very easy for this to be made into the conventional
gangster picture,'' Huston wrote to the producer Hal Wallis,
``which is exactly what it should not be.'' Huston was an avowed
Burnett fan. (He would also direct Jean-Paul Sartre's landmark
existential play ``No Exit'' on Broadway in 1946.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bogart jockeyed to play the leading role. ``You told
me once to let you know when I found a part I wanted,'' Bogart
wrote Wallis. ``A few weeks ago I left a note for you concerning
`High Sierra.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to A.M. Sperber and Eric Lax's ``Bogart,'' the actor
had read the novel before publication, in Redbook magazine, and
knew it was for him. He also knew that he was third or fourth in
the studio players' hard-guy hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Paul Muni quit the studio after Warner Brothers refused
to produce a Beethoven biography for him to star in. And Bogart
himself encouraged George Raft to turn down ``High Sierra'' by
telling him that Roy Earle would merely be one more tough guy
biting the dust. With Huston supporting his candidacy, Bogart got
the role.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart's gritty charisma and tensile authority have kept the
film emotionally fresh. We live in a climate where stars strive to
stay youthful. But as Earle gets out of a life sentence after eight
years in the pen, Bogart strides into view with a hatchet-job
haircut and gray on the sides, a worn black suit and hat and a look
of hard-boiled melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, he sets the movie's dominant texture of electric
rumination. When an anonymous thug picks up Earle outside the
prison gate, Earle directs him to the nearest park, where he tries
to relax on a bench as kids play and a trash collector spears a
front page that happens to have Earle's mug on it. The way Bogart
plays Earle, everything about him says, ``Don't rush me.''
</P>
<P>
   So when he moves into action, his speed and precision are doubly
dumbfounding. Earle knows times have changed when orders from Big
Mac come down through an ex-cop named Kranmer (played by Barton
MacLane). ``He calls the tune and you dance to it,'' the burly
Kranmer tells the reedy Earle _ who instantly whacks him with an
open hand on both sides of his face. Earle doesn't dance for
anyone: a misfit individualism led him into crime in the first
place. And only Bogart could so blithely slap Barton MacLane.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Earle fit into the Bogart persona that would fuel six
decades of bad nightclub impersonations. But the tightening of the
upper lip, the dialogue delivered through a sneer, the slouched yet
forward-tilting posture, the hands that swiftly part his jacket and
smooth his belt line and check his pockets, as if he's frisking
himself, are here convincing parts of a wary crime vet's armor.
</P>
<P>
   Other reflexes come into play whenever Earle gets desperate: his
cheeks quiver uncontrollably when he holds up a general store, and
he bares his teeth like a big cat when he fears he's about to be
cornered.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart had shown portions of this acting arsenal before _
notably as Baby Face Martin in the 1937 screen version of Sidney
Kingsley's play ``Dead End.'' (Bogart's famous turn as Duke Mantee
in the 1936 film of Robert Sherwood's ``The Petrified Forest''
hasn't aged as well; Bogart created Mantee on Broadway and in the
movie is gratingly stagy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``High Sierra'' gave him far more range. There's a crackling
newness to his dry kinesthetic poetry. He masters a dynamic
stillness and generates an air of concentration that expands the
space around his lines. And his idiosyncratic style suits the role.
Roy Earle is at odds with the world. Bogart contrasts surely and
steadily with every other player in it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Donald MacBride delivers a wonderful, beaming
performance as Big Mac _ each fleeting impulse this man has
registers in his face, from his thirst for hard drink to his
despair over partnering up Earle with unworthy soda jerks and
jitterbugs. Bogart, on the other hand, barely shifts expression.
His Earle doesn't want anyone to see to the bottom of him, not even
Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart funnels all of Earle's senses and emotions into a state
of generalized alertness. Even his pals must learn to ``read'' him.
Early on, Marie, afraid of being sent away from camp, lets Earle
know that she knows about the resort heist _ and that his inside
man tipped her off to it.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart makes Earle brighten from the inside out: he respects
Marie's intelligence. But when Earle feels vulnerable, or shamed,
he clouds over and clams up.
</P>
<P>
   This movie is about a man moving through unfamiliar territory to
what Shakespeare called ``the undiscovered country.'' Driving
around Tropico Springs in his dark suit, Bogart's Earle doesn't
lose his feral grace, but he looks as out of place as an undertaker
(or as Nixon on a beach). He doesn't fully accept that, as
Dillinger put it, he's ``rushing toward death.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades to come, Earle's stew of conflict and sentiment and
inchoate impulse would bubble up in the best American action and
suspense films _ in crime epics or films noir like Huston's
``Asphalt Jungle'' (from another Burnett novel), in westerns like
``The Naked Spur'' and ``The Wild Bunch,'' in POW flicks like
``Stalag 17'' and ``The Great Escape'' (which Burnett helped
write).
</P>
<P>
   If ``High Sierra'' has been overshadowed by its successors, it's
probably because of Velma and her club foot. Walsh, the director,
couldn't figure out how to signal that Velma and her grandparents
are projections of Earle's nostalgic imagination, not just cornball
cliches.
</P>
<P>
   For too long, Earle's quest to cure Velma of her limp _ and thus
win her hand in marriage _ comes off as mawkish instead of
self-deluded. But the crucial confrontations are rock-hard,
including those between Bogart and Lupino _ a match made in
underworld heaven.
</P>
<P>
   She rises to the film's summation. Over Earle's dead body, she
asks a cynical reporter to tell her what it means ``when a man
crashes out.'' He says, ``It means he's free.'' She repeats the
word ``free'' as her face fills the frame and passes out of it, and
the camera tilts up to take in the high country behind her. Rarely
has it been so jarring _ and so satisfying _ for a film to close
with the words ``The End.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
