<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S COMING UP FOR 2000 ON MOVIE SCREENS
</HEADLINE>
 4 takes  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: with MOVIES-2000-MAIN, MOVIES-2000-STRAUSS and
MOVIES-2000-WHIPP) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS AND GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having just said goodbye to the 20th century with an
invigorating spate of rule-bending movies, you might think we'd be
looking forward to the cinematic roller coaster ride of our lives
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it looks like we'll be hopping on the usual
merry-go-round of remakes (``Shaft''), rehashes (``Scream 3'') and
regressive formula movies (``Crime and Punishment in Suburbia'')
that Hollywood has been mindlessly churning out for years. Looking
for the next ``Being John Malkovich'' or ``American Beauty''? So
are we. And we don't see the equivalent on this list.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody saw ``The Blair Witch Project'' coming last
year. (This year, the prequel will be out by Halloween.) So we're
keeping our fingers crossed for a surprise or two _ not to mention
a few good films by May. (Take a look at the list. The pickings
seem slim.)
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the release dates are fluid to the point of
being meaningless. Some of these movies will switch slots several
times; some won't even be released at all. And you know what? The
world will probably be a richer place because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy! &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 15
</P>
<P>
   Love Etc.: The new millennium hasn't stopped the French from
making romantic triangle movies. This one's set, well, on the cusp
of the millennium. Charlotte Gainsbourg and Charles Berling kiss
the new age bon jour. (Phaedra Cinema) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 21
</P>
<P>
   Down to You: Freddie Prinze Jr. and Julia Stiles deal with the
joys and pitfalls of first love. (Miramax)
</P>
<P>
   Lollipop Girl in Hard Candy: Revival, if that's the proper word,
of a 3-D porno movie from the 1970s. Stars the late John Holmes.
(Parliament Films)
</P>
<P>
   The Reunion: A wacko holds his fellow alumni hostage. (Good
Medicine Films)
</P>
<P>
   Sitcom: A pet rat wreaks all kinds of psychosexual havoc on an
initially conventional French family. (Leisure Time Features) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 22
</P>
<P>
   A Girl Called Rosemarie: A 1950s German prostitute gets involved
in a big political scandal. (Castle Hill) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 28
</P>
<P>
   The Big Tease: A Scottish hairdresser comes to L.A. to compete
in a big styling contest. Described, alarmingly, as ``Rocky'' in
curlers. Stars ``The Drew Carey Show's'' Craig Ferguson. (Warner
Bros.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cup: Tibetan monks go crazy for World Cup soccer. Filmed in
the Himalayan nation of Bhutan. (Fine Line Features)
</P>
<P>
   Eye of the Beholder: Intelligence agent (Ewan McGregor) tracks
down a beautiful criminal (Ashley Judd). Easy assumption: He has a
hard time turning her in. (Destination)
</P>
<P>
   Grizzly Falls: Bear mom captures human kid. They bond. Bryan
Brown and Richard Harris appear. (Providence Entertainment)
</P>
<P>
   Isn't She Great?: The answer to that question depends on your
stomach for tawdry sex. Bette Midler stars as ``Valley of the
Dolls'' author Jacqueline Susann in this film that emphasizes the
zanier aspects of the trash queen's sad life. (Universal)
</P>
<P>
   Rear Window: Hitchcock's supreme paean to the voyeuristic soul
of the movie experience, newly restored and re-released. James
Stewart and Grace Kelly were at their finest in this masterful 1954
thriller. (USA Films) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 4
</P>
<P>
   Gun Shy: Liam Neeson is an undercover drug agent who's lost his
nerve. Sandra Bullock runs the support group that really isn't
helping him get it back. Claims to be a comedy. (Hollywood
Pictures)
</P>
<P>
   Knockout: Female Latino boxing drama. (Renegade Pictures)
</P>
<P>
   Much Adobo About Nothing: Filipino-American farce. (Traxx
Productions)
</P>
<P>
   Scream 3: More self-referential murder and mayhem _ in case
anybody out there is still interested. (Miramax)
</P>
<P>
   Wirey Spindell: A commitment-phobe's life flashes before him on
his wedding day. Eric Schaeffer wrote, directed and stars. (WinStar
Cinema) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 5
</P>
<P>
   The Adopted Son: Coming of age in Kyrgyzstan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 11
</P>
<P>
   The Beach: Leonardo DiCaprio's finally back in the water, this
time on an idyllic Thai island where trouble's boiling beneath the
pleasurable tropical surface. Directed by ``Trainspotting's'' Danny
Boyle from Alex Garland's well-regarded novel. (Fox)
</P>
<P>
   Les Bonnes Femmes: Claude Chabrol's 1960 New Wave classic
follows the romantic misadventures of four Parisian salesgirls.
(Kino International)
</P>
<P>
   The Red Dwarf: French movie about a little person who runs away
to join the circus. '60s Eurofilm icon Anita Ekberg appears.
(Samuel Goldwyn)
</P>
<P>
   Snow Day: A Nickelodeon co-production about the things that
happen to a typical American family on an atypical day. Chris
Elliott, Iggy Pop and Pam Grier are among the strange cast-fellows.
(Paramount)
</P>
<P>
   The Tigger Movie: Winnie the Pooh and company make an animated
return. (Disney) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 12
</P>
<P>
   Devil's Island: Reykjavik rocks as an Elvis impersonator comes
to 1950s Iceland. (Artistic License) &QL; 
