<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-COACHES-HNS &LR;      01-13 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BLACK COACHES IN THE NFL WALK THE PLANK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This looks horrible. The Green Bay Packers fired
their head coach after one year, when the team finished at .500,
and also dropped their offensive and defensive coordinators. All
three coaches are black, the first such trio in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   This looks horrible, too. The Bay Area had two defensive
coordinators, each of whom had been in his position for two years.
One took the Raiders' last-place defense and moved it into the top
10. The other took the 49ers' top-ranked defense and dropped it
into the NFL cellar. The Raiders' coordinator is a 56-year-old
black man with decades of experience. The 49ers' is 38 and white, a
relative newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was fired this week, and it wasn't the young white
man with the bad statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Was it racism that drove Ray Rhodes out of Green Bay so quickly?
Was it discrimination that shoved Willie Shaw out of Oakland? Are
the standards higher for black coaches than for white ones in the
NFL? I can't say. All I know is that it looks horrible. If it's not
discriminatory, it's certainly depressing.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, the NFL's 31 teams had a total of three head coaches
who were black and 10 black coordinators. By Jan.,12, the numbers
had dropped to two head coaches and seven coordinators, a 33
percent fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow-PUSH Coalition has asked for a
meeting with Packers administrators to discuss Rhodes' hasty
firing. Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy, one of the two black head coaches
left in the NFL, said on Wednesday that he considered Jackson's
efforts misdirected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily think that was the right way to go,
because, to me, the Packers made a move. They hired the guy, and
for whatever reason they decided not to continue with it,'' Dungy
said in an Associated Press story. ``I think we need to look at the
situations where they don't hire people, as opposed to the Packers'
situation, personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy has never been an apologist for the poor track record of
hiring black coaches into the NFL. It's easy to understand why he
would defend the Packers, who hired Rhodes after the Philadelphia
Eagles had deteriorated under his command, making him the first
African American head coach to get a second chance in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   It's just as easy to see why the Raiders could laugh off any
hints of discrimination in their headquarters. They were the first
NFL team to hire a black head coach. They put black players on the
offensive line when it was considered the domain of white
``cerebral'' players. They've had a coach named Flores. They
currently have a top executive named Amy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Raiders replace Shaw, they are very likely to hire
another African American coordinator, possibly even Emmitt Thomas,
who worked with head coach Jon Gruden in Philadelphia and was part
of the purge in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no denying that Shaw's ouster was unusual. The
Raiders have justified it by saying that they expected Shaw to get
a head coaching job soon and that they needed to transfer his
``supervisory'' designation to secondary coach Chuck Bresnahan so
that other teams wouldn't steal him away.
</P>
<P>
   But they could have lifted the supervisory title without canning
Shaw. They let him go for other reasons, reportedly because he and
Gruden weren't in sync, because Shaw was deemed inflexible, and
because the team lost several games on late defensive collapses.
And, oh yes, because this Raiders team underachieved quite
spectacularly and someone had to pay.
</P>
<P>
   All of these reasons make sense, and there are always reasons
for firing employees. There are even more reasons for not hiring
people in the first place. But when those people are black coaches,
the reasons just seem to multiply and then slip under a magnifying
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw couldn't find harmony with Gruden? No racism there, right?
But how did the tow-headed, 36-year-old Gruden become the wonder
kid of the NFL while Shaw, who had a longer, better history, had to
play his underling?
</P>
<P>
   Shaw is inflexible? Sounds like Bill Parcells, Jimmy Johnson,
Tom Coughlin, Buddy Ryan, Vince Lombardi.,.,.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders' defense fell apart in crucial games? The offense
vanished at least as often as the defense, and Gruden's poor clock
management in the Monday night game in Denver cost the Raiders a
playoff spot. Yet Gruden kept his job, and his reputation as a
rising star.
</P>
<P>
   If Shaw gets a head-coaching job, the sting of his Oakland
firing will disappear. Everything will look less horrible. He has
already interviewed with New England and expects more contacts. But
he fears, quite understandably, that the Raiders' dismissal will
hurt his chances.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes may land somewhere else, too, though his prospects for a
head coaching job are slim. Green Bay had good reasons to be
dissatisfied with his performance, and his departure wouldn't look
so horrible if the rest of the NFL had hired more diverse coaching
staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Dungy pointed out that Rhodes' fate was similar to that of Chan
Gailey, who spent two years as head coach of the Cowboys, went to
the playoffs both seasons and still got the ax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes with the territory,'' Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
   But the territory isn't trod by nearly enough African Americans.
That's why one fired head coach and three dumped coordinators add
up to a 33 percent drop. That's why it looks horrible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
