A5263 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-BAMBI14-COX     01-13 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BAMBI14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Before it was a movie, `Bambi' was a book
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Simon &AMP; Schuster has released a new
edition of Felix Salten's novel ``Bambi.'' The book has been
abridged and is illustrated in a realistic style by Steve Johnson
and Lou Fancher.
</P>
<P>
   Salten's novel is, of course, the basis for the Disney animated
movie, and this adaptation retains Salten's essential message that
animals and nature are equally sacred.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Max Schuster brought out the book in 1928 _ it was
published in Germany five years earlier _ with a translation by,
believe it or not, Whittaker Chambers. After the rise of Hitler,
Schuster helped get Salten, a Jew, out of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS IN THE SAND
</P>
<P>
   A recent Gallup Poll offered mildly heartening news. It reported
that most Americans read just about as much as they did 20 years
ago, that they prefer nonfiction to fiction and that the Internet
has little impact on book choices. Women read more than men, and 84
percent claim to have read all or part of a book in the past year,
up from 81 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 7 percent claim to be avid readers, tossing off more
than 50 books in the past year. Most disturbing was the 13 percent
who said they read no books, a figure that has climbed gradually
over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   `ELEMENTS OF STYLE,' REFASHIONED The value of the backlist is
shown by the recent publishing history of ``The Elements of
Style,'' the classic volume by William Strunk and E.B. White. Now
more than 80 years old, revised by White in 1959, and later in
1972, it was recently revised yet again by White's stepson, the
noted New Yorker writer Roger Angell.
</P>
<P>
   The book is published by Allyn &AMP; Bacon, and president Bill Barke
recently told Publisher's Weekly that it had been selling about
230,000 copies every year but that the new edition is expected to
double that amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Elements of Style'' accounts for nearly 2 percent of the
company's annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   All this explains why houses such as Little, Brown are combing
through their rights list to see what might be profitably reissued.
Little, Brown has recently issued new editions of Lillian Hellman's
memoirs and the C.S. Forester ``Hornblower'' novels.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``Great literature must spring from an upheaval in the author's
soul. If that upheaval is not present, then it must come from the
works of any other author which happen to be handy and easily
adapted.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Benchley
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
