<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-PALLISER14-COX     01-13 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PALLISER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palliser's `Unburied' a rewarding tale of betrayal
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Charles Palliser's bewitching ``The
Unburied'' begins just after World War I. A man journeys to Geneva
to confront an elderly woman about a recently published book. The
book is a mixture of correct information and incorrect suppositions
about a famous series of medieval murders in the English town of
Thurchester.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator knows the book's suppositions are false because he
has recently come into possession of the Courtine manuscript, which
lays bare the truth of the murders that were echoed nearly 400
years later in a sad story of human duplicity and the persistence
of evil.
</P>
<P>
   The old woman is soon to die and knows it, but gives away
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   We flash back 50 years to the story of the studious,
determinedly unworldly academic Dr. Courtine, as he arrives in
Thurchester to visit Austin, an old college chum from whom he has
been estranged for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   While in Thurchester, where the murders took place in the
cathedral, death strikes yet again, in the apparently
incomprehensible fashion beloved of those with a taste for
locked-room mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   The new murders aren't that difficult to unravel _ any mystery
aficionado knows to prepare himself for a variation of the old
shell game when a corpse has to be identified by his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``The Unburied'' remains a delight because of an
intricacy that never becomes confusing, and for the perfect ear
Palliser has for Victorian life and its ornate, attractive speech
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   In inexpert hands, this can be a bit like an oatmeal bath, but
unlike many of the writers Palliser is channeling, he keeps the
plot moving and the atmosphere atmospheric:
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in the vast, gloomy dining room in which there were no
other diners, served by a lugubrious waiter with the mournful
solemnity of the last priest of a dying church. The ambience seemed
all of a piece with this ancient, decaying town withs its unlit and
dilapidated streets in which nobody ever seemed to be about.''
</P>
<P>
   He's after a tricky melding here. There are all sorts of hints
of other writers, from the unavoidable echoes of Trollope, provided
by the author's surname, to the Jamesian tenor of the prologue, to
the retrieval of a great, buried Victorian story that is the
novel's centerpiece, which recalls A.S. Byatt's ``Possession.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the shifting time frames _ present day, i.,e.
1919, while the Courtine manuscript, which occupies the bulk of the
book, involves the deep Victorian era as well as solving the
original medieval murders.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the plot, the novel is about the getting of wisdom, for
the initially unsympathetic and blundering Courtine has his own
fears and demons that the narrative helps him solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who invite betrayal,'' a character tells
Courtine in a highly charged, brief encounter towards the book's
end. ``They are demanding towards themselves and don't realize how
hard they are on other people. They make it difficult for others
not to fail them. And in some cases they take a grim pleasure from
being let down.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel is less about its title _ although one aged corpse
does turn up in Thurchester Cathedral _ than it is about the
various permutations of betrayal, and how different people react to
it.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``The Unburied'' explains all of the mysteries of
Thurchester, as well as some of the more complex aspects of human
nature. It's a delicious book, a perfect companion for the
proverbial dark and stormy night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
