<HEADER>
A5265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-CAPECOD-KAYAK14-COX     01-13 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPECOD-KAYAK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruising with this Cape Cod kayak corps a clarion call to
courage
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLEANS, Mass. _ My brother, who is usually so protective,
insists we will be fine. No matter what the kid renting kayaks says
to us: Small-craft advisory, storms coming, lots of experience
necessary. Just wear a life jacket, Johnny says.
</P>
<P>
   My brother, brother-in-law, boyfriend and I are setting sail _
er paddle _ on a 10-mile kayaking adventure in Cape Cod. For weeks,
I've been lifting 5-pound hand weights at my desk.
</P>
<P>
   My brother, Johnny, and my brother-in-law, Seth, have their own
super long (and consequently super fast) kayaks. But my boyfriend,
Greg, and I rent from the kid at Goose Hummock, an outdoor shop
that sells fishing tackle, canoes and woolly jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The kid looks worried. Do we have a lot of experience, he asks?
I say no. (I had been kayaking twice before. Once in Sanibel four
years ago, I fell asleep on the plastic boat and drifted ashore at
a French resort, which made me think I'd bobbed very far indeed.)
Johnny says yes. I say, well, no. Johnny says yes.
</P>
<P>
   I do not know when my little brother became so adventurous. As I
recall, he refused to get his driver license until he turned 18,
for caution's sake. But I am the self-appointed trek leader, so I
sign the death release and pray that we don't end up eating each
other later. We walk down to the dock, which stretches into the
southern bend of Town Cove, beneath a gray-shingled windmill where
families sometimes picnic.
</P>
<P>
   But not today, because the sky is black.
</P>
<P>
   Kayaking isn't hard. I suspect sitting so close to the water
might make some people nervous and of course, it's a lot tippier
than a canoe. But if you curve your legs inside along the sides,
it's not so hard to maintain your balance. These particular kayaks
had rudders, which means we could steer with our feet. Our original
plans had been to kayak along the inside of Cape Cod's arm from
Eastham to Provincetown, about 22 miles. A little too far, even
after months of hand weights. Instead we decided to kayak in the
arm, through its veins, I guess, from Town Cove to where the ocean
has broken through the barrier beach and the salt water has invaded
the marsh.
</P>
<P>
   What's nice about traveling inside the cove is that we can see
into people's back yards where they're moseying around, setting up
fishing poles, wrestling with dogs, and in one case celebrating a
wedding. We are flying by them, on the outgoing tide to the sea,
because Seth and Johnny have scouted out where the fastest currents
are running.
</P>
<P>
   I say the water is acting crazy, smacking over the top of the
kayak and soaking my shorts, and they laugh at me.
</P>
<P>
   We have plenty of water (that was Seth) and plenty of roast beef
sandwiches (thanks to the trek leader who didn't really want to eat
her brother). But can I stop to drink any water? No, because the
mean boys are leaving me behind. Argh. It takes an hour or so to
get through the cove, heading north past Hopkin's Island, a bird
sanctuary, into the mouth of Nauset Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   On our left is Fort Hill, where local soldiers set up guns
during the War of 1812; now it's a popular spot for vacation
photos. Ahead we can see Eastham's Coast Guard Station, where the
ocean ate a parking lot in the blizzard of 1978. But we turn east,
around Snow Point, toward the break in the beach.
</P>
<P>
   We are skirting small sedge islands, called hummocks, past
lobster buoys and clam beds, sometimes in just a few inches of
water. On a nice day, this would be absolutely beautiful. The water
would be quiet, and I would be looking at the marsh birds: tiny
piping plovers and massive ospreys rising above the marsh grass.
But right now, even though the boys claim it's just spray, I think
it's raining. I know it's getting rougher. Waves are breaking over
the nose of my kayak.
</P>
<P>
   And still, all I know about kayaking so far is this: Turn and
face the waves, or tip over. So I am turning and turning, using
those handy rudders over and over again. And I think I'm getting
the hang of it. I can shift my hips without fear.
</P>
<P>
   I experiment with different paddle strokes. Deep. Shallow. I
pretend I am a kayak professional on TV. I pretend I am rounding
Cape May. No, I pretend I am rounding Cape Horn. I have a blister
on my thumb that I mention to Greg. He says, ``that's not going to
stop the trek leader, is it?'' I wonder if I'm being patronized.
</P>
<P>
   High tide is maybe minutes away and the water is rushing out of
the marsh, through the break in the beach, like kids running crazy
from a beehive. We must cross this noisy (and very scary) water,
and I am wondering why. Johnny and Seth tell me lunch is on the
other side. Now I know I'm being patronized, but I don't care. I am
actually talking to myself, saying things like: Mary Ellen, it is
very unlikely you're going to die.
</P>
<P>
   (When I confess my fears later, Greg says: ``You are a
looneybird. At worst, you'd have tipped over, gone bombing around
in your lifejacket, and ended up sitting in 2 inches of water.'')
</P>
<P>
   Johnny goes first, looking like a cowboy. Then Greg gets popped
across like a cork. And OK, I do it too, and it's really not so
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Seth is yelling ``Dig!'' And I dig, whatever that means. And the
next thing I know, we're on the beach, eating chocolate chip
granola bars, trying not to disturb the tern nests, and looking for
white rocks for my desk fountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's brave, weighing yourself down,'' Seth says, looking at
my pile of stones.
</P>
<P>
   Two more hours back. And the kid is happy to see us.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Where to rent kayaks: Our two kayaks from Goose Hummock
(508-255-2620) cost about $33 each for four hours. They also offer
day or weeklong rentals.
</P>
<P>
   In Provincetown, Off the Coast Kayak at 3 Freeman St.,
(1-877-PT-KAYAK) rents kayaks by the half-day for $25 and day for
$40. They also take visitors on kayak tours in Cape Cod Bay, near
Truro and Wellfleet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
