<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-DENMARK14-COX     01-13 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DENMARK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Denmark promises family fun
 &HT;    By Shelley Emling
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark _ While flying here with our children, ages
4 and 18 months, my husband and I made a depressing discovery:
Tivoli, the city's best-loved attraction, was closed for the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   According to the guidebook, which _ I admit _ we should have
reviewed earlier, the famous amusement park is open only from April
to September.
</P>
<P>
   It was early November.
</P>
<P>
   Unsure of how we were going to spend the next three days, we
entered the tourist office to find a hotel room. A man directed us
to the Hotel Ansgar, a clean, pleasant hotel just a five-minute
walk from the center of town. We got a room, which included a big
breakfast of cereal, cold cuts, and pastries, for about $80 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   We began to feel better. Our new goal was to discover _ and
enjoy with children _ a Copenhagen minus its best-known asset.
</P>
<P>
   And this was easy to do. In fact, there was so much to do, it
wasn't long before our itinerary was packed tighter than our
suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   What we liked best is that Copenhagen is truly a city for
walkers, so there's no need to shell out a fortune in cab fares.
Less than a mile square, the city's core consists of five
pedestrian strands, known as Stroget, and the surrounding tangle of
roads and courtyards. Many of the streets in the oldest part of
town are cobbled and winding, bordered by pleasant cafes and shops.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at Radhuspladsen, Copenhagen's central square, these
pedestrian streets meander east. The square is dominated by the
Radhuset (Town Hall), which includes a 350-foot tower that offers
panoramic views right across to Sweden. Also, the Town Hall is home
to the World Clock, which gives such details as the position of the
planets and times around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In front of Radhuset is the statue of Denmark's best-known
writer, Hans Christian Andersen, who was actually not a
Copenhagener at all, but a native of the island of Fyn.
</P>
<P>
   Within easy strolling distance of the square are the cathedral,
Parliament, the old Stock Exchange, and the domes and spires of
various other civic buildings. Each contributes weight to a skyline
that's gloriously free of skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   We spent hours wandering the streets, marveling at how every
Dane appears to be rich, healthy, blond and incredibly good
looking.
</P>
<P>
   According to author Bill Bryson, Copenhagen is the only city in
which gorgeous office girls come out at lunchtime to sunbathe
topless in the city parks. Unfortunately for my husband, it was too
cold for this sort of display during our visit.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the city's atmosphere is startlingly relaxed, which
is something when you consider that the city was twice bombarded by
the British under Admiral Lord Nelson in the 1800s, and that it was
twice devastated the century before by fires blazing through the
wooden houses.
</P>
<P>
   It is also incredibly civil.
</P>
<P>
   Sustaining a seamless monarchy and moderate politics for a
millennium, Denmark has remained modest and peace-loving. There is
little to suggest that it is the capital of a country that once
ruled Scandinavia. And this, I think, is delightful.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of Denmark's civility:
</P>
<P>
   This country of five million citizens boasts six conservatories,
seven symphony orchestras and 230 primary music schools.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many museums it's impossible to count, each with
admirable collections of art and sculpture for all tastes.
</P>
<P>
   One of our favorites was the Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek, an
elaborate building with a vast collection of Egyptian sculpture,
Greek and Roman statuary, as well as works by Degas, Gaugin and
other Impressionists. Glyptotek was given to the city by Carl
Jacobsen, the son of the founder of the Carlsberg Breweries. Its
nucleus is a lush indoor garden, from which you can explore the
nooks and chambers that house what is considered to be the best
collection of Etruscan art outside Italy and Europe's finest
collection of Roman portraits.
</P>
<P>
   A little farther afield is the Frederiksborg Castle, which lies
in the middle of Hillerod, about a 40-minute drive north from
Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest parts of the buildings that make up the castle date
from 1560 and were built by Federik II. The castle was used by the
kings of Denmark for more than 200 years. To say the structure,
with its copper-clad roofs and spires, is impressive would be an
understatement. Most importantly, the Museum of National History is
housed here, and it contains all sorts of historical portraits and
paintings. We made a game of this visit by encouraging our
4-year-old to pick out the portrait of the ugliest _ and most
attractive _ king and queen.
</P>
<P>
   Best for the children, though, is the Louisiana Museum of Modern
Art at Humlebaek, just outside Copenhagen. The museum displays a
vast array of art and sculpture, from around 1945 to the present
day, with works by Giacometti, Moore, Calder and others. But the
best part is the three-story children's area, where budding artists
can paint, sculpt, or just play with Legos to their heart's
content.
</P>
<P>
   If you can shake the children, you may want to check out the
Museum Erotica at Kobmagergade 24, where you can view a wide range
of erotic films, magazines, paintings, postcards, and sex toys.
According to the brochure, you can even study the sex life of Hans
Christian Andersen, although its unclear why you should want to do
such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   We also visited the carefully tended gardens surrounding
Rosenborg Slot, the Dutch Renaissance castle built by Christian IV.
Intending it first as a summer residence, the king loved the castle
so much that he ended up living, and dying, there. Today it's a
museum (yes, another museum) where the crown jewels, as well as a
collection of costumes and royal memorabilia, are housed. But the
surrounding park is the real showstopper. When we visited, the
trees' leaves were every shade of red, orange and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Although there wasn't a slide or swing to be found in the
playground, there was an abundance of ropes to swing on and a maze
of tree logs to climb on. The kids loved it.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes employ a laissez-faire attitude toward their children
in that they rarely keep a close eye on them the way we do in the
states. (Remember the Danish tourist arrested in 1997 for leaving
her baby daughter in a stroller outside a New York restaurant?) And
there is a reason for this.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark is an almost absurdly safe country where the most
malicious crime seems to be bike theft.
</P>
<P>
   This is just another reason why I loved Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at the end of our trip, we were sad to have missed
Tivoli, which would have offered spectacular rides, fireworks
displays, pantomime theaters, and jazz and rock concerts. The
attraction was built in the 1840s by Danish architect George
Carstensen, who persuaded a worried King Christian VIII that a huge
amusement park would distract people from politics.
</P>
<P>
   But we'd be back. One final reminder of why this country is so
splendid came at the airport when we were waiting for our plane to
depart: a play area for children, the centerpiece of which was a
giant pirate ship surrounded by colorful plastic balls. What a
place!
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Other things to see and do with children:
</P>
<P>
   Darnarks Akvarium (Charlottenlund). The array of fish will
tantalize every age group. Daily from 10 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   Eksperimentarium (6 miles north of Copenhagen in the beachside
town of Hellerup). More than 200 exhibitions are clustered in 15
Discovery Islands, each exploring a different facet of science,
technology, and natural phenomena with hands- and body-on exhibits.
Mon., Wed., and Fri. 9-6; Tues. and Thurs. 9-9; weekends 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland in south-central Jylland. It's filled with scaled-down
versions of cities and villages, a Statue of Liberty and Mount
Rushmore, all constructed from 35 million plastic Lego bricks.
Daily 10-8 from April to September.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish Tourist Board can be contacted at (212) 885-9700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
