<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Jan. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Howling arctic winds will numb New England on Friday. In the
wake of Thursday's modest snowstorm that affected only parts of the
region, arctic air will pour south from Canada, keeping daytime
temperatures in the single digits and teens. More importantly,
winds from the northwest will average 20 to 30 mph across eastern
New England, increasing the cooling power of the wind to
potentially dangerous levels. Temperatures Friday night will fall
toward minus 20 degrees in parts of northwest New England. Farther
west, bands of lake-effect snow will develop Friday down wind of
Lake Ontario in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Rough seas, patches of arctic sea smoke and bands of
ocean-effect snow will prevail over waters off the New England
coast as strong arctic winds are moistened over Atlantic waters.
Meanwhile, along the coast of northern Florida, ocean winds will
gust over 30 mph in response to the large pressure difference
between a strong, sprawling high centered over Tennessee and a
trough of low pressure south of Florida. With dry air associated
with the high gaining a foothold on Florida, the stage will be set
for a chilly night Friday night, with a freeze across the northern
part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the big chill in the Northeast, the west-central
Plains will turn milder as winds from the southwest spread across
Kansas, Nebraska and southwest South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   In the Far West, areas of rain and mountain snows will prevail
in the Pacific Northwest, where winds off the Pacific continue to
deliver moisture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snow at Last &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snowflakes finally flew over Boston on Thursday, ending the
record wait for snow. It was a modest snow, with accumulations
through early Thursday afternoon generally less than 5 inches in
eastern Massachusetts. Besides bringing Boston's first snow this
winter, the salient effects of the culprit low pressure system was
to draw arctic air into the Northeast as it moved out to sea. With
the arctic front now lying south of New England, there will be more
occasions for snow. Even though the arctic chill will ease this
weekend, an opportunity for heavy snow in Boston may come Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
