<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAINTING-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: SISTERS, SISTERS, SORROWFUL AND STILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Seattle)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 was sent Jan. 13 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One goal of the Altogether Different festival is to
offer new chances for audience development and expansion to small
or little-known dance troupes. Variety is another goal, hence the
title. But 33 Fainting Spells, which opened the three-week festival
at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday night, is altogether different with
a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorrow's Sister,'' the hourlong piece presented by this
Seattle-based troupe, is a good example of the company's unusual
approach. Dayna Hanson and Gaelen Hanson, who founded this
three-woman group, tell stories, create atmosphere and evoke
emotion through small gestures and moves that in themselves are
about as abstract as movement can get. There are also long passages
when nothing seems to be happening. A woman sits in a chair. Three
women stand in a row looking out at the audience. A woman laughs.
Another stares out a window, her back to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The masterly organization of detail does make for a quick
suspension of disbelief for viewers willing to concentrate hard.
One enters the Hansons' world almost unknowingly, in this case
emerging unprepared for the emotional wallop packed by the closing
moments of ``Sorrow's Sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   The set, lighting and atmosphere suggest a cramped hideaway
pressed in upon by the weight of onrushing disastrous history. Anne
Frank's attic comes to mind. It is inhabited by three women (the
Hansons and Peggy Piacenza) wearing drab black dresses and sturdy
shoes. Suitcases strewn about the floor suggest that they are about
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   A gift of a single metal roller skate is received with blank
bewilderment at a ragbag birthday celebration near the start of
``Sorrow's Sister.'' Disappointing a present though it may be, the
skate is a bit of elegant detritus that gives one of the women a
mobility that is suggestive, choreographically and metaphorically.
</P>
<P>
   Another major event occurs when one of the women stumbles into
the room, bruised and bleeding. She falls sick, curled limply on a
mattress that releases small streams of dust when her fingers
scrabble against it. Her small jolting steps toward recovery and
the others' reactions help to create the sense of a tiny universe
far more potent _ and perhaps even more dangerous _ than the world
beyond the window.
</P>
<P>
   The lighting, by Hallie Kuperman and Lara Wilder, plays an
important part in establishing that universe. ``Sorrow's Sister''
is performed to a carefully knit suite of music and words by Kurt
Weill, Kate Vannah, Paganini, Shostakovich, Dylan Thomas, Dvorak
and Bartok. Like the production, the score represents an impressive
feat of intellectual and emotional weaving of ingredients into a
seamless whole. With ``Sorrow's Sister,'' problematical though it
sometimes is, the troupe aims high but invites the audience along
for the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The piece will be repeated Friday night at the Joyce (175 Eighth
Ave., at 19th Street). Other festival participants are the
companies of Lula Washington, Neil Greenberg, Yoshiko Chuma, Sara
Pearson and Patrik Widrig, Pascal Rioult and Lawrence Goldhuber and
Heidi Latsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
