<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RAMS-HNS &LR;      01-13 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAMS SHOULD BE WARY OF VIKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're the St. Louis Rams right now, you should be a little
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Life has been too easy lately. The wins have come too smoothly.
Their world is similar to that gentle breeze that swirls in the air
just moments before Mother Nature starts unleashing her haymakers.
</P>
<P>
   Something ugly is about to hit St. Louis, something more
commonly known as the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   The best game of the postseason will kick off in the TransWorld
Dome in St. Louis on Sunday. It features the Rams, the best team in
the NFC throughout the regular season, and the Vikings, the best
team in the NFC right now. And if the Rams aren't careful, their
head coach, Dick Vermeil, will have a new reason to shed a few
tears _ his team will be the most disappointed 13-3 bunch in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, for those who haven't noticed, are the most likely
spoilers in this year's postseason plans. They looked that good
even before dispatching the Dallas Cowboys in last weekend's NFC
wild-card matchup. They are hot enough to turn the Rams'
screenplay-type season into something that belongs in ``Scream 3''
and talented enough to take Washington or Tampa Bay in a one-game
shootout. Minnesota hasn't won nine of its last 11 games off sheer
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a defense that some 49ers could start for, the Vikings
can be scary, especially with the way Jeff George has been throwing
the football. You remember him in Oakland. When the Raiders dumped
him last year, he practically had to beg for a job. 49ers general
manager Bill Walsh wouldn't even give him a sniff. The man was
poison, his critics said, and his track record couldn't overturn
that judgment.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, George is something else: one more player with a
suspect character who is bent on proving to the world that given
the right opportunity, he can be a winner, too. Last year, Vikings
wide receiver Randy Moss had it in for his critics. It's George's
turn this season and when you combine the way Moss runs and George
uncorks a football, you produce an image few cornerbacks are
prepared for and even fewer want to face.
</P>
<P>
   But Minnesota isn't just George and Moss and fellow Pro Bowl
wide receiver Cris Carter. There appears to be an attitude around
the Vikings that of all the teams left in the NFC Super Bowl hunt,
they have the edge because they know this terrain better than
anyone else. This is Minnesota's seventh trip to the playoffs in
eight seasons under coach Denny Green.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis hasn't made a playoff appearance since 1989, and the
Redskins haven't accomplished the feat in eight years. As for Tampa
Bay, this is only its second postseason showing in the last 18
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are relying on their opponents flinching when faced
with the pressure of football in January. Minnesota's players also
have personal experience to fall back on. Faced with their own
coronation last season, they learned how easy it is to be favored
for a championship and how difficult it is to win one.
</P>
<P>
   There the Vikings were late last January, sprawled across the
turf at their Metrodome home, wondering why they deserved such a
fate. The Atlanta Falcons had done them in with a field goal from
Morten Andersen in the NFC Championship Game. Suddenly, a team that
won 15 regular-season games and scored more points than anyone else
in NFL history was on suicide watch. A year has passed since that
upset and still the Vikings feel a need to atone for last year's
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they wouldn't be the first team in recent memory to
be both dominant and deflated in one season and then resurgent the
next. The Denver Broncos did it only a few years ago. They went
from being stunned by the upstart Jacksonville Jaguars in the 1996
playoffs to earning a wild-card spot the following year and running
all the way to their first Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are strong enough to do just that. Or should we say
the NFL, and more specifically, the NFC, is weak enough for
Minnesota to make a compelling playoff run. They have an effective
running game once again, with Robert Smith finally healthy. Their
defensive problems are mostly in the secondary, where they actually
start a converted wide receiver at one cornerback. And their
overall offensive talent is sufficient enough to get them 25-30
points when it has to.
</P>
<P>
   In today's NFL, that's enough to advance in the playoffs, but
the Vikings have something else. They think they can beat anybody
they meet in the next couple of weeks. If you're the St. Louis
Rams, you shouldn't take that attitude lightly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
