<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     01-13 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ALBUM OF THE WEEK: SONIC YOUTH'S `GOODBYE 20th CENTURY'  
(EDS: In `PLUS MINUS', replace the words with the typographical
symbols) 
(bl) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONIC YOUTH: ``Goodbye 20th Century'' (SYR).
</P>
<P>
   To send off the 1900s, Sonic Youth acknowledges its roots in a
distinctly 20th-century phenomenon: experimental composers who
embraced improvisation, noise, repetition and the workings of
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The band and friends, including the composers Christian Wolff
and Takehisa Kosugi, perform 10 composers' works in which music is
less an arrangement of sounds than a collision of them or a
meditation on their coexistence. There are wordless witticisms:
George Maciunas' ``Piano Piece No. 13'' _ nailing down the keys of
a piano, as shown on a CD-ROM video that is included _ and Yoko
Ono's ``Vocal Piece for Soprano,'' 12 seconds of a child's screams.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Reich's ``Pendulum Music'' is pure process: the chirping,
calliopelike feedback of a microphone swinging over a speaker.
Kosugi's ``PLUS MINUS'' and John Cage's ``Six'' and ``Four6 '' '
are sequences of textures, realized with Sonic Youth's guitar
vocabulary of shimmers, slides, screeches and distortion blotches;
Wolff's ``Edges'' and ``Burdocks'' place splintered sounds around
fragments of narrative or melody. Pauline Oliveros' ``Six for New
Time,'' written for Sonic Youth, unfolds from consonance to
cacophony.
</P>
<P>
   But the piece that sounds tailored to the band is James Tenney's
``Having Never Written a Note for Percussion,'' an oceanic crest
and ebb of dissonant guitar chords. It was composed in 1971,
anticipating Sonic Youth by a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
