<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      01-13 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SOPRANOS':   THE ZITI'S IN THE OVEN AND THE MATRIARCH'S STILL
NOT DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(dal) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She's dead to me,'' Tony Soprano says about his mother,
spitting out the word ``dead'' as if it were a bullet. He says this
not once but twice in the opening episode of the new season of
``The Sopranos.'' Each time is a reminder of how magically James
Gandolfini embodies this likable, despicable character, and why he
is the greatest of the series' many wicked delights.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Livia, who set up her son to be killed, is not dead
to anyone else. We learn that near the start of the newest episode
(Sunday night at 9 on HBO), as the story is brought up to date in
an extended sequence that is operatic in its reach, with music,
drama, vibrant costumes and outsized emotions converging. If the
music that drives this scene is not exactly Verdi, it is something
more appropriate. Frank Sinatra langorously sings ``It Was a Very
Good Year'' as the characters are captured in silent motion:
</P>
<P>
   Livia is in her hospital bed, having survived the stroke that
left her gasping at the end of last season. Tony is teaching his
daughter to drive when he isn't at his job, being handed a shopping
bag full of cash. His wife, Carmela, is taking baked ziti out of
the oven with the kind of knowing but bored grimace that Edie Falco
has used so brilliantly to define the character. And Uncle Junior,
in an orange jumpsuit, walks down a prison corridor, having
insisted to the FBI that he, not his nephew Tony, is head of the
crime family. Graceful, witty and brazen, that sequence and the
entire first episode are everything fans of ``The Sopranos'' could
hope for.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence is nothing like a recap, though. Viewers who know
the series are likely to yell ``Uncle June!'' in recognition, while
anyone else might be lost. But then we have never heard ``Last week
on `The Sopranos' ...'' That is a small indication of how
thoroughly the series has broken the television mold.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of recaps, deft conversations set up characters and
attitudes. Here, Junior's temporary replacement explains that Tony
was about to smother his mother with a pillow, but her stroke got
there first. And, he continues, Tony was seeing a psychiatrist,
matricide and therapy being given equal weight. That is why Tony's
shrink, Jennifer Melfi, is now receiving patients in a seamy motel
off a New Jersey highway, hiding out from people who assume Tony
spilled family secrets while searching for an emotional
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The only series in years to become a critical hit and a pop-cult
phenomenon, ``The Sopranos'' has established its own family loyalty
and in-joke recognition among viewers. David Chase, its creator,
shrewdly builds on that in the new episodes. We see that Tony's
crew has continued to update its business dealings, running a stock
brokerage with a surprisingly high rate of office violence.
</P>
<P>
   Tony's older sister, Janice, returns from Seattle. She changed
her name to Pavarti in 1978, wears aging-hippie clothes and fills
the fridge with tofu, but she can't lose the family resemblance.
She has Tony's heft and straight-talking manner, and is every bit
as snaky as their mother. ``I wonder what her scam is this time,''
Tony says to Carmela, in a bit of dialogue that is unmistakably
his. ``Whatever it is, I'm going to be five grand lighter before
she raindances back to the commune.'' As played by Aida Turturro,
Pavarti fits right in.
</P>
<P>
   Tony explains to her that Livia's stroke was psychosomatic,
``brought on by repressed rage,'' he says, barely repressing some
rage himself. That diagnosis frees Nancy Marchand, who gets even
better and wilier as Livia, to go on weaving her way through the
plot, keeping everyone off guard about everything except the fact
that Livia is no innocent, dotty old lady.
</P>
<P>
   Carmela's parents appear, garish, believable and hilarious.
Someone's brains are shot out, splattered against a windshield. The
disparate parts of Tony's life continue to mesh in a tragicomedy.
</P>
<P>
   All this is handled with such panache that it seems as if Chase
were daring himself to raise the stakes, and meeting his own
challenge. Did he really have a choice? With viewers' expectations
wildly out of control, ``The Sopranos'' is battling its own instant
legend.
</P>
<P>
   It would be ludicrous, though, to measure this season against
the idea that every scene last year was genius. The next two
episodes (all that were available in advance) should tug
expectations back toward reality. They include wonderful touches.
Uncle Junior gets a medical parole and uses a friendly doctor's
office to do business because the government is forbidden to bug
him there. (Who knew?)
</P>
<P>
   Yet these episodes are sturdy and good rather than blazingly
terrific. It makes sense to remember that the first season didn't
really take off until episode four. Similarly, in the next episodes
plot lines are tossed out that haven't become taut or tangled yet.
</P>
<P>
   There is every reason to think they will be. As the recent
repeats of the first season demonstrated, Chase knew where he was
going. The series grew beyond an easy joke about a mob boss with a
midlife crisis, and became a family epic about characters who are
so fully developed their very thoughts are familiar to us. In
Sunday's episode, Tony asks a wary mob guy into his house, and the
man asks for a guarantee that if he walks in he'll walk out again.
We know he doesn't have to worry; Tony would never kill someone in
his own home. Few characters allow us to read them with such
certainty, while maintaining the realistic capacity for surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the series' shrewd and witty veneer, that look of made
men in loud shirts and pants hitched up under their armpits, the
original ``Sopranos'' achieves greatness because of this
psychological depth. By now viewers can name favorite scenes like
``when Carmela tells off the priest,'' a classic of astuteness and
honesty in which she lets her priest know she's onto his game of
safe flirtation.
</P>
<P>
   Given such sharp psychological definition, it is odd that the
plot about the psychiatrist still rings false, from Dr. Melfi's
unlikely motel room office to a cheap joke about the
mobster-goes-to-a-shrink movie ``Analyze This.'' And the new season
holds another pitfall in the character of Richie Aprile, a former
boss' brother. Richie is mean-spirited and vicious enough to smash
a glass coffee pot across someone's face for petty cash. Yet as
much as he offers a tantalizing distinction between a ``bad''
mobster and a ``good'' one like Tony, who loves his family and
kills only for a reason, the one-dimensional Richie is annoying,
possibly more than the creators intended.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a long, luxurious way to go in this 13-week season,
and even this early ``The Sopranos'' has displayed the depth that
is its most stunning quality. The first episode ends with Tony and
Carmela sitting at their kitchen table in a long silence. We know
them well enough to guess more than what they are thinking; we can
guess what each one thinks the other might be thinking too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE SOPRANOS'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Created by David Chase; Chase, Robin Green, Mitchell Burgess and
Brad Grey, executive producers; Frank Renzulli, co-executive
producer; Martin Bruestle, Allen Coulter and Ilene S. Landress,
producers; Harry J. Bronchtein, Todd A. Kessler and Terence Winter,
co-producers; Bob Shaw, production designer; Phil Abraham, director
of photography.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Gandolfini (Tony Soprano), Lorraine Bracco (Dr.
Jennifer Melfi), Edie Falco (Carmela Soprano), Michael Imperioli
(Christopher Moltisanti), Dominic Chianese (Junior Soprano),
Vincent Pastore (Big Pussy Bonpensiero), Steven Van Zandt (Silvio
Dante), Tony Sirico (Paulie Walnuts); Robert Iler (Anthony Soprano
Jr.), Jamie-Lynn Sigler (Meadow Soprano) and Nancy Marchand (Livia
Soprano). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
