<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RENO-HAITIANS-HNS &LR;      01-13 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-HAITIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAITIANS SEE UNEQUAL TREATMENT IN GONZALEZ CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite growing resentment among many African
Americans about the treatment of Haitian refugees compared with
those from Cuba, Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday that the
government will not change its policy toward illegal immigrants
from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different situations with respect to Cuba and with
respect to Haiti, and the nature of the government in the two
nations is different,'' she said at her weekly news conference
here.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the international custody fight over six-year-old
Elian Gonzalez, whose father lives in Cuba, many in Miami's
Haitian-American community, one of the city's largest ethnic
groups, are demanding that Haitian refugees be treated the same as
Cuban refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Activists claim that Haitians are routinely repatriated without
being offered a chance to request a hearing to determine if they
have a ``credible fear'' of persecution in their homeland, while
Cubans who are not considered a threat to society are allowed to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Under U.S. immigration policy, Haitians and others who arrive
illegally are repatriated to their country. But the Cuban
Readjustment Act of 1966 grants any Cuban who reaches American soil
the right to stay.Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS)
officials say that refugees _ Cuban or otherwise _ stopped offshore
are treated the same, that is, returned to their home country.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian groups counter that U.S. authorities sometimes treat
Cubans caught off the coast differently, allowing them to stay if
they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was found clinging to an inner tube in the Atlantic off
Florida on Thanksgiving Day. His mother and others fleeing Cuba
with him had drowned. After the U.S. Coast Guard picked him up, he
was taken to relatives in Miami. In a case that has made front-page
headlines for weeks, federal and state officials have heatedly
argued over whether he should sent back to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Haitians also cite the example of six Cubans whose boat was
stopped by the U.S. Coast Guard last June. The six jumped from a
14-foot rowboat about 150 yards from shore in a desperate attempt
to reach the United States. But the Coast Guard scooped them up,
preventing them from reaching land. Yet because U.S. officials
admitted using harsh procedures, all six were eventually allowed
into the country.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Day, a ship carrying 411 Haitians was stopped off
the Florida shore. All but four of the passengers were immediately
repatriated to Haiti. The remaining four were taken to a detention
center to receive medical attention. Three have been allowed to
stay because they apparently faced persecution in Haiti. The other
case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian activists claim that the repatriation of most of those
refugees was unfair and in contrast to the extensive consideration
given to Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking for fairness, equality and due process,'' said
Aude Sicard, an activist with the Haitian-American Grassroots
Coalition. ``Haitian children are children too.''
</P>
<P>
   INS spokesman Russell Bergeron said, ``We treat refugees who
reach shore differently because the law treats them differently.
``If the Haitian community would like to change this, they should
tell Congress, not the INS.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
