<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ABORTION14-COX     01-13 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABORTION RIGHTS GROUP CRITICIZES BUSH STANCE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League on Thursday ranked Gov. George W. Bush as one of the
nation's two most anti-abortion governors in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL(cq) President Kate Michelman criticized Bush for signing
seven measures in 1999 limiting access to abortion. The group also
singled out Gov. John Engler of Michigan, who is being touted as a
potential Bush running mate, for approving restrictive abortion
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, state legislatures passed 70 measures limiting
abortion, up from 62 in 1998 and 14 in 1996. They enacted 57
measures tagged by NARAL as pro-choice, up from 22 in 1998 and 19
in 1997, according to the group's annual state-by-state review.
</P>
<P>
   Michelman said the increase in pro-choice measures indicated
that, ``we're just beginning to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential race is a backdrop to everything today,'' she
continued. ``We do this research over an entire year. ... It leapt
out at us that Governors Bush and Engler were from states that were
most aggressive in limiting reproductive rights.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, abortion has taken a back seat in the GOP primary
contest, with conservative activists Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes the
only two candidates consistently broaching it. But as the Jan. 24
Iowa caucuses and Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary near, the issue has
emerged as a way to appeal to more conservative Republican primary
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine publisher Steve Forbes, running second to Bush in most
Iowa polls, is airing an anti-abortion television ad in that state.
And two groups that oppose abortion have taken aim at Sen. John
McCain of Arizona with radio ads in South Carolina, where he trails
Bush. One of the ads accuses McCain _ who has a strongly
anti-abortion Senate voting record _ of flip-flopping on the issue
of using aborted fetuses for medical experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by voters on the campaign trail how he feels about
the issue, Bush answers, ``pro-life.'' He favors a constitutional
amendment banning abortion that would exempt incest, rape and
threats to a mother's life, but said in a broadcast interview in
November that he does not believe the country is ready for such a
move.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would not make abortion a litmus test for
appointing Supreme Court justices, but would look for judges who
strictly interpret the Constitution. Michelman called that code for
appointing judges who would overturn Roe v. Wade, the 1973 decision
that made abortion legal. She said Bush has obscured his stand on
the contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to play down the issue, keep it in the
background,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL criticized a new Texas law that prevents girls younger
than 18 from legally obtaining abortions unless a doctor first
informs a parent or guardian. A girl who doesn't want to notify her
parents can seek a court order allowing her to make the decision
herself. The so-called judicial bypass is designed to protect girls
who have been sexually abused.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also approved more stringent licensing requirements for
private physicians' practices that perform more than 300 abortions
a year. The U.S. District Court in Houston upheld a challenge to
the law in December. The state is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Kae McLaughlin, executive director of Texas Abortion and
Reproductive Rights, said Bush has gone along with efforts to chip
away at access to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they do is undermine the procedure by laying heavy
restrictions on the providers, by implementing waiting periods,
conscience clauses, things that make providing the procedure more
difficult,'' she said. ``He is on the very same path as those who
would ban abortion entirely. It's the same language.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Pojman, executive director of the Greater Austin Right to
Life Committee, local arm of the national group, applauded Bush's
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think he is implementing what the average Texan wants,''
Pojman said. ``He has not been specific about what kind of vice
president or justices he might nominate but he has said he wants
justices who will respect the Constitution and that's all we ask
for. If he does that, and we have every reason to believe he will,
we'd be very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com or (202)
887-8324.
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
