<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT14-BJT-COXUPDATE     01-13 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT14-BJT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Jan. 14, c.
2000.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: MEXICO-SINGER, LOCKHEED-BIAS
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION _ WASHINGTON _ The NARAL Foundation for Reproductive
Freedom and Choice President releases the foundation's annual
review of abortion and reproductive rights nationwide according to
individual state restrictions. The study cites Texas as ``the most
actively anti-choice state in the country.'' (Heath, Austin
American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   MANATEE _ WASHINGTON _ Environmental and animal protection
groups filed suit Thursday against the state of Florida and the
federal government, charging that not enough has been done to
protect the endangered manatee. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-FINE _ WASHINGTON _ The federal government and the
state of Texas will divide a record $30 million civil settlement to
be paid by Koch Industries, a Kansas-based pipeline company accused
of polluting water in six states, the Environmental Protection
Agency announced Thursday. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID _ WASHINGTON _ Florida and the federal Medicaid program
paid nearly $16 million in bills that should have been sent to
local insurance companies, says a new federal audit of state
operations in 1996. The inspector general for the U.S. Health and
Human Services Department urged that the state recover the funds,
but Florida officials said they doubted they could do so. (Malone,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SINGER _ Gloria Trevi, a suggestive Mexican pop singer
likened to Madonna, was arrested in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, on
Thursday, according to Mexican authorities. Trevi and her manager
Sergio Andrade Sanchez are wanted for questioning in allegations
that they corrupted minor girls and held them captive as alleged
sex slaves. Trevi has both shocked and mesmerized Mexicans with her
throaty vocals, bad-girl lyrics and bump-and-grind stage act. She
was on the lam for months. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST _ LONDON _ Maverick historical writer David Irving was
accused in court Thursday of fabricating an order from Adolf Hitler
calling for a halt to mass murders of Jews in 1941 _ a key element
in his argument that the Nazi leader was initially opposed to the
genocide. Irving wrote in his 1977 book ``Hitler's War'' that he
had discovered ``incontrovertible evidence'' that Hitler had
ordered that there would be ``no liquidation'' of Jews. However,
Irving acknowledged in court that he based this assertion on a
misreading of a handwritten note from Gestapo Chief Heinrich
Himmler. Instead of demanding the end of the killing of all Jews,
Himmler's note suggests he spared one trainload of 1,000 Jews
transported Berlin to Riga in Latvia. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-BIAS _A federal EEOC investigation has found that
Lockeed managers have discriminated against blacks at its Marietta
plan and its is still investigating more cases involving gender and
disabilities, according to EEOC notices obtained by the
Journal-Constitution. While Lockheed has denied the discrimination,
the EEOC found that black employees with more than 30 years
experience were passed over for promotion in favor of white
employees who had less experience or senority. Its investigator
found that blacks are disciminated against in regards to training,
promotion and assignements. The EEOC will now begin a concilliation
process, which if unsuceesful, the next step will be a lawsuit.
(Visser, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CUBABOY _ MIAMI _ Even if lawyers for relatives of Elian
Gonzalez get their day in federal court, legal experts are doubtful
a judge would rule that the 6-year-old Cuban rafter should remain
in the United States. As they prepare to file suit in federal court
next week, it appears the relatives' strategy may be to try to
stall Elian's return until Congress convenes Jan. 24 in hopes of
quick passive of a bill granting the boy citizenship _ even though
President Clinton probably would not sign it. Meanwhile, Attorney
General Janet Reno said Thursday the boy should be returned quickly
so ``he can get on with his life.'' (Williams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-LAWSUIT _WACO, Texas _Federal attorneys Thursday asked
for more time to comply with U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith's
order to produce all documents related to the Branch Davidian
wrongful death lawsuit. Asking for two weeks. (England,
Tribune-Herald).
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ESSAYS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ For admissions officers at
colleges and universities across the country, the next six to seven
weeks areis crunch time, akin to a tax preparer's workload before
April 15 or a sales associate's long hours before Christmas. It's a
particularly intense kind of work. How do admissions officials stay
fresh? How do they make sure they're evaluating candidates each
candidate fairly, and not discriminating against a student because
he or she had the bad luck to be the 50th file they've read that
week, after a long day? (Santos, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MINORITIES _ Black and Hispanic men now account for more
cases of AIDS among gay and bisexual men that white men do. This
represents a change from earlier studies, which found that men of
color were growing as AIDS victims, but traced the infection
largely to IV drug use. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ASTRONOMY-BLACKHOLES _ ATLANTA _ Thursday is ``black hole day''
at the American Astronomical Society meeting. Astronomers describe
observations from the Hubble Space Telescope and its newer sister,
the Chandra Observatory, of enormous black holes at the center of
galaxies and evidence suggesting the existence so-called ``naked''
or isolated black holes in empty regions of space. (Nesmith, Cox
News Service).
</P>
