A5308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICAID-FLORIDA14-CO     01-13 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-FLORIDA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLORIDA, FEDERAL GOVERNMENT PAID TWICE FOR HEALTH CARE COVERAGE
 &HT;    Attn: Florida points.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal health care programs and the state of
Florida paid double for medical coverage for thousands of
Floridians, a new audit of 1996 billings has concluded. The excess
cost to taxpayers was estimated at $15.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The duplication was discovered by the inspector general for the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, who called on Florida
to recover the overpayments, including the federal share of $8.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   In the report made public on the Internet on Thursday, auditors
said the Medicaid program paid for thousands of Florida residents
who were already covered by private health maintenance
organizations under the federal Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, taxpayers were paying once through monthly fees to
the private HMOs by Medicare, the federal program for the elderly,
and again through fee-for-service Medicaid, the federal-state
program for low-income recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The study said the state should try to collect funds from HMOs,
including $4.7 million from Humana, the biggest health care group
in the state, and nearly $11.2 million from 50 other HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials, acknowledging the problem, said they have
little hope of recouping the money from the HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Florida Medicaid Management Information System maintains
two years of claims paid data, preventing us from producing the
necessary claims detail from 1996 through our carrier billing
system,'' said Ruben I. King-Shaw Jr., executive director of
Florida's Agency for Health Care Administration, in the state's
response to the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the duplication problem persisted into 1998, said Judy
Hefren, the Florida official in charge of third-party Medicaid
payments.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the state loaded the necessary federal data into
its computer systems to guard against the double payments, Hefren
said in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the problem has now been solved. ``There may be
isolated instances,'' she said, adding that the verification system
now alerts providers and the state health care administration when
a Medicaid applicant has private HMO coverage through Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The HHS inspector general, rejecting Florida's reasons for
failing to recover payments from HMOs, said the federal government
began providing data for fixing the duplication problem in August
1995. The inspector general also offered to work with the state in
identifying double payments to ``facilitate recovery'' of the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
