<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-SOPRANOS14-COX     01-13 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The Sopranos,' HBO's highly acclaimed series about a mafia
family, doesn't sing in season premiere like it did in the
spectacular first season
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disappointment you feel at the end of ``The Sopranos'''
second-season premiere only cinches last year's brilliant
achievement. The opener is a bit of a bore: smart, stylish, bold,
but unengaging at times to the point of narcolepsy. After last
season's wondrous 13-episode arc, ``The Sopranos'' suddenly seems
in search of a reason to go on.
</P>
<P>
   The show itself appears to acknowledge this, when early Sunday
night its principal characters, suburban mob boss Tony Soprano
(James Gandolfini) and his wife, Carmela (Edie Falco), stare
vacantly at each other in bed while a soundtrack reels with Frank
Sinatra's wistful ``It Was a Very Good Year.''
</P>
<P>
   That first season was more than a very good year. Created by
David Chase (``Northern Exposure,'' ``I'll Fly Away''), HBO's
``Sopranos'' was as good as TV gets, an aria in a medium of white
noise. It made high art out of low lives, a worthy sequel to Mafia
classics ``The Godfather'' and ``GoodFellas.''
</P>
<P>
   A huggable thug, Tony Soprano became TV's most loyal family man.
He dutifully served two clans: the nuclear family under his
two-story-with-pool contemporary in suburban New Jersey, which
includes two teenage kids, and the New York-connected crime family
headquartered inside the Bada Bing strip club. Straddling both
worlds, and at the very center of this series, was his aging mother
Livia (Nancy Marchand), a brutally brittle woman who cannily
engineered an attempted hit on her son.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of tending _ and ending _ so many lives drove Tony
to psychiatrist Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco), who prescribed
regular therapy and a Prozac diet. The show's genius resided in
many places _ even the soundtrack was a crankin' beauty _ but its
skill at mining the inner lives of people who otherwise seemed all
itchy, homicidal surface might be its most singular feat.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Sunday's return doesn't live up to where ``The
Sopranos'' left off, but only because it hardly left a thing. With
Livia confined to a hospital bed, and goggle-eyed Uncle Junior
(Dominic Chianese) confined to a jail cell (after the hit he
ordered on Tony failed), there's little for Tony to do but swagger
and swear.
</P>
<P>
   Tony's loose-cannon nephew Christopher (Michael Imperioli) now
oversees a brokerage house _ this is an up-to-the-second mob
portrayal. Dr. Melfi, her life in danger after the botched hit, now
sees clients in a room at a roadside motel. New is Tony's New Age
sister Janice (Aida Turturro), who returns from Seattle and drives
Tony nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna be five grand lighter before she rain dances back to
the commune,'' Tony grumps to Carmela.
</P>
<P>
   So with little but his criminal activity and pestering sister to
occupy him, Tony's now just ... a thug. Both his inner and outer
demons are little more than annoyances. What's to root for?
</P>
<P>
   But there's good news: The meandering ends in the third episode,
when ``The Sopranos'' returns to its staggeringly marvelous ways. A
cold, angling challenger arrives for Tony, and suddenly, in the
transformative manner of this series, he again becomes another
vulnerable lug in a fast-changing world _ just like us.
</P>
<P>
   That's what ``The Sopranos'' does better than anything else:
puts us inside the unlikeliest lives and makes us see something of
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always pretty. But it's incomparable TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos''
</P>
<P>
   HBO Sunday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
