A5319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOL-MICROCASTS-$AD     01-13 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-MICROCASTS-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEW SCHOOLS SIGN UP FOR SAFETY SHOWS
 &HT;    Eds: Cox-state sites listed at end of story.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan 16.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's 110,000 elementary and secondary
schools have been slow to sign up for a series of 10 monthly
satellite-aided telecasts on how to make schools safer.
</P>
<P>
   Announced by President Clinton in June, two months after the
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., the series is being produced
by the National Education Association with technical help donated
by FutureView, a Washington-based programming firm.
</P>
<P>
   The NEA's $500,000 effort was endorsed by three federal
departments and the Learning First Alliance, which consists of the
NEA and 11 other leading education groups that together have more
than 10 million members.
</P>
<P>
   But less than one week before three satellites transmit the
first episode at 2 p.m. EST Thursday (Jan. 20), there are signs
that many of those members aren't interested:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fewer than 130 districts and schools applied for and received
one of the 1,000 free satellite dishes offered by EchoStar
Communications Corp., a direct broadcast satellite company in
Littleton, to public schools that wanted to receive the telecast
from one of the firm's satellites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only 64 of the more than 6,000 educational institutions that
already had dishes had registered on the Education Department's
Internet site to receive the show from other satellites on C-band
or KU-band transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Though advance registration is optional, that is far below the
410 schools and school districts that have signed up to get another
of next week's Education Department shows, which will concern early
childhood education.
</P>
<P>
   EchoStar donated its satellite transmission time for the safety
series. The NEA purchased the time on the other two satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers insisted that they can overcome the early signs of
apathy.
</P>
<P>
   The programs ``will bring this critically needed school safety
information to every school district in the country,'' said NEA
president Bob Chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, school was out in June'' when Clinton announced
the program, said EchoStar spokesman Marc Lumpkin. ``I think we'll
get a lot more schools to sign up for the free dishes as more learn
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers said interest in the first episode, ``Reasons for
Hope,'' is intense in the places where segments of the first
episode were videotaped.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the first episode shows a model program in Columbia,
S.C., aimed at developing appropriate social behavior by children
in first and second grades, and another shows local leaders in
Colorado discussing the lessons they learned from the shootings at
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, every public school will be sent the program
by South Carolina ETV, and in Colorado, the state education
association will sponsor a showing in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is we still have a lot of free satellite dishes
for schools that want them,'' said Roberta Hantgen of the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   She said that starting with next month's show, Apple Computer
Inc. will cybercast the series on its Apple Learning Interchange
Internet site. The National Cable Television Association is also
considering the possibility of asking its members to carry the
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building partnerships is an evolutionary process,'' Hantgen
said. ``So we're not discouraged at starting off with a small
core.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, schools can apply for free satellites at
http://www.safeschoolsnow.org, and satellite-dish operators can
find directions for downloading the school-safety programs at
http://www.nea.org/echostar/schedule.html. To find out if there are
public viewing options in your area, click on ``Reasons for Hope''
at http://stm.xpandcorp.com/default.asp?strCommand &QC; SERIES.
</P>
<P>
   Cox eds: Here are sites in your state among the 122 that got
free EchoStar satellites (and name of person there who was the
contact):
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Douglas County School System (Jerry Bley), Gunnison
Watershed School District (Jon Nelson), Jefferson County Public
Schools (Christian Anderson) and West End Public School (Ron
Harrison).
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA (Baker County (Glenn McKendree), Homes (Jerry Dunn),
Flagler County (Diane Kelly), Lee County (Sandra K. Agle).
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA: Sent earlier to Paul Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA: Pitt School District (Judy G. Rodgers).
</P>
<P>
   OHIO: 8 sites, including two in the Miami Valley: (Dayton Public
Schools, Neal J. Neto, and Valley View Local School District, David
W. Miller)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Pecos-Barstow-Toyagh ISD (Jodi Exum), San Elizario ISD
(Ernesto Rodriguez), Socorro ISD (Charlie F. Wilcox), Terrell ISD
(Hilda Braggs) and Ysleta ISD (Richard Bolanos).
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
