<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     01-13 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. HAS HAD AS MANY FAILED PRESIDENTS AS SUCCESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 16)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the new century rolled around, ratings of the
outstanding men and women of the past 100 years could be found
everywhere _ on TV talk shows, in newspapers and magazines and at
gatherings of individuals interested in history.
</P>
<P>
   The analyses produced no startling revelations or revisions of
the past. Since our tendency is to canonize leaders who share our
philosophy, some Republicans listed Ronald Reagan ahead of Franklin
D. Roosevelt, while Democrats invariably placed Roosevelt far ahead
of Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Each of this year's presidential hopefuls appears to have found
a past president to emulate, just as Roosevelt patterned his New
Deal to some degree on the legacy of Woodrow Wilson and Reagan
sought to resuscitate the starchy image of Calvin Coolidge.
``Silent Cal'' was a tax-cutting Yankee who, as an apostle of the
status quo, believed that ``the chief business of America is
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's effort recalled the comment of Alice Roosevelt
Longworth, Theodore Roosevelt's tart-tongued daughter, when she was
informed that Coolidge had died. ``How could they tell?'' asked the
acerbic Alice.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note that the focus of the last few weeks
has been exclusively on those presidents who were successful in
running the country. None of the prognosticators paid attention to
those who had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the 210-year saga of our government, starting with George
Washington's first inaugural, our destiny has resided in the hands
of about as many poor presidents as outstanding ones.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the poor presidents may have been honest and
able, they simply failed to fill the shoes of giants who preceded
them in the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, William Henry Harrison, John Tyler, Zachary
Taylor, Millard Fillmore, James Buchanan, Andrew Johnson, Ulysses
S. Grant, Rutherford B. Hayes, James A. Garfield, Chester A. Arthur
and Benjamin Harrison could not ignite that latent brilliance that
many presidents possess.
</P>
<P>
   They, therefore, are among the forgotten figures of history. In
the years before and after the Civil War, most found the presidency
to be an office that was too large for their small talents.
</P>
<P>
   The United States fared better in the 20th century. Fewer
failures held the reins of government.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt, who succeeded to the presidency upon the
assassination of William McKinley in 1901, was a charismatic
bombshell, ready to explode in any direction that merited
presidential attention. He and Woodrow Wilson forged the modern
activist presidency that made America a world power and inaugurated
far-reaching reforms designed to better the lot of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt's hand-chosen successor, William Howard Taft, was,
like Jimmy Carter, a kindly, decent man who lacked the leadership
qualities required of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Warren G. Harding, an Ohio newspaper publisher who was
inaugurated in 1921, knew from the beginning that the job was too
big for him. In 1923, as the tawdriness of the Teapot Dome scandal
began to leak out, Harding lamented, ``My God, this is a hell of a
job. I have no trouble with my enemies ... But my damn friends,
they're the ones that keep me walking the floor nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding was succeeded by Coolidge, who spent much of his
five-year presidency napping in the White House while business and
industrial leaders pretty much ran the country.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Herbert Hoover, a talented engineer, who probably
would have been an outstanding president had the Great Depression
not come crashing down on him and the nation. For all his
experience feeding starving Europeans during World War I and
serving as a highly successful commerce secretary in the Harding
and Coolidge administrations, he lacked the imagination to create
federal programs that would provide work for jobless Americans and
help save their homes and farms from foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   In a year-end summary of the last century, four Washington
reporters and their moderator appearing on a televised talk show
said Time Magazine had erred in selecting Albert Einstein as the
person of the century. Although they took no vote, they appeared to
agree that the honor should be shared by Winston Churchill and
Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   They recalled how the defiant Churchill stood alone against
Adolf Hitler's bloody air assault on England in 1940. His
resistance to the Nazis, who bombed London night after night, was
indeed heroic. But what the panelists failed to note was that
Churchill could not have held out against Hitler had Franklin D.
Roosevelt not been in the White House providing him with fighter
planes, submarines and other weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in lauding King's magnificent leadership of the civil
rights movement in the 1960s, they failed to mention the fact that
the monumental legislation that dismantled racial segregation in
public accommodations, voting booths and housing was passed through
Congress by Lyndon Johnson. LBJ, a son of the Confederacy, was
possibly the most brilliant legislative strategist in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Johnson is remembered for his commitment to the
tragic war in Vietnam rather than his achievements on the domestic
front.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon likewise is seen only as the president who was
forced from office by the Watergate scandal, not as the outstanding
foreign policy architect among the presidents of the second half of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, Bill Clinton faces a
similar assessment despite the good he has done in guiding the
nation's prosperity, aiding education and trying to settle
longstanding foreign disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over the current crop of presidential hopefuls, we
should try to determine which candidate can best provide valorous,
enlightened leadership in time of crisis, as did the giants of the
past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBABOY-0114-COX     01-13 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBABOY-0114-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    EFFORTS TO KEEP CUBAN BOY IN U.S. WILL LIKELY FAIL, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international, (w) Washington and (a) national
categories 
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Protests, tearful appeals, angry vows and legal
maneuvering have so far managed to keep 6-year-old Cuban rafter
Elian Gonzalez in this country, but legal experts say those
strategies are likely to falter now that the fight over the boy's
future is headed to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new legal proceedings and the prospect of
a move in Congress to grant the boy citizenship or legal residency
could drag things out for weeks or even months, adding to the
turmoil of a very young boy who has already lost his mother and
nearly drowned at sea himself, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This protracted limbo status is in and of itself
unconscionable,'' said Bernard Perlmutter, director of the
University of Miami's Children and Youth Law Clinic. ``Both sides
share the blame in subjecting this child to needless emotional
distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno made much the same point Thursday,
speaking to reporters at her weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to think about that little boy,'' she said.
``Let's figure out what we do, as soon as possible, and do it in a
dignified and thoughtful way to get him back to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Reno brushed aside a Florida family court judge's
decision to grant temporary custody of Elian to his great uncle in
Miami. She reaffirmed a Jan. 5 decision by U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Commissioner Doris Meissner that the boy should be
returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also encouraged Elian's Miami relatives to file a lawsuit
in federal court, saying that is the proper venue for the matter.
The family's lawyers said they will do so next week.
</P>
<P>
   Their delay may seem curious, but experts say it could be part
of a strategy to string the case along, perhaps hoping that
opposition to keeping Elian here will fade, that Reno's resolve
will falter, or that congressional action might open a new avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to protract all of this so somebody in the end will
shrug their shoulders and give up,'' Perlmutter said. ``But I think
federal officials believe there are important principles at stake
and they want this matter resolved promptly.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was found floating in an inner tube off the coast of Fort
Lauderdale on Thanksgiving Day. His mother and nine other people
drowned after their small boat capsized while they attempted to
flee Cuba. The boy somehow survived, only to become the center of
an international tug-of-war, with his father and Castro's
government on one side and his Miami relatives and Miami's Cuban
exile community on the other.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after Thanksgiving, INS officials traveled to Cuba
and interviewed his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, determining that
he has been a good father and wants his child back. Legal scholars
say that determination is the key to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every legal move made by the family has been aimed at wresting
custody from the father,'' said David Abraham, another University
of Miami law professor who specializes in immigration law. ``They
want custody granted to somebody who wants the boy to stay in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains why the family went to Miami-Dade County family
court late last week, Abraham said. ``They were trying to do an end
run around the fact that they have no case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno blew that strategy away with her announcement Wednesday
that the state court had no jurisdiction, Abraham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigration matters are the exclusive domain of the federal
government,'' he said. ``You can't have the individual states
setting their own immigration policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving the case to federal court likely means the family will
lose, scholars agree. That's because both immigration and
international law solidly back the notion that a child with one
dead parent should go to the other parent, if the surviving parent
is deemed fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Cuba is a communist country doesn't make the
father not the father, or a bad father,'' Abraham said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives have been careful to argue
that while Gonzalez may be fit, he is unable to speak his true
feelings because he is controlled by Castro, and that the
deprivations and taunting Elian would face if he returned to Cuba
would amount to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But they may never get far enough in federal court to make those
arguments. Instead, a federal judge may first ask why they are even
attempting to speak on the boy's behalf, since federal officials
have already determined that role belongs to the father, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to have a hard time even arguing that
they have standing,'' said Michael D. Ray, president of the South
Florida chapter of the American Immigration Lawyers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the family makes it past that hurdle to an evidentiary
hearing, they must convince a judge the boy deserves asylum here _
another hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just say he needs asylum because of the general bad
conditions in a country,'' Ray said. ``It has to be particular
action by the government directed at an individual. In this case,
Elian is a hero in Cuba, so how are they going to convince a judge
that he would be persecuted if he went back?''
</P>
<P>
   The family's other strategy _ to stall until Congress reconvenes
on Jan. 24 in the hopes that a special bill will give Elian U.S.
citizenship or residency _ also faces hurdles. President Clinton
would have to sign such a bill, and he has made it clear he backs
Meissner's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bills are introduced in Congress all the time but are
rarely successful,'' Perlmutter said. ``In this case, it would be
for a child of a very tender age, and over the objection of his
father.''
</P>
<P>
   While Reno and federal officials seem to have the law firmly on
their side, Reno also seems to realize the volatility of the Miami
exile community and the difficulty of actually taking possession of
the boy without the family's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami native, Reno said again Thursday that she won't forcibly
take the boy away from his Miami family.
</P>
<P>
   And lawyers for the family said they will abide by a court
ruling, even if it means sending Elian back to his father.
</P>
<P>
   But observers of Miami's tumultuous politics say that doesn't
mean the boy's return, when and if it comes, will go smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``INS's strategy has allowed a lot of mischief to emerge,'' said
Abraham. ``The politics of this situation don't provide much
optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
