<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     01-13 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: IRVING ON `CIDER HOUSE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ John Irving, one of the nation's most celebrated
novelists, says he has no patience whatsoever with authors who sell
their books to Hollywood and then complain all the way to the bank
about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one who feels writers should complain about films made
from their novels, even if they're bad,'' said Irving, who adapted
his book ``The Cider House Rules,'' for the screen. ``What do they
have to moan about? It's a kind of childish whining. If they're so
purist in their views of novels not working out as films, then
don't sell the rights. No one's twisting your arm to sell the
rights in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving admitted that his experience in Hollywood had pleased
him, especially ``The Cider House Rules,'' which has generally
earned positive reviews and moved into more theaters around the
nation last week. ``I feel as proud of that film as any of my
novels, and I never thought I'd say that about a film based on a
novel of mine,'' he said. ``Cider House,'' directed by Lasse
Hallstrom, features Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron, Michael Caine,
Delroy Lindo and Paul Rudd. It is a saga about an orphan named
Homer Wells who embarks on a journey of self-discovery after
leaving an unconventional but loving orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   Two other films have been adapted from Irving's novels: ``The
World According to Garp,'' directed by George Roy Hill, and ``The
Hotel New Hampshire,'' directed by Tony Richardson. More recently,
``Simon Birch'' was loosely suggested by an Irving book, ``A Prayer
for Owen Meany.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving, who said he was happy with all three of those films, had
not written a screenplay from one of his novels until ``Cider
House.'' (A memoir of his experiences on that film, ``My Movie
Business,'' was published last year by Random House).
</P>
<P>
   He said he found writing a screenplay far easier than writing a
novel. With a movie, ``you don't have the same kind of
responsibility for the language,'' he said. ``It's the absolute
attention to the language that's essential for a novelist. That's
not the case for a screenwriter. As a screenwriter you're simply
erecting the scaffolding for a building that someone else is going
to make, and that someone else is the director. When I feel like
being a director, I'll write a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The director and novelist are, in many ways, mirror images, he
said. ``When you are writing a novel, you are demonstrating to a
reader exactly how something looks and sounds and smells and feels.
The exactness of details is in your hands. In films that's the job
of the director, not the writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing a novel takes Irving about four or five years. ``I'm
just now creeping to the end of my 10th novel,'' he said. It took
him only six months or so to write the ``Cider House'' screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an exercise in writing, a screenplay is pretty easy
compared to a novel,'' he said. ``What's not easy is finding the
right people to write it for: the director, the producer, the
actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving has completed his second screenplay from one of his
novels, ``A Son of the Circus.'' He said he had been working on the
script, off and on, for about 10 years. The film is tentatively set
to start production in the next few months, with a cast that
includes Jessica Lange and Jeff Bridges. But Irving, speaking like
a Hollywood veteran, said nothing was ever certain until filming
actually began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty optimistic,'' he said. ``But you never want to say
anything is definite. `Cider House' almost went into production
three times. And it was almost canceled. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Roar, but No `Lion'
</P>
<P>
   Julie Taymor, who earned two Tony Awards for the Broadway
version of ``The Lion King,'' has been working for years on the
screen adaptation of Shakespeare's ``Titus Andronicus.'' She staged
this violent drama Off Broadway at the Theater for a New Audience
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the play,'' said Ms. Taymor, whose newly opened film
version, ``Titus,'' stars Anthony Hopkins and Jessica Lange. ``And
it so lends itself to cinema. The story is incredible. You've got
eight or 10 great roles. And it's about something that's
extraordinarily timely, violence. The story demands that we examine
the very root of violence in a time when ethnic cleansing, genocide
and racism have almost ceased to shock us.'' Nearly as an
afterthought, she said, ``It's a tremendous contrast to `Lion
King.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Taymor, one of the most provocative and imaginative
directors and designers in the performing arts, said she realized
that her first film had some similarities to her own ``Lion King.''
Both have powerful animal imagery. Both bear the imprint of
Shakespeare. ```The Lion King' is loosely based on `Hamlet,' and it
has a simple mythic story which is similar to `Titus,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new film, which is littered with ritual killings, torture,
suicide and rape, involves the return of the Roman general Titus
Andronicus, (Hopkins) after a long war. Soon he confronts the
revenge of Tamora, queen of the Goths, the new wife of the emperor,
for the ritual killing of her son.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Taymor, the saga of revenge and violence is nothing less
than Shakespeare's most relevant, disturbing and most entertaining
work of art. ``It's about how one becomes violent, what drives
someone to violence, whether it's war or religious belief or lust
or vengeance,'' she said. ``Look at Littelton. Or Timor. Or Bosnia.
There's nothing in `Titus' that's not happening today.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, now being shown in New York and Los Angeles, expands
around the nation next Friday. Ms. Taymor had never made a feature
film before ``Titus,'' and she said she found the experience far
more exhausting than the theater. ``What surprised me were the
complications getting it done, the sheer tenacity you need to keep
going,'' she said. There were money problems, poor weather in Rome
and Croatia, where the film was made, language problems with the
crews, bureaucratic complications. ``It was like manipulating an
army,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater is consuming, too, but it's far more
controllable,'' she said. ``You're in one city, you're in the same
theater. You're not dealing with the fact that the sun goes down at
3 in the afternoon in Croatia, and then it becomes freezing cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taymor has several film projects planned, including a
comedy, ``The Transposed Head,'' based on a story by Thomas Mann.
Several other offbeat projects are also in the works. ``I'm not
attracted to the easy,'' she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy of the Heart
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone denies that he's turning more mellow. But this
filmmaker, who eagerly welcomed controversy with movies like
``Nixon,'' ``J.F.K.'' and ``Natural Born Killers,'' is clearly
embarking _ at least for the moment _ on a creative path that's
different from the one he has followed over the last decade.
Instead of dealing with conspiracies, politics and the dark side,
Stone is turning his attention to a love story.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, an Oliver Stone love story.
</P>
<P>
   He is now in Poland, scouting locations for the film, ``Beyond
Borders,'' which focuses on a romance over more than a decade
between two relief workers. One will be played by Kevin Costner,
who was a star of Stone's most controversial film, ``J.F.K.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone, said he was making the new film for one reason: ``My
mother.'' She has implored him for years to make a love story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised my mother before it was too late that I'd do a love
story,'' said Stone, who said his mother, Jacqueline Goddet Stone,
who lives in New York, was in her late 70s. ``She always loved
`Gone With The Wind.' She always said I'd do a great love story.
This is the complete opposite of football, of `Natural Born
Killers.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of his mother, Stone said, ``I'd love to make her happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's current film, ``Any Given Sunday,'' is one of his more
mainstream and successful movies in recent years. An intimate look
at pro football _ with its moneyed owners and universe of players,
coaches, team doctors, sportswriters and party girls _ the film,
starring Al Pacino, has taken in more than $60 million and seems
headed for financial success. The reviews were mixed. Stephen
Holden, in The New York Times, said that the movie was a
``viscerally charged, razzle-dazzle ode to professional football as
a blood sport,'' but that it was marked by a ``ludicrously upbeat''
finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Given Sunday'' came about because of Stone's fascination
with football as a child in Manhattan, he said. He collected
football cards, tracked sports statistics and followed the careers
of his heroes, Y.A. Tittle, Dick Butkus and Johnny Unitas. Those
former football stars worked on the film; Butkus and Unitas
appeared in the movie as coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film really began with my nostalgia for football in the
'50s, which is so different from the game now,'' said Stone.
``There's no team loyalty now. It's all about making money. It's
about greed. There's this volatility in the culture that's apparent
now in sports as well as films. It doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to his forthcoming film, Stone was asked if the movie
would be a traditional love story. ``Nothing is traditional with
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
