<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5337 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKNOTES13-COX     01-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thriller taps into Cuban ties
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``I, Che Guevara'' (HarperCollins, $24) was published this
month, there were a few good reviews but little buzz about the
pseudonymous author, John Blackthorn. That all changed Wednesday,
when former U.S. Sen. and presidential candidate Gary Hart
announced he was Blackthorn.
</P>
<P>
   Set in contemporary Cuba, the novel explores what would happen
if Che Guevara had not been killed in 1967 and re-emerged as
Ernesto Blanco to lead a peaceful grass-roots revolt. Fidel Castro,
meanwhile, has offered to step aside and allow free elections if
the United States ends its embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the States, Victoria Savidge, a past-her-prime reporter
for an all-politics TV network whose aim is ``all scandal, all the
time,'' heads to Cuba for an interview with Blanco. Romance and
attempted assassinations follow.
</P>
<P>
   It's a thriller with a message, Hart said in a telephone
interview from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to use Cuba as a mirror of our own excesses and to
show the kind of corruption that exists throughout the whole
political system,'' said Hart, 63. ``And it's only gotten worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The media is not treated kindly in the novel, but Hart insists
that's only part of the corruption. ``It's a parody of the media's
excesses. It's not an act of revenge,'' said Hart, whose 1988
presidential campaign was derailed when the media exposed his
relationship with Donna Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show the effects of corruption and what would
happen if a true democratic movement would arise,'' said Hart, who
has visited Cuba and dined with Castro on several occasions in the
past three years. On some visits, he was asked to act as an
unofficial messenger between the two governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I used a pseudonym in the first place,'' said Hart,
who wrote a previous novel under the Blackthorn pseudonym (``Sins
of the Father'') and another thriller with Defense Secretary
William Cohen (``Double Man''). ``I didn't want to jeopardize my
usefulness as a conduit. But I was getting into the `Primary
Colors' problem with Anonymous, so I decided to go public.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Death in the family: Jervey Tervalon didn't have to go far to
find an idea for his second novel, ``Dead Above Ground'' (Pocket
Books, $23.95). The taut story of murder and revenge in New Orleans
is based on a tragedy that struck Tervalon's family in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cousin of mine decided she wanted to have an affair with
this man,'' Tervalon says. ``My grandmother warned her not to date
him, that he kills women. But my cousin said he was so
good-looking, she couldn't resist.''
</P>
<P>
   When the affair went sour and the cousin attempted to break up
with him, Tervalon says, she was found floating in the Mississippi
River in a trunk. In the novel, the main character, ``Mama'' Du
Champ, is modeled after Tervalon's grandmother. The strong-willed
woman tells a captivating tale of revenge, murder, pimps,
prostitutes, voodoo and a baby born to one woman and raised by
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to change a great deal of it, because often the factual
material was more bizarre than anyone would believe,'' says
Tervalon, a 41-year-old California screenwriter whose first novel,
``Understand This,'' dealt with teenage gang violence in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also wanted to protect my relatives,'' Tervalon says,
``because some of the principals are still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Tervalon will sign his book at 7 tonight at Chapter 11 bookstore
at Ansley Mall, 1544 Piedmont Ave. 404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary event: Just because Pat Conroy bowed out of a
proposed deal to write another sequel to ``Gone With the Wind''
doesn't mean he harbors any hard feelings toward Margaret Mitchell.
The author of ``Beach Music'' will be guest speaker Wednesday at
the Atlanta History Center for a benefit for the Margaret Mitchell
House and Museum. A coffee and dessert reception will follow the 7
p.m. lecture at McElreath Hall, 130 W. Paces Ferry Road. Tickets
are $20 and can be purchased by calling 770-578-3502.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Southern lit: William Gay (``The Long Home''), Fred Chappell
(``Look Back All the Green Valley''), Judy Goldman (``Slow Way
Back'') and Robert Morgan (``Gap Creek'') are among the finalists
for the Southeastern Booksellers Association's Book Award.
Nonfiction nominees are Janisse Ray (``Ecology of a Cracker
Childhood''), Bobbie Ann Mason (``Clear Springs'') and Ross Yockey
(``McColl: The Man With America's Money''). The awards will be
presented at a dinner at 7 p.m. April 1 at the Westin Atlanta North
at Perimeter. Information: 1-803-252-7755.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
