NYT-01-13-00 1827EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-SKUBE-THERAPY14-COX     01-13 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-THERAPY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Call for therapy is no guarantee of results
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knows how long it had been since John Rocker held in his
hand a No. 2 lead pencil, puzzling over A, B, C, D or None of the
Above? With its clean pink eraser and fresh yellow paint, the
simple instrument might as well have been a crowbar, prying open
the skull that people think is off-center.
</P>
<P>
   But even before Rocker took himself _ with no great enthusiasm _
to Baltimore for psychological testing, he was being recommended
for therapy. Anyone who said the things he said must need help.
Anyone that far outside the box we know as ``normal'' needs help
getting in it.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, Woody Allen made it almost fashionable to talk
of seeing one's ``analyst.'' Two and three times a week. In the
heyday of psychoanalysis, it was a New York thing. Neuroses were
badges of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Americans might not talk casually of seeing their
analyst _ the word's overtones are too darkly Freudian _ but
millions see a therapist regularly. They share more with their
therapist than they do with their family, friends or any clergyman,
all in the hope that they can find whatever it is that will make
them happy, fulfilled or just less anxious about life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Triumph of the Therapeutic,'' the sociologist Philip Rieff
once called it. If therapy has not entirely replaced religion it
has established itself firmly alongside, drawing upon the
peculiarly American faith in self-improvement and the newer belief
that self-knowledge _ and with it peace of mind _ is found through
psychological techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Americans not only expect happiness as a birthright _ as
promised in the Declaration of Independence _ but also exalt the
role of the specialist and the expert.
</P>
<P>
   Thus have therapists become our happiness experts, the Mr.
Goodwrenches who could help us look under the hood and show us what
screw was loose.
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker himself has made known no strong desire for therapy,
it's widely taken for granted he needs it. ``Get him into
therapy,'' a caller on a sports talk show said the other night,
compressing, in so many words, the sentiments of others.
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly is that going to do?
</P>
<P>
   Not all psychologists agree on therapy's limits or its
possibilities. Does it address a patient's personality, which can
be as superficial as the clothing he wears, or does it address the
character that makes him who he is? Can it address a patient's
character?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think therapy has been vastly oversold,'' says Jack Feldman,
professor of psychology at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would argue that psychotherapy helps people become who they
truly are,'' says John Paddock, a psychologist with a practice in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   What connects the two extremes is the belief in being oneself.
</P>
<P>
   But many people in therapy have to first find themselves, and
nothing guarantees that everyone will like the result. It might
just be that the John Rocker we know is the truest John Rocker
we'll ever see.
</P>
<P>
   In such a case, therapy isn't so much self-discovery as
self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a culture where someone who's out of the norm is
deemed in need of therapy, and that's not always the case,''
Feldman says. ``And it doesn't mean it's going to change anything.
If John Rocker's a jerk, he's going to stay a jerk. He may just
learn to keep his mouth shut when the press is around.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an uncomfortable fact for psychologists and others in the
mental health field that Nazis convicted at Nuremburg did not feel
particularly misunderstood or at loose ends. This is not, of
course, to elevate the importance of a 25-year-old relief pitcher
to the level of war criminals. But when Adolf Eichmann was captured
and tried in Jerusalem in the 1960s, people were appalled that he
showed no pathological symptoms. In The New Yorker, Hannah Arendt
coined the phrase ``the banality of evil,'' outraging thousands who
believed someone obviously monstrous could have come off to as an
everyday bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker defies the everyday, some psychologists wonder what
exactly Major League Baseball wanted to find out when it had him
undergo psychological tests. And whatever the results of those
tests, they divide on what therapy might or might not do for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therapy does generally work, but I don't know what people
expect,'' says Robyn M. Dawes, a psychologist at Carnegie-Mellon
University in Pittsburgh and a prominent researcher in the field.
``What I'd want to know is what the referral question was. You
don't just have someone take a battery of tests. There's something
you want to know, and I don't know what that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Paddock, who is also curious about Major League Baseball's
referral question, uses tests as ``a kind of actuarial predictor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No test is infallible,'' he says, ``but they have been shown
to be valid.''
</P>
<P>
   And they often point the way toward one kind of therapy or
another. ``Broadly construed,'' says Paddock, ``I do not see people
in psychotherapy as sick or crazy, but as people who are having
significant problems in life. I think of depression, for example,
as a problem in living more than as illness.''
</P>
<P>
   For most people in therapy, there is a certain ``logic'' to the
way they see the world. It might be a perverse logic, but without
it the world would make no sense. ``Typically,'' Paddock says, ``if
you dig hard enough and scratch long enough, you will find how it
worked _ it helped minimize a patient's anxiety, or it helped him
feel more secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Paddock talks of a patient's ABC's _ his affect, behavior and
cognition. ``We learn these based on our life experiences, usually
in our family,'' he says. ``When a person comes to me with a
significant problem, it's my job to figure out why it makes sense
in his way of seeing the world. I try to help him block old
patterns and teach him new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a catch, of course: People who are in therapy usually
want to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people don't understand the limits of therapy,'' says
Dawes, whose book ``House of Cards'' is critical of the profession.
``Yes, it can work. But it doesn't necessarily make the world
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1827EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0225 </DOCNO>
