<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBO-FLORIDA-NYTR &LR;      01-13 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-FLORIDA-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 FLORIDA, THE No. 1 FOOTBALL STATE  
 (bl)  
 By MIC HUBER   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Football is king in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way at the high school and college levels for a
long time, but now professional football in Florida has rejoined
the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the three pro teams that call the state home will
be playing conference semifinal games in the NFL playoffs. Two of
the three will be playing each other.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins take on the Jaguars at Jacksonville on
Saturday in a game scheduled to start at 12:35 p.m. The Tampa Bay
Buccaneers will host the Washington Redskins the same day, with the
kickoff set for 4:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That's three teams from one state among the eight NFL
organizations still playing for a spot in Super Bowl XXXIV. There
are 31 teams in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about that the other day,'' said University of
South Florida coach Jim Leavitt, who is busy this week trying to
recruit high school talent for his college program. ``That's
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL is the destination, finding the high school players
with football potential is where the journey begins. And college
football is the path most taken.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need voodoo economics to understand how football
success is generated in Florida. It is called the trickle-up
effect.
</P>
<P>
   High schools supply the college programs in the state with
talent. NFL teams draft the best talent available, more often than
not from the best college programs. And that often means Florida
State University, the University of Florida and the University of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's roster is dotted with players from Florida,
including stars Warren Sapp, Derrick Brooks, Brad Culpepper,
Warrick Dunn and Jacquez Green. Fred Taylor is the key to
Jacksonville's running game. The Dolphins wouldn't be here if not
for place-kicker Olindo Mare, who grew up in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For years, high school football programs in Florida has been
regarded as among the best in the nation. Teams and individual
players, alike, have received national recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that high schools have spring football and weight
training, the ability to be active outside year-round, and the
widespread popularity of football are among explanations for why so
many stars get their start in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Miami built college's dominant program of the
1980s by mining the gold coast for high school talent. Florida
State and Florida have been two of the most successful schools in
the 1990s on the football field by recruiting in high schools
throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more than enough players to go around. Almost
every major college football program east of the Mississippi has
followed the path to Florida in search of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Buchalter, a respected recruiting analyst and writer for
the Orlando Sentinel, estimates that more than 800 players from
Florida play Division I football. The NCAA doesn't keep those types
of figures, but many believe that is a conservative number.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Coker, the offensive coordinator at the University of
Miami, said he has heard 150 athletes from Florida get Division I
scholarships in any one year.
</P>
<P>
   FSU won national titles in 1993 and this past season. Florida
won its national championship in 1996. And since 1991, FSU, Florida
or Miami has played in the game that determined the national
champion in every year but one.
</P>
<P>
   When a state school hasn't played for a national title, it often
is a player from Florida that has helped the team that did win it.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State is one of the many teams that has found success
by recruiting in Florida. There were 10 players on the roster of
the team that beat Florida in the Citrus Bowl, held in Orlando on
New Year's Day. Three of those players are from Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sugar Bowl, both cornerbacks from Virginia Tech were from
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State head coach Bobby Williams pointed to the speed of
the Florida high school athlete as one reason teams search the
state. Spring training is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a Florida athlete, he is probably a little more
refined as a player when you get them out of high school,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring football is important,'' agreed Coker. ``It gives kids
that much more work and exposure, and the opportunity to improve
and refine their skills.'' It's not unusual for players from
Florida to step in as true freshman and play important roles at
major college programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow up playing football in Florida,'' said Leavitt, who
started playing in fourth grade. ``It is ingrained in you. Football
is the No. 1 sport in Florida and kids want to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida universities reap the rewards of those high school
athletes. And it is those schools that are dominating college
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning perpetuates winning,'' Coker said. ``If you win the
state championship, you have a good chance to be playing for the
national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those same Florida athletes who led their college teams
to championship are now doing the same in professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 27 players named to the All-Pro team, selected by
the Associated Press last weekend, played high school football in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive and defensive rookies of the year in the NFL _
Edgerrin James of Indianapolis and Jevon Kearse of Tennessee _ grew
up in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At the pro level, Miami has seen championships in the past. The
Dolphins played in three straight Super Bowls in the 1970s, winning
twice. In winning the 1972 championship, Miami became the only team
in modern NFL history to finish the season with a perfect (17-0)
record.
</P>
<P>
   Mic Huber writes for The Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla., which
is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
