u e BC-TV-CITY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      01-13 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CITY OF ANGELS': MORAL LESSONS OF A NEW SERIES AT AN URBAN
HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever noticed that when a review begins by praising
``the best of intentions,'' you can be pretty sure the other shoe
will drop within a couple of paragraphs?
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels,'' the new CBS drama series from Steven Bochco
and associates, must have been made with the best of intentions. In
portraying life in a gritty urban hospital, it transcends
television's usual narrow view of white American society, focusing
on a wide variety of black characters, from dedicated doctors and
sleazy administrators to ignorant street people. Its stories are
full of unambiguous lessons about overcoming prejudice. Its
production values are never less than first rate.
</P>
<P>
   But with its one-dimensional characters and relentless
preaching, it isn't compelling entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Clunk!
</P>
<P>
   The show, set in the down-at-the-heels Angels of Mercy Hospital
in Los Angeles, will be shown this Sunday night before moving into
its regular slot on Wednesdays. The series was created by Bochco
and two of his ``NYPD Blue'' colleagues, Paris Barclay, who
directed the premiere episode, and Nicholas Wootton, who wrote it
with Bochco. But viewers who expect to be pulled into the story by
the throat, as they are by the best ``NYPD'' episodes (glimpses of
heaven excepted) will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's hour, you'll meet the essential players, starting
with Dr. Lillian Price (Vivica A. Fox), the hospital's naively
earnest new medical director, and Dr. Ben Turner (Blair Underwood),
its broodingly earnest acting chief of surgery. They nearly married
seven years earlier, and Lillian still carries a torch.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how these extremely attractive people talk. Upon meeting
the hospital's creep of a CEO, Ron Harris (Michael Warren), Lillian
says: ``I want to pick your brain about Angels of Mercy _ get a
heads up on how to proceed with my agenda.'' Upon learning that the
hospital's lone Jewish intern, the droopy Dr. Geoffrey Weiss (Phil
Buckman), feels the sting of unvarnished anti-Semitism from black
doctors and support staff, Ben says: ``This can be a frustrating
place for everybody. Just have to take it in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   The patients are mostly salt-of-the-earth types from the
neighborhood, merely symbols like the doctors. The one supporting
character with some hint of life is the hospital's off-kilter
chairman, Edwin O'Mally, played with scenery-chewing relish by
Robert Morse. His evil-eye, gap-tooth grin may not be a substitute
for fleshed-out characterization, but in the land of dripping
dignity, the evil-eyed man is king, or at least a welcome relief.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's show, a black intern, Dr. Wesley Williams (Hill
Harper) learns a valuable lesson. Thinking that the young man lying
in the emergency room with a bullet wound is a gang member, Wesley
sends another patient to surgery instead, telling an astonished
nurse that he wants to ``give my brother some time to reflect on
his lifestyle decisions.'' But he sure is contrite when he finds
out that the wounded man, whose life is ultimately saved by Ben on
the operating table, is another hospital doctor who was attacked on
his way home.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of that episode, Lillian is begging Ben to become the
full-fledged chief of surgery. But he hates being an administrator.
It takes him away from saving lives, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in your heart you love Angels of Mercy,'' she says.
``Please. Be part of the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   He gives her a made-for-television smile and says, ``Nice try.''
Which also sums up the beginnings of ``City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a show you certainly want to encourage. So far, though,
it's not a show you want to watch.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CITY OF ANGELS'
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Created by Steven Bochco, Nicholas Wootton and Paris Barclay;
Rick Wallace and Wootton, supervising producers; Barclay,
co-executive producer; Dayna Kalins, producer; Caroline James,
executive in charge of production; Bob Simon, coordinating
producer. Produced by Steven Bochco Productions; Bochco, executive
producer.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Blair Underwood (Dr. Ben Turner), Vivica A. Fox (Dr.
Lillian Price), Michael Warren (Ron Harris), Robert Morse (Edwin
O'Malley), Hill Harper (Dr. Wesley Williams), T.E. Russell (Dr.
Arthur Jackson), Phil Buckman (Dr. Geoffrey Weiss), Maya Rudolph
(Nurse Grace Patterson), Viola Davis (Nurse Lynette Peeler).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
