<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Jan. 14 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Developments in the long-running
debate on the prices paid for prescription drugs by Medicare
recipients. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-BOY-SENTENCED (Pontiac, Mich.) _ In an unexpected verdict,
a state judge ruled here Thursday that the youngest American ever
charged and convicted as an adult of murder will serve a seven-year
sentence at a maximum-security juvenile detention center and then
be released. The judge, rejecting prosecutors' requests that the
boy be sentenced to additional time in an adult prison after
serving time in juvenile detention, rebuked a system that he said
had gone too far in punishing juveniles. His sentencing also bucked
a trend in which, increasingly, juveniles charged with violent
crimes have been sentenced as adults. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DRUGS-SCRIPTS (Undated) _ The White House drug office has
secretly been pushing TV networks for scripts with anti-drug
messages, and for at least a year has been helping edit the scripts
on selected shows. The White House provided millions of dollars of
financial incentives to networks to make sure the scripts were on
message. By Marc Lacey and Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   SAHARA-VILLAGE (Araouane, Mali) _ The sand woman came out of the
blackness of the village master's house into the desert light,
bearing a bowl of sand her hands had scooped from the doorway and
would deposit several feet away. It is a lifetime's work, this
struggle against the sand, for Souda Cissey and Araouane's other
sand women, a daily contest to prevent the Sahara from burying,
once and for all, this ancient village in West Africa. The world's
largest desert has already taken away a mosque and countless houses
in recent years, the rooftops of some still visible on the sand's
surface, others fallen into the Sahara's bottomless pits. The women
clear courtyards and doorways from dawn to dusk in Araouane, the
once fabled oasis six days by camel north of Timbuktu, the city at
the desert's edge. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Argun) _ The Russian military insists it has
taken back this Chechen town. But on Thursday Russian soldiers
nervously scanned the rooftops and windows of Argun's battered
buildings as they sought to keep order. ``There are snipers
around,'' a Russian officer called out. ``Take care.'' Set in the
Chechen lowlands, Argun was taken by the Russian military in early
December. Today, however, it has become a salient example of how
hard it may be for Russia to take Chechnya and keep it. All across
Chechnya, Russian troops tried to tighten their grip over the swath
of territory ``liberated'' by Russian forces. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLD-BLACKHOLES (Atlanta) _ In a discovery that could help
explain the origin of the earliest galaxies, a new astronomy
satellite has detected the first discreet objects in a mysterious
glow of X-rays that pervades the distant universe. Some of the
faintest of the radiation sources, astronomers said, could be the
most distant objects ever observed. They promise to be important
clues to conditions in the cosmic dark age, the period after the
creation of the universe that began with the big bang and before
the emergence of stars that gave light to the firmament. By John
Noble Wilford.
</P>
</TEXT>
