<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Jan. 14. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BUSH-ADS (Undated) - Choosing Arizona for his experimental canvas,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush plans to air the first ever
Spanish-language television ads in a Republican primary, and
Arizona Sen. John McCain, trying to hold his own against Bush, will
likely also put up ads, aides to both campaigns said. The
television ads could be particularly influential in Arizona because
the candidates are spending most of their time campaigning
elsewhere, and the TV spots are likely all that voters will see of
them. As of today, no campaign swings through Arizona are planned
by any presidential candidate until February. By KRIS MAYES. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TEACHERPAY (Phoenix) - The disparity between teacher pay and other
professional salaries continues to grow, according to the latest
report on the topic. In Arizona, for example, teachers with a
bachelor's degree make $28,106, compared to $43,051 for all other
career folks with the same level of education. Arizona ranks 34th
when it comes to teacher pay, which is one notch higher than last
year. All of this makes headlines as the teacher shortage kicks
into high gear. We talk to teachers and find out what school
districts are trying to do to lure educators, including signing
bonuses in some states. By KELLY PEARCE. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASUSAT1 (Tempe, Ariz.) - The world's first space launch of the
millennium will carry ASUSat1, a diminiutive satellite built by 400
students from Arizona State University in Tempe. The launch from
Vandenberg is scheduled for Jan. 14. By BEVERLY MEDLYN. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOUINARD (Phoenix) - When a hysterical Erica Chouinard, wife of
Diamondbacks relief pitcher Bobby Chouinard, dialed 911 on
Christmas, she joined more than 91,000 people who called police
last year in Arizona to report domestic violence. Like Chouinard,
23,000 people - mostly men - were arrested. The Maricopa County
Attorney's Office prosecuted more than 2,000 cases last year. There
are no statistics to show how they were resolved in court, but a
sampling of similar cases shows that many defendants went to
prison. By VICTORIA HARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
