<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-SINGER-0114-CO     01-13 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SINGER-0114-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    LATIN POP STAR, WANTED ON CHILD-CORRUPTION CHARGES, CAPTURED IN
BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In an act that rivaled Madonna, she spanked her
male fans with belts, held a microphone to her crotch and ridiculed
Mexican politics.
</P>
<P>
   And since she became a fugitive more than a year ago, famous
Mexican pop singer Gloria Trevi has been sighted more often than
Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Trevi finally surfaced for real after Brazilian
police arrested her and her manager on charges in their native
Mexico that they had lured young girls into Trevi's act and abused
them as virtual sex slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Trevi and her manager, Sergio Andrade, were detained by police
in an exclusive neighborhood of Rio de Janeiro Thursday morning,
according to the office of Mexico's Attorney General. The pair was
on a list of fugitives from the law maintained by Interpol, the
international police force.
</P>
<P>
   Trevi rose to fame throughout Latin America, Spain and in
Spanish-speaking parts of the United States in the late 1980s and
early 1990s. Originally from an upper-class family in Monterrey, an
industrial city in northern Mexico, Trevi crafted a sexy,
rebellious image and sang songs in a raspy voice that challenged
men, parents and authority in general.
</P>
<P>
   She became known as Mexico's Madonna because of her skimpy stage
outfits and her twin image as a sex object and feminist fed up with
male domination.
</P>
<P>
   She often posed nearly nude for calendars and posters and amused
fans with her theatrical claims she would one day run for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans have been mesmerized by Trevi's fall from extravagant
pop star to fugitive on the run. On Thursday television stations
breathlessly reported details of the arrest and replayed tapes of
Trevi prancing on stage in torn clothing, tossing her trademark
mane of reddish-brown hair and rubbing Coca Cola over her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm the best daughter in the world. I'm not
saying I'm the best Catholic in the world,'' Trevi said in an old
taped interview, clearly relishing her reputation as a successful
rebel. ``But I love my parents and I worship God.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities are charging Trevi, 30, and her manager,
Sergio Andrade, 44, with corrupting minors by encouraging them to
join a ``school'' and promising to train them to become singers and
dancers in Trevi's group.
</P>
<P>
   The family of one girl, 17-year-old Karina Yapor, told
authorities their daughter was instead sexually abused by Andrade
and forced to work as a prostitute in addition to singing in
Trevi's chorus. They said the girl was 12 when she signed up to
join Trevi and Andrade, who managed and produced Trevi's music.
After Yapor joined the group, her parents said, she severed contact
with her family.
</P>
<P>
   Yapor's parents found out last year that she had been living in
Spain for a time and had given birth to a son. The child has been
turned over to Yapor's parents in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Yapor returned to Mexico in December and tearfully offered
interviews contradicting her parents, saying Andrade was not the
father of her son and that he had never raped her. She said she was
never held against her will.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade's ex-wife, who was also a member of the troupe, and
another girl, tell a different story, however. They claim that they
and other women were virtual prisoners and that Trevi regularly
procured girls for Andrade's pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-wife, Aline Hernandez, wrote a book about the alleged
scandal that captured headlines. Trevi and Andrade both denied they
had committed any abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade owns a home in McAllen, Texas, where it was rumored that
he and Trevi were in hiding at one point. They were also reportedly
spotted in various parts of Mexico and South America. The Mexican
Attorney General's office says it has information confirming that
Trevi and Andrade had traveled through Argentina and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico enlisted the help of Interpol, the international police
force, to track down Trevi and Andrade.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested with the pair on Thursday was Maria Raquenel, a singer
in Trevi's band, ``Boquitas Pintadas,'' or ``Little Painted
Mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss can be reached by e-mail at:
susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
