<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HARRODS-PHILIP-NYT &LR;      01-13 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRODS-PHILIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCE PHILIP CUTS OFF HARRODS CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Buckingham Palace announced on Thursday that it was
withdrawing the royal warrant awarded by Prince Philip, the Duke of
Edinburgh, to Harrods, the London department store that is owned by
Mohamed Al Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   A palace spokesman said the decision was based on a falloff in
business from the duke, who originally granted his endorsement in
1956. ``The warrant will not be renewed because of the significant
decline in the trading relationship between the household and
Harrods over several years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He made no reference to the fact that six weeks ago Al Fayed
called the prince a Nazi sympathizer and accused him of
masterminding a plot with the British security services that
resulted in the 1997 Paris car crash that killed Diana, Princess of
Wales, and her companion, Al Fayed's son.
</P>
<P>
   The Harrods owner had made those allegations in responding to an
unsuccessful libel suit brought against him by a disgraced
Conservative former member of Parliament _ and in court Al Fayed
challenged Prince Philip to sue him if the allegations were untrue.
It appeared on Thursday that the prince had come up with a less
litigious response.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second royal snub of Harrods in the last month. In
December, the queen switched her annual order of 1,500 Christmas
puddings for the palace staff from the famous department store to
Tesco, a leading supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed, 66, is an Egyptian-born businessman who has lived here
for more than three decades and who has conducted a noisy public
campaign since 1994 to persuade Britain to grant him citizenship.
Over the last two years, he has become a particular irritant to the
royal family by persistently theorizing that the Paris crash was a
conspiracy planned by British secret security forces to satisfy
royal objections to a possible marriage between Diana and Al
Fayed's son, Dodi Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed had no public reaction on Thursday, but his spokesman,
Laurie Mayer, said: ``We feel the commercial impact on Harrods
would be negligible. The cachet of royals shopping at Harrods no
longer has the same impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrods now has a year to remove the royal arms from its
stationery, goods, offices and delivery vehicles. Governed by
strict regulations, the warrant enables holders to use the legend
``By appointment'' and to display the royal symbols on its
products.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Brooks-Baker, publishing director of Burke's Peerage,
said the loss of the warrant would hurt Harrods because of what it
signified for the foreign tourists who have a particular reverence
for things royal. Harrods gives its warrant high visibility, with
blown-up full color replicas installed outside its illuminated
Knightsbridge building that can be seen from many blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect that has on people coming from Europe and the
Americas, for example, as well as this country cannot be
underestimated,'' Brooks-Baker said. ``It adds very significantly
to the value of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrods received its first royal warrant in 1913 from Queen Mary
and is one of the few stores in Britain to have them from all four
royal personages with the power to grant them: the queen, the Duke
of Edinburgh, Prince Charles and the Queen Mother.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed might have reason to stay in touch with the palace
staff requiring him to dismantle the ducal warrants. The warrants
from the queen and Prince Charles come up for renewal next year.
</P>
<P>
   Formal recognition of tradesmen who supplied the monarch began
in the middle ages, but it was during Queen Victoria's reign that
the practice of granting royal warrants became established.
</P>
<P>
   There are some 1,100 active warrants, with 20 to 30 new ones
approved and a similar number dropped each year. They have
historically been given to people who became the royal merchant of
choice for such things as coach whips, dog food, cherry brandy,
ceremonial robes and wax flowers.
</P>
<P>
   A Glasgow company is in charge of the bagpipes that greet the
queen when she goes to Scotland, a Lancashire haberdasher makes the
Buckingham Palace chefs' clothes and an Aberdeenshire expert in
stuffing animals and mounting skins is the monarachy's favored
taxidermist.
</P>
<P>
   Records unearthed by The Press Association, Britain's domestic
news agency, show that during the 18th and 19th centuries, royal
warrants included a pinmaker, rat catcher and mole-taker. A man
named Thomas Hewytt was once called upon to ``Serve the Court with
Swannes and Cranes and all finds of Wildfoule.''
</P>
<P>
   The royal cold shoulder may one day nudge furious new statements
against the palace from Al Fayed, but what it brought forth on
Thursday from his spokesman, Mayer, sounded more like something
delivered with a stiff upper lip. ``The Duke of Edinburgh,'' he
said, `` is perfectly entitled to shop wherever he likes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
