<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Jan. 16,
2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE: EURO-ENGLISH-FILMS. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE Story &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACKIE-SUSANN-FILM (Undated) _ Before she started writing
fiction, ``Valley of the Dolls''; ``The Love Machine'' and ``Once
Is Not Enough,'' Jackie Susann spent the better part of three
decades trying to be a star before she died at 56, so it would no
doubt delight her that she's the subject of ``Isn't She Great,'' a
near-slapstick comedy with a melancholy undertow written by Paul
Rudnick and directed by Andrew Bergman. Loosely based on ``Wasn't
She Great?,'' a 1995 New Yorker article by Michael Korda, who
edited ``The Love Machine,'' the film opens Jan. 28 and stars Bette
Midler as Susann. By Karen Durbin. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAMES-TOBACK-FILMS (New York) _ Few film directors can boast a
career like James Toback's. Fewer still might want to. Half a dozen
movies that have not always rubbed critics the right way, or
translated into huge box office profits (or losses, for that
matter). And yet, at 55, this idiosyncratic writer-director still
makes the movies he wants to, lures marquee stars, finds the money
men and, lately, makes the cut at the big film festivals. By Rick
Marin. (Moved). Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NINTH-GATE-FILM (Rome) _ Seated at a corner table at Il
Matriciano, one of his favorite haunts during the dolce vita of the
'70s, Roman Polanski was discussing his desire to make an
important, lasting film. Almost impatiently, he explained that his
latest release, ``The Ninth Gate,'' was not it. ```Ninth Gate' is
fun, it's nice, I think it's a good movie, but after all, what is
it about?'' asked Polanski, 66, the Polish-born director whose
repertory includes ``Repulsion,'' ``Rosemary's Baby'' and
``Chinatown.'' ``It's like every other movie that is made nowadays.
It may be different in style, but it doesn't make any important
statement.'' Actually, ``The Ninth Gate,'' is an occult thriller
opening March 31 that features satanic rituals, exotic locales and
gruesome deaths, and stars Johnny Depp. By Alessandra Stanley.
(Moved). Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL-PEOPLE-FILM (London) _ ``Beautiful People,'' is Jasmin
Dizdar's first feature film, which opens in New York in February.
The film by the young Yugoslav who has become a British citizen, is
a humorous, affectionate and poignant portrayal of a cross section
of Britons whose lives are unexpectedly disrupted by the Bosnian
nightmare in the fall of 1993. ``Beautiful People'' won the Certain
Regard competition at the 1999 Cannes Film Festival. By Alan
Riding. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-SIERRA-FILM (San Francisco) _ Humphrey Bogart was born on
Christmas Day in 1899, and we're sure to be inundated this year
with juicy behind-the-scenes tales about the making of beloved hits
like ``Casablanca'' and ``The Big Sleep.'' But the movie that
marked him as a towering star who would redefine crime movies, and
action films in general, was Raoul Walsh's stirring 1941 melodrama,
``High Sierra.'' With John Huston turning writer-director, he and
Bogart went on to make ``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``Across the
Pacific,'' ``The Treasure of the Sierra Madre,'' ``Key Largo,''
``The African Queen'' and ``Beat the Devil'' _ arguably the most
diverse and compelling credits ever compiled by an American
actor-director team. Although Huston was only the co-writer, ``High
Sierra'' deserves a place near the top of that list. (It returns to
the small screen in March as part of Warner Home Video's new Bogart
Collection.) By Michael Sragow. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BREATHLESS-FILM (Undated) _ An amiably cocky Frenchman in
sunglasses steals a car, mugs people for petty cash to romance a
cute American student and tries to collect money from shady
characters so he can run away with her to Rome, but she seems more
interested in flirting with contacts to secure a writing job,
besides which she is pregnant by the Frenchman and he seems
indifferent to this fact, while a police manhunt closes in on them
both. No wonder they called it ``Breathless''! Actually, the
original title, ``A Bout de Souffle,'' might be better translated
as ``Out of Breath,'' with more somber connotations. Forty years
after it shook up the movie world, Jean-Luc Godard's brilliant
provocation is being revived at the Film Forum in New York City for
one week, April 7-13, in a new print. By Phillip Lopate. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (New York) _ Vincent Canby reviews Peter Shaffer's
``Amadeus'' at the Music Box Theater. (Moved). Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STUTTGART-BALLET (Stuttgart, Germany) _ Two years ago, New York
audiences witnessed the first of the Canadian Reid Anderson's
accomplishments when the Stuttgart Ballet performed at the Lincoln
Center Festival '98: two by its former director, John Cranko's
masterpieces, ``Onegin'' and ``Romeo and Juliet,'' provided a
showcase for the company's dramatic and technical skills. This week
the company returns to New York on Wednesday for four days at the
City Center during a seven-city tour with what it calls ``the other
side of Stuttgart,'' five new pieces (plus one by Cranko, who died
in 1973). By Kate Mattingly. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ZANDER-MUSIC (Undated) _ What is it about Boston and musical
cult figures? The opera producer Sarah Caldwell and the pianist
Russell Sherman are merely the more prominent of recent decades. If
a musician can make it there, in that hotbed of musical culture and
tradition, you might think, he or she can make it anywhere. The
quintessential cult figure of the moment is Benjamin Zander, 60, a
conductor and the founding music director of the Boston
Philharmonic Orchestra. By James R. Oestreich. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEPORELLO-MUSIC-FILM (Toronto) _ On the principle that every
exit is an entrance somewhere else, Tom Stoppard once wrote
Rosencrantz and Guildenstern, Hamlet's dim college pals from
Wittenberg, title roles in a show of their own. Now Barbara Willis
Sweete, a founding partner of the Canadian film production company
Rhombus Media, is doing the same for Leporello, the sidekick of
Mozart's Don Giovanni. Her hourlong film-within-a-film
``Leporello,'' which strings together in their original order
excerpts from Mozart's sulfur-singed operatic masterpiece, will be
introduced at festivals next fall, with television broadcasts to
follow on PBS and cultural channels around the world. By Matthew
Gurewitsch. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIAF-IMITATOR (Undated) _ Where singers are concerned, imitation
is often the insincerest form of flattery. Imitating the sound of
someone else's voice is never solely an act of homage, however
inspired by admiration. Rather, it is a kind of cannibalization,
with one singer feeding on a more singular existing voice and
saying: ``Hey, I can do that. But this way.'' Raquel Bitton, 38, a
cabaret singer from San Francisco, is, to put it mildly, stuck on
Edith Piaf. Since discovering the repertory of Piaf in 1982, Ms.
Bitton, who was herself born in Marrakesh, Morocco, has helped
produce a show about the legendary French chanteuse for National
Public Radio, consulted on a television documentary, composed a
play with music about Piaf's friendship with Jean Cocteau, written
the scenario for a full-length Piaf ballet and, most decisively,
learned to sing very much like her idol. By Barry Singer. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARCADES-PROJECT (Undated) _ Some of us don't read fiction. We
live on history, biography, criticism, reporting and what used to
be called belles lettres. We will be feasting on Walter Benjamin's
``Arcades Project'' for years to come. Just published by Harvard
University Press in the first full English-language edition, ``The
Arcades Project'' should also win readers with broader tastes. A
sprawling, fragmented meditation on the ethos of 19th-century
Paris, ``The Arcades Project'' was left incomplete on Benjamin's
death in 1940. In recent decades, as portions of the book have
appeared in English, the unfinished opus has acquired legendary
status. ``The Arcades Project'' surpasses its legend. It captures
the relationship between a writer and a city in a form as richly
developed as those presented in the great cosmopolitan novels of
Proust, Joyce, Musil and Isherwood. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PAINTERS-ART (Madrid, Spain) From the 15th century to the
18th century, many fine painters were wooed with money, security
and status and in exchange spent their time glorifying the
``ideology'' of the Roman Catholic Church and exalting assorted
popes, monarchs and military heroes. They also produced prodigious
art. This was certainly the case with three masters of the
post-Renaissance, whose relationship with power is the subject of
``Velazquez, Rubens, Van Dyck: Court Painters of the 17th
Century,'' a new exhibition at the Prado Museum in Madrid that runs
through March 5. Each artist had his own style of painting, but
they nonetheless had much in common: their careers coincided during
two decades; they supported the Catholic Counter-Reformation;
Velazquez and Van Dyck looked up to Rubens, 22 years their senior;
and all revered Titian, who died in 1576, the year before Rubens's
birth. But what most united them was that they were first and
foremost court painters. By Alan Riding. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VALIE-EXPORT-ART (Undated) _ Since the late 1950s, the Austrian
artist, Valie Export, has been challenging images of the female
body in media through her own prodigious output of videos, films,
performances, photographs, installations, documentaries and
writings. Represented in scores of exhibitions in Europe since the
1970s, the 59-year-old artist is only now receiving her first solo
exhibition in the United States, from Tuesday through Feb. 27 at
the Goldie Paley Gallery of the Moore College of Art and Design in
Philadelphia. By Michael Rush. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FRANCE (Paris) _ France cleans up after uncommon storms.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ London fancy: Boutique Victorian; Vail
adds 520 acres for skiers and boarders; A Minnesota museum move to
the riverbank; Taking public transit? These maps will help; Daumier
goes to Washington. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
