<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORE OF A LEGEND AND HIS BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   New Releases of Video Cassettes: Reviews by New York Times
Critics  
(dal) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LORE OF A LEGEND AND HIS BLUES
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure about the death of the blues musician Robert
Johnson, except that it was in 1938 at the age of 27. In Robert
Mugge's documentary ``Hellhounds on My Trail: The Afterlife of
Robert Johnson,'' Willie Coffee, a childhood pal of Johnson's in
Mississippi, says the cause was pneumonia. Another source contends
that Johnson was poisoned in a juke joint by the husband of one of
his lovers. The death certificate says syphilis. Coffee reiterates
that it was pneumonia. Anyway, no one knows where Johnson,
enigmatic and mercurial, is buried. Supposedly there are two
graves.
</P>
<P>
   Packed with history and lore and scalding Johnson blues from the
likes of Bob Weir of the Grateful Dead, Honeyboy Edwards, Joe Louis
Walker, Billy Branch and Robert Lockwood Jr. (Johnson's stepson),
``Hellhounds'' is to be released by Winstar on tape and DVD on Jan.
25. Also on Jan. 25, Winstar will issue ``Deep Blues: A Musical
Pilgrimage to the Crossroads,'' a Mugge documentary that begins in
Memphis and winds through northern Mississippi and the rest of
blues country.
</P>
<P>
   Both films are part of a five-film Mugge retrospective that
opens at the Screening Room in Manhattan on Jan. 21. About 20 Mugge
movies about music and musicians from many places but primarily the
South date to ``George Crumb: Voice of the Whale'' in 1976. Those
on video, also from Winstar, include ``Gospel According to Al
Green,'' about the soul star who turned to gospel, and ``Black Wax:
Gil Scott-Heron,'' with the jazz and rap musician performing in
1982 at the Wax Museum Nightclub in Washington. These two films
will also be shown at the Screening Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Blues'' was made in 1990. ``The mission is not only to
document artists who are out of the mainstream,'' Mugge, 49, said
in an interview, ``but also tell about people who are in it for the
music and not for the money.'' Booker T. Laury sings ``Memphis
Blues,'' R.L. Burnside ``Jumper on the Line,'' Jessie Mae Hemphill
``You Can Talk About Me.'' Everywhere is original male pain,
searing and teary. ``Daddy, when is Mama comin' home?'' cries Big
Jack Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson wrote the blues' strongest songs in the '20s and
'30s. In ``Deep Blues'' Lonnie Pitchford sings two: ``If I Had
Possession Over Judgment Day'' and ``Come On in My Kitchen.'' The
film visits Bentonia, Miss., where Johnson is said to have sold his
soul to the devil, a Yoruba sprite and trickster, for mastery of
the blues.
</P>
<P>
   His influence spread to performers like Muddy Waters and on to
the Rolling Stones and the British rockers. After Johnson's songs
were finally copyrighted, Eric Clapton was one of many artists
asked to pay fees for being so derivative. As the story is told in
``Hellhounds,'' he gladly complied.
</P>
<P>
   The film is built around a Johnson symposium held at the Rock
'n' Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland in 1998. The title, a play on
the Johnson song ``Hellhound on My Trail,'' refers to all the
Johnson experts and fans, Mugge included, gathered in a gleaming
I.M. Pei building dedicated to rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a gentle satire of middle-aged white guys _ scholars,
journalists, musicians, filmmakers _ all just obsessed with this
black itinerant musician,'' he said. ``You can't miss the irony.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   BOWFINGER
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. 107.37; DVD, $26.98. 97 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Jan. 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unable to afford the action star Kit Ramsey (Eddie Murphy), the
hard-pressed but indefatigable movie producer Bobby Bowfinger
(Steve Martin) plans to trail Ramsey around town with a camera and
have actors Bobby can afford (meaning they work on spec) accost
Ramsey at the deli or wherever and film whatever transpires for
Bobby's space flick, ``Chubby Rain.'' If that sounds crazy,
remember that it took Tom Cruise two years to realize he had been
in a vampire movie. Eventually, though, Bobby must turn to a Ramsey
look-alike named Jiff (also Murphy). Jiff is pretty good, too,
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, as is Frank Oz's
``Bowfinger,'' which is ``smoothly directed and acted with glee.''
</P>
<P>
   TWIN FALLS IDAHO
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $27.95. 110 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Summoned to a desolate hotel room, a wild, gorgeous young
prostitute named Penny (Michelle Hicks) finds a different kind of
client: a gaunt pair of conjoined twins, Blake and Francis
(portrayed by the identical twins Mark and Michael Polish). The
stronger of the two, Blake, is more attracted to the kind-hearted
Penny. Odd man out and with no place to go, Francis languishes as
he and Blake face larger issues of dominance in a partnership that
can no longer survive. This they do in a film, directed by Michael
Polish, with ``style, gravity and originality to spare'' (Janet
Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE 13TH WARRIOR
</P>
<P>
   1999. Touchstone. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 103 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Jan. 18 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Between a crashing score and a monosyllabic screenplay, it's
hard to get one's bearings in John McTiernan's film. Exiled from
Baghdad for a sexual indiscretion, a poet named Ahmed (Antonio
Banderas) travels to a faraway land, and on the way meets a band of
Norse warriors who enlist him to help combat a flesh-eating demon
army. Anyway, heads roll in a ``slaughter-by-numbers swashbuckler
whose climactic battle seems almost perfunctory compared with what
has come before'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   AN IDEAL HUSBAND
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse his position in Parliament on an Argentine canal
project, and Mrs. Cheveley (Marianne Moore) will spare the dashing
Sir Robert Chiltern (Jeremy Northam) certain disclosures that will
cost him his political career and his marriage to the lovely,
moralistic Gertrude (Cate Blanchett). Robert's friend Lord Arthur
Goring (Rupert Everett) advises that he confess to Gertrude. Robert
balks, but Arthur unexpectedly shines as a wise confidant in Oliver
Parker's likable adaptation of Oscar Wilde's play. Unfortunately,
though, ``as the movie zips along (especially in its second half),
the drama begins to thin'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL FARM.
</P>
<P>
   1999.. $14.98. 89 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barely mentioned in George Orwell's classic, Jessie the dog
becomes the melodious-voiced narrator in TNT's stylish adaptation,
which recalls how rebellious animals took over the farm only to
have their egalitarian dreams destroyed by a megalomaniac pig named
Napoleon. Peter Ustinov, Patrick Stewart, Kelsey Grammer, Paul
Scofield and Pete Postlethwaite supply voices in a shrewd and
thoughtful version of the story, Caryn James wrote in The New York
Times, that nevertheless ``misses that tenuous balance that made
Orwell's work so enduring.''
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE HEART ROAMS.  &QL; 
1987. . $89.95. 80 minutes. &QL; 
George Paul Csicsery's acclaimed documentary follows romance
novelists, their fans and their publishers as they take a jaunt
from Los Angeles to New York on the Love Train.
</P>
<P>
   THE SIMPSONS GO HOLLYWOOD. &QL; 
1999. Fox. $24.98, three cassettes. 45 minutes. &QL; 
Six episodes supposedly spoof Tinsel Town. See Marge try out for
the role of Blanche Du Bois in a musical version of ``A Streetcar
Named Desire''; Willie the groundskeeper strike oil in the high
school basement; Smithers come to the conclusion that he shot
Burns, though Homer gets blamed for the crime; Bart accidentally
gains fame on the ``Krusty the Clown Show''; Krusty relaunches his
career with a TV special starring Bette Midler, the Red Hot Chili
Peppers and others. What does most of this have to do with
Hollywood? Does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
