<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-STUTTGART-BALLET-2TAK     01-13 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUTTGART-BALLET-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURTURING CREATIVITY, WITH A WORLDWIDE VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Kate Mattingly teaches dance history at Ballet Tech, New York's
public high school for dance.  
 By KATE MATTINGLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUTTGART, Germany _ In the late 1960s, the Stuttgart Ballet, an
obscure German troupe, catapulted to international fame under its
charismatic director, the choreographer John Cranko. Then in 1973,
Cranko died suddenly, and the company was left to carry on and
redefine itself.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Canadian Reid Anderson, a member of the
Stuttgart Ballet from 1969 to 1985 and the artistic director of the
National Ballet of Canada from 1989 to 1996, took over the
directorship.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, now 50, saw his mission as four-pronged: to perform
works choreographed by Cranko _ to ``keep John alive'' _ and to
perform classic productions, ballets by 20th- century masters and
``the brand-new.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, New York audiences witnessed the first of
Anderson's accomplishments when the Stuttgart Ballet performed at
the Lincoln Center Festival '98: two of Cranko's masterpieces,
``Onegin'' and ``Romeo and Juliet,'' provided a showcase for the
company's dramatic and technical skills.
</P>
<P>
   This week the company returns to New York during a seven-city
tour with what it calls ``the other side of Stuttgart,'' five new
pieces (plus one by Cranko). This time at City Center for four days
starting on Wednesday, the company will present two programs of
ballets by a multinational group of choreographers: in addition to
the piece by the South African-born Cranko, there are works by
Italian, American, German and Dutch dancemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Since September 1996, Anderson has presented 15 new ballets.
``I'm not talking about a ballet new to the company,'' he says.
``I'm talking about (italics)brand-new(end italics) ballets''
commissioned by and for Stuttgart. ``I have the great good fortune
that I can afford to do so much new repertory _ both monetarily and
as far as my audience is concerned. You have to be able to afford
to fail because making art is a risk. You just hope you pick
somebody with enough talent to do something that lasts over a long
period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The American choreographer Kevin O'Day said during a telephone
interview from his home in New York that he appreciated the
willingness to take risks: ``Here, the presenters want to do the
same stuff that they know will sell tickets _ Merce, Paul Taylor,
Alvin Ailey. Presenters won't take a chance because the reality of
selling tickets is too strong. I get a different kind of sense in
Europe, where the government supports the arts.'' O'Day's ``Delta
Inserts,'' which had its premiere in Stuttgart last April, has its
New York debut on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Stuttgart Ballet ``has gone through a huge metamorphosis in
the last three years,'' Anderson says. The caliber of his dancers
has been foremost among his concerns. In 1996, he let go a number
of company members in order to reshape the ensemble (today, 75
percent of the dancers are his hires).
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in Stuttgart's opera house, Christian Spuck, a company
member, vividly remembers Anderson's talks with the dancers. ``I
was fired,'' he recalls with a grimace. But soon afterward,
Anderson saw Spuck's first piece of choreography and changed his
mind. Not only did the director want Spuck to dance for the
Stuttgart Ballet, but he also wanted his first piece of
choreography in the company's repertory.
</P>
<P>
   This week Spuck's ``Dos Amores,'' his fifth ballet, has its New
York premiere. The German dancemaker, who has already attracted
considerable attention in the European dance world, acknowledges
the freedom Anderson offers: ``Reid gives me everything. I can
choose all the dancers, the ballet master I want to work with. He
says: `Christian, don't be scared. Do what you think you have to
do. It is not important, success or not. You have to find your own
way. And that is fine.' That's quite something for a director to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stuttgart Ballet is renowned for nurturing choreographic
talent. Several of today's leading balletmakers _ William Forsythe,
Jiri Kylian, Uwe Scholz _ started choreographing as members of the
company and went on to direct European troupes. Unlike these
directors, Anderson is not a choreographer, but like Cranko, he is
attracted to and supports innovative choreography. ``I think it's a
positive that I don't choreograph because I am building a company
that dances a wide spectrum of repertory,'' he said. ``That's what
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Anderson's first commissions, ``Kazimir's Colors,'' by
the Italian Mauro Bigonzetti, appears on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In Stuttgart in late December, Bigonzetti rehearsed the lead
couple for his ballet. They were the third cast _ Anderson likes to
give as many dancers as possible the chance to perform _ but looked
first rate. Bigonzetti's ballet, inspired by his visit to a Kasimir
Malevich exhibit in Florence, dresses the dancers in bold colors.
The partnering is asymmetrical, off kilter; the man often moves the
woman by the elbow or underneath the arms. Bigonzetti, who directs
Aterballetto in Reggio Emilia, watched the dancers, gently chiding
``easy, easy'' as they risked everything to get it right.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The approach of the dancers is fantastic,'' Bigonzetti said,
sitting in the Opera House canteen after the rehearsal.
``Everybody's curious: they want to know, they want to see, they
want to do different things. It's incredible that they can do the
modern ballet, the classic ballet and the Cranko ballet. I love
this.'' What makes this possible? ``Their mentality,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation is the John Cranko School: more than 50
percent of the company graduated from this school, which offers
professional training for German and international students.
Anderson may not choreograph, but he does play a major role in
selecting highly qualified dancers from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The nationalities in the 68-member ensemble include Spanish,
Swiss, Russian, Canadian, Ukrainian, Polish, Japanese, Yugoslavian,
Israeli, Czech, Australian and German (English is their lingua
franca).
</P>
<P>
   Scholz's ``Notations,'' a 12-minute solo set to music by Pierre
Boulez, has its New York premiere on Friday, danced by the
globe-trotting star Vladimir Malakhov. A principal dancer with the
Stuttgart Ballet and the American Ballet Theater and a guest artist
with the Vienna State Opera Ballet and the State Opera of Berlin
(Unter den Linden), Malakhov travels extensively in order to work
with the best companies and choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no company in the world that has repertory like
Stuttgart,'' says the Ukraine-born dancer. Scholz created the solo
specifically for Malakhov.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography of ``Notations,'' a showcase of virtuosic
feats, demands constant shifts in space and energy; explosive leaps
are juxtaposed with tight spinning steps. ``It's difficult because
the music is not Mozart,'' Malakhov says, ``it's only sounds.''
Moreover, a hip problem impeded Scholz's ability to demonstrate
movement; Malakhov needed to interpret what the choreographer
wanted. ``I tried to catch all the movement like he wants me to
do,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another display of skill, Cranko's ``Initials R.B.M.E.,'' leads
off both City Center programs. Created in 1972, the ballet,
featuring 40 dancers, highlighted the particular talents of
Cranko's star dancers Richard Cragun, Birgit Keil, Marcia Haydee
and Egon Madsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very special time for the company, and a friend of
John's suggested the second piano concerto of Brahms,'' Anderson
recalls. ``John listened to it over and over again. I remember very
clearly he was very up and very positive. It was autumn: a
beautiful Indian summer _ the colors of the trees were
extraordinary. When he talked about the set and costume design with
Jurgen Rose, they decided that each movement of the Brahms would
have a feeling of a different season.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Hans van Manen's ``Kleines Requiem'' is an austere
ballet for an ensemble of seven. Originally made for the
Netherlands Dance Theater, the company van Manen directed in the
1960s, ``Kleines Requiem'' takes its title from the score, Henryk
Gorecki's ``Kleines Requiem fur Eine Polka.'' Anderson acquired the
piece after seeing its 1996 premiere in the Netherlands. ``It makes
a nice mix with all the other pieces,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the works at City Center reveals a different facet of
20th-century ballet choreography. ``They are all abstract: there
are no tutus and no big sets,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Day, who danced in Twyla Tharp's company and Forsythe's
Frankfurt Ballet, creating a ballet for Stuttgart was a
life-changing experience. ``I feel like I have to leave New York
now because there is no place for me to hang my hat,'' he says.
``In Stuttgart, there is such openness. I tell Reid my idea about
making `Delta Inserts' into a full-evening ballet and he says:
`Sounds great. Let's do it.' In New York, I am working for a lot of
people, but presenters worry about selling tickets with something
that is new. In Europe, there is more possibility for the creative
stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1909EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
