u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-740&AMP;ADD     01-13 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS TRY TO READ BETWEEN THE LINES OF `WORKING DRAFT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A leak of an American working draft of an
Israeli-Syrian peace treaty has created something of a stir here
with the suggestion that Israel is seeking to keep its settlers on
the Golan Heights after a military pullback from the area.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the document, which was distributed by American
mediators last week to both Syrian and Israeli negotiators in
Shepherdstown, W.Va., effectively sets out the opening position of
each side on the central issues under discussion, including future
borders and security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The text was leaked to the Israeli newspaper Haaretz, which
published it Thursday, along with photographs of the document.
</P>
<P>
   Under an introductory disclaimer that it is meant to serve as
``a tool in discussions'' and ``does not necessarily reflect the
views of any party,'' the draft treaty includes two passages
attributed to Israel that many Israelis interpret as an attempt to
retain Jewish settlements on the Golan even after a military
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The document also notes the Syrian position that Israel must
withdraw both its soldiers and civilians from the entire strategic
plateau captured from Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Though Israelis familiar with the Israeli-Syrian issue saw no
change in the widely held perception that Israel will have to cede
at least most of the Golan Heights _ and withdraw its settlers _ as
the price of a peace agreement, the leaked document seemed to serve
efforts to convince the Israeli public that its government was not
selling out. About 100,000 Israelis demonstrated against giving up
the Golan Heights on Monday as Prime Minister Ehud Barak returned
from a negotiating session in Shepherdstown.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are scheduled to resume next week in
Washington, and President Clinton discussed the next round of talks
Thursday in a long phone conversation with President Hafez Assad of
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   What attracted attention in Israel were two references in the
draft document. One referred to the withdrawal of the Israeli armed
forces ``and civilians'' from the Golan Heights as solely a Syrian
position. The other cited an Israeli position that there would be
``arrangements concerning the Israelis and Israeli communities in
areas from which Israeli forces will be relocated'' _ a reference
to the 17,000 Golan settlers.
</P>
<P>
   These items created the impression that Barak was bargaining to
keep the settlers in place, even though the notion that Israeli
settlers would remain under Syrian sovereignty has been rejected by
both the Syrians and the settlers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a clever maneuver by the prime minister,''
said Ariel Sharon, the leader of the opposition Likud Party. ``The
prime minister knows that it will be impossible to live under
Syrian rule. He's perhaps trying to soften up the hard core that is
struggling today against a withdrawal from the Golan Heights. I
know that the prime minister frequently studies the writings of
Machiavelli. This is a perfect example.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Minister Yossi Sarid, of the leftist Meretz Party,
affirmed that keeping the settlers on the Golan ``is an Israeli
position.'' But he added, ``I would be very happy if this position
were accepted by the Syrians, but the chances of a positive
response are slight to nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Uri Savir, a lawmaker who served on the Israeli delegation to an
earlier round of talks with Syria that collapsed nearly four years
ago, said that although leaks such as the disclosure of the
American draft might serve domestic political aims, they would not
help the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually every leak has its purpose,'' Savir said. ``From the
point of view of the negotiations, I don't think such publications
are helpful. The minute the three sides keep a secret, it's a test
of the seriousness of their intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said
the publication of the document was damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It harms the cause of peace,'' he said. ``It makes it harder
for the kind of confidentiality that's necessary to make decisions
to be understood or expected by those who have to make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A Syrian account of the American draft was published on Sunday
by the influential London-based newspaper Al-Hayat, this one
emphasizing Syria's demand for the removal of Israeli settlements
and its insistence on a full Israeli withdrawal from the Golan to
lines held before the 1967 war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Key members of the Senate Appropriations Committee, who ended a
two-day visit to Israel Thursday, said that the United States could
provide substantial funds and peacekeeping troops to bolster an
Israeli-Syrian treaty, but that the burden had to be shared by
other nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certain we can meet whatever objectives the administration
and Congress agree to,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, the
committee chairman. ``We don't know what those will be yet, but we
assume they'll be substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   The five committee members toured the Golan Heights and Israel's
border with Lebanon on Wednesday, meeting later with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has promised the Israeli public that Israel
will receive sophisticated defense and early warning systems to
offset the risks of a withdrawal from the Golan. However, Stevens
said that no financial sums were discussed in the meeting with the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard no numbers, and we didn't expect to hear any
numbers,'' he said. ``We're not at that stage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
