<HEADLINE>
HIGHWAY PROJECT UNEARTHS ANCIENT BOSTON HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a major find, archeologists working in downtown
Boston have unearthed part of Mill Creek, a colonial waterway in
the heart of the old city whose sediment is expected to provide a
broad glimpse of day-to-day living conditions in early Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists working under contract with the Big Dig say the
discovery near Haymarket will illuminate the lives of common
Bostonians from the earliest days of settlement to the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   The long-filled creek, a catch-basin for a vast variety of
human, plant and animal deposits, has yielded ``a record of
environmental change in the city that's unprecedented,'' said
Stephen Mrozowski, a University of Massachusetts at Boston
professor who is chief archeologist for the find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysis of this will reconstruct in tremendous detail the
changing environment of that part of Boston from initial occupation
up through the mid-19th century,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Soil and sediment recovered from Mill Creek, now buried 10 feet
under Blackstone Street, are expected to provide a timeline stocked
with clues about landscape, climate, sanitation, diet and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Excavation at the site began after a Big Dig backhoe struck
artifacts Nov. 16 behind a parking garage near the Holocaust
memorial. The digging yielded two, 2,200-pound millstones, large
pieces of a wooden wheel that turned the stones, wooden bulkheads
that supported the creek bank, leather shoes, animal bones, and a
thick layer of history-rich sediment.
</P>
<P>
   Early colonists dug Mill Creek in 1643 from Mill Pond, which
bordered present-day Haymarket, to the harbor near Faneuil Hall.
Tidal action in the creek was used to power a succession of grist
mills that ground grain for the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The two millstones, intact and remarkably preserved, were
discarded into the creek from a nearby site where the grist mills
had been located since 1646. The stones are believed to date from
the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   UMass archeologists met this week to discuss how to analyze the
findings. Excavation ended Dec. 21 and the site has been re-filled.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as the millstones are _ and they are believed to
be the finest such artifacts ever found from colonial Boston _ the
true treasure is encased in the creek bottom, archeologists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have samples of garbage from the bottom of the canal, and
we're going to be looking for pollen and insects and parasites,''
said Robert Hasenstab, staff archeologist for the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can look at the local environment of Boston's colonial
period: what kinds of plants and trees were growing in the area,
what kinds of bugs were crawling around, and maybe get some
information on disease residing in the trash and the animal bones
and meat scraps.''
</P>
<P>
   The end result: a people's history that gives a day-to-day
subtext to the well-known political headlines of colonial and
revolutionary Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Historical markers of common life have been found before,
including during the 1994 excavation of a nearby 17-century privy.
But what makes the Mill Creek find so intriguing, Mrozowski said,
is the nearly 200-year accumulation of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The privy site was ``fairly specific,'' Mrozowski said. The new
dig has more potential, he explained, ``because basically all of
this botanical material (native to early Boston), all of this
pollen, is making its way into Mill Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   The creek, whose tidal flow powered the grist mill, also was
used as a dumping ground for residents and merchants clustered in
the heart of their growing city. Analyzing this discarded material,
as well as the botanical evidence, should show changes in
landscape, disease, climate and sanitation, Mrozowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what we know of the city is a political or economic
history. We tend to forget that, as all that's going on, there's
another level of reality that's shaping daily life,'' Mrozowski
added. ``What this allows us to do is put all of Boston's history
in a new environmental context that lets us reread it in a way that
may alter what we think about the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The find was unexpected, Hasenstab said, because a decade-old
study had concluded that the area was too disturbed for much
archeological recovery. But after the first millstone was
discovered, the hunt was on: Archeologists recovered another
complete millstone, 5 feet in diameter, and four pieces that each
comprise about one-third of a millstone.
</P>
<P>
   About half the wooden gearwheel that drove the mill was found,
still bearing the cogs that turned the machinery as tidal water
from the harbor rushed along the creek.
</P>
<P>
   Mill Pond was filled between 1807 and 1828; the creek met the
same fate in the early 1830s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
