<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET'S BRIGHT LIGHTS, CIRCA 2000: ELECTRIC COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Norris Column) 
(dal) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices began this year by continuing the 1999
swoon, as Wall Street worried that the Federal Reserve might keep
tightening the monetary noose until the economy _ or the stock
market _ cried uncle. But even as interest rates racheted up,
something strange happened. The woebegone electric utility stocks
began to rally.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? It has long been taken for granted that utility stocks
always fall when interest rates rise. After all, electric companies
borrow a lot of money, and thus suffer when rates rise, and their
shares appeal only to the diminishing band of investors who value
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   So it is worth asking why the stocks are rising. Perhaps it is a
signal that bond rates do not have much farther to rise. Maybe the
move is an early warning that the Fed's rate increases are starting
to slow the economy, something likely to send stock investors
searching for shares whose recession exposure is limited. Perhaps
money managers fleeing technology stocks are trying to buy
something safe. ``I call it the anti-tech movement,'' said Steven
I. Fleishman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   To owners of utility stocks, the idea that they are safe
investments must seem odd. Last year the Standard &AMP; Poor's electric
utility index plunged 23.5 percent, its worst performance in a
calendar year since the monster bear market of 1974, when almost
every stock fell. Meanwhile, the S&AMP;P 500 rose 19.5 percent in 1999.
The best performer of the 29 stocks in the S&AMP;P electrics slid 5.6
percent. The worst lost 37.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the weakness was caused by rising interest rates, of
course, and year-end tax selling may have delivered a final blow to
the stocks. There were worries about how companies would fare as
competition intensified, but it appears that most states are
treating the incumbent companies well as they set the rules for
playing in the new era of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Then the tables turned as the new year began. The electrics are
up 3.7 percent, while the S&AMP;P 500 is down 1.3 percent. No doubt
some traders, in the time-honored if not exactly tasteful Wall
Street cliche, will dismiss the recovery as nothing more than a
dead-cat bounce. They probably expect that Yahoo, which has tripled
or better in each of the last three years but is down 20 percent
this year, will resume its levitation, and they may be right.
</P>
<P>
   But the chances are good that those who are buying the electrics
now will seem wise in a year or two. ``Valuations are at historic
lows,'' noted Pamela Bonnie, the electric watcher for Salomon Smith
Barney, when she turned bullish on the industry last month.
</P>
<P>
   Those valuations are getting noticed. In 1999, Warren Buffett's
Berkshire Hathaway led a group that bought one utility, MidAmerican
Energy. Another utility, TNP Enterprises, parent of Texas-New
Mexico Power, agreed to be acquired in a leveraged buyout sponsored
by a Canadian bank. (When that deal goes through, the holding
company's chairman will be William Catacosinos, whose tenure at
Long Island Lighting in New York left him with more popularity
among investors than customers.)
</P>
<P>
   The newfound interest of financial players in electric utilities
is a tribute to the fact that utility cash flows have not
diminished, even as their stock prices have. A third of the stocks
in the S&AMP;P electric index raised their dividends last year, and the
index now sports a healthy 5.4 percent dividend yield. The stocks
are cheap, regardless of whether Wall Street's love affair with the
Internet is over or about to become more passionate than ever.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
