<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HOMERUNS-CAPITAL-BOS &LR;      01-13 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMERUNS-CAPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYPRESS GROUP BUYS INTO ON-LINE GROCERY COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A New York equity firm, Cypress Group, Thursday agreed
to invest $100 million in HomeRuns.com of Somerville as it acquires
an undisclosed majority interest in the on-line grocery delivery
business.
</P>
<P>
   With plans to expand into 20 other unspecified markets over
three years, HomeRuns.com will be headed by Robert J. Tarr Jr.,
former chief executive of Harcourt General Inc. and The Neiman
Marcus Group.
</P>
<P>
   Hannaford Bros. Co., the Maine-based supermarket chain that
started HomeRuns.com and has run it as a wholly owned subsidiary,
will retain a ``significant investment'' in the on-line service.
HomeRuns.com will continue to buy its inventory from Hannaford at a
``substantial discount,'' Tarr said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarr, who left Harcourt General three years ago, said the
HomeRuns.com management team will be kept intact. Currently, the
company operates only in the Boston market, where it claims to have
about 40,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a terrific platform for growth,'' Cyprus's
vice chairman, James L. Singleton, said of HomeRuns.com.
</P>
<P>
   A deal such as this one was expected. Even before it agreed
recently to be acquired by a Belgian company, Hannaford had said it
needed outside capital to expand HomeRuns.com.
</P>
<P>
   Despite big upfront costs, the on-line grocery business is a
crowded aisle in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The prize is the more than $450 billion that US consumers spend
on groceries a year. Even if on-line retailers divert only a
fraction of sales away from supermarkets, the niche could still be
one of the biggest consumer categories in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   No one, including HomeRuns.com, has reported a profit yet,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research Inc. of Cambridge estimates that consumers
spent $513 million on line for groceries last year, and that the
number should hit $1.1 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy A. DeMello, founder and chief executive of rival
Streamline.com Inc. of Westwood, said on-line grocery sales could
reach $70 billion in five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   With its dense population and its suburbs full of Web-savvy
consumers, Greater Boston is one of the most competitive on-line
grocery markets in the country, DeMello said. Soon, though, many
major markets could have as many choices as the Boston area does
now.
</P>
<P>
   Besides HomeRuns.com and Streamline.com, some Greater Boston
consumers can also buy groceries from Peapod Inc. of Skokie, Ill.,
which is aligned locally with Stop &AMP; Shop Cos., and from
ShopLink.com Inc. of Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Webvan Group Inc. recently attracted attention
with plans to spend $1 billion to build a national network of
highly automated warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's HomeGrocer.com Inc. of Washington state, which has
financial backing from Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Each grocery company offers a variation on the home-delivery
theme. But with so many players, consolidation is likely.
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts, on-line grocery services need high-volume
sales if they're to have any hope of making a profit. That means
rapid expansion to many markets.
</P>
<P>
   Groceries may be the foot in the door for outfits that will
deliver a wide range of higher-margin items, such as dry cleaning,
videos, beauty products, and beer and wine.
</P>
<P>
   HomeRuns.com plans to apply for a liquor license, Tarr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is mostly about being a delivery business,'' said David
Cooperstein, director of on-line retail research at Forrester.
``Someday, you may have three selections for getting something to
your home: FedEx, UPS, or WebVan.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else may set on-line groceries apart from other retail
categories on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe that repeat customers are the key to making on-line
profits, and on-line grocery services seem to inspire more consumer
loyalty than do Web sites selling books or CDs, said Matt Stamski,
a senior analyst at Gomez Advisors in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because groceries are bought so frequently, consumers
tend to get ``committed'' to an on-line grocery service, he said.
``It's not like an on-line bookstore, where you can zip in and out
in 30 seconds. That's why on-line grocery services have phenomenal
(customer) retention rates.''
</P>
<P>
   That consumer commitment is sometimes a requirement. Many
services require weekly delivery and membership fees of about $30 a
month, though HomeRuns.com does not. Placing an order on line can
initially take 45 minutes or more, but that can be shortened as a
consumer becomes more proficient at navigating frequently upgraded
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on Hannaford's board, Tarr said he watched HomeRuns.com
for several years. The company does not disclose financial results,
but Tarr said they're ``materially higher'' than those of publicly
traded rivals. That led him to approach Cypress about investing in
HomeRuns.com, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
