<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIG DEEP WITH INFORMATICA 1.0
</HEADLINE>
  (David Bloom's weekly Digital L.A. column on the intersection of
entertainment and technology) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Sat. Jan. 15. Note (AT) symbol in tag) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Off and on over about three decades, Stewart Brand and his
cohorts created various versions of ``The Whole Earth Catalog'' and
the equally useful quarterly Whole Earth Review.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific resource for people trying to find the best
tools and technology for all kinds of tasks, because Brand defined
the term ``tool'' in the broadest possible way, with essays,
reviews and contact information on everything from computer
software to post-hole diggers.
</P>
<P>
   The last catalog came out few years back, the quarterly shut
down then reopened for a while under other, less interesting
management, and Brand went off to write books about the 10,000-year
clock. Thankfully, however, something of the Whole Earth spirit is
living on, with the release this month of Informatica 1.0.
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``access to the best tools for mastering the
information revolution,'' it fancies itself a Whole Earth Catalog
without the manure spreaders (other than metaphorically speaking;
he does include some politically oriented Web sites).
</P>
<P>
   It's a great resource, loaded with reviews, excerpts, tips on
buying things like laptop computers and broadband services, even
goofy odds and ends like a search through an IBM database of U.S.
patents for hits on the term ``mouse trap.''
</P>
<P>
   Each page-long review gives prices, contact information,
background, related resources, even a product's likely obsolescence
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The book nicely rewards a sustained read, or the serendipitous
opening to a random page. And though the book's organization feels
a bit haphazard, it is functional enough, with an index and table
of contents to make searching a bit more straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect part of my problem is that I long for a good search
engine for the book itself, and ``paperware,'' to use Black's term,
isn't so good for that. I'm guessing a more effective electronic
search tool is included in the CD-ROM (which I didn't get to
review) that can be bought in a bundle with the book, or
separately, through
</P>
<P>
   Author Peter M. Black also promises to issue regular,
downloadable disc updates to the book through the etronica Website,
creating what he calls in the introduction ``a kind of a magazine,
but without the lag time of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   A cool, quirky compendium of goodies for the digital age, I
highly recommend this book even with its minor shortcomings. After
all, as Black admits, this is version 1.0, and the first version of
anything technological always stinks. Imagine how great this will
be when Black hits his stride. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A HIT OF MYTHIC PROPORTIONS
</P>
<P>
   When the third-person fantasy strategy game Myth hit store
shelves a few years ago, it knocked a lot of players for a loop. It
was really one of the first games, particularly on the Mac side, to
do something interesting with 3-D graphics, and was hailed as one
of the year's best. Its successor, Myth II: Soulblighter, was
almost equally praised.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bungie has gathered up the two games, a scenario pack
called Chimera, a bunch of other multi-player levels created by
fans of the game, and electronic versions of strategy guides for
the two games and put them in one three-disc package: Myth, The
Total Codex.
</P>
<P>
   The games aren't as ground-breaking as when they came out, of
course, but there's still lots to love here, with excellent
graphics and good gameplay, plus free Internet play on the
wonderful Bungie.net Website against other Myth-sters. Best of all,
the collection comes with a great price: $19.95. Don't Myth out. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WANTS TO MAKE SOME REAL MONEY?
</P>
<P>
   All the PC gaming companies may have figured that something like
Quake III Arena or Tomb Raider: The Last Revelation would be the
Christmas season's biggest seller, but a funny thing happened on
the way to the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   According to gaming magazine Next Gen, the holiday box-office
champ for PC games turned out to be the computer version of the
insanely popular TV game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,''
minus the moolah when you answer Regis' questions correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The title from Disney Interactive and Jellyvision is certainly
entertaining enough, if lacking that certain something that comes
with sweating over an answer worth a million bucks. It's only
$19.99, though, which probably explains a bit of its wide-ranging
consumer appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope, however, that this PC-side success (there's also an
online version at www.abc.com) doesn't spawn the same execrable set
of copycats that the TV program did. ``Greed: The PC Game'' doesn't
work for me. And if I see a commercial for one more ``Who Wants
...'' knockoff before the February sweeps period kicks in, I'm
gonna make like Janet Leigh (or Neve Campbell) and scream. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THROUGH THE ROOF
</P>
<P>
   With the Consumer Electronics Show safely behind us, it's a good
time to note that the show's sponsor, the Consumer Electronics
Association, has now declared DVD the fastest selling consumer
electronics product ever.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics companies sold 349,000 DVD players in the product's
first year, 1997, then jumped to 1.08 million units in 1998. Final
figures for 1999 are expected to top out around 3.5 million, and
that doesn't count millions more DVD-ROM drives installed in
computers of even modest cost, such as those by budget-conscious
e-Machines and Avatar Technologies' V-Box.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about 5 million DVD players have already been sold,
compared to about 1.1 million VCRs between 1975 and 1977, and 1.2
million CD players between 1983 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, CEA officials said, almost 10 times as many DVD
players were sold in their first year as CD players were, back in
1983. Of course, DVD players are helped by the fact that they are
backward compatible, in that they can also play CDs, whereas CD
players definitely couldn't play cassette or 8-track tapes or vinyl
records.
</P>
<P>
   Digital televisions, by the way, have been selling pretty well,
too, topping out at more than 100,000 units this year, despite a
couple of pretty substantial problems: they cost a lot, anywhere
from $4,000 to $20,000, and there's still not that much to watch,
random sporting events and the CBS evening lineup notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   My latest fave pick for a great DVD is ``The Wall,'' the old
Pink Floyd film that has been completely redone for the digital
age. Just as digital versions of ``Dark Side of the Moon'' were an
early favorite among audiophiles with compact-disc players, so too
will this be with DVD cognoscenti.
</P>
<P>
   The whiz kids over at Sony's High-Definition Data Center put the
original print through a transfer to sparkling high-definition
video, and the soundtrack was carefully remastered to 5.1 channels
from the original stereo under the direction of Chief Floyd, Roger
Waters.
</P>
<P>
   They put in a ton of extra goodies, including two different
documentaries about the film and band. The film itself may not have
been blessed with the visual jaw-droppers of ``The Matrix'' (aka
``The Film That Sold a Million DVD Machines''), but it's a great
disc.
</P>
<P>
   For oddball disc releases just in time for Valentine's Day (yes,
men, it's almost that time, so think ahead), how's about Fox
Consumer Products' release of three two-episode volumes of ``Ally
McBeal''?
</P>
<P>
   Fox is also issuing a boxed, two-disc compilation of all six
``Ally'' episodes, a Vonda Shepard music video and a booklet with
excerpts from ``Ally McBeal: The Official Guide.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you have legitimate wonders about many times you can
watch ``Ally,'' or what impact it might have on your love life, Fox
is also releasing some legitimately romantic movies, like ``Hope
Floats,'' ``Ever After'' and ``One Fine Day.'' Float on. &QL; 
_____
</P>
<P>
   To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloom(AT)earthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. This column
and related material can also be found all week at
www.dailynews.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
