<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5400 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SAHARA-VILLAGE-(TRIMS     01-13 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAHARA-VILLAGE-(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REMOTE SAHARA VILLAGE STRUGGLES AGAINST SAND AND HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARAOUANE, Mali _ The sand woman came out of the blackness of the
village master's house into the desert light, bearing a bowl of
sand that her hands had scooped from the doorway and would deposit
several feet away.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lifetime's work, this struggle against the sand, For
Souda Cissey and Araouane's other sand women, this struggle against
the sand is a lifetime's work _ a daily contest to prevent the
Sahara from burying, once and for all, this ancient village in West
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the world's largest desert has already taken
away a mosque and countless houses, the rooftops of some still
visible on the sand's surface, others fallen into the Sahara's
bottomless pits.
</P>
<P>
   The sand women clear courtyards and doorways from dawn to dusk
in Araouane, the once-fabled oasis six days by camel north of
Timbuktu, the city at the desert's edge, and nine days south of the
salt mines of Taoudenni, a place so desolate and forbidding that
political prisoners were once left there and told they could dig in
return for food and water, or run away.
</P>
<P>
   But run where in the Sahara?
</P>
<P>
   The sand women work except on days when the wind is so strong
that, sweeping down as it does from the eastern dunes, it blows
over sand much faster than they could ever clear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's easier,'' Ms. Cissey, barefoot, said, looking down at
the ever-widening space she had cleared before the entrance. ``The
further you get away from the door, the easier it becomes. You have
less to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30 families still left here have resisted the larger forces
that drove most away: the disappearance of the trans-Saharan camel
caravan, which once served as the main method of trade with the
African interior; the desertification that began with the severe
droughts of the early 1970s and killed the shrubbery necessary to
raise cattle; a rebellion against the Malian government by desert
nomads in the early 1990s that doomed a New Yorker's quixotic
attempt to plant trees in Araouane.
</P>
<P>
   So today, dunes cresting at 40 feet surround this village about
160 miles north of Timbuktu. Smaller dunes have formed inside the
village in the areas between the mud-brick houses, which seem to be
sinking deeper and deeper into the depressions. Sand rises as high
as the rooftops of many houses, whose owners clear only the
entrance. At other houses belonging to people too weak or old to
clear the sand, or too poor to hire the sand women, the inhabitants
must step down from the sand into their homes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' said Bela Bilali, an old man, though perhaps not
the 90 years he claimed to be. ``But what can I do except keep
removing the sand? I rest, then I get up again.''
</P>
<P>
   As his 2-year-old grandson stood beside him sucking on a piece
of raw lamb fat, the old man lay on a pile of sand in front of his
mud house. Although he could not recall the details, he said he had
lost two or three houses to the sand in recent years, the last one
when the wind blew for three straight weeks. Undefeated, he had
rebuilt on the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   Across his house, two other old men, laying still on the sand
and wrapped in blankets to shield themselves against the wind and
sand, told similar tales of lost houses.
</P>
<P>
   Abdi Sultan, a Muslim holy man in his 70s, only his wizened face
showing, recalled that in his youth there were more than 100 houses
here. Many used to be built close together in rows, he said. But
the houses at the ends would bear most of the sand; the homeowners
in the middle invariably refused to help clear the sand, so the
entire row would eventually be buried. Nowadays, houses are built
far apart from one another.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   People are believed to have settled in Araouane even before
Timbuktu was founded in the 11th century. The nomadic Berbers known
as the Tuaregs chose this spot because of its wells and grass for
their cattle, said Abdi Mohammed, imam of one of the three
remaining mosques. The Moors, a people of mixed Berber and Arab
descent, eventually took over the area and brought Islam. They also
brought black slaves from the south to take care of animals and
perform other tasks in a rigid hierarchy that survives to this day.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 3,000 people are thought to have lived here once,
Mohammed said. Now there are only a couple of hundred souls, who
depend entirely on passersby or trips to Timbuktu for food. ``The
people who have decided to stay in Araouane,'' the imam said,
``will stay until the end of their lives or until the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the village served as a stopping point on the
camel caravan trade centered in Timbuktu. Traders brought salt from
the north and exchanged it for gold from the African interior.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the salt is almost worthless, though worth enough to send
Araouane's young black men to dig in the Taoudenni mines during the
current cool season. Moorish or Tuareg traders leading caravans of
30 to 40 camels, with each beast carrying four salt tablets
weighing several hundred pounds in all, pass through Araouane
almost daily on their way down to Timbuktu.
</P>
<P>
   Hamane Hilla, an irrepressibly cheerful man in his 70s, recalled
how he had dug in the Taoudenni mines until he was in his 50s and
his body could no longer stand it.
</P>
<P>
   The Moors, who controlled the mines and remain Araouane's
masters, would advance the miners credit _ less than $10 for five
months' work being the standard, he said. The miners worked six
days a week for their bosses, but were permitted to keep the salt
from the seventh day. Still, the Moors deducted whatever food or
water the miners consumed from their advances, so the miners
usually fell into debt, which sometimes took years to repay.
</P>
<P>
   But things have improved, Hilla said. His son is digging in
Taoudenni now and has been promised more than $40 for four months'
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have his luck,'' Hilla said, smiling, his face
turned away from the blowing wind. ``I'm an old man now. I can't go
to Taoudenni, I can't go to Timbuktu. I can't do anything but go to
the mosque and pray.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was on an aborted trip to Taoudenni in 1988 that an American
named Ernst Aebi, a surrealist painter from Manhattan, stumbled
upon Araouane. In his book ``Seasons of Sand'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1993), Aebi wrote that after being struck by the village's
wretchedness, he planted trees to stop the encroaching Sahara, grew
a communal garden and built a school and even a hotel, which he
called the Araouane Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the American had come to save us,'' said Chirach
Hamma, 27, who learned French in the school.
</P>
<P>
   But the development coincided with a growing rebellion against
the Malian government by the Tuareg nomads. The Tuaregs and Moors,
who proved the most resistant to Westernization under French
colonialism, found themselves marginalized after Mali's
independence in 1960. The descendants of the blacks, who had been
their slaves and received French education, now controlled the
national government and were not particularly open to their
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Tuareg rebels raided and destroyed villages in the Sahara. Peace
came in 1995 but only after the destruction of Aebi's projects.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last couple of years, improvements have come to Araouane.
Italians built a school; the Red Cross, a dispensary.
</P>
<P>
   El Hadje Ahmed, 27, a nurse whom everyone refers to as the
doctor, arrived here in October from his hometown, Timbuktu. The
Red Cross regularly sends supplies, though the locals continue to
practice traditional medicine, which includes stuffing nostrils
with camel dung to fight colds and placing it against an aching
tooth.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed's father, a doctor, had ordered him to Araouane. But the
young man could not wait to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Araouane was a great city!'' Ahmed said, slumped on
the porch of the dispensary. ``Oh! I'd like to go back to Timbuktu
to renew myself, if only for one month. Go out dancing with my
girlfriends. I could never convince any of them to come here.
They'll see there's no dancing here, that all the women are
covered. My girlfriends wear short skirts and they don't wear
veils!''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hated how the Sahara had left a permanent coat of
fine sand on his skin, how the grains found their way between his
teeth and into every meal he ate. He said he hated watching the
sand women's Sisyphean labor, the same sand spilling back into the
spaces they had cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is hell,'' he added with finality. '
</P>
<P>
   The sun had begun to set over Araouane, and the sand women were
collecting the bags of rice or sugar, the equivalent of $1.60, that
they are paid for a day. Jnanbarka Handou Barik is over 50 but has
never set foot outside Araouane. ``I don't know anything about
Timbuktu,'' she said, adding, ``I hope the wind doesn't come
tomorrow, so I can work.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliou Fatima Metou, the man whose doorway she had cleared, took
in the stillness of the air and predicted that there would be no
wind on this particular night. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   But in the predawn hours, before the muezzin roused the faithful
for the day's first prayer, the wind had stirred. Soon the sand
flowed gently from the eastern dunes, rustling by the houses and
doorways all over Araouane, awakening no doubt the sand women from
their sleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
