<HEADER>
A5402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-TEENS14-COX     01-13 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TEENS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Raise Georgia driving age to 17
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The major objections to raising Georgia's driving age
to 17 are the inconvenience to parents and the disappointment to
16-year-olds. But neither is compelling in light of the fatality
rates of young drivers and their passengers. Two out of every three
teens who died as passengers were in vehicles driven by other
teens, usually 16-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gingrey (R-Marietta) is sponsoring a bill that would
hike the driving age to 17 and require parents to sign sworn
statements they've given their child 50 hours of driving
instruction. The proposal won a key ally last week when Gov. Roy
Barnes endorsed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the number of deaths of 16-year-old drivers rose
about 50 percent from 1975 to 1996. During the same period, deaths
among drivers aged 17-19 declined 27 percent. The accident rate
among 16-year-olds is expected to climb even higher because the
country is in the midst of a teen explosion. The offspring of the
baby boom generation is growing up and grabbing the keys to family
cars.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative to raising the driving age, some legislators
endorse more driver's education courses. But it's not a lack of
mastery that leads to many teen crashes. It's a lack of maturity.
Many of them forgo seat belts. They speed. They play games with
their cars. They pile in their friends and joy ride.
</P>
<P>
   Driver's education can teach kids handling skills and the rules
of the road. In Georgia, driver's education programs entail 30
hours of classroom training and six hours behind the wheel. But
those classes don't produce safer drivers, according to the
Insurance Institute for Highway Safety. By raising the driving age
and lengthening the learning phase, Georgia treats the two core
problems _ teen immaturity and driving inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Today's teens are more likely to come from homes with at least
two cars, giving them more chances to drive. Teens don't shop on
Main Street or walk a half-mile to school. They drive 15 miles to
the mall and commute to a regional high school 40 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers also rely on their cars for recreation. Fifty-three
percent of teenage motor vehicle deaths in 1998 occurred on Friday,
Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of kids cram in a car and drive around for hours. With
each additional passenger a teen driver carries, the risk of an
accident multiples. The passengers distract drivers and egg them on
to deadly behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey found that 67 percent of Georgia voters favor
raising the driving age. Legislators should keep that in mind when
the calls come flooding in from parents who want to retire their
chauffeur caps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
