<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-TAKING-NYT     01-13 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-TAKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANIC COMEDY AND KINKS CHANNELED BY JIM CARREY IN `MAN ON THE
MOON', PLUS REVIEWS OF `THE HURRICANE' AND `THE GREEN MILE'  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `MAN ON THE MOON'  &QL; 
Jim Carrey, Danny DeVito, Courtney Love, Paul Giamatti &QL; 
Directed by Milos Forman &QL; 
R 118 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it was better, but it's so stupid,'' says Andy Kaufman
( Carrey) at the start of his and Forman's movie. (Now he tells
us.) Apologies dispensed with, the manic comedian's story jumps to
his excruciatingly white-bread Long Island childhood and then on to
his first club dates. ``I can't sell booze when you're singing `Pop
Goes the Weasel,''' a bar owner complains.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the right agent ( DeVito) recognizes genius of a
sort and sells Andy to television. For a while, ``Saturday Night
Live'' is the only show that can contain his craziness, if barely.
Then comes the big break: Andy lands a steady gig on ``Taxi'' as
the weenie-voiced mechanic Latka Gravas. By then his popularity is
such that he can demand a special of his own and regular spots for
his trash-talking alter ego, the lounge singer Tony Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   When a college audience asks him to do Latka, Andy reads them
``The Great Gatsby.'' Looking for new avenues, he decides to be a
wrestler. Male opponents are too big, so he wrestles women, with
whom he goes rolling and crashing around the ring. A feud ensues
with the professional wrestler Jerry Lawler, who slugs him on the
David Letterman show. Everybody's kidding, right?
</P>
<P>
   But Andy's time is short. He is dismissed from ``Saturday Night
Live.'' His meditation group throws him out. ``Taxi'' is canceled.
When he tells his family and friends that he has lung cancer,
nobody believes him at first. For a finale, he plays Carnegie Hall
and takes the audience out for milk and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE All confrontations seem unthreatening enough.
</P>
<P>
   SEX Andy practices his wrestling in a house of prostitution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 15 Obviously this isn't the most wholesome fare, but
if there's a will, Carrey fans will find a way to attend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP Kaufman, even Carrey's Kaufman, could well escape
many of today's teen-agers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE HURRICANE'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington, John Hannah, Deborah Kara Unger, Liev
Schreiber, Vicellous Reon Shannon, Dan Hedaya &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Norman Jewison &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 120 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Carefully manipulated to land every emotional jab and hook, the
story of Rubin (Hurricane) Carter ( Washington) centers around the
shotgun and pistol blasts that killed three people in a Paterson,
N.J., bar in 1966 and led to trumped-up, racially motivated charges
that landed the fighter in Trenton State Prison for life.
</P>
<P>
   In the ring, Carter's killer instinct takes out top opponents in
as little as one round. He's also a thinking man. In solitary
confinement, his violent side debates his rational side, and he
emerges determined to use his brains to help himself.
</P>
<P>
   He writes a book about his life, called ``The 16th Round,''
which is bought for 25 cents by a boy named Lesra ( Shannon). Lesra
can't read, but has caught the attention of three researchers (
Schreiber, Hannah and Ms. Unger), who have taken him to Canada for
home schooling.
</P>
<P>
   The book becomes the boy's bible. Famous people take up Carter's
cause. Bob Dylan writes a song called ``The Hurricane.'' But with
officials threatened by revelations of false testimony, petitions
for a new trial are denied. Carter withdraws. For the remaining
years he spends in prison (20 all told), he determines to live not
in the heart or the cell, only in the mind.
</P>
<P>
   The only person who can reach him is Lesra, who visits him and
later brings his three friends down from Canada. They, too, are
taken with Carter, who warily accepts them into his confidence.
They move to New Jersey and do much of the investigative legwork
for a new appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly vicious police captain ( Hedaya) suggests that it
might be healthier if the three of them went back home where they
belong. Despite a suspicious car accident, they remain. With much
new material to consider, a hearing is granted. In a movie as
obvious as this one, could there be any doubt of the result? (In
real life, Carter is 62 and lives in Canada.)
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The shootings are gory and in the ring the onslaught
toe-to-toe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Some references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Strong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? UNDER AGE 15. The film clearly is wrong for
the very young, but as R-rated films go, it is a relatively
worthwhile exercise for older children. Parents' choice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 and up. Altogether this isn't the most appealing film
for teen-agers, some of whom will be annoyed at the formulaic,
schmaltzy support of the good guys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREEN MILE'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks, David Morse, Michael Clarke Duncan, James Cromwell,
Bonnie Hunt, Michael Jeter, Graham Greene, Doug Hutchison &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Frank Darabont &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 180 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Now in an old folks home, Paul Edgecomb ( Hanks) recalls a time
in 1935 when he was the chief guard on death row in a Southern
prison. This being a Stephen King story, settle in (at three-hours'
running time, there's a long road ahead) for a journey into the
fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   One day, an enormous man named John Coffey ( Duncan) arrives in
shackles to the cry of ``dead man walking.'' Convicted of the rape
and murder of two little girls, Coffey is really a gentle fellow
who is scared of the dark and calls everybody boss. Inside him,
glowing like a fiery furnace, is an otherworldly power to heal and
prolong life.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in blue serge suits, Paul and his men maintain a
civilized decorum around the cell block. Testing that policy, Percy
( Hutchison), a guard and the house sadist, stomps an inmate's pet
mouse and aspires to a job at a mental hospital where he would
better qualify as a patient.
</P>
<P>
   After walking the green mile, the condemned take their places in
the electric chair, an old contraption that blows lighting fixtures
but, if the sponges placed on their heads are properly wetted,
finishes victims with a minimum amount of agony.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, death row turns curiously rehabilitative. Taking hold
of the afflicted, Coffey cures ills from Paul's urinary infection
to the warden's wife's brain tumor. But to save him there could
well be no miracle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE A steak at a barbecue has an easier time of it than one
prisoner does in the chair when Percy deliberately leaves the
sponge dry, turning the man into a screaming, writhing torch. Other
executions aren't much prettier, and there is a shooting and other
violence on the cell block. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Paul and his wife (Bonnie Hunt) tastefully make up for lost
time after his infection is cleared up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Quite a bit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? UNDER 14 No, this isn't ``Forrest Gump.''
Probably too long and convoluted for most. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17 Hanks and others give fine performances that
transcend the R rating, but many teen-agers (not all) won't want to
hang around through a film more geared to their parents. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
