<HEADLINE>
MARINO BACKPEDALS FROM TALK OF RETIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the fourth quarter of Dan Marino's career, and time is
running out. Even Marino admits he might not have another comeback
in him after this season.
</P>
<P>
   However, he and his Miami Dolphins were supposed to be finished
after last week. Instead, he pulled off the 37th fourth-quarter
comeback of his career in a 20-17 upset of the Seattle Seahawks,
and the Dolphins advanced to tomorrow's AFC divisional playoff game
against the Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Until the clock on the Dolphins' season reads 00:00, Marino is
backpedaling from talk of his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what my future will be,'' Marino said earlier this
week. ``I may continue to play. I may not. ... That's something you
have to look at when the season's over, and I've done that for the
last couple of years. You have to look at what happened and what
the circumstances were during the year. You just have to assess
what you're feeling, and how your body feels and all of those
things, and you worry about it then.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino is the NFL's all-time leading passer with 61,361 yards,
420 touchdowns and 4,967 completions. He also holds the distinction
of being the best quarterback never to have won a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In his second season, in 1984, the Dolphins lost to the San
Francisco 49ers, 38-16, in Super Bowl XIX. Miami has lost in the
AFC Championship Game twice, 1985 and 1992, in the 15 seasons
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my consistency over a 17-year period,'' Marino
said. ``This team was able to rely on me every week, and I feel I
played my position at a very, very high level. The big
disappointment is not being able to win a Super Bowl. That's what
you play for. That's a goal I had, and I still have.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino is 38. His body, which has endured eight operations, is
held together by braces, tape, painkillers and willpower. This
season he missed five games with a neck injury that limited his arm
strength when he returned.
</P>
<P>
   Marino used to win games. This season he has lost them.
</P>
<P>
   His 67.4 quarterback rating was lower than that of Tim Couch,
Jeff Garcia and Jim Harbaugh, among others. His 12 touchdown passes
and 17 interceptions was the worst ratio of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Jimmy Johnson, frustrated that the Dolphins ranked
20th in total offense and tied for 23rd in turnover ratio, has been
openly critical of Marino all season. It is assumed that Johnson,
who also is considering retirement, and Marino cannot coexist on
the same team beyond this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think Dan and I have a very good relationship,''
Johnson said. ``I think some people try to read more into every
statement made than what's really there. I'm fairly forthright as
my assessment of any of our players. The media has made more out of
it than what's really there.''
</P>
<P>
   After the victory Sunday against the Seahawks, Johnson charged
after Marino. ``Hey, Dan! Dan!'' Jimmy yelled to get Marino's
attention. Marino turned to find Johnson giving him two thumbs up.
Marino waved back in acknowledgement.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? It just as well could have been a wave goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
