<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS AT A   MASSACHUSETTS MUSEUM, PLUS ITEMS ON PHOTOGRAPHY
ACQUISITIONS IN HOUSTON, A RESIGNATION AT SOTHEBY'S AND
APPOINTMENTS AT THE WHITNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Germany, Mass., Calif., Texas) (ART ADV 13 : Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT 14  photo clients.
Non-subscribers 15  can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some 92,000 people have visited the Massachusetts Museum of
Contemporary Art, the country's largest center for contemporary
visual and performing arts, since it opened in May. ``We'd hoped to
clear 100,000 the first year,'' said Joseph C. Thompson, the
museum's director. ``We've almost hit our target already.''
</P>
<P>
   Situated in North Adams, Mass., an economically depressed
blue-collar town of 14,000, the museum is attracting the kind of
tourists and homeowners who frequent places in the Berkshires like
Tanglewood in Lenox, summer home to the Boston Symphony Orchestra;
the Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge; the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival in Becket; and the Williams College Museum of Art and the
Sterling and Francine Clark Art Institute, both in Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty percent of our visitors are from the New York
metropolitan area and 30 percent are from Boston,'' Thompson said.
``The rest are from all over the country and the world. We have a
strong international presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its strong program in the performing arts, Thompson
added, the museum also seems to attract a younger audience than do
places like Tanglewood and the Norman Rockwell Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at all the cultural institutions in Berkshire County
is seasonal. The most popular time begins around the middle of June
and goes through October. During the quiet winter months, officials
at Mass MOCA firm up their plans for summer programs while offering
smaller shows.
</P>
<P>
   Friday it is opening ``Super Model,'' an exhibition by artists
who fabricate and photograph artificial landscapes and citiscapes.
The show runs through June 9. The next of the much large
exhibitions, which are to be on view for at least nine months, is
``Unnatural Science,'' a collection of works that use the
discoveries, inventions and methods of science as inspiration. The
show, which will replace of the museum's inaugural show, will take
two months to install, but the museum will stay open so that
visitors can watch it take shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unnatural Science'' will formally open on June 3 and run
through March 15, 2001. It will occupy all 19 galleries. Because
the gallery spaces are fashioned from abandoned mills, 19th-century
factory buildings and overgrown courtyards _ all large in scale _
the museum can show works so big that the average museum doesn't
have room to exhibit them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unnatural Science'' includes two commissioned pieces. One, by
the California sculptor Tim Hawkinson, is an installation piece
that plays on the word organ. The other is by the photographer
Catherine Chalmers and consists of 30 photographs, each three by
five feet and showing a four-step food chain.
</P>
<P>
   The show will also feature several works that have been
exhibited elsewhere. Kiki Smith, for example, will show ``Sky''
from her ``Paradise Cage,'' reworking the version of the piece that
was at the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles last year. In
``Paradise Cage,'' Ms. Smith explores astronomy 500 years ago and
incorporates glass stars and large glass animals in the work.
</P>
<P>
   Also on view will be ``Borealis'' by Steina Vasulka, an American
artist born in Iceland who was a pioneer in video art in the late
1960s. Her piece is being lent by the Center for Art and Media
Technology in Karlsruhe, Germany. It envelops the visitor in
electronically manipulated sounds and images from the stark
Icelandic landscape _ water, waves, volcanic rocks and geological
formations.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces in ``Unnatural Science'' come from various artists,
dealers, collectors and museums all over the world. ``We noticed,
over the last 10 years, an international group of artists working
in the realm of microscience,'' Thompson said. ``Whereas our last
large exhibition featured mostly artists from the 1950s and 1960s,
most of the artists in this show are younger and the subject matter
is hotter, more narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS FOR TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   When the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston opens its $50 million
building in March, with twice the space it has now, the museum will
have its first permanent gallery devoted only to photography.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the expansion, Anne Tucker, the museum's
photography curator, has been enlarging the institution's holdings.
In the process, she has created a model that Peter C. Marzio, the
museum's director, says he hopes will be copied by other
departments.
</P>
<P>
   This week the museum announced that it had acquired 122
photographs: 36 by Diane Arbus, 20 by Brassai, 2 by Gerhard
Richter, 2 by William Eggleston, 30 by Yasuhiro Ishimoto, including
his ``Katsura'' portfolio,'' and 32 by David Levinthal.
</P>
<P>
   Most were gifts. The Arbus photographs, for example, were given
by Gay Block, a photographer from Houston who now lives in Santa
Fe. In appreciation of the gift, the museum's board voted to match
its value with $100,000 to purchase other photographs for the
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of leveraging we're going to try to do in the
future,'' Marzio said. ``For people to see that their donation
creates other donations is important. If it works for photography,
we're going to try to see if it can work in other departments as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   TO AND FRO
</P>
<P>
   More comings and goings this week in museums and auction houses:
</P>
<P>
   _ After more than 27 years at Sotheby's, Thierry Millerand, head
of European furniture worldwide, has decided to leave. ``Sotheby's
has changed so much, with tremendous growth in areas like the
Internet, that I feel my skills can be better used elsewhere,''
Millerand said.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Whitney Museum of American Art the plum job _ curator
of contemporary art _ remains vacant. But Maxwell L. Anderson, the
Whitney's director, created and filled two new curatorial
positions. Christiane Paul, will be adjunct curator of new media
arts. She is the editor and publisher of Intelligent Agent, a print
and online magazine about interactive media technology in arts and
education, and will be responsible for presenting, collecting and
conserving new media works. Michael Hays will be adjunct curator of
architecture. An architectural historian, he is a professor of
architectural theory at Harvard University Graduate School of
Design.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
