<SLUG> BC-STATES-SMOG-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TEXAS SMOG LEVELS ROSE IN 1999
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan. 13 - It's no secret that Texas is one of the
smoggiest states, and 1999 was a particularly bad year, according
to a national report released Thursday by an environmental
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Network and the U.S. Public Interest Research
Group Education Fund estimate that for 555 eight-hour periods in
1999, Texas exceeded the limits of what the Environmental
Protection Agency's deems healthy for ground level ozone, almost a
28 percent increase over the 432 smoggy periods recorded in the
state last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, initial figures reported by state agencies indicate
there was less smog in 1999 on the national level, the report said.
Last year there were at least 7672 eight-hour periods considered
unhealthily smoggy, over 7914 unhealthy periods in 1998. But the
report said that since violations for 1999 are still being
recorded, last year's levels will likely turn out to be higher than
in 1998 once they are all tallied up.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the number of unhealthy eight hour periods, the report
found Texas to be the second smoggiest state, second only to
California, which had 1217 such periods deemed unhealthy to people
and the environment. Other smoggy states included North Carolina,
which had 539 unhealthy periods, Pennsylvania at 512, Ohio at 461,
and Georgia at 407.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Crimmins, spokesman for the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission, said Texas smog in 1999 was due to more
emissions, from a growth in population and manufacturing
industries, and bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC is pushing for ways to reduce emissions, such as
reduced speed limits. ``We don't need any statistical reminders
that Texas has a problem,'' Crimmins said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nation's cities, Houston had the highest concentration
of smog over an 8-hour period in 1999, supporting reports last year
that said that city had surpassed Los Angeles as the urban center
with the most filthy air. The five highest smog concentrations
recorded last summer -- when smog is at its worst -- were all
recorded in the Houston area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
