<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO GRIPING, PLEASE, ABOUT THE BASEBALL HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Good for Carlton Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   Better for Tony Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all for those of us who don't have the stomach for yet
another year of complaints about the indignities and injustices
done to Perez. This time, the Baseball Writers Association of
America voted Fisk and Perez into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Enshrinement into the Hall of Fame is the highest honor the
sport has to offer. It is not an entitlement. The Hall is a place
of honor for the greatest of the greatest. Just making it on to the
ballot is proof positive of a distinguished career.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it, then, that every No vote gets treated like a slap in
the face? Why should Fisk stew because he didn't get in last year _
his first on the ballot _ while Nolan Ryan, George Brett and Robin
Yount did? Why should anybody portray Perez's nine-year wait to get
voted in as some sort of cruel punishment?
</P>
<P>
   To me, the Hall of Fame should be so elitist, the Ivy League
looks inclusive by comparison. Perez was a terrific player, a
leader and cornerstone of Cincinnati's Big Red Machine of the
1970s. He has been a credit to the game, and only 17 players in
major-league history have driven in more runs over their careers.
</P>
<P>
   And he wouldn't have gotten my vote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the inclusion of Perez isn't going to cause me to hold my
nose every time I enter the Cooperstown city limits. It's actually
possible to respect Perez, even admire him, without deeming him to
be Cooperstown material.
</P>
<P>
   One of Perez's contemporaries as a first baseman, Steve Garvey,
was in his eighth year on the ballot. When Perez was in his prime,
Garvey generally was considered the better all-around player.
Garvey got well less than one-half the Hall of Fame support as
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was a productive, but not dominant player whose career
spanned more than two decades. His being from Cuba has nothing to
do with the fact that he isn't ranked anywhere near the top 100 in
major-league history in the best two measures of offensive
production _ on-base percentage or slugging average. The likes of
Fred McGriff, David Justice, Jay Buhner and Zeke Bonura have higher
career slugging averages than Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Blyleven was in his third year on the ballot. Blyleven is
22nd in big-league history in victories, third in strikeouts and
ninth in shutouts. He needed and everybody else on the ballot
needed at least 375 out of the 499 votes cast. He got a measly 87.
Should Blyleven and his supporters read something sinister into the
fact that he was born in the Netherlands?
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame case for Fisk was open-and-shut. Fisk hit more
home runs than any catcher in history. He was a standout defensive
player and handler of pitchers. He also gave baseball one of its
most memorable moments, clouting the 12th-inning home run that beat
Cincinnati in Game 6 of the 1975 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the strong support for Fisk raises questions
about what it takes to get the support of the voters. Consider two
of the candidates on the latest ballot. Both are contemporaries.
Both played the same position:
</P>
<P>
   Player A appeared in the majors from 1969-93. He batted .269
over his career with 376 home runs and 1,330 runs batted in. He
made 11 All-Star teams, won one Gold Glove and played in one
(losing) World Series. He had eight 20-homer seasons and drove in
100 runs twice.
</P>
<P>
   Player B appeared in the majors from 1974 to 1992. He batted
.262 over his career with 324 homers and 1,225 RBI. He made 11
All-Star teams, won three Gold Gloves and played in one (winning)
World Series. He had nine 20-homer seasons and drove in 100 runs
four times.
</P>
<P>
   Player A is Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   Player B is Gary Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk got 397 out of a possible 499 votes, Carter 248. If that
adds up, then somebody must have invented yet another new math. The
biggest knock against Carter is that he smiled too much, that he
was too cooperative with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the case of two sluggers on the latest ballot:
</P>
<P>
   Slugger A played in the majors from 1974-89. He had a .298
career batting average with 382 homers and 1,451 RBI. He had 2,452
hits in 16 seasons, with a .352 on-base average and .502 slugging
percentage. He led the league in home runs three times, RBI twice,
total bases four times, slugging twice and won a Most Valuable
Player award. He made eight All-Star teams, had 11 20-homer seasons
and drove in 100 runs eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Slugger B played in the majors from 1964-86. He had a .279
career batting average with 379 homers and 1,652 RBI. He had 2,732
hits in 23 seasons, with a .341 on-base average and .463 slugging
percentage. He never led the league in an offensive category or won
an MVP award. He made seven All-Star teams, had nine 20-homer
seasons and drove in 100 runs seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Player B is Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Player A is Jim Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Perez got 385 votes, Rice 257. Rice was a dominant, feared
player. The biggest knock against him is that he didn't smile
enough, that he was beyond uncooperative when it came to dealing
with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Good for Carlton Fisk and Tony Perez. The Hall of Fame is a hard
place to get into as anything but a paying customer. And it should
be. Membership is a privilege, not an entitlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-NEWADS14-COX     01-13 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-NEWADS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New `enjoy' commercials seeking Coke Classic revival
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine yourself inside a Coke bottle or pouring a
Coke that morphs into a giant waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Watch a parrot, perched above a cafe bar, give a perfect
imitation of the soft drink being opened, poured and consumed.
</P>
<P>
   Hear young boys compare their first Coke experience to what
kissing a girl might be like.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, you'll be doing just that as Coca-Cola begins a
national rollout of its new Classic commercials in hopes of putting
the pop back into droopy sales of its flagship brand.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second ``enjoy'' TV spots replace the 7-year-old
``Always'' campaign, which went flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising is a very strong part of the marketing mix, and it
has not been as strong in the past few years as we've been
accustomed to,'' said Bob Lovell, vice president of marketing for
Birmingham, Ala.-based Coca-Cola Bottling Company United, the
system's fourth-largest U.S. bottler. Lovell was in Atlanta on
Wednesday evening when Coke unveiled the commercials to its
bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like in winning football, with its emphasis on blocking
and tackling, the new ads return to the basics that built the brand
_ friends, family, fun, happiness, refreshment,'' Lovell said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Conway, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said
the company is also returning to its roots by trying to ``leave
lasting impressions with the viewer on the experience of drinking
Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots do more than just associate the Classic brand with fun
events, as many soft drink ads do.
</P>
<P>
   They try to convey the physical attributes of the product _ the
popping sound of a bottle opening, the fizzle of carbonation and
the tingling sensation of the drink as it hits the back of the
throat. The ads do this while simultaneously attempting to connect
emotionally with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, viewers of one spot are put inside a Coke bottle,
where they see different dance sequences, from hip-hop to merengue.
Dance is used as a metaphor for the emotions that can be stirred up
while drinking Coke. Then, very quickly, the viewer is brought out
of the bottle and into a hopping nightclub where the disc jockey
drinks a Coke.
</P>
<P>
   In another commercial, a Coke pops open, starts pouring out and
then immediately transforms into a Hawaiian waterfall, with a
teen-age boy riding it down. He plunges underwater into a trove of
Coke, grabs one and bursts through the surface to find his friends
drinking the soft drink and laughing at the head of another
waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional spot, with an uplifting orchestral melody, kids
are throwing snowballs and catching snowflakes with their tongues.
The camera tightens on one of the flakes, destined for a young
girl's mouth. But just as it reaches her, the flake dissolves into
a Coke bottle. It's now about 10 years later, she's drinking the
last drop of a Coke on a beach with her friends. The snowflake was
just a distant and pleasant memory of times gone by.
</P>
<P>
   ``How successful these ads are is critical,'' said John Sicher,
editor and publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Coke Classic is the
company's biggest product. Its growth has been relatively slow in
recent years. It's important for Coke and Pepsi to get stronger
growth from their flagship colas.''
</P>
<P>
   No question about it, said the people behind the Coke ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to sell Coca-Cola,'' said Charles Frenette, the
company's chief marketing officer until Feb. 1, when he becomes
head of its European operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a marketing company,'' Frenette said. ``What we do is
give reasons to people to buy and sell our products. ... We want to
revitalize and rejuvenate growth in our flagship brand.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the company expects Coke Classic to be the engine
of growth over an extended period. Recently, however, the opposite
has taken place, with non-cola brands growing considerably faster
than Coke percentagewise.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Coke Classic represented 46 percent of the
company's case sales of carbonated soft drinks in 1998, according
to Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very key to our success,'' said Lovell, the bottler.
</P>
<P>
   So Coca-Cola will be hitting the airwaves in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week of Monday's launch, 95 percent of the U.S.
population will have seen one of the new ads on TV, said Ian
Rowden, the company's advertising director.
</P>
<P>
   Ten spots will be aired over time, including a polar bear
commercial and an animated one featuring aliens and a Coke
spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   The spots, which will also be aired around the world, were
created by Leo Burnett and Edge Creative. Other agencies will
supplement the initial pool of ads, as well as adapt them to local
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Each commercial will end with a corner graphic showing the cap
popping off a bottle and the signature: ``Coca-Cola. enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an invitation, not a command,'' Frenette said.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be radio, print, Internet and billboard ads. On
radio, for example, there are a variety of musical styles,
everything from urban to country to rock.
</P>
<P>
   Coke officials would not say how much they're planning to spend
on the new campaign. For the first nine months of last year, the
company spent $95.6 million on its Classic media advertising in the
United States, according to Competitive Media Reporting. For all of
1998, it spent $115.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Will the new campaign work? Ron Wilson, president of
Philadelphia Coca-Cola Bottling Co., thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottlers were upbeat because the ads had a consistent
message,'' Wilson said after viewing the spots Wednesday at the
Georgia World Congress Center. ``I think they're going to better
connect with consumers. We're selling the uniqueness of Coke, and I
think we've gotten away from that in the past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sicher, of Beverage Digest, said only time will tell how
effective the new campaign will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any soft drink ads, how successful they are will be
determined by the collective jury of the consumer,'' he said. ``We
probably won't know that verdict for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
