<SLUG> BC-FBN-KING-BUCS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY'S KING IS RARE ROOKIE QB STARTING IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Buccaneers quarterback Shaun King spent most of the
season waiting his turn. Now, it is history that awaits him.
</P>
<P>
   King, who has won four of five starts, will become only the
sixth rookie quarterback to start a playoff game when he takes the
field against the Washington Redskins tomorrow at Raymond James
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A rookie quarterback has never started in the Super Bowl. In
fact, since the 1970 NFL-AFL merger, rookie quarterbacks are 1-5 in
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even guys who went to good teams _ the \RJohn\S Elways and the
\RDan\S Marinos _ didn't really take over and take their team to
the playoffs their first year,'' Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy said.
``So, it's something that doesn't happen all the time, but I think
the circumstances were really right for Shaun. He got to sit and
watch and learn for half a year, got a chance to practice and be in
the mix, and then, as the team started to play better, that's when
he stepped in and it kind of worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Marinovich was the most recent rookie quarterback to start
a playoff game. His Los Angeles Raiders lost to the Kansas City
Chiefs, 10-6, in a 1991 AFC divisional playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   The only rookie quarterback to win a playoff game was Pat Haden,
who led the Los Angeles Rams to a 14-12 victory against the Cowboys
in a 1976 divisional playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   King, 22, shows no fear at his date with history.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Smoothie King'' by receiver Bert Emanuel, King won
his first NFL start _ on ``Monday Night Football'', no less. Maybe
King has forgotten how to lose.
</P>
<P>
   As a starter, he has lost only once since Nov. 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nerves. No nerves,'' said King, who led Tulane to an
undefeated season in 1998. ``I know I have a job to do. I'll go out
and do my best. I'm not afraid to mess up. I'm not afraid to fail.
My father has a saying, `If you're worried, you're not praying,'
and I pray a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   King has been the answer to Buccaneers' fans prayers.
</P>
<P>
   He was not transformed into a Tampa Bay hero. He was born into
the role.
</P>
<P>
   King, a St. Petersburg, Fla., native, grew up a Buccaneers' fan.
He dreamed of playing for his hometown NFL team while throwing for
more than 5,000 yards and 50 touchdowns in his final two seasons at
Gibbs High School, just across the bay from One Buc Place.
</P>
<P>
   King was selected by the Buccaneers in the second round of the
1999 draft, the sixth quarterback taken. He began the season as a
typical rookie quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Third on the depth chart, he spent Sunday afternoons wearing a
baseball cap and charting plays.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries to starter Trent Dilfer and backup Eric Zeier saw
King promoted to the front line during the team's Nov. 28 game at
Seattle. In 5 1/2 starts, King completed 89 of 146 passes for 875
yards, with seven touchdowns and four interceptions. If he had
thrown enough passes to qualify, King's 82.4 rating would rank
eighth in the NFC, ahead of Troy Aikman and Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a Cinderella year for him for what he's done for
us,'' Buccaneers quarterbacks coach Clyde Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
   When the clock strikes midnight tomorrow, King hopes the slipper
still fits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
