<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-NH-ART-NYT &LR;      01-13 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-NH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGNING AT THE LEGISLATURE, MCCAIN PUSHES PLAN FOR REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wisconsin)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT16, NYT17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By JODI WILGOREN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Taking his campaign from town-hall meetings to
the state Capitol, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., told the New
Hampshire Legislature on Thursday that if he is elected president,
he will create a cabinet post for a ``reform czar'' to oversee his
efforts ``to restore a government of, by and for the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-minute speech that mentioned Bart Simpson, Henry Luce,
Ronald Reagan and Harry Truman, McCain, a presidential candidate,
told the packed chamber of America's oldest surviving statehouse
that he would veto pork-barrel bills and force the federal
government to fully fund state mandates on special education,
health care, immigration and the environment. He also hailed
publicly financed vouchers for private schools, saying, ``vouchers
means choice, and choice means freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the victims of pork-barrel politics in Washington, and
it must stop,'' McCain said to the legislators, who greeted him
with standing ovations. ``When our politics are perceived as
corrupted by money and lies, trust is lost to cynicism. When our
government has been taken from us by special interests and
big-dollar donors, as it has been, pride is lost to shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-establishment tone was familiar, but it was the first
time McCain had suggested a cabinet-level position _ akin to the
drug czar, the director of the White House Office of Drug Control
Policy _ to coordinate efforts to reform government and the
campaign finance system. That person would kick-start changes in
the tax code, the Department of Education and the military, for
starters, McCain said, and heighten the visibility of the reform
issue overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must reform the institutions of government to catch up with
the changes of the age,'' he said after the speech. Asked whether
Sen. Russell D. Feingold, D-Wis., his partner on campaign finance
legislation, might be a candidate for the new position, he laughed
and said, ``that wouldn't be a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show McCain leading Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
among likely Republican voters as this state prepares to hold the
campaign's first primary on Feb. 1. When McCain started his speech
on Thursday, he had 75 endorsements in the 410-member state
Legislature; he picked up four more before the day was done. Bush
is backed by 61 New Hampshire state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Thursday, over breakfast with 15 police chiefs from
rural New Hampshire, McCain said states should receive federal
block grants for law enforcement, rather than money earmarked for
the hiring of more police officers. And he said every public school
and library being wired to the Internet should have software
installed to filter out offensive material.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the chiefs, who often respond to alarms themselves
because their departments are so tiny, said they had not bothered
to seek the federal grants because they were daunted by the
detailed applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our communities have New York City expectations with
Mayberry R.F.D. budgets,'' David J. Collum, who heads a
seven-member force in Rindge, N.H., told the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the pressures, McCain asked the chief of a
department of four, ``What happens when vacation time comes? I hope
we don't tell the bad guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WESTPOINT-STOCK14-COX     01-13 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTPOINT-STOCK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WestPoint Stevens maintains low profile while `exploring'
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WestPoint Stevens is keeping its ownership plans under
wraps.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest maker of sheets and towels has maintained a
low profile on Wall Street following an announcement in November
that it's exploring a merger, sale or recapitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The West Point, Ga.-based manufacturer said at the time it
wasn't in discussions and hadn't received any offers. The company
has declined to discuss the status since then.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with its lagging stock, WestPoint Stevens hired Merrill
Lynch to advise it on alternatives, but investors may not be that
excited about the prospects. The company has outperformed its
largest competitors, Pillowtex (PTX) and Springs Industries (SMI),
in earnings growth, but its shares had lost about half their value
in the six months prior to the November announcement. The stock
since then has continued its decline, hitting a 52-week low of
$15.18 3/4 on Dec. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed Thursday at $17.25, down 18 3/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens is expected to report earnings Feb 10.
Analysts anticipate a profit of about 57 cents a share. That
compares with 49 cents per share in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said a likely outcome is for Chairman and Chief
Executive Holcombe Green Jr. to take over ownership of the company,
which had a market value of about $921 million Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, Holcombe Green has repeatedly said he wanted
to own the company,'' said analyst Kay Norwood of Wachovia
Securities. Green took the helm at WestPoint Stevens in 1992 when
its former chief, William Farley, lost control of the company
during a bankruptcy restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities include a purchase by a foreign company or a
large non-textile company that can afford to expand WestPoint
Stevens' business, analysts said. A merger with domestic rivals
Pillowtex or Spring Industries, however, could create antitrust
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   If WestPoint Stevens is looking for outside involvement, it's
likely trying to round up equity investors, Norwood said. But that
won't be easy. The U.S. textile industry, plagued by cheap imports
from overseas competitors, has been a risky arena. Profitability in
general has been lackluster, and textile companies tend to be
heavily leveraged.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been trying to position itself more as a
consumer products company than a textile maker, Norwood added. In
addition to its Ralph Lauren line, WestPoint Stevens markets brands
including Martex, Utica and Vellux at department stores and
discount chains.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are looking for consistent top-line and bottom-line
growth, which WestPoint Stevens and other textile makers can't
guarantee, she said. ``They sell fashion items, and if the economy
takes a downturn, people won't buy towels or sheets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
