<HEADER>
A5420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-PRIMATES-EMBROYOS     01-13 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PRIMATES-EMBROYOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONKEY BORN FROM EMBRYO DIVIDED BY SCIENTISTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By GINA KOLATA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists in Oregon have divided an eight-cell monkey embryo
into quarters, creating identical quadruplet embryos. One of them
survived and resulted in the birth of a baby monkey.
</P>
<P>
   In their report, which is being published Friday in the journal
Science, Dr. Gerald P. Schatten of the Oregon Regional Primate
Research Center in Beaverton and his colleagues say this is the
first time that embryos of primates were deliberately subdivided,
resulting in the birth of a live offspring. The splitting of
embryos can occur naturally when an early embryo spontaneously
divides in half, producing identical twins, or thirds or quarters
early in development. Each piece can then develop as an independent
embryo.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, scientists have mimicked this process
by dividing early embryos from other animals in the laboratory and
then implanting them in females, where they develop normally.
</P>
<P>
   The new study involved 107 rhesus monkey embryos that were
divided into anywhere from two to nine pieces to form 368 embryos.
In addition to the monkey that was born after an embryo had been
divided into four, the investigators say they also have four
pregnancies under way with embryos that had been split in half. Two
of those split embryos will be identical twins if they survive
until birth, which is expected in May.
</P>
<P>
   Schatten's group did not achieve nearly the success that was
accomplished with other animals.
</P>
<P>
   The first successful embryo splitting was in 1978, when Dr.
Steen Willadsen, an embryologist in Windermere, Fla., divided sheep
embryos in two. Sixty percent to 80 percent of the split embryos
survived, resulting in the birth of live lambs. When Willadsen
divided the embryos in quarters, half survived; when he divided
them in eighths, 5 percent to 10 percent went on to become lambs.
</P>
<P>
   Willadsen repeated the work, with the same success rate, in
cows, goats, horses and pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Schatten said that while the success rate with monkey embryos
had not been as great as with other species, the importance of his
work was that he had established that embryos could be divided. The
next step, he said, will be to create identical twin and quadruplet
monkeys to study the influence of genes on disease susceptibility.
He also wants to study the possibility of using embryos as a source
of cells that could be used for replacement parts in diseases like
diabetes or Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIDS, Alzheimer's disease, diabetes, cancer, heart attacks and
strokes all could be moved to the cured list if we understood the
genetic basis of the disease,'' Schatten said.
</P>
<P>
   But some said the monkey results so far were a far cry from
cures for these diseases. There is the question, for example, of
why so few of the divided embryos survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the primate embryos are not as suitable as sheep
embryos for artificially producing genetically identical
offspring,'' Willadsen said, ``or the techniques used were not
sufficiently good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
