<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     01-13 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PLAYING   BILLIONAIRE   ROULETTE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is there in the victory of Robert Wood Johnson IV over
Charles F. Dolan that touches off the urge to shout,
``Hip-hip-hooray?''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, we lumpen proles are not inclined to root for any
billionaire with an IV after his name, since it implies continuity
and power, big bucks begetting big bucks. But in this struggle for
control of the Jets, good old Woody came off as a man of the
people, an outsider, a lone wolf, with no looming Vaderian menace.
</P>
<P>
   Woody does not own other sports teams. Woody does not control
what is piped into our television sets. Woody does not raise our
cable rates. He just sells bandages. Good old Woody.
</P>
<P>
   These media-electronic-internet-entertainment conglomerates,
they own everything. They give you the willies.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but now television has the Bomb. CBS, the company
of Edward R. Murrow, used its technology to superimpose its own
corporate logo over an NBC logo in Times Square on New Year's Eve.
It was Dan Rathers' greatest fantasy. His own network essentially
beamed him up.
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications are endless in this high-tech infotainment
industry that used to go by the quaint name of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of these giants has ulterior motives, hidden agendas.
AOL, a company that carries e-mail, is fixing to merge with
Time-Warner, a company that currently employs John Rocker and
Isaiah Rider. You don't know what machinations can come of this.
</P>
<P>
   No longer do we have owners like Horace Stoneham of the old New
York Giants, who merely wanted to lock the manager in his dingy
office in the dingier Polo Grounds and drink the night away with
him. Those, we can now see clearly, were the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaires are restless. They keep making more money, and
they want to own all the teams. Some of them want to own teams for
fun and profit. Some of them want to own teams for control and
profit. There is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The march of the billionaires goes on. With all due respect to
madcap Tennessee laterals and the endless backing-and-forthing of
hockey and basketball, the best action this winter involves rich
people jockeying for position.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, or maybe his body double, fumes at Nets'
games. His YankeeNet empire will buy the Devils one of these hours,
despite John McMullen's obfuscations. The poor Islanders may yet be
liberated from the Curse of the Millstones. The Mets will be
purchased, one of these months, by the would-be man for all
seasons, Charles F. Dolan himself.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the football team Dolan wanted to buy. As soon as
Woody was anointed by the National Football League, he did what any
new owner of the Jets would do. He gravitated directly to Bill
Parcells and said, `Help!'
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Bill Belichick had enough of living in the swirling
wake of the big man who is more shark than tuna. Thursday, the
Battling Bills attended a hearing as the NFL attempts to sort out
Belichick's contract with the Jets. Ultimately, Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue will knock a few heads together and say, ``Get out of
here, you knuckleheads.''
</P>
<P>
   It may cost a draft choice of two, but Belichick will get back
to New England and Parcells will stay on a while with the Jets. How
can you say no to Woody?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue has been busy, first whipping the owners into shape to
accept Johnson over Dolan. Since both these chaps have no shortage
of money, what is there about the Dolan bid that has caused him to
be turned down three _ count 'em, three _ times?
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, which likes to control everything from the length of
socks to the equitable distribution of network swag, had qualms
about controlling Dolan. No matter what the man might earnestly put
down in writing about using only his personal fortune on the Jets,
he still owns Cablevision and much of the Knicks and the Rangers,
and that sounded like mischief to the NFL. This is one of those
times when the normally staid league takes on the aura of a
latter-day attack-terrier trust-buster. The NFL lives with Jerry
Jones. The NFL lives with Al Davis. But neither of these rascals is
aligned with a cable company that own teams in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has won its noble rear-guard action against the forces
of synergy. But don't forget: Television has the Bomb. One of these
days Tagliabue will look in the mirror and, to his horror, see the
grim logo of Microsoft or AOL Time Warner or Cablevision
superimposed on his face.
</P>
<P>
   One of these giants is going to swallow the league whole. In the
meantime, let us have some fanfare for the common man, good old
Woody. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 1952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
