<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERLAND-MICROSOFT14     01-13 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERLAND-MICROSOFT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft invests in site-hosting business
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Interland, a fast-growing downtown Atlanta Web
site-hosting firm, said it has received a $5 million equity
investment from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will invest $7.5 million more should Interland file
for an initial public offering of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the second major investment in Interland in the past
two months. Crest Communications Holdings, Boulder Ventures and
BancBoston Capital invested $20 million in Interland in December.
It was the company's first formal round of venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft investment came after months of discussions, said
Ken Gavranovic, Interland's 29 year-old founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cemented the fact that Microsoft believes in the company
and we both enjoy working together,'' Gavranovic said.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft deal does not restrict Interland to developing Web
sites on Microsoft platforms, but about 70 percent of its
customers' sites already are supported by Microsoft software and
servers.
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic said he plans to use the recent investments to help
fund a national and international sales expansion. Europe is a ripe
market for American Web hosting firms because bandwidth is cheaper
here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company hosts Web sites for more than 70,000 small- to
medium-sized businesses, ranging from Outback Steakhouse to Trees
Atlanta. Businesses pay between $20 per month and thousands of
dollars per month for Interland to host their site. Prices vary
depending on the complexity of the site and the number of expected
visitors. The average monthly charge is between $30 and $40.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started in in January 1998, when Gavranovic
moved to Atlanta from south Florida. He said he chose Atlanta after
learning of its estensive telecommunications infrastructure. Then
he went online and researched U.S. Census figures to learn about
cost-of-living and doing business, as well as the skill level of
area workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic chose a building at the corner of Marietta and
Peachtree streets for its proximity to high-speed fiber-optic
cables, an Olympic legacy. Interland has since expanded into seven
floors of Centennial Tower, at Spring and Marietta streets.
</P>
<P>
   Interland grew in 12 months from 48 employees to more than 300.
The company has averaged 6,000 new Web-hosting customer a month
since July.
</P>
<P>
   Interland's inside and field-based sales force competes against
companies such as Verio, MindSpring Enterprises, Bell Atlantic and
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic has been involved in technology to a high degree from
a young age. As a Texas high school student, he wrote an accounting
software program for a local Galveston hotel. He said he received a
few room nights as compensation, but it was enough to whet his
entrepreneurial appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
