<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SCIATLANTA-POWERTV14-     01-13 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIATLANTA-POWERTV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta may spin off unit
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scientific-Atlanta is considering spinning off a
subsidiary that makes the software powering its digital cable TV
set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   A spinoff of the subsidiary, called PowerTV, could be a bonanza
for Scientific-Atlanta. Companies similar to PowerTV have garnered
market valuations in the billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Liberate Technology, which also makes set-top
operating software, has a market capitalization of $4.4 billion, or
nearly twice that of Scientific-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In a spinoff, Scientific-Atlanta would sell shares in PowerTV to
the public, retaining a stake itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spinoff is one way that the company could maximize
shareholder value,'' according to analyst Greg Mesniaeff of
Robinson-Humphrey in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta executives declined to comment on reports
that they have begun serious talks this week about spinning off
PowerTV.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to take the subsidiary public during the second half
of this year, according to reports in industry trade journals.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives did confirm Thursday that James McDonald, the
company's president and chief executive, told a gathering of
analysts at a recent industry trade show that it was possible
PowerTV could be spun off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make sense,'' says Mesniaeff. ``A spinoff of PowerTV
would allow Scientific-Atlanta management to focus on its core
competency.''
</P>
<P>
   That competency is building and maintaining networks that
transmit cable TV signals.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the company is trying to establish a new product line
called the Explorer 2000. The system enables cable TV operators to
offer high-resolution television, e-mail, Web browsing and
high-speed access to the Internet. So far, Scientific-Atlanta has
sold the Explorer to more than 70 cable TV systems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   A key part of the system is its operating system, developed by
PowerTV. Scientific-Atlanta owns 80 percent of the software
developer, based in the Silicon Valley town of Cupertino, Calif.
PowerTV also has an e-mail reader and a Web browser that works
through digital cable TV systems.
</P>
<P>
   PowerTV has made its software compatible with other digital
systems, including that sold by Scientific-Atlanta rival General
Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Such compatibility gives PowerTV the potential to have a market
larger than just Scientific-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
