A5435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-IOWA-NYT &LR;      01-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-IOWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MAKES LITTLE HEADWAY IN COURTING IOWA FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New Jersey, Iowa)  (See also IOWA-OUTLOOK) 
(dal) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLOAN, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore on Thursday appealed for
support from Iowa farmers and staged an event that attacked his
opponent, former Sen. Bill Bradley, as unconcerned with the
problems of American agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore used the well-scripted meeting to promote his own
candidacy, however, local farmers used the occasion to emphasize to
Gore their own difficulties and their dissatisfaction with the
Clinton-Gore administration. Afterward, many of the farmers
grumbled that they were not happy with any of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing blue jeans and a denim shirt, Gore stood center stage in
a barn near this tiny town in western Iowa and denounced what he
described as the ``deadly threat'' facing America's family farms.
Some farmers said it sounded odd coming from a man who has helped
run the country for the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The message that Gore knows Iowa's concerns best is being
reinforced in new television and radio commercials with a
testimonial by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the floods hit in '93, Al Gore came through for us,''
Harkin says in one commercial. ``When it came to farm credit and
federal crop insurance and ethanol _ Al Gore came through for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``In fact, Al Gore is the only Democratic candidate for
president who has been there for us in our times of need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign had flown a New Jersey farmer, Roy Etsch, who
has 1,100 acres of corn and hay near Princeton, to Iowa to tell the
crowd in Sloan that Bradley never showed any interest in New Jersey
farmers while representing the Senate from that state. Etsch told
the audience that he had never been able to meet Bradley despite
several attempts, and added dismissively that Bradley wouldn't know
the difference between corn and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   Etsch, who said afterward that he was a Democrat who had voted
for Bradley in each Senate election, told the crowd that Bradley
``knows nothing about agriculture and cares less.''
</P>
<P>
   It made good theater, but many of the farmers did not seem
particularly impressed. While America's economic expansion is about
to set a record for its length, farmers are facing desperate times
because of the slump in commodity prices. In the last three years,
6,000 of Iowa's 20,000 hog farmers have gone out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving exact particulars, Gore called for new farm
policies that would make payments to farmers whose prices are
cyclically depressed, for more export markets for agriculture, for
a larger exemption for family farms from the inheritance tax and
for stronger anti-trust action against large agribusiness concerns
that farmers often accuse of setting monopolistic prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear anything new or see that he had any answers,''
Don Hamisch, who farms alfalfa hay, said afterward. Hamisch, a
Democrat, said he was not sure who he would vote for in the
Democratic caucuses but that in the general election he would
probably vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-answer period, some farmers asked tough
questions that were critical of the Clinton administration's
Justice Department, Agriculture Department and Trade
Representative. Whenever a skeptical question was raised, some of
the farmers would nod and whisper ``yes!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mood toward Gore was a bit more positive afterward
than before the meeting, and some farmers said a bit grudgingly
that he seemed to know something about their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us what we wanted to hear,'' said Bill Ortner, who
farms 3,000 acres of corn and soybeans and who earlier had
described himself as unhappy with all the candidates. ``He's tilted
me more to his side. And Senator Bradley is probably out of the
picture now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggested in his talk that conservation programs might be
one way to increase revenue for family farmers, and many in the
audience seemed to welcome that. But many said that they were
suspicious of Gore because of his association with
environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about him being over-protective of the environment, so
that I can't do my job,'' fretted Frank Yanak, a local farmer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LOCKHEED-BIAS14-COX     01-13 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-BIAS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed practiced bias against blacks, EEOC report says
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. _ A federal investigation has determined that some
white managers at Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems
discriminated against black employes by overlooking them for
promotion, training, and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission found that
despite the Marietta-based company's assertion that promotions were
based on seniority and experience, black employees often had more
of both than white employees who won the promotions, according to
copies of the findings obtained by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely serious situation with far-reaching
consequences for employees at both Lockheed's Marietta plant and
other Lockheed plants,'' said Josie A. Alexander, one of the
lawyers representing more than 20 current and former Lockheed
employees. ``My clients believe there is an atmosphere of racism
that permeates the plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed President Tom Burbage denied a racist culture exists in
the plant, and he emphasized that the defense contractor has
long-standing policies forbidding discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the issues that were raised are widespread,'' he
said. ``I think it all relates to the past. I can do nothing about
the past but apologize for it for it. What I can deal with is the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is contesting the EEOC allegations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice Williams-Kimbrough, director of the Atlanta EEOC
district, issued nine findings of racial discrimination, and one
case of discrimination against the disabled. The EEOC also found
Lockheed managers retaliated against one employee for filing an
EEOC complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is continuing in at least 10 other cases that
involve race, gender and disability, Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has teamed up with Johnnie Cochran, the prominent
trial lawyer who became a household name during the O.J. Simpson
case, in pursing the case against Cobb County's largest private
employer. The case could achieve class action status since the EEOC
found discrimination existed against blacks as a group.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC outlined its allegations in ``letters of
determination'' dated Sept. 30. The letters do not carry a legal
penalty. Instead, they are one step in a long process of bringing
discrimination claims under the federal statute.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed and the plaintiffs are tentatively scheduled to engage
in what amounts to settlement talks in February, Alexander said. If
an agreement can't be reached, the EEOC will either issue a
``right-to-sue'' letter to the plaintiffs, or elect to sue the
company itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process takes a lot of time and a lot of investigation,''
Burbage said. ``We work with the EEOC office to understand the
issues and resolve them.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the allegations, however, couldn't have been worse
for Lockheed. The Marietta plant is currently slashing its work
force, has had its leadership reshuffled, has just finished a tough
budget fight in Congress to keep funding for its F-22 stealth
fighter, and is struggling to find buyers for its mainstay, the
C-130J transport plane.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage, who became president in April, said he was frustrated
that there has been so much focus on the allegations of a handful
of the company's employees. He said the company has a good track
record in minority hiring and doing business with minority
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage also said he has set up committees to facilitate better
communication between the blue-collar labor force and upper
management to cut out the filter of middle-management _ where the
EEOC documents indicated the discrimination problem existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any work force that is 10,000 people big, it's not to say
the same frailties don't exist there as you find anywhere else in
society,'' Burbage said. ``If you get a picture of this company by
reading EEOC findings, that's one picture. If you try to get a real
understanding of what this company is all about, that's another
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
