<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MR. PRESIDENT, YOU'VE GOT MAIL _ FROM SYRIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TO: President Clinton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FROM: Bashar.Assad(at)Hama.com
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. President: I saw your letter from Tuesday on my dad's
desk. Dad's not feeling too well these days. He fades in and out.
His elevator doesn't always go to the top floor anymore. So I'm
answering for him with this e-mail. As you know, I'm 34, and
President Assad's eldest surviving son and heir apparent. I was
trained as an ophthalmologist in London and am the founder of the
new Syrian Internet Society. Dad's not into the Web much. I still
tease him that he thinks the Internet is something you catch fish
with on the Euphrates.
</P>
<P>
   Bill _ may I call you Bill? _ I saw you asking my dad to make
some gesture of sweetness to the Israelis if we want to get our
occupied Golan Heights back. Well, Bill, let me ask you something:
Have you ever seen the movie ``Godfather II''? Because that's what
it's like around here. My dad didn't get to be Syria's Godfather by
treating his enemies ``sweet.'' You want my dad to offer the
Israelis a level of normalization that he doesn't have with Lebanon
or Jordan, let alone with his own brother, Rifaat.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, speaking of that lunatic Rifaat, there are days that my
dad would like to do to him what Al Pacino did to his brother Fredo
in ``Godfather II'' _ blow him away while he's sayin' his Hail
Marys. The press says Rifaat's been sitting around Paris and
Marbella, talking by phone with all his buddies in the Syrian Army,
plotting to get rid of me when Dad's gone. Dad just closed down the
illegal port Rifaat was running out of his summer home in Latakia.
The press said we blew it up with 40 tanks _ sort of ``urban
renewal'' with the residents still at home.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Bill, this is Hobbes' jungle here, not Hope, Ark. We
don't do sweetness. To think my dad is ever going to have fully
``normal'' relations with Israelis, who have occupied our land for
33 years, is a chimera. But you're all missing the point. Because
while the Israelis will never have warm relations with us, if we do
sign a peace treaty with them over the Golan it will lead to
normalization of their relations with the whole Arab world. We are
the keepers of the flame of the Arab-Israeli conflict, not that
quisling Yasser Arafat, and when we say it's over, it's over.
</P>
<P>
   My dad is serious, because he knows that the only way he can
turn power over to me is if he can get this Golan issue off the
table. Then I can focus on internal reform and modernization, which
is my strength. If the war with Israel is still on when my dad
goes, I don't stand a chance. Power will go right to the thugs
here.
</P>
<P>
   What you have to understand, Bill, is that my dad's Arab
generation, which was bent on fighting the Jews _ their role isn't
to smile on the Jews now. No one would believe it. Their role is to
declare that the war is over and to pave the way for my generation.
Only my dad can call an end to this war, and only I can normalize
relations with Israel. Only Mao could end the war between China and
the U.S., and only Deng could normalize relations. The Israelis can
have normalized peace with us _ on the installment plan.
</P>
<P>
   What else is in it for the Israelis? Are you kidding? A lot. An
end to the Arab ideological struggle. A shrinking of Iran's
influence, because the Iranians won't be able to work out of Syria
or Lebanon. An end to the bloody war in south Lebanon.
Early-warning stations on the Golan. And eventually an exchange of
embassies and trade. We're offering cold, hard substance and you
want us to bake them a cake! Look, we serve our peace cold around
here. And believe me, it's worth more to the Israelis that way,
because if we do it our way _ properly chilled _ every Arab will
know that we did it on our own terms because we felt it was in our
own interest to call this conflict quits. We will sell an end to
rejectionism to the Arabs, but Barak has to sell full withdrawal to
the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Bill, do you remember that scene in ``Godfather II'' when Hyman
Roth says to Al Pacino about the brutality of the mafia world: What
can we do? ``This is the business we've chosen.'' Well, this is the
neighborhood we and the Israelis have chosen. This ain't Sesame
Street here, pal, and my dad ain't Big Bird.
</P>
<P>
   You want a smile and a shoeshine? A kiss on both cheeks? Call
Arafat. That's his thing. You want to kiss goodbye to this
conflict, call my dad: Hafez al-Assad, the Capo di Tutti Capi
himself. He may be frail, but he's got one last scene in him _ and
I've got the whole next act. Trust me. Warmly, Bashar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
