<HEADLINE>
GEORGE PUTNAM TO STEP DOWN AS CHAIRMAN OF FAMED FUND GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ George Putnam said Thursday he will retire as head of
Putnam Investments, the mutual fund giant founded by his father
before World War II and rooted in an ancestor's 19th-century
landmark court ruling that spawned America's money management
business.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam will step down at the end of 2001 as chairman of Putnam
Management Co., popularly known as Putnam Investments. He will
retire as chairman and president of the firm's funds in June.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund group, John Hill, 57, an independent trustee who
runs an investment advisory firm, will become chairman. Putnam's
47-year-old son, George 3d, a Putnam trustee who runs two financial
services companies, will become president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a young person's business,'' Putnam Sr., 72, said
Thursday from his Florida vacation home. ``Investment management
requires a lot of youth and energy.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``there is a role for old poops like myself when the markets
turn,'' said the retiring executive, who will stay on as chairman
emeritus. ``A little gray hair comforts the shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   His retirement will have more symbolic than actual impact, since
Putnam Investments is effectively run by Lawrence Lasser, its
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a business operations point of view, I don't think the
transition matters a lot,'' said Louis Harvey, president of Dalbar
Inc., a Boston fund consulting firm. ``Larry is driving the machine
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, another senior Putnam executive, Robert Lucey, a
managing director who oversees operations, reportedly told Lasser
he will retire. It was not immediately clear who would replace him.
</P>
<P>
   George Putnam Sr. epitomizes not just Harvard-educated, Brahmin
gentility, but the conservative investment ethos established by his
great-great-great-grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Putnam's historic ``prudent man rule,'' which he authored
in 1830 as a justice of the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court,
established the legal foundation for professional money management.
The landmark decision said a trustee could carefully buy common
stocks on behalf of a client.
</P>
<P>
   The late George Putnam Jr., the senior Putnam's father, set up
an investment fund in 1925 and founded his namesake company, with
the flagship George Putnam Fund of Boston, in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, the nation's fourth-largest fund firm, with 114 funds
and assets under management of $354 billion, is still guided by a
conservative investment philosophy that it calls ``truth in
labeling.'' It promises that portfolio managers will not leap into
areas not outlined in fund prospectuses.
</P>
<P>
   That means a large-cap growth fund won't suddenly load up on
bonds, or plunge into flavor-of-the-moment ``momentum'' plays
outside its mandate. The firm favors team management, not star
stockpickers.
</P>
<P>
   George Putnam Sr. was also an industry leader in hiring
independent trustees to oversee individual funds (and paying them
very well). He has served on the board of dozens of corporations
and institutions, including Houghton Mifflin, General Mills, and
the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam said he would have retired last year after three decades
as fund family chairman, but that Hill had asked him to stay on
another year to give Hill ``time to get up to speed.''
</P>
<P>
   George Putnam 3d is head of New Generation Research and New
Generation Adviser, both in Boston. Hill oversees First Reserve
Corp., in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, which was sold to Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos. in 1970, has
seen sales soar in recent years as the market has boomed. But the
firm _ like many of its competitors _ has also experienced steep
withdrawals as investors have become more impatient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
