<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MINORITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUNT OF AIDS EPIDEMIC MOVES TO MINORITY MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's AIDS epidemic has passed a new milestone: minority
men who have sex with other men have surpassed white gay men as the
group of Americans most likely to have acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The statistic _ 52 percent of all homosexually acquired AIDS now
involves men of color _ is evidence of a fundamental shift in a
disease long identified in this country as predominantly affecting
white gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``These data will surprise many across the nation,'' said Dr.
Helene Gayle of the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
which is publishing the numbers Friday. ``We still think of the gay
epidemic as being largely a white one and may not realize how much
it is spreading to the gay and bisexual minority communities.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gayle added, those who follow AIDS closely
have seen this benchmark a long way off. ``The startling thing
about this. . .is that this trend has been going on all along and
people have kind of ignored this,'' she said. ``The surprise is
that people are surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Phill Wilson, director of the African American AIDS Policy and
Training Institute at the University of Southern California in Los
Angeles, said: ``The tragedy here is that this did not have to
happen. We gay and bi men of color were disproportionately affected
in 1989. . .and yet we did not do enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows what happens when we do not understand the
complexities of race, gender, and sexual orientation in
minorities,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The shift of HIV and AIDS as a predominantly minority epidemic
has more than historical importance, said AIDS experts and
activists. It is much tougher for public health programs to reach
many minority men who engage in homosexual behavior, they said,
because many are more reluctant than white gay men to acknowledge
and modify their risky behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many gay and bisexual Latino and African-American
men who have sexual contact with men, but who identify as
heterosexual,'' said Laurence ``Carrie'' Farrell, an AIDS
specialist at Dimock Community Health Center in Boston. ``There's a
good deal of same-sex behavior there, but it's not talked about at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American men who acquired the human immunodeficiency
virus (HIV) from other men are four times more likely than white
men in that situation to call themselves heterosexual rather than
gay or bisexual, according to a recent, unpublished CDC study of
nearly 8,800 HIV-infected men. Latino men were more than twice as
likely as non-Hispanic whites to consider themselves heterosexual,
despite their homosexual contacts.
</P>
<P>
   The marked ``fear and self-loathing'' that surrounds
homosexuality among black and Latino men ``hampers education
efforts that target gay-identified men, and leads to unknowing
infections of wives and girlfriends and children,'' said Dr. Rafael
Campo of Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The new data also suggest minority males are being infected
through same-sex exposures at younger ages than white men. A
sampling of HIV-infected Americans found that 16 percent of African
Americans were teenagers or in their early 20s, 13 percent of
Latino males were aged 13 to 24, and nine percent of infected white
males were this young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really the most alarming news is how much younger men of color
are becoming infected,'' said Julio Abreu of AIDS Action, a
Washington-based advocacy group. ``Clearly it's not enough to say
we're going to have messages targeted at gay youth. We have to talk
about gay youth of color.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle said the data underscore that the federal government needs
``to expand our efforts directed toward men of color.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDC can identify $137 million last year that was targeted to
African American communities for AIDS prevention efforts, but much
of that was not specifically targeted to black men who engage in
same-sex behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were able to provide $7 million new dollars to
community-based programs for men of color,'' Gayle said. ``But
clearly, $7 million is only a drop in the bucket and more needs to
be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo, the Boston physician, said the Latino community
especially needs to focus more attention on the HIV epidemic. He
noted that a 1998 attempt to convene Hispanic leaders to a ``summit
meeting'' sponsored by the Harvard AIDS Institute was largely
rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite sadly, none of the prominent Latinos came, with one
exception, entertainer Rosie Perez,'' Campo said. ``Elected
officials were invited, prominent entertainers, sports figures,
business leaders. It was quite astonishing to see the silence as we
tried to begin a dialogue on this. . .in the face of these
incredibly shocking statistics. Some congressmen we invited
represent districts that have among the highest AIDS rates in the
nation. None of them came.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, the Boston AIDS educator, said the new statistics
should help arouse interest in minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're close to a tipping point,'' he said. ``I don't
know anyone. . .who doesn't know someone who is infected or
affected by HIV. That means we have reached that critical mass. The
next challenge is: OK, what are we going to do about it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
