<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-N     01-13 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPLETE VICTORY APPEARS ELUSIVE TO RUSSIANS IN CHECHEN TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARGUN, Russia _ The Russian military insists it has again taken
control of Argun from Chechen rebels. But soldiers moving through
the town on Thursday clearly did not think all the danger had
passed, as they scanned the rooftops and windows of the battered
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are snipers around'' a Russian officer shouted. ``Take
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Argun has become a conspicuous example of how hard it may be for
Russia to keep what it has taken.
</P>
<P>
   Across Chechnya, Russian troops tried on Thursday to tighten
their grip over the breakaway republic, in the throes of its second
war in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ingush-Chechnya border, troops all but closed the
frontier and demanded that all males aged 10 to 60 be checked. The
move effectively reversed the Russian policy of encouraging
refugees to return to Chechnya, since families refused to travel
without their men.
</P>
<P>
   And here in Argun, only six miles east of Grozny, the capital,
Interior Ministry troops and militia went house to house, looking
in basements, attics and even wells, as they combed for rebel
diehards and sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to conduct repeated and more thorough checks
across entire Chechnya,'' Interior Minister Vladimir B. Rushailo
said on a trip to Chechnya. ``The militants did not simply
disappear. They are here among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officers said they doubted Argun, first taken by the
Russians in early December, would ever be totally secure.
</P>
<P>
   The latest battle began Sunday. In the fighting, the Russian
military commandant was encircled by militants and gunned down
after two armored personnel carriers that escorted him out of his
headquarters were destroyed, Russian officers said on Thursday.
Russian artillery pounded the city.
</P>
<P>
   The official Russian toll was four dead and five wounded, but
some soldiers said the true figure was higher. ``The say it was
three or four, but in fact 30 died,'' yelled a Russian soldier
standing next to an armored personnel carrier as a small group of
journalists walked past. ``Write that!''
</P>
<P>
   Argun was a dismal place before the fight. It had gas, though
only since December, but no electricity. Pensions, salaries and
subsidies had not been paid, and many of the refugees who came from
even more dangerous areas say they are cold and hungry. The schools
have yet to open and the trains do not run. But the local market
has started to do business again.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels began their counteroffensive early Sunday morning
soon after truckloads of militants zoomed into the city. It is not
clear how the hundreds of militants managed to get through.
</P>
<P>
   Russian army troops are supposed to operate checkpoints along
the roads. They stop young men, checking their trigger fingers for
calluses and ordering them to remove their shirts so they can check
their shoulders for marks of rifle slings and bruises from the
kickback of automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Chechens say they often bribe their way through, and the
vigilance of the Russians appears to fade at night.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m. the militants had clambered on the rooftops and
entered the city center. Yelling, they began their assault on the
railroad station, the militia headquarters and the adjoining base
for elite OMON militia units.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for me to talk about this,'' said an OMON
militiamen who comes from Magnitogorsk, a Ural mountains steel
town, before he turned away with his head down. ``It came out of
the blue. They began shooting from grenade launchers. Only
yesterday the `two hundreds' were taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hundreds'' is army slang for corpses. One explanation is
that a corpse packed in a zinc coffin and wooden crate for
transport weights 200 kilos.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the main fighting lasted 12 hours basically without
a break.
</P>
<P>
   As the rebels pressed their attack, a rebel negotiating team
carrying a white flag approached Russian troops at the railway
station, the scene of the fiercest fighting. The rebels demanded
that the Russians surrender and promised that they could leave. The
Russians refused.
</P>
<P>
   A burnt-out armored personnel carrier and truck provides some
gruesome evidence of what happened to the Russian military
commandant of the town, Col. Vladimir Kushnaryov, who came from St.
Petersburg late last month.
</P>
<P>
   The colonel was gunned down after his armored column was
surrounded. Some Russian officials said that local people asked the
colonel to come to negotiations and that militants shot him from
behind a crowd of civilians as he ventured out of his headquarters.
Others say he was simply trying to see what was happening in the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commandant was riddled with bullets,'' said Oleg, a member
of an OMON unit from Nyzhny Tagil in the Urals. ``Two platoon
commanders were killed and had their ears cut off.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Nikolai Koshman, the Russian vice prime minister
who administers the Russian controlled areas, vowed to track down
the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find those who killed the commandant,'' Koshman
said. ``And we have to find all the accomplices.''
</P>
<P>
   To counter the rebels, the Russians began firing artillery.
Russian troops and residents say that some civilian homes were
destroyed by the shells. Some civilians were being tended to at the
hospital here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the rebels left Sunday night, but the Russians kept on
shelling,'' said Said Magomad Allaudinov, 42. ``The following day
and the next night, they kept shelling the city. It was heavy fire.
Maybe it was mortars. Maybe tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipers, however, were active in the city for three more days.
Elsewhere in the Chechen lowlands, Russian troops took careful
precautions. Transport helicopters skimmed a few dozen feet over
the ground, following the undulating terrain, and zig-zaged as they
approached Argun.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops say they need to do more to prevent rebel
attacks. OMON soldiers say the Russian troops should seal the
routes to the settlements more tightly, including the dirt roads
and pathways that the Chechens know better than the soldiers
</P>
<P>
   But others voiced doubt they could secure much more than a
temporary respite. One officer from an OMON unit from Khabarovsk in
Russia's Far East said he expected the turmoil to continue, as
Russian troops and the rebels tussle over Chechnya and its
resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is money to be made from the oil in Chechnya,
this will keep happening,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
