<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SCHAWB-USTRUST-2TAKES     01-13 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHAWB-USTRUST-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHWAB TO ACQUIRE U.S. TRUST IN FIRST BIG DEAL UNDER NEW BANK
LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first big financial services deal since
Congress changed decades-old banking laws last fall, Charles Schwab
Corp. said Thursday that it would make a leap across both the
country and the investment spectrum to buy U.S. Trust Corp. for
$2.73 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring U.S. Trust, a New York-based private bank that caters
to the wealthiest Americans, would be a big step in the
transformation of San Francisco-based Schwab from a discount
brokerage firm for do-it-yourself investors to a full-service firm
that also offers personalized investment advice to customers
willing to pay for it. Schwab has been adding products and services
to its offerings in an attempt to distance itself from the dozens
of low-commission electronic brokerages that have sprung up in the
last several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers have been telling us they need more help with
their complex financial lives,'' said Charles R. Schwab, who
founded his company as one of the first discount brokerage firms
and built it into the nation's biggest electronic brokerage firms.
Now, he said, the richest of them will have access to services
provided by U.S. Trust, including estate planning, tax planning and
investment management.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab is paying a rich price, offering 3.427 of its highly
valued shares for each share of U.S. Trust. At Schwab's Wednesday
closing price of $37.625, that translates to about $129 a share, or
about 63 percent more than U.S. Trust's Wednesday closing price of
$78.875. That price includes about $150 million in cash and stock
options being offered to every employee of U.S. Trust to keep them
from leaving the company for two years after the transaction, which
is expected to close by July.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Schwab fell about $3 a share Thursday morning but
recovered after analysts were briefed on the deal and closed up
$2.875, to at $40.50. U.S. Trust's shares soared $54.125, to $133.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trust, with $80 billion is assets, is small compared with
Schwab. Schwab took in about $107 billion in new assets last year,
and now has more than $700 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts were recommending that U.S. Trust
shareholders sell their shares now and pocket the profits, others
were recommending hanging on to Schwab stock. Ronald Baron, a money
manager whose company holds about 25 million shares of stock said
he thinks Schwab can become ``one of the most profitable, biggest
businesses in the United States.'' He said, ``I think I'm going to
make 10 times my money in the next seven to nine years. We've
already made 40 times our money in the last eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Executives of both companies acknowledged Thursday that the
match was not an obvious one because the firms appear to have very
different customers and corporate cultures. ``When we first
approached them, I think their reaction was, Why would we combine
with a discount brokerage company?'' said David Pottruck, who
shares the chairman and chief executive titles with Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck said he made that initial contact with H. Marshall
Schwarz, the chairman and chief executive of U.S. Trust, early last
year about a year after he became a private-banking customer at
U.S. Trust. Pottruck, who sold about $100 million of Schwab stock
last year, said that he switched his private-banking account to
U.S. Trust because he was unhappy with the service he was getting
at Wells Fargo before that.
</P>
<P>
   After several meetings between executives of the two companies ,
discussions ended last summer without an agreement. Had a deal been
hatched then, before Congress repealed the Glass-Steagall Act of
1933 that prevented securities firms from buying banks, Schwab
would have needed to restructure itself as a bank holding company,
Pottruck said. To do that, Schwab probably would have had to set
off its business of making markets in stocks as a separate
subsidiary, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in banking laws cleared the way for Schwab to become
a financial holding company with U.S. Trust as a standalone unit.
``When I saw the change in legislation, I thought this could make a
difference for U.S. Trust'' because it would increase the ranks of
potential buyers of the company, Pottruck said. `We were scared to
death of U.S. Trust going into play.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Pottruck said, he was surprised when Jeffrey Maurer,
president and chief operating officer of U.S. Trust, called him in
November to revive discussions of a deal. Schwarz said he and his
management team had concluded that the firms were not as different
as they seemed and that they complemented each other in some
important ways.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Schwab has been an innovator in the use of
technology in financial services, leading the charge onto the
Internet that spawned a raft of competitors, such as E-Trade Group
and Ameritrade Holdings. U.S. Trust has not kept up with
technological advances; in fact, most of its processing is handled
by another bank, Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab plans to change its Web site, one of the most visited
locations on the World Wide Web, to provide U.S. Trust customers
access to up-to-date information on their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will bring them some new types of innovation,'' Pottruck
said of U.S. Trust management. ``They tend to be a little more
cautious and incremental in their thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab also plans to share the research on about 250 stocks
published by U.S. Trust's 25 analysts with Schwab customers who now
receive research from several sources, including investment banks
Credit Suisse First Boston and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. After swearing
for years that they would never tell their customers how to invest,
Schwab executives have been searching for a way to offer stock
research that does not contradict their oft-stated view that most
Wall Street research is tainted by the firms' conflicts as
investment bankers to many of the companies they analyze.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz said U.S. Trust plans to add several analysts and double
the number of companies it covers. But Pottruck said that Schwab
will not be ``pushing a hot stock that is going to double in the
next nanosecond.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The executives said they expect the deal, which is structured as
a pooling of interests rather than a purchase for accounting
purposes, to add a 1 cent a share to Schwab's earnings this year
and 2 to 3 cents a share next year, without any significant cost
savings.
</P>
<P>
   That was not an attractive enough promise for one analyst who
has followed U.S. Trust for several years, Raphael Soifer of Brown
Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything against Schwab but it is a very
volatile, market-sensitive stock and our market forecast is for a
bear market within the next six months,'' Soifer said. A downturn
in the stock market would spell trouble for Schwab, which derives
about 60 percent of its revenue from its customers' trades.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab also faces increasing competition from traditional
brokerage firms, such as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co., which have started offering online stock trading
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing its dependence on market activity is one reason for
Schwab to want to buy U.S. Trust. The company gets almost all of
its revenue from fees paid its wealthy clients for management of
their assets. It aims to attract customers with at least $1 million
in investable assets and is known for a regular survey of the
wealthiest 1 percent of Americans that it conducts.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trust keeps about 1 percent of the assets clients place
with the firm, compared with just 0.67 percent for Schwab. Pottruck
said his firm's cut of clients' assets had been declined from 0.85
percent just three years ago, but Schwab had more than made up for
that shrinkage by attracting about $500 billion of new assets.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon de Oliveira, chairman of J.P. Morgan Asset Management,
which contains the private banking unit of J.P. Morgan, said he was
happy to see Schwab paying such a high price for a competitor.
``It's amazing what a high stock price can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Oliveira said many affluent customers have their money spread
among several financial firms. ``There's a race among a number of
private banks for those customers,'' he said. ``That's the real
sweet spot of the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
