<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-CROWD14-COX     01-13 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CROWD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain shines before a crowd
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ If campaigns take the form that best suits the
candidate, then Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) showed this week why his
campaign prefers the free-wheeling town meeting to formal speeches.
</P>
<P>
   On his 26th trip to New Hampshire, McCain gave two formal
speeches and held six town meetings, during which he typically
spoke for about 15 minutes and then took 45 minutes of questions or
more.
</P>
<P>
   His speech Thursday to the New Hampshire Legislature had a
perfunctory air to it. McCain read his text word for word, and not
particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would create the position of ``reform czar'' if he is
elected, a Cabinet-level position to oversee the reforms that are
the core of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   There was little reaction, even though 75 of the more than 400
New Hampshire lawmakers support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   A McCain town meeting, by contrast, is participatory theater.
</P>
<P>
   They are usually lively affairs, and this week, the audiences
were huge.
</P>
<P>
   If the McCain team feared that his support would wane following
last week's news reports that he had intervened with federal
agencies on behalf of campaign donors, they must have been
comforted by this week's crowd counts.
</P>
<P>
   A midday rally in Dublin, N.H., drew 750 people who saw McCain
hold forth beneath a conveniently placed banner that read, ``Truth
and Courage.''
</P>
<P>
   An evening event in Keene must have made fire marshals nervous
over the way campaign aides stuffed 500 people into a hotel meeting
room.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few people asked McCain about his actions on behalf of
contributors, and there was no evident dissatisfaction in the crowd
with his explanation that he considers it his job as Senate
Commerce Committee chairman to prod sluggish bureaucracies to
action.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Muccino of Amherst, a retired pilot, said after the meeting,
``He did what our elected officials are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The most sustained applause came when he pledged to run a
positive campaign. ``There's going to be no negative comments, no
negative ads from this campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as McCain lays out policy proposals, his campaign keeps
coming back to assessments of character.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what these town meetings are all about. Sometimes I'm
going to tell you what you don't want to hear. But I'm always going
to tell you what I believe,'' he said to applause.
</P>
<P>
   In Dublin, Dorcey Flynn, a health care worker who is still torn
between McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley, voiced a frequently heard
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his air of authority and his decisiveness,'' Flynn
said. ``Yet he also seems ready to listen to information.''
</P>
<P>
   PACKED BUMPER TO BUMPER
</P>
<P>
   McCain, reporters and campaign aides are cheek by jowl these
days on the Straight Talk Express, the campaign bus.
</P>
<P>
   It remains open to reporters from the day's start straight
through to the finish. But so many more media outlets want a piece
of the action that campaign aides are forced to ration the prized
seats in the back with the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   So many people crowded onto the bus Thursday that the driver
warned an aide that he might have trouble if he had to stop
suddenly on the snowy day.
</P>
<P>
   In the back, though, nothing had changed. McCain held forth on
any and all topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of my prison experience, I have never been more tired
than I am from time to time in this campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Camera crews from England, Japan and MTV dropped in and out.
``Are you living la vida loca?'' MTV's Kate Sotak asked above the
whine of the bus's motor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did his quite respectable impersonation of Bob Dole and
rattled off the species, if not the names, of most of his family's
32 pets, including several despised chickens and small dogs.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING JOKES ALONG THE WAY
</P>
<P>
   McCain says he has never done stand-up comedy. Cindy McCain, his
wife, says he watched a lot of Johnny Carson. But McCain reels off
a well-worn cache of jokes whenever he can, which was several times
a day this week in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   On Arizona's lack of water: ``The trees chase the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   On the lead character for the movie version of his memoir, Faith
of My Fathers: ``I want Tom Cruise. My kids want Danny DeVito.''
</P>
<P>
   On why he's running for president: ``My wife says it's because I
suffered several sharp blows to the head in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   On the depths to which his campaign has sunk: ``I spoke at a
West Point graduates' dinner.'' (McCain is a Naval Academy
alumnus.)
</P>
<P>
   On his low standing in early New Hampshire polls last year: ``I
was at 3 percent in a poll that had a margin of error of 5 percent.
So conceivably I started this campaign at minus 2 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   On his attendance at the MTV awards last year with daughter
Meghan: ``The greatest assault on my senses since I was in
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more. And McCain may have a chance to tell them when
he appears Jan. 20 on CBS-TV's ``Late Night with David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
