<SLUG> BC-AILING-HMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SEEKS EXPERT HELP IN POSSIBLE SALE OF HARVARD HMO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN AND RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Officials signaled Thursday they may consider a sale of
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care to an outside buyer, announcing they
plan to hire an investment banker to solicit proposals to
recapitalize the ailing health maintenance organization.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said a firm would be selected
Friday and begin work immediately to provide a ``menu of options''
in 10 days for bringing Harvard Pilgrim back to health.
</P>
<P>
   Further suggesting regulators want to be prepared for a speedy
sale, Reilly said he is invoking a state rule that allows him to
take an extra measure of control over Harvard Pilgrim in the event
of a sale. The move means Reilly would oversee the possible
conversion of Harvard Pilgrim from a nonprofit to a for-profit
company.
</P>
<P>
   While he stressed regulators simply want to explore all options
_ including selling pieces of the health plan to multiple buyers,
or obtaining loans or some otheof finanancing _ the
announcement immediately sparked speculation of a for-profit buyer
and set off a firestorm of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Trade groups, including a coalition of health-care professionals
known as the Ad Hoc Committee to Defend Health Care, unleashed a
flurry of protests. ``This would be a drastic mistake,'' Paul Ling,
a Quincy clinical psychologist who is a member of the committee,
said of a possible for-profit buyer. ``At best, it's a very
short-term solution that will present us with even greater crises
in the not-too-distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State William F. Galvin said Reilly's announcement
is a ``stunning development that would change the entire landscape
of health care in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to calm the storm, Reilly called reporters late in the
day, saying, ``I do not want to leave the impression that we are
seeking a for-profit buyer. In no way shape or form do I want to
say that we are predisposed to anything. We want to pursue every
conceivable option to recapitalize Harvard Pilgrim. That would
include for-profit and nonprofit solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, industry observers have said that other nonprofit health
plans in the state are in no financial condition to buy Harvard
Pilgrim, by far the largest plan in the state. And for all
practical purposes, buyers would be limited to large national
for-profit health insurers such as Cigna Group, based in
Philadelphia; Wellpoint Health Networks, a California HMO; United
Health Care, a Minnesota HMO; or Aetna, a health insurer based in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Conceivably, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts might
be interested in stepping in, but most health executives say the
company does not have the financial wherewithal to pull off such a
feat.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators took control of Harvard Pilgrim Jan. 4 after
health plan officials said they discovered $58.5 million in 1999
losses that they didn't know about before. The discovery meant
Harvard Pilgrim's projected losses for the year soared to at least
$150 million, and possibly as high as $177 million.
</P>
<P>
   A judge's order mandated that state regulators come up with a
plan for bailing out the health plan within 30 days, a feat that
now looks nearly impossible, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said Thursday that officials finally have received what
they believe is their first reliable information about Harvard
Pilgrim's daily cash flow _ an indicator of the health plan's
ability to pay its day-to-day bills.
</P>
<P>
   The report indicated that ``for now'' Harvard Pilgrim can meet
its daily obligations as well as pay some of the debts it already
owes to health providers, Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said they have received their first indication of
the size of Harvard Pilgrim's debts, a report on the HMO's top 10
creditors and how much they are owed. That report will be shipped
to hospitals Friday to see whether the information provided by
Harvard Pilgrim squares with what hospitals say the health plan
owes. Officials declined to disclose details of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials said 100 Harvard Pilgrim employees were
laid off Thursday. The layoffs were part of Harvard Pilgrim's
turnaround plan even before the health plan was placed in
receivership, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampering state officials' plans to move quickly on a Harvard
Pilgrim bailout is the disarray of its accounting systems, which is
so confusing that officials said they can't rely on it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Reilly said he believes enough reliable information
has been cobbled together by accountants hired by the state
Insurance Division to satisfy possible buyers or lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got enough here to solicit serious proposals,'' he said
in an interview Thursday. ``We would expect people who are serious
would want to perform their own due diligence anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials concede the state's timetable to receive offers
for the health plan, which has annual revenue of $2.8 billion, is
ambitious. It calls for offers that must then be evaluated and
negotiated in roughly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said it's unlikely that any plan would be completed
within the 30-day deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
