<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-ABORTION-BUSH-HNS &LR;      01-13 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP CRITICAL OF TEXAS, MICHIGAN IN RESTRICTING ACCESS TO
ABORTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An abortion-rights group Thursday assailed Texas
and Michigan for enacting the greatest number of state laws in 1999
that restrict access to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League,
which actively backs abortion rights Democrats for high office,
blamed Texas Gov. George W. Bush for what the group called the
state's failure to appreciate a woman's right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the leading candidate for the Republican presidential
nomination, and Michigan Gov. John Engler is a close adviser to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Kate Michelman, president of the group popularly known as
NARAL, said presidential politics played no part in the league's
compilation of data for its ninth annual review of state abortion
laws. However, as the information came together, ``it leapt out at
us'' that the GOP front-runner and Engler lead states that enacted
seven laws each last year that restrict abortion access, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana passed the next highest number of laws last year with
five, the group reported.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL issued its report as the group has been airing 30-second
television ads in Iowa and New Hampshire telling voters that a Bush
presidency would threaten the right of women to choose abortion.
Iowa will hold a Republican presidential nominating caucus Jan. 24,
and New Hampshire will hold a nominating primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush uses the slogan `compassionate conservative' to describe
himself but it hardly describes the record he has compiled as
governor when it comes to ensuring women's reproductive health and
rights,'' Michelman said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Bush, she praised the two candidates for the
Democratic presidential nomination, saying that Vice President Al
Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey would ``both
protect a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bush campaign spokesman disagreed with Michelman's
characterization of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush believes all Americans want to reduce the number
of abortions, no matter where you stand on the issue,'' said Scott
McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has tried to reduce abortions in Texas by promoting
teen-age abstinence, streamlining the adoption process and signing
into law last year a measure that requires parents to be notified
before their minor daughters have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to NARAL, the Texas Right to Life Committee, which
opposes abortion, lauded Bush and the state Legislature for
enacting the laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislation that was passed ensures the health and safety
of the women and young girls in our state,'' said Joe Kral, the
committee's legislative director. ``I think Texas has gone in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kral particularly praised the law requiring parental
notification, saying it helps mothers and fathers protect the
welfare of their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL, however, cited that statute as a sign of Bush's
opposition to a woman's right to choose. The group said the law
effectively bars many girls, who fear severe punishment if their
parents discover their pregnancies, from exercising their
constitutional right to choose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, which took effect Jan. 1, girls 17 or younger
cannot get an abortion without one of their parents being notified
_ unless a judge decides otherwise. A judge can grant a ``bypass''
to the notification requirement if he decides that the girl is
mature enough to make her own decision or if notifying a parent
will be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, pressed on whether he would pick a running mate who
opposes abortion rights, has responded that he would impose no
``litmus test'' in making his selection. Asked if he would pick
people for the Supreme Court based on whether they believe women
should have a constitutional right to choose abortion, Bush has
responded only that he would pick jurists who strictly interpret
the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Michelman, however, said Bush's call for such ``strict
constructionists'' on the Supreme Court was a ``code word'' for
justices who reject the idea that the Constitution protects choice
and would vote to overturn Roe vs. Wade, the court's landmark 1973
decision legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear from our findings that the freedom to choose
stands at a critical crossroads,'' she added. ``Down one road lies
an anti-choice president, an anti-choice Supreme Court and an end
to legal abortion. Down the other lies an America in which women
are entrusted with the freedom and knowledge to make informed
choices about their reproductive lives and health.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelman said three of the court's nine sitting justices have
called for overturning the Roe decision. The jurists are Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   If a sufficient number of court vacancies occur, the next
president could have the opportunity to appoint enough justices to
overturn Roe, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation abounds among court observers that Rehnquist, at age
75, might retire if a Republican wins the presidency this year,
giving a GOP chief executive the opportunity to name a like-minded
jurist. Such a switch would yield no change in the three votes
against the Roe decision, as Scalia, 63, and Thomas, 51, appear
poised to remain on the bench for many more years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other six justices, two are expected to retire within
the next several years, potentially giving the next president the
five votes needed to overturn Roe. These two justices, John Paul
Stevens, 79, and Sandra Day O'Connor, 69, have ruled in support of
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other justices, Anthony M. Kennedy, 63, and David H.
Souter, 60, have supported Roe and are expected to remain on the
bench throughout the next president's term.
</P>
<P>
   The views of the remaining two justices, Ruth Bader Ginsburg,
66, and Stephen G. Breyer, 61, are largely unknown as they have not
had occasion to rule on the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seven 1999 Texas laws that NARAL found objectionable do the
following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Require parents be notified before their minor daughters have
an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require parents' consent before their minor daughters receive
prescription contraceptives with state family-planning funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibit school-based health centers that receive state grants
from providing reproductive services, counseling or referrals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deny tax exemptions to not-for-profit organizations that
perform, refer for, or assist organizations that perform or refer
for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deny reproductive services, except prenatal care and care
related to diseases, illnesses or abnormalities related to the
reproductive system, to low-income women younger than 19 who are
enrolled in the Texas Child Health Plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make it a felony for anyone to take a 14-, 15- or 16-year-old
out of Texas or beyond 120 miles of the child's home without
parental permission.
</P>
<P>
   _ Impose a $2,500 licensing fee on doctors' offices, a charge
that NARAL said ``needlessly'' raises the cost of an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
