<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY PUTTING PATIENTS' BILL OF RIGHTS ON FRONT BURNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey of
Texas, predicted Thursday that Congress would pass a patients' bill
of rights this spring and send it to President Clinton by Easter
Sunday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
   But just how far those protections go, specifically on whether
patients can sue health maintenance organizations to enforce their
rights, will no doubt be contentious as Democrats and Republicans
seek the political high ground on a white-hot campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Along with tighter gun control measures and an increased minimum
wage, a strong patients' bill of rights is a top legislative
priority for Democrats on Capitol Hill. Republicans are expected to
try to defuse these election-year issues by acting on them early
and passing more modest versions that are coupled with more
traditional Republican elements.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Armey said in a speech at a health care forum here
that any patients' bill of rights would also include a series of
tax breaks to help millions of people buy health insurance. These
provisions include the use of tax-free savings accounts to set
aside money for routine medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's comment picks up where Congress left off on the
health-care issue last fall. In July, the Senate approved a bill
covering barely a quarter as many patients as a House bill and
giving them a much more limited set of rights. Then in October, the
House overwhelmingly passed a bill that would give patients a wide
range of new rights in dealing with their health insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill was strongly supported by President Clinton,
almost all Democrats and 68 Republicans. But House Republican
leaders opposed the measure and made sure the Republican conferees
named to hammer out a compromise bill with the Senate were on their
side and not on the side of the bill that won the vote. The House
version also included many of the tax breaks that Armey described
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would allow patients to sue health plans in state
courts for damages if the patients were harmed by a denial of
treatment. But Armey said Thursday he favored an alternative that
would allow patients to sue in federal court, where it is believed
the juries are less likely to return big verdicts against health
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The House-Senate conference committee may meet this month to
resume negotiations. But given the depth of support for stronger
patient protections, it is uncertain whether any compromise that
emerges could muster enough support in the House, much less the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very questionable whether you could pass it out of the
House,'' said Laura Nichols, a spokeswoman for Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democrat. who is an author of the
managed care bill that passed, said he welcomed Armey's decision to
act on the bill, but expressed concern over what the result would
be.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday, Armey said the House bill would likely
include a new tax deduction for people who pay at least 50 percent
of their own health-insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Texas Republican also urged Congress to approve
a new tax credit for the 44 million Americans who are uninsured.
``This year Congress will place a major focus on the uninsured,''
Armey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
