<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES TO FOCUS ON SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT AT MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates is stepping down as chief executive of Microsoft
Corp. to focus on developing technologies at the company he grew
from a two-man start-up to the world's largest software producer.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that adds to the uncertainty of the federal antitrust
case pending against Microsoft, Gates turned over the top
management post to Steve Ballmer, who also remains the company's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Gates will continue as Microsoft's chairman and will take on the
new position of chief software architect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm returning to what I love most _ focusing on technologies
for the future,'' Gates said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The transition was designed to help Microsoft beef up its
Internet-related products, said both Gates and Ballmer, who cited
the rapid pace of change in the on-line industry. They insisted the
move had nothing to do with pressure from government antitrust
attorneys who want the company to settle charges it used monopoly
practices to build its dominant market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision Paul Allen and I had has certainly achieved our
dreams,'' Gates said, referring to the partner with whom he
cofounded Microsoft in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   But now the rise of the Internet has created what Gates called
an ``inflection point'' for Microsoft, at which it must recast its
software offerings. He said he could best oversee that in his new
position.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' move wasn't a major surprise to many analysts who follow
the company, at which Ballmer's responsibilities have grown
steadily since he joined in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But it comes at a time of high tensions between the company and
state and federal attorneys. In November, US District Court Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson supported prosecutors' allegations that
Microsoft had bullied its competitors, in part by insisting on
exclusive deals and by blocking the use of competing software
products used to browse the Web. The ruling prompted Microsoft to
begin a new round of talks toward possibly settling the case.
</P>
<P>
   Recent reports have suggested government lawyers are seeking to
break the company up into several pieces, and some observers
searched for hints in the transition that Microsoft might be moving
closer to such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But in announcing the change from the company's Redmond, Wash.,
headquarters, both Gates and Ballmer continued their public
opposition to such steps. Nor was the timing of the move related to
the government's actions, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with that,'' Ballmer said. Earlier he
said ``It would be reckless and irresponsible for anyone to try to
break up this company. It would be unprecedented, and the single
biggest disservice anybody could do to consumers in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Justice Department and for Massachusetts
Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly, who has also joined the case,
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's denials, some observers said Gates' move
might still ease Microsoft's relations with regulators. ``This
could be a subtle message that they've removed the architect of the
company's monopoly,'' said Matthew Nordan, analyst at Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass. Yankee Group chief Berge Ayvazian said
Gates' step ``takes the ego out'' of negotiations and improves the
prospects of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But Athony Picardi, senior vice president at International Data
Corp. in Framingham, Mass., said the transition _ and Microsoft's
continued belligerance toward breakup suggestions _ represented a
missed opportunity. Picardi recently oversaw a study recommending
that, for the good of the industry, Microsoft should agree to split
itself into five operating companies each focused on different
programming areas.
</P>
<P>
   The company, however, has expressed little interest in the idea.
If anything, Picardi said, in his new position Gates will have more
power to insist that software features be sold in packages, a chief
complaint of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, 44, has become the technology industry's archnerd, and
one of the best-known executives in the world. He's also the
richest, largely due to his stake of about 15 percent in Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Operating systems he helped develop, first one known as DOS and
later the Windows systems, now power the vast majority of personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   In books and presentations Gates has portrayed himself as a
technologist and businessman seeking only to improve the spread of
his company's products; a charitable foundation he recently
established has also given away millions of dollars in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet competitors have long criticized Microsoft for its alleged
use of its heavy market share to force bargains in his favor,
culminating in the Clinton administration's ongoing antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' departure comes just days after America Online Inc.
announced its intentions to purchase Time Warner in what would be
the largest merger ever if approved by regulators. Gates and
Ballmer noted the irony and spoke of AOL as one of the top five
competitors Microsoft faces in the Internet space.
</P>
<P>
   To boost profits, Gates and Ballmer also outlined a set of
products they called ``Next Generation Windows Services,'' which
they said would link software products more effectively via
networks and through a variety of palm-sized computers and other
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, 43, is ranked the fourth-richest American, according to
Forbes magazine, primarily from his almost 5 percent stake in
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
