<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-IOWA-1STLD-WRITE     01-13 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-IOWA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MAKES LITTLE HEADWAY IN COURTING IOWA FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Iowa)  (Subs to add attribution in 9th graf, `... the Center for Rural
Affairs ...') 
(See also IOWA-OUTLOOK) 
(dal) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLOAN, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore on Thursday appealed for
support from Iowa farmers and staged an event that attacked his
opponent, former Sen. Bill Bradley, as unconcerned with the
problems of American agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore used the well-scripted meeting to promote his own
candidacy, however, local farmers used the occasion to emphasize to
Gore their own difficulties and their dissatisfaction with the
Clinton-Gore administration. Afterward, many of the farmers
grumbled that they were not happy with any of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing blue jeans and a denim shirt, Gore stood center stage in
a barn near this tiny town in western Iowa and denounced what he
described as the ``deadly threat'' facing America's family farms.
Some farmers said it sounded odd coming from a man who has helped
run the country for the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The message that Gore knows Iowa's concerns best is being
reinforced in new television and radio commercials with a
testimonial by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the floods hit in '93, Al Gore came through for us,''
Harkin says in one commercial. ``When it came to farm credit and
federal crop insurance and ethanol _ Al Gore came through for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``In fact, Al Gore is the only Democratic candidate for
president who has been there for us in our times of need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign had flown a New Jersey farmer, Roy Etsch, who
has 1,100 acres of corn and hay near Princeton, to Iowa to tell the
crowd in Sloan that Bradley never showed any interest in New Jersey
farmers while representing the Senate from that state. Etsch told
the audience that he had never been able to meet Bradley despite
several attempts, and added dismissively that Bradley wouldn't know
the difference between corn and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   Etsch, who said afterward that he was a Democrat who had voted
for Bradley in each Senate election, told the crowd that Bradley
``knows nothing about agriculture and cares less.''
</P>
<P>
   It made good theater, but many of the farmers did not seem
particularly impressed. While America's economic expansion is about
to set a record for its length, farmers are facing desperate times
because of the slump in commodity prices. In the last three years,
6,000 of Iowa's 20,000 hog farmers have gone out of business, the
Center for Rural Affairs, a farm support group, said.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving exact particulars, Gore called for new farm
policies that would make payments to farmers whose prices are
cyclically depressed, for more export markets for agriculture, for
a larger exemption for family farms from the inheritance tax and
for stronger anti-trust action against large agribusiness concerns
that farmers often accuse of setting monopolistic prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear anything new or see that he had any answers,''
Don Hamisch, who farms alfalfa hay, said afterward. Hamisch, a
Democrat, said he was not sure who he would vote for in the
Democratic caucuses but that in the general election he would
probably vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-answer period, some farmers asked tough
questions that were critical of the Clinton administration's
Justice Department, Agriculture Department and Trade
Representative. Whenever a skeptical question was raised, some of
the farmers would nod and whisper ``yes!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mood toward Gore was a bit more positive afterward
than before the meeting, and some farmers said a bit grudgingly
that he seemed to know something about their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us what we wanted to hear,'' said Bill Ortner, who
farms 3,000 acres of corn and soybeans and who earlier had
described himself as unhappy with all the candidates. ``He's tilted
me more to his side. And Senator Bradley is probably out of the
picture now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggested in his talk that conservation programs might be
one way to increase revenue for family farmers, and many in the
audience seemed to welcome that. But many said that they were
suspicious of Gore because of his association with
environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about him being over-protective of the environment, so
that I can't do my job,'' fretted Frank Yanak, a local farmer.
</P>
</TEXT>
