<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BP-ARCO-NYT &LR;      01-13 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BP-ARCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPATIENT BP AMOCO TELLS FTC TO DECIDE ON ITS DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif . , Alaska, Ore . )   (dal) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frustrated with its discussions with the Federal Trade
Commission about its plans to acquire Atlantic Richfield, BP Amoco
on Thursday took steps to force the agency to either approve the
deal or go to court.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the London-based oil giant, which said it would
invoke its right to set a 20-day deadline for the FTC to challenge
the deal, makes clear that the two sides are still far from
agreement about what the oil companies must do to satisfy
regulators. The sticking point is whether the acquisition will hurt
competition or lead to higher gasoline prices, particularly on the
West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a breakthrough, it also means the FTC is likely to go to
federal court in the next few weeks to block the $31 billion deal.
Should that happen, it would be the largest merger ever challenged
by federal antitrust regulators.
</P>
<P>
   There remains a slim chance of a settlement before that happens,
people close to the negotiations said, and lawyers from both sides
are expected to meet on Friday. But historically, the government
does not negotiate with companies once they invoke the 20-day clock
_ a deadline that BP Amoco could lift, if it chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, which has expressed doubts that the deal can be
completed, viewed BP Amoco's statement as a reaffirmation of its
commitment to the merger. Shares of BP Amoco's American depository
receipts rose 81.25 cents, to $57.375, on Thursday. The terms of
the merger value each ARCO share at 1.64 shares of BP Amoco _ or
about $94, based on Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of ARCO, based in Los Angeles, rose $2, to $79 _ still
far short of the merger value, making it clear that many investors
remain skeptical that the acquisition will close.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, FTC staff members urged that the merger be blocked _
a recommendation that analysts who follow the agency say would have
been made only if the staff members believed it would have the
support of the commission's chairman, Robert Pitofsky.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky has not commented on this deal, but he has previously
expressed concerns that the oil industry has become too heavily
concentrated in recent years, following a spate of mergers and
joint marketing agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute about BP Amoco's deal for ARCO focuses on the effect
the merger will have in California and other Western states.
California, in particular, already has much higher gas prices than
other parts of the country. In November, Bill Lockyer, the state's
attorney general, reported that Californians paid an average of 26
cents more for a gallon of gas in the first eight months of 1999
than other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the deal say they fear the acquisition will drive
gasoline prices even higher. They contend that since BP Amoco and
ARCO, combined, own the bulk of the oil produced from Alaska's
North Slope, and since the West Coast gets much of its gasoline
from Alaska, the merged company would have too much control over
Alaskan oil. They also note that ARCO has traditionally been a
low-priced competitor in California, and they contend that such
positioning would end if it is acquired.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies, which believe they have a strong case should
the FTC take them o court, contend that West Coast prices are set
by the world oil markets, not by Alaskan production _ an opinion
shared by several analysts. Supporters of the deal also say that
the higher California gas prices are primarily caused by taxes, a
requirement for special clean gasoline, and other factors. They
further note that BP Amoco has agreed to cut re of North
Slope oil from about 70 percent to 55 percent by divesting 175,000
barrels of daily oil production.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Thursday, BP Amoco said it ``remains ready to
pursue a constructive solution.'' But the company also said it
firmly believed ``the combination would enlarge rather than
adversely affect competition,'' and that it had ``offered, but
failed to get FTC acceptance for, a range of measures designed to
meet the FTC's expressed concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   One proposal that had been offered, the company said, would be
to allocate an additional 210,000 barrels of daily production to
third-party buyers under long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Officials had no comment on Thursday about BP Amoco's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the agency has been lobbied heavily on the
matter. Alaskan officials, including the governor, Tony Knowles,
now favor the deal, following BP Amoco's agreement to divest itself
of part of its daily production and to make other concessions.
Knowles, a Democrat, has been pressing the FTC to approve the
acquisition; otherwise, he has said, further delay will hurt the
Alaskan economy.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including a number of state officials in California
and Oregon, remain concerned that gas prices will rise unless far
more substantial steps are taken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
