<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH REASSURES NEW HAMPSHIRE VOTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Locked in a tight race with John McCain for
the state's first-in-the-nation primary, George W. Bush felt
compelled Thursday to reassure New Hampshire Republicans that he
wasn't taking their votes for granted.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, meanwhile, who has been campaigning virtually nonstop in
New Hampshire, addressed the state Legislature and promised to
shake up Washington by appointing a ``reform czar'' who would be
directed to make federal agencies more responsive to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was met in New Hampshire on Thursday with a front-page
story in the Concord Monitor questioning his commitment to the New
Hampshire primary because of the few days he has spent campaigning
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the people of New Hampshire to understand that I'm in a
fight with a friend,'' Bush told several hundred people at a Rotary
Club luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in a battle for the votes, and I don't want anyone to
think I'm taking anything for granted. I've got a lot of work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bush promised to spend half of January campaigning
in New Hampshire. But the first week of January he spent two days
in New Hampshire; this week and next, he will spend only one full
day.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Thursday that Bush plans 10 more
days in the state, including the week between the Iowa caucuses
Jan. 24 and the new Hampshire primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show a neck-and-neck race between the Texas governor and
McCain, a senator from Arizona, who has staked almost his entire
campaign on a New Hampshire victory.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would appoint a reform czar who would be a
Cabinet-level official similar to the drug czar, who now
coordinates drug policy among federal agencies. McCain said the
goal of the new office would be to ``coordinate, emphasize, kick
ass'' in the federal bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, reform of our public institutions to restore the
public confidence of the people we are sworn to serve will be my
first priority,'' McCain told the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   McCain attributed the problems of local lawmakers to the
wasteful spending of Congress, which he said budgeted money for
projects sought by special interests rather than the needs of
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the victims of pork barrel politics of Washington and
it must stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, speaking to reporters while standing in a snowstorm,
suggested his executive experience in Texas better equipped him for
the White House than did McCain's legislative experience in
Washington as an Arizona senator. And Bush again contrasted the
candidates' tax-cut plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believed the ``two deciding issues'' for New
Hampshire voters would be his and McCain's experience and ``whether
they want to spend more money (on government programs) or send it
back to the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed a $483 billion, five-year tax cut and McCain,
a $237 billion, five-year plan. Bush contends McCain's proposal
would leave too much money in Washington for Congress to spend on
unneeded programs. McCain counters that Bush spends too much of the
surplus when the government needs to reduce its debt and shore up
Social Security for the baby-boomers' retirement.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also addressed federal spending in previewing his
education plan, which he will unveil next week. He said it differed
with Bush's in that his does not cut off federal funding to
poor-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because they (schools) got an F doesn't mean they deserve
to lose their funds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also sought to associate McCain with Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic presidential front-runner, on the tax issue.
Bush said that when he laid out his tax plan ``two voices _ Al Gore
and John McCain _ said it didn't leave enough money in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush answered several questions from audiences at all three New
Hampshire stops.
</P>
<P>
   In Laconia, one plant worker asked the governor how he would
distinguish his presidency from that of his father, former
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've got half my mother in me,'' Bush quipped. But he
dodged a direct answer to the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll let history judge, if I become the president, between
the differences between he and me,'' he said. ``I can't tell you
how proud I am of him. It's a fair question, but I would give you
such an unfair answer, because I'm so subjective.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
