<HEADLINE>
SLIGHT GAIN FOR FORBES IN IOWA; RETURN OF AN IMAGE WITH GEORGE W.
BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass . , Iowa, N . H . )  (dal) 
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   OPINION SURVEYS: SLIGHT GAIN FOR FORBES IN IOWA
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's lead over Steve Forbes, his nearest
competitor in Iowa, has narrowed, but remains commanding among
likely Republican caucus-goers, a new poll shows. The survey,
conducted for a group of Midwestern television stations, put Bush
at 46.3 percent and Forbes at 17.3 percent. That margin is 6 points
less than the previous poll taken for the stations, in November.
The poll of 300 likely Republican caucus voters, taken on Monday by
PSI research of Alexandria, Va., has a margin of sampling error of
6 percentage points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN FILES
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: RETURN OF AN IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Until now, something essential had been missing from the
campaign in New Hampshire: snow. But starting on Thursday morning,
there was a steady snowfall throughout the state, and by the time
lunch was over, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was able to hold his
first wintry news conference. It wasn't much, but for the first
time in this race there was the familiar image from campaigns past
of a front-runner in the flakes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULE:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY Campaigning in Johnston and Des Moines, Iowa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Campaigning in Red Oak, Glenwood and Des Moines,
Iowa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STEVE FORBES Campaigning in Oskaloosa and Pella, Iowa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Campaigning in Concord, Manchester and Salem, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN Campaigning in Hopkinton and Manchester, N.H. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
