<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-IOWA-OUTLOOK-(TRIMS)-     01-13 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-OUTLOOK-(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BOTH FRONT-RUNNERS AND POTENTIAL SPOILERS, IOWA COULD BE
CRUCIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERRY, Iowa _ Over the years, the Iowa caucuses have made some
presidential candidates (like Jimmy Carter in 1976) and unmade
others (like Steve Forbes in 1996). But this time, they have seemed
like a warm-up bout compared with the ballyhooed main event in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   That may be changing. With only 10 days left until Jan. 24, when
tens of thousands of Iowans will assemble in living rooms, clubs
and school halls to declare their preferences, two well-funded,
well-organized underdogs _ Forbes and Bill Bradley _ have
accelerated their efforts. If not to defeat their respective
rivals, Al Gore and George W. Bush, they hope to come close enough
to get a lift as they move to New Hampshire, whose critical primary
takes place only eight days later on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Their task is difficult, not only because many potential caucus
participants, in small towns like Perry as well as cities like Des
Moines, find no great differences among the various candidates on
major issues, but also because most Iowans have shared in the
national prosperity of recent years. Insurgents struggle when times
are good, and Iowa has staged its big upsets in years when jobs
were scarce or the parties were split on ideological lines.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowans often make up their minds at the last minute, and
polls suggest that they have not made their final caucus decisions
yet.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is Muzak to a lot of people,'' said David Yepsen, the
chief political reporter for the Des Moines Register. ``They don't
pay attention until they have to, and that's getting later and
later. In the governor's race last year, Tom Vilsack came from 25
points behind in the last three weeks to win by five points.''
</P>
<P>
   In this year's Democratic contest, Bradley, a former senator
from New Jersey, has decided to devote all or part of every day
until the caucuses to campaigning in Iowa. A certain languor still
marks his personal style, and he still tries to cast himself as a
different kind of politician, who accentuates the positive. One day
this week, he bent his 6-foot, 5-inch frame around a lectern and
chatted for half an hour with schoolchildren about health.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's words in other contexts have taken on an edge,
whether he is accusing Gore of neglecting the interests of Iowa
farmers, many of whom have been left behind in the Clinton-era
boom, or attacking him as a reliable friend of the big tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The latest Iowa poll, taken by the Des Moines Register and
published last Saturday, showed Gore 21 percentage points ahead of
Bradley, about the same margin found in a survey taken last
November. But many of the state's most experienced politicians
think the contest is a good deal closer than that.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the delegates elected this month will
probably be undecided. If the remaining 90 percent are split 60-30
between Gore and Bradley, in that order, the former senator will be
severely hurt. But if Bradley could get 40 percent or better, said
Democratic state chairman Rob Tully, ``that would send him off to
New Hampshire with some momentum, and he'd be able to say that half
the Iowa Democrats had rejected a sitting vice president of their
own party.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular Gov. Thomas Vilsack, a Democrat who has taken no
stance in the Bradley-Gore fight, said that younger voters, many of
whom have never before taken part in the caucuses, are drawn to
Bradley. Across the state, he added, Gore supporters, including the
governor's own wife, Christie, are feeling the heat.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Gore is going to stop at our house in Mt. Pleasant for an
event my wife is hosting next week,'' Vilsack said. ``The fact that
Tipper feels that she has to do that, when Christie is already out
there working for the vice president, shows the kind of deep
inroads Bradley is making.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Vilsack expect an upset? ``Not if you define an upset as
winning,'' he replied. ``I don't think so. The party leadership and
the traditional caucus-goers are too committed to the vice
president. They'll turn out no matter what _ snow or rain, no
matter what the weather is.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As always, the weather will count. Only the most committed
venture out on frosty midwinter nights, and even fewer if it snows
or sleets. The effect is much more substantial than it might be in
a primary, when voters cast their ballots in daylight hours,
usually much closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Gifford, a longtime labor activist in Iowa who is closely
identified with Democratic politics, is backing Gore this year. But
he worries about elderly voters, many of them Gore supporters, in a
state with the nation's third oldest electorate, average age 51.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore needs the seniors to turn up on caucus night,'' Gifford
said. ``If there's an ice storm and they don't come out, and
Bradley's youngsters do, you could get a swing of 15 to 20 percent,
which is a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who is saturating television with an estimated $800,000
in commercials, has moved a cadre of young organizers into Iowa,
many of them trained at Participation 2000, a campaign school at
which Bradley has lectured. But Gore is not likely to be
out-organized, not with the United Auto Workers and the National
Education Association in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley has a solid enough organization to guarantee a
good turnout in places like Dubuque and Cedar Rapids, say
Democratic pros, Gore has capable teams in place almost everywhere.
And Gore volunteers in a Waterloo boiler room made more than 30,000
telephone calls statewide just in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Iowans will respond is a matter of disagreement.
Politicians say that barring really foul weather, they expect the
usual turnout, about 100,000 in each party. But Professor Hugh
Winebrenner of Drake University, a caucus historian, said he
expected a smaller participation, perhaps 80,000 for the Democrats
and 85,000 for the Republicans, largely because ``neither a
candidate or an issue has caught fire.'' Not that the candidates
have not tried; Republican candidates, by his count, have spent a
total of 558 days in Iowa since January 1997, and Democratic
candidates have spent 149.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican figure is a record, Winebrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Travel around the state, and voter enthusiasm seems muted, to
say the least. Here in Perry, a trim little town of 7,300, set amid
the deep black soil of rich farmlands, only 3 of 12 people
interviewed at random said they planned to attend the caucuses this
year, and only one piece of political advertising was evident _ a
big ``George W. Bush'' placard at a crossroads south of town.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Hotel Pattee, a magnificently restored Arts and
Crafts gem, one farmer said, ``I've pretty much lost faith in
politics.'' Another said, ``I'll go, I guess, because I always
have, since I was 21, but I don't think it'll change much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the candidates think they're important,'' said Colette
Wortman, 62, a payroll supervisor at a Des Moines insurance company
who does not plan to attend a caucus. ``They are here to get a
vote, and they don't care about you after you vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Camille Wanna, 31, a stockbroker, said he detected ``a lot of
apathy,'' largely because most people think the outcome ``is going
to be a slam dunk for Bush and Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting at Coe College on Wednesday, Craig Wood, a student,
told Gore, ``I'm concerned about your ability to win.'' But few
potential participants said their preferences would be affected by
national polls showing Bradley with a better chance than Gore to
defeat the Republican nominee. Stan Gore, 44, a systems analyst
with the Principal Financial Group, said he planned to vote for
Gore at a caucus, even though he thought the vice president might
well lose to Bush in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the face of things, Bush seems to have little to fear from
Forbes in Iowa, and his main rival in New Hampshire, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, is skipping Iowa _a tactic that has often
backfired in the past. Forbes trails badly in all the polls. Kayne
Robinson, the Republican state chairman, said that ``if someone is
going to make a run at Bush, the time is now, starting with the
next television debate on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   After a monthlong absence, Forbes returned to the state Tuesday,
and he started an extensive bus tour Thursday. Announcing that
``we're here for the next two weeks,'' he launched a new television
onslaught with a graphic commercial focusing on abortion. It
includes an ultrasound image of a fetus and a woman saying, ``If
someone kills a pet, it's called a crime. If someone aborts a
child, it's called a choice.'' Forbes is relying heavily on
television; he outspent Bush last year by 3-to-2.
</P>
<P>
   But neither he nor the other Republican candidates _ Sen. Orrin
Hatch of Utah, Alan Keyes and Gary Bauer _ has been able to deny
Bush the support of some of the leaders of the state's powerful
anti-abortion forces. Ione Dilley and Paul Carbone, two influential
figures, have sided with Bush, although others have thrown their
support elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the candidates are more or less acceptable to
mainstream Republicans here,'' Robinson said. ``There's no clear
differentiation of philosophy, less than ever before. So people ask
themselves, `Which Republican is most likely to stand up there next
January and take the oath of office?' Most think George Bush is the
answer to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' not-so-secret weapon is his organization, which
Winebrenner called ``one of the best I've ever seen.'' His aides
are also playing the expectations game, suggesting that Bush needs
to get at least half the vote to be considered a winner _ no easy
target, of course, with so many candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa results can take odd bounces. In 1984, former Vice
President Walter Mondale took half the vote, but headlines went to
Gary Hart, whose 16 percent was described as a significant
``victory'' for him.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, a strong Forbes showingin Iowa might not help him so
much in New Hampshire, but softening up Bush might ultimately
benefit McCain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
