<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT14-COX     01-13 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gates announces new CEO at Microsoft
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The handwriting was on the wall, but it took the
passing of the CEO torch from Bill Gates to Steve Ballmer on
Thursday to bring it into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, in particular, has been hinting for months that such a
shake-up was in the works and that the impetus for it would be
Microsoft's push away from the desktop and into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' stepping away from the day-to-day management of the
company and into a role as ``chief software architect'' is aimed at
just that _ creating more and better software that will put the
Internet into the hands of everyman.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Ballmer was the keynote speaker to a packed house
at the giant telecommunications conference SuperComm at the Georgia
World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   He told the telecom executives that the key to
telecommunications in the 21st century would eventually lie in
software provided by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   What was so fascinating about that speech is that it was so
eerily similar to the pitch Ballmer and Gates made to IBM in the
1980s. They told IBM that while Big Blue may have the hardware to
put a computer on every desktop, without software _ software from
Microsoft _ the desktop PC would be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer told the telecommunications mavens that they may have
the dial tone and the infrastructure, but what they don't have are
the tools to make the Internet a rewarding experience for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, he said, was the key to solving the problems of the
telecommunications industry as it worked to bring broadband (high
speed) communications to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are convinced the nature of what we do is more influenced
by broadband than anything else going,'' he said. ``We just want to
see these services deployed. I'm very focused and serious about the
need for speed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, there was a good deal of speculation that Microsoft
would sell its Internet arm, Microsoft Network. In fact, Atlanta's
Charles Brewer, CEO of MindSpring, had tossed out the comment that
he'd like to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution that the company
had no intention of selling MSN, and that, in fact, there were
plans for extensive growth.
</P>
<P>
   In other interviews during the ensuing months, Ballmer stressed
over and over how the Internet was the key to Microsoft's future
and that parts of the company needed to be changed to accommodate
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to do my best to see that the company is successful,
and there are parts of our business that need to be shifted and
reinvented,'' he told the Irish Times while on a European tour last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we've done this year is talked about the
reinvention of the company around the new vision.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked where the company should go next, he said, ``This
next generation Web platform is just a huge opportunity. Think of
Windows as just a part of it. Think of it as a new thing called
i-Windows _ it's a client and it's a server, and it's a set of
services that live out on the Internet. It's a building block.
That's what we're known for.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's news conference, Ballmer and Gates made their
roles clear, and, in many ways, they haven't changed at all.
Ballmer will be the salesman, Gates the engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been chatting with Steve and the board with (the idea of)
getting myself focused on products for a couple of years,'' said
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The switch comes after Ballmer has been effectively running the
company for several years (he became president officially in 1998).
</P>
<P>
   ``Their change in strategy was already under way prior to the
change at the top,'' Summit Strategies analyst Dwight Davis told
C/Net, a Web site that covers technology news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is changing around Microsoft. (People are moving
toward) hosted applications and away from deploying software on
local machines. Microsoft has struggled with this internally for
more than a year, knowing this transition is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
