<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Jan. 14. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Developments in the long-running
debate on the prices paid for prescription drugs by Medicare
recipients. By Robert Pear. (We plan to move the story by 9:15 p.m.
ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center:
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo reefer to BUSH-FATHER; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIMISSILE-TEST (Undated) _ Critics say a recent test of a
defense system was not as successful as originally portrayed. By
James Glanz. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLD-BLACKHOLES (Atlanta) _ In a discovery that could help
explain the origin of the earliest galaxies, a new astronomy
satellite has detected the first discret objects in a mysterious
glow of X-rays that pervades the distant universe. By John Noble
Wilford. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MICH-BOY-SENTENCED (Pontiac, Mich.) _ In an unexpected verdict,
a state judge rules that the youngest American ever charged and
convicted as an adult of murder will serve a seven-year sentence at
a maximum-security juvenile detention center and then be released.
The judge rebuked a system that he said had gone too far in
punishing juveniles. By Keith Bradsher. (The story has moved in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Argun) _ The Russian military insists it has
taken back this Chechen town. But Russian soldiers nervously
scanned the rooftops and windows of Argun's battered buildings as
they sought to keep order. Set in the Chechen lowlands, Argun was
taken by the Russian military in early December. Today, however, it
has become a salient example of how hard it may be for Russia to
take Chechnya and keep it. All across Chechnya, Russian troops
tried to tighten their grip over the swath of territory
``liberated'' by Russian forces. By Michael R. Gordon. (The story
has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SAHARA-VILLAGE (Araouane, Mali) _ The sand woman came out of the
blackness of the village master's house into the desert light,
bearing a bowl of sand her hands had scooped from the doorway and
would deposit several feet away. It is a lifetime's work, this
struggle against the sand, for Souda Cissey and Araouane's other
sand women, a daily contest to prevent the Sahara from burying,
once and for all, this ancient village in West Africa. The world's
largest desert has already taken away a mosque and countless houses
in recent years, the rooftops of some still visible on the sand's
surface, others fallen into the Sahara's bottomless pits. By
Norimitsu Onishi. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,600
words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DRUGS-SCRIPTS (Undated) _ The White House drug office has
secretly been pushing TV networks for scripts with anti-drug
messages, and for at least a year has been helping edit the scripts
on selected shows. The White House provided millions of dollars of
financial incentives to networks to make sure the scripts were on
message. By Marc Lacey and Bill Carter. (Scheduled to move by 9:30
p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   HARRODS-PHILIP (London) _ Buckingham Palace announces it is
withdrawing the royal warrant awarded by Prince Philip, the Duke of
Edinburgh, to Harrods, the London department store that is owned by
Mohamed Al Fayed. By Warren Hoge. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EPA-KOCH-WATER (Washington) _ Koch Industries, an oil pipeline
company, found the weak points in its pipes the easy way, the
government says. It simply waited for the pipelines to break and
spill oil, part of a pattern of negligence that resulted in the
biggest civil fine ever paid for a company for environmental
violations. By Matthew L. Wald. (The story has moved in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-MINORITIES (Undated) _ For the first time, the
proportion of AIDS cases among black and Hispanic gay men exceeds
those among white gay men, federal health officials report. By
Lawrence K. Altman. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
