<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDING LIKE A FATHER, GEORGE BUSH GIVES HIS SON A PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.H.)  (dal) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush put out a call for Dad on
Thursday. And Dad, the former president, came running, telling Iowa
voters that they should vote for his son in the Jan. 24 Republican
presidential caucuses because he was tough enough and experienced
enough to occupy the White House and would ``serve with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be excellent at doing what I tried to do,'' President
Bush said, sounding more like a father than a political promoter.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush's appearance here in the packed high school
auditorium of this southwest Iowa farm town was his first genuine
stump performance for his son, though previously he had appeared a
some fund-raisers, many closed to the public. But it was not an
appearance suddenly scheduled because George W. is in any serious
political trouble in Iowa, scene of the nation's first caucuses. He
is not.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it was an appearance that seemed intended to boost the
governor's lead in Iowa over his nearest caucus contender, the
publisher Steve Forbes. The better he does in Iowa, his campaign
hopes, the bigger will be his ``bounce'' as he heads for New
Hampshire, where the nation's first primary will be held on Feb. 1
and where several polls show him trailing Sen. John McCain of
Arizona. McCain is not participating in the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people who are undecided will take at look at my son,''
the elder Bush said in 30 minutes of off-the-cuff remarks in which
he mixed self-deprecatory humor about his own campaign triumphs and
travails with dead-serious pleas for support for his son.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that at least 10 percent of all likely Republican
voters have not yet made up their minds about whom to vote for. Of
those who say they favor Bush, about half also say they might be
persuaded to vote for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   But about three-fourths of those who say they are inclined to
vote for Forbes say they might be persuaded to vote for someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush had mixed results himself back in the days when
he was competing for votes in Iowa, placing first in the 1980
caucuses but later getting ``dusted'' in New Hampshire, as he put
it Thursday. Eight years later, he stumbled and finished third in
Iowa, yet managed to recover in other contests and went on to win
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   So how much his appearance here this afternoon, along with a
second stop in Des Moines, helped his son is but a guess. But a
number of national polls have indicated that George W.'s high poll
numbers can be accounted for, in part, by the fact that he carries
the Bush name. In any event, Bush campaign officials say the former
president's trip to Iowa to stump would be followed by other visits
to other states.
</P>
<P>
   Further, they said that the governor's mother, Barbara, who has
been out on the stump for some time, would continue her travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's working her heart out for our son,'' the former
president told his audience of 600 or so school children,
townspeople and local farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again he made the point in his 30-minute talk that
during much of his time as vice president and president, his son
had been at his side, helping and observing. In the years since, he
went on, he has served as governor of a state that has an economy
larger than that of most countries and where ``they don't play
softball in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows this stuff,'' the elder Bush said, in a seeming
effort to allay any fears that his son might not have enough
experience to serve as president. ``He knows what the stakes are,''
he went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at my side during a lot. I think he would be excellent
at it. He will serve with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president said at the start of his remarks _ ``These
are remarks, because I don't give speeches anymore,'' he insisted _
that he would have ``nothing bad to say against any of the people
that George is campaigning against right now.'' Nor, he added,
would he offer any ``sour grapes'' or ``bad loser'' comments about
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, he stuck by his word, though toward the end
he made some oblique remarks that came close to touching on the
Lewinsky scandal, saying at one point as he called for new national
leadership:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what I want: I want to see us return to a society with
fundamental values.'' Then, edging in a little closer, he joked
that the Jenny Craig diet company had recently called to ask him
whether he was interested in trying to lose 30 pounds _ an obvious
reference to Monica Lewinsky, who has signed on as a company
representative.
</P>
<P>
   He closed on a family values note, saying that his parents had
taught him to ``be kind, be honest and give somebody else the
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from them about fundamental values,'' he
added, ``and I would hope my son has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2101EST &QL; 
