<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5522 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ANTIMISSILE-TEST-ART-     01-13 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIMISSILE-TEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS OF MISSILE INTERCEPTOR TEST IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A critical test of an interceptor designed to destroy ballistic
warheads, hailed as a success when it took place last Oct. 2, may
not have been such a clear-cut demonstration that antimissile
technology is feasible, critics of the effort say.
</P>
<P>
   The interceptor, a 120-pound ``kill vehicle'' launched on a
rocket and maneuvered with thrusters, is meant to home in on and
destroy missiles carrying nuclear or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In the test, the interceptor did hit a mock warhead _ proof,
according to its backers in the Defense Department, that the idea
is workable. But in recent interviews, Pentagon officials conceded
that the interceptor hit its target only after a series of
technical mistakes caused it to drift off course, and that it
initially picked up on a decoy balloon rather than the warhead.
Critics of antimissile systems say these mistakes show that any
such system could easily be fooled.
</P>
<P>
   The decoy was meant to represent the sort of measures that
hostile countries might employ to confuse a national missile
defense. But without the large, bright balloon, which in this case
happened to be drifting near the smaller and dimmer warhead in the
interceptor's field of view, the test last October may not have
succeeded, these critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says to me is, if that balloon hadn't been there,
then they wouldn't have hit the target,'' said Tom Z. Collina,
director of the Arms Control and International Security Program at
the Union of Concerned Scientists. ``They got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Ballistic Missile Defense Organization at the
Pentagon acknowledged the problems when contacted by a reporter.
But the officials offered an entirely different interpretation of
the sequence of events during the test, maintaining that the
successful interception proved that the system as a whole would
work properly even under adverse circumstances, when not all of its
components were working properly.
</P>
<P>
   If there had not been a balloon, said Keith Englander, director
of system engineering for the Pentagon's missile defense
organization, the interceptor ``would have continued to look in the
space where it had been told to go look for the MRV,'' or medium
re-entry vehicle, the military term for the simulated warhead that
was used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the MRV would have appeared,'' Englander said.
</P>
<P>
   But even within the Pentagon, debate has arisen about how to
interpret the results, according to congressional staff members who
have been briefed by Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear yet whether having the decoy there made the
intercept happen or not,'' said a congressional staff member who
has been briefed by analysts both inside and outside the missile
defense organization at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The new information is likely to raise the stakes for the next
test of the system, scheduled for next week. The Pentagon is
supposed to decide by this summer whether the system is ready for
deployment and present its conclusions to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the previously unannounced details about the test renewed
old questions about the hit-to-kill missile defense program.
Congressional investigators found, years after the fact, that tests
of hit-to-kill systems in 1984 and 1991 had been partly rigged to
make the systems appear more effective than they actually were.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the errors in the last test had not been made public
before, Lt. Col. Rick Lehner, a spokesman for the Ballistic Missile
Defense Organization, said he had not been told about them until he
received a press query.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know about it at all, so obviously it wasn't of much
concern at the program office,'' Lehner said. ``It wasn't like they
said, `Oh, my God, we had a malfunction.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the Oct. 2 test, the mock warhead and decoy were launched
from Vandenburg Air Force Base in California and the interceptor
from Kwajalein Atoll in the Marshall Islands. The interception took
place 140 miles above the central Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But while the test was declared an unqualified success, the kill
vehicle, built under contract by Raytheon, had to overcome two
technical problems to make the interception, Englander said.
</P>
<P>
   First, because an incorrect star map had been loaded into the
vehicle's computer, it could not navigate using the stars once it
had separated from its booster rocket and began using thrusters to
maneuver. Instead, the kill vehicle relied on an on-board, inertial
guidance system, and ``there was some drift error in that,''
Englander said.
</P>
<P>
   That error led to inaccuracies in pointing the heat-seeking, or
infrared, sensors that the vehicle used to locate targets. But even
with the inaccuracies, the vehicle sensed the mylar balloon in the
corner of its field of view. Then, using the balloon as a reference
point, the vehicle continued searching for the smaller and cooler
warhead and eventually found it nearby, in time to home in on it
and destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   The errors ``had no impact on the end result,'' said Lehner, who
called them ``basically meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Englander said the problems had been fixed in preparation for
next week's test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they established in this test is that if they
can see the warhead that they can home with enough precision to hit
it,'' said Theodore Postol, a professor of science, technology and
national security policy at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Postol called that ``a useful demonstration'' but added that it
``has very little to do with a real-world defense.''
</P>
<P>
   In an actual attack, he said, the possible number of decoys
scattered throughout space is unlimited, and the warheads could be
much more difficult to see.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Young, deputy director of the Coalition to Reduce
Nuclear Dangers, an organization that has opposed a quick decision
on the usefulness of a national missile defense, said, ``They can,
as they demonstrated, hit a bullet with a bullet, but the fact is
that doing that reliably is incredibly complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Young added, ``There's no point in trying to deploy something
when the technology is still being developed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
