<HEADER>
A5524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BILL-GATES14-COX     01-13 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILL-GATES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driven Harvard dropout became icon of an industry
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Gates, a onetime computer nerd, was the only
chief executive Microsoft had until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To the world, he was a symbol of American technology. To his
executives, he was a hard-driving boss who preferred high-level
technical discussions to easy banter. Although he began Microsoft
on a shoestring, his is not a rags-to-riches story.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he was the prototype of the new digital generation. He
was born Oct. 28, 1955, to a prominent Seattle family. His father,
William Henry Gates Jr., was a partner in a Seattle law firm and
his mother, Mary, was a regent at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 13 years old, Gates was programming in the
Basic computer language. The gangly and awkward child had turned
pro by 17, selling his first program for $4,200.
</P>
<P>
   He spent a couple of years at Harvard University, but he was an
unexceptional student, preferring all-night poker games and messing
with computers to classes.
</P>
<P>
   When the first affordable small computer came out _ a machine
called the Altair that sold in kit form for $400 _ Gates lost all
interest in school. He had found his true love.
</P>
<P>
   He and Paul Allen _ whom Gates met while a student at Seattle's
exclusive Lakeside preparatory school _ moved to Albuquerque, N.M.,
establishing Microsoft in 1975. While Gates was a too-young,
unlikely looking executive, his competitors soon learned that there
was a deep competitive spirit and even a ruthlessness that could
not be hidden by his squeaky voice, glasses and mop of hair.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Microsoft was assured when Gates bought the rights
to a computer operating system, improved it and then sold it to
International Business Machines Corp. for use with IBM's
then-revolutionary Personal Computer. The name Personal Computer
created the term ``PC,'' and Gates' Microsoft Disk Operating System
became known to almost every computer user as DOS.
</P>
<P>
   The company grew with the PC into the country's largest software
company. Gateshimself became as close as possible to an industry
superstar, eventually eclipsing even Steve Jobs, co-founder of
Apple Computer, as the man most identified with America's dominance
in the digital world.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft made Gates the wealthiest individual in the world,
with a fortune estimated at $85 billion. It also made him into a
man who was a stand-up comedian while serving as a keynote speaker
at industry events but who, in private, guarded his privacy. Within
the industry, he was seen as ruthless with his competitors and his
own executives, pushing his company and its products to dominate
over 90 percent of the personal computing operating system market.
</P>
<P>
   But even his enemies credit Gates and Microsoft as one of the
main reasons America is the acknowledged leader in the software
business. Monetary gain never tempered Gates' competitive drive.
</P>
<P>
   An article published in the December issue of Forbes said,
``Competitors once wistfully looked forward to the day when Gates
had children, in hopes that it would deflect his competitive
spirit. Well? With the arrival of his second child this past
summer, Gates says he's simply more focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates told his Forbes interviewer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very lucky. I don't have to take time to mow the lawn. I
have this great job that I care a lot about, and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates and Microsoft also have been active in philanthropy. He
told Forbes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason for believing that my wealth should be
given back to society _ (and) not, in any substantial percentage,
be passed on to my children _ is that I don't think it would be
good for them. You'd like to have a situation where they really
feel like they really need to get out and work and contribute to
society. I think that's an important element of a fulfilling
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
