<HEADER>
A5525 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-NEWCEO14-CO     01-13 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NEWCEO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longtime lieutenant receives his stars
 &HT;    By Susan Wells
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Other than the timing, nothing about Thursday's news
was a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, Steve Ballmer, 43, has been running
Microsoft day to day, going around the world selling the products
and trying to blunt some of the hard edges his boss, Bill Gates,
displayed during the antitrust trial in Washington and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, the fourth richest man in the world with $28 billion by
The New York Times' reckoning, is a marketer by trade. The big,
affable guy with a shining bald head is a remarkably frank-speaking
executive who last fall rattled the markets by telling a crowd of
business editors that tech stocks, including his own, were largely
overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   He's obviously passionate when he talks about his company but
doesn't take himself so seriously that he can't laugh at some of
the odd positions he finds himself in while defending a company
everyone loves to hate.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by the Irish Times what he thought of a technology
world in which he could cause a 3 percent drop in the Nasdaq with
what he calls a ``throwaway'' comment, he said, ``I think it's a
world in which nobody listens or pays any attention to what I said.
... Obviously, no one agrees with it. Everything's much higher now
than at the time I made my comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer joined Microsoft in 1980 after being lured out of
Procter &AMP; Gamble by Gates, his Harvard classmate. He has been a
close friend of Gates since their student days.
</P>
<P>
   For years he has been the heir apparent to Gates, his golf and
singing partner and the man who calls himself and Ballmer
``interchangeable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ballmer would clearly be Bill's successor,'' John Doerr, a
leading Silicon Valley venture capitalist, told The Seattle Times.
``He's an original.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, despite his easygoing demeanor, is known as an
in-your-face competitor who refuses to compromise on what he sees
as his company's mission``He's the kind of businessman most companies either wish they
had working for them or wish they didn't have to deal with,'' said
a Hewlett Packard executive.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, the son of a Ford executive, grew up near Detroit. He
met Gates at Harvard where the two math wizards connected both
academically and socially. They sang duets at college functions and
have been known since to sing at industry events.
</P>
<P>
   Balmer managed the Harvard football team, edited the literary
magazine and sold ads for the Crimson student newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating magna cum laude and spending some time trying
to break into the movie business, he headed for business school at
Stanford. He was lured away after a year by Gates.
</P>
<P>
   He has been Gates' most trusted lieutenant since joining the
company. He oversaw the development of Windows and brokered the
sometimes tense relationship of Microsoft with IBM.
</P>
<P>
   He became Microsoft's third billionaire, behind Gates and
co-founder Paul Allen, in 1993. He claims he still owns 90 percent
of his original stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is,'' Ballmer told analysts some time
ago, ``I love this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
