<HEADER>
A5536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-FLU-DRUG-NYT     01-13 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLU-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA FORCES DRUG MAKER TO KEEP THE FLU IN AD FOR A REMEDY
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Television viewers who have seen the advertisement
for Relenza, a new flu medication, know that it ends with a woman
who has taken the drug sitting in her kitchen while her husband
fixes chicken soup and the flu, personified by an actor, mills
about. What they may not notice is that the ending is a new one:
the Food and Drug Administration forced the drug's manufacturer,
Glaxo Wellcome, to pull an earlier version off the air.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the agency cited the company for false and
misleading advertising. The original advertisement, which ran
nationwide for a little more than a week, ended as the woman
ushered the flu, played by Wayne Knight, the actor who was the
irritating mailman on the ``Seinfeld'' television series, out the
door.
</P>
<P>
   The difference may seem slight, but agency officials said the
first commercial exaggerated the effectiveness of Relenza, which
does not cure the flu but rather cuts the duration of symptoms to a
little less than six days from seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that the ad as a whole, with the visual images and the
timing, exaggerated the effectiveness of this drug,'' said Tracy
Acker, an official in the division of drug marketing, advertising
and communications at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Acker said agency officials worried that
the original commercial might ``encourage people to use the drug
thinking it's this miracle cure when it has this very marginal
effectiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is not unheard of, the action is highly unusual. Though
the agency sends about 200 letters a year to drug makers
questioning their advertising or promotion, only in a few cases,
Ms. Acker said, does it demand that television advertisements be
altered or removed.
</P>
<P>
   The action was expected to incite a debate over the advertising
of prescription drugs directly to patients, which some experts fear
may encourage patients to demand, and doctors to prescribe,
medicines that may not be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Relenza and another new flu drug, Tamiflu by Hoffman-LaRoche,
have been heavily advertised, and on Wednesday, agency officials
issued a health advisory saying that doctors appeared to be relying
too much on the new drugs. The agency said some patients might have
died because they did not get other, more aggressive, treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the warning had been prompted, in part, by
concerns over heavy television advertising, but they did not say
they had already forced Glaxo Wellcome to pull an ad off the air.
On Tuesday, the agency had posted its violation notice to the
company on its Web site. The notice was dated Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-second advertisement is the centerpiece of Glaxo
Wellcome's national campaign for Relenza, said Julie Dean, a
spokeswoman for the company. She said the original commercial,
produced by the advertising agency Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, began
appearing on Nov. 15 and was withdrawn as quickly as possible after
the FDA's Nov. 23 letter. The new version was first broadcast on
Dec. 4, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that what we put together in the first ad was a
reasonable representation of Relenza's activitthe FDA was
concerned and we addressed that concern,'' Ms. Dean said. ``We
worked with the FDA to make sure that we are sending responsible
and good messages to the consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the ending, the ads are alike, Ms. Dean said. They
begin with Knight, personifying the flu, as he knocks at a woman's
door. He pushes his way inside and within moments, the woman has a
blanket around her shoulders and a thermometer in her mouth. He
muscles his way onto the couch, between her and her husband, and
takes up residence. He awakens her at 2:30 in the morning by
playing the bagpipes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she takes a dose of Relenza, an inhalant, and tries to
throw him out. There the versions diverge. In the original, she
succeeds; in the revision, he is still hanging around, laughing at
the thought that chicken soup could help the patient.
</P>
<P>
   About 300,000 prescriptions for Relenza have been written since
it came on the market last fall, and hundreds of thousands have
been written for Tamiflu. With the flu season in full swing, there
have been a number of news reports about the illness, although some
experts have wondered if the advertising about the new drugs, as
opposed to the flu outbreak itself, is driving the media attention.
</P>
<P>
   Such advertising has been proliferating since August 1997, when
the agency relaxed its restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Woosley, chairman of the pharmacology department at
Georgetown University, questions the benefit to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got serious concerns,'' he said. ``The advertising may
attempt to get information out to patients. That's very important,
and that's the goal. It wasn't the goal of advertising to let them
hype the drugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-GREENSPAN-NYT &LR;      01-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN LEANS TOWARD RAISING INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman,
warned Thursday night that there were limits to how long the
economy could continue barreling along without igniting inflation,
and appeared to confirm the assumption on Wall Street that the
central bank will raise interest rates next month.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the New York Hilton that investors hoped would
provide some guidance about how aggressively the Fed would act to
tamp down inflationary pressures this year, Greenspan stressed that
not even the sweeping transformation wrought by technology has
freed the economy from the laws of supply and demand, and in his
veiled way he left little doubt that he is leaning toward tighter
monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also emphasized that the process of reining in the
economy through higher interest rates is already ``well advanced,''
a phrase that will no doubt reduce fears in the markets that the
Fed is committed to a series of rate increases this year.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing current economic conditions, his focus, as it has
been for months, was on the possibility that the country could run
short of workers, pushing up wages and then prices in an
inflationary spiral that could derail the long expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by the stock market boom, demand for goods and services
is outstripping supply in the domestic economy, said Greenspan, who
was nominated earlier this month by President Clinton to a fourth
term as Fed chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is this imbalance between growth of supply and growth of
demand that contains the seeds of rising inflationary and financial
pressures that could undermine the current expansion,'' Greenspan
said in an address to the Economic Club of New York.
</P>
<P>
   So far there is little evidence that inflation is taking root. A
government report on Thursday, for example, showed that prices on
the producer level remained well contained. But another set of
statistics on Thursday showed that retail sales last month were
stronger than expected, further evidence that the economy roared
into the new year at a speed that most economists, especially those
at the Fed, think is unsustainable over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and many economists now assume the Fed will raise its
short-term federal funds target rate by at least a quarter of a
percentage point at its next policy meeting on Feb. 1 and 2. The
Fed raised the rate three times last year in quarter-point
increments, to 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The economy has responded to the strains on it so far, Greenspan
said, by importing more goods from abroad, luring workers from
other countries, and most of all by digging ever deeper into the
pool of available labor in the United States, where the
unemployment rate has been 4.1 percent for the last three months, a
30-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line, however, is that while immigration and
imports can significantly cushion the consequences of the wealth
effect and its draining of the pool of unemployed workers for a
while, there are limits,'' Greenspan said. ``Admittedly, we are
groping to infer where those limits may be. But that there are
limits cannot be open to question.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also used the speech to call for fiscal discipline on
the part of Congress and the Clinton administration as they prepare
to battle again over how to use the growing federal budget surplus.
And while acknowledging that globalization and technology have hurt
some workers, he defended free trade and unfettered competition as
powerful forces for improving standards of living.
</P>
<P>
   But much of his speech was a long rumination on the degree to
which technology-driven changes have fundamentally altered the
economy. The answer, he said, might be much clearer in another
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may conceivably conclude from that vantage point that, at
the turn of the millennium, the American economy was experiencing a
once-in-a-century acceleration of innovation, which propelled
forward productivity, output, corporate profits and stock prices at
a pace not seen in generations, if ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alternatively, that 2010 retrospective might well conclude
that a good deal of what we are currently experiencing was just one
of the many euphoric speculative bubbles that have dotted human
history,'' Greenspan said. ``And of course we cannot rule out that
we may look back and conclude that elements from both scenarios
have been in play in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while Greenspan clearly marveled in his address at the
power of technology to make business more efficient and the economy
more productive, he was careful to bring the discussion repeatedly
back to the issue of limits, a word he used repeatedly. He said the
Fed did not have the luxury of awaiting the outcome of the debate
over the new economy before deciding whether to act now to rein in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his longstanding skepticism of the value of the
traditional models that seek to predict how inflation will pick up
as unemployment falls in a fast-growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that ``there has to be a limit to how far the pool
of available labor can be drawn down'' before wage gains begin to
outstrip increases in productivity, or output per worker per hour.
Once wages start rising faster than productivity, companies face a
choice between raising prices, which would be inflationary, or
accepting narrower profit margins, which Greenspan said would be a
recipe for recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, if our objective of maximum sustainable growth is to be
achieved, the pool of available workers cannot shrink
indefinitely,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan said tighter financial conditions were already
trickling down through the economy. He noted that interest rates on
corporate debt had risen by a full percentage point since late
1997. The rise in rates, he said, was ``supported by a central bank
intent on defusing the imbalances that would undermine the
expansion.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
