<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5539 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PIAF-IMITATOR-ART-$AD     01-13 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIAF-IMITATOR-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ATTEMPT TO RECAPTURE THE ELUSIVE PIAF MYSTIQUE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Barry Singer's most recent article for The New York Times was about
new musicals and how they get recorded.  
 By BARRY SINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where singers are concerned, imitation is often the insincerest
form of flattery. Imitating the sound of someone else's voice is
never solely an act of homage, however inspired by admiration.
Rather, it is a kind of cannibalization, with one singer feeding on
a more singular existing voice and saying: ``Hey, I can do that.
But this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the greatest vocalists started out imitating somebody.
Sinatra had Bing Crosby; Dylan, Woody Guthrie. Billie Holiday
readily acknowledged both Bessie Smith and Louis Armstrong as
models: Smith for her ``big sound,'' Armstrong for his feeling. Yet
how quickly did these artists transmute their influences into
something wholly original.
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Bitton, 38, a cabaret singer from San Francisco, is, to
put it mildly, stuck on Edith Piaf. Since discovering the repertory
of Piaf in 1982, Ms. Bitton, who was herself born in Marrakesh,
Morocco, has helped produce a show about the legendary French
chanteuse for National Public Radio, consulted on a television
documentary, composed a play with music about Piaf's friendship
with Jean Cocteau, written the scenario for a full-length Piaf
ballet and, most decisively, learned to sing very much like her
idol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raquel Bitton Sings Edith Piaf (The Golden Album)'' (Sparrow
Productions RB4271-2), Ms. Bitton's new CD, is an eerie study in
the outer limits of vocal impressionism. There is the exacting
verisimilitude with which Ms. Bitton (abetted by her elegant
arranger, Bob Holloway) recreates the orchestral environment that
contributed so much to Piaf's mystique: brusque horn- and
string-driven orchestrations, lush and spiny all at once, a velvet
grip that could break a listener in two.
</P>
<P>
   There is the unmistakable passion Ms. Bitton brings to her
invocation of the Piaf vocal spirit, the requisite fierceness of
elocution, fluttery intensity of vibrato and Rs rolled like a
flotilla of drunken sailors along a seaside quay. There is also,
inescapably, more than a touch of ghoulishness about the precision
of this Piaf reanimation. In meticulously reflecting the glow of
Piaf's fire, Ms. Bitton buries most of the ``Little Sparrow's''
incandescence _ her utter emotional nakedness.
</P>
<P>
   Well, how could anyone recapture that? The quality that made
Piaf's singing Piaf was ... well, Piaf. The qualities that make Ms.
Bitton the singer are difficult to define beyond the influences of
Piaf, which is in no way to diminish her accomplishment here but
only to wonder at it.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, the differences are the most revealing. Where
Piaf's voice was, indomitably, a brass instrument, Ms. Bitton's is
more a harder-to-tune reed. Where Piaf slugged out signature tunes
like ``Mon Legionnaire'' at unflinching tempos, Ms. Bitton chooses
a milk-the-emotion pace that adds almost a minute to Piaf's
original recording of that song. Given Piaf's own penchant for
melodrama, that's an awful lot of extra bathos to bathe in.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bitton has recorded three previous CDs. On two of them, ``In
a Jazzy Mood'' and ``I Wish You Love,'' as well as on this one, her
affinity for the music of French popular songwriters of the period
from the 1930s to the 1950s defines her. The spotlight she throws
on these neglected masters _ Paul Misraki, Charles Trenet and Henri
Contet _ is welcome. Though they were a generation of imitators in
their own right, each transcended imitation by re-rendering the
style and substance of the American popular song with a French
spin.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bitton's most adventurous outing is the CD on which she
sounds the least comfortable, ``Changes'' (1996), a
Piaf-goes-to-Nashville take on American country-western tunes
addressed as French chansons. Here, venturing far from her sources,
Ms. Bitton, while much at sea stylistically, reveals more of
herself emotionally, her vocal tone both lighter and more lyrically
exposed, her vibrato less assaultively combative.
</P>
<P>
   We live in imitative musical times, and Ms. Bitton is hardly
alone. Singers like Bobby Caldwell release retro recordings of
vintage Sinatra and Bobby Darin that nearly replicate the
originals. The dominion of hip-hop regards sampling as its power
and glory.
</P>
<P>
   Celine sounds like Streisand, and Mariah like Whitney _ or is it
the other way around? In opera, every new tenor is the next Domingo
or Pavarotti. On Broadway, mimetic musicals like ``Kat and the
Kings,'' ``Swing'' and ``Saturday Night Fever'' are to their
musical sources as minstrelsy once was to African-American musical
expression; grotesque, clownishly imitative diminishments of
doo-wop, big-band jazz and disco, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, these shows offer contemporary audiences a brush with
something predating current MTV sounds. But one wonders what any
listener might take away from these encounters. Can such pallid
imitation illuminate anything at all?
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, there are still exceptions. Harry Connick Jr. and
Diana Krall started out imitating other singers _ he the younger
Sinatra, she Nat Cole. Both, however, have evolved into distinctive
vocal artists. And there is nothing remotely pallid about Ms.
Bitton's Piaf tribute. No doubt it will send a few people out to
buy her CD and many more back to the racks for Piaf's own discs.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be nice, though, if more than a few kept on
listening for a singer with something to say that we haven't
already heard _ and, more important, don't already know?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV16-NY     01-13 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE GOOD TIMES ROLL, EVEN MARXISTS ARE MELLOWING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is remarkable how a booming economy flattens
ideology in this post-cold-war era. The good times in America have
many economists rewriting their views, and none more so than those
who see the world through Marxist eyes. Only the final outcome _
the Day of Reckoning _ sets the Marxists clearly apart from
mainstream economics. And the Day of Reckoning has been postponed.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected the current economic expansion, which started in
1991, to last so long. Certainly not the Marxists, who hold that
too much of the national income has gone to corporate profits in
the 1990s and not enough to labor, a painful imbalance that cannot
be sustained indefinitely. Now that view is being edited. A rising
tide that keeps on rising quiets a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the expansion continues another three to five years,'' said
Ismael Hossein-Zadeh, a Marxist economist at Drake University in
Des Moines, ``the trickle-down effect is bound to be seen
increasingly in wages.'' That raises the possibility, he said, that
the workers, instead of protesting, could get ``sucked into'' the
good times.
</P>
<P>
   Few mainstream economists _ or mainstream politicians _ would
disagree. Democratic and Republican economic policies count on this
happening. The Marxists differ mainly in degree. They do not
believe that companies competing for labor in an expanding economy
will raise incomes enough; they want government intervention to
make income distribution more equal.
</P>
<P>
   They mention measures like a higher minimum wage or laws that
strengthen unions, policies that many non-Marxists also favor. But
for the moment, government intervention gets soft-pedaled almost
everywhere in economics.
</P>
<P>
   Having been wrong so often about when the expansion would end,
economists of all stripes are self-consciously covering all the
bases. Plausibility seems to require no less when so many Americans
respond to polls by saying that they see no end to the good times.
So Anthony Gabb, a Marxist economist at St. John's University in
New York City, offers a forecast acceptable today even on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this expansion continues for 5 to 10 years, I would not be
surprised one bit,'' he said. ``But by the same token, if the
economy went into recession soon, I would not be surprised
either.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-running expansion came up often at the annual meetings
here last weekend of the American Economic Association and various
other social science groups. To most of the economists, the
expansion reflects a well-functioning free market and some good
luck. For the Marxists, the expansion is an anomaly requiring
explanations. Their organization, the Union for Radical Political
Economists, offered the only session devoted entirely to ``The U.S.
Expansion and What Comes Next.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream economists see the expansion as a phenomenon that can
continue indefinitely, until some outside shock or policy mistake
provokes a recession. A stock market sell-off could be such a
shock, or a financial crisis that frightens lenders, who then stop
lending; or the Federal Reserve could raise interest rates too far,
or be too slow to lower them in a pinch. The Fed has been blamed
for almost every recession since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Marxists, in contrast, believe that the expansion contains
the seeds of its own undoing. Their latest revisions try to explain
why it is not yet undone. Some skate pretty close to mainstream
economics.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion, in the Marxist view, is a long upward wave that
started in the '80s, when business got the upper hand over labor
and profits rose. Stability, capital investment, new technology,
rising productivity _ all have reinforced profits, the Marxists
explain. And the brief 1990-91 recession did not stop the wave.
These are observations heard from mainstream economists, too.
</P>
<P>
   The New Economy enthusiasts, in particular, are finding kindred
spirits in a strange place. Or as Gabb put it, ``The system is more
resilient than we may want it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the undoing will come in the struggle to consume all the
output. Wages are rising, the Marxists acknowledge, but not fast
enough. So people borrow, helped by the strong stock market, and
credit flows in from abroad. Rising debt loads are part of any
expansion, but this one is getting to the point that people are
borrowing more just to make payments on existing debt. A shock to
this fragile structure would bring it down.
</P>
<P>
   That is farther than most mainstream economists will go. They,
too, worry about debt, but without a Marxist's pessimism. The
mainstreamers generally hold that policy can save the day. The Fed,
for example, can defuse a debt crisis by quickly lowering rates, a
move that would preserve the expansion and reassure workers.
</P>
<P>
   Marxists doubt that it would be so easy. Much of labor's
``passive acceptance,'' said Fred Moseley, a Marxist economist at
Mount Holyoke College, in a recent paper, ``has been based on the
optimistic premise that the years of `pain' will soon be over and
the U.S. economy will soon return to the more prosperous conditions
of the postwar period, with its steady and substantial increases in
real wages.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Continued stagnation, or worse, would invalidate this
premise,'' he said. ``Perhaps then acceptance will turn into
resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But for now, wages are rising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
