<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5542 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-SOPRANOS-REVIEW-SF     01-13 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MOB RULE: `Sopranos' Resumes Its Morality Tale With a Twist  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 (Eds: Review of ``City of Angels'' follows.)  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bada-bing! ``The Sopranos,'' TV's best and most lethal drama, is
back for 13 more episodes of glorious banality on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   The cable sensation picks up right where it left off. New Jersey
mobster Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini) is still in his strange
funk. His wife, Carmela (Emmy winner Edie Falco), is an exquisite
study in deadpan misery. Tony's mother, Livia (Nancy Marchand), is
in the hospital, and his Uncle Junior (Dominic Chianese) is in the
slammer.
</P>
<P>
   And Tony's psychoanalyst, Dr. Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco),
is in a spectacular snit. It's a bad business, treating mafiosi.
One of her patients has committed suicide because Melfi was
distracted by a Mafia incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many more people have to die because of your personal
growth?'' Melfi asks her most dangerous patient.
</P>
<P>
   Aida Turturro (actors John and Nicholas Turturro are her
cousins) joins the cast Sunday as Tony's ne'er-do-well sister,
Janice. She's scammed her carpal tunnel syndrome disability to the
max back in Seattle and now has a fishy eye on Livia's health and
personal holdings.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a qualitative change from last season, it's in that
barely discernible lift, that extra iota of confidence, that comes
with flash success.
</P>
<P>
   The popular take on ``The Sopranos'' is that it's a dark comedy
about a crook who's also a family man with a thin streak of
normality. But ``The Sopranos'' is more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Series creator David Chase has trimmed the ornate Mafia
orthodoxy of countless movies and TV shows to working size. These
are Jersey strip-mall mobsters. They're ``The Godfather'' without
grand opera.
</P>
<P>
   But while he's fashioned a perfectly authentic batch of modern
mafiosi, Chase has kept and perhaps even improved upon the Mario
Puzo-Francis Ford Coppola saga's notion of corruptive evil.
</P>
<P>
   That's what is too easy to miss in the appeal of the show's cool
grit. There's a reason Tony can't find his bliss at home; at his
strip-joint hangout, the Bada-Bing Club; or in his psychoanalyst's
office. He's a criminal; his life has rotted from the inside out.
</P>
<P>
   The show's rough language _ there are more f-words in one hour
of ``The Sopranos'' than some of the more sheltered among us will
hear in a lifetime _ is symptomatic of the spiritual emptiness in
the characters' lives.
</P>
<P>
   The f-word as an adjective serves to demean the noun it
modifies. As a nonsexual verb, it demeans the direct object. The
language itself is life-negating, and the negation of life is the
rampant disease corrupting Tony's two families, biological and
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, how better to explain the homicidal
relationship between Tony and his mother? She approved a hit on
Tony last season. He retaliated by contemplating snuffing her in
her hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   So the mother-child bond, that eternal icon of literature and
popular sentiment, is turned on its head. The mother is supposed to
be the wellspring of life, the selfless nurturer. Tony's take on
Livia: ``She's the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, as a new season of ``The Sopranos'' gets under
way, Tony is urged to reconcile with Livia. He won't hear of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's dead to me,'' he says repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   But Tony's real problem is his realization, vague but achingly
persistent, that he's dead to himself. His life is an exercise in
his putative occupation, waste management.
</P>
<P>
   That makes ``The Sopranos'' better than cool; that makes it an
inherently smart morality tale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``City of Angels'' comes with a Steven Bochco pedigree _
his producing partners are Emmy winners Paris Barclay and Nicholas
Wootton _ and seemingly perfect timing.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the networks are being criticized for neglecting
minorities on both sides of the camera, this new hospital drama is
television's great black hope. The show's cast and crew are
predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   The midseason series begins with a deft Bochco touch, the freak
death of an overweight rhythm and blues singer. Guest star Garrett
Morris, as the medical director of Angels of Mercy, a rundown
public hospital in Los Angeles, pays a drunken visit to the famous
corpse.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK now, I know an autograph is out of the question,'' he says
to the bagged body, and then proceeds with a morbid photo op
instead. He's caught; exit Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Vivica A. Fox as his no-nonsense replacement, Dr. Lillian
Price. She's an ``accreditation gunslinger'' who ``single-handedly
saved Oakland Memorial from closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Price inherits a staff that includes her former fiance, Dr. Ben
Turner (co-star Blair Underwood). She also inherits the tawdry side
of public health administration in the person of an overseeing
politician and apparent shoe fetishist, Edwin O'Malley (Robert
Morse).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's episode, written by Bochco and Wootton, turns turgid
the moment Fox appears on the scene. Price is a humorless
character, and Fox is a pretty but flavorless actress. Underwood,
himself a somber presence onscreen, further deadens a dreary hour
of drama.
</P>
<P>
   The word is that ``City of Angels'' perks up and finds some
traction in subsequent episodes, so there is at least a scintilla
of hope for a show that's carrying an immense burden at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants to see a winning black drama on TV, at long last,
and the CBS brass knows it would be impolitic to pull the plug
quickly on ``City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   But I know the succession of feelings I had in watching the
premiere. Succeed, please succeed. And then: End, please end.
</P>
<P>
