<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-LINDROS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lindros learning to live with fame
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More days should be like Wednesday. Eric Lindros
played golf. Lindros and several teammates played at Country Club
of the South, thanks to a connection of theirs named Tom Glavine.
Just golf and sunshine on a day off for the Philadelphia Flyers'
walking headline. No new trade rumors. No conspiracy theories about
auto wrecks. No new battles with the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I'm doing,'' Lindros said. Stories just
grow on him. Lindros and the Flyers make their first visit to
Philips Arena tonight to meet the Thrashers. Philly comes in with a
six-game winning streak and hopes of exorcising memories of a
fizzle-from-ahead 4-4 tie with the Thrashers three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   So much has happened since then. To recap:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lindros almost traded to Carolina! Keith Primeau's agent said
he held contract talks with Flyers general manager Bob Clarke,
thereby giving credence to previous reports that Carolina and
Philadelphia discussed a star swap.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lindros was driving! Actually, he was a passenger and his
girlfriend was driving when his car slid off a New Jersey road
after a New Year's Eve party. That didn't stop somebody from
screaming police cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lindros going to Toronto! A report out of Toronto, birthplace
of mutant hockey rumors, said Lindros will be traded to the Maple
Leafs for Mats Sundin. Lindros said, ``It was a load of (junk) in a
dry news week.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy seemingly has swirled around Lindros since he was
drafted by Quebec in 1991. He wouldn't play for the Nordiques and
forced one of the biggest trades in league history. The Nordiques,
now Colorado, received six players, including Peter Forsberg, two
No. 1 draft picks and $15 million. Since then, Lindros has
attempted to live up to that price.
</P>
<P>
   But on-again, off-again collisions with Clarke and the fact that
he is playing under another one-year contract makes for an
uncertain future _ and wonderful fodder for speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guys who go through it,'' Lindros said
Thursday after the Flyers practiced at Philips Arena. ``Rumors can
be started easily. That's just the way it is. A lot of things that
you hear, there's no backing to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it started a few years ago, it did affect me. Nobody
wants to put their heart into something and then you hear that you
might be traded and _whatever. But there's nothing you can do about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros addressed his teammates in October, after the Flyers
started the season 0-5-1. He told them he had let the off-ice stuff
affect him but that it wasn't going to be the case in the future.
The Flyers are 25-6-5 since.
</P>
<P>
   He has struggled of late. He has scored just one goal in his
past 10 games and missed two others because of a chipped bone in
his left hand. But he said, ``In the past week, it has felt a lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The psyche apparently has healed as well, at least until the
contract rhetoric heats up again after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he does is monitored and blown out of proportion,''
teammate John LeClair said. ``It makes it difficult for him. But
through the years, I think he's (learned) that comes with being a
superstar. He's been real good about being able to focus on hockey.
Trade rumors are just a part of hockey. You can't sit there and
play scared.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers have grown so accustomed to this that they don't
believe it will derail their Stanley Cup hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a problem, but it hasn't been,'' coach Roger
Neilson said. ``Right now, it's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
