<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BELICHICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS AND BELICHICK MEET ON THE LEGAL FIELD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time since Bill Belichick walked out on
Bill Parcells last week, ending their 16-year football
relationship, the two former Jets' coaches met face to face
Thursday at a hearing in the National Football League's legal
offices in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was described by Belichick's defense team as a
``hostile witness'' at the eight-hour hearing, which was called by
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue to determine the validity of
Belichick's contract with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Only three people testified at the law offices of Skadden Arps
on the 38th floor of 4 Times Square _ Parcells, Belichick, and,
surprisingly, Charlie Weis. He is the Jets' offensive coordinator
who was called by Belichick's lawyer, Neil Cornrich.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said in a statement he would rule on the dispute next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick resigned as Jets coach last week, one day after he had
succeeded Parcells. The Jets have contended that Belichick's
contract called for him to take over if Parcells stepped down. But
Belichick, who had three years remaining on his contract, claimed
that the uncertainty about who the new owner would be and Parcells'
role in the front office, made the job impossible to take.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wood Johnson IV agreed to buy the team last Tuesday for
$635 million. That sale is expected to be approved by the league
owners next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells entered the building looking glum. He testified for an
hour, and left, refusing to talk to reporters. He walked north on
Sixth Avenue and then, at the urging of the team's security
director, who saw about 40 reporters and television crew chasing
him, made a quick left turn and disappeared among the noontime
crush of pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Weis followed Parcells at the hearing, testifying for about
three minutes. After Belichick finished his afternoon of testimony,
Jets president Steve Gutman presented the Jets' case.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was the only principal of the hearing who consented to
an interview afterward. ``I appreciate the opportunity to present
our case before the NFL and would hope for a quick resolution,'' he
said. ``That's really all I can say at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   However, another of Belichick's lawyers, Jeffrey Kessler, a
sports antitrust lawyer who has represented the players unions of
major league baseball, football and hockey, said that if Tagliabue
ruled against his client, they would take the case to the federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league cannot stop other teams from making offers to, and
hiring, coaches if they would like someone as their head coach,''
he said
</P>
<P>
   Kessler added, ``If the league does not agree with us, we will
take this further.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether this meant seeking redress in the federal
courts, Kessler said, ``We believe the law is very clear. The
courts would not prohibit someone from making a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, claimed Kessler, his case was bolstered because,
he said, the Jets have said they would not take Belichick back.
Thus, according to the attorney, they are preventing him from
making a living.
</P>
<P>
   Asked last week in a conference call if he could see Belichick
back on the Jets, Parcells, ``I don't think so. There is no
possibility that would happen, I would think.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately thereafter, Parcells is expected to name his new
head coach _ which some people expect might be himself again.
</P>
<P>
   But Belichick had been targeted for that post for three years.
He actually was the Jets' head coach before Parcells during the
tumultuous legal wrangling involving the Patriots. At that point,
the Patriots claimed that Parcells was under contract to them, so
the Jets made Belichick their head coach until Parcells could step
in. Shortly after, the Pats and Jets made a deal for draft picks,
that allowed Parcells to become a Jet. Belichick resumed his
accustomed role of Parcells' defensive coordinator, but his
contract called for him to succeed Parcells one day.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday was not about football. All the principals were
brought together in one room. Tagliabue was there for about an
hour. When he entered the building, he said he hoped ``we can get
this resolved fairly and expeditiously.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Ingraham, a friend of Belichick's going back to their days
at Wesleyan University, and a sports attorney, said that everyone
sat at one table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big and expensive,'' said Ingraham, when asked to
describe the table. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
