A5549 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-CHEER14-CO     01-13 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-CHEER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manning's the man in Tennessee
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is Tennessee still Peyton's Place?
</P>
<P>
   As Tennessee prepares for the biggest pro football game in its
history, the state feels torn loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans, in their second season in Nashville, will
face the Colts and former University of Tennessee quarterback
Peyton Manning in an AFC playoff game Sunday in Indianapolis' RCA
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Do Tennessee football fans cheer for the home team or their most
beloved homeboy?
</P>
<P>
   Manning, preparing for his first NFL playoff game, seems unfazed
by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize the unique situation of it,'' he said, ``but it's an
NFL playoff game. That's how I'm approaching it. I know nobody on
the Titans cares where I went to college. I also know nobody on the
Colts cares where I went to college, either. That's kind of the end
of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   But Manning is still the big story in Tennessee, where he was an
All-America passer with the Vols. Manning endeared himself to
locals by passing up the NFL draft in 1997 to return to school for
his senior season. As the Vols' starter, he had a 39-6 record, led
the school to the 1997 SEC championship and broke 33 school, eight
conference and two NCAA records.
</P>
<P>
   After the Colts drafted Manning No. 1 in the 1998 draft,
Indianapolis sold several season tickets in Tennessee, where the
quarterback has more than one street and dozens of children named
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here think Peyton Manning hung the moon, and that
hasn't changed,'' said Tony Basilio, who hosts a sports-talk show
on WIMZ radio in Knoxville. ``Even though he didn't win a national
championship, he will always be the Tennessee football legend.''
</P>
<P>
   While Manning remains a hero in Tennessee, fans were slow to
accept the Titans after owner Bud Adams moved the former Houston
Oilers there in July 1997. The team spent one season in Memphis and
another in Nashville at Vanderbilt, playing in a half-empty
stadium. During the transition, fans seemed more captivated by
Manning's Heisman Trophy campaign in 1997 and the Vols' national
title the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Adams learned the degree of Manning's popularity when Titans
running back Eddie George admitted in 1997 that he voted for
Michigan's Charles Woodson for the Heisman. ``It wasn't the popular
thing, to be a Tennessee Oiler fan around here,'' George recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It still isn't in Knoxville, where Mayor Victor Ashe said he
would not want to write his ``political obituary'' by choosing
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a former Tennessee governor whose
presidential campaign headquarters is located in Nashville, also
took a diplomatic approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be looking out for the hometown boy, and hoping he has a
great game, but he'll be cheering for the Titans,'' a Gore
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Nashville area, Manning might have more fans than
the Titans do. While Adams envisioned the Titans being Tennessee's
team, the rest of the state largely has ignored them.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Titans sold 80 percent of their single-game
tickets to buyers from Nashville and surrounding Middle Tennessee.
Of the 50,000 preferred-seating leases in the team's new Adelphia
Coliseum, more than 80 percent were sold to those same fans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more of the leases were sold in Kentucky and Alabama
than the 1.8 percent bought in Knoxville, about 180 miles from
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make it seem like it's your obligation to cheer for the
Tennessee Titans,'' WIMZ's Basilio said. ``But that's not the case
at all. They're a Johnny-come-lately. They're the flavor of the
month. ... People here want to see Peyton Manning. People in East
Tennessee despise the Titans. They're really a Nashville team, but
they're trying to capitalize on a statewide name.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans might be the flavor of the month, but they're still
not Big Orange.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Dec. 19, Manning fans implored the Fox television
station in Knoxville to dump the Titans-Falcons game for the
Colts-Redskins matchup. Sentiment was so lopsided _ reportedly 20
to 1 in favor of Manning's team _ that WTNZ-TV general manager Rick
Lipps eventually relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to watch one person over a whole team?''
Lipps said. ``Nothing against Peyton Manning or Indianapolis, but
you know, these are the Tennessee Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   George said, ``The pendulum has changed dramatically this
season.'' The Titans, with the AFC's third-best record at 14-3,
sold out every game at Adelphia and went 9-0 at home. A record
crowd of 66,782 fans watched the Titans beat Buffalo 22-16 last
week in an AFC wild-card game, decided on an improbable kickoff
return with 3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to hate bandwagon jumpers,'' said Titans tight end
Frank Wycheck, who threw the cross-field lateral that started the
return. ``Now, I love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
