<HEADLINE>
CONNER RUNS AFOUL OF SAIL CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, N.Z. _ Had they not used an illegal rudder in race one
of the Louis Vuitton semifinals, Stars &AMP; Stripes could be well on
its way to one of the two berths in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   The team was docked a point by the jury for using a rudder it
had built in Australia, a breach of the nationality clause of the
America's Cup protocol.
</P>
<P>
   But things may be getting worse for Team Dennis Conner, which
began this regatta as a long shot and survived to this point as
seven other syndicates _ many of them better funded and with
two-boat programs were eliminated by the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the Prada syndicate filed a protest against
Stars &AMP; Stripes, claiming the team has been using a high-tech
mainsail whose design it got from Young America, which would be a
violation of the rule that prohibits the 11 challenger syndicates
from sharing technology.
</P>
<P>
   Prada claims the Stars &AMP; Stripes mainsail is ``the product of
the intellectual creativity and judgment of the Young America
design programme.'' It is, they claim, a sail Young America began
making but no longer needed when it failed to make the regatta's
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   But Stars &AMP; Stripes senior afterguard member and rules expert
Tom Whidden said the charge is ridiculous and should not even be
accepted for consideration by the jury. Whidden called the protest
a ``desparate measure'' by a team that is afraid it may lose to
Stars &AMP; Stripes on the water. ``It's just kind of sad they would
stoop to this,'' Whidden said.
</P>
<P>
   But Prada's general manager, Laurent Esquier, denied the Stars &AMP;
Stripes claim that Prada withheld the protest until its own chances
came down to a do-or-die race between the two, scheduled for
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a political move to do this now,'' said Esquier.
``We wanted to avoid a frivolous case, and we would not do this if
we didn't have legs to stand on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes' operations manager, Bill Trenkle, chimed in to
deny the charges. ``The sail was not designed by Young America,''
he said. ``These are desperate people taking desperate measures to
ty and win this off the water.''
</P>
<P>
   If the two do race, a win by Prada would end the whole
controversy. But a Stars &AMP; Stripes win could be subject to the
ruling of an international jury and arbitration panel if Prada's
protest is accepted for deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier case of the illegal rudder, the arbitration panel
found that Stars &AMP; Stripes used a rudder in its opening race
against Japan that it had had manufactured in Australia, though
with materials and a design from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the Conner syndicate guilty meant stripping the team of
the point it had won against Japan. In its defense, Stars &AMP; Stripes
said it had interpreted the rules differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that case, we screwed up,'' said Whidden. ``But in this
case, there's nothing there. This is just harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian syndicate also launched a derisive accusation at
AmericaOne Thursday, claiming skipper Paul Cayard had thrown his
race aginst Stars &AMP; Stripes, allowing the Conner team to stay in
the running. As Cayard came back to his dock after the loss, he
found, lining the Italian dock next door, a dozen or so syndicate
members wearing makeshift Pinocchio noses, fashioned out of paper
cones _ a gesture accusing Cayard of lying about trying to beat
Stars &AMP; Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard said he was upset by the Italian jibes. As skipper of
Italy's Il Moro, winner of the Louis Vuitton Cup in 1992, Cayard
became something of a national hero in Italy, hailed as the
country's adopted son, ``Paulo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will just have to live with what's in my heart,'' he said at
a packed post-race press conference in which he faced many hostile
questions. ``And I know in my heart we tried very hard to win the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the press conference, Bill Koch, who was the
17th man aboard AmericaOne Thursday, took the microphone and made
an emotional speech. Said Koch, once a bitter rival who beat Cayard
for the America's Cup in 1992, ``I've sailed more than 100 races
against Paul Cayard, and there's no way he tried to throw that
race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
