<SLUG> BC-MICH-BOY-SENTENCED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY WHO KILLED GETS 7 YEARS AS JUDGE CRITICIZES LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs grafs 10 and 18 to give victim's full name on first reference
_ Ronnie Greene Jr.; story is now 2 takes)  
(bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ A state judge here ruled Thursday that the
youngest American ever charged and convicted as an adult of murder
will serve a seven-year sentence at a maximum-security juvenile
detention center and then be released. The unexpectedly lenient
sentence stunned prosecutors and disappointed lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland County Circuit Court Judge Eugene Arthur Moore rejected
prosecutors' request that Nathaniel Abraham, 13, who was convicted
of a murder committed when he was 11, be sentenced to serve
additional time in an adult prison unless he has clearly been
rehabilitated by the age of 21. Moore also read from the bench a
ringing denunciation of the national trend over the last decade
toward trying and sentencing younger and younger children as
adults, saying that society has leaned too far toward punishment
instead of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Moore called for changes in the 3-year-old law that makes it
possible for children of any age to be tried as adults in Michigan.
He called the law ``fundamentally flawed'' and suggested that the
state return to its practice before 1997 of reserving such trials
and sentences for children who are at least 14 when they commit
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature has responded to juvenile criminal activity
not by helping to prevent and rehabilitate, but rather by treating
juveniles more like adults,'' Moore said in his sentencing opinion.
``The real solution is to prevent an adult criminal population ever
coming into existence.''
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers across the country have been rewriting juvenile
justice codes in response to some constituents' demands that they
get tough on young offenders accused of terrible crimes. But
critics contend, and Moore agreed Thursday, that the juvenile
justice system has far more success at rehabilitation than the
adult correctional system.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan House Speaker Charles Perricone, a Republican who
helped write the state's strict juvenile justice law, said changes
in the law were unlikely as long as Republicans controlled the
state's House, Senate and the governor's mansion. ``At the end of
the day, someone, and I had hoped it would be the judge, should
stand up and ask one simple question: does this individual present
a danger to society?'' Perricone said in a telephone interview.
``We don't need judges on a soap box. We need judges who will
uphold the law.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Engler opposes revising the law, particularly because
the state's prosecutors and judges endorsed it in 1996, said Susan
Shafer, a spokeswoman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, Moore was the president of the Michigan Probate
Judges Association when the law was adopted, and the association
endorsed the law then. Lisa Halushka, the family division chief in
the Oakland County prosecutor's office who was the lead prosecutor
in Nathaniel's case, said that because of this history, she was
especially stunned and disappointed by Thursday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has left me speechless,'' she said. ``As soon as I got the
impression he would go straight juvenile, I thought: Michigan
Probate Judges Association.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel faces a pretrial hearing next week on a separate
charge of breaking into a garage shortly before the slaying. But he
had never been convicted of a crime before he went out on a
hillside on the evening of Oct. 19, 1997, and used a borrowed,
.22-caliber rifle with its gunstock missing to shoot Ronnie Greene
Jr., who was 18 and a stranger, once in the back of the head at a
range of more than 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Fieger, Nathaniel's lead lawyer, said that if Nathaniel
was guilty of anything, it was reckless use of a firearm. But
prosecutors presented evidence that Nathaniel had prepared for the
slaying by shooting at balloons, and had later boasted about the
killing to friends at his elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Moore has declined all interviews during the trial, and did so
again Thursday. He has handled Nathaniel's case from the beginning,
and granted prosecutors permission to try Nathaniel as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Under Michigan law, Moore had three sentencing options. He could
have sentenced Nathaniel to eight to 25 years in adult prison; time
in a juvenile detention center followed by a second sentencing
hearing between his 18th and 21st birthdays to decide on additional
time in an adult prison if he had not been fully rehabilitated; and
time only in a juvenile detention center. Prosecutors, who have
received some criticism here for harshness, recommended the second
option.
</P>
<P>
   At least 44 states have adopted new juvenile justice laws since
1992 that allow more children to be tried as adults.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In one nationally publicized case, Kip Kinkel was sentenced in
November in Portland, Ore., to more than 111 years in prison
without possibility of parole for having fatally shot his parents
and two fellow high school students when he was 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   There has been only one other case in Oakland County of
prosecutors' recommending a combination of juvenile and adult
crime. Moore also presided in that recent case, which involved a
home invasion by another offender who committed the crime at the
age of 16, Mrs. Halushka said. The offender, who was white,
received a six-month sentence in a county jail after he reached the
age of 18 in a juvenile detention center without showing that he
had been rehabilitated, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger welcomed Moore's decision, but said he would proceed with
his plan to appeal the jury's verdict last November. Nathaniel, who
wore a brown and gray shirt with khaki trousers, was expressionless
during the sentencing, but another of his lawyers, Daniel Bagdade,
said he had his hand on Nathaniel's shoulder and could feel his
client trembling.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, Bagdade said, ``Nate looked up at me and the
first words out of his mouth were, `What happened?''' Nathaniel
will turn 14 next week, but psychologists testified at his trial
that he was mentally and emotionally impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's relatives had varying reactions to the verdict. His
grandmother, Joanne Hayden, reacted calmly when the sentence was
read but a minute later leaned against a wall outside the courtroom
and began weeping while loudly crying, ``Oh, Ronnie, Oh, Ronnie,
Oh, my boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Hayden, the dead man's uncle, said he believed Nathaniel
should have received a combination of a juvenile and adult
sentence. Hayden also said that Michigan's law on young offenders
should remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel is black, as was Greene, and the case here has drawn
national attention from civil rights activists. Fieger and these
activists have contended that Nathaniel would have been treated
differently in this mostly white county if he were also white _ a
contention that Mrs. Halushka rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred protesters showed up for the hearing, with many
of them standing in wind-driven snow outside the courtroom, beating
drums and chanting slogans like ``Nathaniel, we love you.'' One of
the protest's leaders, the Rev. Al Sharpton of New York, said after
the sentencing that while he was pleased that Nathaniel would not
be sent to prison, he still believed that Nathaniel should have
been acquitted and that Michigan's juvenile justice laws should be
rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge said some strong and courageous things _ he
convicted the system but he incarcerated Nathaniel,'' Sharpton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 64, has a national reputation as an experienced and
respected juvenile court judge. He was first elected as a juvenile
court judge in a countywide race in 1966, and has won every
reelection campaign since then, usually running unopposed; his
current, six-year term will not expire until the end of 2004. Moore
succeeded his father, Judge Arthur Eugene Moore, on the juvenile
court bench, and his father's portrait still hangs in the county
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Moore ``leans toward more lenient sentences,'' Mrs. Halushka
said. But in this heavily Republican county on the northern edge of
Detroit, the judge makes occasional appearances at Republican
fund-raisers, she said, while adding that elections for judges are
non-partisan and Moore ``is not super-political.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
