<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY YORK MAKES HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- His spirit was willing. So was his 66-year-old flesh.
Alas, Ray York's horse was weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode fitter than that horse ran,'' he joked after Thursday's
eighth race at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   In what is intended as a brief comeback, York finished
second-to-last a board a gelding named Culebra in the 11-horse
maiden sprint but accomplished his goal, becoming the first jockey
to compete in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it very, very much,'' he said after weighing in, not
visibly winded, his sweaty forehead dotted with racetrack dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke good, and down the backstretch I thought, `I got a
shot here!' ``But when I called on him, nothing. I wish I'd had
more horse, so I could have tried a little more of the horsemanship
I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Close to the lead between horses early, 37-1 Culebra quickly
dropped out of contention, safely on the outside of the pack.
Favored Slew Anew won the race to give jockey Corey Nakatani -- 37
years younger than York - - four victories two days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   For York, who rode 1954 Kentucky Derby champion Determine and
3,081 win winners between 1949 and his first retirement in 1985,
this probably was a one-race stunt, but you'd have to say he earned
the achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The Taft, Calif., native trimmed down to 113 pounds by
exercising horses for Culebra trainer Henry Moreno at Santa Anita
four mornings a week since September.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, York was tied with Bill Shoemaker and two other
riders with the six-decades distinction. He had ridden in 1992 at
Bay Meadows and in Del Mar's Rocking Chair Derby for retired
jockeys later in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno wants York, a grandfather of five, to keep riding until
he wins a race. York's girlfriend, Michael McKay, may veto that
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time he gets home and does chores again,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
