<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOLLYWOOD-AD-COLUMN-N     01-13 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTSING: VENTURE AIMS TO RECREATE HOLLYWOOD-MADISON AVENUE
ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: in references to (c)JWT, the (c) is a nontransmittable
typographical symbol that resembles a c with a circle around it,
similar to a copyright symbol)  
(bl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a significant step toward bringing Madison Avenue
and Hollywood closer together, a giant agency is forming an
alliance with a powerful company specializing in talent management
and television and movie production. The affiliation is intended to
help advertisers exploit the puissant potentials inherent in
entertainment marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is J. Walter Thompson USA in New York, part of the
WPP Group, which works for clients like Ford Motor, Kellogg,
Merrill Lynch, PepsiCo, Philip Morris and Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood powerhouse is Basic Entertainment, which manages
actors like Nicolas Cage, Dana Carvey, Greg Kinnear, Brad Pitt and
Adam Sandler as well as producing cable and broadcast network
programs like ``The Sopranos,'' ``Politically Incorrect'' and
``Just Shoot Me.'' Basic also has film and Internet production
interests and represents authors like Martin Amis, Michael
Cunningham and Elmore Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson USA and Basic are forming a nonequity alliance through
a new agency marketing division, (c)JWT, with the ``(c)'' standing
for content. Basic will be compensated for its work with (c)JWT,
and Thompson USA will share in revenue from projects that reach
fruition; terms of those aspects of the agreement were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Access to and control of content, particularly in the realm of
entertainment, are the driving forces behind the transformations
reshaping the media landscape, as demonstrated by the startling
news this week that America Online would acquire Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enormous potential to figuring out how to have some
effective relationship between advertisers and entertainment, and
ultimately the consumer,'' said Brad Grey, chairman at Basic,
formerly known as Brillstein-Grey Entertainment after Grey, the
deal-maker once called ``the new Michael Ovitz,'' and his mentor,
Bernie Brillstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear to us advertisers are a key part of the
entertainment process,'' Grey said in a telephone interview from
his office in Beverly Hills, Calif. ``The dialogue we've started
will help JWT and its clients get closer to the content, the
creative product we spend our time developing and producing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thompson USA-Basic hookup is meant to extend beyond familiar
tactics like product placement, celebrity endorsements and
licensing by involving advertisers in the earliest stages of
content development. As such, it is perhaps the most ambitious
attempt to date at forging stronger ties between Madison Avenue and
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples include the supervision of advertising for
Coca-Cola by Ovitz when he headed the Creative Artists Agency; the
purchase by Creative Artists of a minority stake in Shepardson
Stern &AMP; Kaminsky, a New York ad shop that works for clients like
Southern Co.; and the acquisitions of PMK, an entertainment
publicity agency, and Addis-Wechsler &AMP; Associates, a talent agency,
by the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 30-second television commercial is not going away, but it
will continue to be less important in the media mix,'' said Bob
Jeffrey, president at the Thompson New York unit of Thompson USA.
``If we are going to maintain our leading position in
communications, we're going to have to come up with more ways to
sell brands other than TV spots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies have played catch-up in the digital space,'' he
added. ``This is an opportunity to take the lead by developing
content offline and online, working with Brad Grey and his people
as a creative think tank to come up with fresh ideas about how to
go after consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the alliance will try to recreate the bonds
between Hollywood and Madison Avenue. From the 1930s through the
1950s, agencies were the traffic cops at the center of the
entertainment-advertising intersection, supervising the creation of
radio and television programs for clients from hiring stars and
writers to negotiating production deals with studios to placing the
series on networks.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was a pioneer of that era, developing the long-running
``Lux Radio Theater,'' ``Kraft Music Hall'' and ``Kraft Television
Theater.'' All that ended when increasing production costs made
single-sponsored shows prohibitively expensive for advertisers, and
the TV networks asserted their authority to develop their own
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when agencies controlled the airwaves and had
a pipeline to Hollywood,'' said Marina Hahn, who joined Thompson
New York in May as executive vice president for strategy and
entertainment from the William Morris Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we're no longer driving a lot of the big ideas that shape
popular culture,'' said Ms. Hahn, who will also head (c)JWT.
``Reopening the dialogue with the best minds in Hollywood is a way
to get back a competitive edge.''
</P>
<P>
   As Basic and (c)JWT begin working on projects for Thompson
clients, executives from both expressed their awareness of concerns
that the alliance could blur the lines between content and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be `This actor better be out there saying good things
about our soap,''' said John Liebman, vice chairman at Basic, whose
friendship with Ms. Hahn was the genesis for the discussions
leading to the formation of the alliance. ``And our idea isn't to
get into the ad business.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey echoed those cautions, saying: ``It's not about bringing
the advertisers into the creative process. It's about making their
dollar a more efficient dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one project is already under way for a Thompson USA
client, Warner-Lambert. It's a comedy-centered idea for a new
product under the Listerine brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the agency proposed this, we immediately leapt at it,''
said Marc Rovner, vice president for oral care and professional
markets at Warner-Lambert Consumer Health Care in Morris Plains,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``People consume media just as much as they consume any
product,'' he added. ``As media fractionate, people pick up
entertainment in places other than television.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Listerine project, ``we've talked with a comedy writer''
provided by Basic ``about a range of ideas like cinema advertising,
Internet `viral marketing,' comic books, even CDs,'' Rovner said.
``It's a real benefit to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But can Basic's brain trust top a poster that Listerine once
distributed on college campuses? If memory serves, the poster
showed a bottle of Listerine precariously perched on a ledge at
Notre Dame in Paris alongside a grotesque statue.
</P>
<P>
   The headline: ``Gargoyle with Listerine.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
