<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LIVER-TRANSPLANTS-BOS     01-13 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVER-TRANSPLANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEONS PERFORM RARE `DOMINO' LIVER TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.J.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paula Pereira had decided against millennial
celebrations and was relaxing at home on New Year's Eve in
Kenilworth, N.J., when her pager went off. It was a call from the
Lahey Clinic in suburban Burlington, notifying her that after a 2
1/2-year wait, a donor liver was available.
</P>
<P>
   As she jumped into her car and headed north on the 4 1/2-hour
drive, Lahey surgeons were scrambling to assemble a large team that
at 8 a.m. on New Year's Day would begin New England's first
``domino'' liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Pereira, 28, who has a rare genetic disease, successfully
received a healthy liver from a brain-dead donor and,
simultaneously, gave up her slightly abnormal liver to be implanted
into an older, extremely sick patient who might have no other shot
at a donor organ.
</P>
<P>
   At her young age, Pereira had yet to develop many symptoms of
the progressive disease, familial amyloidosis, in which a gene
mutation causes the liver to make an abnormal protein. Getting a
new liver forestalled the lethal buildup of protein that had killed
her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its flaw, her liver was safely implanted into the
older patient, John Clarke, 65, of Gloucester, whose liver had been
severely damaged by hepatitis C. In time, the liver once belonging
to Pereira might make Clarke ill, but given his age and precarious
health, it might add years to his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the early hours of New Year's Day, when they were both being
prepared for surgery, Pereira met Clarke. ``It was a great
feeling,'' Pereira said.
</P>
<P>
   She was released from Lahey last Sunday. Clarke remains
hospitalized. The Lahey team performed another domino transplant
Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients of a liver from an amyloidosis patient risk
eventually developing symptoms of the disease, ``but it pales in
significance compared to the risk of dying while waiting,'' said
Dr. David Lewis, director of the Lahey liver-transplant program,
who headed the surgical team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us he would never get to the top of the list''
because he was so far down, Clarke's wife, Mary, said. ``This was
his chance _ and he took it.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone in Clarke's situation potentially could receive a piece
of a liver from a living donor, but Lewis said there was no such
donor available for Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line in the domino transplant: two patients would be
aided with just one new cadaver liver. Livers, like most solid
organs, are in desperately short supply for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said about 35 domino transplants have been done, most of
them in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, there was no treatment for amyloidosis patients,
who typically begin having symptoms in middle age, said Dr. Martha
Skinner, who heads the amyloidosis clinic at Boston Medical Center,
one of the largest such clinics. Lewis performed the first liver
transplant for an amyloidosis patient (it was not a domino
transplant) in 1992, while at the New England Deaconess Hospital,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Striking about 1 in 100,000 people, familial amyloidosis is
caused by a mutation that causes the liver to make the protein
transthyretin. Over many years, the protein becomes deposited in
body tissues and leads to numbness and tingling in the extremities,
severe constipation and diarrhea, and electrical irregularities in
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible disorder,'' Skinner said. When a patient
receives a normal liver, she said, ``you stop the abnormal protein
deposit, and it changes the whole course of events.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Lewis who first proposed the domino transplant strategy.
``The thing that struck us,'' he said, was in removing the livers
of amyloidosis patients prior to implanting a donor organ, ``it was
eerie taking out a normal-looking liver.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of discarding it, Lewis said, it would make sense to
offer to someone unlikely to get any liver at all _ an older person
who had not risen very far on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of the recent liver swap were formidable, Lewis
said. For starters, a surgical team had to go to the undisclosed
hospital where permission had been given for a brain-dead patient
to donate the liver and other organs. The removal of those organs
took two or three hours in the middle of the night, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 8 a.m., Lewis led a team that began carefully
removing Pereira's liver, a process that needed ``a little extra
attention'' because the organ was to be reused.
</P>
<P>
   Ethically, Lewis said, the surgeons' first priority was to
ensure that Pereira's transplant was going normally. When her liver
was out and packed in ice and the cadaver liver was being placed in
Pereira, Dr. Roger Evans, another team member, began removing
Clarke's liver in an adjoining operating room.
</P>
<P>
   After he finished transplanting Pereira's new liver, Lewis
assisted Evans in implanting her old liver into Clarke. The
marathon surgery went into the early evening. ``It was a long
day,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was the New Year's weekend, when there normally is
little elective surgery, many beds were empty. Several physicians
were away, and many nurses and other staff employees were taking
the day off.
</P>
<P>
   But key people volunteered to come in, and such critical
services as anesthesia and blood banking were taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people went the extra mile on January 1,'' Lewis
said. And the procedure, he added, ``couldn't have gone better. We
were delighted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
