<SLUG> BC-FBN-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK CONTRACT GRIEVANCE IN NFL CHIEF'S HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven hours of testimony in a meeting room on the
38th floor of 4 Times Square did not bring Bill Belichick to the
Patriots again. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokeswoman Leslie Hammond said commissioner Paul Tagliabue
would not rule on the validity of Belichick's New York Jets
contract until Monday at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from Belichick's attorneys and by the Jets was given
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets received an extension to present more testimony Friday,
but declined, leaving the matter in Tagliabue's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue did attend some of the hearing at the law offices of
Skadden, Arps, arriving at 9:45 a.m. and leaving shortly before
noon. The league's lead counsel, Jeff Pash, heard the testimony of
the witnesses brought forth by the Belichick legal team of Jeffrey
Kessler and Neil Cornrich. Kessler called Belichick and Jets
offensive coordinator Charlie Weis, who was deposed as a hostile
witness.
</P>
<P>
   New York's director of football operations Bill Parcells spoke
on behalf of the Jets, his session lasting about a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Weis knew something that would help Belichick's case,
though Kessler wouldn't comment on why he was called.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also left the building before noon, sporting a scowl
either directed at the waiting media waiting for him or because of
the questioning he received from Kessler.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler is playing hardball with the league, threatening to take
the matter to federal court on an antitrust violation if the league
does not let Belichick out of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it very clear we believe that the league doesn't have
any power or authority to restrict Coach Belichick, that it would
be a violation of the antitrust laws to do so,'' Kessler said. We
explained why that was, in terms of the state of the record and
with respect to the law that applies here. We hope that the league
will come to the same conclusion and that therefore further action
won't be necessary.'' Kessler, who has been involved in player
union matters with the NBA, contends the league ``cannot stop other
teams from making offers to or hiring Belichick if they would like.
We think the law is very clear. If the league were not to agree
with us we would take this further.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said on the issue of compensation for Belichick,
``People are not property. If you have to change and move to your
job, a court does not have the power to enter an injunction to
restrict you, neither can the commissioner of the NFL. There's no
compensation attached to you. There's no collective bargaining
agreement. These are not players, these are coaches. It's a
completely different set of circumstances when it's not bargained
for as part of a union.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler contends Belichick can't go back to work for the Jets
because the Jets ``have conceded'' that they no longer want
Belichick's services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the law is very clear that in these circumstances,
a court could not and would not prevent an employee from going
elsewhere essentially because you'd be depriving him of his
livelihood. He cannot go back to work for the Jets,'' added
Kessler. ``There is no other place in the NFL he can go if the
league blocks him. The courts have been very clear that is not
permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said he presented other arguments in addition to the
antitrust issue, but was not willing to specify.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick emerged from the elevator with his legal team flanking
him. Dressed in a grey overcoat, suit and tie, the former Patriots
assistant coach said, ``I appreciate the opportunity to state our
case before the NFL and I hope for a quick resolution. That's
really all I can say at this point. Any other questions will have
to be referred to Jeff.'' Jets president Steve Gutman was also in
the meeting room, but issued a ``no comment'' through spokesman
Frank Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets contend they have a binding contract with Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Boston attorney Harry Manion, who has represented sports teams
such as the NHL's Pittsburgh Penguins and also has been involved in
antitrust cases in the past, thinks Belichick is getting poor
advice from Kessler.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's (Kessler) silly enough to file an antitrust case on
this matter he'll be bounced out federal court in two shakes,''
said Manion. ``From the league's standpoint I would put no weight
on this threat. It's simply about an assistant coach who signed a
contract and now he's trying to get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is leading to a resolution in which Belichick would be
allowed to become the coach and general manager of the Patriots if
the Jets receive compensation. For now, Kessler does not sound like
a man who is going to accept compensation as a solution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
