<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Settlement to Help A Tobacco Region &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of the $206 billion legal settlement that 46 states
reached with the tobacco industry in 1998, a North Carolina
foundation will be able to provide help to areas damaged by
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit organization, Golden LEAF, for Long-term Economic
Advancement Fund, could begin making grants as early as late spring
in regions of the state tied to tobacco, including parts of eastern
North Carolina heavily damaged by the hurricane last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of these dollars is to bring about some action to
immediately relieve that suffering, and that's what we're going to
do, as promptly as we can,'' said William Friday, the retired
president of the University of North Carolina system who is
chairman of the foundation's board.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the foundation has received $29.3 million from the
settlement. It expects to receive nearly $4.6 billion through 2025.
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Cohen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting in the Dark &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans who work from home might well be puzzled. At the
beginning of the year, the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration gave a strong signal that telecommuters should
expect to be covered by the same safety standards that applied in
their companies' offices.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA wrote what it called an advisory letter to CSC Credit
Services, a unit of the Computer Sciences Corp., that had sought
advice about moving some of its executives into home offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ensuring safe and healthful working conditions for the
employee should be a precondition for any home-based work
assignments,'' OSHA said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   But after the contents of the letter became public, the agency
stressed that there was no change in government policy and that it
would take no new action.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the letter set off a round of criticism from
corporations and lawmakers. A few days later, the agency rescinded
the advisory.
</P>
<P>
   Back at home, meanwhile, telecommuters, who have surged in
number over the last decade, are feeling a bit, well, ignored. In a
survey by the American Management Association, only 7 percent of
1,265 executives of the group's member organizations said their
companies offered employees training to work outside the normal
office environment.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that fewer than half of executives who
telecommute were given necessary equipment. About half reported
that they lacked adequate technical support.
</P>
<P>
   _Mickey Meece
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
