<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANDPARENTS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redeeming the future: Grandparents feel need to lead
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Grandparents _ once considered the
silver-haired sages of the rocking chair _ are no longer content to
spoil, pamper and regale their grandchildren with tales of times
gone by. Now they want to teach them a thing or two while they're
at it.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the lessons they hope to impart may hint at what
they consider failures in the upbringing of their own children, a
recent study shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children do a beautiful job,'' said Ida Brodney, a
grandmother living in Delray Beach. ``But I'm teaching my grandson
to save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up in the Depression,'' she said, pointing to her
husband, George. ``Our children don't know the meaning of a
dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't all the Brodneys and their contemporaries think their
children don't know a thing about. The study released last week by
the AARP suggests that grandparents feel they have to teach morals,
ambition and religion to their grandkids _ if they want the
children to pick up those qualities at all.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the relationship between grandparent and
grandchild comes into sharp relief today as the U.S. Supreme Court
considers what may be a landmark case.
</P>
<P>
   Troxel vs. Glanville pits the mother of two girls against the
parents of their father, who committed suicide years earlier. The
grandparents successfully petitioned a lower court for visitation
rights, but the Washington state supreme court overruled that
decision in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all 50 states include some provision for grandparent
visitation rights. Thirty states allow grandparents to petition for
visitation even if the parents are married and both oppose the
visits. The law is catching up to a wrinkled, and presumably
slower, America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three-generation family never really existed,'' said Karen
Pyke, an assistant professor of sociology at the University of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Waltons' was a bit of a myth,'' she said of television's
beloved mountainside clan.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the good old days in which grandparents guided family
values is likely to be more true now than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty million Americans _ nearly a third of the population _ are
now grandparents, according to Roper Starch Worldwide, a research
group. The proportion of Americans who are grandparents is growing
because we are living longer. In 1900, Americans could expect to
die at the age of 46; by 1985, women were living an average of 80
years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the AARP study reveals that grandparents are seeing
their grandchildren more than many imagined. More than 80 percent
reported interacting with grandkids at least once in the last month
and 44 percent said they saw the children in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Are children like Natalie and Isabelle Troxel _ the preteens at
the center of this week's Supreme Court debate _ any better off for
all this time spent with grandma and grandpa?
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly do not know,'' answered Gretchen Straw, associate
research director for AARP.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some small studies, but nothing that would
make that clear,'' added Margaret Hollidge, director of the AARP's
Grandparent Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do know is that children do better when they are
surrounded by love and the earlier the better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Children are increasingly likely to get most of their loving
from grandparents, who also are raising their grandchildren in
record numbers. According to the U.S. Department of Commerce, 1.4
million children are living in grandparents' homes without either
parent present. That is up 75 percent since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say that may be why grandparents list morals,
ambition and religion as their top priorities, well ahead of
spoiling their grandchildren rotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Grandparents) have lived in a world that has changed
rapidly,'' Pyke said, ``and they are concerned about the world that
their grandkids will live in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandparents want to see their values continue,'' said Amelia
Rose, a facilitator for the Children's Services Council of Palm
Beach County and chairman of the year-old Coalition for
Grandparents Raising Grandchildren. ``Today's parents don't have
time to pay attention to values that their own parents find very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The AARP study _ which focused on 823 grandparents interviewed
in the fall of 1998 _ also revealed that grandparents' values
differed along racial lines. Despite the fact that their education
and income levels were similar, white grandparents were most likely
to list morals as the most important value to impart to
grandchildren, while black grandparents answered ``ambition'' in
response to the same question.
</P>
<P>
   The black grandparents also were more likely than whites to
consider themselves important advisers and to pass their hobbies
and interests on to grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what that means,'' Straw said. ``I think
African-Americans certainly do value economic well-being. These
grandparents are the children of segregation who have personally
experienced problems getting ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Edith Bush of West Palm Beach agreed. She is black and a
68-year-old grandmother of two as well as a member of the Palm
Beach County Partnership for Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black families know it will be a struggle,'' she said. ``If we
all had the same things to begin with, we would all want the same
things for our grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that grandparents value anything more than
the love of their grandchildren. And there is ample evidence in toy
chests across America that grandma and grandpa remain an easy mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give my grandchildren anything they want,'' said Matty
Kombert of Boynton Beach, proud grandmother to 10, mostly living in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want Pokemon?'' Kombart asked. ``Then Pokemon goes to New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
   
</P>
</TEXT>
