<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-COURSE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Course offers guidance on getting ready for marriage
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're hankering for a husband _ we
mean, in an I-do-or-die sort of way _ forget your little black
book. Dig out your checkbook instead.
</P>
<P>
   Because for $9,600, a New York psychotherapist will nurture you
through nuptial boot camp, preparing you for the man of your
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news is, he ain't included. But when he does show up, you'll
be ready (complete with La-Z-Boy and tidy fridge).
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what women spend on face lifts, liposuction, cosmetics
and fitness,'' says Marilyn Graman, whose six-month course,
``Marriage Works: A Step-by-Step Intensive Program Designed to Lead
you Down the Aisle,'' begins Feb. 18 at her Manhattan office. (The
next class starts in September.)
</P>
<P>
   ``So even though women may be ready on the outside, they may not
be ready on the inside. Perhaps there are unresolved issues from
old love affairs. Or maybe they're not ready to give up their
singlehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these things aren't dealt with, a woman can't make progress
toward marriage no matter how much she spends on her exterior.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight women (no boys allowed!) have enrolled for 276 hours of
one-on-one counseling, group therapy, image consulting, relaxation
techniques and house calls.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the ``Making Space for Him'' session, an
interior designer visits each student's home to determine
``man-readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The expert ``will address issues of color, furniture placement,
energy-flow decoration and more to help create the environment that
both soothes and expresses what you are all about,'' a course
description reads.
</P>
<P>
   Advises Graman: ``There are ways to make a man feel more at
home. Have a comfortable place for him to sit and something growing
so he can see that life can be given here.''
</P>
<P>
   Just make sure it's not growing in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leftovers show you don't have a keen interest in your
environment,'' she warns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 13 hours of the seminar are devoted to ``Being a
Goddess.''
</P>
<P>
   An artist-healer ``will show you how to glow from within, be
more calm, and breathe correctly to take in any situation more
fully and stay clear so you can make the best choices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This leads to being more comfortable in the presence of a
husband,'' course literature says. ``A rose is itself, and a bee
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Graman: ``Being a goddess isn't how you look. It has
everything to do with self-respect, about the ability to be very
soft without letting anyone step on you.''
</P>
<P>
   There's even a four-hour class on learning how to graciously
receive ``all the wonderful gifts, tokens and special times that
men are wanting to give.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, ``Marriage Works'' includes a couple of parties
(boys allowed!) just before graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide an opportunity for interaction, but that's not our
focus,'' the counselor says. ``We're here to get women ready. Women
who've found satisfaction elsewhere, but who look at their watch
and realize they don't have the husband and family they thought
they would.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're used to getting results in their professional lives,
and now, they want as much success outside the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
