A5571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WEDDING-TIPSBOX14-COX     01-13 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-TIPSBOX14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting happily hitched: 10 things to keep in mind
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Marilyn Graman, a New York
psychotherapist who specializes in relationships, says that
altar-seeking women should remember:
</P>
<P>
   1) You deserve a mate _ if that's indeed what you want.
</P>
<P>
   2) He shouldn't be like the last guy who didn't work out. If he
is, discover why you chose ``him'' again, and stop the pattern.
</P>
<P>
   3) Uncover hidden conversations within yourself that might be
pushing love away. Do you secretly think you're unworthy of
affection?
</P>
<P>
   4) Open your heart to the man in your life. Let yourself feel.
</P>
<P>
   5) Both of you will make mistakes. Lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   6) Neither of you wants to be criticized, but men can be
especially sensitive _ even if they don't show it.
</P>
<P>
   7) Forget all the male-bashing you've heard over the years. Give
him a fair shot.
</P>
<P>
   8) Before you pick a mate, decide exactly what you want from
him. Be specific. Maybe you don't need him around every day to feel
secure. Or maybe you do. Maybe you need to receive flowers
occasionally to feel special. Or maybe you're allergic to them.
</P>
<P>
   9) He's not your parent even if you get him to behave that way
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   10) Your Mr. Right wants you to be happy. Let him do what it
takes to make you feel that way.
</P>
<P>
   And 10 things women wish men knew 1) Tell her you love her _
often.
</P>
<P>
   2) You're important to her, and don't make her feel like she has
to hide that.
</P>
<P>
   3) Keep your promises because her heart is easily broken.
</P>
<P>
   4) Don't take her for granted. Appreciate how she nurtures you.
</P>
<P>
   5) Love her for who she is, not how she looks.
</P>
<P>
   6) She was trained to make you the center of her life _ and
she's trying to recover. Be patient.
</P>
<P>
   7) She needs space, too.
</P>
<P>
   8) You can listen without trying to help because that does help.
</P>
<P>
   9) She's not your parent even if you get her to behave that way
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   10) Compliment her, and reassure her that she's in your
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
