<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-FLORIDA-ART14-COX     01-13 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-ART14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author chronicles Florida art history in new book
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEQUESTA, Fla. _ Maybelle Mann once told a New York art dealer
that she was planning a book on Florida art. ``What's it going to
be,'' he sneered, ``a pamphlet?''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, the Tequesta historian has the answer: ``No,
a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Her overview of the state's art, titled ``Art in Florida
1564-1945,'' has just been published by Sarasota's Pineapple Press.
An exhibition of the same name runs Saturday through April 9 at the
Florida History Center &AMP; Museum in Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   The show contains roughly 50 paintings, drawings, prints and
photographs. The earliest are two prints by the first European
artist to set foot in Florida, the Frenchman Jacques LeMoyne, who
arrived in 1564 at what is today St. Augustine. An engraving of one
of his watercolors depicts promenading royalty of the Timucuan
tribe: ``The King and Queen Take a Walk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak to people who live in Florida who still don't think
there is such a thing'' as Florida art, said Mann, who has also
written books on the 19th-century American Art Union and painter
William Launt Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, they're right, she said _ at least if you're
talking pre-1945. Like nearly everyone else, the artists who worked
here came from somewhere else and usually had well-established
careers. ``Mainly, they were snowbirds. They came for the climate''
and were struck by the ``exotic'' state, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there was no such thing as a Florida regional style or
subject matter. ``For example, there is very little marine art like
you find in New England, which I think is surprising considering
all the boats on the water,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM VIEWS ART AS HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   Mann said the reason there has been no definitive study of
Florida art is because it has only recently been taken seriously as
a subject. More than 40 collectors and institutions contributed
work to the show, headed by Dan McKenna, a DeLand private
collector. ``He once had a museum of Florida art in St. Augustine,
but nobody came,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said the history center became interested in the show after
board member Alan Holmes read her book in manuscript form.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first exhibition of this magnitude for the
museum,'' said its new interim executive director, George Blanck.
``The show has more to do with the history of Florida itself, as
seen through its art. We don't see ourselves becoming an art
exhibiting institution, per se. But you can portray history in any
number of ways, and art is certainly one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has attracted a roster of top-notch artists. A list of
332 names appears in the book, including that of John James
Audubon, who visited Key West in 1832. His aquatint ``Great White
Heron'' is in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the noted 19th-century landscape painters George
Inness and Martin Johnson Heade, who lived in St. Augustine thanks
to the patronage of railroad mogul Henry Morrison Flagler. Inness
worked in Florida between 1890 and 1894, settling in Tarpon
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Inness' oil ``The Road to Tarpon Springs, Florida,'' also called
``Moonlight,'' is in the show. So is Heade's oil ``St. Johns
River,'' painted sometime between 1890 and 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow Homer and John Singer Sargent also visited the state.
Sargent arrived in Miami in 1917 at the invitation of James
Deering, the industrialist whose home is now the Vizcaya Museum. He
created several watercolors. Homer came to Key West in 1886 and
also painted along the St. Johns River in northeast Florida.
(Neither artist is represented in the exhibition.)
</P>
<P>
   Notable artists who are include Milton Avery, who worked in
Coral Gables, and Frederick Frieseke, an American who painted based
on memories of his childhood in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   No painter of similar stature worked in Palm Beach, although the
island attracted a host of artists in the prewar years. Many were
attracted by society patronage; others came to teach at the Norton
Museum of Art's former art school, including painter Adolph Dehn
and the respected watercolorist Eliot O'Hara. Dehn has a Key West
beach scene in the show. O'Hara is represented by a 1942 watercolor
depicting a Palm Beach via off Worth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN ARTIST STAYED A WHILE
</P>
<P>
   The O'Hara picture is the only local work on view, although
Mann's book dutifully lists a host of artists who worked in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   They include Jane Peterson, Laura Woodward, Anthony Thieme, the
noted Spanish muralist Jose Maria Sert, who decorated island
houses, and Ben Austrian, who was known as the ``Landseer of
Chickens,'' referring to the British artist Henry Landseer, noted
for his animal pictures. While living in Palm Beach, Austria
painted island scenes, not chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Mann also discusses groups such as the Palm Beach County Art
Club and the Association for Artists. Their exhibitions attracted
work by such artists as Theodore Robinson and Maurice Prendergast.
</P>
<P>
   But American paintings were a hard sell, Mann said. ``They
weren't very popular with the rich because European paintings were
what they bought in the '20s,'' Mann said. ``That didn't change
until World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann, 84, said her book represents 20 years of off and on
research. Born in Illinois, she grew up in New York. She returned
to college as an adult and ``kept on getting degrees,'' including a
Ph.D. in American civilization from New York University. She said
she ``got tired of reading about the Civil War'' and turned her
attention to art history. She has always worked privately.
</P>
<P>
   Mann and her husband, Alvin Lloyd, a retired businessman, have
lived in Tequesta for 22 years. Like many of the artists she writes
about, the reason she came to Florida was simple:
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out of the car just after crossing the state line, and
the air was balmy. You could feel a difference _ or imagined you
could. We were hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann said she's probably overlooked a few artists who've worked
in the state. ``Now that the book is published, they'll probably
come out of the woodwork like mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
