<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT BY RISING COSTS, UAL CORP. WARNS OF EARNINGS SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with rising labor and fuel costs, UAL Corp., the parent
company of United Airlines, said Thursday that its earnings this
year were likely to be as much as 28 percent below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement prompted a huge selloff of airline stocks.
UAL's shares plunged 13 percent, or $9.875, to $64.875. Shares of
AMR, the parent of American Airlines, dropped 6.5 percent, or
$4.6875, to $60.25. Delta Air Lines stock fell 4.2 percent, or
$2.1875, to $49.8125.
</P>
<P>
   UAL, which is based in Chicago, said it expected earnings this
year of $7 to $9 a share, well below the $9.82 consensus estimate
from analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, the world's largest carrier, is being plagued
by troubles that are common to the industry and by others that are
singular to its operation. Jet fuel prices increased about 24
percent last year and United predicted further jumps this year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the carnage, several of United's unions were demanding
large wage increases, in part to keep up with competitors and to
replace money generated from the company's expiring stock ownership
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``UAL gave a very sobering message yesterday,'' said Kevin
Murphy, an airlines analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``No
airline outperforms when you're negotiating with labor. If United
gives big wage boosts to its pilots and mechanics, the other
carriers may have to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of United's cost increases caught some analysts by
surprise. Candace Browning, an airlines analyst for Merrill Lynch,
had estimated United's wages would increase $400 million this year,
but raised the amount to $780 million after UAL's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   UAL had begun a program in 1994 to give its employees stock
instead of wage increases. The program is expected to be
discontinued this spring, leaving many UAL employees anxious about
salary increases.
</P>
<P>
   Wage increases from union pressure are common in the airline
industry, but much of United's dispute is expected to come from the
company's pilots, whose contract expires in April. A particularly
contentious issue will be the salary of pilots who fly Boeing 777s,
a twin-engine plane that seats about 275 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilots recently negotiated a base wage of $265 an hour
to fly the 777, which brings their base pay on that plane to about
$240,000 annually. Analysts believe that United's pilots, who trail
Delta's, may seek to match or top that rate. The problem is that
United is expected to have 48 of the Boeing 777s in its fleet this
year, compared with about 11 for Delta, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   But labor was only one of UAL's woes. The company also said that
it expected the average price of jet fuel to be 71 cents a gallon
this year, 6 cents above what most analysts had projected. The
price of jet fuel had averaged about 62 cents a gallon during the
second half of last year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with United's estimate of the fuel price,'' said
Samuel Buttrick, an airlines analyst with PaineWebber. ``We think
the price will be around 65 cents per gallon. But if United's
assessment is correct, then that will be a factor that will affect
the entire industry.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its performance projection for 2000, UAL said it
expected revenue growth in Latin America, the Pacific and North
America. The company said that its revenue would increase 2 percent
to 4 percent this year, but that would be overshadowed by a 6
percent rise in costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
