<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SURVEY-SURVEY_SFCHRON     01-13 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVEY-SURVEY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Bay Area Leads California in Holiday Shopping Online  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The Bay Area leads the state in Internet shopping, according to
a poll that will be released today.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, 27 percent of those surveyed by the Public
Policy Institute of California said they bought a holiday gift over
the Internet last year, and 30 percent said they plan to make an
online purchase this year.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, only 20 percent of those surveyed made a holiday
purchase on the Internet, and 23 percent plan to buy online year.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report released yesterday, Jupiter Communications
Inc. said 25 million consumers across America spent $7 billion
shopping online over the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, a New York research firm, found that 90 percent of
those online shoppers were satisfied customers, a jump from the 74
percent who said they were satisfied by the online experience in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, cybershopping runs a distant second to brick-and-mortar
shopping. According to the PPIC poll, a whopping 77 percent of the
state's residents planned ``very little or no shopping'' on the Web
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to forget about that fact that this is still a new
technology that hasn't taken hold for a large number of people on a
frequent basis,'' said Mark Baldassare, state survey director for
the PPIC. ``I hope the numbers provide a little bit of a reality
check.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit PPIC, which was established in 1994 with an
endowment from Silicon Valley pioneer William Hewlett, included for
the first time several Internet and computer-related questions in
its regular survey of adults in California.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, meant to gauge social, economic and political forces
that could affect state elections, canvassed 2,007 adults by phone
from January 2 to January 10, with an error rate of plus or minus
two percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters asked whether the residents bought any holiday
gifts over the Internet in the past few months. Of the total, 5
percent said they bought ``a lot,'' 15 percent answered ``some''
and 44 percent answered ``no.'' The remaining 36 percent said they
did not use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Bay Area residents questioned, 7 percent said they bought
of gifts online, and 20 percent said they bought some.
</P>
<P>
   Central Valley residents were the least likely to buy online,
with only 3 percent buying a lot and 13 percent buying some. Of
Southern California residents outside of Los Angeles, 21 percent
said they had made some or a lot of purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In another question, 5 percent statewide said they planned ``a
lot'' of online purchases this year, while 18 indicated they would
make ``some.'' But 21 percent answered ``very little'' and 20
percent said ``not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of Bay Area residents said they planned some or
a lot of online shopping this year, compared with 21 percent in the
Central Valley, 20 percent in Los Angeles and 22 percent in the
rest of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The poll revealed that a majority of the online shoppers were
affluent. About 72 percent of people who shopped online frequently
made $80,000 per year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare said he was surprised to find far less opposition in
California to Internet sales taxes than he expected. In fact, 52
percent of the online shoppers favored requiring companies to
collect sales taxes on Internet sales, with 41 percent opposed and
7 percent having no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find instances where people favored taxes,''
Baldassare said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed a Digital Divide still exists between white
and Latino residents in the state. The poll said only 21 percent of
Latino respondents used computers often, compared with 51 percent
of non-Hispanic white residents.
</P>
<P>
   And only 9 percent of Latinos surveyed said they were likely to
buy online this year, compared with 27 percent of non-Hispanic
white residents. Sixty percent said they did not use the Internet
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare said those numbers could indicate lack of marketing
by the high-tech community toward Latinos, who are projected to
outnumber whites in California by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
