<SLUG> BC-FDA-FDA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Eye Laser Gets the Wink From FDA Panel  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Baby Boomers who can't see as well as they used to could soon have
a new alternative to glasses or contact lenses, now that a
government panel has endorsed a noninvasive type of laser surgery
for farsightedness.
<P>
   Yesterday's decision by a Food and Drug Administration advisory
panel was a turnabout for Sunrise Technologies International of
Fremont, whose laser device was rejected by the same panel in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both votes were unanimous, but we like this one a whole lot
better,'' Sunrise Chief Executive Officer Russell Trenary joked
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the full FDA generally follows advisory panel votes,
Trenary said it could be six months before its laser clears the
last regulatory hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise failed its first advisory panel vote in July because
panelists worried the effects of the eye surgery would wear off
over time.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's vote, the FDA panel suggested the product be
labeled as temporary vision correction for farsighted people over
age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are born with farsightedness _ or hyperopia _ but
never notice it, because their eye muscles automatically compensate
for the problem. After 40, however, as the eye muscles lose their
flexibility, many people begin having trouble reading books or
start seeing faraway objects as blurs, said Robert Doyle Stulting,
a medical consultant with Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunrise LTK laser heats a circle of tissue around the eye _
like cinching up a belt _ to do what the eye muscles can no longer
do naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA panel was concerned that this ``belt tightening'' might
relax over time, causing a relapse of farsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   David Gruber, an analyst with Lehman Brothers in New York,
called the temporary designation ``no big deal'' and predicted that
the Sunrise laser would reach a large and untapped market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really safe procedure that is going to be cheaper
than other laser surgery alternatives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has already approved a competing laser surgery technique
for farsightedness from Sunnyvale's Visx. The Visx laser, named
Lasik, is already in widespread use for myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Also called nearsightedness, myopia is the ability to see
close-up but not far away. It manifests itself at an early age and
affects about 75 million Americans _ roughly the same number that
suffer from hyperopia.
</P>
<P>
   In a Lasik treatment, the laser actually cuts the eye and
removes some tissue to correct the myopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it a flap and zap,'' said Gruber. ``You cut the
cornea, flip it over like a door hinge, remove some tissue and flap
it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruber said the Sunrise procedure is less invasive and was
designed specifically for hyperopia. He predicted eye surgeons
would prefer the Sunrise technique for hyperopia because it is
simpler and involves no cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise officials were cagey about the eventual price of the
procedure, but suggested it might run about $1,000 per eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise shares, which had traded as high as $20 in early July,
fell $4 after the first FDA advisory panel rejection. Its stock
ended yesterday at $10.06 after trading was halted while the FDA
panel deliberated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
