<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intel Posts Record Results  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
If we've really entered the ``post-PC era,'' you wouldn't know it
by the financial results Intel posted yesterday.
<P>
   The Santa Clara chip behemoth reported record revenues, net
income and unit shipments for the last quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the fourth quarter was $8.2 billion, up 8 percent
from the year before and 12 percent from the third quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Net income was $2.1 billion (61 cents per share), up from $2.06
billion (59 cents) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding acquisition-related costs, net income reached $2.4
billion (69 cents) in the latest quarter. That was well above both
analysts' consensus estimate of 63 cents, according to First Call
Corp., and the ``whisper'' estimate, 65 cents. Whisper estimates
are given to big brokerage-house customers and often circulated on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, 5 cents of Intel's per-share earnings came not from
operations, but from gains realized by selling shares in companies
Intel's venture fund has invested in, said Mark Edelstone, an
analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in San Francisco. Excluding
those earnings, the figure would be much closer to consensus
estimates and right in line with Edelstone's prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty much what we expected,'' he said, ``but it was a
very a solid quarter and a foundation for what should be a very
strong year 2000. It was all about solid PC demand, plus excellent
execution on Intel's part.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelstone said Intel maximized its product mix between
higher-margin, high-performance chips and lower-margin but
higher-volume ``value'' microprocessors. Intel also increased its
average selling price and slightly exceeded revenue and
gross-margin forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said its gross margins for the fourth quarter were 61.3
percent, up from 58.7 percent for the same period last year.
Company officials had predicted an increase, but only of 2 percent.
Andy Bryant, the company's chief financial officer, said the
unexpected increase was largely a function of
higher-than-anticipated levels of demand.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it set records for quarterly unit shipments not just
of microprocessors, but also of several of its other products:
chipsets, the companion chips that coordinate the various
components of a PC; motherboards, which the company sells to many
PC vendors; and flash memory, a type of memory widely used in cell
phones, digital cameras and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, demand was so strong that Intel's inventories were down
9 percent in the quarter across all product categories. ``They're
less than we'd like, as they have been for several quarters,''
Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Intel customers have complained that the company has
recently been unable to meet their demand. Last week Gateway, a
major PC-maker, blamed Intel for a shortfall in its own revenues,
claiming that its ``supply of key processors and motherboards was
severely constrained, spotty and unreliable.'' Gateway then
announced that it would resume buying some chips from Intel's chief
rival, Advanced Micro Devices.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Otellini, general manager of the Intel Architecture
Business Group, said yesterday that some ``tightness'' in supply
continues but that the company expects it to ease during the
current quarter. ``We expect to be able to satisfy demand for the
first quarter overall,'' he said in a conference call with
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1999, Intel revenues totaled $29.4 billion, up 12
percent from $26.3 billion in 1998. Net income was $7.3 billion, up
20 percent from $6.1 billion the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
