<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel's 4th-Quarter Profit Tops Wall Street Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   After three quarters of results that disappointed investors,
Intel posted fourth-quarter earnings that exceeded Wall Street's
expectations because of strong demand for personal computers and a
shift toward higher-performance chips that have bigger profit
margins. Excluding costs related to acquisitions, profit rose 15
percent, to 69 cents a share, topping forecasts of 63 cents, while
revenue rose 8 percent. Shares of Intel edged down to $91.0625 in
regular trading but soared as high as $95.75 in after-hours
trading.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco Pushes FTC on Deal
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with its discussions with the Federal Trade
Commission about its plans to acquire Atlantic Richfield, BP Amoco
said it would invoke its right to set a 20-day deadline for the FTC
to challenge the deal. The action means the FTC is likely to go to
federal court to block the $31 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   UAL Issues a 2000 Profit Warning
</P>
<P>
   Faced with rising labor and fuel costs, UAL, the parent of
United Airlines, said that its 2000 earnings were likely to be as
much as 28 percent below expectations. The announcement prompted a
huge sell-off of airline stocks. Shares of UAL, based in Chicago,
plunged $9.875, to $64.875. Shares of AMR, the parent of American
Airlines, dropped 6.5 percent, or $4.6875, to $60.25, and Delta Air
Lines' stock fell 4.2 percent, or $2.1875, to $49.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Warns About Inflation
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, warned that there
were limits to how long the economy could continue growing without
igniting inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AOL Reverse Their Slide
</P>
<P>
   Shares of America Online reversed their two-day slide and jumped
by 9 percent as investors began re-evaluating the company in the
wake of its deal to acquire Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai played a part in the courtship between America Online
and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Scant Sign of Inflation Lifts Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after a report of modest inflation calmed jittery
investors. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 31.33 points, to
11,582.43. Broader stock indicators also closed higher. The Nasdaq
composite index finished up 107.19 points, or 2.8 percent, to
3,957.21. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 17.43 points,
or 1.2 percent, to 1,449.68.
</P>
<P>
   Drug Industry Reconsiders Benefits
</P>
<P>
   Drug company executives asked the White House for a cease-fire
in their war over drug prices and said that they wanted to work
with President Clinton and Congress to establish Medicare coverage
of drugs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Avenue Joins Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   J. Walter Thompson USA in New York is forming an alliance with
Basic Entertainment, a powerful company in Hollywood specializing
in talent management and television and movie production. The
affiliation is intended to help advertisers exploit the potentials
inherent in entertainment marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Plans to Buy Back Debt
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department plans to use up to $30 billion of
surplus cash this year to buy back outstanding debt, enticing
investors to sell old bonds that pay interest rates that are much
higher than the current ones.
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries Fined $30 Million
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency fined Koch Industries, one
of the nation's largest oil and gas pipeline operators, $30 million
for contaminating water in six states.
</P>
</TEXT>
