<SLUG> BC-AOL-TIME-WARNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL AND TIME WARNER SHARE PRICES REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two-day slide in the shares of America Online reversed
Thursday as its stock jumped 7.5 percent, to $64.50.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three trading days after the announcement Monday
morning of America Online's deal to buy Time Warner for $165
billion in stock, its shares fell by 19 percent, to $60 on
Wednesday. Analysts said that those investors who followed a
momentum strategy _ investing in companies with the fastest growth
_ sold their America Online shares because they thought the merger
would slow its growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the fastest growing company in the S.&AMP; P. 500,''
said Henry Blodget, an analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``When you blend
these two companies it becomes less attractive to momentum
investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Such investors, however, represent a small percentage of America
Online's overall shareholder base, and analysts said that most
holders appear for now to support the deal.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, said Paul Noglows, an analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q,
America Online's growth was bound to slow because it was getting so
much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Time Warner rose $4.375 Thursday, to $84. They were at
$64.75 on Friday, the day before the acquisition was announced. The
combined company will be called AOL Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts continued to work through the company's prospective
financial position as they project its revenue and earnings. The
deal will force investors in both companies to change the way they
evaluate its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the deal's oddities, America Online has been one of
the few Internet companies to report a profit, but the acquisition
of Time Warner will cause it to lose money for years. Time Warner,
by itself, had only recently started reporting profits, largely
because it had been saddled by the cost of its cable systems and
the debt incurred in the merger of Time Inc. and Warner
Communications 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the huge premium that America Online is paying for
Time Warner's shares will cause it to write off $7.5 billion in
goodwill _ a noncash accounting charge _ from its earnings each
year for the next 20 years. That means the company will lose money
for about five years, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most companies in the cable television industry, which
typically do not show profits, Time Warner has been valued on its
pretax operating earnings.
</P>
<P>
   America Online hopes that its investors will similarly look past
the lack of profit to its operating earnings and cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not at all clear what value to put on those figures.
</P>
<P>
   Blodget calculates, for example, that before the merger America
Online was trading at 55 times its pretax operating earnings, while
Time Warner had a multiple of 14.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, he calculated, will have combined
operating earnings of $11 billion in 2001. Blodget figured the
company's multiple to pretax operating earnings should range
between 25 and 40, implying a stock price between $55 and $88 a
share. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0393 </DOCNO>
