u a BC-PUFF-DADDY-GUNS-NYT     01-13 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUFF-DADDY-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUFF DADDY INDICTED OVER GUNS IN NIGHTCLUB SHOOTINGS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan grand jury Thursday charged Sean Combs,
the rap performer better known as Puff Daddy, with possession of
two illegal handguns as part of its investigation into shootings
that wounded three people on Dec. 27 at a Times Square nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Combs took the unusual step of testifying in his own defense,
but the indictment appears to rely on the account of a 42-year-old
father of three who was his part-time driver that night. While the
testimony of the driver, Wardell Fenderson, is sealed, evidence
presented by prosecutors indicated that he saw Combs throw a gun
out the window of the car as they fled police.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment presents another daunting challenge for Combs, a
30-year-old multimillionaire, Grammy-winning artist and producer,
who socializes with the city's elite and has a knack for surviving
seemingly disastrous blows to his career.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he faces poor sales of his latest record, other artists
leaving his recording label and rumblings of discontent from his
corporate backer, Combs must now resolve criminal charges that
carry a penalty of up to 15 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper, whose business empire includes the Bad Boy
Entertainment music label, a restaurant chain, a clothing line and
a television production company, added the lawyer Johnnie Cochran
Jr. to his legal team Thursday and issued a statement vehemently
denying the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to indict me is wrong,'' Combs said. ``I'm
innocent and we will prove it. I am putting my faith in God, and I
know my name will be cleared.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez, the singer and actress who was in the car with
Combs, stood by him Thursday. She issued a statement saying she had
``cooperated fully'' with the district attorney's office and was
``surprised and saddened'' by the indictment. ``I was with him that
evening,'' she said. ``At no time did I see him with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Cochran said, ``We ask the public, Sean's
millions of fans and those with whom he is involved in various
business ventures to withhold judgment until the case is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charged Combs with possession of a 9 millimeter
handgun found inside the car, and with possession of another 9
millimeter gun that was thrown from the car as it sped away from
the crowded Club NY on West 43rd Street. Two of Combs' associates
were also named in the indictment: Jamal Barrow, a rapper, who has
been charged with three counts of attempted murder stemming from
the accusation that he pulled his own gun and fired it three times
in the club, and a bodyguard, Anthony Jones, on a weapons charge.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Manhattan District Attorney
Robert M. Morgenthau said that a 1999 Lincoln Navigator in which
Combs was riding had secret compartments for hiding contraband or
other materials. He said nothing had been found in the
compartments.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement officials who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said there was evidence that Combs and his bodyguard
tried to stash the guns in the compartments as the police pursued
them but were unable to open them. Combs threw his gun out the
window, they said, and Jones placed his on the car floor. Someone
walking down Eighth Avenue saw the gun thrown from the vehicle,
picked it up and later turned it over to police, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials also said Thursday that they were
investigating accounts that Combs was heard in jail, where he was
held overnight, offering Fenderson, the driver, a $300,000 ring and
$50,000 in cash if he would back up Combs' version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Brounstein, the lawyer representing Fenderson, declined
to comment Thursday on whether the driver testified before the
grand jury. But he thanked the panel for not indicting his client
and praised prosecutors for a ``fair'' investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Fenderson is not a member of the tightly knit group of employees
and friends who work for Combs, according to people familiar with
the case. For the last five years, they said, he worked as a
full-time private driver for a wealthy person and had only worked
for Combs on weekends since October. The wealthy person has
dismissed Fenderson out of apparent concern about fallout from the
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
