<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5598 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV16-N     01-13 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERVISING THE GRAYBEARDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Conn., Ga.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Look. Mary Rodas can spot it a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   It's not malicious, but it's certainly cutting, even though
she's used to it. That is because at age 24, Ms. Rodas is a vice
president at Kardz.com, a New York City company that delivers
inexpensive gifts matched with greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she has been in the toy business since she was 14,
when she helped create the Balzac, a cloth balloon ball that helped
turn Catco, a division of Catalyst Toys, into a $70 million
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   And so when she gets the Look _ a raised eyebrow, a questioning
glance _ she is not surprised. ``I go into meetings with people who
are my parents' and grandparents' age,'' said Ms. Rodas, who
supervises five people, all significantly older. ``When people meet
me their first response is: `Who's this little kid?' Or else they
say, `Can I speak to your boss?' And I point to myself and say,
`That's her.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodas said she earned respect through hard work and getting
to know her workers. ``I know my product, and within time people
realize that I'm talking to them as an individual and an equal,''
she said. ``I've been in this industry for 11 years. I know what
I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The workplace is now filled with young whippersnappers,
and some supervisors are half the age of their staff. The Labor
Department says 5.2 million people ages 20 to 34 were in management
last year, up from 4.8 million in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In the executive ranks, some older men try to compete by using
hair color and chemical peels. But for young executives, managing
older people is more than an aesthetic challenge. Among the
questions they ask themselves are: Will I be taken seriously? Will
they resent taking orders from someone so young, especially when
they were in this industry before I was born?
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself as a kid running this multimillion-dollar
company,'' said Gregg Levin, 31, chief executive of Perfect Curve,
Inc., a company in Sudbury, Mass., that makes racks for baseball
caps and related products. ``Sometimes I feel I'm just playing. A
president is in his 50s or 60s, not 31.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Levin _ who counts his father among five employees _
dismissed a 38-year-old subordinate. ``I'm younger than he is and
this guy hasn't caught a break his whole life. But as much as I
wanted to help the guy, I have a business to run.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other issues. Levin's father, who is 66, does not use
a computer. ``He takes out his legal pad and spends an extra hour
on something that takes me four and a half minutes on the
computer,'' he said. ``Everyone in the company is computer literate
and we have to adjust to him. Sometimes I lose my patience, but I
have to be cognizant of the fact that he's 66.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin is also aware of his own appearance. No flannel shirts,
baggy jeans or eyebrow rings. ``I'm always in a suit and tie,'' he
said. ``If I'm going to represent my company I've got to do it in a
mature fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Young supervisors need to realize that they cannot overlook the
experience of older employees, said Bruce Tulgan, 32, founder of
RainmakerThinking Inc., a consulting firm in New Haven. ``Older
people know what's been tried in the past, what worked and what
didn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not just enough to look mature; you've got to
act that way. Reggie Bradford, 33, chief marketing officer of
Healtheon/WebMD, an online health care company in Atlanta, is in
charge of 45 people ages 19 to 53.
</P>
<P>
   ``You respect the fact that a 30-year health care veteran may
understand the business,'' he said. ``But I can bring new
approaches and new solutions to older problems.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice? ``Check your ego at the door.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be resistance, of course. Bradford _ who himself
reports to a 30-year-old chief executive, his college roommate _
recalled that when executives were considering a partnership with
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., an older employee discouraged them.
``He said no traditional media company that large would partner
with a Web site,'' Bradford said, ``but he was wrong.'' The deal
went through in December. ``Youth won out over experience.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin is a Manhattan writer. Her column on starting out in
the world of money appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
preludes(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
