<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE SHOWS WITHOUT BORDERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y., Conn.)   (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Peter Nathan, the word ``no'' is merely a request for more
information. In the 1970s and '80s, Nathan, a trade show
impresario, arm-wrestled Soviet and Chinese apparatchiks into
allowing him past their frontiers to produce a variety of Western
industry shows.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he will preside over the five-day U.S. Healthcare
Exhibition _ the first American trade expo in Cuba in more than 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the trade embargo against Cuba (which does not
include medical supplies) and the tug-of-war over Elian Gonzalez,
6, the survivor of a shipwreck, Nathan is convinced that now is the
time to open up the Cuban market.
</P>
<P>
   Producing a trade show in that environment requires someone
special, said Steven Hacker, president of the International
Association for Exposition Management in Dallas, who called Nathan
``the Green Beret of international exhibitors.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, Nathan, 66, demonstrates that the advantages, and the
risks, of being an early mover extend far beyond the technology
world. With his forays into untested markets, Nathan is trying to
go where even major multinationals often stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Is the payoff worth it? ``Definitely,'' he said. ``The
authorities from those countries are pleased when someone takes an
interest in their country, and so, going forward, you have the ear
of the right people.''
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian benefits of medical equipment and
pharmaceuticals would make the trade fair an easier sell to both
governments, he felt. While it took three years to get Washington's
approval, said John S. Kavulich, president of the U.S.-Cuba Trade
and Economic Council in New York, Havana approved in just 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely incredible what he's accomplished,'' Kavulich
said. ``Anyone else would have given up after getting turned down
so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Kavulich told Nathan that he should consider his show
a success if only 10 exhibitors showed up. As of last week,
Nathan's company, PWN Exhibicon International LLC of Westport,
Conn., had signed more than 100. The principal sponsor is Archer
Daniels Midland, and other exhibitors include Eli Lilly, Medtronic,
Hewlett-Packard and Eastman Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   . Nathan relishes breaking into new territory. In 1971, long
before glasnost, he organized the first American industrial
machinery show in Russia, overcoming currency and language
barriers, shipping catastrophes and ``unfathomable amounts of red
tape.'' But dealing with Moscow became much easier, and other
successful shows followed.
</P>
<P>
   To make it in the business, ``you have to be a professional,
round-the-clock problem solver,'' he said. He has seen many of them
_ waking up to blizzards and an exhibit hall fire _ at McCormick
Place in Chicago _ and giving up many a night's sleep in union
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Why put on shows in markets like Cuba? ``The short answer is the
Mount Everest one,'' Nathan said. ``It's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, his wife of 45 years, Sandy, enjoys the challenge,
too. She will be working as an on-site administrator in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan arrived on these shores in 1937 as a 4-yearold
German-Jewish immigrant; his family had fled the Nazis. He received
a bachelor's degree in life sciences from the University of
Connecticut in 1954. While waiting to start at the Marine Corps
officers school, Nathan took a temporary job as an office boy at
Clapp &AMP; Poliak, an exhibition company based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in the Marines during the Korean War, he
returned to the firm, eventually rising to partner. (He stayed with
the company until it was sold in 1982.)
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, the federal government hired Clapp &AMP; Poliak
to organize an air and transportation show at Dulles International
Airport outside Washington. That was the start of a long
relationship. Two years later, unhappy with local management of
Expo 74, the world's fair in Spokane, Wash., the government
persuaded Nathan to run the event for six months.
</P>
<P>
   President Richard M. Nixon, who was increasingly enmeshed in the
Watergate scandal, flew out to open the fair. While being escorted
around, Nixon pointed to the walkie-talkie in Nathan's hand and
asked, ```What's that?''' Nathan recalled. ``I explained it was a
two-way radio. Nixon replied, `It's not a tape recorder is it?
Because I don't like those things.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Nathan put on the first two American electronics
exhibitions in China. At the first, in Beijing, the booths were
overrun by 20,000 Chinese consumers, leading panicky officials to
call in security. It wasn't needed. The friendly stampede was
simply the result of tremendous interest in American products. As
with the first show in Russia, many more exhibitions followed.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan expects his Cuban odyssey to have a similarly happy
ending. The licenses and approvals that he sought for so many years
were eventually granted. And the federal departments that stymied
Nathan for three years _ State, Commerce and Treasury _ are now
sharing a big booth at the show to encourage future trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very enthusiastic about the expo,'' said Charles S.
Shapiro, the director for Cuban Affairs at the State Department. He
attributes the turnaround in large part to President Clinton's call
last year for more people-to-people contacts with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Hollywood version should be called ``Mr. Nathan Goes
to Havana.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Pedersen-Pietersen is a Manhattan author and public
speaker. Her column profiling people whose work is their passion
appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
yourmind(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
