WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: EX-STATE CHIEF CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha Jayaram, the former actress and onetime chief
minister of the state of Tamil Nadu, won an important victory in a
criminal case when charges against her in a reportedly crooked land
deal were dropped. The same state court also upheld an earlier
ruling, absolving her of guilt in a reported coal-importing scam.
Two other charges against her are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: CABINET SHAKE-UP
</P>
<P>
   In a move aimed at demonstrating its will to step up economic
reforms, the government appointed a leading industrialist, Park Tae
Joon, as prime minister, and the country's corporate restructuring
chief, Lee Hun Jai, as finance minister. The changes were among a
shuffle of nine ministerial posts ahead of parliamentary elections
in April. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: DEFENSE AIDE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Minister of Defense Jose Gallardo has unexpectedly resigned in
the midst of the most serious political crisis since President
Jamil Mahuad took office in 1998. Gallardo, a retired army general,
had been instrumental in assuring that the armed forces remained
loyal to Mahuad, and had been expected to stay on after the
president demanded his cabinet step down.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: MURDER SUSPECT HELD
</P>
<P>
   The police announced the arrest of a man they say took part in
the murder of Jaime Garzon, Colombia's most popular comedian. Juan
Pablo Ortiz, described as a professional hit man, was captured in
Medellin, but authorities have not said whether he has indicated
who ordered the killing of Garzon, a member of a government
commission who sometimes helped gain the release of hostages seized
by left-wing rebels.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: PUTIN MAKES IT OFFICIAL
</P>
<P>
   As Acting President Vladimir V. Putin formally announced his
candidacy for president, his principal rival, Yevgeny M. Primakov,
was reported to have told a meeting of parliamentary leaders that
he would drop out of the race, preferring to run for speaker of the
lower house of Parliament. Political analysts said that would
markedly improve Putin's chance of winning a majority in the March
26 vote, avoiding a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SOFTWARE PIRATES HELD
</P>
<P>
   German and Danish police officers arrested members of what they
described as a major software-piracy gang, seizing more than
100,000 CD-ROMs loaded with illegally duplicated programs ranging
from Windows 98 to computer games. The group, which called itself
Akira, had been selling the software at bargain prices over the
Internet since late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: FIERY PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Three relatives of soldiers killed fighting Kurdish rebels set
themselves on fire at a cemetery in Ankara. The two men and a woman
were protesting the government's decision to postpone hanging the
condemned Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan. Onlookers
doused the flames, and the victims were taken to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: SECURITY ALERT
</P>
<P>
   Security around some courthouses has been tightened after a pipe
bomb exploded outside a court building during a bail hearing for
two members of a vigilante group that police investigators suspect
is involved in a string of bombings in Cape Town and the
surrounding area. A 25-year-old man sustained second-degree burns
in the blast, which occurred in Wynberg, near Cape Town, while the
two men were in court on charges unrelated to the bombings.  &QL;
</P>
