<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEXSKOL-FUND14-COX     01-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXSKOL-FUND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ethics problems plague Texas school fund
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As State Board of Education members on Thursday
sought to fix ethical and management problems with the $20 billion
Permanent School Fund they oversee, they treaded back into an
ethical dilemma by recommending the hire of a financial consultant
who may have violated a board ethics rule.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Russell Stein, a senior vice president for
First Union Securities, violated the ethics rule, which prohibits
people or businesses from contacting board members as they
deliberate on their contracts. Stein confirmed that he had coffee
with three board members on Thursday morning, including the
chairman and vice chairman of the board committee deciding his
contract. Later Thursday, the committee _ in a split vote _ voted
to hire Stein to evaluate performance of the board's private
money-management firms.
</P>
<P>
   While some board members said that is a clear violation of the
ethics rule, others disagreed, saying Stein was not under the rule
because board members merely were extending his existing contract
rather than hiring him to a new one. His previous contract expired
in November.
</P>
<P>
   The board, during the past year, has been embroiled in factional
fighting _ mostly between its Republican social conservative
members and other Democrats and Republicans _ over management of
the school fund. The acrimony has prompted some state lawmakers to
call for replacing the elected board with an appointed one.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the second time Stein has been accused of violating
the ethics rule. Last fall, he contacted seven board members
through intermediaries as they deliberated on his contract. The
rule aims to prevent influence-peddling by companies seeking board
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Stein in the previous meeting violated our no-contact rule
and I think he recently violated our no-contact rule,'' Democrat
Will Davis told board members Thursday. ``I don't think its
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein said he did not violate the no-contact rule. ``I do not
think I violated the no-contact policy by being at a breakfast
table in a crowded restaurant and Bob Offutt and David Bradley
walking up and sitting down in an open crowded restaurant,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was the lone board member on the five-member committee who
voted against hiring Stein to a three-year contract to evaluate a
dozen investment firms that manage about a third of the Permanent
School Fund. Board Chairman Chase Untermeyer (R-Houston) abstained.
Casting votes in favor of Stein were Offutt, a San Antonio
Republican who chairs the committee; Bradley, a Beaumont Republican
who is vice chair of the committee, and Democrat Joe Bernal of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract approved by the committee, Stein's firm would
be paid about $76,000 a year to evaluate private money managers,
which invest about $7 billion of the school trust fund. The full
15-member board still must vote to the contract with Chicago-based
First Union Securities, which is likely to happen today.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over Stein's contract came as the board took
steps to hire a lead financial consultant to oversee the school
trust fund. The Chicago firm that held the contract quit last year,
citing conflicts and instability on the education board. The
company, Richards and Tierney, however, has bid on the contract.
They said their bid was contingent on the board working out its
conflicts. On Thursday, the fund committee selected six companies _
including Richards and Tierney, as finalists for the contract,
which ranges from $200,000 to $400,000 a year. A final selection is
expected in March. Meanwhile, the House Committee on General
Investigating is examining decisions the board has made regarding
management of the Permanent School Fund, and another Senate
Committee is reviewing its investment policies and practices.
Though the Permanent School Fund, a trust fund that funnels about
$700 million a year to Texas public schools, for decades was
operated quietly and conservatively, it has been plagued by
allegations of mismanagement, influence peddling and ethics
violation for the past several years. The fund consists mostly of
stocks and bonds, as well as oil and gas royalties from public
lands. In 1995, the board hired several private firms to help
manage some of the fund in an effort to maximize investments. The
board increased private money managers to a dozen in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A review by the State Auditor and the Attorney General cleared
money managers of the allegations. The Attorney General review
chided the board for not following its own rules, including the
no-contact ethics rule.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
