<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-TELECOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN'S TELEFONICA TO BUY OUT 4 PHONE COMPANIES IN LATIN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spain's dominant telephone company, Telefonica
SA, said Thursday that it would offer $21.5 billion in stock to buy
out four big phone companies that it already controls in Latin
America, tightening its grip on the region.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica will also realign the Latin American businesses along
product lines, separating the wireless and data units from the four
companies and merging them with the Spanish assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most important operation since Telefonica
became a company,'' said Juan Villalonga, the former state
monopoly's chairman, who oversaw its privatization in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The deal cements Telefonica's position as the leading
communications company in Latin America. It is offering to buy out
shareholders in Telefonica de Argentina SA, Telefonica del Peru SA
and two Brazilian companies, Telesp Participacoes SA, a fixed-line
company in Sao Paulo, and Telesudeste Celular Participacoes SA, a
wireless operator. Telefonica is offering to pay a premium of 40
percent over the average market price for each company during the
five trading days immediately before the deal was announced in
Madrid late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the companies rallied in Latin America after the
announcement, and the broad markets surged too. Investors are
``more likely to go for this than having bits and pieces of the
firms pulled off,'' said Stephen Heaps of Merrill Lynch in London.
</P>
<P>
   The offer, however, did not include Chile's main telephone
concern, Compania Telefonica de Chile, which Telefonica also
controls as the largest shareholder. Villalonga said Chilean law
prohibited an all-stock offer. But some analysts said the decision
was a result of complaints last year from fund managers who said
that Telefonica had paid too little for the Chilean company's
Internet unit, which became part of Telefonica's new Internet
company, Terra Networks. Terra made a rich stock market debut in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, it hardly hurt Chilean Telecom's stock. Its
American depository receipts surged $3, or 16.6 percent, in New
York on Thursday, to $21.125, in heavy trading of 1.75 million
units. Telefonica closed here up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica's board will seek approval Feb. 4 to issue 922
million shares to pay for the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica made its first investments in Chile in 1990 and has
since expanded to seven Latin American countries, including a $6
billion purchase in 1997 in Brazil's telecommunications
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   When the acquisition is complete, expected in four months,
Telefonica will close its Latin American division, and the company
will be organized along product lines.
</P>
<P>
   It has no immediate plans for a share sale in what will be the
new wireless unit, Telefonica Moviles, or the data unit, Telefonica
Datacorp. But another division, Telefonica Media, created late last
year for broadcasting properties in Spain and Latin America, will
be floated this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other companies are segregating their businesses,'' Villalonga
said. ``Increasingly, the interest comes for one or two lines of
the business and not the whole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
