<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TREASURY-DEBT-NYT &LR;      01-13 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURY-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PLANS TO BUY SOME BONDS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Throughout the deficit-plagued 1980s, the Treasury
Department struggled to find novel ways of financing the
government's ballooning daily expenses even as tax receipts fell
further and further behind.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Treasury still has a cash-flow crisis, but of a
different kind: It must figure out what to do with the windfall
cash generated as tax receipts continue to soar above expenses _ at
least until Congress and the White House agree how to spend or
refund the riches.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, outlined on Thursday by Treasury Secretary Lawrence
H. Summers, is to make the Treasury Department for the first time a
buyer as well as a seller of bonds. The Treasury, following some
standard Wall Street tactics, will start intervening in the open
market to manage its $3.6 trillion debt. Not unlike a company's use
of spare cash to buy back its own stock in hopes of propping up the
share price, the government hopes to lower its overall debt
interest payments as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The department plans to use up to $30 billion of surplus cash
this year to buy back outstanding debt, Summers said. It will try
to entice investors to sell old bonds on which the government pays
interest rates that are much higher than the prevailing rates
today. Using spare cash to play the bond market in this way is
unprecedented, senior Treasury officials said, though the
government jumped into the market to swap new debt for old debt in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying back old, higher-interest debt allows us to manage the
federal debt in a way that saves the American taxpayer money,''
Summers said in rolling out the debt buyback program, which was
first broached last summer. ``This is a new and welcome debt
management challenge for the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The program will not be the main way the government reduces its
overall debt. That is done more or less automatically by paying off
investors whose bonds come due without issuing lots of new bonds.
In the last two years _ when the government started generating
surpluses for the first time since the 1960s _ it has reduced debt
by $140 billion in that way.
</P>
<P>
   The new intervention is aimed at accelerating the reduction of
debt and at increasing the trading of the bonds that remain in the
market. By limiting and simplifying the menu of bonds, the
government can increase buying or selling of what is on offer. That
reduces the risk investors take in buying the bonds, and means they
will often accept slightly lower interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of such financial wizardry tend to be measured in
basis points, or hundredths of percentage points. But when the
government has $3.6 trillion in publicly traded debt outstanding,
even a hundredth of a percentage point in savings equals $360
million in taxpayer money that can be used for some other purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials did not predict how much could be saved
through the buyback program, in part because it depends on how the
market reacts. The Treasury would like to buy back bonds paying
nearly 14 percent interest, as some old government issues do, and
force investors to buy newer issues that pay just over 6 percent.
But investors might well choose to hold to the higher-paying bonds,
even if the Treasury offers a nice premium in the open market to
buy them back.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury looks set to have plenty of extra cash to try its
hand at market intervention. After the budget surplus reached $69
billion in 1998 and $123 billion last year, the Congressional
Budget Office is predicting a surplus of $161 billion in fiscal
2000.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
