<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-NEWBERRY14-COX     01-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEWBERRY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Literature industry awaits Newberry contest
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Harry Potter may have cast a spell over the New
York Times Best-Seller List, but in children's bookstores around
the country, they're talking about only one thing this week. Who
will win the big prizes Monday in San Antonio _ the Newbery for
children's literature and the Caldecott for picture books. (The
Coretta Scott King Award for African-American literature is
announced at the same time but doesn't have the same clout in the
market.) Potter's creator, J.K. Rowling _ a Brit through and
through _ isn't eligible for the strictly American award. (No
matter that the name Newbery comes from an 18th-century British
bookseller.)
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, booksellers act like show-biz types just
before the Oscars, calling and e-mailing each other about who's
going to take home the medal (which is bronze, though the seal that
goes on the winning book is gold). Buzz about who will win
dominates list-servers such as Pubyac and Child-lit, where
children's librarians talk up their preferences. And the talk can
be all over the place, since the Newbery finalists aren't known in
advance _ they're announced on the same day as the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit and think about it all the time,'' says Tiffany Durham,
community relations director at Toad Hall children's bookstore.
``When `Holes' (by Austin writer Louis Sachar), which was set in
Texas, won last year, I was surprised. I didn't know if it would
have universal appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachar says his sales have tripled, maybe quadrupled, since he
won the award, and ``Holes'' has been translated into every
language he can think of. ``The Newbery is the one,'' he says.
``It's given me greater recognition as a serious author.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachar's favorite for this year's prize is ``Monster'' by Walter
Dean Myers, the story of a 16-year-old on trial for his supposed
role in shooting a convenience store owner.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about this year's winner includes Texan Kimberly
Willis Holt's ``When Zachary Beaver Came to Town,'' the story of a
13-year-old boy who realizes what is important in life when ``the
fattest boy in the world'' visits his small West Texas town. In
November, ``Zachary Beaver'' won the National Book Award for Young
People, the same award Sachar received before the Newbery. (Some
view the NBAYP as the Golden Globe of children's literature,
occasionally predicting Newbery honors. In 1969 the same book won
both; again in '75, '80 and '98.)
</P>
<P>
   A Publishers Weekly poll of children's booksellers picked Holt's
book for honorable mention _ a silver seal on the book _ along with
Gail Carson Levine's ``Dave at Night,'' a book about a Jewish boy
growing up in a New York orphanage who discovers a wider world in
Harlem. The poll showed Christopher Paul Curtis' ``Bud, Not
Buddy,'' about a 10-year-old African-American boy on the run from
foster homes in search of his father, as Best Bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   Awarded by the Association for Library Service to Children,
Newberys are chosen by a committee of 15 librarians _ half elected
by the association, half appointed by its president. Their names
remain secret until after the awards are made. Committee members
spend a year reading the thousand-plus books submitted. There will
be only one winner; honor books, they stress, are just that _ not
runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The books come in clumps, in spring and late fall,'' says
Austin librarian Jeanette Larsen (of the Texas State Library and
Archives Commission) who served on the Newbery committee in 1991
and 1997. ``Boxes and boxes and boxes arrive. Publishers don't want
to rule anybody out that might have a chance, and they don't want
to offend their authors by not nominating them _ even if they
aren't likely to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members come up with their top three choices twice,
then meet in closed session to talk about their favorites. The
winner must have a certain number of first choice points to get the
medal. ``My favorite may not be the group's first choice to get the
medal, but the winner will be a book I can hold my head up about,''
Larsen says. They meet Friday, Saturday and Sunday at the ALA
midwinter meeting to read, talk and vote. ``It's a lot of fun,
actually,'' Larsen says. ``It's so much fun to sit around and talk
about books.'' The final days are under tight security, with
committee members carrying books in plain brown wrappers so
publishers won't know who the finalists are.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I look for in a Newbery is something distinguished,''
Larsen says. ``Does it hold up? Can I read it two or three times? A
week later, can I tell you anything about the plot? I also look for
inconsistencies. Are the characters believable? Nonfiction is more
difficult. You have to ask if it's telling the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Though such thoroughness means many of the choices are right on
_ 1968 winner ``From the Mixed-Up Files of Mrs. Basil E.
Frankweiler'' and 1961 winner ``Island of the Blue Dolphins'' are
still wildly popular _ not all the decisions have stood the test of
time equally well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little House on the Prairie'' author Laura Ingalls Wilder won
four silver seals, but no gold. Likewise, E.B. White's beloved
``Charlotte's Web'' received only honorable mention, as did the
still popular ``Mr. Popper's Penguins'' _ the book Al Gore says was
his favorite as a child. ``But not many kids would want to read
`The Story of Mankind,' the 1922 Newbery winner,'' Larsen says. And
who's heard of ``Thimble Summer,'' the book that beat out the
penguins? Perusing a list of past winners, Louis Sachar admits that
``most of them I haven't heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Several winners and honor books enjoy additional fame because
they have gone on to become movies or television shows, such as
``Sarah Plain and Tall'' (1986), ``Mrs. Frisby and the Rats of
NIMH'' (1972), and ``Sounder'' (1970). ``Miracles on Maple Hill''
won the gold Newbery in 1957, but today more people recognize Texan
Fred Gipson's Honor Book ``Old Yeller,'' which was made into a
classic film.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Todaro, head librarian at the Rio Grande branch of Austin
Community College, served on the committee in '78-'79. ``Publishers
who were members of the American Library Association originated the
award (in 1921),'' Todaro says, though it was first given in 1922.
``They were trying to increase the number of people interested in
writing quality children's books. It's not a popularity award.
You're looking for quality. No one says the kids will love it.''
Sometimes they do. Sometimes they don't. (My son tells me that at
his school the student nickname for required reading ``Roll of
Thunder, Hear My Cry,'' the 1977 Newbery winner, was ROT.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the market change dramatically,'' Todaro says. In
the early years there were lots of animal books (``Smoky,''
``Animal Family,'' ``Misty,'' ``Old Yeller,'') and more recently,
books written as journals. ``The awards reflect the best of what is
being written for children at that particular time. But in terms of
a life, some stand out more than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
