<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-HURRICANE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Washington's passion powers `Hurricane' story
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Here comes the story of the Hurricane,'' Bob
Dylan sings in the ballad he wrote for middleweight boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter when the African-American fighter was
wrongfully imprisoned in the 1960s for the murder of three people
in a New Jersey tavern.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Dylan no longer performs ``Hurricane'' in
concert, but actor Denzel Washington brings Carter's tale to the
screen with the same impassioned delivery that makes Dylan's song,
written to benefit Carter's legal defense, so mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane'' also picks up where Dylan's song left off,
with Carter serving three consecutive life terms, writing his
autobiography ``The Sixteenth Round,'' enduring numerous twists and
turns as a result of ongoing legal battles and finally meeting
Lesra Martin (Vicellous Reon Shannon), the young man with whom
Carter would forge a profound and life-sustaining friendship.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial amount of this story takes place within the
confines of a jail cell as we watch Carter try to impose an
athlete's discipline upon the initial chaos and eventual monotony
that define prison life. Extended stays in solitary confinement eat
away at the boxer, producing wrenching scenes of Carter fighting
for his sanity. Veteran cinematographer Roger Deakins (``Dead Man
Walking,'' ``Fargo'') perfectly captures the mood of these prison
sequences with appropriately claustrophobic shots and a roving
camera that tracks Carter's internal journey from spiritual peace
to despair and back again.
</P>
<P>
   As Carter writes his autobiography, the story flashes back to
the events that led up to his arrest. While these scenes suggest
that Carter enjoyed a certain amount of respect and local celebrity
as a result of his promising boxing career, they also reveal the
prejudices that shadowed Carter's daily life, particularly as they
related to Vincent Della Pesca (Dan Hedaya), a corrupt New Jersey
detective.
</P>
<P>
   Della Pesca's presence in the story raises the issue of creative
license, which director Norman Jewison (``Moonstruck'') and
screenwriters Armyan Bernstein (``One From the Heart'') and Dan
Gordon (``Murder in the First'') make liberal use of in order to
dramatize certain events. Della Pesca is a fictional character who
represents many detectives and police officers associated with
Carter's ongoing case. In an otherwise restrained narrative, Della
Pesca's malevolence becomes a little too hokey, as does the
presence of Martin's do-gooder Canadian guardians, who assist their
charge in establishing contact with the imprisoned boxer.
</P>
<P>
   It's often refreshing to watch a movie, particularly one based
on actual events, in which the director and screenwriter allow a
certain amount of ambiguity to creep into characterizations and
actions within the story. For instance, ``The Hurricane'' suggests
ever so slightly that like any person, Carter had his vices, which
nicely humanizes the character without passing judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Other ambiguities are better left alone, such as the subtle
tension that runs between Carter and Martin's guardian Lisa Peters
(Deborah Kara Unger) later in the film. In reality, Carter and
Peters married after his release from prison, but in the film,
their interaction is reduced to a distracting blip in an otherwise
focused story.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers interested in seeing an accurate chronology of Carter's
life will find greater satisfaction in his autobiography and the
book ``Lazarus and the Hurricane,'' co-written by Sam Chaiton and
Terry Swinton (played in the film by Liev Schreiber and John
Hannah) about Martin's relationship with Carter and the Canadian
group's successful efforts to overturn his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But for those viewers looking for a stirring, intense account of
one man's fight for justice, ``The Hurricane'' delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
