<HEADER>
A5616 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-MOTHER14-COX     01-13 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MOTHER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mother' rescued by its mostly female cast
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``All About My Mother,'' Pedro Almodovar's big
sloppy kiss to womanhood, has been greeted with effusive valentines
from critics who commend Spain's bad-boy director for crystallizing
his old thematic passions with fresh, grown-up aplomb. Some have
called it his best film. It's not.
</P>
<P>
   There's no disputing the skill and feeling with which Almodovar
paints this emotionally charged comic melodrama, and he has few
peers when it comes to inspiring actresses to greatness.
``Mother,'' opening today at the Arbor, is an accomplished,
sometimes affecting work brimming with fine performances by an
(almost) all-female cast. There's a lot to admire. Almodovar fans
shouldn't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Mother'' demonstrates that Almodovar hasn't grown up much
at all. He still cleaves to a teen-age boy's view of women that's
awash in romanticized sexism. He worships women _ for their
indomitable spirit, their maternal virtue, their beauty and their
knack for camp. His idealism moves him so far as to see
transvestism as a sort of divine transfiguration, something perhaps
to be envied. (While he turns women into saints, at least he
doesn't turn them into Madonnas. The puckish filmmaker equally
adores angel-whores _ all manner of sassy misfit.)
</P>
<P>
   Maudlin nobility has little place in good art, and ``Mother''
suffers from Almodovar's woozy regard for his characters. It feels
like a mature work, but I think that's a response to how confident
a filmmaker Almodovar is. Unlike his ``Women on the Verge of a
Nervous Breakdown,'' ``Tie Me Up! Tie Me Down!'' and 1998's
superior ``Live Flesh,'' the new movie never seems poised to spin
out of control, which would suit his florid fawning. It's more
contained, less intoxicating and, finally, one of his least
interesting films.
</P>
<P>
   We instantly know we've entered Almodovar terrain. ``Mother'' is
drenched in those famous Skittles primaries. The sun-splashed
apartments gleam with the rainbow-y innocence of a preschool. What
goes on inside, of course, are matters for a higher grade and
darker hue.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its title and thematic cues from ``All About Eve,'' that
catty celebration of femme fortitude and backstage bickering,
``Mother'' lurches from comic fizz to emotional arias that are
sometimes so wrenching they're hard to watch. Despite the grave
undertones, Almodovar is a feel-good artist, and the sorrow-pocked
laughs come liberally, justifying the movie's Day-Glo palette.
</P>
<P>
   When tragedy strikes a mother and her teen-age son, the
distraught mother, Manuela (Cecilia Roth, who's spectacular),
leaves her Madrid home for Barcelona, seeking her ex-husband to
tell him what has happened to the son he never knew. There she
reunites with an old friend, the haggard but saucy transvestite
prostitute Agrado (a tartly funny Antonia San Juan, whose face, an
asymmetrical jumble, looks like it was hit by an earthquake).
</P>
<P>
   As the women encounter a young pregnant nun (Penelope Cruz) and
a flinty but compassionate stage actress (a wonderfully seasoned
Marisa Paredes), we see how all of their lives are variously
entwined by coincidence and fate, forging among them a predestined
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   Though bawdy humor and points of great poignancy dot the way,
the story's strained serendipity is a bit much. It's too humid and
precious to be taken seriously and denies us full emotional
involvement. Almodovar is working with shopworn archetypes _ the
broken mother, the kooky friend and the Bette Davis-esque theater
queen straight out of ``Eve'' _ and employs them in a schematic
melodrama that doesn't flow so much as clunk. (When a key character
dies, it's handled too hastily to register with us.)
</P>
<P>
   The wealth of roles women must assume to get through life's
hardships is Almodovar's central theme. Survival through cunning is
the province of women _ an idea embodied in the film's
transvestitactresses _ but the artifice is piled on so
gleefully, it's hard to get to the beating heart of the message.
Almodovar kills us with kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
