A5619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-GIRL14-COX     01-13 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GIRL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A poignant struggle revives a life `Interrupted'By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _The title of ``Girl, Interrupted,'' the moving
film based on Susanna Kaysen's memoir about her experiences in a
psychiatric hospital, comes from Dutch artist Jan Vermeer's
painting, ``Girl Interrupted at Her Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaysen reveals this with two separate anecdotes, and through her
words we understand the changes she has undergone between the time
she first saw the painting as a 14-year-old and when she viewed it
as an adult after spending nearly two years in McLean Hospital in
Massachusetts in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdotes are absent from James Mangold's film, but the
transformation comes across quite powerfully in Winona Ryder's
portrayal of Kaysen. Ryder subtly conveys that a change has taken
place from when we first see her heading in a cab toward the
imposing brick hospital (named Claymoore in the movie) and at the
end of the film, when she is riding away in the same taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest challenge for Mangold and co-screenwriters
Lisa Loomer and Anna Hamilton Phelan was adapting Kaysen's episodic
autobiography into three acts. The movie occasionally suffers
because of this, particularly during dramatic moments manufactured
for climactic purposes. In the film, Susanna becomes more of a
goal-oriented heroine and less of an enlightened voice leading us
through her sometimes hellish but often poignant experiences.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ``Girl, Interrupted'' effectively preserves some of the
book's tone through its creative use of flashbacks, linked to the
present by sound bridges that match snippets of dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   After the movie begs off its interminable close-ups of Ryder's
huge dark eyes, we can appreciate her intense but restrained
performance. After attempting suicide with a bottle of aspirin and
a vodka chaser, Susanna's introduction to the other young women at
Claymoore is frightening enough to emphasize the troubling limbo
she occupies, while also revealing that she could be worse off
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   At Claymoore we meet Lisa, the ward's most intriguing resident
and possibly its most far gone. Played with characteristic passion
by Angelina Jolie, Lisa is not unlike the charismatic R.P. McMurphy
that Jack Nicholson made famous in ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangold makes good use of the movie's supporting cast to offer a
more nuanced, gently humorous portrait of the hospital. Worth
noting is Brittany Murphy's Daisy, an incest survivor who collects
chicken carcasses and talks endlessly about the small apartment her
father has purchased for her with its one bedroom and _ the most
Freudian of slips _ an ``eat-in chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaysen's memoir begins with the observation that it's easy to
wind up in a place like Claymoore. ``Girl, Interrupted'' shows us
how, with feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
