<SLUG> BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RICHER MIX OF CHIPS HELPS INTEL EXCEED EXPECTED PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After three quarters of results that
disappointed investors, Intel Corp. on Thursday posted
fourth-quarter earnings that exceeded Wall Street's expectations
because of strong demand for personal computers and a shift toward
higher-performance chips with better profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company soared in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Intel reported net income of $2.11 billion, or
61 cents a diluted share, up 2 percent from $2.06 billion, or 59
cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Revenue rose 8
percent, to $8.21 billion from $7.61 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding charges and costs related to acquisitions, profit was
$2.4 billion, or 69 cents a share, up 15 percent from $2.08
billion, or 60 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
Analysts had expected Intel to earn 63 cents a share, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Intel had earnings of $7.31 billion, or $2.11 a
diluted share, up 21 percent from $6.07 billion, or $1.73 a share,
in 1998. Revenue rose 12 percent, to $29.39 billion from $26.27
billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Before Intel reported its results, its shares fell 18.75 cents,
to $91.0625. But in after-hours trading, they rose as high as
$96.125.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's strong results defied some predictions that the company
would fall short again because of an inability to deliver chips in
adequate numbers. That speculation gained credence earlier this
month when Gateway said its earnings would fall short, in large
part because the computer maker could not get enough chips from
Intel. Gateway subsequently said it would begin buying some chips
from Intel's archrival, Advanced Micro Devices Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually a quarter that was just as solid and a little
bit better than we expected,'' Andy Bryant, Intel's chief financial
officer, said in an interview. While he would not comment
specifically on Gateway, Bryant said, ``From our point of view, we
met all of our product commitments to customers during the
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said Intel expected the favorable market for PC's to
continue this quarter but revenue would be down slightly from the
fourth quarter because of seasonal trends.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest quarter, analysts said, Intel was faced with
supply constraints and effectively shifted production to
higher-performance chips from those that Gateway wanted. The
strength of the overall PC market, and Intel's dominance within
that market, meant Intel was able to sell these higher-priced chips
and reap higher revenues and profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth quarter for Intel was about solid PC demand and
Intel's ability to drive a richer mix of products,'' said Mark
Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``I think
they had to struggle to keep up with demand and in that kind of
environment you're going to try to manage your mix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
