<HEADLINE>
TAKING ACTION TO FIND HER OWN FEMALE IDENTITY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Michael Rush's book ``New Media in Late 20th-Century Art'' was just
published by Thames and Hudson.  
 By MICHAEL RUSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some 20 years before Karen Finley smeared herself with chocolate
to express her outrage over the brutal treatment of women's bodies
and 30 years before Eve Ensler started delivering her ``Vagina
Monologues,'' Valie Export cut the crotch out of her jeans and
walked into a Munich art-film house known for showing sexually
explicit films. Parading up and down the aisles in a performance
action titled ``Genitalpanik,'' she dared the cowering, mostly male
devotees to look at a real body.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1950s, Ms. Export has been challenging images of
the female body in media through her own prodigious output of
videos, films, performances, photographs, installations,
documentaries and writings.
</P>
<P>
   Represented in scores of exhibitions in Europe since the 1970s,
the 59-year-old artist is only now receiving her first solo
exhibition in the United States, from Tuesday through Feb. 27 at
the Goldie Paley Gallery of the Moore College of Art and Design in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Linz, Austria, Ms. Export arrived in Vienna at the
height of what has been called Viennese Actionism, a 1960s movement
of radical performance artists (Otto Muehl, Gunter Brus, Hermann
Nitsch, Rudolf Schwarzkogler) known for graphic body mutilations
and for protests that landed some of them in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Repulsed by war, resenting the continued reverberations of
Nazism and rejecting the lionization of Modernist artists, the
movement sought to insult the pretensions of art and society
through brutal performances that unleashed unconscious impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Export was not technically a part of the group, it
was in this environment that she developed her own brand of what
she called Feminist Actionism, partly in response to the male
Viennese gang of four's often blatant misogyny. ``All my works are
self-portraits,'' she says, including one of her first ones, the
changing of her name from Waltraud Hollinger to Valie Export in
1967. ``I no longer wanted the name of my father or my former
husband; I wanted my own, easily recognizable name, which could
also be a logo for my art.''
</P>
<P>
   So she made a nickname out of Waltraud (Valie) and appropriated
the name of a popular cigarette brand, Export, as the ``perfect
expression of my desire to export my inner ideas outside into the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Export, now a professor of multimedia performance at the
University of Media Art in Cologne, Germany, relates the
development of her early work to the international style of art she
encountered at an exhibition in Sweden in the mid-'60s, where she
saw performances by John Cage, artworks by Arnulf Rainer and the
Fluxus artist Dick Higgins, and the avant-garde films of Michael
Snow and Hollis Frampton.
</P>
<P>
   She mentions only male artists, but only because there were so
few female models at the time. She and a loose multinational
consortium including Carolee Schneemann, Adrian Piper and Joan
Jonas from the United States, Niki de Saint Phalle (France), Ulrike
Rosenbach (Germany), Friederike Pezold (Austria) and Lygia Clark
(Brazil), to name a few, were the pioneers who inspired current
artists like Janine Antoni, Pipilotti Rist, Mona Hatoum and Zhang
Huan.
</P>
<P>
   What's striking about Ms. Export, in addition to her longevity
in what has often been a hostile art environment, is her
extraordinary diversity. Though feminism was her springboard, her
artistic investigations reveal a deep knowledge of psychoanalysis,
linguistics, literature (especially Gertrude Stein, Virginia Woolf,
Antonin Artaud and Samuel Beckett) and the history of art,
expressed in a dizzying collection of work in many mediums.
</P>
<P>
   Her early photographic work (several samples of which will be on
display in a separate exhibition from Jan. 23 through March 4 at
Klemens Gasser and Tanja Grunert Gallery in Manhattan reveals a
keen interest in conceptual relationships between architecture and
the body. With the eye of a Berenice Abbott, she photographed
trains, street corners and edges of buildings, and injected her own
particular sensibility by putting her body on the ledge of a
staircase or curved around the corner of a street, as if to assert
the self in an anonymous urban environment.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the 30-year retrospective at Moore College are 60
posters made in conjunction with the ``Genitalpanik'' action, a
24-monitor video installation of sewing-machine needles pumping up
and down, and Ms. Export's award-winning experimental film,
``Syntagma'' (1983), containing a kaleidoscopic array of images
that explore a woman's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Elsa Long-hauser, the gallery's director, the
exhibition is part of Moore's International Discovery series, a
biannual survey of work from lesser-known international artists.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why she thought Ms. Export was so little recognized
here, Ms. Long-hauser said her situation was not unique: ``If
you're not part of a fashionable trajectory, for whatever reason,
the system can pass you by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
