<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-SPEECH-AR     01-13 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-SPEECH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TURNS SHOWMAN IN BROAD STATE OF CITY ADDRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In front of a lush, eye-popping backdrop of the Times
Square New Year's Eve celebration, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani delivered
a theatrical State of the City address on Thursday that was both a
reprise of what he considers his greatest triumphs and an effort to
impose his legacy on New York City far into the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The speech often sounded like a long goodbye, but at other times
like the first words of Giuliani's undeclared U.S. Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be my last State of the City speech,'' Giuliani
said at the beginning, before a packed City Council chamber of
invited supporters and television cameras. He concluded nearly an
hour and 40 minutes later with a wistful ``I'm never going to have
a better job,'' then added, ``I've loved it tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Giuliani defeat his expected Senate opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, he will have only a year left as mayor. If he
loses, he will have only two years left, because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made some of his most striking proposals in education,
which is also his most vulnerable area with voters. His plans
included the proposed sale of 110 Livingston St., the Board of
Education's legendary and ramshackle headquarters in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   At first, many listeners thought he was joking, but he meant it
seriously, even as he made light of his remarks last year that the
Board of Education should be ``blown up.'' His aides acknowledged
later that the board would have to approve the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that for now he wanted to move the board _ his
ultimate dream is to abolish it entirely _ to a more modern,
``smart'' building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also made one of his most aggressive attacks yet on the
city's teachers, saying they do not deserve an across-the-board pay
raise in coming negotiations, but rather salary increases based on
merit.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor particularly singled out the teachers' union, which is
expected to support Mrs. Clinton in the Senate race, for what he
called its ``job protection system.''
</P>
<P>
   He added with extravagant disgust and a touch of bitter
amusement that children who attended the city's summer schools
actually saw their reading scores decline.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth year that the mayor dispensed with a lectern
and teleprompter and instead delivered his address ambling around a
small stage without notes.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the speech, the mayor prepared for the event
with Elliot Cuker, an acting coach. While it made for a far more
watchable delivery, the textless presentation did cause the mayor
to forget a major proposal his aides had disclosed to reporters on
Wednesday: $2 billion in commercial and business tax cuts over the
next four years.
</P>
<P>
   After concluding with a plea that the residents of New York
``should never give in and, please God, we should never turn back
to the way we were,'' Giuliani suddenly came back to the stage and
announced that Peter F. Vallone, the City Council speaker, had just
asked him what had happened to the tax cuts. Giuliani announced
them quickly, then began an encore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art of leadership in this city is saying,'' Giuliani said,
``yes, it can be done in the greatest city in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani neglected few areas of his administration in a
sprawling list of plans for what he described as a city enjoying a
renaissance brought on by him.
</P>
<P>
   Although many ideas were reiterations of previous plans nicely
dressed for the occasion, and most need approval from either the
City Council, the State Legislature or the Port Authority, three
new proposals stood out: a state-of-the-art laboratory for DNA
testing of people suspected of crimes; an ``aggressive driving''
program that would take away the cars of people arrested for not
just drunken driving but reckless driving; and the addition of up
to 200 heat-seeking infrared cameras to help firefighters determine
the source of a blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also proposed extensive redevelopment projects around
the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
