<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER14-COX     01-13 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pitcher gets heavyweight advice
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baseball officials may not yet have decided what to do
with Braves relief pitcher John Rocker. But they can be assured he
had his own private diversity training Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The same day the Atlanta chapter of the NAACP spoke out against
Rocker, he sat cross-legged and wide-eyed in a chair in the living
room of Andrew Young, one of the most influential leaders in the
city's, and nation's, civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who made millions of enemies by spouting inflammatory
remarks to a Sports Illustrated reporter last month, took comfort
in Young's reassurances. He also took advice from the former
Atlanta mayor on how to deal with hatred.
</P>
<P>
   And that was only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Rocker broke his silence in a nationally telecast
interview with Peter Gammons of ESPN, the man now labeled a racist
by much of the nation spent the afternoon seeking and receiving
support from Young, being pleasantly surprised by a visit from
former NBA star Isiah Thomas and facing Hank Aaron, the home run
king who'd spoken out adamantly against Rocker when the Sports
Illustrated article was released.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker walked out of Young's Atlanta home Thursday afternoon and
headed to Aaron's BMW dealership in south Atlanta, clutching a copy
of Young's book, ``An Easy Burden,'' about the civil rights
movement. Inside the front cover, in Young's handwriting, were the
words: ``John Rocker, Welcome to the struggle. Keep faith, Andrew
Young.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta way has been, we do make mistakes, none of us is
perfect, but we've got to learn to live together,'' Young said.
``Nobody's going anywhere. When we make mistakes, we help each
other up.''
</P>
<P>
   Young had counseled Rocker in an Atlanta Journal-Constitution
editorial, which caught the attention of Macon Mayor Jack Ellis,
who had offered Rocker his support. Ellis contacted Young and that
set off an afternoon of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker met Ellis and his father, Jake Rocker, in a KFC parking
lot off the freeway in South Atlanta and they drove over to Young's
home.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Rocker had stopped on the way from Macon to buy Rocker a
foot-long turkey sub sandwich. By the time Jake Rocker left to
drive back to Macon after 6 p.m. on Thursday evening, the sandwich
was still in the front seat of his sports-utility vehicle,
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Young greeted Rocker and company at his back door, ushered them
into his living room and got to the point quickly after exchanging
handshakes and hellos.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see happening is something I guess all of us has to
learn, and that's you can't let people make you mad,'' Young said.
``My dad always said if you lose your temper in a fight, you'll
always lose the fight. The main thing you did was you let him get
your goat and let him get you ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can stay in control of your temper, you can stay in
control of your situation. I think you made a mistake. I don't
think anyone has a right to condemn you for that. I don't think
there's anyone that can say he lost his temper so he doesn't have a
right to play. I think if you keep losing your temper, you won't be
able to play. I think that's what New York fans do to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Young had to say centered on how Rocker should
handle himself from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be picketing,'' Young said. ``Martin Luther King, when
he was picketed, he never tried to speak to them directly. In his
mind, he'd say, `I'm going to convince those people in my speech
that what they have on their signs is not true.'''
</P>
<P>
   Young told Rocker stories from when Young lived in New York and
had a New York reporter say to him: ``You don't think the South
African government is legitimate, do you?'' Young said he responded
``no'' and the headlines in the next morning's paper were ``Young
attacks South African government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to learn the ways of dealing with the press,''
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Young suggested Rocker enlist the support of his teammates who
are minorities, encouraged Rocker's efforts to contact his
teammates and urged him to let his actions speak louder than any
words. He applauded the fact that Rocker was playing in a celebrity
softball tournament this weekend in Miami, with former Brave Dennis
Martinez, to benefit hurricane relief for Nicaragua. Rocker also
played in the event last year.
</P>
<P>
   After about 20 minutes, they were greeted by Thomas, now a
businessman interested in creating a minor league basketball league
with a team in Rocker's hometown. Thomas was on his way to Macon
when he found out Rocker was meeting with Young in Atlanta and
asked if he could come by.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who got into a racial public relations mess himself when
he made a disparaging remark about Larry Bird, dropped in, along
with former Atlanta Hawk Michael Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas greeted Rocker with his patented perfect smile and reeled
him in from a handshake to a bear hug. They immediately fell into
conversation about a common friend in the minor leagues and about
sports. As the conversation moved into the sitting area, Young
turned it to more serious topics. Thomas chipped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a good opportunity for you,'' Thomas told
Rocker. ``You have the opportunity to really talk about how
diversity and inclusiveness is what sports are all about.''
</P>
<P>
   After about 20 to 30 minutes, Thomas got up to leave, first
stopping to talk with Jake Rocker. Thomas hugged the older man and,
as he did, said, ``There's a bigger fight to fight than this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker and his father and Young then left for Aaron's BMW
dealership, where Aaron and Rocker spoke privately for nearly 25
minutes in Aaron's glassed-in office in the showroom.
</P>
<P>
   As members of the news media multiplied outside the doors of the
dealership, Rocker and Aaron came out of the office and went into a
conference room, joining a larger group that included Young, his
publicist Lee Echols and Jake Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly another half-hour, the men discussed Rocker's
situation and what his approach should be. Several times during the
discussion they glanced at a reporter and asked that certain
comments be off the record.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Jake Rocker described how he and his wife, Judy,
had struggled with this situation. As he spoke, John Rocker put his
hands to his head, and Aaron nodded without speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron told Rocker a story of taking abuse from a fan during his
minor league days in Macon, where Aaron broke the color barrier in
the South Atlantic League. He told Rocker how he always tried to
keep his reactions to himself, to lean on his teammates, to laugh
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that I'm giving him advice in doing is in
trying to get his life back together again,'' Aaron said after the
meeting. ``What he said was very offensive. And I told him it's
something that it's hard for me to forgive. But I'm glad I had the
chance to talk with (him). ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Who am I not to forgive? I don't mind forgiving. But I want
people to understand if I did something wrong, then admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Rocker admit it to Aaron?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Aaron said. ``He said, 'I was wrong, what I said.' But
he doesn't know how to say it. And the way he said it on ESPN with
Peter Gammons was not the way to say it. He just put more fuel on
the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said Rocker was much more convincing in person, and that
he believed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to learn more about him, but I do forgive him,''
Aaron said. When asked whether he should be playing for the Braves
this season, Aaron said, ``I didn't say that. I don't know what
they should do with him.''
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Jake Rocker told Aaron about how good it
made him feel when a group of school boys, all black, had waved at
John as he turned the corner driving his silver Corvette, with
Andrew Young riding shotgun, on their way to the dealership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, I think it was my car,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker may or may not be a racist, but he is a realist. Time
will tell what others decide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
