A5633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER-BRAVES14-C     01-13 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-BRAVES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker gains some player support
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Both drafted in the summer of 1994, they took almost
all the steps together, from West Palm Beach, Fla.; Eugene and
Macon, Ga., and Durham, N.C. John Rocker and George Lombard were
teammates in the Atlanta Braves' minor league system for much of
the past decade. As the Braves' closer attempts to extricate
himself from the mess he created, Lombard has six years experience
by which to judge him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people John is out there,'' Lombard said Thursday.
``He's got that closer mentality and he's a crazy guy. He has been
since that first day I met him down in West Palm. But I mean, he's
from a good family. I've spent the night over at his house, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lombard, who has resumed workouts in town after a month in the
Venezuelan winter league, is one of the few teammates Rocker has
reached to discuss his racially charged comments in Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first comment to him, when he called, was `Well, John, you
know how to keep yourself in the media.' That was the ice
breaker,'' Lombard said. ``But I told him he's got himself in a
little bit of a hole here. That was right before he sat down with
ESPN and he hopes this will help him out.''
</P>
<P>
   So, did it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was definitely in favor of John,'' Lombard said.
``I thought Peter Gammons did a good job helping him out. After
some of the things that were said, it's going to be hard to win
back a lot of the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Rocker's first public appearance from his home in El
Centro, Calif., relief pitcher Rudy Seanez took special interest.
During his rookie season, the two filled the same role as setup
men. Seanez has spoken with him twice, but not since his first TV
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it went OK,'' Seanez said. ``It's like anything. You
can't satisfy everyone and I think no matter what he does, there
are still going to be some people questioning him. He maybe could
have made some things more clear. But that's Rocker.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Braves initially doubted Rocker's future with the
club, Seanez already anticipates Rocker's opportunity to meet with
the entire team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope it all gets done in one shot,'' Seanez said.
``Have a closed-door meeting with all the players and get everyone
in there and take however long it takes to get it all out. Then
once those doors open back up, that's it. Get on with the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
