<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MICH-BOY-SENTENCED-2N     01-13 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-BOY-SENTENCED-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PONTIAC, Mich.: as adults. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one nationally publicized case, Kip Kinkel was sentenced in
November in Portland, Ore., to more than 111 years in prison
without possibility of parole for having fatally shot his parents
and two fellow high school students when he was 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   There has been only one other case in Oakland County of
prosecutors' recommending a combination of juvenile and adult
crime. Moore also presided in that recent case, which involved a
home invasion by another offender who committed the crime at the
age of 16, Mrs. Halushka said. The offender, who was white,
received a six-month sentence in a county jail after he reached the
age of 18 in a juvenile detention center without showing that he
had been rehabilitated, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger welcomed Moore's decision, but said he would proceed with
his plan to appeal the jury's verdict last November. Nathaniel, who
wore a brown and gray shirt with khaki trousers, was expressionless
during the sentencing, but another of his lawyers, Daniel Bagdade,
said he had his hand on Nathaniel's shoulder and could feel his
client trembling.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, Bagdade said, ``Nate looked up at me and the
first words out of his mouth were, `What happened?''' Nathaniel
will turn 14 next week, but psychologists testified at his trial
that he was mentally and emotionally impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's relatives had varying reactions to the verdict. His
grandmother, Joanne Hayden, reacted calmly when the sentence was
read but a minute later leaned against a wall outside the courtroom
and began weeping while loudly crying, ``Oh, Ronnie, Oh, Ronnie,
Oh, my boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Hayden, the dead man's uncle, said he believed Nathaniel
should have received a combination of a juvenile and adult
sentence. Hayden also said that Michigan's law on young offenders
should remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel is black, as was Greene, and the case here has drawn
national attention from civil rights activists. Fieger and these
activists have contended that Nathaniel would have been treated
differently in this mostly white county if he were also white _ a
contention that Mrs. Halushka rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred protesters showed up for the hearing, with many
of them standing in wind-driven snow outside the courtroom, beating
drums and chanting slogans like ``Nathaniel, we love you.'' One of
the protest's leaders, the Rev. Al Sharpton of New York, said after
the sentencing that while he was pleased that Nathaniel would not
be sent to prison, he still believed that Nathaniel should have
been acquitted and that Michigan's juvenile justice laws should be
rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge said some strong and courageous things _ he
convicted the system but he incarcerated Nathaniel,'' Sharpton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 64, has a national reputation as an experienced and
respected juvenile court judge. He was first elected as a juvenile
court judge in a countywide race in 1966, and has won every
reelection campaign since then, usually running unopposed; his
current, six-year term will not expire until the end of 2004. Moore
succeeded his father, Judge Arthur Eugene Moore, on the juvenile
court bench, and his father's portrait still hangs in the county
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Moore ``leans toward more lenient sentences,'' Mrs. Halushka
said. But in this heavily Republican county on the northern edge of
Detroit, the judge makes occasional appearances at Republican
fund-raisers, she said, while adding that elections for judges are
non-partisan and Moore ``is not super-political.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
