<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RECKLESS-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI VOWS TO SEIZE VEHICLES OF RECKLESS DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning next week, people accused of driving recklessly in New
York City will face misdemeanor charges and the forfeiture of their
cars, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown, which the mayor announced in his State of the
City address, will be modeled after the city's policy of seizing
the vehicles of people arrested on charges of driving while drunk,
a controversial practice that has withstood court challenges so
far. The mayor said the expanded effort was necessary because
traffic deaths had increased sharply in the city last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get arrested for reckless driving to the point where we
charge you with a misdemeanor, we're going to take your automobile
from you,'' the mayor said. ``And we're going to take it from you
because we're entitled to it and because it'll remind you that this
is important. This kills people. It also kills you.''
</P>
<P>
   To enforce the new policy, the Police Department has equipped 25
patrol cars with front- and rear-mounted video cameras, which will
be used to record speeding cars as they approach and then pass the
police.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that officers would be
posted in problem areas, and that the videotapes they recorded
would be used to buttress cases in court. He declined to disclose
any of the crackdown's planned sites.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, officers will be instructed to look for
indicators of danger when considering whether to arrest drivers or
merely give them a traffic citation.
</P>
<P>
   The threshold will be crossed, Safir said, any time a vehicle is
seen performing three dangerous moves or moving at twice the posted
speed limit. For the purpose of enforcement, reckless moves will
include weaving in and out of lanes, following vehicles too closely
or entering shoulders to pass other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a state law that defines reckless driving as
driving that ``unreasonably interferes with the free and proper use
of a public highway'' or that ``unreasonably endangers'' others,
the commissioner acknowledged that the law gave the police much
latitude. But he said enforcement would be reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to necessarily seize a vehicle that is doing
30 miles per hour in a 15-mile zone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Giuliani's policy drew a strong response from the
New York Civil Liberties Union. Norman Siegel, the organization's
director, said it was ``unfair and excessive'' and would probably
lead to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to challenge initiatives that basically hang
you first and try you later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While civil libertarians objected to the seizures, the
announcement was praised by advocates for walkers and bikers who
have long complained that the city was too soft on reckless
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the police truly target driving that endangers pedestrians
and cyclists, this could start a renaissance for nonmotorized
travel in New York,'' said Charles Komanoff, who heads Right of
Way, a pedestrian rights group. ``Maybe ordinary New Yorkers, not
just daredevils, will finally be able to ride a bike and feel
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Police were unable to provide fatality statistics related to
reckless driving, but said that even though alcohol-related
fatalities fell, the total number of traffic deaths in the city
rose, to 416 last year from 367 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
