<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LISTEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LISTEN UP!: Startup guides fans through the wide world of
online  music  
 (Eds.: With MUSIC-LISTEN-HOW and MUSIC-LISTEN-PICKS)  
 By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ The urbane, exposed-brick offices of the San
Francisco startup Listen.com are decorated with kitsch. Action
figures brandish swords and stun guns atop computer terminals. A
Village People eight-track tape lies on one desktop; a Sammy Davis
Jr. LP is lovingly displayed on another.
</P>
<P>
   For the youthful employees of Listen.com, the action figures
represent the need for lightning-quick reflexes in the brave new
cartoon world of dot-coms. The vintage records and eight-tracks, on
the other hand, represent creaky ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the future of recorded music appears to be in the
online download of music files _ MP3s, or some similar digital
distribution system. In less time than it takes to make and break a
teen pop sensation, Listen.com has established itself as the
pre-eminent authority on the music industry's latest wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com is a sort of Yellow Pages of online music, with links
to existing music files that it updates and reviews daily. The
company, which started its Web site in June, has already amassed a
directory of nearly 40,000 artists who have songs available online.
</P>
<P>
   Stamping itself as the only authority on the subject, the
company has just released ``Listen Picks,'' a CD compilation of
some of the staff's favorite downloadable songs, by established
bands (Pavement, Public Enemy, Kelly Willis) and relative unknowns
(Astronaut Wife, Crooked Fingers, Supreme Beings of Leisure).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a record store _ we're the cool guys in the record
store who know where everything is,'' says Tim Quirk, former leader
of the band Too Much Joy and a free-lance writer who has gone
``straight'' as a Listen.com reviews editor.
</P>
<P>
   The company, still privately held, has already taken on $35
million from key investors such as Sony Music. Chris Blackwell,
founder of Island Records, recently joined the board of directors.
The company has business partnerships with just about every online
music site of note, including MP3.com, Emusic, Liquid Audio and
Riffage.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company operates as a ``portal point,'' like Yahoo, with
revenue generated from ad sales and referral fees paid by its
partner music sites. A former publisher of Us magazine was recently
hired as vice president of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, Listen.com has grown from a few dozen employees to
more than 100. Based on the city's Potrero Hill, along a stretch of
Web-related music offices now dubbed Audio Alley, it is preparing
to expand into an adjacent building, a former metal-bending plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a compound pretty soon,'' says Editor in
Chief Nick Tangborn.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen-style office space is a lot quieter than might be
expected. Staff members are buried in computer terminals and
headphones, each listening to the latest download in his ``queue''
and pecking out reviews.
</P>
<P>
   With 20 reviewers and 35 total editorial staffers _ many of them
DJs or members of local bands such as I Am Spoonbender, Mover and
Blue Sky Roadster _ the company says it might have the largest
full-time music editorial team anywhere. (Music magazines such as
Rolling Stone have large teams of editors, of course, but use
mostly free-lance writers.)
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Bardeen, a 26-year-old reviewer in braids and stocking
feet, has a reputation as one of the company's sassier writers.
``We try to give the music a fair assessment, not just spiral into
gratuitous violence on the music,'' she says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Among her recent discoveries: the Egyptian singing star Oum
Kaltoum (``nobody realized she was basically the main classical
Arabic singer'') and the Drs. Clarke, a pair of rapping brothers
who have recorded a whole album of songs about their medical
specialty, asthma. ``That was amazing,'' says Bardeen. ``Totally
brilliant. I think everybody appreciates the absurdity of some of
this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The links on Listen.com can be organized in several ways _ by
genre (rock/alternative, easy listening, ``darkside'' electronic),
by established artists (``Big Shots''), by critics' picks.
</P>
<P>
   Bardeen says the directory might eventually break down listings
in other ways _ by geography, for instance: ``If you wanted to find
fellow yodelers in Oklahoma, you could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any yodelers from Oklahoma among the Listen.com
staff, but there certainly are young men and women with a variety
of alternative lifestyles. Their common ground is their infatuation
with music. ``This is a cool job,'' says Quirk. ``At what other
company would the CEO call you into his office frantically just to
show you the new Clash picture he got for Christmas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other jobs are mindless,'' says Erin Geiger, an editorial
coordinator. ``Here, you really care about the product.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
