<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LISTEN-HOW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNLOADING MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: For use with MUSIC-LISTEN-SFCHRON)  
 By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding and listening to music online is easier than it might
seem. ``Players'' are software products that enable your computer
to recognize an MP3 file and play it back. Many are available free
for download, including WinAmp, MusicMatch, Microsoft Media and
Real Jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to locate an MP3 file of a song you want to
hear. Once you've downloaded the song, just open the downloaded
file on the player.
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com has a helpful ``Beginner's Guide'' on its Web site.
One employee says it's the reason he came to work for the company:
``It has a real `Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy,' don't-panic
vibe to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
