<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW AT LISTEN.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: For use with MUSIC-LISTEN-SFCHRON)  
 By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some recent reviews from Listen.com, the San Francisco company
that tracks online music:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; P.I.M.P. (PARTY IN MY PANTS) (ambient break beats): &LR;  ``New
Age-approved ambient stylings to upbeat funky breaks grooves.
Something for every type of party.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; OTTO'S DAUGHTER (rock/alternative/darkwave): &LR;  ``What Garbage
would sound like with Marilyn Manson in the producer's chair.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; BEN H. (experimental rock/novelty): &LR;  ``Danceable
head-bobbers that conjure images of dwarves running through dark
alleyways.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; INTERMISSIONS (new wave/synth pop): &LR;  ``Quiet, depressive
arrangements of trite beats with self-pitying melodies.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ADMIT 2 (soul/R&AMP;B): &LR;  ``Plenty of dance-y pop appeal and
hooks you'll need a lobotomy to shake.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; LION'S SHARE (progressive metal): &LR;  ``Jagged shards of
Swedish mythical-metal ... Ten thousand chain mail-wearing
berserkers provide backing vocals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-DRUGS-2NDTAKE     01-13 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DRUGS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: fee-for-service program.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This idea is somewhat similar to the president's proposal and to
a bill introduced in August by Sens. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine, and
Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Binder acknowledged that the government would need to set ``some
minimum standards'' for such drug benefits. ``Any company that
wanted to provide services within those ground rules could apply to
do so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up this theme, Gilmartin said: ``One could envision a
drug-only insurance option, with plans competing against one
another. The important principle is that these insurance plans
would compete for Medicare beneficiaries, not for a contract with
the federal government. That's a key distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   The new stance was prompted, in part, by the comments of Clinton
administration officials who said last month that the industry
would bring price controls on itself if it kept resisting public
demands for Medicare drug coverage. After reading those remarks,
the executives said, they were shaken, but also saw some hopeful
signs, and they requested a White House meeting to search for
common ground.
</P>
<P>
   Drug company executives said they had begun asking the same
question as Clinton: Why are they working frantically to develop
great new medicines for the elderly if many of the intended
beneficiaries cannot get or afford them?
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, Medicare would pay half of a
beneficiary's drug expenses, up to certain limits. The maximum
federal payment would start at $1,000 a year and would rise
gradually to $2,500 in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies infuriated the White House last year when they
attacked Clinton's proposal in a series of television and newspaper
advertisements featuring an arthritic Medicare beneficiary named
Flo. The advertisements suggested that the Clinton plan would put
big government inside the family medicine chest and force all the
elderly into a government-run insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Clinton complained that the industry had blocked
congressional action on prescription drugs by spending ``millions
of dollars on an all-out media campaign filled with flat-out
falsehoods.'' He ordered ``a sweeping study'' to document the
impact of high drug prices on the elderly. Democrats say the study
will provide them with ammunition for daily denunciations of the
drug industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmartin said that if Flo reappeared on television, she would
not just criticize Clinton's plan. ``It's important now for Flo to
also be for something positive,'' Gilmartin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MCCAIN-PETITIONS-N     01-13 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCAIN-PETITIONS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN CHIDES BUSH OVER BALLOT CHALLENGE  
 (bl)  
 By JODI WILGOREN   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE, N.H. _ Invoking images of communist repression, Sen. John
McCain on Thursday called upon Texas Gov. George W. Bush to stop
his supporters in New York state from challenging McCain's petition
to appear on New York presidential primary ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that New York Gov. George Pataki and state Republican
chairman William Powers have both endorsed Bush for the Republican
nomination, McCain said Bush could easily give the signal for them
to back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that the Berlin Wall is down,'' McCain said as he
rode a campaign bus between events here. ``People should be able to
get on the ballot in states. I'm sure that if Governor Bush told
them, don't do that, don't remove McCain's name, they would
respond. Everybody knows that I am a legitimate candidate. I should
be on the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Portsmouth, Bush said he would leave the
question of who appears on the ballot up to local party officials,
regardless of their connection to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for all of us to play by the same
rules,'' Bush said. ``I'm confident that Chairman Powers will run
the party in a way that is fair for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokeswoman, Karen Hughes, said a decision on petition
challenges was up to New York party leaders. And a top lawyer for
the state's Republican hierarchy said the petition challenge was
going ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether McCain's name will appear on the ballot
for New York's primary on March 7 has been the subject of political
wrangling in the New York for months, but Thursday was the first
time that it attracted the attention of the candidates themselves
on the national campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   New York is infamous for having the most complicated system for
qualifying for the Republican primary ballot, requiring candidates
to collect a certain amount of signatures of registered voters from
each of the state's 31 congressional districts. In some other
states, candidates qualify simply by raising a certain amount of
money or being deemed by state officials as legitimate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign submitted enough signatures to qualify for
the ballot in 25 congressional districts, and Bush supporters in
New York announced earlier this week that they were filing what are
known as general objections to the petitions, the precursor to a
challenge. Officials said they would be searching for signatures of
people who were not registered voters, not Republicans or not
residents of the specific Congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   It is a longstanding tradition in New York for front-runners to
bring such challenges against underdogs, but McCain Thursday
denounced New York state Republican officials as ``apparatchiks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not have the kind of Stalinist politics that the state
of New York, the Republican Party, has been practicing,'' he told
reporters after a speech to the New Hampshire state Legislature in
Concord
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never consider, ever consider,'' he said, ``allowing a
supporter of mine to challenge Governor Bush's right to be on the
ballot in all 50 states.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush's campaign, said, ``That's
the party's business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
