<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EPA-KOCH-WATER-1STLD-     01-13 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-KOCH-WATER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PIPELINE COMPANY FINED $30 MILLION FOR NEGLIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Texas, Okla., La., Mo. and Ala.)  (REWRITES with details and quotes adding 400 words; ADDS graphic
note.) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the nation's largest pipeline operators quit
inspecting its lines for much of the 1990s and instead found flaws
by waiting for the pipes to break, the government said Thursday,
announcing that the company, Koch Industries, had agreed to pay a
fine of $30 million, the largest civil environmental penalty to
date.
</P>
<P>
   In fining the company, the Environmental Protection Agency said
Koch had failed to inspect its lines for cracks and corrosion,
resulting in leaks of three million gallons of crude oil, gasoline
and other oil products in 300 separate incidents in the last nine
years. It said the leaks, in six states from Texas to Missouri and
Alabama, had fouled lakes, rivers and Gulf Coast shorelines,
killing migratory birds and thousands of fish.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be shared by the federal government, which will
put it in a fund for oil-spill cleanups, and Texas, which did not
say what it would do with the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pollution that could have been and should have been
prevented by Koch Industries through the proper operation and
maintenance of their pipelines,'' Carol Browner, the agency's
administrator, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Browner characterized the investigation and court case
against Koch as one of the most contentious ever carried out by the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for Koch, Mary Beth Jarvis, said in a
telephone interview that the company always maintained its system
well, had spent $980 million on environmental improvements since
1990 and had reduced the number of spills by 96 percent. She said
she could not provide more details of its performance.
</P>
<P>
   At the environmental agency, Steven A. Herman, the assistant
administrator for enforcement, said that to save money, the company
did not inspect its pipelines for corrosion, or pressure-test them,
but simply found flaws by waiting for them to fail. ``It was
cheaper not to maintain them,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the spills was one on June 2, 1994, northeast of Wichita,
Kan., when a pipeline burst because of corrosion, releasing 79,000
gallons of unleaded gasoline. As a result, four houses were
evacuated and part of the local public water supply system was shut
down. In October of that year, a 47-year-old pipeline ruptured
because of operator error, dumping 90,000 gallons of crude oil into
a creek leading to Corpus Christi Bay in Texas. The incident
damaged wetlands in an area that is home to four varieties of
endangered sea turtles, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Other spills were far smaller, in the tens of gallons each.
</P>
<P>
   Koch (pronounced COKE) is owned by one of the most powerful
families in the Midwest, the Koch family, who collectively are
worth about $6 billion. The conglomerate, with its headquarters in
Wichita, is one of the nation's largest privately held companies.
</P>
<P>
   Although it does not divulge financial details, Ms. Jarvis said
it employed more than 12,000 people in its pipeline, refining,
fertilizer, ranching and other operations. It operates about 10,000
miles of natural gas pipelines and 25,000 miles of other pipelines
around the South and Midwest. Government officials said its gross
annual revenues were about $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jarvis said that Koch had been praised by regulators for its
environmental work.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was part of a settlement between Koch Industries and
the government after charges were brought against the company in
federal district courts in Houston and Tulsa. Under the agreement,
which was filed Thursday morning in the court in Houston, the
company was not required to admit any wrongdoing. In addition to
the $30 million fine, it will pay $5 million for environmental
projects in the six states: Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Louisiana,
Missouri and Alabama. It will also improve its leak-detection
systems and hire an auditor who will report back to the government
on its progress.
</P>
<P>
   The spills occurred from 1990 to 1999, Ms. Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said it had taken them months to put the case
together, partly because the company did business under many
different names, and when it reported spills, sometimes understated
their volume by 90 percent. But Ms. Jarvis said the company had
sometimes overreported the volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the instantaneous action of reporting a pipeline accident,
you can be off in either direction, and we were off in either
direction,'' Ms. Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   Some spills contaminated land, but the settlement was reached
under the Clean Water Act, which sets damages for hazardous
materials, including oil and gasoline, that flow into navigable
waters. The largest civil environmental fine before this one also
came under that act, against Smithfield Farms, for $12.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon paid much more after the grounding of its tanker the Exxon
Valdez, but nearly all of that payment was to compensate for the
value of animals, birds and fish killed by the spill, rather than
as punishment, which was the case here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
