<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      01-13 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE RACE IS FORCING HILLARY CLINTON OUT OF COCOON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton was leaving a news
conference in White Plains earlier this week, she noticed a small
group of reporters gathered on the street. Mrs. Clinton walked past
her Secret Service contingent and, with no aides in sight, struck
up a conversation about how, by her account, she had just
mishandled a question about gay marriage. Mrs. Clinton chatted for
nearly five minutes before retreating to her motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment entirely out of character.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven months since Mrs. Clinton began traveling around
New York as a prospective candidate for the U.S. Senate, she has
constructed a largely controlled and often remote existence. As a
rule, she has participated in generally staged events, mostly
avoiding spontaneous contact with the public. She has held only a
few formal news conferences. She has declined interviews with
journalists and editorial boards. Her agreement to appear on ``The
Late Show With David Letterman'' on Wednesday night was a reminder
that she has yet to sit down for the television news shows that are
normally standard stops for anyone running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Mrs. Clinton prepares to formally announce her
candidacy, there are signs of a thaw, evidenced both by her
relenting to Letterman and her presumably spontaneous stroll over
to the reporters in White Plains. She has held two news conferences
this week, and her aides say they are preparing to grant a series
of interviews, with reporters, editorial boards and television news
programs, coinciding with the formal declaration of her candidacy
in the first week of February.
</P>
<P>
   For any other candidate running for public office in New York,
this would be a relatively effortless, and unremarkable, turn of
events. But Mrs. Clinton's uneasy passage into being a candidate
reflects one of the central difficulties she faces in adjusting to
this new life: the struggle between her overriding caution and
distrust of the press on one side, and the pressure to burst
through the White House bubble of staff and security on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The push-and-pull of Mrs. Clinton's past and her future _ from
being the cocooned first lady in the White House to becoming a
buffeted candidate _ has until now remained in the background of
her campaign. But it looms larger now that her candidacy seems
inevitable, and as the pressure grows to act more like a
conventional candidate, be it from Letterman or from The Daily
News, which assailed her on its editorial page for declining an
interview with its editorial board.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's relative remoteness contrasts almost daily to the
actions of her expected Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani. The mayor holds almost daily news conferences, and while
he certainly doesn't answer every question put to him _ he has made
a habit of refusing to answer questions if he senses that they are
driven by Mrs. Clinton or her campaign _ he is out there in a way
that Mrs. Clinton is not.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also has a weekly radio call-in show, frequently
appears on the Sunday morning television interview shows, and holds
monthly town hall meetings. He has been known to call reporters and
even newspaper publishers to register a thought or a complaint.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, part of Mrs. Clinton's posture is beyond her
control. Unlike Giuliani, she travels with a troop of Secret
Service agents who can make it difficult for any member of the
public to come within 50 feet of her. In addition, there are
typically dozens of reporters following her wherever she goes;
spontaneous engagements are cumbersome when you are being tracked
by a bear of a press corps.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Mrs. Clinton intentionally created this life of
relative seclusion, after her disastrous effort to shepherd a
national health care program into law in 1994 and the backlash over
her role in the Whitewater real estate deal. Before then,
on-the-record interviews and off-the-record lunches with reporters
were a regular part of her schedule. Since then, for example, Mrs.
Clinton, has not brought reporters along on her plane when she
traveled, a way of discouraging coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends describe her as intensely distrustful of the press,
and as she has turned to New York, she has been the subject of some
fairly critical coverage, particularly in The New York Post. All of
that has reinforced the first lady's reluctance to lower her guard.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that based on the evidence to date, Mrs. Clinton
would seem to be a skillful and even personable candidate. Although
she tends to be exceedingly cautious in discussing tough issues,
she has made only a few errors to date.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Mrs. Clinton's advisers, noting just how strongly she
is disliked by much of the public, have argued in recent weeks that
the best thing she could do to shed the baggage of her past is to
appear in unscripted public settings, so the public could get a
better sense of the woman who has for six years stood mostly in
Clinton's shadow. As the first lady was walking off Letterman's
stage, to a hug from the host and applause from the audience, it
seemed fair to say that this is one bit of advice the first lady is
likely to take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
