<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-REPUBS-FLAG-NYT &LR;      01-13 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBS-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPUBLICANS AND THE CONFEDERATE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Both leading Republican candidates for president, Sen. John
McCain and Gov. George W. Bush, are being too clever by half in the
perennially inflammatory debate over a Confederate flag in South
Carolina. By declining to take a principled stand in this key
primary state, the candidates are pandering to bias and
perpetuating an outdated and ignoble practice from past Republican
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   For years, South Carolina has been the only state to fly the
Confederate flag over its Capitol. Black South Carolinians and many
whites rightly view the flag as a reactionary symbol of slavery and
segregation, but they have sought in vain to have it removed. The
NAACP has declared an economic boycott against the state for as
long as the flag flies, but Republicans in the state legislature
have blocked all attempts to lower it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for whom the state's primary Feb. 19 will be a crucial
test, has made conflicting statements on the flag. On Sunday,
facing a national television audience, he properly called it
``offensive'' and a ``symbol of racism and slavery.'' A day later,
addressing South Carolina reporters, he reversed himself and called
the flag ``a symbol of heritage.'' This was unmistakable code
language that conservative white Republicans _ McCain's base in the
state _ have long used to justify keeping the flag flying over the
Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been no more principled. While he has said he would not
fly the Confederate flag over the Texas Statehouse ``because of the
symbolism,'' he has also repeatedly said that the matter was for
South Carolinians to decide. This won't do. It fails to take into
account the concerns of a minority that lacks the political
strength to expunge this affront to its dignity as an equal.
</P>
<P>
   Other states across the South have long since moved beyond this
ugly debate. Alabama, the last to do so, removed its flag from the
Capitol dome in Montgomery in 1993 after black legislators won a
lawsuit. Business leaders throughout the region, eager to compete
in a cosmopolitan global market, have been at the forefront of
efforts to remove the alienating emblems of a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign in South Carolina recalls earlier efforts by the
Republican Party to tap into residual segregationist impulses, from
Richard Nixon's Southern Strategy to Ronald Reagan's appeal for
``states' rights'' at a county fair in Philadelphia, Miss., in
1980. Today's Republicans are playing a cynical and, one might have
hoped, obsolete game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5657 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-13 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN NEEDS WISE ASSISTANT ON BENCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pete Dalis has done Steve Lavin a terrible
disservice. He calls himself an athletic director but he's really
just another indulgent parent, showering a stubborn, mollycoddled
Lavin with more freedom and responsibility than he was prepared to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the whole thing now is blowing up in everybody's face.
Isn't that so often the case when benevolence comes before common
sense in decision-making, same as in the dictionary?
</P>
<P>
   Dalis handed Lavin the keys to the Porsche of college basketball
programs in 1996 despite the fact Lavin never had been behind the
wheel of any program at any level.
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't steered a pre-owned Pinto, much less a late model
sedan. The sum total of his collegiate coaching experience had been
barking directions from the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   We're not here today to question Dalis' decision to wrench the
wheel from Jim Harrick, hand it to Lavin and then protect Lavin
with an obscene amount of insurance in the form of a rollover
contract that effectively allows the fourth-year coach to walk away
unscratched from any crash. That's well-trodden territory by now.
</P>
<P>
   If Dalis was inclined to let Lavin learn to steer a vehicle as
powerful as the UCLA basketball program in the fast lane that is
the Pacific-10 Conference, fine. But Dalis had a responsibility to
all the student-athletes going along for the ride and to all the
fans and boosters, too, to make sure Lavin had a veteran assistant
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's inexperience cried out for somebody riding shotgun who
had been down the trail before, and was familiar with the terrain
and maybe knew a few stretches to avoid, and wasn't at all shy
about speaking up if Lavin took his hands off the wheel, or failed
to see the potholes up ahead or wasn't sure which way to proceed
when confronted with a detour.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin looked instead to his best buddies from high school. He
promoted Jim Saia (whom he had lobbied Harrick to hire for the
third assistant's job). And he put Steve Spencer on the payroll in
Saia's old position when he might have had Spencer's mentor at Cal
Lutheran, Mike Dunlap. That made about as much sense as employing
Stephen King's typist to write the next top-selling thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin didn't listen to the people who advised him to look for
someone with more depth to his resume. It was almost as if Lavin
didn't think his joyride at UCLA was going to last very long so he
decided, what the heck, he might as well let his friends share in a
few of the thrills.
</P>
<P>
   If Dalis had exercised more authority over Lavin then, there
wouldn't be all the skidding we're seeing now. For the same reason
kids have to drive in the company of an adult for a while before
they can set out by themselves, Dalis should have insisted Lavin
have a mature adult to ride out his first few seasons with him.
</P>
<P>
   Dalis should have made Lavin's sudden promotion _ or the
generous new contract Lavin wrung out of the Bruins after his
memorable first season, which ended two victories shy of the NCAA
title game (Thank you, Cameron Dollar and Charles O'Bannon) _
contingent on Lavin hiring someone with head-coaching experience to
balance his, ahem, youthful exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Dalis didn't, he said Thursday, was because ``When I
hire head coaches, I give them a certain latitude to hire their own
people. You hope they've made good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to trust the instincts of a Bob Toledo, who paid
his dues for years in the high school and college ranks, and
another thing altogether to bestow autonomy on someone who hadn't
yet had a chance to earn it.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to bash all the criticism directed toward Lavin, Dalis
seemed to buttress our argument. ``No one's born a head coach,''
Dalis said. ``People go through a learning process. People grow
into the job.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are those for whom the usual learning curve is
more like a race course straightaway. They can go quite far, quite
fast, with the proper mentoring. Pat Riley, when he started out
with the Lakers, had Bill Bertka. Phil Jackson has had Tex Winter.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin could have had someone like, say, Don Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson played for UCLA under John Wooden in 1951 and 1952 and
later developed big men Swen Nater and Mark Eaton while he was
coaching at Cypress College.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty more teachers where Johnson and Bertka and
Winter come from. They have much to offer, these men who have been
involved in basketball longer than Lavin has been breathing and,
yet, don't act like they know all there is to learn about the game.
</P>
<P>
   They have something half a million dollars can't buy: The wisdom
borne of experience.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine USC coach Henry Bibby throwing any kind of
defense at UCLA that former Cerritos College coaching great Jack
Bogdanovich hasn't seen and couldn't counter.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine Dan Gadzuric looking so lost in the post if
Johnson was around to teach him a move or two.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine UCLA players showing scant improvement from
one year to the next with Bertka in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, it's not hard to imagine UCLA boosters scurrying to
sign up for the game show, ``So You Want to be a Millionaire'' in
the hopes of winning enough to buy out Lavin's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Their lifeline?
</P>
<P>
   That's an easy one. It would have to be Dalis. He's the only one
can supply the answers to the questions that have every UCLA fan
stumped. &QL; 
!hair! &QL; 
!ital!
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a
week. She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
