<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WARNER-MERGER-ART-1ST     01-13 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-MERGER-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER-LAMBERT BEGINS MERGER TALKS WITH PFIZER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., N.J.)   (Editors: Subs to correct stock prices in 16th graf.)  (ART ADV:
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an abrupt change of heart, executives at Warner-Lambert Co.
said Thursday they were negotiating a possible union with Pfizer
Inc., a suitor and rival they have battled for two months.
</P>
<P>
   That decision could leave Warner-Lambert's first choice as a
merger partner, American Home Products, alone at the altar for a
third time in two years. Either merger would create the world's
largest drug company.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert executives made their decision after the
company's shareholders increased their demands that the company
accept the far more lucrative offer from Pfizer. Pfizer's offer is
now worth about $75 billion, based on Thursday's closing stock
prices, while American Home's stands at about $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been the board's objective to secure the best
possible transaction for Warner-Lambert shareholders,'' Lodewijk
J.R. de Vink, chairman of Warner-Lambert, said in a statement,
``and we will now pursue discussions with Pfizer to determine if a
combination with them to achieve that goal is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert shareholders had favored Pfizer's hostile bid
ever since it was made in early November, just hours after
Warner-Lambert and American Home said that they planned to merge.
But the shareholders have recently turned up the heat because of
worries about the thousands of lawsuits filed against American Home
by people who took the company's diet-pill combination called
fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   American Home agreed in October to pay $3.75 billion to settle
claims from people who said their health suffered from the diet
treatment. But many people have refused to accept the settlement
and are instead continuing to pursue their claims separately.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, a Mississippi jury awarded $150 million in
compensatory damages to five plaintiffs, four of whom said the
drugs had caused them to develop primary pulmonary hypertension, an
often fatal lung illness. The company then agreed to settle 1,400
cases brought in Mississippi for $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's decision caused American Home's stock price to slide
_ and the Pfizer bid to look even better to Warner-Lambert's
shareholders _ because it could mean that the cost of settling the
diet-drug lawsuits will be much greater than American Home
expected.
</P>
<P>
   American Home said Thursday it was not willing to simply go
away. ``We continue to support a strategic merger of equals of
Warner-Lambert and AHP under our existing merger agreement, the
terms of which remain under full force and effect,'' an American
Home spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Under that agreement, American Home stands to get as much as $2
billion in break-up fees if Warner-Lambert decides to merge with
Pfizer or another company. Some analysts said they were not sure
what the final outcome would be in what they called a bloody war
among the drug makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely not a certain deal because there is
significant animosity between Warner-Lambert and Pfizer,'' said
Neil Sweig, an analyst at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, Warner-Lambert had bitterly fought Pfizer's bid,
filing several lawsuits and refusing even to talk to Pfizer
executives. For its part, Pfizer has tried in recent weeks to oust
members of the Warner-Lambert board and replace them with directors
supporting Pfizer's offer.
</P>
<P>
   If a merger takes place, Sweig and other analysts expect
significant layoffs at Warner-Lambert, which is based in Morris
Plains, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert has 43,000 employees, 3,000 of whom work in New
Jersey. Pfizer, based in New York, has 46,400 employees worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert is considered a prize in the pharmaceutical
industry because of Lipitor, its blockbuster cholesterol treatment,
and for other products it is developing. Warner-Lambert already has
a marketing agreement with Pfizer to sell Lipitor, a drug analysts
project could have worldwide sales of about $5 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, both shareholders and analysts praised
Warner-Lambert's decision Thursday. Warner-Lambert rose $5.125 a
share, to $91.9375. Pfizer gained $1.9375, to $37. And American
Home rose 43.75 cents, to $42.625.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the announcement was bound to accelerate the
merger frenzy in the drug industry.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts speculated that American Home, based in
Madison, N.J., would quickly seek another partner or become a
takeover target of other drug makers. Analysts suggested that
SmithKline Beecham PLC might move to merge with American Home or
that American Home would try to take over Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, a
move that could break up the plans of Pharmacia and the Monsanto
Co. to combine. Pharmacia is led by Fred Hassan, a former American
Home executive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, American Home failed in attempts to merge with
SmithKline and later with Monsanto because of conflicts about which
corporate executive would have control.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell B. Weiner, a spokesman at American Home, said that the
company would not comment on any merger speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pipeline of rich products,'' Weiner said. ``We're in
good shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
