A5780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MOB-FUGITIVE-NYT &LR;      01-13 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOB-FUGITIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE HELD ON 1992 COUNT OF FIXING GOTTI JURY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., N.C., Ill.)   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bosko Radonjich's life has been marked by
international intrigue, including, by his own account, days as a
Serbian freedom fighter, a CIA operative and a close adviser to
Radovan Karadzic, the former Bosnian Serb leader and fugitive war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI officials said it was intrigue in Brooklyn, in the
service of another larger-than-life criminal figure, that landed
Radonjich, a Yugoslav emigre and former New York City parking lot
owner, in federal custody this month.
</P>
<P>
   Radonjich was arrested at the Miami airport on New Year's Day on
a 1992 indictment that charged him with tampering with a juror to
help fix the first federal racketeering trial of John J. Gotti, the
boss of the Gambino crime family. The case, in 1987, made Gotti's
reputation as a crime boss who could not be brought down.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the trial, the authorities said, Radonjich served
as an incongruous ethnic bridge: he headed the Irish gang known as
the Westies, a cadre of violent toughs who often did the bidding of
Gotti's Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Radonjich, who became an international fugitive after the
indictment, was arrested after U.S. Customs Service inspectors at
the Miami airport, alerted by an advisory about Radonjich's
traveling companion, discovered the 1992 warrant in the jury
tampering case. Radonjich and his companion, who was later
released, had arrived from Cancun, Mexico, and were bound for the
Bahamas, officials said. They did not identify the companion.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest was first reported Thursday by Ganglandnews.com, a
Web site that covers organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   While it was the Brooklyn charge that led to his arrest, law
enforcement officials said that based on notes and photographs
found in his possession, Radonjich's days of international intrigue
appeared far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The search revealed he had pictures of the Iraqi Embassy in
Havana,'' the official said, adding that Radonjich also had ``some
notes about U.S. military installations in Georgia and North
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   The official had no explanation for the pictures or the notes,
but said that at least one of the two men had recently traveled to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The material was sobering for law enforcement officials, given
Radonjich's past. He pleaded guilty in 1978 to conspiracy charges
in the 1978 bombing of the home of the Yugoslav consul's home in
suburban Chicago and a plot to bomb a Yugoslav social club in that
city.
</P>
<P>
   Wiretaps in the case recorded him talking about the Chicago
bombing and making an admission that he took part in the June 23,
1975, bombing at the Yugoslav mission to the United Nations in New
York, officials said. No one was injured in that attack and no one
was ever charged in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Radonjich and his five co-defendants in the Chicago case were
identified as Serbian nationalists. Radonjich was released from
prison in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The jury tampering indictment against Radonjich and George Pape,
a longtime friend, charged that the two men conspired with Gotti,
the crime boss' brother, Gene, and Salvatore Gravano, then the
Gambino family underboss, to fix the case.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 federal trial that resulted in Gotti's conviction on
murder and racketeering charges, Gravano testified that he gave
Radonjich $60,000 with which to bribe Pape, who was later convicted
and sentenced to three years in prison in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Maloney, who was the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn
overseeing Gotti's case in 1987, praised Radonjich's recent arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important,'' he said. ``It's very frustrating to
know that people like Bosko are bold enough to tamper with the
system,'' he said, adding that the relatively light penalties for
jury tampering make it worth it for some criminals to try to fix
their cases. ``It pays to try to fix the jury because you get far
less time than for some substantive crimes,'' Maloney said. ``So if
you're facing life, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Radonjich himself acknowledged some role in the jury tampering
in a 1997 interview in Yugoslavia with Esquire magazine. He also
said he was a close adviser to Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader
accused of genocide. But he said, he loved America and hoped to
return someday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
