<HEADLINE>
JACK E. BROWN, A COMPUTER INDUSTRY LAWYER, DIES AT 72 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Ariz., Calif., Mass., Ill, Iowa)   By NICK RAVO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack E. Brown, a lawyer prominent in several early cases
concerning the computer industry and intellectual property, died on
Jan. 6 at his home in Paradise Valley, Ariz. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said Paul F. Eckstein, an attorney
at Brown &AMP; Bain, the Phoenix law firm that Brown founded 40 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's specialty was high-technology litigation, particularly
copyright violations. Most notably, he represented Apple Computer
in its unsuccessful ``look and feel'' case in 1989 against
Microsoft's Windows operating system. A U.S. District Court judge
ruled against Apple, holding that an element of an interface, like
the recycle bin on the Windows screen, infringed on a copyright
only if it looked exactly the same as another interface, in this
example, Apple's trash basket.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was more successful keeping the Franklin Computer Corp.
from cloning the Apple II personal computer in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He also represented IBM, Intel, Unisys and United Technologies,
among other companies.
</P>
<P>
   He was listed recently in the National Law Journal as one of the
100 most influential lawyers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Edward Brown was born on March 15, 1927, in Omaha. He
received a bachelor's degree from Northwestern University and a law
degree from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. House of Representatives in
1972 as the Democratic Party candidate in the 4th Congressional
District of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is survived by his wife, Suzanne; two sons, Charles, of
Mesquite, Nev., and James, of Phoenix; two daughters, Abigail
Brown, of Phoenix, and Amanda Chang, of San Francisco; a brother,
Milton Brown, of Des Moines, and five grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
