<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ANTI-MCCAIN-AD-NYT     01-13 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-MCCAIN-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUE ADS, HIS TARGET, ARE TURNED ON MCCAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Though John McCain, like all the presidential
candidates, has been spared from television advertising attacks by
his rivals, he has not escaped negative advertising entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Recently two conservative groups have broadcast commercials that
attack McCain, in one case not only for his position on the issue
that matters most to the group but also for a campaign finance
proposal that would have limited the organization's influence.
</P>
<P>
   Before changing his campaign finance bill in the fall in an
unsuccessful effort to win passage, McCain's proposal would have
not only banned soft money but also regulated the very ``issue
ads'' that are being used against him.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Americans for Tax Reform, an antitax group, has run
ads in New Hampshire maintaining that McCain's overhaul of the
campaign finance system would harm conservatives and help
Democrats, a stance that has also been taken by the front-runner
for the Republican nomination, Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee has run an advertisement in
South Carolina saying McCain is not taking a strong enough stand
against abortion. And in New Hampshire, another advertisement from
the group chides him for making this joke about his memory: ``The
nice thing about Alzheimer's is you get to hide your own Easter
eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Americans for Tax Reform, the Right to Life Committee
opposes McCain's campaign finance proposal as well.
</P>
<P>
   Grover G. Norquist, the executive director of the antitax group,
has worked closely with the Republican Party leadership in the
past. In October 1996, for instance, Norquist accepted millions of
dollars from the party to pay for an influential direct-mail
campaign to assure voters that Republicans would not cut Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In a Republican presidential debate last week, McCain addressed
the advertisements of Norquist's group, telling Bush, ``You've got
a supporter right now that's running attack ads on me.'' He also
questioned who was paying for the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist said in an interview that the ads were financed by his
organization's members and that the purpose was not to sway voters
but to persuade McCain to abandon a ``stupid'' policy regarding
issue ads.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of issue ads say they purport to explain a policy issue
but are actually thinly disguised campaign spots that promote or
attack a candidate. One of those run by Americans for Tax Reform,
for example, urges voters to ``call John McCain and tell him to
leave the Republican Party alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Since late last month, the McCain campaign has issued several
blistering attacks on Norquist, saying his drive against the
senator is motivated by what they describe as his career as a
lobbyist for clients like Microsoft that depend heavily on
companies' being able to make soft-money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans for Tax Reform is a wonderful-sounding name,'' said
former Sen. Warren Rudman of New Hampshire, national co-chairman of
McCain's campaign. ``As far as I'm concerned, it's a front
organization for Grover Norquist's lobbying activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Norquist, along with several other conservative groups,
including the National Rifle Association and the Christian
Coalition, began working against McCain's presidential campaign in
September, traveling to New Hampshire and South Carolina to
denounce the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Of the campaign's counterattack against him, he said, ``This is
a desperate attempt by the McCain people to attempt to persuade
people not to pay attention to the charges raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing any notion that the ads were intended to help Bush,
he said his group undertook a $200,000 radio advertising campaign
against the governor on a complicated state tax issue in Texas
during the Bush re-election drive in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PRISON-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      01-13 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTRICTIONS LIFTED AT 2 PRISONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York state correction officials have ended lockdowns at two
prisons where inmates were accused of plotting a statewide strike
that was to begin on New Year's Day, officials said Thursday .
</P>
<P>
   In the lockdowns, all 2,100 inmates at Sing Sing in Ossining,
Westchester County, and all 1,800 inmates at Green Haven prison in
Stormville, Dutchess County, had been confined to their cells 23
hours a day, except for visits, emergencies and some essential
jobs, since Christmas Eve. The department ended the lockdown at
Sing Sing late last week, and at Green Haven on Monday after no
major disruptions occurred at either prison, said James B. Flateau,
a spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   But some prison guards, relatives of inmates and advocates of
inmates' rights said that many prisoners had refused to work.
</P>
<P>
   The state correction commissioner, Glenn S. Goord, ordered the
department to lock down both prisons on Dec. 24, after live
ammunition was discovered at Sing Sing, and inmates were accused of
plotting a prison strike. State prison officials and inmates'
advocates said that prisoners had been planning strikes at at least
eight state prisons largely to protest parole policies that some
regard as too strict.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a prison guard at Sing Sing was charged with planting
the ammunition, and he resigned after an investigation by the
Department of Correctional Services and the state police. But
Flateau said the loosening of restrictions had nothing to do with
the charge against the officer.
</P>
<P>
   He added that despite rumors of a strike, and fears of resulting
violence at several state prisons, there were no significant
instances of work being stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Guards and inmates' relatives and advocates, however, have
reported that a work stoppage did occur at Green Haven beginning
Jan. 3, the first day some inmates were required to return to their
jobs after the holidays, and that many prisoners refused to leave
their cells or eat meals.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Fitzpatrick, director of public relations for the New York
State Correctional Officers and Police Benevolent Association, a
union that represents state prison guards, said that about
three-quarters of the inmates at Green Haven are expected to work
or attend classes when there is not a lockdown, but that most of
those inmates had refused to leave their cells last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are not back to normal yet,'' he said. ``Inmates are
eating and coming out of their cells a little more, gradually,
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Green, executive director of the Center for Law and
Justice in Albany, an inmate advocacy group, said she had received
about 20 letters from Green Haven inmates and about 15 calls from
their family members saying that many inmates had refused to go to
work, and that some had participated in a hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the 72,000 inmates in state prisons work in jobs
from prison maintenance to furniture making and earn an average of
$1.05 a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2328EST &QL; 
