<HEADER>
A5791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PUFF-GUNS-1STLD-WR     01-13 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PUFF-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUFF DADDY INDICTED OVER GUNS IN NIGHTCLUB SHOOTINGS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Fixes spelling of Wardel in 2nd graph, fixes name of club
where shootings occurred, other changes throughout, including
additions at end on his lawyers and his businesses.)  
(jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan grand jury Thursday charged Sean Combs,
the rap performer better known as Puff Daddy, with possession of
two illegal handguns as part of its investigation into shootings
that wounded three people on Dec. 27 at a Times Square nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Combs took the unusual step of testifying in his own defense,
but the indictment appears to rely on the account of the man who
was his part-time driver that night. While the testimony of the
driver, Wardel Fenderson, 42, is sealed, evidence presented by
prosecutors indicated that he saw Combs throw a gun out the window
of the car as they fled police.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment presents another daunting challenge for Combs, a
30-year-old multimillionaire, Grammy-winning artist and producer
who socializes with the city's elite and has a knack for surviving
seemingly disastrous blows to his career. Even as he faces poor
sales of his latest record, other performers leaving his recording
label and rumblings of discontent from his corporate backer, Combs
must now resolve criminal charges that carry a penalty of up to 15
years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper, whose business empire includes the Bad Boy
Entertainment music label, a restaurant chain, a clothing line and
a television production company, issued a statement vehemently
denying the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to indict me is wrong,'' Combs said. ``I'm
innocent, and we will prove it. I am putting my faith in God, and I
know my name will be cleared.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez, the singer and actress who was in the car with
Combs, stood by him Thursday. She issued a statement saying she had
``cooperated fully'' with the district attorney's office and was
``surprised and saddened'' by the indictment. ``I was with him that
evening,'' she said. ``At no time did I see him with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charged Combs with possession of a 9 mm handgun
found in the car, and with possession of the 9 mm gun that was
thrown from the car as it sped away from the crowded Club New York
on West 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Combs' associates were also named in the indictment: a
rap protege, Jamal Barrow, who has been charged with three counts
of attempted murder stemming for the accusation that he pulled his
own gun and fired it three times in the club, and a bodyguard,
Anthony Jones, who faces a weapons charge.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, the Manhattan district attorney,
Robert M. Morgenthau, said that the 1999 Lincoln Navigator in which
Combs was riding had secret compartments. He said nothing had been
found in the compartments.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement officials who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said there was evidence that Combs and his bodyguard
tried to stash the guns in them during the police chase, but were
unable to open them. Combs threw his gun out the window, they said,
and Jones placed his on the car floor.
</P>
<P>
   Someone walking on Eighth Avenue saw the gun thrown from the
vehicle, picked it up and later turned it over to police, the
officials said. And at least one other witness had seen Combs
brandish a gun inside the club after an altercation with a group of
men, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials also said Thursday that they were
investigating accounts that while Combs was being held for
questioning overnight after the chase, he was heard in jail
offering Fenderson, the driver, a $300,000 ring and $50,000 in cash
if he would back up Combs' version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Brounstein, the lawyer representing Fenderson, declined
to comment Thursday on whether the driver testified before the
grand jury. But he thanked the panel for not indicting his client
and praised prosecutors for a ``fair'' investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Fenderson is not a member of the tightly knit group of employees
and friends who work for Combs, according to people familiar with
the case. He had worked for Combs only on weekends since October.
</P>
<P>
   Combs has hired two new high-profile lawyers, Benjamin Brafman
and Johnnie L. Cochran Jr., and they spoke for him at a news
conference. Cochran urged ``the public, Sean's millions of fans and
those with whom he is involved'' in various business ventures to
withhold judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to Combs' business partners appeared to reflect
his shifting financial fortunes. Along with slow sales of his
latest album and the departure of the popular group the LOX from
his label, the shooting also derailed the career of Barrow, also
known as Shyne, whose new album was expected to revive the label's
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Bertelsmann A.G., the vast German corporation that
underwrites Combs' label, declined to comment on his indictment
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannine Amber, features editor at Vibe magazine, said it was
far too early to count out Combs, who has pushed beyond the
traditional boundaries of rap stardom to achieve unusually high
status among both blacks and whites. While the charges may hurt his
standing among wealthy socialites who attend his lavish parties,
she said, many of the disenfranchised may decide he is being
demonized. She added, ``I'm sure there are fans out there for whom
this looks like a witch hunt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
