<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS FOR INVESTMENT IN POOR AREAS
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton Thursday proposed giving more tax
credits to businesses that invest in the country's poorest areas,
telling audiences in New York City that such spending is both a
moral obligation during these flush times and squarely in the
economic self-interest of those who have thrived the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we keep this going?'' Clinton asked, referring to the
nation's remarkable prosperity in a speech at the Sheraton New York
in Midtown Manhattan. The president suggested that the answer lies,
almost paradoxically, in those parts of the country that have
largely been left behind by the information age _ places like the
inner city of East St. Louis, or the remote towns of Appalachia, or
the immigrant neighborhoods of Brooklyn, a borough whose poverty
rate is more than double the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those booming regions where the job market is tight and
new growth raises the specter of wage-driven inflation, depressed
areas offer the possibility of growth without inflation, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the unemployment rate in Brooklyn drops from 9.4 percent to
4.1 percent, where it is nationwide, you can get a whole lot of new
jobs there,'' Clinton said at a conference sponsored by the Wall
Street Project, the Rev. Jesse Jackson's initiative to get
corporations to open their boardrooms and capital to minority
groups. ``And then,'' Clinton continued, ``those people that have
the jobs spend their money there, and that won't contribute to
inflation. It will keep the economy growing, and the same thing is
true all across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The president took several specific steps Thursday to flesh out
what aides are calling his ``new opportunity agenda.'' After a
lengthy telephone conversation in the morning with President Hafez
Assad of Syria about peace negotiations with Israel, Clinton
proceeded by motorcade from his new home in Chappaqua to Brooklyn,
where he opened a small-business development center at Boricau
College in Williamsburg. The center, largely financed by the Small
Business Administration and a $100,000 grant from Citigroup, will
offer $13 million in new loans and management training to
Brooklyn's 93,000 small businesses, a third of which have minority
owners.
</P>
<P>
   At the center, Clinton announced a plan to increase to $5
billion from $2 billion the amount of money available during the
next 10 years for his ``New Markets'' tax credits, a program that
gives companies a 25 percent tax credit for each dollar invested in
community development projects in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would push to expand the federal government's
empowerment zones, depressed areas where some employers are
eligible for 20 percent tax credits on up to $15,000 in wages per
employee. Clinton said he would ask Congress to approve an
additional $4 billion over 10 years to, among other things,
increase the number of zones to 41 from 31. He said the Treasury
Department would spend $30 million on pilot programs to encourage
11 million low-income families with no bank accounts to open
low-cost ``First Accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed the notion that the nation, weeks away from
setting a record for the longest economic expansion, was uniquely
positioned to make these investments. ``If we can't do this now, we
will never do this,'' he said in Manhattan. ``This is the only time
in the lifetimes of most of us here that we've ever had a chance to
give everyone a shot at the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a theme shared by House Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, the Republican leader, who issued a statement this week
saying he was ``very excited to see the president unveil his ideas
for community renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation,'' Hastert said, ``is enjoying an unprecedented
period of economic growth, and it is important that no community be
left behind.'' Hastert promised to work with the Clinton
administration to come up with a package of tax and regulatory
relief to stimulate investment in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Clinton shared a podium with Jackson at a
Rainbow Coalition gala at the New York Stock Exchange. He then
headed to a fund-raising dinner at the Fifth Avenue home of John
and Margo Catsimatidis. The dinner with 60 couples raised $250,000
for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, the president also got in several plugs
Thursday for Hillary Clinton's performance Wednesday on the ``Late
Show With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said in Brooklyn, ``I thought I was supposed to
be the funny one in this family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
