<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PROGRESS IS REPORTED IN ANTITRUST TALKS
</HEADLINE>
   (With MICROSOFT-GATES) 
(rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Microsoft's top executives said Thursday that
they were still hopeful of settling the government antitrust case
against the company before a federal judge issues his final ruling.
And they said company officials had had far-reaching internal
discussions about their options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some amazing discussions and wild ideas about what
we would do,'' Steven A. Ballmer, the company's president, said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Bill Gates, the chairman, repeatedly ruled out any
breakup of Microsoft, emphasizing that its software strategy could
succeed only with a unified company.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the settlement talks said Thursday that there
had been little progress toward a negotiated settlement, and the
two sides had rarely even met face to face in the course of
mediation by Richard A. Posner, a federal appellate judge in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   They said the Justice Department and the 19 states suing
Microsoft were increasingly leaning toward a severe ``structural''
remedy _ breaking up the company or forcing it to license its
software to rivals. Still, such remedies could take many forms,
they said, and the plaintiffs have not settled firmly on a single,
preferred remedy.
</P>
<P>
   If the mediation talks collapse, the two sides will go back to
federal court in Washington before Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
for final arguments scheduled for Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about press reports that the government would seek to
break Microsoft into two or three separate companies, Ballmer said
such a move would be ``reckless beyond belief'' and would harm
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer said he would be ``the point man'' in the company's
decision-making in the settlement talks but that Gates would
continue to be involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
