r a BC-TEACHERPAY-AZR &LR;      01-13 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERPAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER PAY LAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - The salary gap between teachers and other
professionals with similar educations is growing, a new report
says.
</P>
<P>
   Educators' annual salaries are an average $8,000 less at the
start of their careers and lag $24,000 by age 50, reports Education
Week's annual survey.
</P>
<P>
   The decades-old disparity heads toward crisis levels as states
hold teachers more accountable and schools struggle to fill
teaching posts, experts say. Two million teachers will be needed in
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries for professionals with bachelor's degrees jumped 17
percent from 1994 to 1998, said the report, based on U.S. Census
data. Teacher salaries inched up 1 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to recruit the excellence you want without
making the salary package attractive,'' said Tim Rockey, a
government teacher at Sunnyslope High School in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Rockey has taught and participated in salary negotiations for a
quarter-century. With a master's degree and 24 additional higher
education hours, he makes $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona pays its teachers an average of $35,025, the 34th lowest
salary in the nation, according to a report released by the
National Education Association, the largest teachers union.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the grim numbers, Arizona school districts dangle
incentives, including signing bonuses. But the short-term fixes
won't solve the problem, many teachers say.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching ranks used to be plump with ``missionaries,'' folks
willing to live the lower-middle-class lifestyle for the chance to
mold young minds. But today, Jan. 14, there's just not enough money
to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   After several years, some leave what they consider a ``Peace
Corps'' job to make enough money elsewhere to start or support a
family.
</P>
<P>
   Those who stay often take on second jobs. Dianne Erbe teaches
seventh grade at Sun Valley Elementary School in Peoria during the
day and rings up groceries at Safeway at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going back to get my master's,'' said the 41-year-old, who
is in her fourth year of teaching and who makes about $28,500 a
year. ``I'm trying to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers get larger raises if they further their education.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Kotterman, president of the Arizona Education Association,
says to hire and retain good teachers, ``money really is the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't apologize for trying to find more money for
teachers,'' Kotterman said. ``They deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   She says that responsibility rests with lawmakers, who fund
schools each year.
</P>
<P>
   However, state Rep. Steve May countered, the Legislature has
funneled more money to education. The problem is that school
districts aren't pumping it into teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to bite the bullet and give more money to teachers
than administrators,'' the east Phoenix Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   May said there are other things the Legislature might do to help
teacher salaries, such as adding more school days or offer them
special tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Another legislator, Sen. Scott Bundgaard, R-Phoenix, plans to
introduce a bill next week that would bump up teachers' base salary
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   But with state attention on reducing class size and buildings, the money may not be there.
</P>
<P>
   If teacher pay isn't bulked up, Joni Burd is fearful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make a living,'' said the special-education reading
teacher at Underdown Junior High in Cashion, a ranching community
in the Phoenix's West Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pay in her district: $23,500. After 18 years as a
teacher, the 43-year-old mother of two makes $30,500.
</P>
<P>
   She gets tired of hearing outsiders say that teachers have it
easy because they get summers off and merely baby-sit during the
school year. Not a week goes by that Burd isn't working 40-plus
hours in her classroom and taking papers home to grade.
</P>
<P>
   However, this teacher doesn't let the negative comments, hard
work or low pay get her down.
</P>
<P>
   Why does she stay? ``It's the kids,'' Burd said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kelly.Pearce(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or at (602) 444-8979. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
