<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO RUN ADS IN SPANISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Choosing Arizona as his experimental canvas, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush plans to air the first ever Spanish-language
television ads in a Republican primary, campaign aides said.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, trying to hold his own against Bush, also likely
will put up ads, though not in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The television ads could be particularly influential in Arizona
because the candidates are spending most of their time campaigning
elsewhere and plan no campaign visits here until February.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the air war will be Steve Forbes, who also will launch
new TV ads in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, who has blanketed the state with ads for a month, the
Spanish-language spots will only intensify a surprisingly ardent
effort to win Arizona. For McCain, advertising, once unimaginable
because of its cost, could help him beat back the front-runner in
his home state.
</P>
<P>
   In confirming a possible ad buy, McCain aides were quick to add
that if they are victorious in New Hampshire and South Carolina,
they won't have to run ads back home.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers said they plan to run television ads targeting
Hispanic voters in both English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-language ads are intended to draw in Hispanic voters
not only for the primary but also for a general-election battle,
advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Merrill, a pollster at Arizona State University, noted the
Spanish-language ads are aimed a population that rarely votes
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is saying is, `I've got resources beyond what I need
for the primary process, and I can already start my
general-election campaign,' '' Merrill said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
