<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASUSAT1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU SATELLITE SET FOR LIFTOFF TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(TEMPE, Ariz.) - A tiny satellite built by 400 Arizona State
University students will be the first launched worldwide in the new
millennium, if all goes as planned tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The launch from Vandenberg Air Force Base in central California
is scheduled for 8 Arizona time. The light from the launch should
be visible on the western horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a sense of pride to make history,'' said ASU
Professor Helen Reed, faculty adviser on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ASUSat1 will be the first of four payloads launched into orbit.
The others belong to the Air Force Academy, Stanford University and
the Air Force Research Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's satellite weighs 12 pounds. It will make maps focusing on
Earth vegetation and weather, as well as help ham radio operators
communicate with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Reed and key student participants will be in the control room at
Vandenberg during liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   Other students will staff a ground station at ASU to listen for
the satellite's beacon as it passes 500 miles above the campus
early Saturday, Jan. 15, traveling 5 miles a second.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a six-year countdown.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Reed and the students approached Orbital Sciences Corp.
in Chandler with the idea of a student-built satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had mechanical people build the structure, software people
write the code that controls the satellite and electrical people
build our own boards,'' said Sarah Stanford, 21, an electrical
engineering senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be neat to see our work become successful.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
