<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS ORDERS JET BY BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the first time in its 30-year history, Airbus
Industrie significantly beat Boeing in winning orders for new
airplanes last year.
</P>
<P>
   The final numbers released Thursday by Airbus showed it bested
Boeing by nearly 20 percentage points _ 59 percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, the Airbus backlog of planes on order is now
nearly equal to that of Boeing. Airbus has a backlog of 1,445
planes, against 1,512 for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great year for Airbus. They beat Boeing fair and
square,'' said Joe Campbell, chief aerospace analyst for Leahman
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't see Airbus being able to sustain this level of
difference between themselves and Boeing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Boeing said the numbers show it is clearly time
for Airbus to end its use of government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing congratulates Airbus on its successes, which underscore
the fact that Airbus should no longer need government subsidies to
compete in the market place,'' said Randy Harrison, spokesman for
Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of subsidies has been a sore point with Boeing for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   The gap in orders between Airbus and Boeing last year was even
wider than a first look at the numbers suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus said it had 476 firm orders in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, according to its web site, had 391 new orders in 1999.
But analysts said the Boeing figure is misleading because it
includes planes ordered in 1998 and in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In mid December, Alan Mulally, president of Boeing Commercial
Airplanes, announced that Boeing, to be consistent with the way
Airbus does things, would for the first time count orders from
customers who did not want to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   That meant Boeing was adding 163 such orders from unidentified
customers to its 1999 total, Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   But some of those orders had been placed in 1998 and in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, the analyst, said 59 of the planes were actually
ordered the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Harrison said the figure was 58 planes. Using that
number, Boeing ended the year with only 333 new orders in 1999s. So
the 476 orders claimed by Airbus represents about 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has long argued that Airbus has on occasion counted
commitments in its order totals and not firm orders as Boeing does.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus said Thursday, in announcing its 1999 results at a news
conference in Paris, that it only counted orders for which a
contract was signed and a down payment was made.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison would not say if Boeing still suspects that Airbus has
fudged its numbers, but he did hint in a comment that Boeing is
suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1994, Airbus has claimed to have won about half the
orders,'' Harrison said. ``This year, six years after they first
claimed near equality in orders, we will deliver 480 planes and
they say they will deliver just over 300. So one has to wonder at
what point their orders take the form of aluminum rolling out the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing delivered a record 620 planes, while Airbus
delivered 294.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit likes to make the point that
deliveries are a much better way to judge Boeing's performance
against Airbus. That's because orders can change and also because
airlines pay the bulk of the purchase price of a new plane upon
delivery, not when the plane is ordered.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Beoing had 45 order cancelations and Airbus had 46,
according to calculations by Leahman Brothers' Campbell and other
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Taking that into account, Boeing had net 1999 orders of 288
planes and Airbus had net orders for 430 planes.
</P>
<P>
   Only once before, in 1994, has Airbus claimed to have beaten
Boeing in new orders. But that was at a time in the industry when
orders were so far down for both manufacturers that the Airbus
victory was considered insignificant. And considering the
cancellations that year, it was pretty close to a dead heat,
according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Airbus win is an important measure of how far
Airbus has come toward its goal of being Boeing's equal, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Airbus a lot of credit,'' said Bill Fiala of
Edward Jones. ``They have done a great job of taking a company with
less than 20 percent market share and getting to 50 percent. But
that's only half the equation. They also need profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is a consortium of four companies from France, Germany,
England and Spain. It does not make public its financial
performance and most analysts believe Airbus has sold planes at
huge discounts to gain market share against Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus said the 476 planes ordered in 1999 have a list price of
about $30.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said its 391 orders would be valued at about $28.3
billion at list prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell, the industry analysts, said the actual dollar
values of the 1999 orders by Boeing and Airbus are much less when
discounts are taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   He calculated that Boeing's 332 new orders are worth about $17.5
billion and the 476 Airbus planes are worth about $21.9 billion at
discounted prices.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have said repeatedly over the last year the
company will walk away from a deal if it can't make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have welcomed such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather Boeing have 30 percent market share and hefty
margins than 50 percent and struggling to show a profit,'' Fiala
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Venz, an Airbus spokesman, said the European plane maker
is winning the competitions against Boeing because its planes have
greater commonality, such as similar cockpits. And that means cost
savings to customers.
</P>
<P>
   He also dismissed reports that Boeing has been losing market
share because of pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing has been saying that for 10 years,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``Whenever they lose it always comes to pricing.
If Airbus is such a notorious under pricer, why would we ever
lose?''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research, discounted
commonality as the reason for the Airbus gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does Airbus explain the former success of Boeing,'' he
asked. ``I don't see that Airbus planes have any more commonality
now than they used to have.''
</P>
<P>
   He said pricing, not commonality, best explains the Airbus wins.
Boeing can't compete as it once did because of its own undoing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's cost skyrocketed two years ago when its assembly lines
faltered as the company ramped up production to record levels.
Boeing took about $3 billion in unanticipated charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They screwed up royally,'' Nisbet said of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing must continue to get its production costs down so it can
offer airlines more attractive prices for its planes if it wants to
be competitive with Airbus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new executive team is making great progress in
cutting costs, Nisbet said. He expects Boeing to narrow the order
gap this year, and possibly overtake Airbus again by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long slow process,'' Nisbet said. ``What Boeing did was
like throwing sand in a smoothly running engine. You can't wash it
out. You have to rebuild it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-00 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000113.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5803 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-BOEING-HUGHES-SPI &LR;      01-13 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-HUGHES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING BUYS HUGHES' SATELLITE ARM FOR $3.75 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company, added
what analysts describe as another jewel to its crown Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced, as expected, that it has agreed to buy
Hughes Space and Communications Co., the world's largest maker of
communication satellites, for $3.75 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing intends to be No. 1 in space,'' said Boeing Chairman
Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition is a significant step forward in executing
our goal of becoming the industry leader in integrated space-based
information and communications.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes pioneered the development of communication satellites and
has built nearly 40 percent of all communication satellites now in
operation. It has a backlog of about 36 satellites worth some $4.1
billion, said Jim Albaugh, president of Boeing Space and
Communications division.
</P>
<P>
   The division, which Boeing has said will be the fastest growing
segment its business, will see revenues and earnings jump by 35
percent in 2001 to about $10 billion as a result of the
acquisition, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue could double to $20 billion over the next several years,
Albaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Space and Communications remains the smallest of Boeing's three
core groups. The other two groups are commercial airplanes and
military aircraft and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The new unit will be named Boeing Satellite Systems and will be
part of the Space and Communications group headed by Albaugh.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Boeing also gets two smaller businesses _
Hughes Electron Dynamics, a supplier of satellite components, and
Spectrolab, which makes satellite solar panels.
</P>
<P>
   The three businesses employ about 9,000 poeple, mostly in El
Segundo, Calif., the headquarters of Hughes Space and
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   During a teleconference with reporters, Condit, Albaugh and
Debby Hopkins, Boeing's chief financial officer, said the
acquisition will provide Boeing with new opportunities to grow the
company and increase profits in commercial and government
communication systems and services.
</P>
<P>
   Those new areas include space-based air traffic control
management systems that would allow airlines to monitor their
planes in flight.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also wants to use the Hughes acquisition to help it
develop so-called broadband communication services for commercial
planes. Passengers, for example, could easily tap into the Internet
during a flight.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believed Boeing paid too much for the business,
since the satellite unit had sales of about $2.3 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Hopkins said new tax regulations will allow Boeing to write
off $500 million of the purchase price, so Boeing is actually
paying $3.25 billion for the satellite maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have acquired a property at the right price,''
Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been talking about new ways to grow the company for
about a year, Hopkins said, and during that time Hughes Space and
Communications has always been its No. 1 acquisition priority, even
before it was on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite maker is a unit of Hughes Electronics, which is
owned by General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move is good for both Hughes and for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes has wanted to sell the last part of its aerospace
business so it can focus on providing entertainment and data
information services. The cash from Boeing will allow Hughes to
invest more in DirecTV and in its planned Spaceway system to
provide Internet service from satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Albaugh said Hughes executives contacted Boeing last fall about
buying the satellite-making part of their business.
</P>
<P>
   He described the subsequent negotiations as ``on and off for
some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Boeing not bought Hughes, he said, Boeing would have had to
make other costly investments in new technology.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the acquisition, Albaugh said, Boeing is now well
positioned to be a significant player in emerging space and
communication markets.
</P>
<P>
   He described Hughes as a ``world class'' operation.
</P>
<P>
   Either the Justice Department or the Federal Trade Commission
will next review the deal for possible anti-trust problems. Boeing
said it hopes to close the sale in June if the government gives its
approval.
</P>
